A5841 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     04-28 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS HASH IT ALL OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ A mischievous Forum employee, possibly to his own
professional detriment, decided Tuesday to spell out the common
perception of L.A.'s underachieving professional basketball team.
The electronic scoreboard at midcourt read ``Fakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Lakers, losers of three games in a row, the latter
two by a combined 49 points, can argue. The evidence is damning,
and mounting daily.
</P>
<P>
   But after a 2{-hour team meeting Tuesday, they cling to the
belief, or the hope, that this season is still salvageable, and
that the upcoming playoffs won't simply be another national stage
for their self-destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Calling their situation a crisis would imply a desperation level
the Lakers don't care to acknowledge. But ignoring a string of six
losses in eight games would make them fools indeed.
</P>
<P>
   So team co-captain Derek Harper called a players-only meeting to
start the day. That was followed by a film session, which was
followed by another group therapy session, with coaches included.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, those who talked said the right things. But
even they admitted that at this point, talk means little.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a requirement, if after five games you get your
(butt) torn open, you have to get together to talk about
something,'' Rick Fox said, after initially pleading not to be
interviewed. ``But we've talked and talked a lot this year. I'd
like to think that we would follow up behind some of our talk....
It's enough talk. You're either gonna be on board, commit to
winning being the most important thing, or you're not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very evident that the only way we're gonna win a
championship right now is if we all sacrifice our time and effort
to make each other better players, and to help each other and to
lay it out there day in and day out. We obviously haven't done a
good enough job of that, or we'd be doing a better job in the win
column.''
</P>
<P>
   Still heralded as one of the NBA's most talented teams, the
Lakers are 12-13 since acquiring sharpshooter Glen Rice, 6-8 in
April, and are giving up an average of 101.5 points in their last
10 games, second worst in the league during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The whys and hows and the X's and O's of it all are tough to
figure. All the Lakers know is they have four games left to pull
themselves together. The meeting, therefore, was a review of where
they've been, how they've gotten to this point and where they're
going.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hashed out some things as a team,'' coach Kurt Rambis said.
``The whole idea was to try to get everybody on the same page,
thinking and doing the right things at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a positive meeting. I think it was an honest meeting.
There was some frustrations that were aired. People expressed their
opinion and we got everybody on the same page in terms of how we
should be playing and what we are capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Early returns were good. Practice was so intense that Travis
Knight and Tyronn Lue had to leave midway to treat minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the real test will be Thursday, when the Pacific
Division-champion Portland Trail Blazers come to the Forum, and in
the Lakers' other remaining games with Seattle, Dallas and Portland
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to say things in a locker room, it's easy to come
out and have one good practice,'' Rambis said. ``This team is in a
growing and maturing stage. Do we carry it over to (Wednesday's)
practice, do they have the same enthusiasm and intensity that the
emotions brought out in the meeting? And do we carry it over into
the next ballgame, and do we build on that?''
</P>
<P>
   Players scattered quickly after practice in standard
circle-the-wagons mode. Harper waved off reporters, saying ``I've
said all there is to say.'' Shaquille O'Neal stuck around long
enough to say he wasn't talking.
</P>
<P>
   So the elaboration fell to Fox and Kobe Bryant. By some
accounts, it's Bryant who's at the center of the Lakers' turmoil,
due to a perceived rift between him and O'Neal, a perception both
players downplay.
</P>
<P>
   But Bryant acknowledges that the Lakers' ill performances only
feed such perceptions, and the losses themselves can pull a team
apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lose, people tend to break off because they tend to
look at themselves and see what each individual can do to benefit
the team,'' he said, ``but then if you keep losing in that fashion,
you tend to break up even more. Then you read what's going on in
the paper, you tend to break up even more. I don't think it was
ever a matter of turmoil. It was a matter of losses giving you the
illusion that there was some type of turmoil.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
