</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES RESCUE CLEMENS AND NIP RANGERS, 7-6 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Roger Clemens could have filled a corral with
all the family and friends who came to see the New York Yankee
right-hander pitch here on Tuesday night and attempt to break the
American League record for consecutive victories.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 40 folks on Clemens' pass list watched him
surrender five runs in the first inning and depart before the third
inning with a hamstring injury. But solid relief pitching by Hideki
Irabu and ninth-inning batting heroics by his teammates propelled
the Yankees to a 7-6 victory and kept Clemens from suffering his
first loss in nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he still has a chance of breaking the American
League record of 17 consecutive victories, a mark he currently
shares with Dave McNally (Baltimore 1968-69) and Johnny Allen
(Cleveland, 1936-37). Carl Hubbell, the Hall of Fame left-hander
for the New York Giants. holds the major league record of 24
consecutive victories, set in 1936-37.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees got Clemens off the hook with a two-run rally in the
ninth off John Wetteland. Chuck Knoblauch walked on four pitcehes
to lead off, Derek Jeter and Paul O'Neill followed with singles for
the tying run, and Chili Davis fetched the the tiebreaker home with
a sacrifice fly with the base loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanton, who got the final out in the eighth, got the
victory, Mariano Rivera, who pitched a scoreless ninth, got the
save, and Clemens, whose injury was still being evaluated after the
game, got the sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' last loss was May 29, 1998; his streak of 17
consecutive winning decisions began last June 3, and in that time,
as on Tuesday night, he was occasionally rescued from a potential
loss by run support. On April 15 he allowed seven runs to Baltimore
and did not get a decision because the Yankees came back to tie the
game before losing.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers pounded him on Tuesday night, to the delight of
the Texans who nearly filled the Ballpark at Arlington, where
Clemens is no longer welcome. After Clemens asked Toronto to deal
him in the off season, his agents, Randy and Alan Hendricks,
controlled the trade talks and, for reasons they believed
beneficial to Clemens, effectively scuttled possible swaps with
both the Rangers and the Houston Astros. Clemens landed with the
Yankees, and in donning pinstripes, Clemens scarred his image in
his home state. A twister of boos touched down here when Clemens
was introduced before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is accustomed to hostile crowds, but rarely does his
control fail him in the way it did on Tuesday night. Clemens
typically throws three pitches _ fastball, forkball and a curveball
_ and his accuracy is such that his catchers often can keep their
glove perfectly still in receiving his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Clemens' fastball seemed to flop out of his
hand like a water balloon. He had no command of his breaking ball,
and his forkball hung in the middle of the strike zone. He was ripe
for feasting and e Rangers indulged: of the 53 pitches Clemens
threw in his two innings, the Texas hitters swung and missed only
once.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Meriwether, the home plate umpire, did not give Clemens
anything extra around the edges of the strike zone, and time and
again Clemens would throw a pitch to the fringe, Meriwether would
call a ball, and Clemens would pause for just a moment in silent
protest. With his poor command, Clemens needed the fringes.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Clemens walked Tom Goodwin leading off, and with
Chuck Knoblauch edging closer to second base in case Goodwin tried
to steal, Mark McLemore pulled a ground ball to the right side.
Knoblauch, who otherwise would have been in position to make the
play, missed the ball with a headlong dive: a single.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer, 2 for 26 in his career against Clemens, singled
through the middle to drive in the Rangers' first run. But the
parade of Texas hitters was only starting: Juan Gonzalez walked,
Rafael Palmeiro singled, Ivan Rodriguez reached on a fielder's
choice, Todd Zeile smashed a double to the wall in left-center.
</P>
<P>
   The fans cooed ``Roger, Roger,'' to the tune of ``Darryl,
Darryl.'' Clemens finally retired Lee Stevens and Royce Clayton to
end the first, but he had allowed five runs and thrown 36 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens retired the Rangers in order in the second, but at some
point, he strained his left hamstring. As Texas prepared to bat in
the third, the pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre went to Meriwether
and informed him of Clemens' injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
