</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-DOWNTURN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING REASONS FOR DISNEY PROFIT DIP AS EASY AS ABC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the   ``f'' financial news wire.) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Mickey Mouse's magic touch may be
disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney Co. shares plunged 7 percent Tuesday after the
entertainment giant announced that its year-to-year profit will
decline and likely lead to companywide cost cutting.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusually blunt assessment, Chairman Michael Eisner said
in a statement, ``Although the Disney franchise has a demonstrated
ability to drive long-term growth, we are definitely not satisfied
with our current performance. As a result, we are taking a number
of steps, including an across-the-board assessment of our cost
structure to address the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The profit decline _ attributed in great part to its acquisition
of ABC _ continues a yearlong malaise that has soured Wall Street
on Disney stock, which had been a star performer for most of
Eisner's 15-year tenure. Since May, amid an unprecedented bull
market, Disney shares have fallen 23 percent to $32.50 from their
record $42.375.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street doesn't love Eisner anymore,'' said Barry Hyman,
an analyst with Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent analysts Andrew W. Marcus at BT Alex. Brown and Jill
S. Krutick of Salomon Smith Barney downgraded Disney. ``We are
currently looking at cutting our earnings estimates,'' said Linda
Bannister of Edward Jones. ``Right now, everything is under
review.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney reported, as expected, a 30 percent drop in profits to
$269 million, or 13 cents a share, in its second quarter ended
March 31.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, purchased three years ago as part of the $19 billion buyout
of Capital Cities/ABC, is part of the problem with profits held
down by higher costs and lagging ratings at the No. 3-rated
network.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner did not indicate whether any layoffs are coming among the
110,000 Disney employees. ``We intend to make our businesses more
efficient, increase our cash flow and position ourselves to better
capitalize on the long-term growth potential of our brands,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman said a redefinition of Disney's business plan rather than
job cuts is likely. ``Laying people off is a superficial
solution,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman said Eisner might be considering forcing affiliate TV
stations to pick up programming costs or a step as drastic as
merging ABC with another network. He also recommended starting to
close Disney Stores, which now number more than 700. ``Something
has to be done intrinsically at ABC because they are fighting an
uphill battle with no clear answer yet,'' he said. ``To really
solve the problem, there's got to be a change at the core level.
It's going to be a tough road because there's not a quick-term
fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Bannister said looking at costs is a sensible strategy. ``That's
exactly what they need to do,'' she said. ``Disney has to be able
to grow earnings and they haven't seen earnings growth. Taking a
hard look at costs isn't a bad idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Operating income for broadcasting actually came in better than
some analysts expected, rising 9 percent to $261 million due to
ESPN's performance and improved national advertising, but low ABC
ratings, high programming costs and ongoing softness in local ad
revenues held down profits.
</P>
<P>
   Operating income in the creative-content segment plunged to $163
million from $339 million last year, boosted by the re-release of
``The Little Mermaid'' and ``Peter Pan.'' Theme parks and resorts
continued to be the star performer with a 13 percent rise in
operating income to $305 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company said results should improve in the next two quarters
but warned that the current fiscal year's final results will lag
last year's totals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become the same story, quarter after quarter,'' Hyman
said. ``There's really not much you can do on the network level.
And the concept of the Disney Store is fading out so they have to
ask themselves if they want to go the way of Planet Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner is credited with transforming Disney from a stodgy theme
park-film company with $2 billion in annual revenues to a global
entertainment colossus with $24 billion in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   He has weathered criticism over his compensation, which amounted
to more than half a billion dollars last year due almost entirely
to his exercise of stock options, and other issues mainly because
the stock price quadrupled over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street still has confidence in theme parks and motion
pictures, an area in which Disney has scaled back investment
moderately in recent years. Analysts also have been impressed with
Eisner's strategy of getting Disney established as an Internet
portal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
