<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT CRUISE PAST NETS, 95-76 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Alonzo Mourning was in Florida nursing
an injured right eye and still, it was not fair.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Nets, with a front line of itinerant professional
basketball players, were no match for a Miami Heat team filled with
fury after losing a 20-point lead and the game to the hated New
York Knicks on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   While the absences of Mourning, who was injured in Monday's game
in Cleveland, and the Nets' Keith Van Horn would seem to cancel
each other out, that simply was not so. Not with the Nets already
having been severely depleted; Jayson Williams, Jim McIlvaine, Rony
Seikaly, Scott Burrell and Eric Murdock all are out for the season
and so is Van Horn, who broke his left thumb in Sunday's victory
over Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, the Nets muddled through Tuesday night's
game at the Continental Arena while the still well-stocked Heat
roared. It added up to Miami (31-14) going ahead by 18 points in
the first quarter and rolling to an easy 95-76 victory before a
crowd of 15,883.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the 945th of Coach Pat Riley's career, placing
him second behind Lenny Wilkens (1,148), one game ahead of Bill
Fitch. Riley, however, played down the milestone, calling it just a
number, and instead drew more satisfaction from the fact that
Miami's number for clinching home court throughout the Eastern
Conference playoffs over Orlando (30-17) and Indiana (29-17) was
down to two.
</P>
<P>
   Without having Van Horn and his 21-point average to worry about,
Miami went with a simple strategy of hounding Stephon Marbury.
Trapping him on pick-and-rolls, the Heat took Marbury out of the
game and forced the other Nets to take charge. They couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted them to feel our heat, show them that they couldn't
take it to us,'' said Tim Hardaway, who helped hold Marbury to 10
points, 6 assists, 5 turnovers and 4-of-14 shooting. ``This team
feels good things are coming. The only thing that messed us up was
Sunday's game. We're still thinking about that and we don't want to
let it happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity for such a comeback was there, since the Heat
led by as many as 22 points in the second quarter and by 26 in the
third, but with the Heat staying focused and the Nets featuring
Mark Hendrickson (who started in place of Van Horn), Jamie Feick
(who is a shade shorter than 6 feet 8 inches), David Vaughn and
William Cunningham on the front line, there was little chance of
that happening.
</P>
<P>
   Those four were not in the National Basketball Association
before the Nets signed them to 10-day contracts in late March.
Cunningham, who played for the Nets under two 10-day contracts
earlier this season, was at home in Alabama as recently as Monday
before getting a call from the Nets after Van Horn went down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were at full force tonight, there is no way that
happens,'' said Kendall Gill, who scored only 8 points. ``We were
caught off guard and that's what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   If Mourning had not been hit in the eye in Cleveland, there is
no telling how large the deficit would have been. A candidate for
the league's most valuable player award, Mourning had been
absolutely unstoppable in his three games against the Nets,
averaging 27 points, 15 rebounds, 6 blocked shots and several
thunderous dunks. He is listed as day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Kittles had 17 points and 6 steals for the Nets, who visit
Detroit on Wednesday, and Chris Carr led them with 18 points, 16 in
the fourth quarter against the Miami reserves. By that time, it was
fair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
