<HEADER>
A5858 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN     04-28 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MO HOPES HE'LL SOON RETURN TO FIRST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Mo Vaughn said there's a chance he'll return to first
base before the end of the current homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn started at DH for the fifth game in a row Tuesday since
returning from disabled list April 22. He used Tuesday to take a
step towards returning to first by lessening the rigidity of the
tape job on his sprained left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day it's getting better, Vaughn said. ``The way we've
been taping the whole time, it's been a tight job. And I think the
muscle's stronger than we felt it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn participated in batting practice and fielding drills
before Tuesday's game without any tape on the ankle. For the game,
the ankle was taped but not as tight.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Terry Collins put a pinch runner in for Vaughn in the
seventh inning of Monday's game. Vaughn's spot in the lineup came
up in the ninth inning with the game tied, but the Angels had Tim
Unroe up instead. Unroe struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he doesn't like coming out of a game, but he
understands the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to do it,'' Vaughn said. ``We talked about that. I
know the game. It would be kind of selfish if I tried to stay in
the game. But if I was healthy, it'd be difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   He may be the 12th man on a 12-man pitching staff, but Scott
Schoeneweis is showing he belongs.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis' outing Monday was key in the Angels' 4-3, 11-inning
victory over Toronto. He threw three scoreless innings -- the
eighth, ninth and 10th innings -- allowed only two hits (both
singles) and didn't allow a Blue Jays baserunner to reach second
base.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis, 25, was cut in spring training, then brought back
to the club when Rich DeLucia was released. Still, he only made the
team because Collins and his staff decided to go with 12 pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said it all along, and I know it's cliche, but I'm just
glad to be here,'' said Schoeneweis, who has a degree in history
from Duke University. ``You can't trade the experience of being
here for anything. Whatever role I have in the big leagues is fine
with me. Just being here is great.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis has been a starter all his life but is making the
adjustment to life in the bullpen just fine. In seven games, he is
0-0 with a 4.76 ERA. But throw out his first game -- in which he
had the major-league-debut jitters (5 runs in one-third of an
inning) -- and Schoeneweis has allowed one earned run in 11
innings.
</P>
<P>
   He followed starter Chuck Finley around during spring training
-- ``I probably annoyed the hell out of him,'' he said -- but now
spends his time picking the brains of the relievers and bullpen
coach Joe Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge difference in every respect,'' Schoeneweis said
of going from starter to reliever. ``From how you prepare for games
to working out and conditioning. Everything's different but when it
comes down to it, pitching is pitching. If you make your pitches
and execute your game, you'll have success.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins admitted the club wondered about how Schoeneweis would
make the adjustment from starter to reliever.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the only question,'' Collins said. ``He's got a good
arm, good stuff. He throws hard and he throws strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins has indicated that he might not be able to keep 12
pitchers much longer. With the starters going deeper into games,
there is not enough work to go around for all the relievers.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis might be the one to go, despite his success. But he
says he is grateful for the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took a big risk to put me in this situation,'' he said.
``I appreciate them having the confidence in me to do that. But I'd
rather be a reliever in the big leagues than a starter at triple-A,
and that's what it comes down to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels and Blue Jays play the third game of their four-game
series tonight beginning at 7:35. Tim Belcher (1-1, 8.53 ERA) will
start for Anaheim against Toronto's David Wells (3-1, 3.42).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
