<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARIYA'S SEASON ENDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Don't bet against Craig Hartsburg in a poker game.
The Anaheim coach certainly had his best poker face on Tuesday
morning when he responded to a question about the status of Ruslan
Salei's shoulder by quietly saying ``the biggest blow to us is that
Paul Kariya won't play, he broke his foot in the last game.''
</P>
<P>
   One reporter was so caught off guard that Hartsburg was asked
``who? and he matter of factly responded ``Paul Kariya.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariya was injured early in the third period of Sunday's Game 3
when he blocked a shot by Detroit defensemen Nicklas Lidstrom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was a problem, but I didn't know it was that bad,''
said Kariya, who continued to play after being hit on the side of
the foot.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim captain was hoping to play as late as Monday, even
after he found out the foot was broken, but by Tuesday morning
Kariya and the Ducks knew better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not worth the risk,'' said Hartsburg.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays showed that Kariya suffered a ``W shaped fracture of the
foot -- ``it's not a little break, it's substantial,'' said
Hartsburg, who did add that no surgery is planned.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya said he expects the healing process will take at least
4-6 weeks, but the winger can't be too careful.
</P>
<P>
   He bruised a foot blocking a shot late in the 1995-96 season,
started favoring one leg and suffered an abdominal injury that
forced him to miss training camp and the first 11 games of the
'96-97 season.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, who played in all 82 regular season games this season
after recovering from a bout of post-concussion syndrome, was upset
at the turn of events but not despondent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel sorry for myself, I didn't last year,'' he said.
``Everything happens for a reason, I just don't know what that
reason is now.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, who has worked very hard to become a complete two-way
player, said the injury wouldn't change his approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would do it again,'' he said. ``If anything I wish I could
have turned my foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a fluke thing, I was just in the wrong position.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg certainly didn't want to lose one of his two offensive
stars, but he praised Kariya's effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some might say he shouldn't be doing that (blocking shots),''
he said. ``But that's a loser's mentality. Paul paid the price for
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the game, but it's bad luck for Paul,'' said
Ducks center Steve Rucchin. ``It's pretty unfortunate, considering
what has happended to him in the past, but he had a terrific year,
he has a lot to be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Detroit defenseman Chris Chelios, who has had numerous battles
with Kariya over the years, had a unique answer when asked if he
was sorry to see Kariya hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's a trick question, I'm not going to answer it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lidstrom was at least gave Kariya credit for his
willingness to play an all-round game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see (Steve) Yzerman do it (blocking shots) all the time,''
he said. ``It shows that they are into the game and want to play as
good on defense as they do on offense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
