<SLUG> BC-ROCKETDYNE-EPA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA EPA TO PROBE STATE-ROCKETDYNE RELATIONSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TERRI HARDY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ A division of the state Environmental
Protection Agency will investigate questions about the relationship
between Rocketdyne and state health officials over operation at the
Santa Susana Field Laboratory in the Simi Hills northwest of Los
Angeles, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are allegations disclosed in the Daily News that state
Department of Health Services officials suppressed a cancer study
of residents and cooperated with Rocketdyne company officials to
try to get rid of an independent citizens oversight group directing
health investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The state EPA's toxic substances control division will conduct
``an independent review outside the DHS,'' said Anita Gore,
spokewoman for Grantland Johnson, secretary of the state's Health
and Human Services Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, including Assemblywoman Sheila Kuehl, D-Encino, have
pressured Gov. Gray Davis and Johnson for the investigation and
called for three top DHS administrators who oversaw health
investigations at Rocketdyne to be fired.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Tuesday to the head of the state EPA, which oversees
the Division of Toxic Substances Control, Johnson said his agency
is ``very concerned that a thorough and independent review of
Assembly member Kuehl's concerns be performed, and that these
concerns be responded to quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuehl's office was pleased but the co-chairman of the oversight
committee said he was concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DTSC is as captured by Rocketdyne as is the DHS,'' said
Daniel Hirsch, co-chairman of the oversight committee, accusing the
regulatory agencies of having too close a relationship with the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is needed is a thorough housecleaning of both agencies,''
said Hirsch, who also is president of the anti-nuclear group
Committee to Bridge the Gap.
</P>
<P>
   After the Daily News in 1989 reported that radiation and other
pollution had been released at the Santa Susana Field Laboratory, a
massive federal cleanup was begun. In 1991, lawmakers _ concerned
that the DHS was not properly overseeing studies of possible health
effects _ formed a citizens oversight panel that included
scientific experts.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said that over the years, they believe a too-close
relationship between Rocketdyne and the DHS has continued. In the
meantime, criticism has been raised about the DHS' handling of
other health matters, including suppressing a survey it
commissioned on the state's smoking ban and failing to track
children known to have lead poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the chairman of the state's Joint Legislative Audit
Committee said his group would be taking a broader look at the DHS.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehl and others charge that the DHS suppressed a 1997 cancer
survey taken of residents around the field laboratory. The document
was found earlier this month through a request made under the
state's public records act.
</P>
<P>
   Another document discovered was a proposal from Rocketdyne to
oust the current citizens oversight panel with a group of the
company's handpicked replacements. The DHS followed up with a
time-line indication when and how the committee could be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Rocketdyne and DHS officials have strenuously denied that they
have an inappropriate relationship, and insisted they are innocent
of wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 0042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
