<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALENS-ROCK-HALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVE TO HONOR VALENS GETS BOOST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY YVETTE CABRERA  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The campaign by his family and supporters to get
Ritchie Valens inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame has
received a boost from a local congressman and the head of the
Recording Industry Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of U.S. Rep. Howard Berman, D-Mission Hills,
Hilary B. Rosen, president and chief executive officer of the
Washington, D.C.-based association, said Tuesday she will make it a
priority to recommend the rock 'n' roll legend from Pacoima as a
nominee next year to the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ritchie Valens deserves to be nominated and I'm going to work
with the congressman on that,'' said Rosen, a board member of the
Rock and Roll Hall of Fame Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Valens' aunt, Ernestine Reyes of suburban Pacoima, who has been
working since 1995 to get Valens inducted into the Hall of Fame,
said she was hopeful that Rosen's support would bring Valens the
recognition he deserves. Even today, Reyes continues to receive
about 20 pieces of fan mail a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't express how much he deserves to be in the Rock and
Roll Hall of Fame,'' said Reyes. ``He did so much in the short time
that he lived and I pray to God that he'll get up there soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Valens' record company and family have gathered thousands of
signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes will be gathering petition signatures during the fifth
annual Ritchie Valens festival, called ``The Legend Lives On,'' on
May 7-8 at Ritchie Valens Recreation Center in Pacoima. The
postcard petitions are part the campaign launched several years ago
by Valens' former Los Angeles record company, Del-Fi Records Inc.,
to get him nominated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will do everything in my power to raise this issue with my
fellow board members and to encourage Mr. Valens' induction,''
wrote Rosen in a response to Berman's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Berman's spokesman, Tom Waldman, said Berman is confident that
Rosen's support will make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Recording Industry Association is very well-respected. Her
support certainly gets us further than ever before,'' said Waldman.
</P>
<P>
   Valens, who died at the age of 17 in an Iowa plane crash on Feb.
3, 1959, was nominated for the first time last September, though he
had been eligible for the Hall of Fame since 1983. Eligibility
begins 25 years after an artist's record is released.
</P>
<P>
   Berman, who last spring began actively campaigning on Valens'
behalf by lobbying the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame nominating
committee, sent letters to Rosen and her fellow board members last
February, seeking their support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of Valens' friends and contemporaries, including Little
Richard, Eddie Cochran, Buddy Holly and Jerry Lee Lewis, have
already been inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame. Yet he
is overlooked year after year ...,'' wrote Berman, whose
congressional district includes Pacoima, where Valens grew up.
</P>
<P>
   The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame Foundation presents all eligible
artists to a nominating committee, then selects the nominees
through a series of votes.
</P>
<P>
   The nominees are then placed on a ballot sent to an
international voting body of more than 800 members from the music
industry, including artists, producers, journalists and other music
industry executives. Between five to seven artists are selected
annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
