<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5877 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     04-28 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOZING ANGELS HAVE NIGHTMARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Angels' performance against the Toronto Blue Jays
on Tuesday night should have been rated ``R.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Revolting.
</P>
<P>
   Regretful.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for the Angels, their 10-1 loss before 17,899 at Edison
Field counted for only one loss in the standings. Time will tell if
there is any residual effect.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels made only two physical errors. But the mental errors,
those that are not counted on the scoreboard, were numerous. It all
started with Angels starting pitcher Omar Olivares, whose mind
seemed to drift in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   With two out and Shawn Green on first base in the first inning,
Olivares failed to pay much attention to Green, who stole second
base easily.
</P>
<P>
   After walking Carlos Delgado, Olivares drifted off again. Green
and Delgado got such good jumps on an Olivares pitch that catcher
Matt Walbeck didn't even bother to make a throw, as Green and
Delgado stole third and second, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Fernandez followed with a two-run single, then caught
Olivares napping again. As Olivares stared in at the catcher,
Fernandez took off for second. Olivares turned and threw to second,
but neither shortstop Andy Sheets nor second baseman Randy Velarde
was at the bag, and the ball sailed into center field.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez took third and Olivares was charged with the error.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Blue Jays had four runs, four hits and four stolen
bases in the inning. And it only got worse.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares (2-2) was gone by the time the Angels played like
clowns again _ in the fifth inning. After a double, Green stole
third on pitcher Mike Magnante. It was Green's third steal of the
game, despite just one steal all season going into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado followed with a grounder to first baseman Darin Erstad,
who caught Green too far off the bag at third and began a rundown.
Third baseman Troy Glaus got the ball and ran Green toward the
plate. Problem was, he never caught up and never threw the ball,
allowing Green to score.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus and the Angels got a second chance to get the rundown play
right later in the inning, with Glaus catching and tagging Delgado
as he ran toward the plate. However, it allowed the two other
runners to move up a base to second and third, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the sixth inning when Velarde dropped a throw on a
relay from the outfield, allowing Jose Cruz, who had doubled in two
runs, to move to third on the error.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough for many of the fans, who booed, including one
fan who went down to the dugout and berated the Angels players as
they came off the field at the end of the inning. The fan was
cheered as he walked away.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jays starter Pat Hentgen (1-1) threw seven scoreless
innings, allowing only three hits. The Angels' only run of the game
came on Sheets' home run in the eighth inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
