<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANCHERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRANTS BEDEVIL RANCHERS ON ARIZONA BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 and DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOUGLAS, Ariz. _ Dale Cureton's voice turned soft and wistful as
he recalled the good old days here on the sprawling Rocker M Ranch,
just a jackrabbit sprint from the Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke of a time when the same handful of deferential Mexican
farm workers repeatedly used his place as their first stop-off
point on their way north.
</P>
<P>
   They cleaned Cureton's barn. He gave them a cup of well water, a
sandwich and a place to sleep in the hayloft.
</P>
<P>
   Today, more than a hundred footpaths littered with toilet paper,
water bottles, plastic bags and dirty diapers cross the Rocker M,
10 miles east of Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   They've been beaten into the desert floor by the endless stream
of illegal immigrants _ as many as 10,000 a month _ who take on
this arid obstacle course of rattlesnakes and thickets of prickly
pear, mesquite, agave, ocotillo and cholla spines that tear the
flesh.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine all the drugs and groups of people coming by
here at night,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cureton still runs into the occasional solo Mexican. But most of
the time, he said, the visitor is carrying a backpack full of
marijuana. Cureton quickly heads the other way.
</P>
<P>
   Cureton's 14-year-old son, Randy, shook his head disgustedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is like the drug capital of the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Here on the front lines of the illegal immigration crisis,
residents like Cureton say they're caught between the illegals and
federal government, forced to endure property damage from both
sides and helpless to stop a slow-motion ``invasion'' that's
recently and ominously speeding up.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents have decided to be helpless no longer. About 30
landowners have formed the Concerned Citizens of Cochise County to
lobby government officials to control the flow of illegal
immigrants through this, the most heavily crossed area in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, one member of the organization personally
detained a group of 27 illegals on his ranch and called the U.S.
Border Patrol. The organization last week asked Gov. Jane Hull to
send the Arizona Army National Guard to the Douglas area.
</P>
<P>
   That was followed by an emotional meeting Saturday in Bisbee
among 200 Cochise County residents, U.S. Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz.,
and U.S. Attorney Jose de Jesus Rivera. The citizens were warned
about taking the law into their own hands.
</P>
<P>
   Cureton said he wouldn't dare do that. But he said the ranch
north of the Rocker M had two pickup trucks stolen in recent weeks.
He also said his other neighbors have had vehicles stolen and their
homes burglarized.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Still, Cureton said that on most days he's bothered more by the
federal government than by the illegals.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol tears down gates and runs roughshod across the
30-section ranch, Cureton said, at times shining floodlights in his
bedroom window late at night.
</P>
<P>
   Once he got so mad that he ran a Border Patrol vehicle off the
road, Cureton said; the agents inside came at him with weapons
drawn.
</P>
<P>
   But many other area ranchers say they welcome any help they can
get _ even from Big Brother.
</P>
<P>
   Larry and Thelma Vance, retirees who live three miles east of
Douglas, say their property is a maze of trails left by interlopers
tromping through by the hundreds each night. Mexico is one mile
south, through whitethorn, greasewood and catclaw. The house is
defended by barbed wire, an inner cyclone fence and wrought iron
around the patio.
</P>
<P>
   On just one evening in February, a Border Patrol tower recorded
800 people going by the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's not an invasion, what is?'' Thelma Vance asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sympathize with them trying to come here and make a better
life for themselves,'' she said, ``but their country has to take
care of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Vance said it's time for U.S. leaders to tell their
southern neighbor, ``Either you do something about it, or we're
going to _ which might even mean an invasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many people who have influence on our
representatives, and don't want to insult Mexico and tackle real
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``A solution? Either 5,000 Border Patrol officers, or put the
military here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers and other border residents complain about cut fences,
trash, thievery and vandalism. Beyond all that, they say the stream
of illegals makes them fearful of crime.
</P>
<P>
   Though few ranchers report any assaults or armed robberies by
immigrants, they say the desperation of smugglers _ known as
``coyotes'' or ``polleros'' _ keeps them worried.
</P>
<P>
   Next door, Larry Vance Jr. climbs a 30-foot-tall tower in his
back yard and uses infrared binoculars to watch out for
``two-legged coyotes that are illegal to shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Vance, who keeps a pistol on the coffee table, is
co-chairman of the concerned citizens group.
</P>
<P>
   Others in Cochise County have taken the law into their own
hands. Roger Barnett, owner of the Crossroads Ranch northeast of
Douglas, said he and some armed pals patrol the 22,000-acre
property on weekends, looking for trespassers.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, Barnett and two other men came across
footprints. ``We saw the tracks. It looked fresh,'' he said. ``So
we followed 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnett said he and his friends found about 30 immigrants
covered with blankets and grass. Some ran, but only one managed to
get away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We marched 'em to the road and called Border Patrol,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Just in recent months, Barnett said, trespassers flattened
fences, stole a truck from the ranch yard and emptied an
8,000-gallon water tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're leaving trash all over the place,'' he added. ``If
this was any other country besides the United States, they'd have
troops on the line and there'd be bloodshed.''
</P>
<P>
   Cureton doesn't want to see that. In fact, he wants to move on
to greener pastures.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocker M has been up for sale in recent months. Potential
buyers marvel at the bargain-basement price, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then they come for a visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a guy come down from Wyoming in January talking about
how he couldn't wait to put his deposit down,'' Cureton said. ``But
then he went up on the road by the Mexican border and watched the
train of people going by.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never head from him again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
