<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-KATZENBERG-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KATZENBERG OUTLINES EISNER SHOWDOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Their strong relationship at The Walt Disney Co.
ravaged by a contract dispute, Jeffrey Katzenberg has testified
that Chief Executive Officer Michael Eisner came to his home and
told him to ``behave yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The showdown came after Katzenberg quit Disney in 1994, despite
warnings he would lose a blockbuster bonus if he didn't stay for
two more years. He later sued the studio for more than $250
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't understand why a game was being played with me,''
Katzenberg said Tuesday during the second day of trial, which will
determine whether Disney owes him $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was unhappy with the press that was going on and
somehow thought I controlled it,'' Katzenberg said, under
questioning from his lawyer, Bert Fields.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg sued Disney in 1996, seeking past and future profits
from hits that came under his watch, such as ``Beauty and the
Beast'' and ``The Color of Money.''
</P>
<P>
   The case was partially settled last year, but the parties still
have to go through the damages phase of trial.
</P>
<P>
   While both parties agree Disney must cut Katzenberg a check, the
amount is still at issue.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Disney lawyer Louis Meisinger appealed to
the private judge handling the case, Paul Breckenridge, asking him
to keep the trial from degrading into a personal battle between two
men.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner will get a chance to respond to Katzenberg's allegations
on the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg also testified Tuesday that his last meeting with his
boss before he left Disney was in Eisner's office, where he told
the chief executive officer that a deal memo that spelled out his
bonus was easy enough for his 11-year-old to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stood up from his desk and literally backed away,''
Katzenberg said, contending that Eisner told him to leave the room.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a fraud claim, Katzenberg and the studio are
disputing how the interest on his 2 percent bonus should be paid
and are asking Breckenridge to determine what inflation rate should
be applied.
</P>
<P>
   Disney also claims Katzenberg should not get money for
merchandise that is sold in Disney-owed outlets, such as Disney
Stores and its theme parks.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg spoke quietly during his five hours on the witness
stand, and was told by the judge to keep his answers short.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg is scheduled to return to the witness stand today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
