<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGBROTHER-GUNS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER MUST CHOOSE GUN OR ROLE AS YOUTH MENTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM HERMANN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steven Haynes wants to be a Valley Big Brother, to serve as a
much-needed friend and mentor to a fatherless boy.
</P>
<P>
   His credentials seem in order: a single man with a clean record,
employed for 12 years in a responsible job where he's now a
supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   But Valley Big Brothers/Big Sisters says no.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Haynes is a Phoenix police sergeant who, like
many officers, typically carries his gun while off duty. And Valley
Big Brothers/Big Sisters says he can't do so while he is with a
Little Brother.
</P>
<P>
   Organization officials say they must be especially cautious in
setting conditions for their children. For Haynes, the decision is
an over-reaction that seems to defeat the goal of finding positive
role models for youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is an unreasonable fear about guns here,''
Haynes said. ``I am a police officer, trained in the use of a
pistol, and it strikes me as irrational to disqualify me over this
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   A Valley Big Brothers/Big Sisters executive said confidentiality
rules forbade her from discussing the Haynes case specifically, but
said the organization's policy about guns is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever the child is around our volunteers who own guns they
either must have them locked up or the ammunition must be separate
from the gun,'' said Madeleine Stilwell, director of operations.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix police don't know how many of their 2,600 sworn officers
carry weapons off duty, but a department spokesman estimated the
number as ``fairly significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Mike Torres said the department will not take sides in this
issue. But he noted that last year off-duty officers intervened in
two armed robberies and used their pistols in both cases.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, a suspect was confronted at gunpoint and
apprehended. In the other, a suspect was wounded, then apprehended.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is just that sort of situation that gives Valley Big
Brothers/Big Sisters pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a concern that a police officer carrying a gun off
duty might have to step in during a crime _ use a weapon he is
carrying when a child is there,'' Stilwell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern always must be for the safety of the child.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres said responding to a crime in progress is not the only
reason an off-duty officer might carry a pistol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officers who know they're going to be in a fairly tough area
often go armed,'' he said. ``But also some officers whose duty has
brought them into contact with some questionable characters carry a
weapon as a matter of self-defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Haynes, 35, has dealt with questionable characters during his
years on the force. For about three years he supervised a patrol
squad in one of the most crime-ridden areas of the South Mountain
Precinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dealt with some extremely violent people as part of my
job,'' Haynes said. ``I recently had a guy who I'd arrested come up
to me when I was off duty, but then he thanked me for arresting him
and starting to get his life turned around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it could have gone the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Haynes said he applied to be a Valley Big Brother last summer,
and was impressed by the thoroughness of the background check the
organization did on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to know everything about me, asked some very
personal questions,'' said the unmarried, childless Haynes. ``But I
had no trouble with those questions and am glad they are so
thorough.''
</P>
<P>
   The only blemish on his service record, Haynes said, relates to
a traffic stop in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I saw a furtive movement from the man I'd stopped,
something dangerous, and there wasn't, but I fired my weapon,''
Haynes said.
</P>
<P>
   He wounded the man in the arm. The man recovered and the city
paid a settlement, Haynes said. He received a one-day suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes said that during the fall and winter he progressed
through Valley Big Brothers/Big Sisters security checks and
meetings. Finally came an inspection of his Mesa house, and then
came the issue of carrying a firearm while off duty.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked by the organization if he would agree not to carry
a gun while off duty. ``I said I was sorry, but I couldn't agree
that I never would carry a gun off duty when I was with my Little
Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Haynes got the word: Unless he would agree not to
carry a gun when not on duty and with a Little Brother, he wouldn't
get a Little Brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have a lot to offer to a young person,'' Haynes
said. ``I want to show a young man the importance of honesty,
working hard, being a good student. It is the kind of values my
father gave to me and I want to do that for another young person.''
</P>
<P>
   Stilwell said the organization's directors specifically
discussed the question of off-duty officers carrying guns around
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have about 20 officers from various agencies who are
volunteers, and this question has not caused a problem in those
cases,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board has decided to keep with the policy that police
volunteers should not have weapons when with a child. Our concern
is if the police officer used the weapon when a child is there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not easy,'' Stilwell said. ``But if we err, we have to
err on the side of the child.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
