<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-MOVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS UNVEILS NEW BID TO KEEP PATRIOTS OUT OF HARTFORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Challenging Connecticut's deal to move the New England
Patriots to Hartford, Massachusetts officials announced on Tuesday
night that they had put together a rival plan that is backed by the
National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Paul Cellucci and top state legislators said Massachusetts
would provide $70 million for parking, landscaping and other
improvements for a new stadium next to the old one at Foxboro,
about 30 miles south of here.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the Patriots would pay for the $250 million
stadium, with generous loans from the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are second acts in American life,'' said the Senate
president, Thomas F. Birmingham. ``It appeared the Patriots were
irretrievable lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders said the state House and Senate would vote
on the package in time for it to be considered when NFL owners meet
to consider the Patriots' move in late May.
</P>
<P>
   The new plan is quite similar to a previous one that was
acceptable to the Patriots but was deemed too generous by the
speaker of the state House, Thomas Finneran. Under that plan, the
Patriots would have put in $200 million for the stadium and the
state $72 million.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's prospects for keeping the Patriots began to slip
publicly on Friday when the NFL commissioner, Paul Tagliabue,
traveled to Boston to lobby state officials and business executives
to come up with a deal to keep the team. In recent weeks, Patriots
officials have grown concerned about the site Hartford had chosen
for a $375 million stadium for the team, and NFL officials worried
about the drawbacks of moving the team out of of a major television
market.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is the nation's sixth-largest television market; Hartford
is the 27th.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the Patriots, Robert K. Kraft, has made no comment
in recent days as Tagliabue worked with Massachusetts to devise a
plan. But officials here took his silence as a willingness to at
least consider an offer from his home state.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, Gov. John Rowland, who had endured much
criticism for the lucrative terms he granted the Patriots, has
become annoyed at the precariousness of a deal that he thought was
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Massachusetts, with all due respect, has had five years to
work on this,'' he said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal announced on Tuesday night, Massachusetts would
require to pay a $1 million user fee a year to cover the costs of
new highway ramps to the stadium and other improvements, which
would help the state would incur to pay for the changes, and
$400,000 annually for use of the satellite parking lots built by
the state. That element was not part of previous packages discussed
by Massachusetts and the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this is a viable alternative to Connecticut,''
Cellucci said. ``Now this will be a decision for the National
Football League and the owners.''
</P>
<P>
   Any move by the Patriots would have to win the approval of
three-quarters of the NFL team owners. Massachusetts officials said
that if Kraft did not jump at their offer, they may present it to
the owners directly. ``He may not be the master of his own fate,''
Birmingham said.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut had begun negotiating with Kraft after the
Massachusetts Legislature had refused to approve the incentives
that he demanded.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut plan, which was approved by the Legislature in
December, called for the state to pay the entire cost of the
stadium and guaranteed Kraft a profit on the sale of club seats and
sky boxes. Although the Massachusetts plan would require Kraft to
finance the stadium, the proposal was made more attractive by a
recent change in NFL policy on new stadiums in the largest markets.
Kraft would be able to borrow half of the money from the NFL, and
would be able to repay it with revenue from premium seats that
otherwise would go to the visiting team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
