r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-RUMORS-LADN     04-28 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-RUMORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. AREA SCHOOLS STRUGGLE TO QUELL RUMORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Daily News staff writers David R. Baker, Charles F. Bostwick and
Cecilia Chan   contributed to this story.) 
BY STEVE CARNEY and TROY ANDERSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At Quartz Hill High School, two students were
arrested Tuesday for threatening to blow up the school, authorities
said. Students said it was a prank and no bomb-making materials
were found.
</P>
<P>
   At Granada Hills High, the principal sent out a letter to the
homes of all 3,500 students to quell rumors that some dire event
would occur ``Friday or Saturday or Monday or Cinco de Mayo or May
6 or May 20.'' And she invited each of the students to write her
back expressing their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In schools throughout the Los Angeles region and all over
America, police and school officials are grappling with a new
phenomenon in the aftermath of the Littleton, Colo., high school
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor or fact, fantasy or reality, the fear of campus violence
has taken on a new seriousness in the lives of children, parents
and authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain sense of alarm among law enforcement and
school officials and students bombarded with exposure,'' said June
Arnette, associate director of the National School Safety Center in
Westlake Village. ``Everybody is concerned they don't overlook any
possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   A tip from a student led deputies to arrest two Quartz Hill High
students, ages 14 and 15, in the Antelope Valley on allegations
that they threatened to bomb the school. Another boy was cited for
possessing an inert grenade, and three other youths were suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies found a school map with escape routes; a copy of ``The
Anarchist's Cookbook,'' a book that contains bomb-making
instructions; and a note reading ``DARC, or Death, Anarchy, Revenge
and Chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we confronted them, they said they were just joking
around,'' said Detective Steven Owen of the Los Angeles County
Sheriff's Department. ``We can't take it as a joke, unfortunately,
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Lancaster sheriff's Sgt. Darrel Brown, who also is a board
member of the Antelope Valley Union High School District north of
Los Angeles: ``This is all post-Littleton hoax stuff. They were
looking for the reaction from their fellow students. Now they're in
serious trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the youths' comments were spread by word of mouth
around the campus, alarming many students and parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids stayed home today,'' Brown said. ``Parents kept kids
home.''
</P>
<P>
   At Granada Hills High, Principal Kathleen Rattay said rumors
were rampant. For example, a lunchtime fire in a trash can Friday
turned into a story that someone had lobbed a bomb into the
receptacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very upsetting to see so many of our students are
fearful,'' she said. ``There has been absolutely nothing to
substantiate any rumor.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoaxes or not, school officials across Southern California said
that in light of the Colorado shooting they have no choice but to
check every threat of violence.
</P>
<P>
   A student wearing a gothic outfit and another student who
threatened to ``shoot up the place'' at El Camino Real High School
in suburban Woodland Hills last week prompted increased security at
the school.
</P>
<P>
   School officials confiscated the student's clothes and called
his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``His parents were absolutely shocked and embarrassed by their
youngster's actions,'' said Principal Ron Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing came of the student's threat to attack the school. ``At
this time we believe it was an idle, irresponsible comment made by
a student to pester another student,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Burbank Unified School District, Marissa Rosoff, the
coordinator of school safety, said there have been no rumors, but
that students seem more forthcoming with their concerns. ``They
have brought forward things they are worried about,'' Rosoff said.
</P>
<P>
   And in Glendale, north of L.A., parents have been calling
schools for information about safety programs, but none has
reported peculiar problems, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Conejo Valley Unified School District in neighboring
Ventura County, administrators said there have been eight or nine
rumors of threatened violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are just very general _ Something bad is going to happen
at one of the schools sometime this week,'' said Richard Simpson,
assistant superintendent of instructional services for the
district.
</P>
<P>
   Each was taken seriously and checked out, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a number of phone calls, mostly from parents who are
trying to do one of two things _ give us a heads-up on what they've
heard from their own kid or make sure we heard about it and are
looking into it,'' Simpson said. ``That's the kind of information
we want.''
</P>
<P>
   By asking students at Granada Hills High to write her, the
principal said she hoped it would stem the rumors, ease fears and
help get troubled students into counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Among the students' replies:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I've heard rumors from my friends I want you to check out.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I'm terrified. I cry at night because I worry about these
things. Please help us.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``You're blowing everything out of proportion. Leave us alone.
We'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Lieberman, a Los Angeles Unified School District
psychologist, said rumor control is vital in the aftermath of any
tragedy, although spreading rumors is almost a teen-age hobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it is a natural part of adolescence, to take certain
stories and stretch it out,'' Lieberman said. ``And for others,
it's a passive-aggressive way of showing they need some
attention.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
