<P>
   HUNGARY-PAPRIKA (Zeged, Hungary) _ Driving south from Budapest
across the Alfold, the Great Hungarian Plain, you pass men walking
behind horses, guiding plows through earth the color of Hershey
Bars. The willows are wearing gauzy-green spring outfits, and the
forsythia is blooming. It is March, planting season in paprika
country. Paprika doesn't amount to much in the American kitchen.
But for the Hungarians, paprika is a way of life, a source of
flavor as indispensable to their cuisine as lemongrass is to the
Thais and basil is to the Neapolitans. Each Hungarian consumes a
pound of the stuff a year. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   FAT-COOKING (Undated) _ Fat. For years, it's been a four-letter
word so repugnant to many of us that it only required three. And
yet the best chefs know they can't be great without it. Sometimes
they use a lot. Sometimes a little. No one is campaigning for a
diet dominated by what used to be called artery-cloggers, but in
the high-priced world of the occasional indulgence, where a dish is
valued most for its artistry, fat _ duck, goose, butter or olive
oil, even lard _ is the unspoken ingredient cooks rely on more than
most diners might ever imagine. By Melissa Clark.
</P>
