<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5902 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     04-28 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE'LL SEE MORE OF THIS ODD PAIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ And so we bid a fond adieu to Paul and Teemu, the most
entertaining odd couple this side of ``Dharma and Greg.'' The Magic
Wingdom show starring Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne is officially
on hiatus until the fall, the Mighty Ducks' season pulled from the
playoff lineup by the Detroit Red Wings in a four-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   A broken right foot kept Kariya off the ice on Tuesday. That
left the Ducks with virtually no leg to stand on against the
two-time defending Stanley Cup champions. They did well to keep
their balance for the better part of two periods before the Wings
knocked them out of the Western Conference quarterfinals with a 3-0
win at the Arrowhead Pond.
</P>
<P>
   When the Magic Wingdom show resumes in the fall, the NHL will be
a programming arm of ABC and its cable stepsister, ESPN. This means
you can expect to see quite a lot of the two mightiest Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne and Kariya, like ``Dharma and Greg'' stars Jenna Elfman
and Thomas Gibson, are beholden to the same boss. That would be the
sovereign heads of the vast Disney empire, of which ABC and the
Mighty Ducks are separate _ but synergetic _ nation-states.
</P>
<P>
   The hope throughout the league is the mountain range of hype
that marks the Disney landscape will be a boon for the NHL's
declining television ratings. What would it hurt to have Selanne
and Kariya appear as themselves on ``Sports Night,'' the ABC
sitcom? A little cross-promotion, after all, can go a long way
toward broadening hockey's audience.
</P>
<P>
   The timing is serendipitous, what with the NHL losing its most
recognizable face earlier this month (not that many people seemed
to notice; Wayne Gretzky's final game attracted roughly the same
number of television viewers as the final round of that week's
Senior PGA event).
</P>
<P>
   How to divert eyeballs from the links to the rinks? It won't be
easy, especially now that Gretzky is off to join the celebrity
golfing circuit. To be sure, Gretzky's retirement has created a
black hole as vast as Saskatchewan. The good news is there are a
few stars capable of penetrating The Great One's gravitational
field.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya and Selanne are two of them. Pittsburgh's Jaromir Jagr
and Detroit's Sergei Fedorov _ who collected six points in the
Ducks series _ are two more. Led by NHL commissioner Gary Bettman,
the powers-that-be wisely seem inclined to assemble a constellation
instead of hanging all their hype on a single star, as the NBA did
with the Lakers' Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   It'd be pure folly to force-feed the public one personality when
there's a terrific player for almost every taste. For those
enamored of all skaters North American, there's Kariya, a
contemplative, creative, quick, quiet type.
</P>
<P>
   His sound bytes might not dazzle you, but his game surely will.
The winger, who is of Canadian-Japanese descent, has feet like
Ronaldo, a release like Dan Marino, a work ethic like Michael
Jordan and a decency that calls to mind Tony Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   So what if he guards his privacy as carefully as the late Joe
DiMaggio? The smallish (5-foot-11) forward bares all of himself on
the ice. To wit: He broke his foot in Sunday's Game 3 while
blocking a shot, a dirty little job many a star would be loath to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr and Selanne have the same grit and magnetic auras, too.
Each is equal part sniper and showman. Selanne's 47 goals led all
skaters during the regular season. So did Jagr's 127 points.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne used to race cars in his homeland of Finland during the
offseason; the Pittsburgh Penguins' Jagr, who is from the Czech
Republic, has gone shopping in drag in an effort to avoid
detection. Then there's Fedorov, who is from Russia but looks as
though he came straight out of a Calvin Klein ad.
</P>
<P>
   The first player to get his own signature line of hockey skates,
Fedorov is the crown prince on the nearest thing the NHL has to a
dynasty. Lately he has attracted more attention for the company he
keeps off the ice; his gal pal is tennis vixen Anna Kournikova.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne, Jagr and Fedorov represent the NHL's changing face. In
1979-80, when Gretzky entered the league, only six percent of the
players were from outside North America. Now 24 percent hail from
Europe. It's a global game, even if a myopic American sporting
public is the last to recognize it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
