<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5903 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-ASTROS-HNS     04-28 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds was a one-man wrecking crew Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   He flirted with a no-hitter for 6 innings.
</P>
<P>
   He drove in three runs.
</P>
<P>
   He made a spectacular grab of a line drive that knocked him
backward onto the mound.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he and the Astros knocked out the Arizona
Diamondbacks 11-0 at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds came within seven outs of a no-hitter before allowing a
single to right field by Luis Gonzalez in the seventh inning. He
and reliever Brian Williams combined on a six-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   One batter earlier, Reynolds indicated something special was
possible when he caught a line drive from Matt Williams, igniting a
standing ovation from the crowd of 19,396.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about it,'' said Reynolds, who retired 20 of
the first 22 batters he faced. ``After making that play, I tried to
nit-pick too much to Gonzo. He's a good hitter, and he's swinging a
hot bat right now. I didn't want to walk another guy, so I made too
good of a pitch and he did his job and got a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, a former Astro, lives a couple of blocks from Reynolds
in Sugar Land.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a quality pitcher. He's a legitimate No. 1 (starter),''
said Gonzalez, who was 0-for-2 before extending his hitting streak
to 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   It was 2 hours, 54 minutes of beauty, with Reynolds and the
Astros doing no wrong. The Astros provided their ace with plenty of
support with a season high in runs and also shined defensively.
</P>
<P>
   The 11-run margin of defeat matched the Diamondbacks' worst in
their 13-month history.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' first shutout of the season was a costly one.
Shortstop Ricky Gutierrez suffered a fracture on the back of his
left hand when he was hit by a pitch in the fourth inning. He is
expected to miss four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros provided Reynolds with all the support he would need
during a six-run fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds (4-1), who signed a three-year, $21.5 million contract
extension in January, allowed five hits, walked two and struck out
five in eight innings. He ran his scoreless-innings streak to 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tough to put something together against,'' Arizona
manager Buck Showalter said. ``You give him a cushion, and it
creates a pretty tough night. He's not a secret in anybody's book
that has to face him.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds has won 11 of his past 13 decisions since last Aug. 14.
In his four wins this season, Reynolds has allowed 11 earned runs
and 35 hits while striking out 35 in 34 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought he had a chance (at the no-hitter,'' Astros
manager Larry Dierker said. ``His control was sharp, and he wasn't
throwing anything (hittable) over the plate. He wanted to pitch the
shutout, but he had over 100 pitches (106 total) and was worn
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds credited good location of his fastball, curveball and
split-finger fastball for his success. He rarely was behind in the
count, and he kept the Diamondbacks off-balance with several looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every hitter he threw a different sequence of pitches,''
catcher Tony Eusebio said.
</P>
<P>
   The same cannot be said for Diamondbacks righthander Armando
Reynoso. Whatever he threw, the Astros hit. Nine Houston batters
had at least one hit, with Eusebio going 3-for-4. Craig Biggio,
Derek Bell, Jeff Bagwell and Ken Caminiti _ the top four spots in
the batting order _ went a combined 7-for-17 with six RBIs and five
runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   And the Astros came up with a couple of clutch defensive plays
to preserve first Reynolds' no-hit bid, then the shutout.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Tony Womack sent a grounder up the middle. Biggio
made a backhand snag and threw from the left side of the infield to
make the play. Then with two runners on in the eighth inning, Bell
threw out Kelly Stinnett, who was attempting to score from second
base on a single by Steve Finley.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros went ahead 7-0 after sending 11 batters to the plate
in the fourth inning against Reynoso and reliever John Frascatore.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso held the Astros to one hit and one run over the first
three innings with six strikeouts but quickly ran into trouble.
Caminiti led off the fourth with a single up the middle, and
Richard Hidalgo followed with a double that sailed over the head of
Gonzalez and off the scoreboard in left field. Two batters later,
Eusebio sent a sharp line drive past the pitcher into center field
to score Caminiti.
</P>
<P>
   After Reynoso (1-1) hit Gutierrez to load the bases, Reynolds
helped his cause with a perfectly executed bunt down the third-base
line that scored Hidalgo. Biggio then send a two-run double to
right field to put the Astros ahead 5-0. Bell chased Reynoso with
an RBI single to center field, and the Astros showed no mercy
against Frascatore, who surrendered an RBI single to Bagwell. The
Astros had six of their 14 hits in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Biggio put the Astros ahead 8-0 with a solo home
run to left field.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso, who hadn't pitched since April 18, lost for the first
time in six starts this season. He allowed seven runs and six hits
in 3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros added three more runs in the seventh inning off
Diamondbacks reliever Brian Anderson, the big blow a two-run double
by Reynolds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 0145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5904 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATHEDRAL-GAYS-SFCHRO     04-28 1612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHEDRAL-GAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 A GAY CANTERBURY IN BIBLE BELT  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Like all things Texan, the new $20 million church about
to break ground in Dallas is big, and the congregation building it
is one of the fastest-growing in the country.
</P>
<P>
   What's not so Texan is that this church is lesbian and gay, and
the architecture _ a great slumping, tilting, bending, iceberg-like
mass _ is cutting edge.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as ``the first cathedral of the 21st century'' and
architect Philip Johnson's crowning legacy, the Cathedral of Hope
will be a great gathering point for homosexual Christians _ a kind
of gay Canterbury _ planted in what pastor Michael Piazza calls
``the buckle of the Bible Belt.''
</P>
<P>
   For super-architect Johnson, a gay man who at 92 may be building
the last great project of his career, religion is art. ``I would
work for the devil himself if he came around the right way,''
Johnson said in a phone interview from his New York office.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we architects all like to do is to make beautiful shapes.
It's very hard to make a beautiful shape out of an office building.
But a church is a challenge and a wonderful thing, because you can
create sacred space.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said there is no question that this will be one of his
greatest works ``because of the scale and the purpose. Religion is
the most important thing you can make into architecture. Throughout
history, religion has demanded the greatest work from architects
and sculptors.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Europe's great Gothic cathedrals, the new church is
intended not only to house a congregation that has already outgrown
a large new building finished just six years ago, but to serve as a
spiritual center, a ``psychological cathedral for gays and lesbians
around the world,'' according to church literature.
</P>
<P>
   That a gay cathedral would rise in such unfriendly territory _ a
Southern Baptist culture where homosexuality is an abomination and
political and religious leaders have made a holy crusade of
fighting it _ may seem odd.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's only natural, argues assistant pastor Paul
Tucker, who was raised in Alabama as a fundamentalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us come from very conservative religious backgrounds,
and they're told horrible things about themselves and made to
believe horrible things about themselves, because of who they
are,'' said Tucker, who calls such thinking ``religious abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any heterosexual would say their sexuality is
not a core of who they are _ it's just a basic, deep part of us _
and yet the heterosexual world has said to gay and lesbian people,
this is not a good part of you, and it can't be a part of your
faith, and it can't be a part of a healthy life,'' Tucker says.
``This has just really caused huge, huge damage to gay and lesbian
people, and that's why having a place like this is so important, to
give people a beacon of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Dallas churches, while opposed _ often vehemently _ to
homosexuality, mostly leave the Cathedral of Hope alone. Religion
is highly valued by Dallas culture, almost trumping hostility to
homosexuality. And the Cathedral of Hope baptizes more new
Christians every month than other Baptist churches in Dallas,
Piazza said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So although they really have this issue about being gay as a
sin, they also are glad we're going to church,'' Piazza said.
``It's been at the very least an attitude of tolerance. While they
may disagree with us theologically on the issue of homosexuality,
they appreciate the church and what it does and the fact that it is
a church _ that we really are trying to provide a spiritual home
for people who they don't really want.''
</P>
<P>
   The church's success is unarguable. Dr. Lyle Schaller, one of
the world's leading church consultants, estimates that with a
membership of 2,400, the Cathedral of Hope is now one of the
nation's largest Protestant congregations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is rough, but I would put it in the largest one third of
the largest one percent,'' Schaller said. ``In other words, 99.7
percent of other congregations have fewer people at worship.''
</P>
<P>
   The church, with a congregation of 2,400, has already amassed,
largely from its own ranks, more than $7 million of the $20 million
needed to complete its new building. The groundbreaking for the
bell tower _ which will contain an electronic registry of people
who have died of AIDS _ will begin within weeks. The construction
of the building itself is expected to start sometime next spring
and last until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure it will be a remarkable building, an abstract
behemoth of concrete-on-steel construction that will bend upward in
great curved intersecting planes. The concept is an outgrowth of
Johnson's ``Gatehouse'' at his home in New Canaan, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   When people walk into the new church, Johnson said he wants them
to experience ``a sense of awe, the same thing as I get when I go
into Chartres Cathedral in France.''
</P>
<P>
   The effect will come from a combination of light, shapes and
colors, he said, that is as much sculpture as building. Church
literature calls it ``a new kind of architecture freed from the
constraints of the straight line and rigid adherence to the rules
of gravity.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising drive has gone national with events in New York
and Los Angeles and another planned soon for San Francisco, but
most of the money is coming from local residents in contributions
ranging from a few dollars to $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience for the cathedral is pretty narrow,'' said
development director Randy Spraybary. ``It's people interested in
art or architecture or our cause, so it's more low-key than you
might expect for a nationwide campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``cause'' itself is anything but low-key, however. Pastor
Piazza, a 44-year-old ex-Methodist minister from Georgia, regularly
battles fundamentalist preachers on television, and the church has
just settled a lawsuit with cable superstation WGN in Chicago to
air a half-hour documentary originally titled ``Holy Homosexuals''
after a book Piazza wrote, but has since changed to ``Cathedral of
Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The paid broadcast began airing nationally April 8, after it was
turned down by WGN as well as ABC television, Discovery Channel,
Black Entertainment Television and Odyssey. The church sued, and
WGN settled by agreeing to air the piece.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza also held a rally recently to accuse Texas Governor
George W. Bush, the front-runner for the Republican presidential
nomination, of pandering to religious conservatives by opposing
adoptions by gays and a hate-crimes bill. ``He wants the world to
believe that he is a compassionate conservative,'' Piazza said.
``We want the world to know that his compassion does not extend to
all the citizens of Texas.'' Bush had no comment on the statement.
</P>
<P>
   The church is part of the gay and lesbian Universal Fellowship
of Metropolitan Community Churches, founded in Los Angeles in 1970
by the Rev. Troy Perry, who sought a place for gays excluded from
mainline churches.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas congregation has grown eight-fold in the last decade,
through an energized worship service that Piazza describes as
``enthusiastically liturgical,'' combining the emotionalism and
fervor of evangelism with the intellectualism of mainstream liberal
worship.
</P>
<P>
   The service opens with lively music from a huge choir and small
orchestra. The pastors wear robes and Piazza speaks from a pink
marble altar shaped as a triangle.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lyle Schaller, one of the world's leading church
consultants, described the Cathedral of Hope as offering ``an
exceptionally high-quality ministry that is very comprehensive and
very relevant. I think they have superb preaching, an
extraordinarily high quality and carefully designed worship, a very
sophisticated counseling ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. George Exoo, the so-called Church Man for his critiques
of Protestant services, gave the Cathedral of Hope his highest
five-star rating in a review for the local magazine ``D.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Readers who find my admiration shocking should visit the
place,'' Exoo wrote, calling the service ``exceptional for the
incredible emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza ``deftly balances scholarship and contemporary context,''
Exoo said. ``Here the prayer rail of the Assemblies of God and the
communion rail of High Church Christianity meet. . . . Here I found
worship that wrenches tears from dry eyes (my eyes anyway) and
sends the rush of energy up the spine. This spiritual vibration is
one I can never predict, and no amount of planning can force. It's
worship with a capital `W.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The church performs 75 gay and lesbian commitment ceremonies
each year, offers counseling by 22 professional therapists and two
psychiatrists, and plays host to a variety of support groups
including a choir of men with AIDS called Positive Voices.
</P>
<P>
   Marriages are ``a way for us to say our relationships are good
and our relationships are healthy and they can be as blessed as
anybody's,'' said Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Corbin, a church member with AIDS, described why the church
is so important. After being raised near Dallas by a ``very
religious father'' and growing up ``believing that I should never
have been born,'' Corbin said ``I knew I was different. . . . I
didn't know why, I didn't know what to do about it, and many times
I contemplated suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Corbin said something kept telling him ``to hang on, there's
something for you. And when I found this church, I knew immediately
that's what that voice was telling me 25, 30 years ago. That this
was what I was supposed to wait for . . . to live to experience
this wholeness, after feeling so hopeless.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
