<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS SWEPT ASIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ If the Mighty Ducks were going to be swept, their
coach wanted them to go out fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks made Craig Hartsburg proud as they fought the two-time
Stanley Cup champion Detroit Red Wings to the bitter end in a 3-0
loss before 17,174 at the Pond on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The victory completed a four game sweep of the Ducks, who were
missing one of their stars completely _ Paul Kariya was out with a
broken foot after blocking a shot in Game 3 _ while one (Teemu
Selanne) was simply missing in action.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly 37 minutes of non-stop hitting and skating by both
teams the Red Wings scored on their first power play chance of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   With Marty McInnis in the penalty box for slashing, Jason
Marshall's attempt to clear the zone took a bad bounce off the side
boards at the Anaheim blue line. Matt Cullen couldn't control the
puck and Tomas Holmstrom bullied his way to the slot and chipped a
shot past Guy Hebert on the glove side at 16:44.
</P>
<P>
   The noisy crowd got noisier when it appeared the Ducks had tied
the game 33 seconds into the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall's shot from the right point bounced high in the air
after hitting Detroit goalie Chris Osgood. Moments later the puck
was in the net and the Ducks were celebrating, but it was ruled
that Marty McInnis had tipped the puck in with a stick that was
above the level of the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   That was the Ducks' last glimmer of hope. With Anaheim pressing
to tie the game, Brendan Shanahan scored a breakaway goal with 8:09
left in the game. Slightly more than three minutes later Vyacheslav
Koslov put the game on ice.
</P>
<P>
   With the loss of Kariya and defensemen Ruslan Salei (injured
right shoulder), Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg was forced to
shuffle his lineup. Defenseman Dan Trebil and wingers Johann
Davidsson and Mike Leclerc got their first action of the series and
Tomas Sandstrom replaced Kariya on the No.1 line.
</P>
<P>
   Youngsters Leclerc, Davidsson, Antti Aalto and Jeff Nielsen
along with veteran Ted Drury helped set the tone in the opening
minutes with a tenacious forecheck that kept the Red Wings hemmed
in their zone for most of the opening five minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks outshot the Red Wings 16-14 in the opening period but
failed to convert on their two power play chances. Osgood stopped
Marshall's bid five minutes into the game and barely got a glove on
Kevin Haller's blast from the top of the slot midway through the
period.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks also had a four-shot flurry late in the period, but
once again Osgood turned them back.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end, Hebert was sharp as well, getting his left pad
on a shot by Vyacheslav Kozlov with eight minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks had some chances early in the second period. Sandstrom
was pulled down by Chris Chelios, but once again Anaheim couldn't
convert on the power play. McInnis made a great move to get wide
open in the right circle while the Ducks had the man advantage,
only to miss the net with his slap shot.
</P>
<P>
   Before Holmstrom finally broke through, the Red Wings' Kris
Draper hit the post and Kirk Maltby was denied by Hebert's quick
glove hand directly in front of the net after he intercepted a pass
by Haller.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
