<HEADER>
A5908 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT &LR;      04-28 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES HAMMER YOSHII AND BEAT METS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Masato Yoshii needed to come through with a good
start Tuesday night to silence his critics and solidify his shaky
status in the Mets' rotation. But with a chance to reassure his
teammates and Manager Bobby Valentine, Yoshii could not.
</P>
<P>
   He could not control his pitches or the Padre batters who
alternately watched them sail by as balls or knocked them for
timely hits. He walked five, the most walks he has yielded in 33
major league starts. The Mets lost to the Padres, 6-2, their third
straight defeat, and Yoshii's hold on his place in the rotation
became even more tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   But Valentine said Yoshii would make his next scheduled start.
``This isn't the time to talk about that,'' Valentine said about
shifting Yoshii to the bullpen. But clearly Yoshii is in danger of
being moved aside.
</P>
<P>
   The last two of Yoshii's walks came around to score in the
fifth, a half inning after the Mets had briefly tied the game at
2-2 on Brian McRae's first home run of the year. Yoshii (1-3) had
opened the fifth innocently enough by retiring Reggie Sanders on a
pop-out. But he then walked Tony Gwynn and Wally Joyner on
consecutive 3-1 counts.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bobby Bonilla nor John Franco were in the game. So the
crowd of 25,113 at Shea turned its wrath on the good-natured
Yoshii, who had lost his touch again just as the Mets had gotten
back in the game. Out came Bob Apodaca, the Mets pitching coach. To
no avail, as it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii allowed a single to left to former Met Dave Magadan to
load the bases. And then Greg Myers, who had come on to catch for
the Padres after Jim Leyrtiz had suffered a bone bruise in his left
thumb during a second-inning Yoshii at-bat, rocked a Yoshii
offering over McRae's head in center field.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn and Joyner scored easily. And even though the slow-footed
Magadan was easily nailed at the plate by Rey Ordonez's relay
throw, the Padres were up 4-2 _ and Apodaca was on his way back out
to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   That brought on cheers from the crowd. But as Yoshii walked into
the Mets dugout, all he heard was a nasty chorus of boos. Bonilla
was one of the first to console him. According to Yoshii, Bonilla
said ``There's no way that you're going to get booed more than
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Mike Piazza, in just his second game back from the disabled
list (and obviously still trying to regain his timing) heard it
from some of the fans in the bottom of the fifth, when he popped
out on the first pitch he saw from Andy Ashby with runners on first
and third and one out.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was no question as to whom the fans regarded as the
real villain. But even though Yoshii had come in with a 7.47 ERA
after three starts, Valentine refused to be critical of the
Japanese right-hander.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
