<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5920 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-WEST-HNS &LR;      04-28 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-WEST-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Remember when the Rockets were chasing San Antonio for the third
seed in the Western Conference, Phoenix was a possible lottery team
and Utah was a lock for the Midwest Division title?
<TEXT>
<P>
   That was little more than a week ago. Now, as the clock on the
NBA's microwavable season nears zero, all of the above has changed
and the popcorn is still popping.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs no longer are worried about what is in the rearview
mirror, thanks to a four-game lead over the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix not only has risen to the sixth seed in the West but,
thanks to a swoon by the Los Angeles Lakers, is only two games in
the loss column from catching the Lakers for the fifth seed and a
chance at a first-round matchup with the Rockets. However, LA holds
the tiebreaker over the Suns thanks to a 3-1 edge in the season
series.
</P>
<P>
   And Utah, which has lost four of six, has seen its Midwest
Division lead cut to 1{ games over the Spurs. The Jazz travels to
Texas this weekend to play the Rockets on Friday and San Antonio on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   What does it all mean? Conclusions made just 10 days ago _ when
the Rockets appeared well on their way to tying San Antonio for the
third seed _ might no longer be valid, and that inevitable
first-round clash with Los Angeles is not so certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not mathematically decided yet, so you've always got to
keep your options open,'' coach Rudy Tomjanovich said Tuesday as
the Rockets took a day off following back-to-back games. ``Our
scouting people are putting all the possible opponents in there.
But it sort of looks like it's going to be LA.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I looked at the paper this morning, the first thing I
said was, `It could be Phoenix.'''
</P>
<P>
   Before taking the court April 18 for what proved to be a
demoralizing loss at San Antonio, the Rockets had hopes of claiming
the third seed, which at the time meant opening the postseason
against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days later, those hopes have been dashed after a 2-4
stretch, including losses to two of the league's worst teams _
Dallas and the Los Angeles Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Nos. 1-5 in the West remain the same, but Phoenix (24-21)
has a 1{-game edge on Sacramento (23-23) in the seventh spot.
Minnesota (22-23), which has dropped four in a row, is tied for the
eighth spot with Seattle (22-23).
</P>
<P>
   At least the Rockets (28-17), who have five games left, can
narrow their choices to the Lakers (27-19) and the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like playing a card game,'' Tomjanovich said. ``You
pick up those cards, and that's the hand you're dealt. Our job is
to make sure we've got all the data so we can do our job as a staff
to prepare the team. We've got guys scouting all those teams.''
</P>
<P>
   It might not matter whom the Rockets face if they play the way
they played Monday in a 22-point win over the Lakers. Conversely,
the opponent will be of little importance if the Rockets perform as
they did Sunday in a 24-point loss at Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obvious thing that is most important to us is defense, but
why we don't do it one day and why it's there the next day is a
mystery,'' Tomjanovich. ``I'm sure if people knew what the reason
for that was, they would have a little jar of stuff that you could
take and bring it every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody says the right things, but it's an action, not a
word. You can't talk about it; you have to do it. The thing is, you
can't turn it on and off. That's when you wind up with that boulder
rolling down the mountain and the boulder's too big, you can't hold
it back. We talk about that all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   That matched the Lakers' sentiments following the sound defeat
to the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to realize you can't keep waiting to turn it on,''
Lakers guard Derek Harper said. ``The longer you wait, the harder
it is and the more you start to realize that it may not be a matter
of turning it on, it may not be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles, which has lost six of its last eight, will find out
soon with two of its last four games against Portland. Phoenix has
an easier schedule as it takes on Minnesota twice, Sacramento,
Denver and Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Positioning is not as important as playing better down the
stretch,'' Harper said. ``It doesn't matter who we face; we have a
lot of work to do. It's past the time to panic.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
