<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5931 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-DALY-HNS &LR;      04-28 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DALY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
THE WOODLANDS _ This week, it's the Shell Houston Open.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next week, it will be New Orleans, a town John Daly says he
``used to love for all the wrong reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Every week Daly plays on the PGA Tour, it's a visit to another
city that, during the overlapping good and bad times of years past,
presented him with two terrific opportunities: To win a golf
tournament and to attend the most extreme parties he could find.
</P>
<P>
   When Daly returns to places with so many memories, like this
week at the Tournament Players Course at The Woodlands, he faces
the same challenges on the golf course. But what he contends with
during the rest of his life is so much different.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of finding the nearest open tab, Daly finds the nearest
open slot on the practice range or retreats to his home away from
home to play a little guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how it's going to be pretty much forever,'' Daly said
Tuesday before a practice round at the TPC. ``Everybody says it
gets easier after a while, but I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly celebrates his 33rd birthday today. It's another milepost
on the long and often-bumpy road to sobriety. The drinking binges
that landed him in rehab programs and at the rock bottom of his
profession have been chronicled time and again.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Daly is trying to forge a different life to go along with
his different lifestyle. He does things that in the bad old days
used to take a back seat to cocktail hour.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not easy. Daly never is given the opportunity to forget
where he has been and the difficulty in putting his past behind
him. He gets it from all sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear things _ and a lot of them are not very good
things,'' Daly said. ``Especially from people in the gallery.
They'll say things. But I always ask people what their favorite
food is. If they say steak, I tell them to picture not being able
to eat another steak for the rest of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Daly is up against with alcohol. To borrow a line
from a John Hiatt tune, he couldn't stand up after one, until 20
had him down on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   And now, the first one doesn't get him.
</P>
<P>
   Daly said part of the best therapy for him is talking about his
personal life. That's something he has been cautioned against by
some. But he thinks it is a necessary part of his rehabilitation
from alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to some of the (Alcoholic Anonymous) meetings, and they
always tell me to stop talking to the media about it,'' he said.
``But I don't mind talking about it. Maybe by me talking, it will
help somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I know it helps me to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does Daly cope these days? What has replaced liquor as
the passion in his life?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found more hobbies,'' he said. ``I practice golf a lot
more than I used to. And I've gotten into playing the guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the major thing is I've really gotten involved in my
charity tournament. We do a Make-a-Wish tournament in Memphis. I
spend a lot of time working on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I just try to find as many things as possible to
occupy my time.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that keeps Daly going is he knows a lot of
people are pulling for him. Fans and a lot of members of the media
would like to see Daly put his life and his golf game back
together. He still has problems with both. He constantly battles
his weight and a smoking habit, which is far less impairing but
could be just as damaging in the long run as his past drinking
problems.
</P>
<P>
   He worries just as much about his weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``For fat boys like me, it's always a struggle,'' he said. ``My
weight's up right now, as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   But better his weight be a problem than any distilled products.
And Daly has been lucky to have a strong group of supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very fortunate to have a lot of good people around
me,'' Daly said. ``I've had great support. Even when I'm playing
bad or I feel bad vibes around, people have been great to me and
helped me. And whether I play good or bad, I feel like when I walk
off the golf course I can feel good about myself.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his game, Daly still hits the ball as long as anybody
else. The only question is whether he can find it all the time
after he hits it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year has been kind of the same as the last three years,''
Daly said of his golf game. ``The only thing I've done different is
I've scheduled myself a little better this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually by now, I'm burned out because I've played 12
tournaments or so. But I've tried to schedule a little more time
off this year. I played nine tournaments through the Masters, then
I took the last two weeks off, and I think it's helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly's season has been up and down. His best finish was a tie
for 14th at the Phoenix Open. He also tied for 20th at Tucson and
tied for 21st at the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic. He ranks 103rd on
the money list with just over $146,000.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been no major charges up the leader board. Daly
has missed the cut twice and withdrew from The Players Championship
because of back problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been close,'' he said. ``I've had plenty of opportunities
to get into the top 10. It just hasn't happened yet. One day, I'll
have trouble putting; other days, it's something else. I just
haven't been able to put four good rounds together yet.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes this might be the week he breaks through. Last year,
Daly's best finishes were fourth place at Los Angeles and Honda,
both early-season events.
</P>
<P>
   Daly said the SHO is, for him, one of the tournaments in which
he would love to contend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majors are what we always strive for,'' Daly said. ``I
really believe there are five of them now because The Players
Championship has gotten so big.
</P>
<P>
   ``But every tournament out here, if you have a chance to win,
it's special. I've always loved coming to Houston. I haven't been
back here in a couple of years, but it's one of the places I've
always enjoyed playing on tour. This one is one of those
tournaments that sticks out for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of the times Daly has spent here. But also
because he's looking forward to forging new memories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
