<HEADER>
A5932 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-BALKANS-SFCH     04-28 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BALKANS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CALIFORNIA REPRESENTATIVE FORCES VOTE ON BALKANS  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ A House committee rejected two resolutions Tuesday
by California Republican Tom Campbell that would have called for
the United States to either declare war on Yugoslavia or withdraw
all its forces within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the House International Relations Committee rejected
both resolutions, Campbell will use the mandates of the Vietnam-era
War Powers Act to force a vote on the two measures Wednesday before
the full House, where they are expected to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell himself opposes declaring war on Yugoslavia _ he voted
against his own resolution _ and supports the removal of all U.S.
troops from the Balkan conflict. But he said his foremost concern
is the Constitution, and he was successful in his primary goal of
forcing a reluctant Congress to debate U.S. involvement in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculing as ``sophistry'' the Clinton administration's
insistence that the military engagement in Kosovo is an ``armed
conflict'' but not a war, Campbell said, ``We are at war, and
that's the truth and we ought to admit it and proceed or pull back
our troops.''
</P>
<P>
   The war declaration failed by a 49-to-0 vote, while the panel
rejected the troop withdrawal 30 to 19.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of both parties were crafting alternatives to Campbell's
resolutions Tuesday. The GOP plan would require congressional
approval for the use of ground troops, while the Democratic
proposal would authorize the use of force short of a formal
declaration of war.
</P>
<P>
   The committee debate Tuesday exposed deep fissures within both
parties on the wisdom and strategy of the NATO air campaign against
Yugoslavia. Yet despite grave doubts on both sides, Congress is
loath to do anything that could be seen as undercutting the U.S.
military or the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., said he was ``sorely tempted''
to vote for the war declaration, and he called on the Clinton
administration to immediately request congressional authorization
for the use of military force in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman said the administration and its NATO allies are ``at risk
of repeating in the Balkans the very mistakes we made in Vietnam''
by waging a limited air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman said the administration is attempting an ``in-between
approach'' that says ``we have enough of a national interest to
become involved in an armed conflict with (Yugoslav President
Slobodan) Milosevic but not enough of a national interest to do
what is required to prevail in that conflict. This is a
prescription for defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Republicans, along with many Democrats, argued that a
declaration of war goes too far and would weaken the NATO alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is extremely important not to Americanize this
engagement,'' said Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., a former Hungarian
refugee who supports the NATO action. ``Not one ally has declared
war on Yugoslavia,'' Lantos said.
</P>
<P>
   Lantos drew a sharp distinction between the conflict in Kosovo
and World War II, where the United States sought the unconditional
surrender of Germany and Japan. ``We are engaged militarily with
much more limited objectives,'' said Lantos, adding that NATO is at
war with Milosevic and his army, not with the people of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Lantos also argued that President George Bush, who reluctantly
sought and won the approval of Congress to use force in the Persian
Gulf, did not seek or get a declaration of war when he committed a
half-million troops.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa Republican Jim Leach agreed with Lantos' assessment. A war
declaration would imply ``a much more uncompromising stance to seek
victory at all cost,'' Leach said, and would not only ``Americanize
the conflict further,'' but would signal that the United States
``would stop at nothing less than the conquest of Yugoslavia.''
Such aims, he said, ``are against the interests of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Chabot, R-Ill., said he would support Campbell's war
declaration because he is concerned that NATO is in danger of
becoming ``a police force in Europe,'' and that the United States
rather than Western European is footing most of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   If both of Campbell's measures fail in the House, as expected,
he said he will file suit in federal court arguing that the Clinton
administration is violating the Constitution by engaging in war
without congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said he would be happy to support an alternative like
the Senate resolution passed weeks ago, authorizing U.S. military
engagement in Yugoslavia, or the bipartisan Senate resolution by
Arizona Republican John McCain, to use ``whatever means necessary''
to pursue the war. But the administration refused to offer such a
measure, he said, and he preferred the more constitutionally
clear-cut declaration of war or withdrawal of troops.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1973 War Powers Act, the Senate will be required to
vote on both Campbell resolutions by mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman warned of a ``constitutional crisis'' on May 25 __ 60
days after President Clinton notified the country that bombing of
Yugoslavia had begun. ``On that day,'' Gilman said, ``the Clinton
administration will become the first administration since the War
Powers Resolution was enacted in 1973 to be in plain, undeniable
violation of that law, unless Congress has declared war or enacted
statutory authorization for military operations.''
</P>
<P>
   The law was enacted over President Richard Nixon's veto,
prompted by his decision to bomb Cambodia during the Vietnam war.
Its authors sought to ensure that no future president would ever be
able to commit the United States to war without congressional
approval and, by extension, public support.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, the act has proved toothless, as presidents
of both parties have ignored it during military actions in Grenada,
Panama, Iraq and Somalia, relying instead on their constitutional
authority as commanders in chief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
