<HEADER>
A5933 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     04-28 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IT was in America's heartland, the birthplace of pro football, in a
mammoth old stadium with the wind swirling, the crowd barking and
defeat lurking in the darkness, that John Elway fulfilled his great
promise.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Broncos became AFC champions that day, though not
winners of the Super Bowl for another 11 years. The inhabitants of
the Dawg Pound in the city of Cleveland were left to gnaw once more
on the bones of remorse. And the golden boy became a man.
</P>
<P>
   The mark of a quarterback is not his passing percentage or the
style of his delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Pro football is constructed not on beauty but on toughness of
will and intensity so strong that dreams become reality when they
could as easily have become nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   The mark of a quarterback is what he can do when the situation
is hopeless, his hands are freezing and his uniform is soaked with
grime and sweat and blood.
</P>
<P>
   The mark of a quarterback is to win. Now and forever, John Elway
is truly a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Not just because he finally took his Broncos to the NFL's
equivalent of the peaks of the Rocky Mountains with back-to-back
Super Bowl titles over the past two seasons. But for the way he
brought them back again and again in times when nobody but Elway
ever thought it was possible.
</P>
<P>
   Long before he became a two-time Super Bowl champ, Elway
inspired the kind of legends that Ben Hogan did in golf and Satchel
Paige did in baseball, or the myths that followed Lincoln into
history.
</P>
<P>
   They would tell you of his high school days at Granada Hills in
Los Angeles, when he would stand on the 50-yard line and a teammate
in the end zone would throw a ball up in the air and Elway would
hit it dead center, like shooting a duck from midfield. They told
him to hit his receiver in the numbers once, and he asked, ``Which
one?''
</P>
<P>
   He could write his name with a football, make it sing Dixie or
open a bottle with one at 20 paces. He completed more passes than
the Fifth Fleet on leave. And did it all without a hint of scandal
or controversy or being disliked.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you were a defensive end. ``He stands there and laughs at
you,'' the late Lyle Alzado once said. ``It's like a Tom and Jerry
cartoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Or a Superman comic book, where he always came to save the day.
Elway led the Broncos to fourth-quarter comebacks 47 times in his
career. But none more dramatic and more significant than that
twilight drive into history and into our consciousness, taking them
98 yards in 15 plays in five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   I sat in the frigid, drafty press box that day at legendary
Cleveland Stadium, where Groza kicked, where Feller pitched, where
smash-mouth football was played without any concessions to modern
technology, and marveled at the sight of a cocky prodigy blossoming
into a mature, knowing genius. I can summon up the image in my
mind's eye as easily as the memory of the cold northern Ohio gale.
</P>
<P>
   With his speed and strength, he transformed potential losses
into gains. He won the AFC title, and he put the Broncos on the
track that would eventually, more than a decade later, take them
all the way to the top. Twice in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I thought about before that game was that great
quarterbacks come through in great situations,'' Elway said. ``They
make the big plays in the big games.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, in this age of instant gratification and wretched excess,
there are those who would tug at the sleeve of Elway's No. 7 jersey
in the hope that he would attempt to do it one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Are we never satisfied? Are we so concerned that if the golden
boy with the million-dollar smile retires, then we must be getting
old as well? Or is it just the case of losing too much too soon,
what with 1999 already taking Michael Jordan and Wayne Gretzky from
our live TV screens and relegating them to the videotape archives?
</P>
<P>
   Is this the first true indication that the Y2K bug is for real?
</P>
<P>
   The sports heroes of a generation are disappearing like
fireflies at the sign of the first frost, and the face looking back
at us in the mirror suddenly has tiny wrinkles around the eyes.
Who's next to go _ Kobe Bryant, J.D. Drew and Ricky Williams?
</P>
<P>
   It is always easier to leave one year too late than one year too
soon, and in that regard, too, this decision fits Elway. He rarely
did things the easy way.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, he lost three Super Bowls before grabbing those last
two. He loved for it to be late and tight and tense.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe he could have done it all again. But why?
</P>
<P>
   John Elway proved he was a winner a long time ago, before the
rings, before the glory, in the late gloom of another Cleveland
winter, and leaves us with chills that didn't all come from the
wind off Lake Erie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
