<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOZING ANGELS HAVE NIGHTMARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Angels' performance against the Toronto Blue Jays
on Tuesday night should have been rated R.
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Revolting.
</P>
<P>
   Regretful.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for the Angels, their 10-1 loss before 17,899 at Edison
Field counted for only one loss in the standings. Time will tell if
there is any residual effect.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels made only two physical errors. But the mental errors,
those that are not counted on the scoreboard, were numerous. And
once they got behind early, the offense seemed to disappear. If not
for a home run by Andy Sheets in the eighth, the Angels would have
been shut out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stunk, there's no other way to put it,'' Angels manager
Terry Collins said. ``(Tonight) we will come back and play better,
because if we don't we will find somebody that will. You don't make
those kinds of mistakes and win ballgames. You don't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to pick up the intensity a little bit, and it'll be
picked up tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels right fielder Tim Salmon just shook his head when asked
about the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``No intensity, just nothing,'' Salmon said. ``We couldn't field
it, couldn't hit it, couldn't pitch it. Every aspect of our game
wasn't there tonight. It was pretty embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to come out with intensity. They're a good team. We
got down by four runs (in the first inning), but I don't care.
We've got to keep going out and playing our game. We've been beaten
up, but we haven't given up. But today we fell apart. I hope this
was the first and last time that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   It all started with Angels starting pitcher Omar Olivares, whose
mind seemed to drift in the first inning. With two out and Shawn
Green on first base, Olivares failed to pay much attention to
Green, who stole second base easily.
</P>
<P>
   After walking Carlos Delgado, Olivares drifted off again. Green
and Delgado got such good jumps on an Olivares pitch that catcher
Matt Walbeck didn't even bother to make a throw, as Green and
Delgado stole third and second, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Fernandez followed with a two-run single, then caught
Olivares napping again. As Olivares stared in at the catcher,
Fernandez took off for second. Olivares turned and threw to second,
but neither shortstop Sheets nor second baseman Randy Velarde was
at the bag, and the ball sailed into center field.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez took third and Olivares was charged with the error. In
all, the Blue Jays had four runs, four hits and four stolen bases
in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened, I need an exorcist to find out,''
Olivares explained. ``I did feel weird.''
</P>
<P>
   And it only got worse for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares (2-2) was gone by the time the Angels played like
clowns again in the fifth inning. After a double, Green stole third
on pitcher Mike Magnante. It was Green's third steal of the game,
despite just one steal all season going into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado followed with a grounder to first baseman Darin Erstad,
who caught Green too far off the bag at third and began a rundown.
Third baseman Troy Glaus got the ball and ran Green toward the
plate. Problem was, he never caught up and never threw the ball,
allowing Green to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could do that play all season long and it'll never happen
like that again,'' Magnante said. ``It's over. Forget it. Let's
face it, we embarrassed ourselves. Every single person on this team
knows what we played like and what has to be done to do our job.
It's one thing to get beat, another thing to get beat like that.''
</P>
<P>
   That was enough for many of the fans, who booed, including one
fan who went down to the dugout and berated the Angels players as
they came off the field at the end of the sixth inning. The fan was
cheered as he walked away.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jays starter Pat Hentgen (1-1) threw seven scoreless
innings, allowing only three hits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
