u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-REDSOX-TWINS-BOS &LR;      04-28 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
TWINS BEAT RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-RED SOX-TWINS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ What is it about playing the Red Sox that brings
out the best in the Minnesota Twins?
</P>
<P>
   If you have an answer, mail it to Boston manager Jimy Williams,
who watched in horror as his team surrendered a 4-0 lead Tueday
night and wound up losing to Minnesota again, 6-5, before 10,681
Twins fans who are beginning to appreciate a team that never seems
to give up.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins have won two straight from Boston after losing four in
a row to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played good,'' said Williams, who sees no pressure after
starting the season 10-10. ``We just got beat. We got 142 to go,
including one (today). Let's come out and play our best. Get some
hits and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   For sure, the Sox made the plays and put up five runs on 11
hits. Righthander Mark Portugal pitched three strong innings to
start off, but then things got out of synch. And the Sox generally
will lose when that happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been coming here for a long time and Tom Kelly has always
had a team that never gives up,'' said Mike Stanley. ``He's got to
be some kind of motivator because I've never seen these guys lay
down. They're always trying to do something.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do a lot of things. Little things that produce one run at
a time. A lot of running. Bunting a guy over. Doug Mientkiewicz is
a pretty good hitter. They had him bunting in the eighth inning
when they took the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal didn't lose the game by himself, but a four-run cushion
wasn't enough. The lead had been built in one inning, the second,
on Damon Buford's two-run triple and Darren Lewis's two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal gave up single runs in the fourth and fifth innings and
the Boston bats went cold.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, still holding a 4-2 lead, Portugal gave up a
leadoff home run to Marty Cordova. In came lefty Rheal Cormier, and
two hits and a ground out later, the game was tied at 4-4. The
Twins just didn't quit.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth inning, reliever Jim Corsi set the stage for
disaster by giving up a leadoff single to Ron Coomer, who was
sacrificed to second. Walks to Terry Steinbach (intentionally) and
Chad Allen loaded the bases. Corsi then got the second out of the
inning as pinch hitter Brent Gates grounded into a forceout back to
the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Guthrie replaced Corsi and needed an out to preserve the
tie, but he gave up a two-run single instead to Todd Walker, and
the Red Sox were toast.
</P>
<P>
   A pinch-hit home run by Reggie Jefferson in the ninth wasn't
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Losing is never any fun, but this loss left a particularly
bitter taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't blame anyone,'' said Stanley. ``(Boston pitchers)
have been pretty darn good up until this point. I can't remember
that many leads that we've had after six innings that we lost. We
haven't played consistent baseball on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just came off a huge series (against Cleveland), winning
two of three from probably the best team around at that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing to lose two to these guys. Not to slight
them, but we'd like to have kept the momentum going. Now we're
playing for our lives and hoping not to get swept.''
</P>
<P>
   But the pitchers must take some blame. Three good innings is not
good enough for a starter. And don't underrate the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what team or what hitter you face,'' said
Portugal. ``If you pitch up in the strike zone you're going to get
hit. I got some balls up in the zone and they hit them hard.
Hopefully I won't be doing that next time out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
