u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BKN-CELTICS-PISTONS-BOS &LR;      04-28 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
PISTONS BEAT CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
 BKN-CELTICS-PISTONS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their locker-room door remained closed much longer than usual.
There was a good reason. The Celtics had several issues to discuss
Tuesday night. If you happen to see a Celtic in the next couple
days, try to avoid using the word ``turnover''; it's a sensitive
subject.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing Rick Pitino didn't ask one of his players to
hand him a stat sheet following the team's 92-85 loss to the
Detroit Pistons. That player probably would have turned the paper
over, too, just as the team turned the ball over 25 times at the
FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   The ball wasn't the only thing that was unstable in Celtic
hands. Any lead was kind of slippery as well. Most of the 16,408
fans in the building thought the game was won in the third quarter.
The Celtics led by 16 with 1:07 remaining. They didn't score in the
next 6 minutes 10 seconds. You will not be surprised to learn that
the 16-point lead had been cut to 1, 73-72, before the Celtics
would score again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hadn't turned the ball over so many times, we would have
blown them out,'' said Paul Pierce, who led the Celtics with 21
points.
</P>
<P>
   Well, put it this way: A group of people can watch a movie and
see many different things; so can a group of people watching a
basketball game. Turnovers were a problem. But if you took all of
them away, you still would have had a Pistons team with Grant Hill
and Jerome Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why we turned it over, I think, was Jerome Williams,'' Pitino
said. ``He just pressured the ball and we got careless with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Celtic coach and director of operations M.L. Carr tried
to trade for Williams several times. That's because Williams hunts
for the ball every second he is on the court. He finished with an
incredible 11 offensive rebounds (14 overall), 21 points, and 7
steals. Every time the Pistons missed, there was Williams around
the ball. It drove Pitino nuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took the game away from ourselves,'' Pierce said. ``Too
many turnovers and we let Jerome Williams have too many rebounds. I
mean, Jerome Williams is a good player, but he had a career game
against us and you can't let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Every Celtic who started had at least two turnovers. Ron Mercer
had five of them; Walter McCarty finished with six. McCarty's
turnovers shadowed his 17 points and 11 rebounds. The forward was
talking to someone after the game when he was told that Pitino
wanted to see him in his office. The two men could have talked
about Williams. Or Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we tried to do after we went to Grant was
that we tried to go back to Grant,'' Pistons coach Alvin Gentry
said. ``And then we went back to Grant, they made the adjustment,
and we went to Grant again. And after we went to Grant and they
made another adjustment, we tried to go back to Grant again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill finished with 32 points, 19 in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the smartest coach in the world,'' Gentry said, ``but
I just figured out I can throw it to 33 and he can get something
done.''
</P>
<P>
   After two Hill jump shots and a Lindsey Hunter layup, the score
was tied at 80 with 3:30 remaining. The Celtics knew they were in
trouble then. Not just because they had no one who could stop Hill.
And not because they acted as if the ball was dipped in mud. They
were in trouble because they couldn't score. They shot a chilling
14 percent in the fourth quarter. Their judgment wasn't the best,
either: they attempted a season-high 28 3-pointers and made 10 of
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons, trying to maintain their playoff position, were
fine after that. They scored the next 7 points _ two Hill postups
and a wide-open Jud Buechler three _ to win the game. It was 87-80
with 90 seconds left and fans started to leave. Many were angry.
Some cursed the free throw shooting of Vitaly Potapenko, who missed
five of his six attempts. Others screamed at Pitino, begging him to
send double-teams toward Hill earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It baffles me we came up with the win,'' Hill said. ``It
looked like they were the team in the seventh spot and we were out
of the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the fourth quarter. That's the 12-minute stretch in which
the Celtics reminded you why they will be in Secaucus, N.J., next
month. They left town Tuesday night for Miami, to prepare for a
game against the Heat. You can be sure it wasn't a pleasant flight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
