<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGERS UNLOAD ON HINCLIFFE, MARINERS DON'T HIT BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ This time, Brett Hinchliffe forgot to duck.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the mound for the first time since trading punches
with Anaheim's Todd Greene in a Sunday ESPN-TV game, the Mariners
pitcher took on the Detroit Tigers Tuesday night at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a fair fight.
</P>
<P>
   Hinchliffe got bruised good, serving up home runs to Brad
Ausmus, Karim Garcia and Damion Easley in a 5-1 loss. The rookie
suffered through four innings of blows to his earned run average.
Even worse, no one stepped up to defend him, with Seattle's big
bats falling silent again.
</P>
<P>
   At least only 19,617 were ringside to see it.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariner defeat was the second in two nights in what quickly
has become an uncomfortable homestand and dropped the club to 8-12
overall _ one off last year's pace, when an underachieving Seattle
team finished nine games under .500.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries have been a handy excuse so far this season, but one
now starting to wear thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that's a big factor as to why we're not
functioning as we should,'' Mariners manager Lou Piniella said.
``Every team has injuries and needs to play through them. That's
why you have a 25-man roster.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners shuffled theirs after Tuesday's stumble, announcing
they will activate veteran reliever Mark Leiter from the disabled
list and had purchased shortstop/second baseman Rafael Bournigal
from Class AAA Oklahoma City, the Texas Rangers' top farm team. To
make room, reliever Melvin Bunch and shortstop Giomar Guevara were
sent to AAA Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   Bournigal, who spent last season with the Oakland A's and hit
.225 in 209 at-bats, is considered a better glove man than Domingo
Cedeno, a free agent signee now filling in for the injured Alex
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bournigal?'' said a surprised Cedeno as he dressed in the
subdued Mariners clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Hinchliffe, back in action after being ejected, fined and
suspended three games for his part in the melee in Anaheim, was in
trouble from the outset against the Tigers. Gregg Jeffries lined
the youngster's fifth pitch of the game to left-center for a
single. Fortunately for the Hinchliffe, Jeffries got greedy, tried
for a double and was thrown out by Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie's seventh pitch was rocketed down the third-base line
by Easley for the two-base hit that Jeffries coveted. Tony Clark
walked with two outs. Hinchliffe, however, escaped without damage,
getting Dean Palmer on a fly ball. But that would be the only time.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Ausmus homered to left with two outs in the second.
Garcia socked a three-run homer to right in the third, also with
two gone. Easley finished the long-ball assault with a solo homer
in the fourth, again with two outs. All fastballs. All rookie
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was up with the ball,'' Piniella said of Hinchliffe. ``He's
got to stay down. He doesn't pitch hard enough to stay at the
belt.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinchliffe (0-1) said the layoff didn't bother him. He simply
got careless when he supposedly had the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``All their runs came with two outs,'' the Detroit native said.
``Sometimes you get too relaxed in that situation _ you shouldn't _
and you lose concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Detroit lefty Jason Thompson (3-2) never wavered from
the task at hand. Following Brian Moehler's lead from the night
before, Thompson was in command throughout his six-inning stint,
permitting only Butch Huskey's RBI single in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The Tiger starter was so good, he struck out the side in the
first inning after putting two runners on. He got three infield
popups in the third. He escaped a two-out, base-loaded jam in the
fifth, retiring Jay Buhner on one pitch, a fly ball to left. He had
seven strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's thrown three aces in a row for us,'' Detroit manager
Larry Parrish said. ``He's got great stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Thompson, Mariner hitters were called out on strikes
four times with runners in scoring position, not exactly an
aggressive approach. The manager has noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're struggling with men on base,'' Piniella said.``It's been
our problem. ``We haven't gotten the big hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's time to look back nine days, to Hinchliffe and
Anaheim. At least on that day, the Mariners were throwing punches,
not just standing there and taking them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
