<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS SWEPT ASIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ If the Mighty Ducks were going to be swept, their
coach wanted them to go out fighting. That was the least Craig
Hartsburg expected from his team in Game 4 of the opening-round
playoff series with the Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit did dispose of the Ducks in four games thanks to
Tuesday's 3-0 victory before 17,174 at the Pond, but Hartsburg was
as pleased as a losing coach could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never be happy when your season ends,'' he said. ``But
we played hard and battled and we lost to the team that probably is
going to win the Stanley Cup. They are the best team I've seen
since I started coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks were missing two of their stars _ Paul Kariya was out
with a broken foot and Teemu Selanne was simply missing in action,
recording just one shot on goal. The Ducks battled for nearly 37
minutes, but it wasn't enough to satisfy Anaheim center Steve
Rucchin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard work is one thing, but I don't take any satisfaction out
of it at all,'' he said. ``This series is hard for me to swallow.
I'm not going to say we could have beaten them, but we could have
made it closer.''
</P>
<P>
   What especially disappointed Rucchin was the fact that the Red
Wings scored on their first power play of the night after the Ducks
had squandered three of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a close game, but they obviously know what it takes to
win. We have to learn that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings broke the scoreless tie with Marty McInnis in the
penalty box for slashing. Jason Marshall's attempt to clear the
zone took a bad bounce off the side boards at the Anaheim blue
line. Matt Cullen couldn't control the puck and Tomas Holmstrom
bullied his way into the slot and chipped a shot past Guy Hebert on
the glove side at 16:44.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief moment, it appeared that the Ducks had tied the game
33 seconds into the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall's shot from the right point bounced high in the air
after hitting Detroit goalie Chris Osgood. Moments later, the puck
was in the net and the Ducks were celebrating, but it was ruled
that McInnis tipped the puck in with a stick that was above the
level of the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   That was the Ducks' last glimmer of hope. With Anaheim pressing
to tie the game, Brendan Shanahan scored a breakaway goal with 8:09
left, and just three minutes later Vyacheslav Koslov put the game
on ice.
</P>
<P>
   With the loss of Kariya and defensemen Ruslan Salei (injured
right shoulder), Hartsburg was forced to shuffle his lineup.
Defenseman Dan Trebil and wingers Johann Davidsson and Mike Leclerc
got their first action of the series and Tomas Sandstrom replaced
Kariya on the No.1 line.
</P>
<P>
   Youngsters Leclerc, Davidsson, Antti Aalto and Jeff Nielsen
along with veteran Ted Drury helped set the tone in the opening
minutes with a tenacious forecheck that kept the Red Wings hemmed
in their zone for most of the opening five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks outshot the Red Wings 16-14 in the first but failed to
convert on their two power-play chances. Osgood stopped Marshall's
bid five minutes into the game and barely got a glove on Kevin
Haller's blast from the top of the slot midway through the period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 0242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
