<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING LIKE A RIDE ON THE PAYTON ROLLER COASTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Undoubtedly there are more treacherous jobs than
taking a basketball ride with Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Public-relations person for Big Tobacco, for instance. Wife (or
husband) of Dennis Rodman. Feminist defender of Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Still, attaching one's wagon to Payton's star is not for the
light of weight or the fragile of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence was plentiful in the past couple of Sonic contests.
Since they were both against the venerable Utah Jazz, the measuring
stick had some merit.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday in Salt Lake City, Payton walked straight off the edge of
the Earth _ the place on the map marked ``Thar Be Dragons.'' He was
2-for-11, finished with five points and the Sonics were hatcheted
by the Jazz 98-81 on national TV.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night at KeyArena, Payton returned from the abyss,
became the center of the universe again, potted 30 points, and the
Sonics beat the Jazz wire-to-wire, 90-85.
</P>
<P>
   There was no particular explanation for the discrepancy between
games. Oh, Sonics coach Paul Westphal tried. After Sunday's game,
he said Payton might have been ill. By Monday, when asked by a
reporter how Payton was feeling, Westphal had blanked on his little
fib.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game yesterday, Westphal was back on more familiar
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just didn't have it,'' he said. ``That happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Westphal, the mysterious vaporization doesn't
happen often. When it does, Payton tends to respond as he did
Tuesday, redeeming himself with various growls, sneers, scoops and
whoops.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot was upset, at least as far as playoff rankings _ No.
9 beat No. 1. Moreover, it added up to a split of the four-game
season series with the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Add that to the 2-1 series advantage the Sonics hold over the
Lakers as well as the Trail Blazers, whom they meet in Portland
Wednesday night, and the thoughts of Karl Malone sounded less like
the
</P>
<P>
   &UR; rr &LR; usual false flattery from the vanquished locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe there's four or five teams in the league that
are much better than their records,'' said Malone, who went for 29
points and 13 rebounds. ``The Sonics are one of them. You look at
them and say, `How'd they get that (22-23) record?'''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night certainly was one of those looks _ for the first
16 minutes. The Sonics were up 35-11 and on their way to the
series' fourth rout in four games, further testimony to the
deleterious effects of a compressed schedule that would not be
permitted upon the sled dogs of the Iditarod.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, the Jazz galumphed back into the contest. They did
the two things they always do when the night becomes what amounts
to a Payton bungee jump _ they tried to get under his skin and in
his face.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' monumental lead began to come apart late in the
second quarter when the Jazz banged Payton in the head and eye,
provoking the usual smoldering retaliatory recklessness. Payton
picked up his NBA-leading 20th technical foul, plus a flagrant foul
against his chief tormentor, John Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   As the lead dissipated under a 24-8 run, Westphal benched Payton
for the half's final minute, and received an earful similar to what
Payton was dishing to the Jazz and the officials. He was
approaching a personal record for words per minute, which might
have been the evening's most notable historic moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him don't let Stockton get under your skin,'' Westphal
said. ``It's the only thing he can do. He can't guard you.''
</P>
<P>
   A calmer Payton came out in the third quarter and lit up the
Jazz for 11 points. But this time the Jazz were throwing
double-teams at him 25 feet from the hoop. It didn't stop Payton as
much as it slowed the rest of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually their third game in three nights prevailed upon
the Jazz and they sputtered down the stretch while Payton got his
groove back.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, Payton was cavalierly dismissive of his Sunday
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ain't you used to me having a bad game?'' he asked of his
questioners. ``I did all the other things. When I focus on scoring
25 points a game, I shouldn't be on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as the season edges nearer the brink, every Payton slip
or spectacle gets magnified. The burdens and resentments he has
carried because of the first poor season in his Sonic tenure have
bubbled tensely. A national magazine recently reported that Payton
was plotting a ``Paul or me'' ultimatum after the end of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   That's the sort of thing that leads to speculation that perhaps
Payton took a game off Sunday just to underscore his value,
particularly in contrast with Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal wasn't buying any hidden agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's sending a message, you have to know what the message
is,'' said Westphal, claiming ignorance. ``Sometimes, guys just
have bad games.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's no fun for conspiracy theorists.
</P>
<P>
   But as entertainment, the Payton Thrill Ride, while hardly
championship caliber, just might be able to extend its stay one
week longer into May.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 0245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 02:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
