</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS HOLD OFF JAZZ TO STRENGTHEN PLAYOFF POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Their start was super. Conversely, their finish was
even more surreal.
</P>
<P>
   But style points count for nothing as far as the Sonics are
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   So what if they blew a 24-point lead in the first half. Never
mind that the Utah Jazz had a chance to force overtime in the
closing moments Tuesday night at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   All that matters is the Sonics eventually drowned the Jazz 90-85
in the first of what amounts to be a six-game season for the
Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly for the Sonics, they drew even with idle
Minnesota for the eighth and final seed in the Western Conference
playoff standings. They are also a half-game behind seventh-seeded
Sacramento, which beat San Antonio Tuesday at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything can happen,'' said Sonics guard Gary Payton, who
scored a game-high 30 points and dished out eight assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we just have to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as quickly, the Sonics must forget about having avoided one
of their biggest losses this season with a huge win. The Sonics
left immediately after Tuesday night's game for Portland, where
they play the Pacific Division champion Trail Blazers Wednesday in
the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have to come back (today) and win another one, or
(beating Utah) means nothing,'' said forward Detlef Schrempf, who
scored four of his 18 points from the free-throw line to hold off
Utah during the final 15 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're to the point where every game is do or die,'' Schrempf
added.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night turned out to be a microcosm of the Sonics'
season.
</P>
<P>
   Their 37-13 lead in the second quarter was a high note. The
bottom fell out in the fourth. Then, the Sonics somehow managed to
land on their feet.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle clung to an 86-83 lead with 21 seconds remaining. Utah
fouled Dale Ellis, who could have sealed the victory. But Ellis
missed both free throws and Karl Malone rebounded the second miss
with 19 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Bryon Russell then sank a pair of free throws that made the
score 86-85. Schrempf, though, followed that with two free throws
that put the Sonics in front, 88-85.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics escaped moments later when Schrempf rebounded John
Stockton's game-tying 3-point attempt, then made two more free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are all playoff games now,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal
said. ``We have confidence we can beat these good teams. We've been
doing it regularly enough this year, and this team still has
something left in it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a much different showing by the Sonics, who were blown
out 98-81 last Sunday in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Payton rebounded the best. He made 10 of 20 shots after a
2-for-11, five-point outing at Utah. Payton negated Malone's 29
points for the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're fighting for their playoff lives,'' Malone said.
``They came out real aggressive tonight and you have to give them
credit for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite wilting during Utah's comeback attempt, the Sonics set
the tone early. They matched Utah's rough and physical play from
the start.
</P>
<P>
   They rode an aggressive start by Payton to an 18-8 lead midway
through the opening quarter. The Sonics ended the period with a
10-2 run that put them ahead 29-10.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fewest points scored in a quarter by a Sonic opponent
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out pumped,'' center Olden Polynice said. ``We were
very physical and our defensive matchups were a little different.
It threw them off a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' rigid defense and higher energy level kept Utah from
doing much of anything right in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Then, tempers flared late in the second quarter when Malone,
Payton and Stockton got ornery.
</P>
<P>
   It all boiled over when Payton receive his league-leading 20th
technical foul with 2:47 left in the half after giving referee
James Capers an earful.
</P>
<P>
   And he wasn't done.
</P>
<P>
   Payton then walked toward Malone and challenged him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to split my face open,'' yelled Payton, who
was referring to an incident that involved Malone on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix's Joe Kleine needed 30 stitches and plastic surgery
after Malone's elbow resulted in a broken nose and split lip during
Utah's loss.
</P>
<P>
   Of Stockton, Payton said: ``I'm not going to back down from him.
If he hits me I'm going to hit him back. I don't care what the
officials say.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton, who had 14 points at the time, was called for an
offensive foul on the Sonics' next possession. Payton then picked
up a flagrant foul after he intentionally shoved Stockton to the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   The extracurricular activity changed the tone of the game.
</P>
<P>
   When Westphal sent Payton to the bench to cool off, Utah went on
a run. Malone scored on three straight possessions in the final
1:38 of the period. The Jazz cut the Sonics' lead to 45-35 at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics led 67-54 after the third. They actually held an
84-74 advantage with 1:56 left in the fourth before holding on for
the win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
