<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 03:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5958 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAINKILLER-DOCTOR-SFC     04-28 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAINKILLER-DOCTOR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DOCTOR, 2 DRUGGISTS ACCUSED IN 9 DEATHS  &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  REDDING, Calif. _ Prosecutors are accusing a Shasta County
physician and two pharmacy owners of causing at least nine deaths
in what they call a drug-selling scheme designed to defraud the
state Medi-Cal insurance system.
<P>
   Dr. Frank B. Fisher and his two co-defendants, Redding pharmacy
owners Stephen and Madeline Miller, have been charged with murder
in connection with three of the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   More charges have not been ruled out, however, in the most
dramatic confrontation in recent memory between law enforcement and
a physician involving the use of narcotics for control of chronic
pain.
</P>
<P>
   State prosecutors linked the defendants to the six additional
fatalities Tuesday as a preliminary hearing into the criminal
charges began in Shasta County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's walk-in clinic in the town of Anderson and the Miller
pharmacy in Redding have been shut down since their arrests in
February. All three defendants are being held in County Jail in
Redding.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary hearing is expected to continue for at least
three weeks. During opening statements Tuesday, Deputy Attorney
General Gary Binkerd likened the defendants to common ``street
pushers'' whose sole interest was to pump out ``staggering
quantities'' of pain drugs most patients didn't need.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the three alleged murders, evidence will show ``no less
than six additional deaths are attributable to this scheme,''
Binkerd said. He added that records indicate Fisher became the
largest prescriber in the state of one opiate drug, a slow-release
form of morphine called OxyContin, and that his drug orders
accounted for 46 percent of all the OxyContin prescribed in
California.
</P>
<P>
   However, Fisher's defense team believes that it has some strong
arguments, particularly in connection with the murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   Forensic reports and other court documents raise questions about
just what caused many of the deaths deemed suspicious. One victim
may have died after a vehicle accident, for example, and another is
said to have succumbed to natural causes.
</P>
<P>
   Medical experts say there is no set upper limit on dosages of
opiate painkillers, whose most dangerous side effects tend to
diminish as patients grow tolerant of the medications.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Hallinan, a prominent San Francisco attorney who is
representing Fisher, called the murder allegations ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Five of the nine alleged victims, Hallinan said, were not even
Fisher's patients but instead were getting drugs from acquaintances
or from street sources when they died.
</P>
<P>
   Hallinan's involvement in the case has already raised its
profile beyond the Redding area.
</P>
<P>
   He showed up in court Tuesday along with a nationally known pain
specialist, Virginia physician William Hurwitz, who is serving as a
technical adviser for the defense. Hurwitz sat in the front row of
a small courtroom packed with Fisher's former patients and
supporters, some of whom have begun circulating a newsletter and
selling T-shirts to support his defense.
</P>
<P>
   Legal and medical experts have been unable to find any prior
instance in which a doctor has faced multiple murder charges under
similar circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Hurwitz, for example, temporarily lost his right to practice
medicine in 1996 after being accused of over-prescribing pain
medications. He won reinstatement in 1997 amid a spate of national
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts fear the Fisher case may make it more difficult for
chronic pain sufferers to find doctors willing to treat them,
considering the stigma attached to narcotics use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any such kind of criminal prosecution has a chilling effect,''
said Ben Moulton, executive director of the American Society of
Law, Medicine and Ethics in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony began Tuesday with Dr. Ann Murphy, medical director of
Shasta Community Health Center, a nonprofit hospital that began
seeing many of Fisher's patients after he was jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said that after examining Fisher's patients, she
concluded that he was operating far beyond the bounds of sound
medical practice. Patients were ``set up for a fall,'' she said, by
his prescribing ``too much medicine, too freely, in a reckless
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallinan's pointed cross-examination suggested that such
judgments may be open to debate, and Murphy conceded that she has
had no recent formal training in the proper use of pain
medications. She testified that patients, under California law, are
entitled to get whatever level of drugs they need to alleviate the
pain, although ``not if it kills them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
