<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6161 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN29-CO     04-28 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OK, kids, you have our attention
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I am still scared.
</P>
<P>
   I should feel some relief that the siege at Columbine High
School is over. The two members of the black-clad ``Trenchcoat
Mafia,'' Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, are no longer a
threat. They killed themselves, ending a Hitler birthday
celebration that slaughtered 12 other students and one teacher and
left 16 students injured. A girl who was in the school library when
the student-terrorists attacked managed to survive by begging one
of the killers to spare her life. Such humane response was
transitory. The killers, self-acknowledged outsiders, immediately
turned from her and shot popular student Isaiah Sholes, 18, in the
face. Several students said the killers laughed as they went about
their bloody work, loudly proclaiming intent to kill people of
color and athletes. The arsenal of explosives and weapons the
killers stockpiled was transported to the suburban Denver school in
student backpacks. Police more than 30 explosives, many with
elaborate timers. One is in awe at the intelligence necessary to
research and create such instruments of death. How I wish the two
youngsters had invested their talents in school science projects
designed to improve lives rather than destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   The final solution to whatever Angst, anger or rejection the
gang members felt was as cold and as calculated as that of their
spiritual mentor, Hitler. So I am scared, really scared, that
though two perpetrators of this unconscionable violence are dead,
the forces that created them are still with us. Today's children,
in growing numbers, are experiencing a numbing of the sensibilities
that make one human. The resultant product is killers without
consciences, many of whom revel in the only power they perceive
they own _ the power to destroy. They willingly commit violence
without thought of consequences, not even at the cost of their own
lives. Such youngsters are to be feared; people who do not value
their own lives cannot value the lives of others. How adults can
move from fear of our youths to restoration of nurturing control is
our challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Already, learned professors are proffering theories about this
latest atrocity. The most seductive explanations absolve the public
at large, focusing more on parents too permissive or strict,
inattentive or overindulgent.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent other causes identified include the availability of
guns and other weaponry, providing youths opportunities to act on
motives that otherwise might dissipate. Also, that amorphous
culprit, the media _ not advertisers or consumers _ is being blamed
for desensitizing children to violence. And depersonalized, but
cost-effective, gigantic warehouse schools are said to deny
children an identity within any group at a time when they
desperately need to develop a sense of self-worth.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, some analysts hypothesize the most patent of all
rationales: Children who kill are mentally ill. Therefore, we need
more money for psychiatrists, school counselors and
behavior-altering drugs. Once the current hysteria is diffused,
however, none of these conclusions is likely to inspire specific
action beyond installation of more electronic barriers and monitors
to shore up school security plans. The evil blooms of violence will
be cut, the roots stunted, but they are destined to grow and menace
us again.
</P>
<P>
   Springfield, Ore. Jonesboro, Ark. Pearl, Miss. Now Littleton has
shown us that we can't find a hiding place sufficiently removed
from mainstream violent culture to protect children. So we must act
collectively, without partisanship of any kind, to create an
environment that can save all of them. We adults must communicate
to our children in words and action that we believe in moral
limits.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I'm so scared. I fear we're incapable of that kind of
selflessness until after children kill to get our attention _ if
then.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
