A6162 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELSO-COLUMN29-COX     04-28 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bagpiper blows sour
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Andrew Mackay must have a large knot in his kilt
located about where he sits down.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a guy who writes a travel piece for the Glasgow
(Scotland) Sunday Herald taking cheap shots at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   And he comes from a country where the people eat sheep guts on
purpose? Haggis, a traditional Scottish dish, is a mixture of
oatmeal and sheep innards.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew, here in Texas we are smart enough to throw that part of
the sheep away.
</P>
<P>
   In an April 4 article about his visit to Austin, Mackay hurled
several nonsensical barbs at my fair city.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew, what's this business about the Continental Club on South
Congress Avenue being ``a country and western club and gun shop''?
Is that your attempt to make Texans sound like a bunch of
gun-toting nutbags?
</P>
<P>
   If you had gotten out of your room at the Austin Motel and
crossed the street to the Continental, which you say you did, you
would have known the Continental and Just Guns, a couple of doors
down, are two different businesses. So blow it out your bagpipe,
laddie.
</P>
<P>
   In his article, Mackay referred to the Lone Star State as ``a k
a 268,600 square miles of scrub and cow country near Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   I guess the guy didn't make it to Barton Springs Pool, or the
Hill Country, or maybe even outdoors. Maybe he spent all of his
time here at Capital City Tattoo on Sixth Street, having ``Robert
Burns'' etched on his butt.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of cows, at least ours are not crazy and taking
Prozac, Andrew. I didn't realize mad cow disease was transmittable
to humans until I read your screwball ramblings, pal.
</P>
<P>
   But the capper was when Andrew wrote that the best thing he did
in Austin was ``get on a plane to Albuquerque.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll give you that one, buster, as long as you promise not to
show your Scots derriere around these parts again.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew's piece chapped Austinite Diane Holland, who is living in
Bearsden, Scotland, with her husband, Rick, a Motorola engineer.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it chapped her so much that on Tuesday she called me
from Scotland to report that country has a few of its own flaws.
</P>
<P>
   The food in Scotland is scary, Diane said, particularly the
haggis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, well, maybe it was just a delicacy here and nobody
still eats it here, but they do,'' Diane said. ``But it's real
greasy and real disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but could you use it to patch holes in plaster? ``There's
enough grease in there that when it dries, it would stick
forever,'' Diane said.
</P>
<P>
   The people are clannish. ``Glasgow looks down on Edinburgh, and
Edinburgh thinks Glasgow is dirty and nasty,'' Diane said. And
they're probably both right.
</P>
<P>
   The service industries are unreliable about showing up to fix
stuff. If you call a plumber, ``they just never come,'' Diane said.
``You've got a 50-50 chance of seeing them.''
</P>
<P>
   You can't get Mexican food. Diane says they couldn't get cable
TV so they had to get a satellite dish. The homes are so old that
there's sediment in the bath water.
</P>
<P>
   But what can you expect from a place where the people used to
paint themselves blue for battle and mooned their enemies?
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6163 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN29-COX     04-28 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The good among the bad
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It was hard for Karen Weyhrich to know what to
say, what to do. She never faced anything like it, never dreamed of
anything like it at her high school in the late '60s. ``The thing
we were most afraid of was getting caught smoking a cigarette,''
she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   She camped out at her church, St. Frances Cabrini in Littleton,
Colo., down the street from Columbine High School, comforting
hundreds of survivors. The church lost four students from its youth
group; two others were injured. Teens are telling stories like
this:
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen approached students and asked, ``Do you believe in
God?'' _ shooting them if they said yes.
</P>
<P>
   Valeen Schnurr, a member of the youth group, said yes. ``She was
sprayed nine times with shrapnel,'' Weyhrich said. ``Not a living
organ was touched, and she's coming home soon. She's in her
hospital room proclaiming her love for God and reaching out to
others, feeling concerned for her classmates who died and their
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a living martyr.''
</P>
<P>
   In the news, Weyhrich said, we hear only about the gore. The
evil. The kids gone bad.
</P>
<P>
   She's seeing something else, something the news cameras don't
find as compelling. ``These kids believe in the Lord, and they're
teaching their parents to love the Lord. They want their school
back and they want to go back soon. And when they go, they want to
take the Lord back with them.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a time of anguish, but also a time of spiritual
courage and renewal. ``It has been horrible here,'' Weyhrich said.
``We're going to feel this forever; we'll never be the same.'' Yet
she has also seen parents and children ``hugging and crying and
praying like never before.'' Support and prayers have poured in
from all over the country, all over the world. A spontaneous prayer
service Wednesday night drew 800 people, so many they had to set up
folding chairs in the gym.
</P>
<P>
   Weyhrich lives in nearby Englewood, Colo. She found herself in
the Denver suburb after her husband, Bill, was transferred to the
region by his employer, Borden Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Weyhrich was volunteering at the church when word came about the
shootings. Her own children, Peter and Abby, attend Arapahoe High
School in Littleton. ``There are ladies who work here who have
children in the school. You can imagine the terror, not knowing
what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Weyhrich's children are afraid. ``We've talked about the copycat
thing,'' she said. She can't promise Abby and Peter _ or the
Columbine High School survivors _ their lives will never be touched
by violence. ``We can only promise them love, and faith,'' she
said. ``That's why we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids will walk back into that school,'' she vowed. ``The
killers and the violence will not win.''
</P>
<P>
   After the innocence of her youth in Dayton, Weyhrich can't
imagine what these kids are going through: ``They stared death in
the face, and waited for four hours to escape.'' And came out
affirming their faith, sharing it with their parents.
</P>
<P>
   After a week in which the nation has talked of little else but
youth alienation, with what has gone terribly, horribly wrong with
some of them, what a profound testament to what is right with so
many.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: marymccarty(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
