EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, April 28, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Thursday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-CLUSTER (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Armed with a
public-records request, an anti-nuclear group recently began
sifting through dozens of file cabinets in the state Department of
Health Services. What they found has opened up a fissure between
the Legislature and California health officials, who are being
accused of conspiring with corporate interests and withholding
crucial health information from the public. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-CARTS (San Francisco) _ The San Francisco Shopping Cart
Task Force has moved to make it tougher for the homeless to have
shopping carts, urging the city's Board of Supervisors to require
businesses to prevent cart theft. By GREGORY LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   FUGITIVE-ARREST (San Francisco) _ Nearly 20 years after a daring
escape from San Quentin prison in a makeshift kayak, a 78-year-old
bank robber was back in custody after allegedly robbing a bank in
Florida. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-ABORTION (San Antonio) _ The clay angel Victoria
Hinojosa molded is a ``memorial'' to Isabella. A basket cradling
doves inside a Christmas tree bulb is in honor of Michael. She
named her children, even though she's never seen them or had any
proof of their gender. Through Project Rachel, Hinojosa is able
reconcile with herself and forgive those involved in the abortions
of the children. By SUZANNE HOHOLIK. (Photo availabe of Wieck
database.)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-NEWS (San Francisco) _ Television news just can't multitask.
It knows how to hover over a story like a single-minded bird of
prey. It can swarm over Los Angeles looking for O.J., but only
until Jon Benet Ramsey comes along, or Monica Lewinsky. Then it
skitters off and drops a net on something else. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ One guy on the Web is calling it
``Geek Profiling,'' and I guess I partly fit the profile, or at
least did in high school. A group called the National School Safety
Center has issued a checklist of danger signs to watch for in kids.
These include mood swings, a fondness for violent TV or video
games, cursing, depression, and antisocial behavior and attitudes.
That's most kids I've ever known. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   TEMP-WORKERS (San Francisco) _ I wanted to work as a temp
because I was interested in observing the ways people behave in a
corporate environment. Temping has a long and honorable history,
which lasts just over 15 minutes. That's the amount of time it
takes a temp to discover that, in terms of office status, he or she
ranks just below the fax machine and right above the spittoon. By
DAVE FORD.
</P>
