<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS29-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is the identity of the pilot of the Stealth fighter that
went down in Yugoslavia not being released? I've heard he wasn't an
American.
</P>
<P>
   A: A NATO representative in Brussels, Belgium, told Q&AMP;A that
details about missions are never made public. But the Pentagon was
somewhat more forthcoming. The reason the pilot's identity wasn't
made public is a simple one, said Defense Department spokesman
Bryan Whitman: He asked not to be identified. In interviews with
the media, pilots often give only their first names to protect
their privacy and that of their family.
</P>
<P>
   When photos of the Stealth's wreckage were published, a person's
name was clearly visible painted on the aircraft, but that wasn't
this pilot's name. There are far more pilots and crew members than
there are aircraft, Whitman explained. The pilot, by the way, was
an American flying from Aviano Air Base in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My husband and I have planned a vacation in Jamaica in the
very near future. Given the political unrest there, how can we
obtain information to decide if there are tourist safety concerns?
</P>
<P>
   A: The State Department hasn't issued any sort of warning or
advisory against travel to Jamaica, so you'll have to use your own
judgment. Recent rioting sparked by gasoline price increases left
nine people dead and businesses gutted by looters, but the unrest
wasn't directed toward tourists. For updates as they occur, call
the State Department's Citizens Emergency Center hotline,
202-647-5225. The Jamaican government, meanwhile, is launching an
advertising blitz and is organizing a ``massive fly-in'' of travel
agents in an attempt to entice tourists to continue visiting the
island.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently described Sandy Berger's background before he
became national security adviser for the United States. I've heard
that he once was a lobbyist for the Chinese. Can you confirm?
</P>
<P>
   A: That appears to be so. Before he joined the Clinton
administration, Berger was on the staff of Hogan &AMP; Hartson, a
Washington law firm. In a Washington Post article in January 1997,
Berger was described by Rep. Nancy Pelosi (D-Calif.) as the ``point
person'' at the firm for the trade office of the Chinese
government. ``He was a lawyer-lobbyist,'' Pelosi said of Berger. In
the article, Pelosi decried what she called the revolving door by
which lobbyists become administration policymakers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where does the term ``flea market'' come from?
</P>
<P>
   A: Two sources have differing explanations, so take your pick:
(1) From Morris Dictionary of Word and Phrase Origins: Open-air or
street markets have so many secondhand articles of all kinds for
sale that they're believed to gather fleas. (2) From The Facts on
File Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase Origins: In Dutch Colonial
days, there was a market in downtown Manhattan known as Vallie
Market, at the valley (or foot) of Maiden Lane. It came to be
abbreviated as Vlie Market, and this soon was prounounced ``flea
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Despite many months on the job, White House press secretary
Joe Lockhart still appears to me to be uncomfortable and often
inarticulate when addressing the Washington press corps. What is
his background?
</P>
<P>
   A: Lockhart, who succeeded Mike McCurry, has an extensive
background in broadcasting and political campaigns. Before joining
the White House in 1997, Lockhart was national press secretary for
the Clinton-Gore 1996 re-election campaign, and previously he was a
senior vice president of Robinson Lerer Sawyer Miller, where he
brought ``an international media and U.S. political background to
the management of sensitive communications issues,'' in the words
of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   His political experience includes working with all three losing
Democratic presidential campaigns in the 1980s, for Jimmy Carter,
Walter Mondale and Michael Dukakis. His broadcast journalism
experience includes serving as foreign producer for SKY Television
News (London), Europe's first 24-hour television direct broadcast
news service. He also was deputy assignment manager for CNN, and
before that he was an assignment editor for ABC News. At the 1980
Democratic National Convention, he also covered the Pennsylvania
delegation for NBC News.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm interested in supporting the presidential candidacy of
Bill Bradley, but I can't find out how to contact his campaign
organization. I read Q&AMP;A in Stars and Stripes, so can you assist me
with this information?
</P>
<P>
   A: Glad to help. The address: Bill Bradley for President, 395
Pleasant Valley Way, West Orange, NJ 07052 (or call the U.S.
numbers 1-888-643-9799 or 973-731-2100). You also can sign up to
support his candidacy at his Web site:
www.billbradley.com/main/home.htm
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'd like to plan my summer vacation to include a performance
by the Air Force Thunderbirds. When and where can I see them?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Air Force Air Demonstration Squadron, the Thunderbirds,
will be appearing widely. These are some of this year's dates and
locations:
</P>
<P>
   May: 1, Shell Air and Sea Show, Fort Lauderdale, Fla.; 9,
Mountain Home Air Force Base Air Show, Mountain Home, Idaho; 12,
Hill AFB Air Show (near Ogden), Utah; 14, Joint Services Open
House, Andrews AFB, Md. (near Washington, D.C.).
</P>
<P>
   June: 5, Airfest '99, Mankato, Minn.; 16, McConnell AFB Air
Show, Wichita, Kan.; 19, Hamilton International Air Show, Hamilton,
Ontario; 26, McChord AFB Air Show (near Tacoma), Wash.; 27, Travis
AFB Air Show (Fairfield, 150 miles northeast of San Francisco),
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   July: 3, The Team U.S. National Hot Air Balloon Championship and
Air Show, Battle Creek, Mich.; 10, Thunder Over Niagara, Niagara
Falls, N.Y.; 17, Prairie Air Show 1999, Bloomington, Ill.; 24, U.S.
Air and Trade Show, Dayton, Ohio; 31, Armed Forces Air Show, Avoca,
Pa.
</P>
<P>
   August: 14, Whiteman AFB Air Show, Knob Noster, Mo.; 21, Chicago
Air and Water Show, Chicago; 28, Great New England Air Show,
Westover AFB (35 miles north of Windsor Locks, Conn.), Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Before planning a trip, check first for possible changes: USAF
Thunderbirds, 4445 Tyndall Ave., Nellis AFB, NV 89891
(702-652-9945).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since China uses a different calendar year from the rest of
the world, how is it coping with the Y2K problem?
</P>
<P>
   A: Under the Chinese calendar, the Year 2000 milestone came and
went millennia ago. But that has nothing to do with how it will
deal with the Y2K bug, because the calendar based on Jesus' birth _
even though most scholars agree he likely was born between 3 and 5
B.C. _ is common internationally in a technological age in which
the world needs a standard.
</P>
<P>
   So China's computer problem also will show up at midnight Dec.
31. The problem, in fact, will be uniquely difficult among the
world's countries because more than 90 percent of the software used
in China is pirated. This means technicians can't call in
manufacturers for help, or receive software updates on tackling the
situation. On top of that, the Chinese computer system includes
equipment and software from almost ever hardware- and
software-producing country in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The only positive in all this is that China, as a developing
country, has a lower reliance on computers in daily life. Seventy
percent of China's population is rural, and more than 100 million
people aren't connected to the electricity grid.
</P>
<P>
   (End Take 1 of 2 takes.)
</P>
