<HEADER>
A6170 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS29-TAKE     04-28 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS29-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 2)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I've always heard that merchants cannot impose a minimum if a
person wants to use a Visa credit card to charge the product. Is
that true?
</P>
<P>
   A: Go ahead and charge that 25-cent candy bar if you want to.
Visa says merchants ``absolutely'' are not permitted to establish
minimum (or maximum) transaction amounts. All merchants are
expected to follow Visa's regulations on this subject, and the
regulations are enforced through Visa member financial
institutions. If you're having a problem with a merchant who won't
allow you to charge an inexpensive item, Visa advises checking with
the financial institution that issued your Visa card. Its telephone
number is on your Visa statement and probably on the back of your
card. Each institution knows the regulations and can file a
complaint regarding the merchant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more than 4 million merchants worldwide who accept
our card,'' said Visa publicist Debbie Bromowitz in San Francisco.
``We depend on our customers to be our eyes and ears in monitoring
their acceptance of the terms.'' Q: Two inmates who served 12 years
in prison on a murder conviction were released recently after a
judge dismissed charges against them. DNA tests from the crime
scene didn't match either man. What kind of compensation are they
being given?
</P>
<P>
   A: None, at least for the time being. Only two states, New York
and Illinois, have laws compensating those incarcerated wrongfully.
Dennis Fritz, 49, and Ron Williamson, 46, who were released April
15, were tried, convicted and imprisoned in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for both men have called for legislation to compensate
people wrongfully incarcerated for years. ``These men deserve
compensation,'' said Barry Scheck, Williamson's attorney, in an
interview with The Oklahoman. Scheck, a member of the Innocence
Project, which has handled 41 cases nationwide in which DNA testing
has exonerated defendants, said awards in New York and Illinois
have amounted to $65,000 to $100,000 a year for the time people had
been incarcerated.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Fritz said he was leaving Oklahoma because he
was ``very distrustful of the legal system'' there. He said he
planned to live with his mother in Kansas City, Mo. Williamson, who
said he isn't bitter about his imprisonment, added that he planned
to visit Florida, and then would go on a cruise. After that, he
said he may move to Missouri, also.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much is Charlton Heston paid by the National Rifle
Association to be its president? Do you have an address where
concerned citizens can write him to express our discontent?
</P>
<P>
   A: Heston's position is ``unpaid and essentially volunteer,''
said NRA spokesman Jim Manown. The address: Charlton Heston, c/o
National Rifle Association of America, 11250 Waples Road, Fairfax,
VA 22030.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is feminist theology?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Westminster Dictionary of Christian Theology explains:
``Feminist theology takes as its first agenda the criticism of the
masculinist bias of Christian theology. Feminists therefore see
Christian theology as having been done in exclusion of women's
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently read several times that Johnny Cash suffers from a
rare neurological ailment called Shy-Drager Syndrome. What is this,
and where does it get its name?
</P>
<P>
   A: Also known as multiple system atrophy, Shy-Drager is a
disorder of unknown cause in which many parts of the nervous system
degenerate, according to the Merck Manual of Medical Information.
</P>
<P>
   Shy-Drager is similiar in many ways, such as causing movement
disorders, to Parkinson's disease, but it also causes malfunction
and destruction of the autonomic nervous system, which regulates
blood pressure, heart rate, gland secretion and eye focusing.
Degeneration of the cerebellum sometimes causes incoordination. The
treatment of Shy-Drager is the same as for Parkinson's, but
includes the drug fludrocortisone to help raise blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The syndrome takes its name from the American neurologists who
first observed and documented it, George Milton Shy and Glenn A.
Drager.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the Mercedes-Benz plant in Tuscaloose, Ala., open for
public tours?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Tours are offered five times a day, Monday through
Friday, at 9, 9:15 and 11 a.m., and 1 and 1:15 p.m., by reservation
only. Call 1-888-286-8762 or 205-507-3300. The visitors center and
exhibition hall are open 9 a.m.-5 p.m. weekdays, 10 a.m.-5 p.m.
Saturdays. Admission is $4 for ages 12-54; $3 for ages 6-12 and
older than 55. The visitor center, exhibition hall and plant are at
Vance, Ala., at Exit 89 (Mercedes Drive), on I-20/59 about 20 miles
east of Tuscaloosa.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A friend and I are having a disagreement. Who is the
highest-paid player in Major League baseball?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you mean long-term contract, if you said it's pitcher
Kevin Brown, you were right. The former Georgia Tech star is
getting paid $105 million over seven years by the Los Angeles
Dodgers, for an average of $15 million a year. As reported in
December when Brown became baseball's first 100-million-dollar man,
the agreement includes no deferred payments and allows for
twice-monthly charter jet flights from Brown's home in Macon, Ga.,
to Los Angeles at the Dodgers' expense during the season to allow
his wife, Candace, and the couple's young sons to visit. If you
mean salaries for this year only, Albert Belle is being paid just
under $12 million by the Baltimore Orioles, while Brown is being
paid $10.7 million, with a salary of $15.7 million for the
remaining six years of his contract (for the $105 million total).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard Garrison Keillor mention having a new baby daughter.
Who is his wife? I've never seen any personal information about
him.
</P>
<P>
   A: Gary Edward (his real name) Keillor, host of ``A Prairie Home
Companion,'' rarely consents to be interviewed, which is why you
haven't read much personal information about him. He has been
married three times: No. 1, Mary C. Guntzel; No. 2, Ulla Skaerved;
and No. 3, Jenny Lind Nilsson.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you define the term ``ethnic Albanians''? Why are they
called that, instead of just plain ``Albanians''?
</P>
<P>
   A: The ethnic Albanians are a majority _ or at least they were
until the recent mass exodus and slaughter by Serbian forces _ in
Kosovo. Kosovo is a province of southern Yugoslavia in the Serbian
republic, which neighbors Albania. The people who live in Albania
are the ``just plain Albanians,'' as you put it. The term ``ethnic
Albanians,'' for Kosovars who have cultural ties to Albania, has
been used to distinguish between those who live in Albania and
those who don't. The Serbs, NATO claims, intend to drive the ethnic
Albanians out of Kosovo, which they claim as theirs. This ``ethnic
cleansing'' is what caused NATO to launch a military offensive
against Yugoslavia's government.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In what year did daylight saving time begin?
</P>
<P>
   A: The United States adopted the plan in 1918, but repealed it
in 1919. It also observed daylight time from Feb. 9, 1942, to Sept.
30, 1945, due to World War II (the reason: to conserve energy by
reducing evening use of lighting). After the war, many states
established some sort of daylight saving time. Beginning in 1967,
the entire nation went on daylight time from the last Sunday in
April to the last Sunday in October.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, during the Arab oil crisis, Congress enacted
daylight time from Jan. 6 to Oct. 27, 1974, and from Feb. 23 to
Oct. 26, 1975, again to conserve energy. Since 1987, daylight time
has begun on the first Sunday in April.
</P>
<P>
   (End)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
