<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6173 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-REDSOX-HOBSON29-C     04-28 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REDSOX-HOBSON29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hobson warns of `mistakes I made'
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ Butch Hobson sat behind a desk in the visiting
manager's office Monday afternoon at Roger Dean Stadium wearing a
Red Sox T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, Butch Hobson.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, a manager's office.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, a Red Sox T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so he's with the Class A Sarasota Red Sox of the Florida
State League and not the Boston Red Sox of the American League, for
whom he once played and later managed.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way from those glory days _ Hobson slugged 30 homers
and drove in 112 runs as Boston's regular third baseman in 1977 _
and an even longer way from the glory days when he was Bear
Bryant's quarterback at Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   But that's how it goes when a guy is 47 years old and has seen
his life almost disintegrate.
</P>
<P>
   Hobson, fired in 1994 after the third of three losing seasons as
Boston's manager, was arrested May 4, 1996, while managing the
Class AAA Scranton/Wilkes-
</P>
<P>
   Barre (Pa.) team in the Philadelphia Phillies' organization when
Drug Enforcement Administration agents seized 2.6 grams of cocaine
from him in a Pawtucket, R.I., hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies suspended him, and fired him three months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't using drugs at that time,'' Hobson said. ``I had used
them during my playing career. It was easy to walk into a bar in
Chicago or New York and find a drug of your choice. It was the
thing to do, and I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, given another chance to assume a position of leadership,
Hobson is telling young people not to sabotage their futures.
</P>
<P>
   Hobson admitted nothing more than being ``in possession of the
cocaine for 12 minutes,'' which he said Monday is how long it was
from the time he received the package, mailed from a friend, until
DEA agents showed up in what he has forever presumed to be a sting
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Hobson was required to enter a diversion program and perform 60
hours of community service (he says he put in more than twice that
many hours), and the charge was expunged from his record. He was
out of baseball briefly after incident, but spent the past two
years as a special assignment scout in Boston's organization before
being offered the Sarasota job this season.
</P>
<P>
   From that bully pulpit, Hobson delivered a don't-do-what-I-did
message to the entire Red Sox family when spring training opened in
Fort Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a counselor,'' Hobson said, ``but what I'm telling
these guys is: `You don't think it can happen to you? I'm the man
to see.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind talking about the mistakes I made. Put it out
there every single day. I'm good at this. I get their attention.''
</P>
<P>
   If only, he wishes, someone long ago had gotten his.
</P>
<P>
   He remains Butch from small-town and still hometown Fairhope,
Ala., but maybe there's a little more Clell Lavern Hobson Jr. to
him than there used to be.
</P>
<P>
   He's a grandfather to two boys, Tucker and Drew, sons of his
oldest daughter, Allene, from a first marriage. Two other daughters
_ Libby, a junior at Alabama, and Polly, a freshman at SMU _ also
are from that marriage. Hobson and his second wife, Krystine, are
parents to young sons K.C., Hank and Noah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy doing just what I'm doing,'' Hobson said. ``I'm not
looking for anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   He put on a pair of glasses and filled out a lineup card.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Hobson, managing again, wearing a Red Sox T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stoda writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
