<SLUG> BC-RAC-BISHER-DERBY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Derby field open as ever
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the 100th birthday of the Kentucky Derby, 23 horses
were allowed to squeeze into the starting gate. Anybody who owned
anything with four legs that could whinny wanted to get his animal
on the track. Ten horses spilled over into the betting field _
that's for those commoners not considered threat enough to have
their own betting slot _ and one of them finished second. It was
more a stampede than a race, and amazing that through all that
traffic a favorite named Cannonade was able to find a way to the
finish line first.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the Kentucky Racing Commission limited the starting
slots to 20 has there been a cast more befuddling than the one
going into the gate this weekend. The bettor who is best at darts
should have an edge. Put the names of all the horses on a board,
throw a dart, and you've got as good a chance as any.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, it looked as if the best three-year-olds were in
the West. Then one of the best, Exploit, went down. But Bob
Baffert, with the ready quip and silver thatch, had plenty left in
his bountiful stable. Indeed, when Churchill Downs closed the book
on future wagering, Prime Timber stood the favorite at 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   The champion two-year-old, Answer Lively, has fared about like
most juvenile champions. He's 15-1. Another strong juvenile
finisher, Yes It's True, took a drop in class and is off the board.
Cat Thief, Lemon Drop Kid and Lucky Roberto, Mack Robinson's
longshot winner of the Hopeful, peaked too soon.
</P>
<P>
   There shouldn't be any common sense in Baffert sending
Silverbulletday out against the boys in the Derby. That would show
a lack of confidence in his two male stars, General Challenge and
Prime Timber, and if there is anything the bon vivant Baffert is
long on, it's confidence. With Excellent Meeting to go with
Silverbulletday in the Kentucky Oaks, and the other pair in the
Derby, he has a double-barreled shot at both prizes.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the Ashland Stakes aboard her at Keeneland, jockey
Jerry Bailey said of Silverbulletday, ``She's the best filly I ever
rode,'' and that covers a lot of fillies. But you can hardly see
the need of her in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Some unusual mystery is coming in from the sheiks in the United
Arab Emirates, operating as Godolphin Stable. Worldly Manner won
the Del Mar Futurity last year and was bought by one of the
Maktoums for $5 million, taking him out from under Baffert. Aljabr
is a complete mystery. ``He finished second behind Worldly Manner
in a `trial' race among Godolphin Stable horses in Dubai, then won
a second `trial' which Worldly Manner sat out,'' which reads like
an intramural scrimmage. Somebody must know how to unravel the
mystery, for Worldly Manner was bet down to 9-1 in the future book.
You gets yer money down and you takes yer chances here.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for horses that have come into the Derby at
the top of their game, there are two choices, Stephen Got Even and
Menifee. Stephen Got Even was running allowances races at
Gulfstream when I first heard of him, then won the big tuneup at
Turfway _ beating another of Baffert's herd _ and shot right into
the middle of the picture. He stalked the pace going wide, then
took charge in the stretch. All of his credentials pass muster.
Menifee came out of Florida behind in his homework, but he caught
up in the Blue Grass. Pat Day found a hole in traffic, pulled him
wide and beat Cat Thief and Vicar the way you like to see your
horse win. And at 9-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   It's a muddle. One big jigsaw puzzle that only the 125th
Kentucky Derby can solve for you. Right now I'd lean toward Stephen
Got Even, Prime Timber, Worldly Manner (with Bailey up) and
Menifee. But this is the guy who came off Spend a Buck, and I might
change directions several times after I get there.
</P>
<P>
   Furman Bisher is Sports Editor of the Atlanta Journal, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
