<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-TIME-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 THE BEST TIME to be ALIVE: `No Time Like the Past' (A Panel
Moderated by RUSSELL BAKER)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (This article has already moved to Centerpiece and Millennium
Plus partnership clients. To publish as a one shot _ and for
millennium rates and packages _ please contact one of these New
York Times Syndicate sales representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; For release: April 18 or thereafter &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Editors: See THE LOCAL ANGLE box below &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Has there been in the last thousand years a single best time to
be alive? In this age of faith in progress, it's easy to answer
quickly: Yes, right now. But does that almost automatic response
stand up to informed comparison with past times?
</P>
<P>
   To answer this question, The New York Times Magazine convened a
panel, moderated by the longtime New York Times columnist Russell
Baker, comprising the following scholars:
</P>
<P>
   _ Thomas Cahill, author of ``The Gifts of the Jews'' and ``How
the Irish Saved Civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ann Douglas, professor of English and comparative literature
at Columbia, and author of ``Terrible Honesty: Mongrel Manhattan in
the 1920s.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Elaine Pagels, professor of religion at Princeton, and author
of ``The Origin of Satan.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Orlando Patterson, professor of sociology at Harvard, and
author of ``Rituals of Blood: Consequences of Slavery in Two
American Centuries.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jonathan Spence, professor of history at Yale, and author of
``The Chan's Great Continent: China in Western Minds.''
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSELL BAKER: None of us are living in this time by choice.
We're here because of somebody else's decision. Maybe, given our
druthers, we would prefer to be somewhere else _ I would bet in
most cases not in the future. The idea is to debate a little about
the ideal time to live in, if you had your own choice.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose some people would say this is the ideal time. I'm
prepared to argue against that, but for the most part I'm here to
listen to your opinions. Mr. Spence, you would probably like to go
back in time?
</P>
<P>
   JONATHAN SPENCE: Absolutely. I would be very interested to live
my life in Hangzhou. I know where my villa is going to be: on the
west side of the lake in the hills, looking down on what was then a
totally unpolluted lake, and what was a kind of large and
prosperous rural pleasure resort. A beautiful city.
</P>
<P>
   BAKER: What year is it on the Christian calendar?
</P>
<P>
   SPENCE: I would be born around 1540. One of the problems here is
I'd like to have a bit of money. I don't want too much, because the
official agents from Beijing would take it away from me. This was
one of the most urbane and cultured times in all of Chinese
history.
</P>
<P>
   I've always studied the Manchu Dynasty and modern China and the
revolution, and that was from 1644. But I would like to live in the
Ming Dynasty _ not knowing, of course, that the Ming was going to
fall. So I do need to die shortly before 1644. That was a great
time of scholarship, and it was also a great time for scholarship
for women.
</P>
<P>
   If it's all right, I want to be married to my real-life wife at
the same time, but my Chinese language would be much better in this
life. As a couple, we're always going to be able to play elegant
poetry games, word games that the Chinese have always loved to
play.
</P>
<P>
   And the reading _ the texts about that 16th-century period in
Hangzhou show an amazingly energized society. People read very
widely. It's a magnificent period in painting. The food is
magnificent. It is not a slave society. Booze is available but not
excessive. It's pre-opium, no heavy narcotics. And the distribution
of food in that region is efficient. It was a rich time to live.
</P>
<P>
   BAKER: It sounds like a paradise. How about you, Mr. Cahill?
</P>
<P>
   THOMAS CAHILL: Sticking within the confines of the last thousand
years, I find myself drawn to the 14th century. I would love to
have gone to a Christmas party in medieval London with Geoffrey
Chaucer. I would love to have been around when Giotto began to
paint _ this man, influenced by the spiritual realism of Francis of
Assisi, asking himself: What do human beings really look like? And
then trying to make them in that way. I would love to have been
there when Joan of Arc began to muster the troops.
</P>
<P>
   BAKER: They burned her.
</P>
<P>
   ELAINE PAGELS: I think that this would be a fascinating journey,
but I'd want to go with a full set of inoculations and an American
passport.
</P>
<P>
   CAHILL: How long do you want to be present?
</P>
<P>
   BAKER: Since this is an intellectual exercise, I think you have
to assume that you're going to be part of the culture of the time.
We'd all like to cruise around and watch Columbus come ashore.
</P>
<P>
   CAHILL: I find it difficult to reduce myself to one spot.
</P>
<P>
   DOUGLAS: But we all are reduced to one spot. And you'd live how
long? Thirty years in about 1390? You'd hardly have time to get
around to see everything you said you wanted to see.
</P>
<P>
   SPENCE: In Hangzhou, there were long-lived people, maybe 90 year
olds, edging 100. They also had wonderful food, which didn't even
require teeth! Delicious rice pilaf dishes, soft lotus-root dishes.
</P>
<P>
   BAKER: Mr. Patterson?
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO PATTERSON: I chose three periods, excluding the period
following the civil rights movement in America. That has obviously
been the best time for Afro-Americans, but sticking to it would rid
the discussion of any fun. Working backward, my third choice would
have been to be a moderately prosperous New England farmer who
lived around 1750 to 1830 _ embracing the Revolutionary period.
</P>
<P>
   I would have been about 26 in 1776, so I would have fought in
the Revolutionary War. I would like to have had the opportunity to
talk intellectually with Madison, to club with Hamilton, to tell
Jefferson what a fraud I thought he was _ that really, it's not
fair that he should have a place in history just because he wrote a
great paragraph.
</P>
<P>
   My second choice is to have lived in Tokugawa, Japan, about the
18th century. I would not want to have been a samurai. By then,
they were no longer warriors; they were basically quasi
bureaucrats. And I wouldn't particularly care for the official
culture that the shogun imposed, although it was quite fascinating
_ those tea ceremonies. They would have been far too restrictive
for me.
</P>
<P>
   I would like to have been a moderately prosperous merchant
around the 1730s, participating in what the Japanese call the
floating world, which is a kind of counterculture to the official
world imposed by the shogunate. They had a ball!
</P>
<P>
   I'd have been drawn to Kabuki dramas, to the fashion, to the way
they subverted the official ideology so that when the shogun said,
``You can no longer wear fancy clothes; you have to wear cotton if
you're a merchant,'' they wore cotton on the outside and silk on
the inside.
</P>
<P>
   I think the life expectancy may well have been much better
living in Japan at that time than in Europe. And it was a very
peaceful period. They threw out the Europeans and were able to
develop their own culture.
</P>
<P>
   Now I come to my first choice. It's in the 14th century. It's a
city-state that produced some of the most beautiful art in the
world. Can you guess?
</P>
<P>
   PAGELS: Siena?
</P>
<P>
   PATTERSON: No. I wouldn't want to be in Renaissance Italy if you
paid me. There were towns where a third to a half of the population
was dropping dead from the plague!
</P>
<P>
   The little city-state I had in mind would have been the town of
Ife in Yorubaland, in what's now western Nigeria, somewhere about
the mid-to-late 14th century. I would want to have been a sculptor,
one of the people who produced those incredible bronze heads or the
terra-cotta work that you now can see in the British Museum. Again,
the life expectancy would have quite possibly been higher than for
a working man in Europe at that time.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice to have been a bourgeois gentleman in Holland
during the golden 17th and early 18th centuries, having your
portrait done by one of their great painters, but they were
involved with the slave trade. The same was true of the British.
</P>
<P>
   You think about being an entrepreneur in late 18th- and
19th-century England. You saw this incredible transformation, the
Industrial Revolution; the steam engine and all the rest. The
trouble is, one can't help thinking about the plight of the
displaced masses and the kids who were being sent down into the
mines.
</P>
<P>
   BAKER: I wonder if I could change the focus to the idea of
progress. Do we all believe in progress?
</P>
<P>
   SPENCE: It seems to me it's not so much comfort or progress that
we're talking about; it's those who actually are drawn to live in a
period of extraordinary change and struggle vs. those who, I think,
want a period of enormous cultural subtlety and development.
</P>
<P>
   I tilt toward the latter, a time in which the culture is still
immensely lively, but the idea of progress would not exactly be the
point.
</P>
<P>
   CAHILL: I would speak for progress. We are at the end of the
bloodiest of all centuries, to be sure. And it is not a universal
consciousness, by any means, but I think there is a consciousness
of the necessity for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ------------------ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -0- &QL; 
