<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 AT SARATOGA: `Benedict Arnold, Hero'  
 &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece and Millennium
Plus partnership clients. To publish as a one shot _ and for
millennium rates and packages _ please contact one of these New
York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.  By R.W. APPLE JR.  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 c.1999 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; For release: April 18 or thereafter &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Editors: See THE LOCAL ANGLE box below &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   ___  &UR; A revolutionary turning point. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On June 22, 1777, 8,200 seasoned soldiers, including a German
brigade in blue, Indians in war paint and more than seven regiments
of British infantry in scarlet headed south from their base in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Their commander was Gen. John Burgoyne _ Gentleman Johnny, they
called him _ a playwright, bon viveur and member of Parliament. He
was headed straight into the battle of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The British plan was simple. Burgoyne would sail down Lake
George, capture Fort Ticonderoga and march on Albany. There he
hoped to meet the troops of Gen. William Howe, advancing up the
Hudson, and those of Col. Barry St. Leger, advancing east from Lake
Ontario. The rebellious colonies would be cut in two.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Burgoyne's operations went according to plan. He
captured ``impregnable'' Ticonderoga with ease. But instead of
continuing by boat down Lake George, he pushed south on foot. It
took him three weeks to reach the Hudson, north of Saratoga, and by
then the Americans had regrouped.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, he sent an undersize force into Vermont on a raid for
cattle and horses; it was clobbered, losing 600 men. Then Burgoyne
heard the worst news: He was on his own. Howe had set off to attack
Philadelphia. And when Benedict Arnold _ hero in this phase of the
Revolution, villain in the next _ arrived at Fort Stanwix, Colonel
St. Leger hastily abandoned it.
</P>
<P>
   Burgoyne's lines of communication with Canada were fragile, and
he concluded that he had no alternative but to press on to Albany
and hope for help there. Anticipating a decisive engagement,
Washington sent reinforcements to Gen. Horatio Gates of the
Northern Continental Army _ Arnold and his 1,200 men and Daniel
Morgan and his 500 crack riflemen.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 12, Gates' force dug in on the west bank of the Hudson
atop a hill called Bemis Heights. On Sept. 19, Burgoyne's men
reached Freeman's Farm, almost within sight of the Heights.
Burgoyne hoped to outflank Gates to the west and then drive his foe
into the river.
</P>
<P>
   Gates kept the bulk of his force within his entrenchments. The
troops he sent forward were hard pressed until Arnold, cursing,
rallied them, galloping hither and yon like a man possessed. ``He
was our fighting general,'' a comrade wrote later, ``as brave a man
as ever lived.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle lasted from noon until sunset. It ended
inconclusively, but the British lost a third of their force. Arnold
had saved the day.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, the Continental Congress fled Philadelphia for
Lancaster, Pa., and 11 days later it moved farther west to York,
Pa. Washington was losing his grip; between Sept. 11 and Oct. 4,
the Americans were beaten at Brandywine, Paoli and Germantown.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, much was at stake when Burgoyne rolled the dice at
Saratoga once more on Oct. 7. He threw most of his force into a
final effort to turn the enemy's flank. Gates, jealous, had
relieved Arnold, but the latter, fuming in isolation as battle
raged, shouted: ``No man shall keep me in my tent today. If I am
without command, I will fight in the ranks, but the soldiers, God
bless them, will follow my lead.''
</P>
<P>
   And so they did. His horse was killed and he was severely
wounded in the leg, but Burgoyne had to retreat, and, on Oct. 17,
surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   The consequences were undeniable: France entered the war on the
American side. When Washington and his ragtag army, wintering in
Valley Forge, Pa., received news of the alliance in the spring of
1778, their spirits were lifted; the road was open to ultimate
victory in October 1781.
</P>
<P>
   The millennium would see other great battles, such as Gettysburg
and the Marne and D-Day. But in the last 1,000 years, I think, only
the defeat of the Turks by Jan Sobieski near Vienna in 1683 rivaled
Saratoga. It turned back the tide of Islam. Saratoga did more.
</P>
<P>
   It launched two centuries of revolution elsewhere. It marked the
beginning of the end of the British Empire. And it breathed life
into the United States of America.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (R.W. Apple Jr. is chief correspondent of The New York Times,
based in Washington.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; THE LOCAL ANGLE: &LR; 
 &UR; Here are a few ideas to localize this piece. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What American history can be visited in your region? Check out
the following websites for details and ways your readers can become
involved in preserving historic battlefields and buildings.
</P>
<P>
   1. The Civil War Trust  &QL; http://www.Civil War.org/cwt-trav.htm &QR; 
leads to state tourism websites, special events around the country
and The Civil War Discovery Trail with more than 500 historic sites
in 28 states. Phone 703-516-4944.
</P>
<P>
   2. The National Park Service  &QL; http://www.nps.gov &QR;  maintains
the National Registry of Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
