<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-MACEDONIA _ NEPROSTINO REFUGEE CAMP, Macedonia _ A
fellow journalist bemoaned to me that the news these days is so
depressing, since so much of it centers on the Kosovo crisis. The
observation is heard frequently from readers: Why isn't there more
good news in the paper? My reply: Look closer. (Holmes, Cox News
Service). 20. WITH PHOTO (mug).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (k) Commentary and (i) International categories.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ My swimming pool made it
through the winter in fine shape. Drats. (Murray, Cox News Service)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ It was hard for Karen Weyhrich
to know what to say, what to do. She never faced anything like it,
never dreamed of anything like it at her high school in the late
'60s. ``The thing we were most afraid of was getting caught smoking
a cigarette,'' she recalled. She camped out at her church, St.
Frances Cabrini in Littleton, Colo., down the street from Columbine
High School, comforting hundreds of survivors. In the news,
Weyhrich said, we hear only about the gore. The evil. The kids gone
bad. She's seeing something else, something the news cameras don't
find as compelling. (McCarty, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ will not move today.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Andrew Mackay must have a large
knot in his kilt located about where he sits down. Here's a guy who
writes a travel piece for the Glasgow (Scotland) Sunday Herald
taking cheap shots at Austin. And he comes from a country where the
people eat sheep guts on purpose? (Kelso, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-COLUMN _ Today's children, in growing numbers, are
experiencing a numbing of the sensibilities that make one human.
The resultant product is killers without consciences, many of whom
revel in the only power they perceive they own _ the power to
destroy. They willingly commit violence without thought of
consequences, not even at the cost of their own lives. Such
youngsters are to be feared; people who do not value their own
lives cannot value the lives of others. How adults can move from
fear of our youths to restoration of nurturing control is our
challenge. (Jefferson, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
