<P>
   FOOD-CYBERSPICE _ A weekly column looking at the plethora of
recipes on the Internet. (Parham, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-MONTICELLO _ CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. _ When Thomas Jefferson
returned from Paris after four years as envoy, his fellow Virginian
Patrick Henry scoffed that he was ``so Frenchified that he abjured
his native victuals.'' Though it has been two centuries, the
Jeffersons have not forgotten the slight. ``Patrick Henry,'' says
the man with the long strawberry locks and fair, freckled
complexion. ``I believe he liked to go out in the woods and eat
bear meat.''No one would ever accuse Rob Coles of abjuring his
native victuals. A fifth great-grandson of Jefferson, through his
daughte r Martha, the 47-year-old actor grew up eating hot dogs and
prefers Brunswick stew and cornbread to fancy continental cooking.
Like his famous forebear, whom he impersonates in 200 appearances a
year, Coles eats his vegetables. But there are limits to his
enthusiasm. ``Jefferson grew 16 varietes of peas,'' he says. ``I
love peas, but, I mean, come on.'' (Auchmutey, Cox News Service).
WITH ILLUSTRATIONS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MAY 2.
</P>
