<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Column: What $400 Will Buy In a PC System  
 By David Einstein   
 c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Question: &LR;  I have been asked to advise a school about
purchasing new computers. I know that E-Machines sells a system for
$399, but I recall also reading about another machine that goes for
$299. Unfortunately, I forgot its name and how to contact the
company. Any help would be appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer:  &LR; The company you're referring to is Microworkz
Computer, which is based in Seattle. Microworkz makes low-cost PCs
for the corporate market and recently announced it was getting into
the consumer space with a series of low-cost ``Webzter'' systems
designed for people who want a computer mainly for the Internet.
The low-end model, called the Webzter Jr., sells for $299. It
includes a 300-MHz Cyrix chip, 32 megabytes of memory, a
3.2-gigabyte hard drive and a 56K modem.
</P>
<P>
   However, it doesn't come with a floppy disk drive or a CD-ROM
drive, both of which are standard equipment on most PCs. They cost
an additional $99, which brings the price of the system up to $398.
</P>
<P>
   The $399 etower from Emachines features a 333-MHz Cyrix chip, 32
megs of memory, a 2.1-gig hard drive, a 56K modem and both CD-ROM
and floppy drives.
</P>
<P>
   Neither system comes with a monitor. So which one is a better
choice? Well, the Microworkz PC has a slightly bigger hard drive,
and it comes with Corel's WordPerfect software suite as well as a
year of free Internet access. But Emachines offers a faster chip as
well as a more powerful video subsystem, which means it should be
better at running video games.
</P>
<P>
   You can find the Emachines systems at Best Buy and other office
and computer stores. Microworkz is selling its systems directly
online at www.webzterpc.com.
</P>
<P>
   E-Mail Problems
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have just installed the new Microsoft Internet Explorer 5,
which includes the latest version of Outlook Express. Now I can't
send e-mail. Every time I try, the computer attempts to use my old
GTE Internet account, which I canceled months ago when I switched
to Earthlink. Is there any way I can change the server on the
e-mail to Earthlink?
</P>
<P>
   A: There sure is. Open Outlook Express, then choose Accounts
from the Tools menu. Tab over to Mail and you should see all the
mail accounts that are set up for your system. If Earthlink is one
of them, select it and click the Set as Default button.
</P>
<P>
   If Earthlink isn't listed, you'll have to create a new mail
account. Click the Add button, then click Mail. The Internet
Connection Wizard will then guide you through the process. You'll
need the names of Earthlink's incoming and outgoing mail servers,
which Earthlink can provide.
</P>
<P>
   After creating the new account, set it as the default (if it's
the only one listed, it will automatically be the default). And
feel free to remove any accounts associated with your old GTE
connection.
</P>
<P>
   A Lost Address
</P>
<P>
   Q: How come in Microsoft Internet Explorer I don't have an
Address line? I had one before.
</P>
<P>
   A: Have you looked under your desk? Seriously though, you
probably disabled it inadvertently. To set things right, choose
Toolbars from Internet Explorer's View menu, then click Address
Bar. The Address Bar, which includes the space for Internet
addresses, should return to your desktop. Another way to do the
same thing is to right-click on any open space in the gray area at
the top of the screen and choose Address Bar.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K Worries
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a Dell Optiplex GMT 5166 computer that I purchased in
February 1997. Am I likely to experience Year 2000 problems when
January 1 rolls around? If so, what can I do to prevent them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Computers built more than a year ago may have problems
recognizing the year 2000 _ which could lead to all kinds of
problems with software programs that take their cue from the
computer's clock. The two primary areas of concern are the BIOS,
which includes information the system needs when it starts up, and
the real-time-clock itself.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's Web site (www.dell.com) lists Y2K certification status
for its computers, and it shows that yours needs a BIOS upgrade _
which you should be able to download from the Dell site. Good luck.
</P>
<P>
   PC owners worried about Y2K can also put their minds at ease by
using a program such as Norton 2000 ($49.95) or McAfee 2000 Toolbox
($29.95). Both programs can diagnose _ and in some cases fix _
hardware problems, as well as deal with software applications that
could have Y2K glitches. Apple says its Macintoshes should not have
Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
If you create and delete a lot of files and install and remove a
lot of programs, chances are that after a while your PC will slow
down because information on your hard disk gets all out of order.
To remedy the situation, give your disk a tune-up with Disk
Defragmenter, a utility program that comes with Windows. You'll
find it by clicking the Start button, then going to
Programs/Accessories/System Tools.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-21-99 2118EDT &QL;
</P>
