<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6205 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-WEB-ONLINE-SECURI     04-28 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEB-ONLINE-SECURITY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALARMS RAISED THAT SOME ONLINE SHOPPING MAY NOT BE SAFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PAUL SHUKOVSKY   
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Some of the little guys who sell on the Internet may
have just dealt e-commerce a setback.
</P>
<P>
   A computer technician at a Bellevue, Wash., Internet service
provider says he found evidence that consumers who give private
information such as credit card numbers to small, online stores
can't count on the information being kept safe from theft.
</P>
<P>
   The technician for Blarg! Online Services discovered that
``shopping cart'' software used by small online retailers often may
be improperly installed, making private consumer data accessible to
anyone on the Web who might misuse it. One Blarg! executive said
the problem could have a chilling effect on e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   While no one knows how many retail sites on the Worldwide Web
are not secure, Blarg! executive Marc Lewis said when technician
Joe Harris checked Monday, ``We were shocked; there were literally
thousands'' of sites that use shopping cart software and thus pose
a potential problem. Harris checked just a sample of the
approximately 4,250 sites using the software and found about 300
that were not secure.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Blarg! posted a warning on Bugtraq, an e-mail
security advisory that goes out to about 22,000 computer
professionals. The report was picked up by the Los Angeles Times on
Thursday and received wide national attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also tried to contact Visa and MasterCard fraud protection
and they didn't seem very interested,'' said Lewis. ``Then we tried
contacting a few of the software providers for shopping cart
services and most of them did not return our calls or passed it off
to the Web site developer.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is with the Web site developer, said Lewis. Often
small companies will hire a solo, free-lance developer to put
together a retail Web site. These Web developers may choose not to
follow the proper protocols for installing the software ``because
they want to get the site online and get their check,'' said Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amateur Web developers are not experienced enough to put
together a secure system,'' Lewis said. ``They are doing a great
disservice to their clients as well as the Internet community at
large. People won't buy things (online) anymore if they don't trust
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he knows of at least one large Internet service
provider that also provides shopping cart software that is
reviewing the security of all its sites. ``Now that people know
that the problem exists, they are working toward fixing it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone else had gotten the data earlier, they could have
done bad things,'' said Lewis. ``They could have imprinted credit
cards and used them... and unfortunately, there wouldn't be too
many people to protect consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, the giant Seattle-based online bookseller, on
Thursday pronounced its site ``absolutely safe. There have been no
breaches of security at Amazon and we would expect none,'' said
spokesman Bill Curry. ``Customer privacy and security is of
paramount importance to us and we have multiple layers of
protection to ensure the trust of our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   While Curry would not reveal specifics about Amazon security, he
said the company does not use off-the-shelf shopping cart software.
</P>
<P>
   But Curry agreed that it is important that people feel
comfortable and safe when they shop online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of where people shop on the Web, we want people to
have a good experience because it builds confidence in e-commerce
for all.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite concerns about security, consumers spent $9 billion on
online purchases last year, according to figures cited by the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Blarg! technician Harris discovered the problem during a
conference call with a Blarg! client and a shopping cart vendor,
said Lewis. When they asked Harris to perform an improper technical
step that would have made the consumer data easily available to
anyone, it ``alarmed him and he would not do it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Harris checked the Web to see how many other sites were out
there with improper security, he found thousands using the
software. Then, when he started sifting through some, he was able
to call up ``about 300 actual order files with customers' phone
numbers, home addresses and credit card numbers as well as what
they ordered,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris believes ``it's only the tip of the iceberg'' and there
are hundreds more out there with with improperly installed shopping
cart software. ``There are so many would-be Web site developers out
there who don't know how to set up an online store safely, but they
don't tell their clients,'' Harris said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing anyone wants to do is kill the golden goose of
Internet commerce. But this isn't good,'' he said. ``Full
disclosure is the best policy. If the site doesn't have a privacy
statement or if it doesn't clearly spell out how they secure their
data, then shop elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   So called shopping cart programs that are vulnerable to Web
thieves if improperly installed include those from Order Form,
Seaside Enterprises, QuikStore, PDGSoft and Mercantec.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sites didn't follow their guidelines. The (software)
vendors shouldn't be blamed,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Myrtle Beach, S.C.-based QuikStore spokesman Dwight Vietzke said
only two of its estimated 700 users have reported problems with
shopping cart installations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a case when human error comes into play,'' Vietzke said.
</P>
<P>
   The shopping cart software, if installed incorrectly, saves
customer order information in an unsecured file, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Web surfers can download files containing customer names,
addresses, telephone and credit card numbers, expiration dates and
order data simply by using a search engine like Hotbot or AltaVista
and punching in a few simple search words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those files aren't meant to be accessed by a Web browser.
There is no reason for it to be listed there in the Web site
tree,'' Harris said. ``If it's not encrypted, it shouldn't be
there.
</P>
<P>
   Online stores usually retrieve order information using
encryption and other security measures, but the orders are
sometimes placed in a file on the Web site's computer system that
is easily accessible to an outside Web surfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think most companies see the magnitude of this. They
have to take action very quickly,'' said Tara Lemmey, president of
San Francisco-based Electronic Frontier Foundation, a non-profit
group that promotes online privacy.
</P>
<P>
   When correctly installed, shopping cart software creates a file
for confidential information that is inaccessible to outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-23-99 0122EDT &QL;
</P>
