<SLUG> BC-CPT-SHOOTINGS-WEB-CHAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITES BUSY AS MANY SEEK OUTLET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PATTI HARTIGAN   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A family in Orem, Utah, sent out kind words and electronic
prayers. A free-lance Web designer in California set up an on-line
condolence board. Teen-agers in chat rooms alternated between
anger, despair, and tough-guy posturing. Harvard professor and
child psychiatrist Alvin Poussaint counseled parents and teens in a
live chat on America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Wednesday, Web sites with the words ``trench coat'' in
their addresses were bombarded with hits Wednesday, despite the
fact that these sites had nothing to do with suspected killers in
Tuesday's Littleton, Colorado school rampage or with their group,
the Trench Coat Mafia. Rumors blanketed bulletin boards and dubious
news sites before being quickly swatted down by vigilant Web users.
And in Golden, Colorado, at the offices of the Jefferson County
Schools, an official worked to dispel such rumors and set up a
on-line resource center in the aftermath of the tragic shootings at
Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   As it has in other crises, the Internet was both a labyrinth of
misinformation about the shootings as well as a comfort zone for
concerned citizens. ``Please be careful about taking any
information about this event from unreliable Internet sources,''
warned John Adsit, who set up the site for the the county school
system. (The site is at
http://204.98.1.2/communications/crisis/crisis.html.) Adsit was
responding to a series of on-line hoaxes and rumors that emerged
instantaneously on-line, even as police and rescue workers were
still clearing the school building of explosives.
</P>
<P>
   On America Online, for instance, more than a hundred users
altered their member profiles to include references to the killings
and the Trench Coat group _ seeking to draw attention to
themselves. In addition, several news reports broke late Tuesday
about an AOL page alleged to have been posted by deceased gunman
Eric Harris, one of the two students who went on a wild shooting
rampage at the Colordo high school. The address for the AOL site,
which is posted on many electronic discussion groups, has been
removed from the server, but it is said to have featured pictures
of the kind of pipe bombs used in the Tuesday's attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been working with the FBI since (Tuesday) night, and
our folks here pulled content to preserve some information they
thought was relevant to the case,'' said AOL spokesperson Kim
McCleery.
</P>
<P>
   At least one other site was pulled from the Internet Wednesday,
and others posted disclaimers. An adult entertainment site with an
address that seemed affiliated with the fringe group received so
many hits Wednesday it temporarily suspended its business and
posted this message: ``This site has nothing to do with the Trench
Coat Mafia...I'm just as disturbed and saddened as the rest of you
about the events that transpired in Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Internet users aimed to inflame the tragedy even as it
was still unfolding. In the discussion group
alt.motorcycles.harley, a user who used the handle Queen Jeff
alleged that the attack had been unleashed by ``gay bikers''
seeking revenge. The user posted the message via the popular
on-line service Dejanews.com. ``We are a very democratic site, and
we don't alter content,'' a spokesperson for the New York-based
Deja News, Inc said ``It's unbiased _ that's the beauty of it. The
company does not control content. That is too Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   But while hoaxers used the Internet to posture, other users
sought solace and comfort in discussion groups and live chat
forums. Marian McKenna Olivas, a California Web designer, set up a
condolence site on her business pages (see
http://www.wecanhelp.net/columbine.html). ``I lost my second child
(to meningitis, not violence) and was just moved by the sight of
parents waiting to hear from their children,'' she said. ``I
decided to set up a place where people could send sympathy.'' The
site was receiving 10 condolence letters an hour Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, various on-line sites offered cyber
counseling: At family.com, for instance, therapist Sylvia Rimm
posted a piece called ``What to Tell Your Kids.'' Poussaint fielded
questions on AOL; friends supported each other in such forums as
alt.teens.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere on-line was a mix of heartfelt emotion and false
bravado. ``I could make a bomb,'' boasted an AOL member in a chat
room. Recipes for explosives are, in fact, readily available
on-line.
</P>
<P>
   But for every braggart on-line Wednesday, there was a somber
counterpoint. This message appeared on Olivas' bulletin board
Thursday night: ``All I can say is I'm sorry. I live in Jonesboro
(Arkansas), and I went to the high school at Westside when last
year there was the shooting. I know how hard it is and I know how
hard it will end up being.'' The posting was signed, ``Sincerely,
Erin.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-22-99 1358EDT &QL;
</P>
