<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-PRICES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HP'S CASE, SPEED THRILLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By SIMSON L. GARFINKLE   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With personal computer prices crashing, companies like Hewlett
Packard are scrambling at the high end.
</P>
<P>
   These PC makers are attempting to build powerful systems, loaded
with features, at a price point high enough to provide a healthy
profit margin. A major weapon for the computer companies is Intel's
new Pentium III microprocessor, a chip that can command a
significant premium because it is the latest and fastest from
chipmaker Intel .
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, of course, Intel created a different kind of
stir with its Pentium III. Every Pentium III chip contains a unique
serial number that can be used to track the movements of consumers
on the Internet. As a result, some privacy groups, including the
Electronic Privacy Information Center, have called for a boycott of
this chip.
</P>
<P>
   But does it make sense to boycott Intel's latest and greatest?
Eager to find out, and curious about what it would be like to
``drive'' the world's fastest PC, I asked Hewlett Packard to lend
me its top-of-the-line home computer, the HP Pavilion 8490.
</P>
<P>
   The Pavilion 8490 is an imposing machine. The system comes with
a Pentium III microprocessor screaming along at 500 Mhz. (That's
more than 100 times faster than the original IBM PC, which had a
clock speed of just 4.77 Mhz.)
</P>
<P>
   The Pavilion 8490 comes with not one, but two optical drives.
One is a CDROM/DVD drive that can play movies directly from an
optical disc onto the computer's screen. You can buy DVD movies in
the stores now for less than $15; there are literally hundreds of
titles. The second optical drive is a compact disc recorder (CD-R).
Black CDs can be purchased for roughly $2 each at Staples and most
computer supply stores.
</P>
<P>
   Two drives means that it's easy to copy from one CD to another.
In fact, the HP Pavilion comes with disc-copying software
pre-installed. (Unfortunately, you can't copy DVD discs, because
they store data in the a different format.)
</P>
<P>
   The HP Pavilion also comes with a fancy keyboard that includes
an extra row of buttons for playing audio CDs. There is also a big
volume control, and buttons that are supposed to automatically
launch your favorite application programs, sort of like station
presets that you might see on a car stereo.
</P>
<P>
   This whole package costs roughly $2,500 for the basic
configuration. That includes 128MB of RAM, a 17.9GB hard drive, and
a fax modem. Throw in another $150 and HP will install a Diamond
Viper 550 video card with 16 megabytes of video RAM,
high-performance 3D graphics, and a rock-solid refresh. (The
Pavilion's built-in video is an 8MB ATI Rage, which flickered
somewhat on my monitor.)
</P>
<P>
   You'll also need a monitor. HP sells a 15-inch multimedia
monitor (which means it has a set of built-in speakers) for $299
and a 17-inch monitor for $449.
</P>
<P>
   So how does the whole package work together?
</P>
<P>
   Quite well. As long as Microsoft's software is cooperative. I
was amazed by how much faster programs like Outlook Express and
Internet Explorer ran on the 500 Mhz Pentium III. I had thought
that the main factor limiting these programs was the speed of my
Internet connection, which is a fairly zippy cable modem from
MediaOne. But running on the Pentium III, Web pages just snapped
into place. The browser's ``Back'' button gave me instantaneous
satisfaction. Even mundane activities like hitting the ``Page Up''
and ``Page Down'' keys were noticeably faster. The increased speed
made the computer more enjoyable to use.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, faster doesn't mean more reliable. I consistently
had problems with drivers and other system software. Blue screens
would appear with writing on them, telling me that an illegal
operation had occurred. Sometimes the computer would just freeze up
for no apparent reason at all. Thankfully, the computer also boots
fast!
</P>
<P>
   Some of the built-in software didn't work properly, either. The
Pavilion comes with Symantec Fax Starter Edition, but it never
worked for me. I ended up installing WinFax instead. The special
``media'' buttons on the HP keyboard stopped working when I
installed Internet Explorer 5. The computer that I got came with
the Viper 550 video card, but the DVD playing software for the
built-in ATI video system. HP says that this was a mistake made
with my particular machine. Still, the only way that I could play a
DVD was by removing the Viper card and using the built-in video.
</P>
<P>
   I was also annoyed by a high-pitched chattering that accompanied
certain kinds of screen operations, such as moving a window or
redrawing a page of text. The chattering sounds a lot like the old
Apollo workstations from the early 1980s. I believe that it comes
from the power supply when it's called upon to supply a little
extra juice for transferring images to and from the screen. HP told
me that I could make the noise go away by changing a jumper on the
inside of the computer. I changed the jumper, but the noise
remained.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond ultra-fast speed, the Pentium III also brings a whole
bunch of new instructions that software vendors can use in their
products. Dragon Systems, for instance, has a version of its speech
recognition software that uses the special Pentium III instructions
to achieve faster recognition and shorter training times than was
with previous microprocessors. I tried a beta release of the
program and was amazed by the improvements _ you can now train
Dragon in just 3 minutes, as opposed to half an hour. Dragon's
product is a real reason to purchase the Pentium III, rather than
the competing chips from AMD and other vendors that are nearly as
fast but much cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the privacy-shattering Pentium III goes, I must have
visited more than 100 Web sites during the time that I've been
testing the machine. Not one of them asked to download an applet
that could read the processor serial number (PSN).
</P>
<P>
   And why would they? Pentium IIIs are in the vast minority on the
Internet today. Why would any Web site restrict an area so that the
majority of Internet users couldn't access it?
</P>
<P>
   Overall, HP's Pavilion is great system if you want to watch
movies, master compact discs, or if you just need to have the
zippiest computer on the block and you are willing to pay for it.
Configured as it is, this is a computer that will last for several
years without the need to upgrade. But if you do decide to get it ,
you're probably better off buying your own 17-inch monitor for $300
and hooking the computer up to your stereo system. You'll get
better sound, and save money as well.
</P>
<P>
   (Simson L. Garfinkel can be reached at
plugged-in(at)simson.net.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-22-99 1354EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
