<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-GOVERNOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRGINIA'S `INTERNET GOVERNOR' WOOS SILICON VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. _ James S. Gilmore III, the governor of
Virginia, stood on the steps of the Netscape Communications Corp.'s
headquarters last Tuesday and smiled in the morning sun. The man
Virginians know as the ``Internet Governor'' was 3,000 miles from
his constituents but he insisted he felt at home in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I speak their language,'' Gilmore said. ``We're on line
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the governor correctly interpreted the ties remains to
be seen. One thing is certain: as the worlds of politics and high
technology increasingly come together, Gilmore is a man who would
like to be at the nexus.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Virginia's high-technology economy has surged
and Gilmore, a Republican, has made Internet policy central to his
18-month stint in office.
</P>
<P>
   He helped create and signed what supporters deemed the nation's
first comprehensive set of state Internet laws, created the first
state technology cabinet post, made fast ties with Virginia's
technology industry and aggressively recruited technology companies
to consider making Virginia their home.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is seeking to parlay his efforts into a national role.
Last December, he was named to a federal commission charged with
studying Internet tax issues, and he hopes the Internet policies
pioneered in Virginia will be used as a blueprint by other states.
</P>
<P>
   His three-day tour of California last week represented a
coming-out party of sorts, an effort to sell himself and Virginia
at ground zero of the digital revolution. He said he felt a warm
reception from executives at the likes of Netscape, Oracle and
Cisco Systems. But it was also clear that Gilmore's portrayal of
Virginia as the ``Internet state'' did not overly impress the
industry titans in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody comes here trying to get a little Silicon Valley
dust on their shoes,'' said Netscape's chief executive, James L.
Barksdale, during his meeting with the governor, though not
appearing to refer to the governor personally.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, what made the visit to Netscape particularly
symbolic is that Netscape recently was purchased by America Online,
the brightest jewel in Virginia's high-technology crown.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to America Online, Virginia is home to MCI Worldcom
and one of its subsidiaries, Uunet, as well as Psinet. Gilmore is
fond of saying that thanks to the presence of those companies _
Uunet and PSInet are Internet service providers _ 50 percent of all
Internet traffic goes through Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   More generally, Virginia's high-technology economy has been on a
tear. Over the last five years, the technology sector has generated
more than 60 percent of the growth in the state's economy,
according to the governor's office. The office also projected that
the number of technology businesses in Virginia would grow to 5,300
by 2002, up from 3,400 now.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore says he has never called himself ``the Internet
Governor,'' but he does not mind the title a bit. ``If somebody
wants to refer to me as that, I won't run from it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To his detractors, Gilmore is a Johnny-come-lately who has tried
to transform himself into a ``governor.com.'' Critics say he hardly
uttered a word about technology until after he became gvernor in
1997 and has since sought to take credit for Virginia's
high-technology growth. They point out that Gilmore's gubernatorial
opponent, Donald S. Beyer Jr., was much more closely tied to
northern Virginia's technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high-tech economy has been booming for years,'' said
Kenneth R. Plum, chairman of the Democratic Party of Virginia.
``He's gotten on board and is riding it for all it's worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Plum and other critics do not dispute that Gilmore and
the Internet industry have become fast friends in the intervening
months. Many in the industry say the gvernor is one of the few
politicians who has made a truly concerted effort to understand
their new economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's recognized what the Internet is, how it got there and
what impact it can have'' said Stephen M. Case, the chief executive
of America Online, adding that Gilmore's efforts in Virginia are
being emulated elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a recognition this is a launching pad,'' Case said.
``The policies set in Virginia could become a blueprint.''
</P>
<P>
   It has not hurt the governor's standing among the state's
technology companies that he has offered tax breaks to support
their growth. For example, he engineered an $18 million tax break
for America Online as an incentive for the company to build a new
data center in Prince William County.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters also credit Gilmore with being the first governor in
the nation to create a technology cabinet post (although Democratic
critics in the state contend they had the idea first). The
secretary of technology post is held by Donald W. Upson, a former
marketing executive, who is charged with attracting high-technology
business to Virginia and exploring how the state can use
information technology internally.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the work of a state commission created by Gilmore, he
signed the nation's most broad-based state Internet laws last
month, giving force to seven bills called the Internet Policy Act.
Among other things, the act has provisions to protect consumer
privacy, make it a crime to use encryption for criminal activity
and make it a criminal offense to send unsolicited commercial
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous other states are considering Internet-related laws, and
some are patterning them after the work of Virginia, said Paul
Russinoff, state policy counsel for the Internet Alliance, an
industry trade group.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a fan of heavy regulation on the Internet, you may
find the Virginia act unsatisfying, but it is one of the few policy
initiatives I've seen at a state level that takes a realistic
approach,'' Russinoff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying there aren't other `Internet governors' out
there,'' he added. ``But Governor Gilmore is absolutely focused on
the medium.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-25-99 2044EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
