<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW RATINGS GIVE LYCOS A REASON TO CELEBRATE  
 ANTI-VIRUS COMPANIES SOUND A NEW ALARM  
 TAKING TO THE ROAD WITH A NEW INTERNET PITCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the Internet business, the top of the heap is a very unsteady
place. And nobody knows that better than Bob Davis, chief executive
of Lycos Network Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Media Metrix, which measures Web traffic, announced
that in March the Lycos network of 11 sites, including the search
service Lycos.com, surpassed Yahoo in audience reach for the first
time. That means that more people visited a Lycos site in March
than a Yahoo site _ 31.9 million people vs. 31.3 million. Lycos,
however, is still outranked by America Online and Microsoft sites.
</P>
<P>
   But Yahoo asserted that its figures did not include
Broadcast.com or Geocities, which the company is acquiring. In the
case of Lycos, however, the numbers do reflect its acquisition of
Wired Digital, which it announced plans to acquire last fall. That
deal has not officially closed, though Wired Digital has already
become part of the Lycos Network, which is based in Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Davis is celebrating, if only for the moment. ``What the
ratings say is that today we've got the No. 1 spot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a first; it's never happened where Yahoo hasn't been
the dominant one,'' Davis said. ``It shows there's still
competition on the Web.'' He attributes Lycos' rise to its focus on
what he calls ``organic applications,'' like Tripod, an online
community site that the company acquired last year, and other
projects that encourage communications among Web surfers.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Lycos announcement of taking first place is
premature, or even inaccurate, Davis has other reasons to
celebrate. In February, Lycos struck a deal to merge with USA
Networks, the media and electronic-commerce company controlled by
Barry Diller. Under that agreement, Lycos, along with Ticketmaster
Online-Citysearch, will become USA/Lycos Interactive Network.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Virus Companies Sound a New Alarm
</P>
<P>
   When the clock strikes midnight on Monday, it will set off a
nasty version of a computer virus known as CIH 1.2 that is capable
of deleting part of the contents of hard drives and preventing
computers from booting up.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent weeks there has been an outbreak of a different
sort: Various makers of anti-virus programs have sent out news
releases warning of the virus and touting their own software for
use as a preventive measure. Several anti-virus companies, like
Network Associates Inc. and Computer Associates International Inc.,
said they were offering free CIH virus patches for download from
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   All this simply underscores a constant tension in the anti-virus
community, which on the one hand exists to eradicate viruses and on
the other thrives on their existence and benefits from copious
press about the potential dangers.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of CIH, the companies insist they are not blowing
the potential dangers out of proportion. Variants of the CIH virus
attack computers on the 26th of each month, but the one programmed
for Monday is considered the most virulent strain; it is known as
the ``Chernobyl virus'' because it hits on the anniversary of the
meltdown of the nuclear reactor in the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most prevalent file virus in the wild,'' said Sal
Viveros, marketing manager for Network Associates.
</P>
<P>
   The CIH attacks files that can be opened in Windows 98 and
Windows 95, including Word and Excel files. The virus can be passed
by e-mail, floppy disk or other means, but is easily detected and
destroyed by most anti-virus software.
</P>
<P>
   Previous incarnations of the CIH virus have not proved as
harmful as computer security experts warned at the time. Still,
makers of anti-virus software are not out of line in bringing
attention to this latest strain, said Kathy Fithen, manager of the
CERT Coordination Center, a federally financed computer-virus
response team at Carnegie Mellon University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not hysteria,'' she said. ``What they are doing is
alerting customers that they need to update software. And that's
good.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MATT RICHTEL
</P>
<P>
   Taking to the Road With a New Internet Pitch
</P>
<P>
   He is flush from the recent initial public offering of
iVillage.com, in which he got insider stock as a participant in the
Web site's Armchair Millionaire section. Now, Lewis Schiff, a New
York-based Internet marketer, is touting his latest venture,
Invest-o-rama, an online listing of some 10,000
financial-information sites on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff recently bought into Invest-o-rama, which was started
four years ago by Douglas Gerlach, and hopes to use the billboard
to attract other investors to help expand the site.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff paid $20,000 for a 14-foot-by-48-foot billboard ad, which
went up on April 15 and is strategically placed along Silicon
Valley's most traveled artery, Highway 101.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure the most influential people know about
what we're doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the next two weeks, at least, if they are driving on the
highway, they couldn't miss it if they tried.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-25-99 2041EDT &QL;
