 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Net brings campaigns, activism to masses 
By Omar L. Gallaga  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If an e-mail titled ``Gas Out'' hasn't arrived
in your inbox yet, there's a good chance you'll receive a copy of
it in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail, which asks that all drivers avoid buying gas for one
day (April 30) in order to cripple ``the so-called oil cartel'' and
reduce gas prices, sounds like it will be about as effective as
changing the channel during a Nike commercial in an effort to
eliminate sweatshop working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   What's more interesting than the message is the medium. The
anonymous originators of ``Gas Out'' have created a phenomenon by
using e-mail for this grass-roots protest. Some, however, would
call it an annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   Political action is a logical progression for the Internet,
which has brought us instant messaging, electronic commerce and
CD-quality music for the downloading. Social activism has always
strived for getting a message to the masses and what better, more
efficient way is there than e-mail?
</P>
<P>
   Grass-roots campaigns on the Internet have been around since
before the Web grew to prominence. Like-minded folks would meet in
newsgroups and start mail-in campaigns against companies or
organizations. In some cases, fan groups organized e-mail campaigns
to save their favorite TV shows. When Comedy Central canceled
``Mystery Science Theater 3000,'' for instance, a group of fans
organized their protest efforts on alt.fan.mst3k and used e-mail to
spread the call.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, online groups have gained attention by protesting a
new user identification feature in Intel Corp.'s Pentium III
processor (Intel has since decided to add an option for disabling
the feature), fighting unsolicited commercial e-mail (the Forum for
Responsible and Ethical E-mail has worked with legislators here on
anti-spam legislation), and most importantly, fighting to save
``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman.'' Though that campaign failed, CBS is
bringing the good doctor back in a series of TV movies.
</P>
<P>
   What's next? Expect a flurry of activity on the Web next year as
the 2000 campaigns get into full swing.
</P>
<P>
   As the next election cycle spins faster, the Internet will play
a much larger role than it did as an embryonic public medium in
1996. Aristotle Publishing Inc., a San Francisco-based political
software company, said it estimates presidential and congressional
candidates will spend at least $20 million in Internet banner
advertisements next year.
</P>
<P>
   Jay McAniff, a spokesman for Aristotle, said the company is
reaching the very people on the Internet they hope will vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with a segment of the population that's
typically more educated, more affluent and more likely to vote,''
he said. ``This political cycle, we expect online activity will
mimic the overwhelming response to people for electronic commerce
last Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason it is such a great match for political campaigns is
because the Internet itself lends itself to public discourse,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Voters will be able to find information given by candidates on
official Web sites, but will just as likely be able to find things
some politicians may not want you to see _ their voting records,
finances and any messages anyone on their staff has ever posted to
a newsgroup, courtesy of Deja News, which catalogs newsgroups.
</P>
<P>
   Be it through e-mail protest or an online political pep rally,
Internet activism and campaigning is turning the Web into a global
town-hall meeting _ one with nearly unlimited boundaries and
unlimited opportunity to make the public's voice heard.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-26-99 1041EDT &QL;
</P>
