 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Online textbook seller also carries required-reading lists 
By Mark Clothier  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Amazon.com and Barnes &AMP; Noble are finding that the
Web, while not yet a medium for profit, is a solid place to sell
books.
</P>
<P>
   Now, textbook sellers are getting in on the act.
www.efollett.com not only sells the books, it posts required
reading lists for courses at more than 600 colleges. Not every
school is available.
</P>
<P>
   Before you can buy books, you have to pick a school. That's
where www.petersons.com comes in. Peterson's is ranked by print and
online magazines as the Web's best college guide. Peterson's offers
online applications, financial aid information and grad school test
preparation aids that can be downloaded.
</P>
<P>
   www.finaid.com is the top-rated site for financial aid
information. The site has a link to www.fastweb.com, a free
scholarship database.
</P>
<P>
   What's the best way?
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo! Internet Life's standing feature, ``Old Way/Net Way,''
takes a look at which is the best way to do everyday tasks,
Internet or traditional methods.
</P>
<P>
   This month considers designing and ordering note cards, finding
rare wine and registering your car.
</P>
<P>
   For note card ordering, the Web won. Yahoo! used www.iprint.com
and paid $74.99 for 200 cards, plus $9 to get them delivered in two
days. It took 15 minutes to pick and order, and two days to get
them. The traditional, card store way cost more ($105.50 for 200
cards delivered in two days) and took longer (one hour in the
store.)
</P>
<P>
   The wine hunt was a draw. It was shorter to search online than
in stores, but both proved fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   Car registration was easier online. It took less than one minute
to download and print the form vs. 28 minutes in line at the
registration office.
</P>
<P>
   Movies, and nothing but
</P>
<P>
   Ever wondered who played the vaguely familiar crew-cut guy who
testifies in the courtroom scene in ``A Few Good Men,'' but you
don't want to drop the four bucks to rent it?
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's help online.
</P>
<P>
   www.imdb.com is like having direct access to someone who does
nothing but eat and sleep movies. The site lists about 2.3 million
film entries, including information about actors, directors,
writers, composers, cinematographers, editors, production
designers, costumers and production designers.
</P>
<P>
   You can also search for information about one actor. The Noah
Wyle freaks out there might already know that the ``ER'' star
played Cpl. Jeffrey Barnes in ``A Few Good Men.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the Internet Movie Database, you can find out on which
popular TV series Wyle made a guest appearance, and in which movie
he also worked as associate producer.
</P>
<P>
   Hand-held DVD player on way
</P>
<P>
   Panasonic is coming out with a hand-held version of the DVD
player.
</P>
<P>
   For now, digital video discs mostly are used to store movies.
Panasonic's new hand-held model is called the DVD-L50 PalmTheater.
</P>
<P>
   It retails for $1,099 and is expected to be on the market by
May.
</P>
<P>
   The palm-sized model weighs about 2.5 pounds, including the
battery. It is 5.51 inches by 5.96 inches and is less than 2 inches
thick. The 5-inch LCD monitor comes with 280,000-pixel resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-26-99 1041EDT &QL;
</P>
