 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Linux inventor's bluster no match for Microsoft's battalions 
By Bill Husted  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I'm writing this while on vacation. I don't tell you
this to rub it in _ although it is a perfect spring day, and I do
own an excellent hammock.
</P>
<P>
   The reason I want you to know about my vacation is that I see
better when I back away from something and look from a distance.
That works with redwood trees, people and the computer world.
</P>
<P>
   For years, before my wits deserted me and I became a full-time
editor and a part-time reporter and columnist, I traveled annually
to Comdex, the big computer show. For at least seven years, I stood
in line with the other propeller heads waiting to hear the Gospel
according to Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates, the Microsoft co-founder, has been the keynote
speaker for Comdex back since the days before computers were trendy
appliances and available in a wide selection of colors. This year,
according to the news reports, Gates _ as usual _ outed the newest
version of Windows that's under development.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't business as usual at Comdex. Gates is no longer
the youthful developer, arrogantly challenging the audience. In
fact, Gates spent a lot of time talking about a nifty new mouse
Microsoft has developed.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the role of innovator and boy genius was usurped by a
fellow with a first name that would be right at home in a comic
strip and an operating system that was once considered a joke by
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Linus Torvalds, the developer of an operating system called
Linux, was also at Comdex. And his operating system _ long a
favorite of computer wizards but not taken seriously as competition
for Windows _ was on center stage. Torvalds, who spoke on the same
day as Gates, was taking no prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Torvalds didn't tell the Comdex crowd that now, based on
alliances with IBM and some other computer giants, Linux should be
taken seriously as competition to Windows in the high-level
business and Internet market. He didn't shuffle his feet and thank
the computer world for beginning to rally behind the dark horse of
an operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said of Microsoft: ``We will crush them.''
</P>
<P>
   All the world, including the part of it populated by people who
stay up late at night eating cold pizza and writing computer
programs, loves a David and Goliath story. So the audience went
wild. No matter which side of the fence you sit on, no matter how
wedded you are to Microsoft products, there's little warm and
cuddly about the giant software company. So the enthusiasm for such
a challenge is understandable.
</P>
<P>
   And Linux really is a terrific product that's catching on.
International Data Corp., which tracks stuff like this, predicts
the sales of Linux will grow at 25 percent for the next few years.
So Torvalds has a reason to be a little exuberant. But, sitting
here, eyeing my hammock, far away from the maddening Comdex crowds,
I keep hearing a small voice _ either an especially talented
mockingbird or the voice of reason.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what the voice is saying:
</P>
<P>
   In a battle, God is on the side of the army with the biggest
battalions.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not here to debate the comparative merits of Linux and
Windows. I'm not smart enough to do that. And you either are smart
enough _ and have formed an intelligent opinion _ or you're like a
lot of folks and care more about the pollen count than comparing
operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   What I am here to tell you is that other, more powerful
companies have made the same boast of crushing Microsoft ... and
have done it with at least as much logic. Think of Apple and its
really terrific computer and operating system. Think of IBM, which
sold OS/2, an operating system that was more stable and more
powerful than Windows. It's the same _ only more so _ with Linux.
It's a wonderful operating system, and Torvalds is a smart guy. But
Gates has a killer advantage.
</P>
<P>
   If you are sitting near a PC, just turn it on and you'll see the
advantage. Microsoft may not own the hearts and minds of the
computer world, but it doesn't need to. Its outsized battalions are
sitting there on the battlefield of your computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-26-99 1041EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
