<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6227 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-VIRUS-THREAT-ART-     04-28 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-VIRUS-THREAT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAREFUL USERS COULD AVOID VIRUSES, SPECIALISTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients. 
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
 By ROSS KERBER   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once the threat of computer viruses caused panic among technical
specialists and yawns among the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Now the responses are reversed. Far-reaching computer networks
make it easier than ever for harmful programs to wipe out data. But
even as computer users become more fearful, defenses against
electronic epidemics have improved to the point where antivirus
technicians sound like doctors giving routine advice for reducing
the risk of catching a sexually transmitted disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're practicing safe computing you should be OK,'' said
Raul Elnitiarta, an engineer at Symantec Corp. in Santa Monica,
Calif., which makes programs to detect and disable troublesome
code.
</P>
<P>
   Those who don't take precautions run the risk of losing days or
weeks worth of work _ as computer users around the world, including
more than 100 Boston College students, discovered Monday, when the
virus known as Chernobyl struck their hard drives. The virus is so
named because it was set to activate itself on the anniversary of
the Russian nuclear disaster 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Thought to have been created in the Far East, the Chernobyl
virus is often embedded in other programs downloadable from the
Internet. It strikes at computers running the 1995 and 1998
versions of Microsoft Corp.'s Windows operating system, overwriting
the first 2,048 sectors of hard drives with gibberish and causing
the computer to think the rest of the drive is empty of data.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists have known of the virus for more than a year, and
after arming themselves with the latest software, most businesses
and large institutions reported few problems Monday.
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon just seven sites across the country,
representing about 30 computer users, had made formal notifications
they were affected, said Bill Pollak, spokesman for the Computer
Emergency Response Team.
</P>
<P>
   The group, part of a federally funded institute, is located at
Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh. ``We're not hearing
anything that would indicate it was big in the US,'' Pollak said.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, an estimated 100,000 computer users in the United
States were affected by the so-called Melissa virus that spread
over the Internet last month. The Melissa virus caused more
widespread damage because it was distributed via commonly used
e-mail programs; Chernobyl, by contrast, infected only users who
had downloaded certain executable programs to their PCs.
</P>
<P>
   But woe befell plenty of people who weren't running electronic
countermeasures _ particularly local college students, who often
obtain free copies of pirated software from the Internet rather
than pay retail prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely ridiculous,'' said Patrick Morrissey, one
of the Boston College students whose records were vaporized Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   When Morrissey turns on his laptop now, the screen reads
``operating system not found,'' leaving inaccessible thousands of
e-mail messages and a 1,000-word theology paper due Tuesday at
10:30 a.m. ``I don't know what I'm going to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so annoying,'' said his roommate Drew Wetzler, who lost
to the virus eight hours of work he had done for an accounting
project.
</P>
<P>
   Morrissey acknowledged using pirated copies of certain word
processing programs available via the Internet, programs
specialists say are particularly likely to be infected. Still, he
said BC's computing center should have sent around e-mails to warn
students of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   A college spokesman said an update on a school Web site was
sufficient notice for the school's 8,600 undergraduates. In any
case, said spokesman Jack Dunn, they should have installed copies
of an antivirus program that was sold at the start of the academic
year.
</P>
<P>
   To those who didn't, Dunn said, ``We're sorry they put
themselves in that position.'' At Boston University, computer
consulting services director James Stone said a half-dozen students
called in with complaints about their hard drives Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Their options were limited, Stone said. ``Either they can hire
an expensive data recovery service or they can scratch the drive
and start again,'' he said. ``There's no good option.''
</P>
<P>
   Wire services reported the Chernobyl virus also struck at
computers in Finland and Russia. Bloomberg News reported that
Malaysia's stock exchange said computer systems at 12 of the
country's 60 brokerages were infected, slowing trading.
</P>
<P>
   Still, damages could have been worse, said Brooks Talley, test
manager for InfoWorld, a San Mateo, Calif.-based magazine published
by International Data Group in Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Melissa virus got everybody's imagination going
and they started to take steps'' to use antivirus software, Talley
said. The average company of 100 people today spends about $23 per
employee per year on antivirus programs, he said, and home users
should expect to run antivirus protections about once a month.
</P>
<P>
   Virus creators are also developing more powerful programs to
test those measures, said John Vranesevich, principal of the
AntiOnline Web site that monitors hacking groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see more of this because of the growth of
Internet computing, the more companies do collaborations on line,
and the more distance-learning projects there are,'' he said.
``When something gets created and released it's spreading on a much
larger stage.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Francie Latour of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-27-99 1354EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
