<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6278 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-28 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MUCH OF A BAD THING IN LITTLETON 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One guy on the Web is calling it ``Geek
Profiling,'' and I guess I partly fit the profile, or at least did
in high school.
</P>
<P>
   A group called the National School Safety Center has issued a
checklist of danger signs to watch for in children. These include
mood swings, a fondness for violent television or video games,
cursing, depression, and antisocial behavior and attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   That's most kids I've ever known. After the shootings last week
at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., maybe most American
adults fit the geek profile, too. Littleton is a big story, but
there has been too much of it.
</P>
<P>
   The danger signs are all flashing.
</P>
<P>
   My mood has swung between depression at the predictability of
the news stories and relief at how well kids in Littleton have
responded to the disaster that befell their school.
</P>
<P>
   I've been feeling antisocial.
</P>
<P>
   I turned down a chance to go to Littleton and join the media
crush _ not because I think I'm too good for that, but for reasons
of mental health, mine and the people of Littleton. One fewer
reporter wouldn't have meant much to them, but it did to me.
</P>
<P>
   I've been angry because I can't take any more stories trying to
jerk tears out of me. I've been cursing the TV for profiting off
others' grief 24 hours a day, every day for a week.
</P>
<P>
   Fondness for violent TV? Not usually, but when the shooting
started last Tuesday, I watched a lot of CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Here comes a mood swing again. The kids in Littleton have
spontaneously gone to their churches in groups of dozens and
hundreds to talk to their youth ministers, to build memorials and
regenerate their community.
</P>
<P>
   The culture lives. Kids are resilient, and I don't care what
their profile is.
</P>
<P>
   If you're stuck too firmly in front of the TV, you'd think
America is a series of events that come with logos and theme music.
``The Impeachment of the President.'' ``Crisis in Kosovo.'' ``The
Killings at Columbine.''
</P>
<P>
   School shootings, the most unpredictable events, lead to the
most predictable coverage.
</P>
<P>
   First there's the awful live coverage, with lame commentary by
bubble-headed local anchors. Eventually we get to the healing and
need-for-closure phases, but first we have to go through the blame
phase, the decline of culture (or rise of gun culture) phase, and
the quick-fix phase.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody in the media is a psychologist. Every lawmaker wants
to pass laws.
</P>
<P>
   It's all very depressing. Pardon the mood swings and warning
signs again.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe some good has come of the Littleton massacre. Probably
very little.
</P>
<P>
   Some kids at a junior high in Texas were arrested for trying to
bomb their school. Trench coats have been banned at schools in the
Denver area. The San Francisco Board of Supervisors has called for
bigger warning labels on video games.
</P>
<P>
   As if the pictures of futuristic mayhem on the boxes aren't big
enough to attract kids already.
</P>
<P>
   In El Cajon, Calif., an eighth-grader was expelled for talking
about bombs and shootings the day after the Littleton massacre,
even though his comments weren't directed at anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Every talking head was talking about the same things. They
blamed guns, parents, video games, lack of religion, violent movies
and TV, or some combination thereof.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the talking heads weren't expelled the way the
kid in El Cajon was.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton introduced some gun-control proposals Tuesday.
None of the proposals would have prevented the two teen-age killers
in Littleton from getting their hands on the shotguns a friend
apparently bought for them.
</P>
<P>
   They took a year planning their raid. The best way to have
stopped these kids would have been to notice danger signals more
obvious than depression _ like swastikas, for example.
</P>
<P>
   New gun laws may make some people feel better, but they won't
prevent another school shooting. Colorado Gov. Bill Owens called
these events a cultural virus.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is deeply embedded in our culture, but it hasn't
caused a full-blown plague. School shootings aren't as frequent as
they seem. They just all look alike, and the media goes overboard
on each one in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   And you wonder why they all look alike.
</P>
<P>
   The culture lives. Maybe that's the mood swing talking again,
but we can escape the media morass. We can go out to the ballpark,
go mountain biking or go to a cafe and talk about books and movies
that have absolutely no violence in them. Yes, there are a few.
</P>
<P>
   We can even talk about violence. It won't hurt, even if these
days it would get you expelled from eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons I turned down the chance to go to Littleton
is that I've covered a mass shooting before, in a courthouse in
Orlando, where I then lived. It's disturbing to see your community
laid low with grief. It's also inspiring to see how the community
responds to attack and pulls together.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't want to see that as an outsider in Littleton, one of
thousands of outsiders bearing notebooks and microphones. We have
our lives to live, filled with mood swings, cursing, depression and
antisocial attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that, the culture lives, and it isn't in decline.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
