<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6341 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-MACEDONIA-042     04-28 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-MACEDONIA-0429-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LETTER FROM MACEDONIA: DON'T HAVE TO LIVE LIKE A REFUGEE
 &HT;    With Photo Mug of Holmes.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEPROSTINO REFUGEE CAMP, Macedonia _ A fellow journalist
bemoaned to me that the news these days is so depressing, since so
much of it centers on the Kosovo crisis. The observation is heard
frequently from readers: Why isn't there more good news in the
paper?
</P>
<P>
   My reply: Look closer.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five weeks, an exodus of biblical proportions has
taken place. Hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians fled into
neighboring countries. The grim trauma they experienced in Kosovo,
their forced deportations at gunpoint, the killings and rapes, is
unquestionably bad news.
</P>
<P>
   But the safety and care of most of the refugees since crossing
the border -- so many of them in such a short amount of time -- is
the good news. It could have been a disaster and at the outset it
looked like one in the making. Thanks largely to NATO and the hard
work of private aid groups, it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   The best of all the camps in Macedonia is the one formally known
as Neprostino, and more widely called ``the German camp.'' It was
built about a month ago by German NATO troops in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans graded the hilly terrain and spread a few tons of
white gravel as a base. They set up spacious tents complete with
wooden floors, cots and heaters. There is a mess hall, a field
hospital, even a school and a playground for the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, over a range of green hills, there is another camp
called Radusa, established by the cash-poor Macedonian government.
Of the makeshift, month-old tent cities now home to Kosovo
refugees, Radusa is the worst.
</P>
<P>
   There, flimsy tents are pitched on a muddy hillside. When it
rains, as it does often in the spring, the water cascades down the
slopes and into the tents. There is drinking water, but none for
washing clothes. Showers are taken in shifts at a tent set up
outside the camp's gates.
</P>
<P>
   Officials and field workers for the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) get prickly when asked about this
striking disparity in the camps. The German camp, they are quick to
point out, is the exception, not the rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not realistic,'' explained a U.N. field worker, citing
the cost and logistics her organization simply cannot bear.
</P>
<P>
   Then perhaps, as NATO redefines its new role in the world, it
should be in the business of providing a rapid-response service for
refugee crises. Why shouldn't the standards set by the Germans at
Neprostino be THE standard?
</P>
<P>
   The military have the cargo planes, tents, field hospitals,
latrines, portable kitchens and experience to get the job done
quickly. Aid agencies, some 200 of them operating in Macedonia and
Albania, hold meetings, solicit donations, divide responsibilities
and often struggle with time-consuming logistics.
</P>
<P>
   The people who work for the the UNHCR and for private,
non-profit organizations like CARE and the Red Cross are
hard-working and well-meaning. Their field workers are true heroes.
But in the army, a colonel tells his troops to erect the camp by
nightfall or have a damn good excuse why it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's participation, phased out in recent weeks as the refugee
flow dwindled, may be necessary again -- and sooner, rather than
later -- if an expected new wave still in Kosovo floods the
borders. Already this week, several thousand more Kosovar refugees
have come across into Macedonia, prompting UNHCR officials to warn
that camps packed beyond capacity were ``on the verge of rioting''
because of tensions.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's actions have been not only humane, but also politically
useful to blunt criticism from some parts that it is the punishing
air strikes that provoked the ethnic cleansing by Serb-led Yugoslav
forces that in turn, prompted the mass exodus of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the motives, the results count. For the most part the
refugees have a tent over their heads, are being fed and are
receiving medical care -- the aid arriving quicker and in greater
volumes had the alliance not been involved.
</P>
<P>
   This is good news and it is something that Americans and the
citizens of the other 18 NATO countries should feel good about. In
the worst of times for the people of Kosovo, America and its allies
have demonstrated that they can be the best of humanitarians.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
