<P>
   KOSOVO-TOWN (Surdulica, Yugoslavia) _ Story from the town where
roughly 20 civilians, including children, were killed in NATO
attack that hit residential area. The attack destroyed 3 houses in
one place, 10 in another, many damaged. Plus other developments,
including the dismissal by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic of
Vuk Draskovic, the deputy prime minister. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ A full-blown debate on Kosovo is
expected as the House votes on a declaration of war and cutoff of
funds. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton meets with
congressional leaders on Kosovo. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Developments from NATO headquarters:
NATO may give an account of how a missile accidentally hit
civilians. Javier Solana, the secretary general, discusses the
Washington summit at great length. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Berlin) _ Germany becomes a focus of diplomatic
efforts with Kofi Annan, the U.N. secretary general, and Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder talking _ they see no quick resolution _ and
Viktor Chernomyrdin, the Russian envoy due in Berlin on Thursday.
By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis on the
Clinton Administration's efforts to have Russia bail out NATO with
a Kosovo solution. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RESERVES (Birmingham, Ala.) _ On U.S. reservists who are
being called to active duty, or waiting to hear if their names are
on the list. By Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   We are considering, among others, a feature on refugees who
remain in Kukes, tales of massacres and sexual assaults from
recently arrived refugees and the tenuous position of NATO in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-SANCTIONS (Washington) _ The United States will announce
today a major policy change that would allow food and medicines to
be shipped to countries allegedly supporting terrorism, including
Iran, Libya and Sudan, a U.S. official said. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMF (Washington) _ Developments on an IMF deal with
Russia. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Washington) _ Folo on the yesterday's reports of
Chinese spying to obtain U.S. nuclear secrets. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS (Jerusalem) _ Palestinians, meeting in Gaza,
wrap up their talks on a declaration of statehood by suspending the
debate until after the May 17 Israeli election. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PROTESTS (Shanghai) _ In its first public comment on a
recent demonstration in Beijing, the Chinese government calls the
protest by a Buddhist group ``completely wrong.'' By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-U.S. (Tokyo) _ Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi
prepared Wednesday for his summit meeting with President Clinton,
working on his economic policy and on his pitching arm. By Nicholas
D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-DEATH-PENALTY (Geneva) _ The U.N. Human Right Commission
votes for a moratorium on the death penalty leading to its
abolition. The U.S., in opposition, finds itself on the losing
side. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-SOCSEC (Washington) _ Two key House Republicans unveil a
plan that they say would insure Social Security's solvency for most
of the next century without cutting benefits or raising taxes. But
with the Republican leadership determined not to press ahead on the
issue, the bill is dead and the only chance of jump starting the
issue is if the White House makes some bold move -- an option under
consideration. By Richard L. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
