<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   STEEL-COMPETE (Weirton, W.Va.) _ A movement to impose quotas on
imported steel and roll back imports to pre-1998 levels is picking
up momentum in Congress. Critics deride quota legislation as
dangerous, illegal and unnecessary. Not only do they say it would
cost American consumers an estimated $6 billion, but it comes when
the American economy's demand for steel is at an all-time high.
Moreover, it would violate world trade agreements and could lead to
a trade war. Just last week, for instance, Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan waded into this growing debate, saying such
protectionist efforts are both futile and harmful. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   MCKESSON (Undated) _ Shares of McKesson HBOC Inc., the nation's
largest drug wholesaler, plunge 49 percent after the company says
it will restate earnings for the fourth quarter and year, saying it
improperly recorded sales from its recently acquired HBOC software
unit. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Netscape officials give
depositions in the Microsoft antitrust trial. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   SONY-EARNINGS (Tokyo) _ Sony reports a $364 million operating
loss for the first quarter, its first quarterly loss in
four-and-a-half years. The company has been hurt by falling prices
for computer monitors and cellular phones and by weaker demand for
consumer electronics in Asia. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   EURO-MISSILES (London) _ Folo on reports that British Aerospace
is talking with France's Lagardere and Italy's Finmeccanica about
merging operations to become the world's second-largest missile
manufacturer. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Undated) _ An update on talks between United States
and Chinese negotiators on China's entry into the World Trade
Organization. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLER-EARNINGS (Detroit) _ DaimlerChrysler said first-quarter
profit rose 23 percent, on strong sales of its Mercedes-Benz and
Chrysler passenger cars and light trucks. Earnings were at the low
end of expectations. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE-AWARDS (New York) _ The National Magazine Awards
announces winners. By Alex Kuczynski.
