<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, April 29:
</P>
<P>
   KIPS-DECORATOR-SHOW (New York) _ A pair of monumental columns of
wire, not marble, and filled with oranges, stand sentry at the
entrance to the Kips Bay Boys &AMP; Girls Club Decorator Show House.
They are the latest indication that the American home has become a
place for navel-gazing. It's show-house time again, that riotous
seasonal decorating ritual in which angst takes a holiday and rooms
by decorators and architects _over half of them new to the
showhouse _ offer a heavy dose of visual caffeine. By Patricia Lee
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   INFIDELITY (Undated) _ Over the course of his 12-year marriage,
Tom Griffin, a banker from Annapolis, Md., had racked up a
considerable extramarital track record. One night in bed, his wife
Mary asked him whether he had ever strayed, and Tom, sick of the
deception, confirmed her worst suspicions. Two months later, their
marriage held together with prayer and Scotch tape, the Griffins
(not their real names) went to their first session with Frederick
DiBlasio, a therapist and professor of social work at the
University of Maryland. By Joseph Hooper.
</P>
<P>
   CIANI-AT&AMP;T (Undated) _ Suzanne Ciani lives in seclusion at the
end of a dirt road in bucolic Marin County, California, but her
most famous piece of music is heard about 280 million times every
day. In 1988, balancing commercial work with her career as a
composer, she created what may be the world's best-known audio
signature: the miniature chordal flourish that introduces every
AT&AMP;T call. By Philip Nobel.
</P>
<P>
   DESIGN-PRINCESS (New York) _ Earlier this month, Christina
Magnusson, a sophisticated 50-something Swede, sat in a Manhattan
hotel suite and discussed well-designed juice glasses,
toothbrushes, kitchen utensils, furniture, cars and houses. The
fact that Mrs. Magnuson is a sister of King Carl XVI Gustav and
thus a princess, might make her interest in juice glasses seem
strange. But in Sweden, where the creation of everyday objects has
been elevated to a fine art, the term ``Design Princess'' is a
serious honorific. By Andrea Codrington.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SLIPCOVERS (Undated) _ On the vererable slip cover and the fight
over devices to keep them from slipping. By Steven J. Stark.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-TOURS (Undated) _ From an 1811 farmhouse in Doylestown,
Pa., to ocean-front gardens in Rye, N.Y., to a Park Avenue duplex
apartment, show houses and house and garden tours will be open in
the next three months, and also in October, in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
