<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6350 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-DERBY29-COX     04-28 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-DERBY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some fleet-footed winners for Derby Day
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Derby Day on Saturday, and we've got the horse movies right
here. We're talking horse racing, not horse heroes like Flicka and
Trigger or equine-themed psychological treatises like ``The Horse
Whisperer'' and ``Equus.'' And we're talking about movies that have
a lot to do with racing, so don't everybody write in asking where's
``Ben-Hur's'' chariot race.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, horse racing was once the second most popular
sport in movies (behind boxing). In the '30s, the studios churned
out 44 track-themed films. By the '80s and '90s, the number had
dwindled to a trickle, reflecting, perhaps, the culture's growing
lack of interest in betting on horseflesh when they can blow big
bucks on the NBA and the NFL. But during Derby Week, everybody gets
a little horse crazy. Here are a few video winners.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A Day at the Races'' (1937).
</P>
<P>
   The Marx Brothers do for the backstretch what they did for the
arias in their hit ``A Night at the Opera.'' Allan Jones, an
``Opera'' alum, plays a horse owner who dreams of winning the big
race. Maureen O'Sullivan (Tarzan's mate and Mia Farrow's mom) is
his dream girl. Harpo plays a jockey. Chico is a tout who pretends
to sell ice cream (``Get your tutsi frutsi ice cream!''). And
Groucho is a shady vet who woos wealthy Margaret Dumont. Near the
end he swears his affection for her saying, ``Marry me and I'll
never look at another horse.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Thoroughbreds Don't Cry'' (1937).
</P>
<P>
   Judy Garland and Mickey Rooney really do put on a show in a
barn. A barn on the backstretch at Santa Anita (replicated on the
MGM backlot down to the last bale of hay). He's a big-headed,
sometimes crooked jockey and she's a true believer who lives with
her aunt, Sophie Tucker. This was their first film together and the
chemistry was so apparent that one reporter recalls seeing mogul
Louis B. Mayer leaving an early screening ``with the air of a man
heading to the pari-mutuel window to place a bet on a sure thing.''
In this case, the sure thing led to seven more Garland-Rooney
movies.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Story of Seabiscuit'' (1949).
</P>
<P>
   A quaint reminder that once upon a time, lightning-fast nags
were as famous as any pro athlete (and none were ever tried for
solicitation, rape or murder). Barry Fitzgerald plays the fleet,
four-legged champ's very Irish trainer, and Shirley Temple, making
the transition from child star to love interest, provided the name
above the title (never mind that by the time the movie was filming,
she was a wife, mother and soon-to-be divorcee). In her
autobiography, Temple sums up the entire enterprise pretty well as
``a movie for anyone wanting to know all about Seabiscuit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Casey's Shadow'' (1978).
</P>
<P>
   Director Martin Ritt once again demonstrates his ability to
inject ambience and texture into small-scale stories. Walter
Matthau is a struggling Louisiana horse trainer, raising three sons
on a wing, a prayer, a Bud and a belief in a horse that'll put him
in the winner's circle. Matthau's performance is a small gem, and
Ritt makes us feel the dust and dashed dreams that hover around
little no-name tracks where the purses are small but the effort _
and the dreams _ are as huge as those of any Triple Crown
contender.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Phar Lap'' (1983).
</P>
<P>
   A story like this probably belongs on something like ``Mysteries
and Scandals of the Sports World.'' In the '30s, a Down Under race
horse named Phar Lap became an international star and headed to
America to beat the best. Instead, the animal died under mysterious
circumstances (I'm not ruining anything; that's how the film
begins). Was the death accidental or foul play? Director Simon
Wincer (``Eraser,'' ``Free Willy'') toys with several
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Black Stallion'' (1979).
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't seen it, see it. If you have, see it again.
Carroll Ballard's adaptation of Walter Farley's children's classic
about a wild stallion and the boy who could tame him is a true
classic that transcends age and genre.
</P>
<P>
   DVD NOTE:
</P>
<P>
   ``National Velvet,'' the 1945 classic about the horse-crazy
British girl (Elizabeth Taylor) who disguises herself as a boy to
ride in the Grand National Steeplechase, comes to DVD without any
special features. Frankly, it doesn't need any. The chance to see
this state-of-the-studio-art as it originally looked is a bonus in
and of itself. It's difficult to say which is more gorgeously
glowing _ the lush green countryside or the 11-year-old Taylor's
flawless complexion. Horsey-set note: The horse she rides in the
film was a grandson of Man O'War.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
