<HEADER>
A6351 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-ELIZABETH29-COX     04-28 0227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ELIZABETH29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A royally riveting Elizabethan romp
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Elizabeth'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   An old-fashioned bodice-ripper tricked out with some '90s
feminist trappings, this melodrama about England's greatest queen
is mainly a chance to soak in star Cate Blanchett's presence. For
all the skullduggery and glittering costumes _ not to mention seven
Oscar nominations this year, including a nod for best picture _
she's the one who carries the movie.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, it's the tale of a spirited young lass who chooses a
sort of living death for the sake of her country. Given that, it
makes sense that the movie is shot with the shadowy gloom that
seems equal parts Hammer Horror and MTV.
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for historical accuracy here. Instead, admire a
supporting cast of scoundrels, including Joseph Fiennes as
Blanchett's deceptively sweet suitor, Sir John Gielgud in a
blink-or-miss-him cameo as the pope and Geoffrey Rush (in the role
that should've earned his Oscar nomination; instead he got one for
``Shakespeare in Love'') as the shrewd adviser who keeps
Elizabeth's head from landing where her mother's did, on the
chopping block.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
