<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Happiness'' (unrated) _ ``Happiness'' may be the most ironic
movie title of the '90s. This controversial film is a bleak,
unsparing and yet relentlessly comic look at several residents of
New Jersey whose lives are defined by sexuality, including the
pedophilia of a family man played by Dylan Baker. Writer-director
Todd Solondz says he prefers the expression ``sad comedy'' to
``black comedy,'' but ``Happiness'' is about as dark as they come.
Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Taste of Cherry'' (unrated) _ A sad-eyed middle-aged man
(Homayon Ershadi) circles the sandy roads outside Teheran, Iran,
seeking a stranger to do a very specific task. Symbolic and slow,
this award-winning Iranian film isn't for all tastes. But Abbas
Kiarostami's patient, elemental direction exerts a pull that
transforms the simplicity of the tale into something profound. With
subtitles. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``At First Sight'' (PG-13) _ Val Kilmer plays a blind man who
regains his sight. But this fact-based drama never finds its focus.
Mira Sorvino plays Kilmer's new love, but the chemistry between the
stars is as bleak and gray as the wintry setting. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Stepmom'' (PG-13) _ Susan Sarandon and Julia Roberts play
competing moms _ one biological, the other step _ in this
comedy/weepie that tackles some complex ``blended family'' issues,
then cops out by giving a character a fatal disease. Still, the
sturdy cast does much to redeem the mush-headed script (add Ed
Harris in the dishonest role of doting dad who somehow never sees
his kids). Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Thief'' (R) _ This Russian fable of fathers and sons
will steal your heart. In 1952, as Stalin inflicts his style of
``paternalism'' on the Soviet Union, a young boy and his widowed
mom are wooed by a soldier (Vladimir Mashkov) who isn't what he
seems. As allegories go, this one's transparent. But the film's
considerable strength lies in its poetic vignettes, telling visual
details and three wonderful performances. With subtitles. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   Notable videos on sale
</P>
<P>
   Francois Truffaut: Fully restored, with new translations and
subtitles. ``The 400 Blows,'' ``Shoot the Piano Player,'' ``The
Last Metro,'' ``Confidentially Yours,'' ``Love on the Run,'' ``Two
English Girls,'' a VHS six-pack, $119.98; $19.98 per tape, $29.98
per DVD.
</P>
<P>
   TV: ``The X-Files'': ``Home/Herrenvolk,'' ``Unruhe/Paper
Hearts'' and ``Tunguska/Terma,'' $14.98 per tape, $39.98 for all
three. ``The Simpsons'': ``Mr. Lisa Goes to Washington/When
Flanders Failed,'' ``Bart the Murderer/Like Father, Like Clown,''
``Treehouse of Horror II/Lisa's Pony,'' $9.98 each.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel Gillespie write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
