<HEADER>
A6359 &Cx1f; tad-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-POLITICS-$ADV050     04-28 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-POLITICS-$ADV0502-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES FIND GOLD IN HIGH TECHNOLOGY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington, (f) financial and (p) political
categories
 &HT;    With contribution chart at end of story
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON --- Al Gore may not have invented the Internet, but
he is connecting to Silicon Valley. So far, the vice president has
pulled in hundreds of thousands of dollars from California's
high-tech corridor.
</P>
<P>
   And he is not alone. Nearly every presidential candidate is
tapping into support among the nation's growing tech elite, who
until recently have been minor players in national politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology community is playing a bigger and bigger role
in presidential politics,'' says Scott Olsen, director of campaign
finance at Common Cause, a Washington-based watchdog group. ``And
we expect that trend only to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   The technology community, flush with funds from a soaring stock
market, has a new-found interest in Washington as lawmakers turn
attention to policies that affect the computer and Internet
industries. And presidential hopefuls, eager to capitalize on this
interest, are hitting up wealthy tech mavens for support.
</P>
<P>
   The non-partisan Technology Network political action committee
(TechNet), Silicon Valley's first vessel for a foray into national
politics, has hosted an estimated 140 political events for state
and federal candidates in the last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other political groups, though, TechNet is bipartisan,
with teams supporting both Republican and Democratic candidates.
And it leverages its power by hosting events and bundling many
individual contributions to a particular candidate, rather than
dishing out the federal PAC limit of $5,000 a pop to individual
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Although the fund-raising frenzy is just underway, presidential
hopefuls filed quarterly reports with the Federal Election
Commission April 15 -- giving the first inkling of how candidates
are faring in the money chase.
</P>
<P>
   Gore leads the pack with $8.9 million raised, followed by George
W. Bush with $7.6 million. Democrat Bill Bradley places third with
a $4.3 million campaign war chest.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Responsive Politics, a non-partisan watchdog
group in Washington, estimates that technology contributions
accounted for about 7 percent of the nearly $21 million raised by
those three candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The organization could not analyze records of other candidates
because they were not filed electronically.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance experts say the early returns represent the tip
of the technology fund-raising iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   Many candidates are just organizing Silicon Valley teams and a
few have attended lucrative events in recent weeks that aren't
reflected in the April 15 reports.
</P>
<P>
   Gore already has raised roughly $600,000 from individuals who
listed their occupations as being in communications or electronics.
Individuals are limited to giving $1,000 to any one politician for
each election.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Responsive Politics estimates $75,250 of Gore's
money came from computer executives, including Netscape
Communications co-founder Marc Andreessen (cq) ($1,000 ), now with
America Online, and Michael Morris ($1,000), vice president and
general counsel of Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   These figures don't include another $400,000 raised for Gore in
early April at a Silicon Valley fund-raiser hosted by TechNet
founder John Doerr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The support for Gore is much deeper and broader than it
appears from these first numbers,'' says Wade Randlett, TechNet's
Democratic political director.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, however, has surprised some Silicon Valley observers,
pulling in roughly $1 million at an April 13 fund-raiser in a swank
San Francisco hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who spent a year teaching at Stanford University, has
garnered $19,925 in contributions from computer executives in 1999,
according to the Center for Responsive Politics. Supporters include
Steve Jobs ($1,000), of Apple Computer, and Daniel Case ($1,000),
of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, the brother of America Online Chairman Steve
Case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley made a lot of friends when he was living out here,''
says John Deikman, a managing partner of Bay City Capital in San
Francisco whose wife organized the April event. ``He spent a lot of
time with the high-tech community and he really learned how our
industry works.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say, however, that Bush should not be overlooked
either.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Bush has not left Texas during the state's
legislative session to travel to Silicon Valley, his supporters are
gearing up for big events in June.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Bush has received $67,750 from computer executives,
including contributions from Netscape Communications founder James
Barksdale ($1,000), and Gregory Slayton, ($1,000), founder of My
Software.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Kvamme, managing partner at the venture capital firm of
Kleiner Perkins Caufield and Byers in Menlo Park, Calif., said a
handful of Silicon Valley big-wigs and Bush supporters have flown
to Austin, Texas, to talk strategy with the governor.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush team is planning two big galas in Northern California,
on June 30 and July 1, at which they expect to raise the flag for
the Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Silicon Valley business leaders have offices in Austin,''
said Kvamme, ``They are very comfortable with what Bush is doing in
Texas. So there might be more Republican support than you would
expect.''
</P>
<P>
   High-tech executives tends to be libertarian, with less of a
party allegiance than other business leaders, Silicon Valley
political activists say. That means the field is still wide open
for candidates to line up support among the nation's newest group
of political players.
</P>
<P>
   The race for Silicon Valley's money is only beginning, says
Larry Makinson, executive director at the Center for Responsive
Politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the charmed industry and everyone is lining up to
take their money. They've got the picking (of candidates) to do.''
</P>
