<HEADLINE>
THOROUGHLY DESERVING HALL ENTRANT: WAYNE LUKAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ He may not be Mr. Nice Guy, but Tuesday D.
Wayne Lukas was all smiles as it was announced that he had been
elected to the National Thoroughbred Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas has had his disagreements with the Hall, most notably
concerning his eligibility. The former quarterhorse trainer was not
credited with being a full-time thoroughbred trainer until 1974,
and the Hall has a 25-year waiting period for trainers. While
acknowledging that there had been gaps in his career, Lukas, 63,
maintained that he trained his first thoroughbreds in the early
'60s, and he would threaten not to attend the event if he were
elected. But all was forgiven Tuesday, and Lukas, who will be
inducted Aug. 9 at Saratoga, could not have been more gracious.
</P>
<P>
   ``This honors the people who got me there,'' said Lukas. ``I
have six alumni, head trainers who learned under me, including two,
Bobby Barnett (Answer Lively) and Dallas Stewart (Kimberlite Pipe),
who will face me in the Derby Saturday. They all came out of this
program and they have really made a mark by doing well. They are my
guys. I've worked with a lot of good guys and a lot of good owners.
And I've been blessed with a lot of good horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I am most proud of is that, by August, my stable
will have won $200 million. That's a milestone, it's significant.
There are 49 sires standing in Kentucky alone that I trained and a
lot of mares who have `black type' (been in-the-money in stakes
races). That represents a lot of return to the people who I trained
for. Only the late, great Charlie Whittingham ever earned as much
as $100 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas is not at Churchill Downs solely to accept honors. He is
training two colts for the 125th running of the Kentucky Derby, Cat
Thief and Charismatic, and each has a legitimate chance. This will
mark the 19th consecutive Derby in which Lukas has been represented
and he's won three (Winning Colors, 1988; Thunder Gulch, '95, and
Grindstone '96).
</P>
<P>
   Cat Thief has not won this year but has been consistent, running
second twice (Fountain of Youth and Blue Grass), and third twice
(Hutcheson and Florida Derby). Charismatic, who once won a $62,500
claiming race, has redeemed himself with a fourth-place finish in
the Santa Anita Derby, the best prep of the season, and a strong
tally in the Lexington at Keeneland April 18. Owned by Overbrook
Farm, Cat Thief, a son of Storm Cat, will be ridden by Mike Smith;
while Charismatic, a son of Summer Squall, is owned by Bob and
Beverly Lewis, and will have the services of Chris Antley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident with my situation,'' said Lukas. ``I feel I've
done what I can. I may finish fifth or 15th, or maybe win it. We'll
see. My whole program with Cat Thief has been to try to improve
him. We've had a few wrinkles with him. We've double-dribbled a
couple of times. If we had changed a few things in the Fountain of
Youth and Florida Derby, he would have won them and been one of the
favorites for the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charismatic has just been exploding in the right direction.
That may be the best kind of horse to have for the Derby. When he
won the Lexington (at 12-1), it didn't surprise me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas is not among the many who see this field, certain to reach
the limit of 20 when post positions are drawn, as evenly matched.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are maybe six in here who seem like they can win it,''
said Lukas. ``They are the horses whose feet have been held to the
fire, the ones who have been tested. Both of (Bob) Baffert's horses
(General Challenge and Prime Timber) appear strong. Carl
(Nafzger's) horse (Vicar) has run well, and (Nick) Zito has a good
horse (Stephen Got Even). Plus mine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking at half a dozen. I'd be surprised if one of the
horses who have done less jumps up. It could be another Gato Del
Sol year'' _ lightly regarded Gato Del Sol paid $44.40 in 1982 _
``but I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
LUKAS'S HALL OF FAME NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
D. Wayne Lukas, who was named to throughbred racing's hall of fame
Tuesday, has compiled quite a few accomplishments: &QL; 
--Trained 19 Eclipse Award winning horses, the most champions of
any trainer. &QL; 
--Won 10 Triple Crown events. &QL; 
--Won six consecutive Triple Crown events with four horses,
beginning with the 1994 Preakness and Belmont with Tabasco Cat and
continuing with Thunder Gulch (Kentucky Derby), Timber Country
(Preakness and Belmont) and Grindstone (Kentucky Derby). &QL; 
--Won 13 Breeders' Cup races, the most of any trainer. &QL; 
--Leading money-winning trainer in the US 14 times. &QL; 
--Set one-year record for money earned, $17.8 million in 1988. &QL; 
--518 graded-stakes victories and 927 stakes overall. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
