<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FACE OFF' IS A CHANCE TO GAIN A VOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new weekly series of vignettes on Lifetime television is
tackling issues in women's sports. And as brief as they are, the
segments are already drawing a response akin to male-dominated
sports talk radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Face Off,'' which premiered April 11, features 52-second,
rapid-fire debates between co-hosts Christine Brennan and Mary
Murphy on topics such as whether ``lady'' in the name of women's
college teams is degrading (Brennan says yes, Murphy no) and
whether ballroom dancing should be an Olympic sport (both
emphatically _ too emphatically for some viewers _ agree it should
not).
</P>
<P>
   Viewers are then invited to weigh in with their opinions at
http://www.lifetimetv.com. After the ballroom dancing segment,
dozens did, not shying away from calling the co-hosts everything
from ``ignorant'' to ``men in drag.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stunned,'' said Murphy. ``I just got raked over the
coals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we're getting them riled,'' said Brennan.
</P>
<P>
   So is Brian Donlon, who came up with the show's concept. ``Mary
and Christine are getting killed, killed,'' said Donlon, vice
president of sports at Lifetime and instigator of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Not that every segment is expected, or intended, to draw the
kind of heated reaction the network got from ballroom dance fans.
``There are issues in women's sports,'' said Donlon, ``and I was
trying to come up with a way to tackle some of those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like sitting at my kitchen table at home, or
sitting at a bar watching a game disagreeing with someone,'' said
Murphy. ``It's the American way of discussing sports.''
</P>
<P>
   A new vignette will air each Sunday night at 10:45 p.m., and
replay four times during the week. This Sunday, Brennan and Murphy
will debate whether the weight of a woman athlete should be
included on programs and rosters if a man's weight is included for
the same sport.
</P>
<P>
   The co-hosts come to the show from different sporting realms.
Brennan, author of ``Inside Edge'' and ``Edge of Glory,'' two books
on figure skating, is a former Washington Post reporter and now a
USA Today columnist, while Murphy is the former head coach and
general manager of the WNBA's Sacramento Monarchs. Coincidentally,
the two were classmates at Northwestern University in the late
1970s, where Murphy was a basketball star and Brennan was managing
editor of the student newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Their shared background, said Brennan, eases the way for
spirited debate. ``You can get down and dirty,'' she said, ``when
you have that kind of respect that goes way back.''
</P>
<P>
   In an annoucement expected to be made Wednesday, the duo will
also be analysts on one of Lifetime's WNBA broadcast teams this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I don't want them disagreeing just for the sake of
disagreeing,'' said Donlon. ``This is Siskel and Ebert going to
women's sporting events.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Donlon said a little controversy is a good thing. ``It's
even sparked debate in my own house,'' he said. ``My wife doesn't
like them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Making the grade
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Providence College senior Gladys Ganiel of Harrington, Maine, is
a recipient of the NCAA's Walter Byers Scholarship. Ganiel, a
political science major with a cumulative grade-point average of
3.986, will receive $12,500, with which she plans to pursue a
doctorate at Trinity College in Dublin. During her career at
Providence, Ganiel, a standout in track and cross-country, has been
named an Academic All-Amnerica five times . . . The Massachusetts
Mad Dogs professional baseball team is adding a woman to its
roster. The Mad Dogs, based in Lynn, have signed Tammy Holmes, an
outfielder who played with the now-defunct Colorado Silver Bullets.
Holmes, who led the team in batting average (.341) and RBIs (42),
was on the volleyball team at the University of California at
Davis, and was trying to earn a spot in the ABL before it folded.
The Mad Dogs open their fourth season May 28 at Fraser Field in
Lynn against the Allentown (Pa.) Ambassadors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
