<SLUG> BC-WOM-WNBA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSING THE BUCKS NOT EASY IN WNBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The WNBA players finally appear ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of a tentative agreement two weeks ago proved
premature, as the deal was shelved last Thursday and the WNBA and
the players' union resumed negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   On a conference call Tuesday, player representatives voted on
the lastest proposals, and several players, including Pauline
Jordan of the Sacramento Monarchs, assumed the vote was positive.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Wheeler, the director of operations for the players'
association, told the callers that there was a majority vote but
did not indicate if it was up or down. The players will be
receiving their ballots for ratification by next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you could just tell it passed, because our reps were
saying, `It's a good deal; let's go play,' '' said Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Neither management nor the union would confirm the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The sides have been haggling ever since the players formed a
union last fall and sought their first collective bargaining
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed four-year pact, the minimum salary for
rookies and veterans will be increased from $15,000 to $25,000 for
rookies and $30,000 for veterans. The minimums would be increased
in 2002 to $30,000 for rookies and $40,000 for veterans.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits package includes year-round health and dental
benefits, pension, maternity benefits, and life insurance.
</P>
<P>
   But even Jordan, who will be earning more than her salary of
under $20,000 last year, sounded more resigned than overjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never be relieved when it doesn't add up to what the
company is making, but this is what we have to do for the time
being,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the first women's professional basketball
league, the American Basketball League, was formed. In 1997, the
WNBA was created under the auspices of the NBA. Last year, the ABL
folded and the WNBA owned a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   But, since last Thursday, the future of the surviving women's
league was in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The league's management-player relationship seemed to be
mimicking that of its male counterpart. Like the men's recent
experience, negotiations soon stalled. The men's season was cut
short by a lockout; the women's was in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   While there was no lockout, the league announced collective
bargaining talks were at an impasse last week, just nine days after
both sides had hailed the league's first contract.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was supposed to mark the league's third player draft.
Instead, management and players were huddled in conference rooms,
eying the clock and the calendar, mindful that the 32-game season
was scheduled to open June 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're continuing to talk, but there is no deal at this
point,'' said WNBA spokesman Mark Pray Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   WNBA president Val Ackerman said last week that ``if there is no
deal, we have no choice but to postpone the season indefinitely.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wheeler, one of the union's chief negotiators, said Monday
she was ``cautiously optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The major issues have not changed,'' said Wheeler. ``It's not
that they've come up with new issues, but the ones we have have to
be hammered out.''
</P>
<P>
   An executive committee of five players had been in on the
negotiations, and Billy Hunter of the NBA players' union has been
to about half of the meetings, according to players' association
spokesman Dan Wasserman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just sort of creeping toward the finish,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They edged closer Tuesday, although neither side would confirm
that the deal was completed.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Levy, an agent in New York who represents 33 WNBA players
and nine players who were with the ABL, said he was confident last
week that the settlement ``was a done deal.''
</P>
<P>
   So when the deal fell off the table last week, Levy said he was
stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like when you get that letter from Ed McMahon that says
you're a winner,'' he said. ``Then you open the envelope and
discover you have no rights at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that was an exaggeration, since the minimum salaries and
other major points were not contested. But there was still
wrangling over issues such as required player appearances and the
licensing agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Levy said that in addition to negotiating new contracts for the
WNBA players he represents, he also has to fight for his ABL
players who were left without a league in the middle of last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been through so much, and now this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do the players have to scramble for a spot on the
roster (under the new rules, each team can add three ABL players,
with the exception of the two expansion teams, which can draft
five), they also will be collecting much smaller paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ABL players were shocked when they learned they'd be
getting one-quarter, or one-fifth what they had been making,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the players make the minimum salary.
</P>
<P>
   Among the elite, who make a reported $200,000 and were
conspicuously silent when the negotiations broke down, are Rebecca
Lobo of the New York Liberty, Sheryl Swoopes of the Houston Comets,
and Lisa Leslie of the Los Angeles Sparks. Joining them this season
no doubt will be Tennessee star Chamique Holdsclaw, who graduates
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Cavalli, who was one of the founders and CEO of the ABL,
said he got no pleasure out of the fact that the WNBA was having
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the experience of the ABL shows that women's
basketball is very fragile,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take any joy in their troubles, and actually I feel
good about some things they got from the legacy of the ABL,'' he
said, citing the ABL's year-round medical benefits, its 401K plan,
and the establishment of a players' advisory board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are things that distinguished the ABL,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Curvy, who works for Bob Woolf Associates and represents
Kara Walters, formerly with the ABL's New England Blizzard and
currently on the national team, said Tuesday that he was confident
that a resolution was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This league is not going to fold,'' he said. ``They have the
backing of the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Which could be a good or a bad thing, based on the NBA's recent
labor problems.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who played her college ball at the University of
Nevada-Las Vegas and also played in Russia, Spain, and Italy,said
that when the league was formed the players were told ``they'd make
it so we don't have to go overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the mimimum salary rising only to $40,000 in 2002,
Jordan said that's hard to imagine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the two leagues would be separate, but when it came
time to negotiate, they are both the same,'' said Jordan. ``Our
league is the same, just with a W in front of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
