<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFESSIONS ON A BRIEF BIKINI FLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The thing is, they're really comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   No self-respecting American man would ever wear one in public,
of course. I wouldn't even walk out of the fitting room with one
on.
</P>
<P>
   But the bikini-bottom bathing suit I had wedged myself into felt
. . . good. Nice snug fit, without turning me into a soprano.
Support in spades.
</P>
<P>
   And despite worrying that I would look like the Pillsbury
Doughboy with a rubber band around his waist, I merely looked
chunky, a little thick.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, if I hadn't tried the suit on, I never would have known
the hygienically correct phenomenon familiar to every woman who has
ever tried on a swimsuit: the complementary try-on panty.
</P>
<P>
   (I didn't go to medical school, but it clearly wasn't designed
for men. Complete coverage was not attained. Let's just leave it at
that.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet the relatively pleasant, private experience I had in no way
changes the rule when it comes to who should wear bikini bottoms in
public:
</P>
<P>
   Supermodels and competitive swimmers only.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, as anyone who has ever visited any of the
nation's public beaches can tell you, many men _ most of them
European, judging from the accents _ openly defy this rule,
shoehorning themselves into tiny suits that cover almost nothing;
what they do cover is somehow . . . isolated, so that more
attention is drawn to it.
</P>
<P>
   Ugh. Kill the spotlight, Dieter. Some things need to be left to
the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   At least Americans think so. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lettin' it all hang out
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``American men are the only ones who wear the trunks,'' said
Jamie Hircock, the manager of Everything but Water, a swimsuit
store. ``We're so into image. You go down to Brazil, and you'll see
men in skimpier bikinis than some of the girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Note to self: Cross Brazil off potential vacation list.
</P>
<P>
   Hircock actually prefers trunks to briefs on men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think trunks are sexier,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That's one benefit. Another is the way they camouflage your
belly. Well, almost. But the bikini lets it all hang out, so to
speak.
</P>
<P>
   The occasional guy can get away with wearing one without
nauseating results. For instance, in his role as Fox Mulder on
``The X-Files,'' David Duchovny once wore a skintight red Speedo.
Think anyone noticed? Check out The David Duchovny Red Speedo Poems
Page (http://members.tripod.com/Wheelbarrow/speedo.html) for proof.
</P>
<P>
   In one offering, called ``Comet,'' a poet named Ree T writes,
``A red Speedo caresses his loins/like a comet caresses the night
sky. Blazing is its color/shocking is the speed with which it is
soon gone.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, it's not Shakespeare. But these suits do caress your loins,
and they do attract attention. &QL; 
Belly laughs
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I stayed in the dressing room. What else could you
do? Walk up to the sales clerk while wearing what looks like the
head cover for a golf club and ask if it fits properly? I was
afraid she would slap me. Or worse, laugh.
</P>
<P>
   I tried on a brand called Sauvage. Despite its skimpiness, the
suit goes for $39. It wasn't as humiliating as some of the suits
you see, which make it appear as if you're wearing a change purse.
The Sauvage gave me more of the look of an Olympic swimmer gone
badly to seed.
</P>
<P>
   Guys like anything worn below their waist _ trousers, shorts,
underwear, whatever _ to ride just below the belly button. The
bikini swimsuit rides a good five inches below, making it feel as
if something is missing. And it is _ the rest of the suit.
</P>
<P>
   It was while studying the topography of my belly that it
occurred to me: Since so much more is exposed, there is so much
more to find fault with.
</P>
<P>
   I was obsessing over my figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just what women do,'' Hircock said. ``It's so traumatic
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is another reason I'd never sport one of these suits in
public. Haven't these women suffered enough already? &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
