<SLUG> BC-BKN-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFFS MAY REDEEM THIS IRREGULAR SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1999 NBA season ends a week from Wednesday. It will go down
as an ill-advised attempt to squeeze 50 games into 80-something
days, an unqualified nightmare for even the most casual purist.
</P>
<P>
   The offense has been routinely lamentable, from the nightly
shooting horrors to the unthinkable 49-point submission by the
Chicago Bulls. In terms of sheer offensive futility, we haven't
seen anything like this in a generation. Players were out of shape,
coaches were out of sorts, and everything was out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it seemed. Yes, some individual and team
(itals)statistical(unitals) marks are at an all-time low. The
league's leading scorer will have the lowest per-game average since
that stat became the benchmark in 1969-70. (Before that, it was
total points.) For the first time since 1953-54, the last year with
no shot clock, we may have a season in which no team averages 100
points. There undoubtedly are other lowlights.
</P>
<P>
   But as the season winds down, we look at the
(itals)standings(unitals) and we wonder how different it would have
been had there been a real, 82-game season. Rick Pitino might try
to convince you otherwise, but the reality is that the NBA could
have adopted a 20-game season, a 40-game season, or a one-game
shootout and you'd still likely see the teams where they are today.
</P>
<P>
   Out West, the biggest surprise is probably Portland's ascension,
although the Blazers figured to be better with the acquisitions
they made. But Utah is still the king until proven otherwise and
the Jazz, at last glance, held the top spot, albeit precariously.
San Antonio? We figured they'd be good, and they are. Houston? We
figured they'd be there, and they seem to be.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers? Well, has there been any more satisfying sight to
watch from afar than the implosion of Jerry Buss's favorite toy?
Sure, they might magically get their act together for the
postseason, but that would represent a turnaround of staggering
proportions. This is a team that has just come off losses of 27 and
22 points to the Spurs and Rockets, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The East hasn't produced many surprises, either. We all had
Indiana pegged as the team to beat, and while they've wavered, the
Pacers are still in the hunt and leading the Central Division. Most
of us picked Miami to win the Atlantic Division, and that's
probably what's going to happen. Orlando and New Jersey are the
biggest surprises, for opposite reasons. The Knicks? They're the
Lakers of the East.
</P>
<P>
   While the teams inevitably sorted their way to their respective
stations, it is the players who've really borne the brunt of the
truncated schedule. They were asked to be ready with virtually no
training camp and that was only after they'd spent weeks reading
and hearing about the unlikeliness of any season at all.
</P>
<P>
   Then they were greeted with a schedule unlike anything they'd
seen before. At first, it didn't look all that bad. When Larry Bird
passed through town a week ago, he said he initially thought the
schedule was a bonus. Upon further review, Bird conceded, ``It's
beyond imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   NBA players are no different from most other highly skilled
workers: They need time to hone those skills. Imagine Keith
Lockhart moving the Pops around like an NBA team this season with
no time for the oboes to get their act together. That's the biggest
downside to the season. The players weren't ready when it started
and many still aren't ready now that it's almost over. Where's
Ralph Nader when you really need him?
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on, as a player, I thought to myself, `This is going to
be great,' '' the Pistons' Jud Buechler said Tuesday. ``There are
no practices! I'd much rather play games. But that's what has hurt
the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, the toughest thing is not practicing. If you're
playing great, on a roll, in a rhythm, bring on the games. But if
you're not, if your shot's not there, if your team is not clicking,
if you're losing, you need practice. There's no practice time.
That's been the toughest thing.''
</P>
<P>
   We know coaches would tell us _ they have been telling us _ that
a lack of practice time has been the biggest hurdle. How refreshing
to hear it from a player. In its rush to get in games, not to
mention placate its broadcast allies, the NBA tried to put the
toothpaste back into the tube.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been much more logical to extend the season into
July. Or to eliminate a round of the playoffs. But NBC wouldn't go
for a season in July because people supposedly don't watch
television in the summer. The owners wouldn't accept a loss of
playoff revenue. So the game lost.
</P>
<P>
   This will all be forgotten, and quite soon. The playoffs begin a
week from Saturday and then, and only then, will NBA life assume a
degree of normalcy. Teams in the hunt will luxuriate at the thought
of playing one opponent over a span of several days with minimal
travel. Coaches will have time to prepare. The quality of play may
even improve when, in the past, it has tended to deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that will be the lasting lesson of this season. Skeptics
always have said that the regular season is meaningless anyway.
They may have had their point driven home by what we just saw in
the last three months _ and what we're about to see in the ensuing
two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6369 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARENT-LIABILITY-BOS &LR;      04-28 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENT-LIABILITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWS HOLDING PARENTS LIABLE GAINING GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When a recent under-age beer party in suburban
Washington got a little rowdy, the police came and gave warning
citations to the teenage drinkers while slapping a $1,000 fine on
each of the parent-hosts.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is common across the country: A growing number of
state laws and local ordinances are holding parents accountable and
financially liable for their children's illegal, malicious, or
destructive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally understandable,'' said Martha Minow, a professor
at Harvard Law School. ``People want an explanation and someone to
blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, a week after the Littleton, Colo., high-school massacre
and in response to it, President Clinton upped the ante on blame.
He proposed making it a federal felony for adults to either
knowingly or recklessly allow youngsters to possess guns that are
later used to kill or injure another person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to redefine the national community so that we have
shared obligation to save children's lives, and we've got to get
out of this crazy denial that this won't make a difference,'' said
the president, flanked by 40 members of Congress who showed support
for his package of gun-control measures.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that parents could go to jail for the crimes of their
children isn't quite so popular with some criminal attorneys, who
fear the federal law could be selectively enforced. Many family
therapists are lukewarm, too, saying parents might be more
reluctant to intervene with troubled youngsters if they feared the
involvement could incriminate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is going to stop kids who are out of
control,'' said Dr. Victor Strasburger, a professor of pediatrics
at the University of New Mexico. ``Threats are meaningless to the
parents who are disorganized and inadequate, and they aren't going
to help the parents who are trying to do the best job they know how
in raising extraordinarily difficult kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Strasburger, the author of ``Getting Your Kids to Say No in the
'90s When You Said Yes in the '60s,'' said baby-boomer parents who
``stopped the Vietnam War should be able to stop the war on the
nation's playgrounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet many baby-boomer legislators have helped enact criminal laws
in 13 states in the last decade to punish parents whose child
commits a crime. Those criminal laws have been enforced less than
the more popular civil parental-responsibility laws that impose
fines on parents of children who drink alochol under age or commit
acts of vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, where Columbine High School seniors Eric Harris and
Dylan Klebold allegedly gunned down 12 students and a teacher
before killing themselves, the parents could be subject to two to
six years in jail if it were proved they permitted the boys to
possess a firearm and there was ``substantial risk'' it could be
used in a felony. Under Colorado law, the parents could not be held
responsible for the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that seemed to be just what Jefferson County Sheriff John
Stone was suggesting when he said, ``Parents should be held
accountable for their kids' actions,'' after bomb-making materials
and the barrel of a sawed-off shotgun were found in Harris's home
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I would be a little concerned about my son's room if I
went in there and I found a sawed-off shotgun barrel,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Soler, president of the Youth Law Center, a private,
nonprofit group, called the White House initiative on parents and
guns ``a good idea'' because it sends parents a strong message
about the high cost of ignoring warning signs in their children. As
a practical matter, he said, it also makes adults suffer the
consequences if they are careless and reckless with the weapons
they own.
</P>
<P>
   Minow, an expert in family law, called the president's proposal
``a symbolic action that comes too late in the day'' and would have
little practical effect in curbing youth violence and alienation.
It also poses the danger of selective prosecution of adults and the
``perverse effect'' of possibly putting more distance between
parents and children, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most constructive thing the law can do is support
preventive practices,'' Minow said. ``We need to address the
central issue for every kid, which is the absence of sustained
contact in the life of an adult.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Harris and Klebold died in the Columbine rampage, the
search for answers to what went wrong in Littleton starts with
their parents. James Alan Fox, dean of the College of Criminal
Justice at Northeastern University, said it is both normal and
unfair to blame them for the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People point fingers at the parent and say, ``Why didn't you
see it coming?' or `Why didn't you heed the warning signs?''' said
Fox, who is a member of the president's advisory committee on
school shootings. ``Often, the red flags are only crystal clear in
the aftermath. Rather than pointing fingers, we should embrace
families. This is a really sad thing for them, and we should assist
them, not assail them.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Knight, director of cultural studies at the conservative
Family Research Council, said it could be nonsense to hold parents
responsible for their child's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if a kid drives the family car into a crowded store?
Should the parents be held liable?'' Knight said. ``You have to
look at it case by case. Not every parent is negligent because a
kid has turned out to be a bad apple.''
</P>
<P>
   California in 1988 passed a law to make parents liable for acts
of gang violence. The measure proved unworkable, according to
Soler, because prosecutors could not persuade courts that the
parents were responsible for, much less able to control, the
criminal behavior of their offspring.
</P>
<P>
   But laws can serve purposes other than putting mom and dad
behind bars. For some, parental-responsibility laws might provide
both a wake-up call and a crutch to put busy parents in touch with
their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is enormous concern, and should be in our
country, about the extent to which parents are not involved with
their children or aware of what is going on in their lives,'' said
Dr. Steven Marans, a child psychoanalyst at Yale University's Child
Studies Center and also a member of Clinton's committee on school
shootings. Some parents ``really do need support to pay attention,
including the support of the law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6371 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-MEDICINE-BOS &LR;      04-28 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-MEDICINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO SPORTS DEALS ARE A NEW GAME FOR HEALTH CARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doughnut makers and shoe peddlers learned decades ago that
advertising on ballpark billboards and scoreboards let them tap
into the magical selling power of professional sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   More recently Fortune 500 firms, from utilities to computer
suppliers, have gotten into the game, offering deals on electricity
and e-commerce in return for the right to say they're the
ballclub's official supplier.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a different lineup of players aggressively pitching
their wares via sports celebrities: hospitals, doctors, and other
health providers.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Giants will be paid $15 million by Catholic
Healthcare West, while the Boston Celtics are teaming up with New
England Baptist Hospital. And lots of other clubs in hockey and
basketball, football and baseball, are forging their own alliances
in ways that are raising disturbing ethical questions. Some
analysts say it's a slippery slope for the teams, which might be
tempted to put money ahead of competence when they endorse or hire
doctors; others insist it's unseemly for health-care companies to
spin their services in a way that seems to trivialize their mission
of saving lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new thing and it's troubling,'' said Dr. Frank Jobe,
whose 35 years with the Los Angeles Dodgers make him the dean of
Major League physicians. ``You just wonder if you're always getting
the best doctor when you take the highest bidder.''
</P>
<P>
   George Annas, a health lawyer and medical ethicist at the Boston
University School of Public Health, is even more distressed by the
trend: ``It's a sign of the times for medicine, which are bad right
now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no rationale, not even a pretext of a rationale, that
if I need somebody to diagnose me I should go to the person who
works for the Celtics. It's like the British buying from the vacuum
cleaner company for the queen, which gets to put the royal seal on
its vacuum . . . We don't have kings and queens here, but we have
professional sports teams, they're our celebrities.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph DiLorenzo, the Celtics' senior vice president for
administration, said he understands the concerns yet feels they
aren't warranted with his team. ``We have given Baptist that
ability to call themselves our official health-care provider,'' he
said. ``Baptist is the preeminent sports-medicine hospital in the
region, if not the country . . . but we have the ability to get any
treatment we deem needed regardless of the source.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time questions of conflict have arisen
between pro teams and their physicians. The issue is perpetually
cited with Dr. Arthur Pappas, the Red Sox doctor who's also a
part-owner, and with every team that puts a physician on its
payroll even as it tries to reassure players that the doctor
represents them, not the team.
</P>
<P>
   It's also not the first time hospitals and HMOs have raised
hackles by aggressively peddling their products in the increasingly
cost-competitive, consumer-sensitive world of American medicine. In
New England, cancer patients are taking to the airwaves to endorse
their favorite facility while slick brochures feature faces of fat
people made thin through anti-obesity programs.
</P>
<P>
   The latest deals between teams and health-care providers,
however, raise new concerns about clubs' relationships to their
medical staffs _ and about how far hospitals should go in using
glitz to sell their services.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Giants are on the cutting edge of that debate
as they prepare to move into their new stadium a year from now. In
addition to plush seats and great views, Pac Bell Park will have a
6,200-square-foot medical clinic that provides rehabilitation and
other services to nearby homes and businesses, as well as to the
Giants. The new arrangement, under which Catholic Healthcare will
pay the team about $15 million over 10 years, is an outgrowth of an
existing deal where the health firm runs special days at the
ballpark, advertises on billboards, and is part of the Giants' Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of marketing, our new relationship with the Giants
will be a tremendous leap forward; it would take us 10 years to
generate the kind of awareness we'll get with this relationship,''
said Robert Polzoni, vice president of communications at Catholic
Healthcare. ``The provision of health care to the team is a
separate issue from our partnership . . . If we don't do a good job
they have every right to find someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   That's generally the way it works with marriages between teams
and health companies, from the Jacksonville Jaguars to the
Philadelphia Eagles, Tennessee Titans and Orlando Magic. The club
gets money and services in return for letting the company advertise
that it is the official health-care provider. The doctor treating
the team, meanwhile, almost always is affiliated with that company
but is paid by the team.
</P>
<P>
   That's a big switch from the old setup, where teams simply went
out and looked for the best doctor. And it has caught on to the
point where the National Hockey League says that 18 of its 27 teams
have some sort of sponsorship arrangement with a health-care
company.
</P>
<P>
   But do such deals pose problems?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an area which could be fraught with issues if teams and
hospitals enter into arrangements where the only reason the
hospital or physician is providing services is because of some
compensation or marketing arrangement,'' said Lou Woolf, executive
vice president at New England Baptist, which recently completed a
$32.5 million training center in Waltham that the Celtics will use
for the next 12 years, in return for tickets, advertising, and
other non-cash payments. Baptist also gets the reflected glory of
letting its paying customers work out near the Celtics, and of
having its doctors be the team's doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The new Baptist-Celtics deal shouldn't pose any conflicts, said
Woolf, because ``for the last 12 years Baptist has provided the
Celtics with services which they decided year after year to keep
utilizing totally independently of any marketing arrangements.''
And while Celtics' team doctor Arnold Scheller is affiliated with
Baptist, Woolf said, ``he's totally independent of'' the new
marketing arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Yet other teams, including the Giants, have switched doctors as
a result of their new financial arrangements with hospitals. ``It
just strikes me that if doctors are chosen at least partly because
they put up money for the team, it puts them in an awkward position
to give unbiased care,'' said Dr. William E. Straw, who was the
Giants' doctor for 13 seasons and whose medical group represented
the team for 25 years until last season, when the team signed on
with Catholic Healthcare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also puts the team in an awkward position: If its doctors
don't give good care would the team look the other way?'' asked
Straw. ``The Giants gave us the same offer they gave Catholic
Healthcare West, to put up $15 million, and we said, `No, thank
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Some clubs appear to be sufficiently concerned about such
conflicts, or at least the appearance of them, that they won't
reveal details of their deals with health companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't see where it would be necessary or appropriate
to comment on the elements of our contract'' with Baptist/St
Vincent's Health System, said Dan Connell, senior vice president
for marketing of the Jacksonville Jaguars. ``But I can assure you
that at no time have or will the Jacksonville Jaguars compromise
getting and providing the best health care for our players or our
staff.''
</P>
<P>
   An Orlando Magic spokeswoman, meanwhile, declined to discuss the
team's health-care arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   But information that is available gives some in the medical
world pause. ``Our official position is that we praise teams that
come down on the side of quality and refuse to let too many
competing interests get in the way of their selection of doctors,
but the fact is that as business owners they do have competing
interests,'' said Marc Allen, vice president of the Association of
Professional Team Physicians, a consumer education group
representing more than 250 doctors working with pro clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Altchek, team doctor for the New York Mets, also is
concerned: ``It's very common now for doctors to pay to be the team
doctor, and they're like sponsors of the team. That's where the
conflict comes in. They're not just there because they're the best
doctor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
