<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6374 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KING-GORDON-ART-BOS &LR;      04-28 1595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-GORDON-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPHEN KING HOMERS OFF TOM GORDON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos (2) are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lost in the Maine woods, 9-year-old Trisha McFarland battles
hunger, fatigue, marauding insects, and worse in a desperate effort
to stay alive. Her sole link to civilization: a portable radio on
which she listens to Red Sox games and to the exploits of her hero,
ace relief pitcher Tom Gordon. Gordon becomes the girl's personal
inspiration and, as time and hope both slip away, her imaginary
trail guide, too.
</P>
<P>
   Trisha is the title character in ``The Girl Who Loved Tom
Gordon,'' frightmeister Stephen King's new novel, which debuted
last week at No. 2 on The New York Times bestseller list. This
being King's world, Trisha must also contend with a spectral beast
of awesome power and malevolent intent. (No, not George
Steinbrenner. Even scarier.) Because King metaphorically milks the
closer's function _ to save his team's hide in the late stages of a
ballgame _ for all it's worth, you can bet your 1986 Bill Buckner
card as well that Trisha's fate will go to a full count in the
bottom of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Other prominent authors have woven real-life figures into their
fiction, to be sure. E. L. Doctorow in ``Ragtime,'' for one. W. P.
Kinsella, for another, in the peerless baseball novel ``Shoeless
Joe,'' from which ``Field of Dreams'' was made. And while charming
enough and flattering to the pitcher, Gordon's role in the King
novel is not going to make many lit majors forget Lewis Carroll's
White Rabbit. (Rabbit Maranville and Clay Carroll, maybe.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, the pairing of King and Gordon seems supernaturally
provident to millions of New Englanders. One, because King is one
of us _ a monster of a Red Sox fan himself. And two, because
``Flash'' Gordon happens to hold the most hair-raising job on the
planet's most divinely challenged baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   (Cubs fans, feel free to stop reading here.)
</P>
<P>
   So what does Gordon think of his induction into literary
immortality? We put that question to the two principals, author and
save artist, in a conference call not long ago, just hours before
Gordon landed on the disabled list with an inflamed elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a man like Stephen King to do something like this is truly
a blessing to me and my family,'' said Gordon, who was ``most of
the way'' through King's 224-page novel at the time.
</P>
<P>
   (We won't tell him how it ends.
</P>
<P>
   (Nor will we blame King for Gordon's elbow woes. We believe the
interview and mysterious injury were an eerie coincidence. Not The
Curse of the Bangor-bino or some such nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   (Really.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all my family is talking about,'' continued Gordon. ``I'm
very excited about it. I'm just grateful it was Stephen King doing
this and not somebody pulling a prank.''
</P>
<P>
   King broke in, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm just glad I didn't decide to do `The Girl Who Loved
Darryl Strawberry,' '' he quipped, referring to the New York Yankee
outfielder who was recently busted on charges of cocaine possession
and soliciting a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was writing a short story,'' he added. ``So I
never thought much about the name issue until it grew into a novel.
At that point I figured I'd better get in touch with Tom and see if
it would be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   King confirmed that the germ of his story (``Hansel and Gretel
with just Gretel around,'' as he described it) was the idea of
someone specializing in pressure situations, as Gordon does. At one
point King has Trish begging, ``God, if You can't be a Red Sox fan,
be a Tom Gordon fan.'' You don't have to be a Harvard Divinity
School graduate to understand how that line resonates with Red Sox
Nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem to go through much of our lives not thinking about God
until we get into a real jam,'' King observed. ``Then we're praying
for somebody to come along and get us out of trouble. The idea of
closing a ballgame began to merge in my mind with the idea of this
girl being lost in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I started to notice that Tom points to the sky when
he finishes a ballgame, which to me says, `I saved the game by the
grace of God.' Since I wanted to say something about God in this
book, Tom seemed like the perfect person for this girl to have as
her hero. I was delighted to find out he was a good guy, too. I
figured he was, but I hadn't met him before writing the book.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon smoothly fielded the compliment and tossed it back in
King's direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very appreciative of what Stephen has done,'' he said.
``My teammates ask me lots of questions about (King). Now they'll
probably be less shy about going up and talking to him. I tell them
he's one of the best people I've ever met. We didn't get a chance
to go fishing yet, but we sure are going to. Stephen came down to
my house this winter and we had a great time. I'm looking forward
to taking him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was converted from so-so starter to stellar reliever two
seasons ago. Last summer _ King's story takes place in June of 1998
_ Gordon set a major-league record for consecutive saves (43). His
total of 46 led the American League and established a new
single-season mark for Boston pitchers. Gordon, who lives in Avon
Park, Fla., during the off-season, was toiling in a spring training
game last year when inspiration struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just came to me,'' he said of his signature
index-finger-to-the-sky finish on the mound. ``I've always believed
in God, that he's blessed me with a certain strength and ability.
For a while I didn't think about it much. But then people started
to bring it up and ask me why I do it. That's just the way I see
things, I guess. The first thing I do when I get up every morning
is thank God for what he's given me.''
</P>
<P>
   King is the author of more than 30 novels and short story
collections, all of them extra-base hits. He is wealthy enough to
be mentioned in all seriousness as a future owner of the Red Sox,
should the team come up for sale. A resident of Bangor, Maine, King
and his wife, Tabitha, also a well-regarded writer, spent their
first winter out of New England this year. Taking a house in
Longboat Key, Fla., the Kings happily accepted an invitation to
meet the Gordon family, which includes Tom's mother and his five
children, aged 3 to 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got to Avon Park, it felt just like home _ except warm
and with orange trees,'' sais King. ``Tom took us to a local
restaurant and it seemed like everyone in there knew him. We went
to the local high school where he works out with the baseball team,
stuff like that. It's a small town with a family feel to it, and
that made me feel very comfortable, because that's where I come
from. There's a lake across from his mother's house and Tom's got a
great-looking boat. I'm looking forward to going out fishing with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   But, said King, of the proposed fishing trip, ``you can't make
fun of me, Tom. I haven't done it in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said that when he started reading King's book and
thinking about a little girl alone in the woods, he flashed back
(no pun intended) to his own childhood. What was his scariest
moment as a kid?
</P>
<P>
   Gordon: ``My scariest moment was going into the woods to hunt
for treasure and running into these pirates, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he have any imaginary friends?
</P>
<P>
   Gordon: ``There were so many kids in our neighborhood, I didn't
need any. I always imagined myself as Superman, though. All the
kids imagined they were some superhero or other.''
</P>
<P>
   Does King's story make himthink twice about going hiking in the
woods with his own kids?
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, laughing: ``I've never been big on hiking, anyway. I
might try a trail or two, but I don't think I could stay out all
night. And I don't go in the woods much anymore because they pretty
much knocked them all down where I live in Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Since King brought up the subject of God, we asked the writer if
he was praying for the Sox to keep Gordon, given the team's
unfortunate history of letting star players go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' said King. ``When Mo Vaughn went _ it's not a
question that they can't play without Mo, they've already proven
they can win games without him. It's more a case of getting to like
a guy, of him starting to feel like family in a way. So no, I hope
that doesn't happen with Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   Added King, ``Certainly it never crossed my mind while writing
this book to ask what Tom's contract situation was. Hopefully,
we'll be rooting for Tom Gordon in a Red Sox uniform for many years
to come. And I'd root for you anyway, Tom. Unless you were playing
against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon: ``I appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, King was asked about the fate of Fenway Park (talk
about spine-tingling suspense yarns) and the ownership of a
franchise that has not won a World Series since the days of H. P.
Lovecraft. King sounded fatalistic on the future of the olde ball
yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fenway is old and not user-friendly in a lot of ways,'' he
admitted. ``But it's a place I love. The good thing about Boston
is, the politicians, business leaders, and labor unions are so
screwed up, it will probably be five years before anybody can turn
a spade on a new stadium anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Does King realize that if he buys a piece of the Red Sox, he
could wind up as ``The Man Who Owned Tom Gordon''?
</P>
<P>
   King, howling: ``Oh, man. I just want to go fishing with him. I
don't want to boss him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
