u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-BOS &LR;      04-28 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC GESTURES ARE VIEWED AS UNLIKELY TO END DEADLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A political solution to the conflict in Yugoslavia
is likely to remain elusive, despite a flurry of diplomatic efforts
this week and overtures by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
such as allowing the Red Cross to visit three POWs, foreign policy
experts said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's latest gesture _ permitting the Rev. Jesse Jackson
to lead a religious delegation, scheduled to leave Wednesday for
Belgrade to visit the POWs _ was part of the Serb leader's effort
to divide NATO and split American public opinion about the
conflict, the US and British analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a small move, it makes him look good in his own domestic
propaganda war, to show he's playing by the rules and that NATO is
the aggressor,'' said Joshua S. Goldstein, professor of
international politics and foreign policy at American University.
</P>
<P>
   But Goldstein and other analysts said the United States is
playing its own games, too, including using the Russians to broker
a deal with Milosevic to end the conflict but without giving Moscow
room to maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Susan L. Woodward, senior fellow in foreign policy studies at
the Brookings Institution and an expert on the Balkans, said the
Russians can't ``completely violate their own interests or just act
as a kind of lap dog of NATO. They've got to have something to work
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the current stalemate, Woodward and other analysts
forecast a lengthy conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't easily see any negotiated solution in the near
future,'' said Anatol Lieven, a fellow at the Institute for
Strategic Studies, a London-based think tank that focuses on
national security.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the signals from Yugoslavia have been mixed. After
holding the POWs nearly a month, Milosevic allowed the Red Cross to
visit and now presumably the US delegation led by Jackson. One of
Milosevic's deputy prime ministers, Vuk Draskovic, earlier this
week fueled speculation about the weaknesses of the Serb military
by saying that NATO's bombing campaign had ravaged Kosovo and that
his government was prepared to accept a UN force that would include
NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Milosevic allowed a second visit by representatives of
the International Committee of the Red Cross with the three US
soldiers, who were captured March 31 along the Macedonia-Kosovo
border. US officials, however, complained that the POWs had been
denied their full visitation rights under international law.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic also is permitting Jackson and Joan Brown Campbell,
general secretary of the National Council of Churches, to enter
Belgrade to visit with the soldiers. They are leading about a dozen
interfaith leaders on what Jackson called ``a pilgrimage of faith,
not of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said the Yugoslav ambassador to the United Nations,
Vladislav Jovanovic, has assured their visit with the POWs. The
group plans to take Bibles and tape-recorded and written messages
from the soldiers' families. She said Yugoslav authorities told
them they will also be allowed to videotape the soliders.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's Under Secretary of State, Thomas R.
Pickering, met with the group Monday night and said the
administration ``can't bless'' the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Though Campbell could not confirm whether the group would meet
with Milosevic, she said the ministers would urge the release of
the POWs if they did.
</P>
<P>
   She also said the religious leaders were not ``naive'' about
Milosevic's motives. ``They have a propoganda machine. We all do,
and I think there's every likelihood that he will try to use this
for his own purposes in his own country,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   David Leavy, a spokesman for the National Security Council, said
US officials could not ``guarantee safe passage for private
citizens'' to Belgrade, but ``we will do everything within our
power to make sure that Reverend Jackson's mission is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatic efforts have increased since NATO's three-day summit
here ended Sunday without an agreement on sending ground troops
into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy secretary of state, Strobe Talbott, left Moscow
Tuesday after meetings with former Prime Minster Viktor S.
Chernomyrdin, Russia's special envoy on Kosovo, and Foreign
Minister Igor S. Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   UN Secretary General Kofi Annan is scheduled to arrive in Russia
later this week, and in the past few days, phone conversations have
taken place between Clinton and Russian President Boris N. Yeltsin,
Vice President Al Gore and Chernomyrdin and Tuesday, between
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright and Ivanov. The foreign
ministers of Greece and Canada also are due in Moscow this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to see this issue resolved diplomatically, if
diplomatic ways and means can be found that lead to Serb acceptance
of our political objectives,'' said State Department spokesman
James P. Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   But those objectives _ that Serb forces leave Kosovo, allow the
refugees to return, and accept an international security force with
NATO at its core _ ``are unshakable,'' Rubin said. ``There is no
compromise on those objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieven of the Institute for Strategic Studies in London said,
``If Russia is actually going to negotiate a compromise, then
clearly NATO has to be prepared to compromise on something or NATO
has to be prepared to go on fighting until the Serbs are
defeated.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's no good thinking that Russia is going to pull
some kind of a magical hat on this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6380 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-28 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP STUDIES VARYING RELIGIONS AND BELIEFS AS A WHOLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spend any time these days delving into what's hot on the
religious and spiritual scene and it won't take long to figure out
that many Americans seeking answers and meaning to life's mysteries
are turning to the East.
</P>
<P>
   From Buddhism to Hinduism to Taoism, practices and belief
systems born in Asia have captured the imagination of many
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama, the spiritual and political leader of Tibet, the
birthplace of one branch of Buddhism, is virtually a household
name. Books on Zen, yoga, and meditation fill shelves at Barnes &AMP;
Noble and Borders.
</P>
<P>
   But long before karma, reincarnation, and nirvana became part of
our spiritual lexicon, there was one person who played a small but
critical role in bringing Eastern spirituality to the West _ Helena
P. Blavatsky.
</P>
<P>
   Most people probably have never heard of her, or the ideology
she founded. But Blavatsky, a 19th-century Ukrainian immigrant to
New York City, not only helped introduce America to Eastern
spirituality, she and her followers, it could be argued, were also
trying to unite the world's major religions long before
interreligious dialogue became fashionable.
</P>
<P>
   In 1875, Blavatsky, who had spent time traveling in Tibet,
founded the Theosophical Society in New York and authored several
books outlining her beliefs. Blavatsky argued that all the world's
great religions and philosophies, from Christianity to Hinduism to
Islam, stem from a universal curriculum or philosophy designed to
allow humans to live in harmony.
</P>
<P>
   The term theosophy means ``divine wisdom,'' and its
practitioners compare the world's religions to the branches of a
tree whose trunk is one all-encompassing religion.
</P>
<P>
   All the founders of these different religions came from, and
were inspired by, one source, explains Zachary Lansdowne, an
Arlington engineer who is president of the Theosophical Society in
Boston. It was founded in 1922 and has about 70 members.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are several thousand theosophy followers in the
United States embracing an ideology that seeks to reconcile the
differences and divisions among religions.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, theosophy has attracted some major figures, such
as noted Harvard psychologist William James and Albert Einstein,
who reportedly kept a copy of one of Blavatsky's most famous books
on his desk.
</P>
<P>
   Among the principles theosophy promotes is the idea of
reincarnation _ karma _ or the notion that our actions in this life
determine our fate in our next life, and the belief that humans
were created by intelligent design and did not evolve.
</P>
<P>
   Blavatsky said her ideas were inspired, Lansdowne explained, by
her contacts with members of the spiritual kingdom, including
Jesus, Buddha, saints, and some of history's great religious
philosophers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She believed there were several who worked specifically with
her to found the Theosophical Society because they felt there was
need to bring these ideas to the public,'' said Lansdowne, who
first became interested in theosophy while studying philosophy and
religion in San Francisco 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   While Blavatsky's claim may seem odd, theosophy has evolved into
a small but mainstream movement that appeals to spiritual seekers
content to find a place that seems to blend the best major
religions have to offer. In fact, the Theosophical Society in
Boston has become a one-stop religious market offering weekly
classes on a variety of topics touching on different religions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we offer that other denominations don't is one place
where you can learn about many different belief systems,''
Lansdowne said. ``Some of our members describe our organization as
kind of a poor man's Department of Religion at Harvard.''
</P>
<P>
   Theosophy followers conduct meditations to celebrate different
festivals associated with great religious figures, including Jesus
and Buddha. This week they are celebrating the Festival of Wesak,
which Buddhists associate as the time when Buddha was born,
achieved enlightenment, and died.
</P>
<P>
   Theosophy is an opportunity to learn the same basic truth in
different ways, Lansdowne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a way to appreciate our commonality. There is a nucleus
of universal humanity without distinction of race, creed, color,
gender, religion, or anything else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
