<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T LOSE HOPE ON GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those ready to surrender on gun control are missing the point.
It was never going to happen from the top down. The National Rifle
Association has a stranglehold on the Republican Congress. But the
pressure for reform, like lava from a volcanic fissure, is
irresistable from the bottom up.
</P>
<P>
   In dozens of different ways, like molten lava oozing through
wrinkles of the earth's crust, the societal urge to limit the
access to deadly weapons emerges gradually, fitfully, slowly, but
with inexorable thrust.
</P>
<P>
   If modern American society can do what it has done to rein in
the catastrophic damage caused by the lure of tobacco, similar
restraints can be imposed on firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco model is apt. The human lust for nictoine is one of
physiology's grand conundrums. That humans crave this drug so
strongly, despite the destruction wrought by its delivery system _
smoke _ is an established behavior pattern, documented physically
and psychologically. No one can deny that the lure of the gun is
another primordial urge. Having at hand a concealable weapon that
can bring instant death to an enemy or a tormentor at the flick of
a finger is terribly alluring to those in fear.
</P>
<P>
   And our media, both information and entertainment branches, are
fixated on creating fear. Fear moves people. That's why the evening
news is larded with violence and threats of violence. Fear sells,
and entertainment conglomerates understand that by salting
shootouts and garrotings and punch-ups into the entertainment menu,
they can build audience share.
</P>
<P>
   Putting eyeballs in front of TV sets is what broadcasting is all
about. Violence is like pornography. It has that neck-snapping
duality that drags our eyes from whatever to comprehend the sudden
danger. Adrenaline is the hole card up the sleeve of the visual
salesman. So guns are everywhere in our media culture. They are
``The Great Equalizer'' of a thousand cowboy movies. And gang
movies. And drug movies.
</P>
<P>
   Given all that kind of free advertising for the advantages of
gun possession, that the heater in your holster helps you to wipe
out your enemies, take what you want, and blow away societal
restraints, it is remarkable that more people don't covet guns. The
gun lobby has so much going for it.
</P>
<P>
   Till there's another high-profile outrage, like the
assassination of a famous person, or a bloody swath scythed by the
Columbine High School shooters in Colorado. Such mass executions do
not have to be swallowed whole by a society that has lost its
spirit of self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   We can control guns and we don't have to live in fear of the
200-million odd firearms salted away in this country. When many
teen-agers fear that the unstable kid who confronts them might have
access to one of the 60 million handguns in America, no wonder some
kids are afraid to go to school by day or out by night.
</P>
<P>
   There have been nine school shootings in just two years, with
almost 100 people shot on school grounds. Every day 14 kids, age 18
or younger, die from bullets. Every day a total of 94 people are
fatally shot, some by their own hand, says John Rosenthal, the
founder of Massachusetts-based Stop Handgun Violence.
</P>
<P>
   You have to be a certain age to buy alcohol or drive, but
disturbed kids can lay hands on killer weapons. The government
regulates toy guns so kids don't kill themselves accidentally; but
the craven Congress cowers before the gun lobby, so real guns are
virtually unregulated at the federal level.
</P>
<P>
   But there are successes. Massachusetts has the nation's best
record on regulating firearms. Over the past four years, Rosenthal
calculates, the state has witnessed a 41 percent reduction in
gunshot injuries and deaths. That spawned ``the lowest violent
crime rate per capita in the country,'' he argues. ``Massachusetts
gun laws work.''
</P>
<P>
   How? By requiring training, licensing, a 21-year-old age limit,
safe storage, child safety devices, and limits on gun dealers
operating out of their car or garage sales. We enforce the
assault-weapons ban, and banned ``Saturday Night Specials.'' We
track gun traffickers, steer kids away from guns and gangs, and
encourage police chiefs to go slow on issuing gun permits.
</P>
<P>
   This works. It's not as dramatic as the tobacco crackdown that
wrested $300 million per year for the foreseeable future for
Massachusetts from the cigarette manufacturers. But similar legal
pressures tighten the noose around the gun makers.
</P>
<P>
   The British showed what an aroused populace could do after their
own horrific school massacre; they banned handguns. We're not there
yet. We still produce a gun every 20 seconds in this country. But
the death toll is hard to hide. No amount of blather from Charlton
Heston can obscure the fact that 34,000 people die annually from
gunfire, intended or accidental, almost as many as the 40,000 who
perish in car wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   The gun lobby is strong in rural areas. But the tobacco lobby
was thought to be even stronger, and richer, and more invincible,
and tobacco is on the ropes. We regulate alcohol, a bit; we're
starting to regulate tobacco. And we'll get there on guns.
Gunpowder cannot be as addictive as nicotine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
