<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOKING GLASS FOR LITTLETON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ What now?
</P>
<P>
   The heroic coach has been eulogized. The Christian martyr has
been buried. One of the presumed killers has been laid to whatever
uneasy rest awaits a boy who laughed as he and a friend strolled
through Columbine High School, executing 12 classmates and a
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   For those left to make sense of the worst schoolhouse shooting
in US history, the question of the hour is: Where do we go from
here?
</P>
<P>
   Not until the funerals end this week will the hard questioning
begin here. But not the general, philosophical questions the entire
nation is asking about alienated youth, distant parents, gun
control, dress codes, violent video games, cyberspace, and
adolescent cliques.
</P>
<P>
   In this Denver suburb of 35,000, the questions need to be much
more specific, much more personal.
</P>
<P>
   The pastors and youth ministers of the evangelical Christian
churches, who have wrapped a grief-stricken community in their
tender embrace, need to ask themselves whether that warm welcome
would have been extended had two hate-filled, non-believers knocked
on the doors of their sanctuaries.
</P>
<P>
   If the measure of a person's righteousness is whether he accepts
Jesus as his savior, where did that leave Dylan Klebold, who
celebrated Passover last month and whose great-grandfather was an
Ohio businessman and philanthropist for whom the Jewish Community
Center in Columbus is named?
</P>
<P>
   The star athletes, whose macho exteriors have been softened by
their tears, need to ask themselves how far they pushed Dylan and
Eric Harris, the social outcasts who stormed their high school
eight days ago to exact revenge on their tormentors.
</P>
<P>
   If conformity is the price of acceptance, where did that leave
Eric, whose style of dress and scorn for sports earned him the
epithet ``faggot'' in the corridors of Columbine High, where he and
other misfits were regularly spat upon and shoved into lockers by
some of the well-scrubbed, Scripture-citing young men now in
mourning for their murdered friends?
</P>
<P>
   The loose confederation of Columbine outcasts known as the
Trenchcoat Mafia needs to ask itself how much it knew of, or
silently suspected, the deadly plot hatched by Eric and Dylan a
year before the pair laid seige to the school last Tuesday, a day
on which many of the ``mafia'' were inexplicably absent.
</P>
<P>
   If the cost of individualism is isolation, aren't members of the
Trenchcoat Mafia now experiencing their social alienation in full,
many of them afraid to leave their houses, fearing harrassment or
worse?
</P>
<P>
   Frank DeAngelis, the principal who says he had not heard of the
Trenchcoat Mafia until last week, needs to ask himself just how big
is too big a school for one man to manage.
</P>
<P>
   If DeAngelis had never heard of a clique that advertised its
existence in the high school yearbook, doesn't that suggest that it
is not only the architecture that makes so many American high
schools like Columbine, with 1,965 students, resemble factories?
</P>
<P>
   To confront these questions is not to exempt the killers from
ultimate responsibility for their acts. It is to acknowledge the
obvious, if painful, truth that the carnage at Columbine did not
occur in a vacuum. To consider only the actions of the gunmen is to
insure that our children never learn the larger lessons, about
tolerance and mutual respect, so crucial in a culture as diverse as
our own.
</P>
<P>
   It would be naive to expect that the stratified world of
adolescence would yield automatically to a more accepting impulse
in the aftermath of this tragedy. But it would be even more
foolhardy to ignore the anger that the gunmen's violence has
reignited against ``Goths'' and ``freaks.''
</P>
<P>
   By any yardstick, Littleton is a lovely town, full of fine
people. A fast-growing prairie suburb at the foothills of the Rocky
Mountains, it is a place where homeowners leave their doors
unlocked and no one worries about sending a child to the corner
store alone for bread or milk.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not only Littleton's minivans and skateboard parks
that are familiar symbols of middle-class America. In its
intolerance of those who are different, in its indifference to
those who are marginalized, Littleton, Colorado could be Anytown,
U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   If the residents of Littleton conclude that Dylan Klebold and
Eric Harris embodied Satanic evil loosed on a God-fearing
community, how will they, or we, ever entertain the need for change
and reconciliation?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's email address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
