<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WHITE-KNUCKLER FEEDS HIS FEAR OF FLYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of course when I heard that the new John Cusack movie, ``Pushing
Tin,'' concerned flight controllers, I ran out and saw it. The
critics were right; as a dramatic work it lands a few hundred feet
short of the runway. But for aviation lore, it doesn't disappoint.
``Squawk-ident,'' ``wake turbulence,'' and the descriptive
``aluminum shower'' for midair collision _ I could listen to that
jargon all day.
</P>
<P>
   There's very little I haven't done to grapple with my flying
anxiety. I sat through the movie ``Turbulence,'' which the
Hollywood web site Ain't-it-Cool News fingered as the worst movie
of 1998. I've flown in the jump seat of the Boston-New York
shuttle. I've stood in the cockpit of a Pan Am 747, somewhere over
Greenland, and listened to the pilot boast that he could program
the plane to land at Kennedy Airport without touching the controls
again. (True.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course I read Darcy Frey's New York Times magazine story on
the New York TRACON (Terminal Radar Approach Control) center, which
inspired the Cusack movie. I've hung out in the control tower at
Logan. Man! Are those controllers jumpy. They all looked like
31-year-old amphetamine addicts, which is exactly the stage of
alertness I'd encourage in the man or woman guiding my plane
through 10,000 feet over Narragansett Bay.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent cross-country flight I developed the usual
jitters and planted myself next to one of the off-duty pilots on
board. He was very pilot-like; articulate, self-confident,
reassuring. Some of the stuff he told me was old hat. I knew about
the many backup systems built into commercial aircraft, and I had a
pretty firm grip on how the on-board TCAS (Traffic Collision
Avoidance System) worked. I had even read about the 747 stress
tests, when the wings withstood 200,000 pounds of lateral pressure
without breaking.
</P>
<P>
   At my request, this man shared his most harrowing flying
experience, a flight to Salt Lake City in which 14 passengers were
injured. Sketching on a cocktail napkin, he showed me how strong
westerly winds create maelstroms of turbulence on the Colorado side
of the Rockies, where his plane was that day. He flew out of the
trouble, which lasted less than 20 seconds. I was too gracious to
mention that my paranoid-encyclopedic knowledge of airline
disasters included United Airline's Flight 585, which banked out of
control on final approach to Colorado Springs in 1991.
Investigators theorized that the mountain turbulence may have
caused the plane's rudder to go haywire.
</P>
<P>
   I solicit flight horror stories so I can see how my own
experience stacks up. One flight attendant told me she got her hair
caught in a ceiling seam during a wild ride over _ yes _ the
Rockies. My brother-in-law, who looks out for my interests, once
called me from the business section of a particularly bumpy
AeroMexico flight. ``They're screaming in economy,'' he reported.
Happily, everyone arrived safely.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, of course there's a copy of the definitive ``Why Airplanes
Crash'' front and center on my office bookshelf, and no, I would
never miss an article by either the Atlantic's William Langewiesche
or the Wall Street Journal's William Carley, the best aviation
journalists in America. Carley's latest scoop, about a fully loaded
United Airlines 747 that missed San Bruno Mountain near San
Francisco by 100 feet (WSJ, March 19) is yet another feather in his
cap.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the strange thing: My anxiety notwithstanding,
there's virtually nowhere I wouldn't fly. Every time I'm sitting
inside a plane that breaks through the clouds, I marvel at the
privilege of seeing a piece of creation most humans have never
seen. The Utne Reader recently listed ``Overseas Air Travel'' as
one of 50 things worth saving from the 20th century, along with
Alcoholics Anonymous, crossword puzzles, ice cream cones, the
zipper, and ``Rocky and Bullwinkle.'' Yes, on all counts.
</P>
<P>
   And the benefits of flying far outweigh the aggravation. Five
hours of sporadic terror in return for a same-day trip to Ireland,
or California? Save me a window seat, and I'll be the first one
down the jetway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
