<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6388 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-FLAN-ART-BOS &LR;      04-28 1686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FLAN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE QUEST FOR A PERFECT FLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Includes recipes)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN CORTISSOZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dessert fads come and dessert fads go _ remember tiramisu? _ but
I remain loyal to flan.
</P>
<P>
   I grew up in Barranquilla, Colombia, and in Miami, two places
where the caramel custard that the Spanish call flan is a beloved
institution. Since moving to Boston, I've been obsessively
searching for a flan that comes close to the ones of my childhood.
At every new restaurant, the first thing I do is check the dessert
menu. If there is flan, I'll pass up all kinds of tempting and
trendy confections in the hope that this will be the flan to rival
the ones I grew up with.
</P>
<P>
   The flan I love is a homey and comforting dessert. It's usually
just topped with caramelized sugar but is sometimes made with
apples or other fruit. It has none of the cachet of its glitzy
cousin, creme brulee, but it's denser and much more satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for my quest, I've found that flan by other names
does taste as sweet. It's called creme caramel by the French, pudim
by the Portuguese, crema caramella by the Italians, and caramel
custard by English speakers. It's all flan to me.
</P>
<P>
   Flan originated in Spain, probably around the sherry-producing
region of Jerez, says Mario Leon-Iriate, co-owner of Dali
restaurant in Somerville, Mass., which serves a luscious flan
flavored with orange. Egg whites were added to sherry barrels to
clarify the sherry, he explains, and the whites would sink to the
bottom, taking any impurities along. ``After the sherry makers used
the egg whites, they had to do something with the yolks,'' he says.
So they gave the yolks to local orders of nuns, who devised various
rich desserts, including flan. The traditional formula includes
several yolks, in addition to whole eggs. Though Dali's recipe uses
condensed milk instead of the extra yolks, Leon-Iriate likes the
story. But, he concedes with a laugh, ``the French probably have a
different explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   Azita Bina-Seibel, co-owner of Lala Rokh on Beacon Hill in
Boston, doesn't have a theory about the origins of the dessert, but
she does serve a lovely, delicate creme caramel at her Persian
restaurant. She explains that the French pastry-making tradition is
very strong in her native Iran and that creme caramel is very
popular there. ``Ninety percent of households in my country, when
they have dinner parties, will serve a creme caramel for dessert,''
says Bina-Seibel.
</P>
<P>
   The flan against which I measure all others is probably also the
product of a cross-cultural exchange. I found it in Miami, which is
flan heaven with its jumble of Latin and Caribbean cultures.
Practically every little Cuban cafeteria and Latin or Haitian
restaurant makes a good version of caramel custard. But I found
this flan at the house of my friend Nellie Khoury.
</P>
<P>
   The Khourys, though Lebanese, had lived in Haiti before coming
to Miami, and the recipe of Nellie's mother doubtless owed equal
thanks to the French and Latin influences. Whatever its
antecedents, her flan was spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   I did try to make Mrs. Khoury's flan once, but I never got past
caramelizing the sugar. I wound up with a pan full of blackened
sugar crystals and splatter burns on both arms. For years after
that unfortunate incident, I decided to let other people make flan
for me.
</P>
<P>
   I've tasted a lot of flan since then. When it's good, as Mrs.
Khoury's is, the custard has a delicate vanilla taste that combines
with, but isn't overpowered by, the caramel sauce. It has the
smooth, velvety texture of pudding, but with more substance. When
it's bad, it's coarse and grainy, or so gelatinous it bounces back
against your spoon, and the caramel often tastes burnt. There's a
lot of bad flan out there.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, during my search for flan, I have actually found
several that measure up to, and even surpass, Mrs. Khoury's. (Lucky
for me, because I misplaced her magic formula after the sugar
fiasco.) I've even learned to caramelize sugar and found some good
recipes, so that now I can have good flan whether I eat out or stay
home.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
CARAMELIZED SUGAR
</P>
<P>
   I've tried several methods of caramelizing sugar, but the most
effective one is also, happily, the easiest. Use this method to
prepare the custard cups before proceeding with any of the recipes
that follow.
</P>
<P>
   Butter (for custard cups)
</P>
<P>
   White sugar (see recipes for amounts)
</P>
<P>
   Have on hand the number of custard cups called for in each
recipe. Grease them lightly with butter and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large saucepan or skillet over medium-high heat, heat the
sugar. Periodically swirl the sugar around in the pan, so it heats
evenly. Continue until all the sugar has melted and turned a light
caramel color, about 10 minutes. Watch carefully to avoid burning
the sugar, and handle with caution _ it's very hot.
</P>
<P>
   Pour enough of the caramelized sugar into each custard cup to
coat the bottom and sides. Set the cups aside and make the custard
filling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
DALI'S FLAN
</P>
<P>
   The Dali menu calls this ``Ubiquitous Flan.'' If only that were
true, flan aficionados everywhere would be a very happy bunch. In
fact, it's quite out of the ordinary. The orange peel and triple
sec give the custard a refreshing flavor. It is very easy to make,
and the long cooking time at low heat produces a perfect, firm but
creamy texture.
</P>
<P>
   For the caramel:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   For the custard:
</P>
<P>
   12 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 cups light cream
</P>
<P>
   1 can (14 ounces) condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup triple sec
</P>
<P>
   Peels from 2 oranges
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   Set the oven to 250 degrees. Prepare 10 6-ounce custard cups
with the 2 cups of sugar (see the method above) and have on hand 2
roasting pans that will hold the cups without crowding.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine the eggs, sugar, cream, condensed milk,
and triple sec. Beat lightly until well mixed. In a blender, blend
the orange peels and the milk until the peels are completely ground
up. Strain the milk mixture into the egg mixture. Beat lightly,
then strain again.
</P>
<P>
   Fill the prepared custard cups about 3/4 full of custard. Place
the cups in the roasting pans and fill the pans with enough hot
water to come about 3/4 of the way up the sides of the cups.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 2 to 2 1/2 hours or until a knife slipped into the
center of the custard comes out clean. Remove the pans from the
oven. Remove the custard cups from the pans and let them cool on a
rack. When they have cooled, cover them with plastic wrap or tin
foil and refrigerate. To serve, run a knife around the inside edge
of the custard cup, then invert onto a serving plate.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
LALA ROKH'S CREME CARAMEL
</P>
<P>
   This is the lightest of the three custards. It is easy to
prepare and has a wonderful vanilla taste, while the lemon zest
adds a subtle complexity.
</P>
<P>
   For the caramel:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   For the custard:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups whole milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Zest from 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   5 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   Set the oven to 350 degrees. Prepare 6 8-ounce custard cups with
the 3/4 cup of sugar (see the method above) and have on hand a
roasting pan that will hold them without crowding.
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan, combine the milk, cream, lemon zest, vanilla, and
sugar. Cook the mixture on high heat until it foams. Remove from
the heat and allow to cool completely. (It will take about 45
minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   When the milk mixture is cool, beat the egg yolks in a bowl
large enough to hold the milk mixture. Pour the milk mixture
through a strainer and whisk into the yolks.
</P>
<P>
   Fill the prepared custard cups about 3/4 full of custard. Place
the cups in the roasting pan and fill the pan with enough hot water
to come about 3/4 of the way up the sides of the cups. Bake for 1
1/2 hours. Remove the custard cups from the pans and let them cool
on a rack. When they have cooled, cover them with plastic wrap or
aluminum foil and refrigerate. To serve, run a knife around the
inside edge of the custard cup, then invert onto a serving plate.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
REDBONES' CARAMEL CUSTARD
</P>
<P>
   Don't go into this Southern barbecue restaurant asking for creme
caramel or flan. They'll tell you in no uncertain terms that they
serve caramel custard. This version is the sweetest of the three,
which makes sense when you think of the Southern desserts it shares
billing with, such as pecan pie.
</P>
<P>
   For the caramel:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   For the custard:
</P>
<P>
   12 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   6 eggs
</P>
<P>
   3 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   6 cups whole milk
</P>
<P>
   Set the oven to 325 degrees. Prepare 10 8-ounce custard cups
with the 2 cups of sugar (see the method above) and have on hand 2
roasting pans that will hold them without crowding.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, combine the yolks, eggs, 1 1/3 cups of
sugar, and vanilla. Whisk until well mixed.
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan, combine the milk and the remaining 1 2/3 cup of
sugar. Scald the mixture, but make sure it does not boil.
</P>
<P>
   When the milk mixture is hot, add a little to the egg mixture
and whisk. Add the rest of the milk to the egg mixture, whisking as
you pour. Strain the custard to remove any coagulated egg
particles. Skim any bubbles off the hot custard mix.
</P>
<P>
   Fill the prepared custard cups about 3/4 full of custard. Place
the cups in the roasting pan and fill the pan with enough hot water
to come about 3/4 of the way up the sides of the cups. Bake for 2
hours _ checking frequently after 1 1/2 hours _ until the custard
is set. Remove the custard cups from the pans and let them cool on
a rack. When they have cooled, cover them with plastic wrap or
aluminum foil and refrigerate. To serve, run a knife around the
inside edge of the custard cup, then invert onto a serving plate.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
