<HEADER>
A6389 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NEWS-HNS &LR;      04-28 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NEWS FAILS THE TEST ON KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Television news just can't to focus on more than
one thing at a time.
</P>
<P>
   It knows how to hover over a story like a single-minded bird of
prey. It can swarm over Los Angeles looking for O.J. Simpson, but
only until Jon Benet Ramsey comes along, or Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Then it skitters off and drops a net on something else, rousting
it out for the American public to gasp at, lingering until it's
drained of meaning, or, in the case of Kosovo, leaving too soon
because Littleton was calling.
</P>
<P>
   Is this any way to keep the public informed? Television coverage
of the Littleton nightmare, an undeniably important story, has now
gone into around-the-clock overkill. The networks and 24-hour news
channels, during their yearlong Monica binge, managed to avoid the
war's early warnings (you thought President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia started saber-rattling yesterday?), even as the American
public was crying, ``enough Monica, already.''
</P>
<P>
   The war in Kosovo _ an international story of enormous
complexity _ is a worthy subject for this kind of blanket coverage.
It is one story that stands up to, and would have benefited more
from, recaps and analysis and government briefings.
</P>
<P>
   But you'd have to excuse a refugee from Kosovo who suddenly got
hold of a television set for asking, ``Where did we go?'' The
Littleton massacre rocked this country for a legion of reasons, and
important stories will continue to emerge. But the story did not
necessitate 24-hour coverage; it quickly turned to thinly veiled
exploitation _ O.J., Jon Benet, Monica, by another name.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's either talking about Littleton, even when there's
nothing new to say, or they're on site. ``Nightline,'' MSNBC, CNN,
Larry King, Fox News, all the major networks and everyone's
favorite local television anchors. All the seedy TV shows are
taking advantage of it _ from the daytime talk shows to the
tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside Edition'' has been egregious, tracking down a victim of
the similar shooting in Paducah, Ky., and the father of one of the
Jonesboro, Ark., gunmen. Not to mention student eyewitness accounts
from Littleton and the father of a slain Littleton girl crying for
the nation, snagging huge ratings for ``Inside Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to criticize tabloid shows for feasting on the remains
of the horror, but the line between TV news coverage and tabloid
coverage is nearly indistinguishable these days, something that
couldn't be said as recently as five years ago. Some syndicated
tabloid shows are going out of business now that ``mainstream''
news has gotten seamier in order to compete.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a hopeless suggestion that TV news organizations learn
from the past, given that they haven't up to now. One of the main
problems with a 24-hour news environment is that it's easy to
forget that coverage does not exist in a vacuum. A full day of
Colorado coverage on CNN _ if that were the only outlet available _
might be fine. But Colorado is suddenly the center of the universe
for every station, all the time.
</P>
<P>
   You know things have hit the saturation level when Nickelodeon _
the children's cable channel _ has to ask Linda Ellerbee to explain
(wonderfully) what's going on to the little ones. On April 22 she
aired a special on gun violence and talked about Littleton. Three
days later she hosted a special on the Balkans for the same
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Ask yourself why we need these shows. Answer: Because children
can't get away from the relentless news coverage, either. Even MTV
is talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   While Kosovo has been pushed to the side, at least there has
been improved coverage. CNN has been leading the pack as usual and
often advances the story when it doesn't have its eye on kids
crying in Colorado. (This is with mandated restraint: An in-house
CNN memo cautioned producers and reporters not to engage in pack
journalism, not to stake out grieving parents and not to put
microphones in front of crying kids _ a memo that hasn't always
been followed.)
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC _ wisely _ has John Hockenberry doing his nightly show
from Albania. But Kosovo is no longer sexy. Even though we should
have averted our eyes from Littleton by this point, TV news says
no, there's more. But is there? If we have to suffer through one
more empathetic reporter, one more analyst trying to explain why
all of a sudden kids have morphed into mini Hitlers, or one more
fade-out of students huddled and crying, we'll burst.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that fixating back on Kosovo is the answer.
Balance, that's the key. Maybe it's easier to try and fail to
explain two nut-job teen-agers than it is to dissect a political,
religious and ethnic struggle on the other side of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, it's time to pack up and get out. There are
other events we're ignoring, both at home and internationally.
</P>
<P>
   Linger too long, and reality gets bent by all of this
time-filling, repetitive analyzing and emotional hand-wringing.
</P>
<P>
   Proof of its fruitlessness? Look no further than the target
receiving much of the blame for Littleton: TV.
</P>
<P>
   Television is always the whipping boy of the outraged.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton _ perhaps hinting that his V-chip idea and the
much-pondered ratings system won't be enough _ called on Hollywood
to censor itself.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst after paid, talking-head analyst rants about the
destructive nature of television, conveniently forgetting that
people were actually killed _ some randomly, many without reason _
before television came along. Even a crib-sheet knowledge of
American history should tell us that long before anyone sat in
front of that box, unspeakable violence occurred.
</P>
<P>
   And there has not been one instance when a news anchor has
responded to the demonizing of TV by saying, ``That plays well in a
time of crisis or an election year, but you know it's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Why botch an interview that is offering, for the umpteenth time,
a scapegoat for this atrocity?
</P>
<P>
   Do you think Milosevic grew up on cop dramas? Did ``Walker,
Texas Ranger'' drive those teen-age boys to kill? It might be nice
to pin it all _ even Kosovo _ on Jerry Springer, but it won't
stick.
</P>
<P>
   Talk like that comes from filling time, which you do in
television when you run out of things to say, when your video
images have faded.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6390 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-MAGAZINE-BOS &LR;      04-28 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MAGAZINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIT TECH MAGAZINE FINDS KILLER APP: COMMERCIALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER MIT TECH MAGAZINE, ON PLATEAU, FINDS KILLER APP:
COMMERCIALISM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In July 1996, R. Bruce Journey flew to New York to pitch
advertisers on Technology Review, the MIT alumni magazine that had
just named him publisher.
</P>
<P>
   But a vice president at the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather ad agency turned him
down. The mix of articles in Journey's magazine was too esoteric,
the adman said, citing an article about robots used to clean up
land mines.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `Bruce, I can buy your magazine's readers 40
different ways,' '' Journey recalls of the rejection.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation turned out to be a big turning point for the
Technology Review, which had existed quietly for years as a
contrarian journal on science and policy.
</P>
<P>
   Journey decided to refocus the magazine more closely on its
parent university's hallmark: technology and its commercial
applications. Since then he has replaced most of his staff and
launched a makeover that has shifted the magazine, nearly a century
old, into the booming arena of publications on business and
technology. Now it competes against hot books like Wired and Fast
Company.
</P>
<P>
   The new mission seems to be working. A year after a revamped,
bimonthly version of Technology Review hit newsstands, it claims a
paid circulation of 205,000, more than double the 92,000 it stood
at last year. Advertising is up (Ogilvy &AMP; Mather takes more
interest now). The magazine expects to turn a profit next year. And
it has been nominated for a National Magazine Award for coverage of
controversial topics such as human stem-cell research and
Internet-governance policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``With technology being such a hot topic these days, they had to
go more commercial,'' says Reed Phillips, partner at a New York
media investment banking firm. ``They're following the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics charge that the changes amount to corporate boosterism.
But others such as Phillips say the new look only reflects the
shift of influential research away from universities and into
for-profit corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Technology Review remains unusual among magazines published by
university alumni societies. Most of them write about research at
their home universities and are distributed mainly to graduates.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, few Technology Review articles concern events or
research at MIT. (A separate alumni notes section is included with
copies of the magazine sent to 40,000 subscribers who graduated
from the Cambridge university.)
</P>
<P>
   Before the arrival of Journey, a 1976 graduate of Gordon
College, the magazine was published eight times a year and was
often likened to Science magazine and Scientific American. Stories
ranged from a feature about living in Boston without owning a car
to a polemic about the dangers of food irradiation. Editors boasted
of covering ``technology and its implications.''
</P>
<P>
   But members of the alumni board complained that the magazine was
too negative and unpredictable to justify annual subsidies of $1.6
million. They supported Journey when he fired the magazine's 22
staffers in November 1997 and invited them to re-apply for their
old jobs. Today, only six of the 22 still work at the magazine,
which is housed near MIT's athletic fields.
</P>
<P>
   One board member, 3Com Corp. founder Robert Metcalfe,
contributed $500,000 to support a direct-mail circulation drive.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Technology Review officially describes itself as ``MIT's
magazine of innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really about new technologies and how they get
commercialized,'' says John M. Benditt, who began as editor in
September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   To some longtime readers, such rhetoric suggests the magazine
has sold out. ``Please don't turn TR into a company claque,'' wrote
one reader from Chicago in a letter published last year. ``Your
crass entrepreneurial cheerleading leaves me cold,'' wrote a reader
from California.
</P>
<P>
   But Technology Review hasn't backed off controversial public
policy issues. For example, when asked to cite some of the
magazine's best recent work, Benditt mentions a piece by staffer
Antonio Regalado last summer, ``Biotech Taboo.'' It described how
research into human embryonic stem cells was cloaked in corporate
secrecy because of past unwillingness by the federal government to
fund research involving tissue from aborted fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the story's focus on policy, Benditt says, it still fit
the magazine's new emphasis on covering commercial innovation.
``The new TR is very interested in the kinds of policy that have a
bearing on how quickly innovation happens,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Another article, ``The Web's Unelected Government,'' described
the MIT-based consortium that sets technical standards for the
World Wide Web and detailed criticism that the group was too
secretive. (The article was written by Simson Garfinkel, a
contributor to this newspaper).
</P>
<P>
   The piece drew complaints from officers of the consortium, who
expected better treatment from a fellow MIT institution. ``It's a
question of whether the issues are treated with the seriousness you
would hope something affiliated with MIT would have, or whether it
came across like a tabloid,'' says one officer, speaking on
condition of anonymity. ``In trying to prove they're not a house
organ, they've swung too far in the other direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Benditt says he isn't troubled. ``I thought it was fair and
balanced,'' he says of the story, ``and that's what you set out to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 92,000 people who subscribed to the magazine before the
makeover, fewer than 1,000 canceled their subscriptions, says
Journey.
</P>
<P>
   That loss has been more than offset by new readers. Soon the
magazine will mail copies of its July/August issue to 205,000
readers _ a target its business plan didn't call for until
mid-2000.
</P>
<P>
   One of its main competitors, Fast Company magazine, based in
Boston, had a total paid circulation of 256,000 as of the end of
last year, according to the Audit Bureau of Circulations.
California-based Wired magazine had 511,500.
</P>
<P>
   More readers means more ad revenue for Technology Review from
companies like IBM Corp., which ad agency Ogilvy &AMP; Mather has
brought on board. Others include Boeing Co. and General Motors
Corp.'s Corvette division. Between 40 and 55 pages of ads run in
each issue _ up from around 15 pages a year ago. And rates per page
have climbed with the circulation increase: Technology Review now
charges more than $18,000 a page, up from $7,200 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Journey says the magazine expects 2000 revenue to reach $10
million, up from $2.4 million in 1997. The magazine also is
considering becoming a monthly, Benditt says.
</P>
<P>
   Readership of many technology magazines is up in part because
``there's an immense hunger everywhere for information, ideas, and
examples of what's going on,'' says William C. Taylor, a cofounder
of Fast Company, which is owned by New York real estate developer
Mortimer B. Zuckerman. He also owns US News &AMP; World Report and The
Atlantic Monthly.
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor thinks readers soon may become more discriminating.
``As with all things in American life, what happens is there's an
excess supply to satisfy demand. In this case, there are far too
many articles and magazines about the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Journey agrees but says his magazine's focus on development in
areas other than information technology will set it apart.
</P>
<P>
   Business gains aside, Journey says he is most pleased by a nod
of approval from the American Society of Magazine Editors.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the group named Technology Review _ and competitor
Fast Company _ among five candidates for a National Magazine Award
for general excellence for publications with circulation between
100,000 and 400,000. Technology Review's reinvention shows
``refreshing clarity and authority,'' the judges wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Winners will be announced in New York on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
