<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH RALLY FUELED BY MORE THAN HYPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been written in many places, including here, that
technology stocks have climbed to outrageous heights. We're not
backing down from that opinion _ at least not yet. But after poring
through the first-quarter earnings reports of the nation's
technology giants, it is hard not to come away impressed, both by
their current performance and their future potential.
</P>
<P>
   As Buffalo Springfield once sang, ``There's something happening
here.''
</P>
<P>
   A few things jump out:
</P>
<P>
   --The big tech companies are putting up great numbers.
Microsoft's earnings were up 43 percent; IBM's were up 42 percent.
EMC grew its revenue by 36 percent; Lucent Technologies' sales were
up 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   --The tech companies are doing well overseas, even in parts of
the world that are struggling economically. Gateway, the personal
computer company, said its first-quarter sales rose 65 percent in
Japan, a country in its second straight year of recession. The
Gateway experience is not a fluke. According to International Data
Corp., a Framingham research firm, PC sales in Japan grew 23
percent in the first three months of the year. IBM's revenue in the
depressed Asia-Pacific region was up 20 percent in the first
quarter. Microsoft's Asian sales rose 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to point out that many traditional companies _
the representatives of the old economy _ found the going a lot
rougher overseas. Household names like Gillette, Coke, and Procter
&AMP; Gamble all blamed their disappointing first-quarter sales on weak
foreign demand.
</P>
<P>
   So why are businesses and consumers in Latin America and Asia
still buying computers and telecommunications equipment even as
they are cutting back their purchases of soft drinks and dish
detergent? ``They are doing it because they have to,'' says Ben
Hock, manager of John Hancock's Growth Fund. ``If they don't make
these investments they will die.''
</P>
<P>
   Hock may be overstating the case, but not by a lot. The rest of
the world is well behind the United States in the technology race,
and it is a race other countries cannot afford to lose. Over time
that means they will need to close the gap in personal computer
use, Internet use, and communications technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think two-thirds of our opportunity is outside the US,''
says Jeff Baum, a spokesman for Lucent, which registered a 61
percent hike in foreign sales in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   --The US economy can't seem to get enough technology.
</P>
<P>
   According to IDC, US shipments of personal computers rose 24
percent in the first quarter, far more than anyone anticipated. The
drop in computer prices seems to be stimulating new purchases; the
growing popularity of the Internet is another big selling point.
Forrester Research of Cambridge estimates that 38 million
households will be on line this year, up from 24 million two years
ago. Cellular phone use is growing, although not quite as rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   On the corporate side, IDC estimates that the typical large
American company is increasing its telecom spending at a rate of 32
percent per year.
</P>
<P>
   Economists have noticed. They point out that spending on
business equipment is climbing at the fastest rate since the 1960s.
That capital spending has fueled the current expansion, boosted
productivity, and helped keep inflation low by allowing businesses
to cut their costs.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years into the current recovery, the process shows no sign
of losing steam. ``It's the wave of the future,'' says Allen Sinai,
chief economist at Primark Decision Economics in Waltham. ``It's
why the potential for technology companies is open-ended.''
</P>
<P>
   --Technology begets more technology. Remember the old kids song,
``The thigh bone's connected to the knee bone, the knee bone's
connected to the shin bone . . .,'' technology works much the same
way. As electronic commerce booms, it drives demand for more
computers, which in turn drives the demand for more chips and
software, which drives the demand for more of the switches and
routers the telecom companies produce. ``The whole thing feeds on
itself,'' says Thomas Willmott, president of the Aberdeen Group, a
Boston consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Does all of this good news mean that technology stocks should
sell at 60, 70, or 100 times earnings? Or that Internet stocks
should go up 10 or 20 percent each day?
</P>
<P>
   No. But it does mean that technology is reshaping the world,
that the pace of change is faster than most of us appreciate, and
that the whole process is not going to stop anytime soon. In other
words, technology rules, something investors need to keep in mind
as they make their choices.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   Even if the planes don't crash and the power doesn't go off,
there is still plenty to worry about as the year 2000 approaches.
Like will you get your paycheck?
</P>
<P>
   A new survey by the consulting firm of Towers Perrin found that
nearly 70 percent of companies polled said they were not finished
testing the Y2K readiness of their human resources systems. Some
companies said they wouldn't be ready until December.
</P>
<P>
   Towers Perrin noted that in addition to issuing paychecks, human
resources departments have to handle interactions with benefits
providers like 401(k) plans and health insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
