<SLUG> BC-ART-THRACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THRACE'S GOLDEN LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The ancient Thracians had neither written language nor
a fixed capital city, so it's not surprising that most of us have
only the vaguest notion of who _ and where _ they were. An
incentive to expand that notion comes in ``Ancient Gold: The Wealth
of the Thracians, Treasures From the Republic of Bulgaria,'' at the
Museum of Fine Arts through June 6. The title alone is a help. The
Thracians were rich, and they lived in what is now Bulgaria,
although the map on the Torf Gallery wall indicates that they also
ranged into what is now a troubled part of the world _ Serbia,
Macedonia, and Bosnia _ as well as reaching south into Greece and
north to Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   Gold is golden in museums, whether it's the treasure from King
Tut's tomb that's the big draw in the Egyptian Museum in Cairo or
the Trojan gold owned by the Pushkin Museum in Moscow. Tales of how
such treasures were discovered only add to their allure. The
Thracians, who made their money by levying huge taxes on goods
passing through their strategically located territory, didn't leave
monumental architecture behind. Much of the Bulgarian gold now at
the MFA came from burial mounds, some excavated by archeologists,
but others dug up accidentally, by farmers or construction workers,
within the last century. Discovered after the era when ancient
artifacts were routinely spirited off to Western Europe or America,
these have remained in Bulgaria, where they're divided among 19
museums. Now, though, they're on the road, for a US tour to several
venues. At the MFA, they're in the care of classical curator John
Herrmann, who calls the more than 200 objects in the Boston
presentation ``the cream of Bulgarian national treasures.''
</P>
<P>
   Artisans in Varna, on the Black Sea, produced the first known
gold objects worked by human hands, some 7,000 years ago. Their
Thracian successors worked in gold for millennia: The objects in
the MFA show are as recent as AD 400. Like this society of many
tribes itself, the Thracians' designs fluctuated wildly over that
huge expanse of time. The metalwork at the MFA shows influences
from Persian to Hellenistic, a stylistic range from fully modeled
figures to flat, elaborate interlace, iconographies, and
mythologies from East and West _ sometimes within the same piece.
</P>
<P>
   The show is installed not in chronological order, but according
to theme, starting with horses. The importance of the horse to this
warrior culture is instantly evident in the adornments the
Thracians lavished on the beasts. The silver-gilt appliques on
bridles and harnesses weren't merely ornamental: They provided
divine protection as well. Lacking written accounts of their
conquests, the Thracians spelled them out on horse trappings. One
silver medallion depicts the Greek hero Heracles slaying the Nemean
lion, a theme the Thracians appropriated to show the exploits of
their own kings.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the works in the MFA, when the Thracians weren't
battling, they were drinking _ often out of rhytons, ceremonial
vessels, generally in the shape of a bull's horn. The lower part of
one rhyton in the MFA, from the Panagyurishte Treasure discovered
in 1946, is in the form of a goat. Fleet and graceful, its legs
extending into space, it appears to fly. The wine comes out of a
tiny spout in its chest. The goat was a sacrificial animal,
Herrmann notes, and the red wine squirting from it would evoke its
blood, and connect it to a liturgy.
</P>
<P>
   While the sheer quantity of 24-karat gold in the exhibition
dazzles, the craftsmanship impresses even more, especially the
granulation and filigree work on the beaded necklaces Thracian
noblewomen wore. Details like the feathering effects on wings add
depth to surfaces your eye would otherwise bounce off. And on a
stunning gold laurel wreath that once crowned the head of an
aristocrat, the delicately veined leaves reach out in all
directions. Here is nature given immortality.
</P>
<P>
   An exquisite phiale _ a shallow dish _ depicts Heracles'
seduction of Auge, a priestess of Athena, with great psychological
detail and sense of movement. The lusty couple _ you wonder who's
seducing whom _ fairly pop off the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The longest-known Thracian text fits on a small and simple ring.
The alphabet is ancient Greek; the words have yet to be fully
deciphered by scholars, but the show's fine catalog offers a recent
suggested translation. Coming from a bellicose society, it is
particularly touching: ``I your young wife, the chosen one, am
dying next (to you), my resting in peace, (I) who brought up the
children.''
</P>
<P>
   A vivid tour Herrmann recently gave ended with a gold cylinder
shape, rather plain by the standards of this show. ``Fertility, in
both humans and animals, was of paramount importance to the
Thracians,'' he said by way of introducing the object. ``There was
no Planned Parenthood. No population control. The more the better.
Hence this penis shield.'' It's impossible not to note that while
this essential item of protection may well have belonged to the
bloodiest warrior on the block, he was rather modestly endowed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
