<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUGITIVE-ARREST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELDERLY ESCAPEE JAILED IN FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Nearly 20 years after a daring escape from San
Quentin prison in a makeshift kayak, an elderly thief was back in
custody as a suspect in a Florida bank robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Forrest Silva Tucker, who has a criminal record dating back to
the 1930s and is a member of the ``Over the Hill Gang'' of robbers,
was arrested near Pompano, Fla., April 22 by the police and the
FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker, 78, was wanted by the FBI for allegedly holding up
several south Florida banks and committing other robberies dating
as far back as the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker was nabbed while visiting a girlfriend in the Pompano
Beach area. When Broward County sheriff's deputies attempted to
pull him over, he refused to stop and led the authorities on a
low-speed chase. The chase led to a school parking lot, where
Tucker became trapped and crashed into a palm tree trying to flee.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested by officials without incident and is being held
without bond at the Broward County jail on charges of bank robbery
and reckless driving.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators found burglary tools, weapons, police scanners and
a large amount of cash in his vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Tucker pulled off a daring escape from the San Quentin
prison when he and several other inmates built a makeshift kayak
and floated several hundred yards to shore and fled. Tucker
escaped, but the others did not.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker was 15 when he was first arrested for stealing a bicycle.
He was arrested several times thereafter for bank robbery and
served time in Florida and California, including the notorious
Alcatraz prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
