 Wednesday, April 28, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following
stories for Thursday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call
Susie McBee or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag
appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House is expected to vote to
deny funding for any U.S. ground forces in Kosovo unless President
Clinton first gets permission from Congress to deploy them. Clinton
promises he will do that. House members are also expected to defeat
a resolution that would declare war against Yugoslavia and one that
would require Clinton to withdraw troops now in the Balkans. By
JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   APACHE-KOSOVO (Washington) _ As the much-touted Apache
helicopter gunships prepare to attack Yugoslav forces, military
officials are seeking to lower expectations that the high-tech
aircraft will produce any rapid turn-the-tide results. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   CUOMO-POVERTY (Washington) _ Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo
calls for major investment in ``the places the economy forgot.'' He
cites medium-sized cities, Indian reservations and regions such as
Appalachia that are being left behind amid unprecedented
prosperity. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Warfare in the Balkans has
compounded the problems that Al Gore faces in seeking to become
Bill Clinton's White House successor. History teaches that with one
major exception, the political parties of the presidents who have
presided over lengthy military engagements abroad have lost in the
following elections. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
</TEXT>
