<SLUG> BC-TEMP-WORKERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TEMPTATIONS OF BEING A TEMP 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE FORD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I recently decided it would be a terrific idea
to work as a temp.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that writing doesn't pay really well. Honest.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, I wanted to work as a temp because I was interested in
observing the ways people behave in a corporate environment, where
millions of dollars are at stake and every employee is compelled to
dress like a cast member of ``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, I wanted to work as a temp because, well, because writing
doesn't pay really well.
</P>
<P>
   Temping has a long and honorable history, which lasts just over
15 minutes. That's the amount of time it takes a temp to discover
that, in terms of office status, he or she ranks just below the fax
machine and right above the spittoon. Ha ha, I'm just kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Offices don't have spittoons anymore.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't expect temps to know that. Temps come to
corporateland from all walks of life, otherwise known as ``I am an
artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, a temp has as firm a grip on business reality as
does, say, a cat. Funnily enough, a cat is likely to show more
presence of mind when the office copier jams.
</P>
<P>
   Artists are very sensitive. This causes them to do zany things,
like creating nine-day performance pieces with bat sonar
soundtracks, and temping because they believe it will bring them
scads of cash. Artists also are very imaginative, by which I mean
they are very dumb, mainly because they fail to ``imagine'' that
they would make more money by gluing a dust speck to a steel I-beam
and selling it at a fancy downtown gallery than they'll make in
7,594 hours of filing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there comes a happy moment when a reputable temp agency,
whose offices are conveniently located in the back of a primer-
painted 1974 Dodge van, assigns an eager temp to his or her very
first corporate job.
</P>
<P>
   The temp arrives bright-eyed Monday morning at 9 sharp. This is
no mean feat. For most artists, ``early morning'' means ``just
after sundown.''
</P>
<P>
   The canny temp takes some comfort in the fact that, in today's
zinging, info-techno-driven economy, people _ including those with
``permanent'' positions _ are expected to stay at the same job for
no more than three days.
</P>
<P>
   Temps who do find a suitable placement are delighted to discover
the joys of working downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Can I say this? What is it with you downtown people? The
tattoos, the dreadlocks, the kooky shades, the saggy pants and
those bikes you slam around the sidewalks _ what company do you
work for? And does it hire temps? Downtown is a jungle, albeit one
with salad bars.
</P>
<P>
   You come face to face with keen competition, shoving crowds,
crazy traffic, tribal conflict and wild roaming beasts. And that's
just in the Starbucks coffee line.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's back to work. If you're a temp, you resume activities
so mind-numbing that you won't notice the blood trickling down your
right hand, a result of having stapled your first three fingers
together. Unfortunately, you also stapled the chief executive's
monthly paycheck to your fingers, which means he now makes a
monthly salary somewhere in the eight digits, not including your
thumb.
</P>
<P>
   But there are trade-offs for having to do work a third-grader
could complete with more skill and panache.
</P>
<P>
   For example: free pens. Also, any company worth its cyber-salt
will have great Internet access. This means you will spend 7 hours
and 40 minutes of your eight-hour day logging on to
KINKYTHINGS.com, where you will become deeply involved in a
supercharged ``instant message'' exchange with a person who, you
discover as details emerge, is seated in a cubicle 8 feet away from
you.
</P>
<P>
   This person's on-line title is ``HotStuff.'' This person's
real-life title is ``Your Supervisor.''
</P>
<P>
   One more thing. For any artist in a temp job, there is plenty of
time to work on personal projects. Not that I would do so; I
believe in doing the work I'm paid to do.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ford writes and works as a temp in San Francisco.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
