r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONKY-TONK-LABEL-TEX     04-28 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONKY-TONK-LABEL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLY BOB'S ROUNDS UP ITS OWN RECORD LABEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHIRLEY JINKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Some nightspots imprint their logos on
matchbook covers or paper coasters or T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Bob's Texas is going that one better: This week, the
extreme honky-tonk is debuting its own record label, ``Live at
Billy Bob's Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The recordings became available Tuesday at Billy Bob's Texas,
Wal-Mart and Tom Thumb locations. Eddy Raven, John Conlee and Pat
Green, all headliners this year at Billy Bob's, are the first stars
featured on the CDs, which cost $16.98 each.
</P>
<P>
   Billboard magazine says the Fort Worth nightclub is the first
such venue to have its own record label. The CD series will include
only live recordings made at the club during concert appearances,
mostly by veteran performers, and most songs will be vintage
audience favorites. The discs were recorded on 32-track digital
audio equipment set up in a former backstage dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   The label is a cooperative venture between Billy Bob's and Smith
Music Group of Fort Lauderdale, Fla., headed by North Texas native
Rick Smith. The five-year record deal with Smith Music Group calls
for as many as 12 to 20 titles a year. Smith also produces and
licenses music to national retailers including Pier 1 Imports, J.C.
Penney, Whataburger and others.
</P>
<P>
   The first act recorded was Merle Haggard on New Year's Eve. That
CD will be released in June. Future releases will include Roy
Clark, Moe Bandy and Joe Stampley.
</P>
<P>
   During Clark's recent taping, there were no distracting
mechanics onstage, nor any retakes or lengthy technical pauses to
dampen his momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it turns out that we can capture the magic from the
audience that we always have here,'' Clark said backstage before
going on. ``They don't ever want you to quit here, and you don't
want to leave, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he expects ``a feeding frenzy'' when other venues
realize that they could do something similar, though he says only
Billy Bob's has the reputation to sell it. Ray Price and Waylon
Jennings are contracted to do albums, Smith says, and deals are
pending with the Bellamy Brothers, Kris Kristofferson, Crystal
Gayle, Lee Greenwood and Charley Pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with these guys is it's so hard to promote them
individually anymore. So we're bringing them all under the Billy
Bob's banner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said the ``greatest hits'' aspect of the song selection
was a benefit to artists like him, whose lifetime catalog is more
important than any new material he might record.
</P>
<P>
   Quality control, however, was a concern from the outset. Things
can get pretty rowdy at Billy Bob's on a Saturday night. Eddy
Raven, who has played two or three dates at the club every year
since it opened in 1981, knows this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was skeptical at first,'' he said. ``Would it be good
quality? But it seems like they're doing it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Crow, who hosts a weekend Texas music program at KSCS/96.3
FM, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is studio quality, but yet you get a live feel,'' said
Crow after he heard the Pat Green preliminary mix. ``A lot of live
albums, you hear the crowd too much, but this is just right.''
</P>
<P>
   Green's inclusion here is an anomaly, because the young Texan is
an up-and-comer who released a live album just last year. But Crow
said Green's CD could give the entire project a certain
contemporary sheen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, Billy Bob's could have a superstar on their label,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Shirley Jinkins writes on country//western music for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 548-5565. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
