<HEADER>
A6466 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-ABORTION-HNS     04-28 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-ABORTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC PROJECT HELPS YOUNG WOMAN COPE WITH TWO ABORTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photo available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUZANNE HOHOLIK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The clay angel Victoria Hinojosa molded with her
own two hands is a ``memorial'' to her daughter. A basket cradling
doves inside a Christmas tree bulb and surrounded by dried rose
buds is in honor of her son.
</P>
<P>
   Isabella and Michael.
</P>
<P>
   She named them, even though she's never seen them or had any
physical proof of their gender.
</P>
<P>
   Hinojosa calls herself a mother ``whose children aren't here
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   They're gone because the resident of San Marcos, Texas, has had
two abortions _ the first when she was 19 and the second at age 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``I chose the abortions because I was weak and couldn't stand up
to my parents,'' Hinojosa said. ``My self-esteem was so weak. I
needed them to be encouraging and they said `no.'''
</P>
<P>
   Five years have passed since her last abortion, and during that
time Hinojosa has gone from the lowest point in her life to a place
where she smiles again and doesn't punish herself.
</P>
<P>
   She credits friends in Austin who opened their home and hearts
to her, and eventually led her to a program offered by the Diocese
of Austin called Project Rachel.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the greatest fears a lot of us have is that God will
punish us for wasting what he gave us,'' Hinojosa said of the
theory that some women who have abortions become infertile. ``It
was through Project Rachel that I knew God had forgiven me.''
</P>
<P>
   And through Project Rachel, Hinojosa is able reconcile with
herself, her unborn babies and God. The program encouraged her to
name the babies, create memorials to them and forgive those
involved in the abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The post-abortion reconciliation program was started in the
Archdiocese of Milwaukee in 1984 by Vicki Thorn and has been
adopted by the National Conference of Catholic Bishops. Dioceses
across the United States are encouraged to start it, and so far 110
have.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel was the woman in the Old Testament who ``mourns her
children ... because her children are no more.'' Thorn said she
started the program after watching a friend ``suffer through the
pain of her abortion. ''
</P>
<P>
   She said Catholic women are just as likely to have abortions as
non-Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about saying `Shame on you.' It's about saying,
`We're here for you,''' Thorn said. ``It isn't about inducing guilt
trips. It's really about a journey, it's not about magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Open to people of all faiths, the program offers a variety of
counseling to help women, men, family members and friends who have
had some role in an abortion. It includes eight weekly group
sessions, a weekend retreat, individual counseling from a priest or
a licensed mental health professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to bring them to face their abortion honestly, but in
a safe, confident context where they understand we wouldn't even
have this program if it wasn't for the love of them and love of
their child,'' said Helen Alvare, spokeswoman for the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops. ``We don't hold ourselves out to
these women as better or worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church has been steadfast in its opposition to
abortion, but in 1995, Pope John Paul II called for women who had
abortions to come back to the church in his encyclical that reads
in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``You will come to understand that nothing is definitively lost,
and you will also be able to ask forgiveness from your child, who
is now living in the Lord. With the friendly and expert help and
advice of other people and as a result of your own experience, you
can be among the most eloquent defenders of everyone's right to
life.''
</P>
<P>
   While the program has been available for 15 years, the
Archdiocese of San Antonio is now launching Project Rachel.
Counselors and priests have been trained, and the first weekend
retreat is planned for September.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has a new name, post-abortion counseling has always
been available to people involved in abortions, said Monsignor
Lawrence Stuebben of the San Antonio archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't something we just started to do. If five years ago
someone came and said they had an abortion, we wouldn't say `You're
gone,' I've cried and welcomed them back,'' he said. ``If this
person wants to stand rightly before the God of the church, then we
need to do everything we can to help them do it. There are those
who have had abortions who say, `God, I'm sorry. I want to come
home.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Parks coordinates the program in San Antonio. She said
a society that made abortions legal also expects women who end
their pregnancies to walk out of a clinic and continue with life
unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are not allowed to grieve. You're suppose to be happy,''
she said. ``Abortion is a deep wound. A woman has to be brought to
a sense of forgiveness by herself and her church before she's fully
able to be accept the forgiveness of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of abortion rights argue that trauma is not the main
emotion linked to the procedure. Jo Ann King-Sinnett of Planned
Parenthood of San Antonio said women who are upset or experience
depression represent a small percentage compared to those who are
fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is depression or emotions felt it may be related to
other problems or complications by the unintended pregnancy,'' she
said. ``Studies have shown that the No. 1 emotion that women feel
after having an abortion is relief. They're able to go on with
their life.''
</P>
<P>
   But going on with her life was the last thing Hinojosa could do
after her first abortion at age 19. Immediately following the
15-minute procedure in her hometown of Houston, she recalls sitting
in a recliner chair in a room with other women. Television sets
were on.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a woman crying and I wanted to console her, but I
couldn't. I felt empty inside,'' she said. ``There was nothing
inside me to give. In order to get through something like this, you
have to be so completely numb.''
</P>
<P>
   Her parents wanted her to get on with her life, but she ended up
dropping out of Austin College and started working in public
theater where she always accepted erotic roles and often dressed in
provocative clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't turn to drugs or alcohol. I just wanted to publicly
shame myself,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hinojosa met an old friend through the theater, started a
relationship with him and was pregnant again.
</P>
<P>
   This time, her first reaction was to keep her baby, but her
parents opposed the idea. Her boyfriend told her it was her
decision, and in the end, she terminated the pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Hinojosa said all trust with her parents was broken and she's
never been able to rebuild a positive relationship with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The abortions ripped our family apart,'' she said. ``I was so
angry at them and they didn't understand and they've never wanted
to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight months after the second abortion, Hinojosa moved to Austin
to start life over. She met people she calls ``very religious'' who
introduced her to Project Rachel.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong Episcopalian, Hinojosa was reluctant to attend, but
she found it was just what she needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing they want is for you to tell your story. Many
women have this story hidden in them an average of 12 years,'' she
said. ``It's important to tell. It's no longer this secret, this
personal hell.''
</P>
<P>
   After completing Project Rachel, Hinojosa converted to the
Catholic faith. She's now a director of Project Rachel in Austin
and also works at a crisis pregnancy center.
</P>
<P>
   Her small apartment in San Marcos, a town south of Austin, is
typical of a college student except for the many religious icons
and pictures of saints decorating the walls. Among those items are
the two memorials to her babies _ the clay angel and the Christmas
bulb in a basket of roses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've created these art pieces to remember my kids,'' she said.
``I don't want to replace them, I don't want to cover them up. You
never get over it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
