<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUMMY BARS COULD SAVE YOUR LIFE!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ann Strawser of Arlington, Texas, saw our request from Lane
Bowles for a chewy chocolate bar and e-mailed the following:
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just reminiscing recently about the day our neighbor
in Ohio, in the '70s, brought us a plate of these bars. They have
been our family's favorite ever since and a must at Christmas time.
They cut best when cool, if you can wait that long. We always have
to dig out a few while they are still warm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our daughter in Ohio always gives us a container of these to
eat on our long drive back to Texas after Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know when you might slide into a snow bank and have
to live on them for a few days.''
</P>
<P>
   FUDGY OATMEAL BARS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 48 bars
</P>
<P>
   1 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup white sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup margarine
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   3 cups dry oatmeal
</P>
<P>
   Filling, recipe follows
</P>
<P>
   Cream together the sugars and margarine. Add eggs, flour, baking
soda and oats.
</P>
<P>
   Mix well. Press 2/3 of mixture into a 9-by-13-inch pan. Cover
with filling and sprinkle with remaining oatmeal mixture. This
mixture is kind of sticky, but try to distribute it as evenly as
possible over the top. Bake at 350 degrees for 30 minutes. Check
after 25 minutes, especially if using a glass dish. Do not
overbake.
</P>
<P>
   Cool. Cut into bars.
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces (1 cup) chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   14-ounce can sweetened condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 3/4 cup nuts, optional
</P>
<P>
   Combine and melt over low heat.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per bar with nuts: 171 calories, 9 grams
fat, 22 grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 11 milligrams
cholesterol, 107 milligrams sodium, 47 percent of calories from
fat.
</P>
<P>
   A breakfast treat: Ginger Green saw the request for
pineapple-carrot muffins.
</P>
<P>
   She said the recipe from the Star-Telegram was easy to find
because she uses it all the time.
</P>
<P>
   PINEAPPLE-CARROT MUFFINS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 15
</P>
<P>
   2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shredded carrots
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce can crushed pineapple
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup melted margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Combine flour, sugar, baking powder, spices. Stir in carrots,
raisins and nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Combine undrained pineapple, eggs, margarine and vanilla. Stir
into dry ingredients until moist. Spoon into greased muffin tins.
Bake at 375 degrees for 20-25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 197 calories, 6 grams fat, 33
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 28 milligrams cholesterol,
141 milligrams sodium, 29 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
