<P>
   CIR-JOB-SEARCH (Undated) _ Before the Internet, job searches
were done in person. College career offices were nerve centers on
campus, as places where students would leaf through binders full of
career information and sign up for interviews with employers who
came to campus. Job fairs required attendance. The firm handshake
and clear gaze were the order of the day. Now most students visit
career centers on line first. They post resumes and search for job
information on the Internet. They may close the deal in person, but
they often start in front of the computer. By Lisa Guernsey
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
