<HEADER>
A6478 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-METROPOLITAN-OPERA-AR     04-28 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METROPOLITAN-OPERA-ART-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE OPERA, FOR GOOD OR ILL, IS GRAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2)  
 (Eds: Please note subslug for OPERA-HOUSES-EXPENSES)  
 (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is no other company like it, and yet the
Metropolitan Opera may end up a model for the future. In the season
just closed and the one to come, the Met continues a practice of
self-sufficiency and free enterprise that is largely unfamiliar to
the international opera world.
</P>
<P>
   But now we see the free-spending ways of government-subsidized
opera houses being strenuously curbed. Indeed, the adventurous, the
innovative and sometimes the reckless are no longer automatically
underwritten by generous European ministries of culture.
</P>
<P>
   The new bedfellows in opera are financial responsibility and
art, and it is not love at first sight. European houses once looked
down on the Met as a business operation bent on staying in
business. Things have changed. London's Covent Garden is
momentarily silent for renovations and fiscally on its knees.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 major Italian houses that once threw away lavish new
productions after a single use are sweating over money. France is
still generous, but even German houses are finding they need more
performances of ``Die Fledermaus'' to pay the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Seven times a week, more than 200 times a year, the Met puts
forth seamlessly managed theater. Its backstage is the envy of the
world. Things work; people work. Foreign directors know the
built-in problems _ the size of the house, in particular _ but they
love to come.
</P>
<P>
   For whether their productions are good or bad, they have a good
chance of being honestly portrayed. Opera always comes with a
degree of chaos, but here there is less.
</P>
<P>
   So the Met becomes a subject of study. Europeans never had to
learn about private fund-raising but need to in a hurry. The Met
knows. It is efficient and productive and earns the vast percentage
of its income. Government support runs from small to laughable (now
less than half a percent).
</P>
<P>
   Those erstwhile European critics had a point. The Norman
Rockwell-like realism and standard repertory depressed us all, and
to a degree still do. But through all the missteps and victories of
this last season, one feels a new conscience in place. Works that
must be done are being done, and pragmatic businessmen who care
about art are finding ways to make it possible.
</P>
<P>
   The appetite for opera's hit parade, lavishly produced, remains
voracious. This season I counted 21 performances of ``Aida,'' 19 of
``La Boheme'' and 14 of ``Tosca.'' The Met's new ``Traviata,'' the
latest of Franco Zeffirelli's overstatements, did not appear until
late November but was worked hard thereafter (13 times).
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to argue artistically against these productions.
``Aida'' can't be big enough, but ``Boheme'' is an ensemble opera,
even a chamber piece, and aside from Zeffirelli's very successful
Act III, Puccini's intimate lives tend to be swallowed by
overpopulation. ``Tosca,'' also from Zeffirelli, suffers from a
similar elephantiasis. The new ``Traviata'' seems more interested
in Empire-style interior decoration than in music.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this is grand opera, with the emphasis on ``grand.'' And
there is a part of our operatic hearts that will always long for
the shallow spectacle. Indeed, opera's loyal majority worldwide
clamors for opera to be grand: it wants operas that it knows and
wants them to be big. There is nothing wrong with that. It is part
of the tradition, and for intendants raising money and selling
tickets, it is fiscal necessity.
</P>
<P>
   But look what else the Met gave us this season: Schoenberg's
``Moses und Aron,'' a historical document if not great opera but
hardly a barn-burner at the box office. ``Wozzeck'' returned, the
hair-raising theatrical experience that ``Moses und Aron'' will
never be. ``Katya Kabanova'' was a connoisseur's delight if not
catnip for the ticket buyer. Robert Wilson's ``Lohengrin,'' initial
kinks reportedly worked out, returned as well.
</P>
<P>
   The solution has been sane: play difficult pieces fewer times. A
smaller audience will have the substance it craves, and the chances
of gapingly empty houses are diminished. ``Katya'' and ``Moses und
Aron'' played six times. ``Wozzeck'' only three.
</P>
<P>
   It is an oversimplification but not completely untrue that the
Met balances itself between two very different men. Joseph Volpe
manages a house whose workings he has learned from the ground up;
and he is known by employees as a tough and often unforgiving
administrator. Volpe is, if not by training, then by experience, a
man of the arts, and one can infer from his actions over the last
few years that he will do the right thing even if it is not to his
personal taste.
</P>
<P>
   James Levine, who oversees the music and conducts large portions
of the season, is Volpe's alter ego. Opera is by its nature a world
of exaggerated emotion and gesture, so it is difficult not to think
that some element of power struggle is in play.
</P>
<P>
   These are two big but different personalities. Volpe does not
shy from unpleasant decisions and in fact seems to relish them. His
unbending attitude toward such operatic egos as Kathleen Battle and
Angela Gheorghiu, both of whom have felt Volpe's exclusionary
wrath, has been correct if brutal; yet one almost feels that he has
enjoyed his decisiveness too much.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Levine avoids unpleasantness, hates confrontation but knows how
to get his way. We should rejoice in how well Volpe is running
things; bad productions and bad singers find their way into the
house, but there are more and more good ones. Never forget,
however, that Levine is the binding force at the Met. It could be a
well-run house in his absence; but if it is a great house, it is,
at the end of the day, because of him.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think we truly take in what a great conductor James
Levine is. Greatness is best seen at a distance, and he is before
us on an almost daily basis. I have never heard Levine's best
qualities come across on records, but as his symphonic work with
the Met Orchestra expands, perhaps that will come.
</P>
<P>
   His work in the opera house, experienced firsthand, produces
wonders of coordination, and I know of no one else who can project
powerful emotional force with such utter instrumental elegance.
That was clear to anyone at the recent revival of ``Wozzeck,''
where shattered nerves and flawless sound were not in conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the appearance of Valery Gergiev as a Met associate
threatens Levine's hegemony is not yet clear, but it is profitable
_ and here I think Volpe has done a good thing _ to have some
musical brutishness to counterbalance the amazing beauty of
Levine's conducting. In times to come, Gergiev will be remembered
as the busiest of our conductors, but Levine _ for his command of
the German and Italian repertory and for his dedication to modern
music _ will have the more profound effect.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Opera enjoys a powerful donor base, wonderful
organizational skills and perhaps the best pit orchestra anywhere.
It has James Levine. The Met also has New York, media capital of
the world. Top-rated singers, who can earn bigger fees elsewhere,
come here not only to sing in a house that works but also for the
extraordinary exposure they receive.
</P>
<P>
   The Met must battle artistically with a space that is literally
twice too large but whose 3,800 seats, filled, are necessary to
survival. This season, ``The Queen of Spades'' occupied all of that
room with great success; Britten's ``Billy Budd'' (not done this
year) does it better than any Met production I know.
</P>
<P>
   Given the right piece and some imagination, the house works; its
acoustics are very good, considering the distances sound must
travel.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the physical nature of the place has a
disconcerting effect on both performance style and the way opera
voices are developed and managed. Mozart can be beautiful here, but
it is very different from Mozart in Vienna's tiny Redoutensaal.
</P>
<P>
   Young singers and their teachers know that the Met is a major
part of a successful career and that many beautiful voices of
limited carrying power will not work in it. Big becomes better, and
this can be unfortunate.
</P>
<P>
   For a company to make its living at the Met's level is a
constant struggle, and the conflict between commerce and art is
carried on daily. So wise in so many ways, the house makes
decisions that from the outside look inscrutable.
</P>
<P>
   The casting problems for ``La Traviata'' began as bad luck, but
the solutions to a series of dropouts and dismissals were just bad
thinking. Handel's ``Giulio Cesare, which closed the season, was
well sung but vulgar to the eye. Carlisle Floyd's ``Susannah'' is a
sweet little opera, but setting it down in the grandness of the Met
was not wise.
</P>
<P>
   Successful institutions like the Metropolitan Opera will always
attract the sharpest criticism and the closest scrutiny. This is
both fair and unfair, but it is so. Indeed, if this house had less
intrinsically to offer, if its gifts and accomplishments were not
so obvious, there might be more patience for things gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But the Met needs no one's charity. That listeners want and
expect so much of it is the highest compliment that could be paid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
