<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SELL-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORYTELLERS VS. TOY SELLERS: WE ALL LOSE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How quaint to recall the days when doubting a movie's honesty
meant wondering whether its hero was standing on a box. Now there
are more important things to question: whether the box is virtual
or real, and whether it contains anything that the film might want
to sell.
</P>
<P>
   With the growing prevalence of the many-tentacled corporate
concept known as vertical integration, we've seen ever more
ingenious ways to undermine what appears on screen. Would-be hits
on the summer horizon offer an invitation to visit the Web site,
buy the toys, wear the T-shirt, hear the soundtrack and play the
video game. Oh, if there's time left over, see the movie, too.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of this tie-in mentality are most noxious, though
least dangerous, when the hucksterism is at least out in the open.
The already execrable ``Baby Geniuses,'' a Tri-Star Pictures
release, amazingly found a way to make itself even worse: one
sequence featured a tot visiting a shopping mall to play with
merchandise by Sony, the studio's parent company.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers bombarded by advertising in once-sacrosanct places, like
milk cartons or the movie theater itself, have every reason to
resent such glaring product plugs in the midst of a story. A film
like the otherwise admirable ``Election'' should be able to
illustrate what being in second place means without using a Pepsi
for a prop.
</P>
<P>
   True, we've long since grown inured to commercial opportunism.
And it doesn't often do serious damage to a story. Though the
satire ``EdTV'' was undercut by the actual brand names that flashed
(not so satirically) on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   But this casually venal atmosphere has softened resistance to
so-called vertical thinking, whereby a film company, its corporate
parent and other, synergistically linked interests can manufacture
films to suit their collective interests. Need No. 1 will always be
an audience, but beyond that, there's no telling where the
strategic thinking may lead.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it in terms of the most influential pop idea of the
moment, the virtual reality game. And think of moviegoers as
reluctant players, never sure they can trust what they see. Have
the characters in a film's story been created for dramatically
legitimate reasons, or are we merely watching a prospective action
figure with a pulse? (``Small Soldiers'' found a way to offer
both.)
</P>
<P>
   And are the principals' fates being manipulated for the sake of
a franchise? In sequel-prequel circles, it's always been a given
that nobody worth rehiring deserves to die. But any movie directed
by a filmmaker whose television commercials looked great on the
Super Bowl is just as liable to take that same puppeteer's approach
to exposition.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it was unnerving last summer to learn that whole
cities were being blown up as afterthoughts in ``Armageddon''; only
at a late stage in the filmmaking was it determined that Paris
should go kaboom for the sake of more exciting advance promotional
spots for the film. Decisions like that reduce viewers to woefully
insignificant creatures on a film's overall food chain.
</P>
<P>
   When the movie's mission is defined in terms of corporate goals
and tie-in opportunities, the audience's role is reduced to simply
showing up. No filmmaker builds for the future with such tactics.
But when the marketers' thinking is sufficiently vertical, the
future doesn't last much past opening weekend anyhow.
</P>
<P>
   It was no accident last summer to find that the runaway sleeper
hit, ``There's Something About Mary,'' showed no apparent concern
for any of these business strategies. The Farrelly brothers' comedy
looked happily oblivious, and that was a hefty part of its charm.
If their film hoped to pitch anything besides big laughs, that
strategy never showed, and in any case it would have been obscured
by such an oversupply of anarchic glee.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of seemingly dumbed-down escapism, whether from
the Farrellys or Adam Sandler, is a reaction against the slick
cinematic engineering that prevails elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   If one response to vertical integration and its monolithic
thinking is rebellion, there's also a worse one: boredom. When a
film becomes the nexus of such a complex marketing juggernaut,
inevitable consequences include weariness and even deja vu. Nobody
on this planet will be able to approach the ``Star Wars'' prequel,
``The Phantom Menace,'' with a sense of discovery.
</P>
<P>
   So much commerce rides on this product, so much advance flogging
has been necessary, that the film's own innate appeal is
compromised. Even the ``Phantom Menace'' screenplay will be out
before the film itself arrives.
</P>
<P>
   It goes without saying that an incestuous corporate climate is
more beneficial to incestuous corporations than to filmmakers _ at
least in the short run. Over time, it helps nobody.
</P>
<P>
   When films are denatured enough to make splendid products, they
will have morphed into something very different from bona fide
events (``Saving Private Ryan,'' ``Shakespeare in Love'') that
audiences don't dare miss. The more a movie resembles a plaything
or theme park ride, the more easily it is cloned and copied until
it loses any compelling spirit of its own.
</P>
<P>
   And the more audiences are reduced to bit players in the
corporate hit-making, the less inclined they may be to buy, play,
wear, read or snack as instructed. The more vertically integrated a
film's conception and marketing, the less distinct the film is from
all the other products.
</P>
<P>
   Until we reach that point in the assembly line, let's hope that
seeing the movie still counts for more than chewing the gum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1507EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
