<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6484 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUNKYARD-SCULPTOR-2TA     04-28 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUNKYARD-SCULPTOR-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONUMENTS OF JUNK ARTFULLY COMPACTED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Tenn.)   (af)  
 By ELIZABETH HAYT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few months ago, Nancy Rubins received a phone call
from out of the blue. For her, it was like winning the Lotto. The
director of a kunsthalle in Austria said he had heard that Air
France had a defunct Concorde airplane.
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Rubins was willing to create an installation at his
kunsthalle, the director promised he would arrange for her to have
the plane free of charge, not to fly but to use as material for her
art. ``I was just salivating,'' she recalled. ``I couldn't wait to
get my hands on an entire Concorde and cut it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Few people would relish such an opportunity, let alone receive
the offer, even though it didn't work out in the end. But Ms.
Rubins, 46, a sculptor who creates monumental works out of oversize
junkyard debris is in the Rolodex of certain suppliers of airplane
parts. They call her when something special comes in, like a
dismembered fuselage, a severed wing or a battered engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The colors and shapes are just gorgeous,'' she said. ``They're
really voluptuous. I love the holes, the orifices. They're almost
obscene.''
</P>
<P>
   For her show that opened Saturday at the Paul Kasmin Gallery,
Ms. Rubins has created an extravagant aluminum-and-stainless-steel
sculpture out of a few thousand pounds of colorful airplane parts,
as well as 600 pounds of wire. Despite its heft, the work is
designed to cantilever effortlessly from one end of the gallery to
the other, cresting like a titanic wave nearly 15 feet into the air
over a wall dividing the space.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks precarious,'' said Ms. Rubins. ``But in actuality,
it's very solid. The sculpture is bolted to the floor. Plus,
airplane parts are quite light. After all, they are meant to fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the work was created specifically for the gallery, the
sculpture was actually reassembled there after it was first built
atop a staggeringly steep hill in Topanga Canyon, Calif., where Ms.
Rubins lives with her husband, the artist Chris Burden. Dogs loll
about their modest, light-filled house packed with the miniature
toys and train tracks that Burden uses in his art.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rubins' trove of refuse litters the grounds _ piles of hot
water heaters and an old mobile home that were once part of a
sculpture, along with heaps of airplane parts. It is here, against
the surrounding landscape of rugged, olive-colored hills textured
with cactus plants, where the scent of eucalyptus and lemon trees
perfumes the air, that Ms. Rubins fabricates many of her pieces.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of three assistants, it took a month to complete
the work now on view. To determine the scale of the sculpture, Ms.
Rubins marked off the gallery's dimensions and layout on her gravel
driveway with pieces of string. Climbing up and down a scaffolding,
she and her assistants constructed a steel armature onto which the
airplane parts were fastened with a web of wire cables. ``I kind of
engineer by the seat of my pants,'' she said, explaining how she
achieves her gravity-defying compositions in which the jagged,
roiling forms appear to be suspended in a midair crash, like a clap
of visual thunder.
</P>
<P>
   Because Ms. Rubins' materials call to mind technological
obsolescence, destruction and the discarded waste of a consumer
society, her work has been read as social commentary. But the
artist insists that her concerns are purely formal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really interested in the balance, engineering and
tenuousness of the objects, as well as the dynamic tension and
energy created by the wires,'' she said. ``We build these things in
a very gradual way. A continuum starts happening with one piece
attached to another. I'm thinking about the way that crystals or
cells grow. I'm interested in the bigger picture. People can draw
very specific conclusions about the materials, to find something in
it for themselves, but that's not what makes the piece work as a
work of art.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 70s, Ms. Rubins has been developing her signature
monumental style and precarious compositions from scrap-heap finds.
But it was during her childhood growing up in Tullahoma, Tenn.,
that she first became enthralled with objects discovered by
happenstance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played in the woods and there were Civil War trenches,''
she recalled. ``Sometimes we'd find arrowheads and bullet casings.
I remember these wacky art shows in the Appalachian mountains where
local painters would set up their paintings on trails in the woods.
That was my cultural exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rubins attended the Maryland Institute of Art in Baltimore
and received her Master of Fine Arts degree in 1976 from the
University of California at Davis, where she created igloolike
sculptures out of mud, concrete and straw. After graduate school,
she became fascinated with bricolage artists, who make their work
from found objects.
</P>
<P>
   She discovered Antonio Gaudi, the Catalonian architect who
designed fantastic facades out of ceramic tiles and cut stone. She
was awed by Simon Rodia, who built Watts Towers, and Grandma
Brisbee, a folk artist who constructed houses out of glass bottles.
``The desire to make something beautiful out of whatever you have
got appealed to me,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   Thus inspired, she started scavenging the local Goodwill and
Salvation Army stores in San Francisco, where she was living at the
time, collecting nearly 300 television sets for 25 to 50 cents a
piece. She packed them together with concrete and painted them
florescent orange. But the objects just did not ``transcend their
TV-ness,'' she said, with lingering disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a cataclysmic event occurred, and a light bulb went off in
her head. Late one night, an actual earthquake hit, and Ms. Rubins
watched in disbelief as the concrete walls in her apartment began
to undulate. ``I never thought something that hard and solid could
be so fluid,'' she said. ``It embraced a certain contradiction that
I started thinking about.''
</P>
<P>
   And so began her experimentation with the nature of gravity,
found objects and stability versus movement. At first she
constructed thin, free-standing concrete walls that oscillated when
she pushed them. Then she layered the concrete with a new cache of
Salvation Army finds, small appliances like hair dryers, electric
shavers, waffle irons, and hot dog cookers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The result was a wall _ 22 feet long, 12 feet high, no wider
than a toaster _ imbedded with thousands of consumer castoffs. ``I
figured out what you can do with materials and how to cantilever
things from the experience of making those works,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   By the 80s, Ms. Rubins had moved on to Herculean projects. With
money from the Washington Project for the Arts, an alternative art
center in the capital, she built ``Worlds Apart'' (1982), an
assemblage of steel, concrete and electric appliances that
mushroomed 45 feet into the sky alongside the Whitehurst Freeway
near the Watergate building. Provoking public outrage, the piece
was decried as a visual atrocity. (After that, Ms. Rubins gave up
public commissions.)
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Paul Schimmel, the chief curator of the Museum of
Contemporary Art in Los Angeles, was impressed. ``To take the
muscularity of Abstract Expressionism and push it to a monumental
level, the work was no longer a public sculpture but an outdoor
monument,'' he said. ``Nancy is really about formalism. Her roots
are in David Smith and John Chamberlain. But no one had ever taken
it to the heroic level that she had, and to do it in D.C., where
there are these public monuments, was really something. It created
an uproar.''
</P>
<P>
   Realizing that Ms. Rubins was both extending and challenging the
tradition of modernist sculpture, Schimmel watched her closely for
the next 10 years. He took increased notice when she started using
enormous inanimate objects, like hot water heaters, dishwashers and
cut-up trailer homes _ ``swollen appliances,'' as she described
them _ to create organic-looking forms. When the time came for
Schimmel to put together ``Helter Skelter,'' his 1992 blockbuster
exhibition about contemporary Los Angeles artists, Ms. Rubins was
prominently featured. In fact, her work dominated the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a sculptor waiting to happen, and it was explosive,''
Schimmel said of Ms. Rubins' behemoth work _ 65 feet in length _
made of trailers and hot water heaters bound together by steel
cables. ``It was a monstrous construction, absolutely beautiful in
its finesse. There were passages in this piece that were like
poetry, and others that were ferocious.''
</P>
<P>
   The show brought Ms. Rubins immediate recognition and critical
acclaim in both Europe and New York. She was included in the 1993
Whitney Biennial for which she concocted ``Mattresses and Cakes''
(all of Ms. Rubins' titles are literal, simply listing the
materials in her pieces). With characteristic excess, she rolled up
and bound together 10,000 pounds of mattresses and smeared them
with 1,000 pounds of Entenmann's cakes, which gave off a sugary
scent, and suspended the entire contraption from the ceiling. The
work was robust, decadent and sensual, the tumble of
sweet-smelling, heaving forms suggesting Baroque representations of
ecstasy and exultation.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, Ms. Rubins not only created a similar
installation for the Aperto section of the Venice Bienale, but she
also had her first show at Paul Kasmin, where she again exhibited a
mattress piece. (Using a shovel and plastic gloves, she scooped the
cake off the mattresses, which were only slightly stained, and then
re-used them recoated with fresh confections.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Ms. Rubins did an installation at the Museum of Modern
Art, densely packing the Projects Room with airplane parts that
hazardously jutted out from the gallery space.
</P>
<P>
   ``In nature or in a museum, Nancy is an exuberant and
uncontainable intruder,'' said Robert Storr, a curator in the
department of painting and sculpture. ``But it's the cohesiveness
of her cantilevered chaos that, in the end, makes her work sit so
well in both settings.''
</P>
<P>
   Working back from three dimensions to two, Ms. Rubins is also
exhibiting, for the first time, a new body of work: collages. To
create them, she photographed her sculptures, cutting out and
crumpling the images and reconfiguring them on archival paper.
Overlapping the forms to achieve a circular pattern, Ms. Rubins
built up bas-reliefs that suggest the centrifugal arrangement of
chrysanthemum petals.
</P>
<P>
   Is a silver conelike image in one of the collages an airplane
engine or a gas tank? Ms. Rubins cocked her head and blinked, as if
she had never before pondered that question. ``I have no idea,''
she said. ``It doesn't matter. These are things that just make
sense to me. They have tubes, liquid goes in and out of them. They
have systems throughout. And you have to admit, they're good
looking, aren't they?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1509EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6486 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLOCKHART-FILM-2TAKES     04-28 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOCKHART-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLY MCBEAL DUSTS OFF HER SHAKESPEARE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Iowa, N.J.)   (af)  
 Margy Rochlin's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was about
``Mad TV.''  
 By MARGY ROCHLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There were those in the team of British hair and
makeup experts hired to give her the fairy-tale makeover for
Michael Hoffman's adaptation of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' who
expected nothing good from Calista Flockhart. And they told her so.
</P>
<P>
   Cast as the lovesick Helena, the television star was going to
pop over from America and proceed to be finicky, imperious and
exasperatingly unaware of just how horribly she was mangling the
Bard's words.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were laughing when they told me this, saying I was a nice
surprise,'' Ms. Flockhart said with a little shrug. ``So I thought,
`Well, I'm not going to take this as an insult.'''
</P>
<P>
   Had she decided to take umbrage, it would be because of this: In
the nearly eight years that Ms. Flockhart lived in New York, she
went from being a busy waif ingenue Off Broadway to a budding waif
ingenue on Broadway. Her Laura Wingfield in a revival of ``The
Glass Menagerie'' was declared ``near perfect'' by Newsweek, ``her
pathological shyness so organic that it's painful to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was back in 1994, three years before she locked the
door to her Greenwich Village apartment and moved to Los Angeles to
become the crown princess of neurosis on Fox television's ``Ally
McBeal.'' Now everyone assumes she can't tell a Greek chorus from a
chorus line.
</P>
<P>
   ``People only know me from `Ally McBeal,''' said Ms. Flockhart,
who came up with two adjectives that are frequently affixed to
those who ply their trade on the small screen. ``Bad,'' said Ms.
Flockhart. ``Cheesy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this idea that if you're on television, you must not
be a very good actress. That's a stigma that's going to take time
to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   One person's stigma, though, can be a movie studio's selling
point. In order to lure ``Ally McBeal'' fans into the movie
theater, Fox Searchlight, which financed the film for a reported
$13 million, will begin running commercials for ``William
Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream'' on the highly rated Fox
television series Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After all, in a way, Helena is just Ally in a high-necked
corseted frock. Both are unmarried. Both are singularly obsessed
with the idea of finding not just a man but a soul mate to
incorporate into their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both are going through, um, emotional turmoil,'' said Ms.
Flockhart, who devotes much of her time as Helena determinedly
pedaling after her beloved Demetrius (Christian Bale) on a bicycle
and being coldly rebuked even when she delivers the plea echoed by
so many doleful blues singers and the occasional stalker: ``Use me
but as your spaniel/Spurn me, strike me, neglect me, lose me/But
give me leave unworthy as I am to follow you.''
</P>
<P>
   Not the modern comedy disguised as a period piece that is
``Shakespeare in Love,'' nor as endlessly faithful as Kenneth
Branagh's four-hour ``Hamlet,'' Hoffman's version of ``A Midsummer
Night's Dream,'' which opens May 14, is contemporary in spirit
while being conscientious about theme, text and Elizabethan
diction.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when Ms. Flockhart recites Helena's lines, it's in
an accent that makes her sound as if she were from the same olde
English neighborhood as Michelle Pfeiffer's Fairy Queen and Kevin
Kline's Nick Bottom, as well as that of the other all-star players
_ which is more than can be said for Keanu Reeves's arch Valley boy
in Branagh's ``Much Ado About Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The time frame of the 400-year-old romantic comedy has been
moved to the end of the 19th century, and the exterior scenes were
shot in Tuscany, so that everyone and everything was bathed in the
area's iridescent golden light. But one of the most noticeable of
Hoffman's changes is how he used the subplot that Ms. Flockhart
appears in as an entry point for moviegoers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of productions treat the four lovers as interchangeable
tools of the farce, but I really tried to get people grounded in
their problems,'' said Hoffman. The amorous gridlock to which he
referred can be broken down thus: Helena (Ms. Flockhart) loves
Demetrius (Bale), Demetrius loves Helena's best friend Hermia (Anna
Friel) who loves Lysander (Dominic West), who in turn loves Hermia
back.
</P>
<P>
   To become one of Hoffman's pivots, Ms. Flockhart studied briefly
with a dialect coach and read her copy of the play until the pages
were in danger of disintegrating. But the rigors of her day job
meant that one afternoon last May an otherwise unrehearsed Ms.
Flockhart found herself on a soundstage at Rome's Cinecitta studio
repeatedly practicing a pratfall from her bicycle on a faux hillock
in the Magic Forest set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very jet-lagged, sort of green with exhaustion,'' said
Ms. Flockhart, who only two evenings before had wrapped the 23rd
episode of ``Ally McBeal,'' then jumped on a plane only to spend
the entire flight obsessing about whether she could erase a
season's worth of acting tics, whose slightest appearance in the
film would brand her unconvincing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play a part for so long, it becomes part of who you
are,'' said Ms. Flockhart. ``So I went there with fear, going, `I
don't have enough time to let Ally go.' But once I got there, I
figured, `Whatever happens, happens.' Because once you're in the
middle of something, you're forced to move ahead. I was much busier
wondering how I was going to be able to ride that bike.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was the little things that helped her leave
behind her Boston lawyer. ``I'm a big believer in shoes _ they can,
like, tell you who exactly your character is,'' said Ms. Flockhart
of her high-heeled buttoned boots. As for the waist-length
pre-Raphaelite tresses she wore, they might have also assisted her,
were they not hair extensions that she was required to sleep in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wig was fun, but it didn't transform me,'' said Ms.
Flockhart, who on her days off would wander through the narrow,
cobbled streets of Rome with her ersatz locks twisted into pin
curls and swathed, ethnic turban-style, in a scarf or her white
silk nightie. ``After I had it on for five minutes, I sort of
forgot it was on my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether she forgot, or whether she never intended to, Ms.
Flockhart kept her anxieties to herself. ``You don't spend very
much time talking to Calista about what she's nervous about or
afraid of,'' said Leslie Urdang, who produced ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream.'' ``But I don't think anyone on the set thought of her as
anything but poised. She's really private.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet now she has a legion of followers who can spew her core
biographical details, as well as ace such pop quiz questions as,
``What instrument did she tootle away at in her junior high school
band?'' ( She played the flute.) Or ``How will she spend her summer
hiatus from `Ally McBeal'?'' (Putting her art before her movie star
ambitions, she will appear for five weeks in a
still-to-be-announced Off Broadway production.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Currently, theater insiders are betting that it will be either
John Van Druten's ``I Am a Camera'' or William Mastrosimone's ``The
Woolgatherer.'')
</P>
<P>
   Although she was born in 1964 in Freeport, Ill., her parents _
Ron Flockhart, a Kraft Foods executive, and Kay Flockhart, a
schoolteacher _ moved with such regularity that their only daughter
(Ms. Flockhart has an older brother, Gary) believed it emotionally
accurate to say she was from Boone, Iowa, where she spent every
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where my grandparents lived, and all my relatives,''
said Ms. Flockhart, whose recollection of herself as a child is as
the ``strong, silent type _ and maybe the comedian.'' She added:
``I spent a lot of time alone, fantasizing. Some people kind of
live in their minds and some people socialize. I was sort of a
person who did both.''
</P>
<P>
   As often as not, though, her social urges prevailed. It was as a
Shawnee High School football cheerleader and student council member
that Ms. Flockhart, as a slightly built 18-year-old, left Medford,
N.J., for New Brunswick, N.J. Even she wasn't sure why, but she'd
decided to major in acting at Rutgers University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I didn't want to be undeclared,'' said Ms. Flockhart,
who found herself in a fine arts program that essentially assumed
the lien on her life and returned it to her, by then a
precision-trained technician, four years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can do anything,'' said Paul Giamatti, who was the milksop
husband Andrei to her calculating wife Natasha in the Roundabout
Theater Company's 1997 production of ``The Three Sisters'' and once
just sat there, during rehearsal, watching as Ms. Flockhart worked
on a scene where her Natasha, the play's least likable character,
manipulates Andrei by flirting with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``She must have done it 10 million ways, and every time it was
completely different. One time, it was very sexual. One time, very
cold. One time, she made it be all about my belly. It was
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   One Sunday evening, after taking her bows at that night's
``Three Sisters'' performance, Ms. Flockhart took the redeye to Los
Angeles for a Monday morning audition. Although she'd appeared in a
couple of soap operas, a few television movies and several films
(most notably, she played the timorous fiancee in ``The
Birdcage''), she was hardly on a track that would lead to her own
hourlong television comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were faking it, just trying to be polite,'' she
recalled, about a roomful of ``Ally McBeal'' producers and Fox
television executives who roared appreciatively through her tryout.
The next thing she knew, Ms. Flockhart was living in Los Angeles
and her life had boiled down to leaving her rented West Hollywood
apartment as the morning sun rose, acting for 14 hours, then
returning home to memorize her next day's lines.
</P>
<P>
   Anything else that happened to her _ and some things that hadn't
_ was meticulously noted by the news media. Ms. Flockhart, who is a
perennial in the tabloids, won't be sending valentines to
journalists any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a person who the press has really picked on _ and I'm not
particularly in love with them,'' said Ms. Flockhart.
</P>
<P>
   It was at this year's Emmy Awards that Ms. Flockhart showed up
in a sleeveless, scooped-back Richard Tyler pink gown that drew the
wrong kind of attention to her skin-and-bones figure. Since then,
whenever Ms. Flockhart's name comes up, so does the she's-too-thin
controversy that continues to engender speculation.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Flockhart, for example, ordered and ate a spinach,
tomato and cheese egg-white omelette one recent afternoon at a West
Hollywood restaurant, it was hard not to wonder if she was hungry
or playing healthy for a reporter. Either way, the serving of a
light omelette had created an awkwardly heavy atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she is expansive on the subject. When it comes to the
reading on her bathroom scale, Ms. Flockhart and the world are in
perpetual disagreement. ``The world is telling me I'm too skinny _
and that's just a matter of opinion,'' Ms. Flockhart would say
later. ``It's my choice to weigh what I want to weigh. Maybe I just
have it together. This whole societal obsession with physical
appearance is really the problem _ not my weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a year ago, Ms. Flockhart told this reporter, ``Some weeks,
I'm a water-glass-half-empty person and some weeks I'm half-full.''
Back then, she was a newcomer to Hollywood who would stiffen
irritably at innocuous questions.
</P>
<P>
   But recently it was a half-full day for Ms. Flockhart, who
seemed ready to drive through the streets of Los Angeles in her
rented gray Volvo sedan until she ran out of time, gasoline or
things to say about everything she noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think that's, like, someone who's just had a face
lift?'' she mused about a motorist with a gauze-wrapped head in a
yellow Mercedes in the lane next to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there's something you can't complain about!'' she said,
when three thuggish teen-age boys froze in their tracks
midcrosswalk upon recognizing Ms. Flockhart's familiar face and
smiled at her to show their love.
</P>
<P>
   She was at a stoplight when she was asked why, in Italy, she
picked up nothing of the language but ``grazie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, back off!'' replied Ms. Flockhart. But this time, she was
laughing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
