<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6490 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAR-WARS-FILM-2TAKES     04-28 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-WARS-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD HITCHES ITS WAGON TO `STAR WARS'  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ga.)   (Eds: Please note subslug for NOTTING-HILL-FILM)  
 (af)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Nikki Rocco, the president of distribution at
Universal Pictures, and her colleagues are nervous. Who can blame
them?
</P>
<P>
   Surveying the summer-movie landscape, the studio had at first
intended to open its high-profile romance ``Notting Hill,''
starring Julia Roberts and Hugh Grant, a month after the release,
on May 19, of George Lucas's ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace,'' one of the most anticipated films in years.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Universal executives sat down, took a second look
and decided on a more innovative, if riskier, plan: move ``Notting
Hill,'' which is about a Hollywood star and a British bookshop
owner who fall in love, right into the eye of the storm. Now, it
will open only one week after the new ``Star Wars,'' when frenzy
over the science-fiction film is likely to be at a peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at this long and hard and decided, what better way
to capitalize on the fabulous box-office business than to be able
to open on that weekend,'' said Ms. Rocco. ``The target audience
for `Star Wars' is young males. `Notting Hill' has definite female
interest. And not everyone in North America will go and see `Star
Wars.'''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but the $115 million Lucas film _ which is being
released by 20th Century Fox as the first of three ``Star Wars''
prequels, tracing the life of Anakin Skywalker, Luke's dad _ has
generated enormous early interest. So much interest, in fact, that
not only rival studios but also theater owners across the country
have had to alter the way they make decisions for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten more phone calls on `Star Wars' than any movie
we've played,'' said Mike Patrick, president of Carmike Cinemas,
which is one of America's top theater chains, based in Columbus,
Ga. ``But different types of phone calls: corporations want to buy
out the theaters for one or two shows; people want to buy 100
tickets at one time. What's going to happen _ I think, I hope _ is
that other pictures will capitalize on the success of `Star
Wars.'''
</P>
<P>
   For the rival Hollywood studios, the magic word is
``counterprogramming'' _that is, positioning romances, comedies and
arty films against the ``Star Wars'' juggernaut, rather than going
head to head with it. The result of this thinking is that when it
comes to movies, the summer of 1999 is not going to be a
traditional summer.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last year, when ``Armageddon,'' ``Godzilla,'' ``Lethal
Weapon 4'' and ``Deep Impact'' squared off, this year won't be
offering an assortment of big-budget, big-star extravaganzas from
which to choose _ even though just as many movies are being
released over all.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw `Star Wars' coming for a couple of years,'' said Joe
Roth, chairman of Walt Disney Studios. ``It immediately cut off
your appetite to get involved in a really expensive movie because
you're eliminating the first half of the summer, between Memorial
Day and July 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth's studio, of course, does have several films to present
this summer, among them the animated ``Tarzan'' (June 18), with
music by Phil Collins, and a drama, ``Instinct'' (June 4), with
Anthony Hopkins and Cuba Gooding Jr. ``You don't want to be out
there with a big movie,'' said Roth. ```Titanic,' for example, just
suffocated the marketplace for big movies both here and overseas
for weeks. There's a real chance you'd be swept away.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, said Lorenzo di Bonaventura, president of
production at Warner Brothers, Hollywood's appetite for big-budget
films has diminished. ``It's so hard to make these movies, and it
gets harder and harder because of cost and attendant problems,'' he
said. ``The process can be really unpleasant, it's often hard to
make a profit and the Internet has altered the way films are put
together. You can't expose your film to preview audiences the way
you did before. Veteran filmmakers used to use that process, but
now you're at risk of people saying on the Internet that the film
doesn't work, or the ending doesn't work. You can't experiment in
the ways you did before.''
</P>
<P>
   Like their neighbors at Universal, di Bonaventura and his
colleagues at Warner Brothers are especially nervous. If there is a
``big film'' this summer beyond ``Star Wars,'' it's their ``Wild,
Wild West,'' directed by Barry Sonnenfeld. An action fantasy based
loosely on the 60s television western, it stars, among others, Will
Smith, Kevin Kline, Salma Hayek and Kenneth Branagh.
</P>
<P>
   The film is in the midst of last-minute reshoots, there are
rumors of problems and the budget is spiraling (Warner Brothers
insists that it's only a little more than $105 million).
</P>
<P>
   The counterprogramming strategy is based on recent history:
successful films like ``As Good as It Gets'' and ``Good Will
Hunting'' opened just before ``Titanic'' at the end of 1997, and
the John Travolta hit ``Phenomenon'' arrived at the same time that
``Independence Day'' did in the summer earlier that year.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after ``Star Wars,'' the studios are releasing
several comedies, including ``Austin Powers II: The Spy Who Shagged
Me,'' a sequel to the successful spy spoof starring Mike Myers
(June 11); ``South Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut,'' based on the
hit Comedy Central television series (June 18), and ``Big Daddy,''
in which Adam Sandler plays a man forced to raise a little boy
(June 25).
</P>
<P>
   Dreamworks is perhaps showing the greatest counterprogramming
courage _ or greatest temerity _ by releasing a low-budget romance,
``The Love Letter,'' in the same week that the Lucas film opens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, `Star Wars' is opening against us,'' said Terry
Press, the Dreamworks marketing chief. ``The Love Letter'' stars
Kate Capshaw, Blythe Danner, Ellen DeGeneres and Tom Selleck and is
directed by Peter Chan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a very good weekend for moviegoing, and we
believe there's an audience of older females who will want to see
this film,'' Ms. Press continued, sounding some of the same notes
that Universal's Ms. Rocco had. ``After all, this is the one
breathing segment of the population that I don't think is an
automatic `Star Wars' attendee.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, women, an audience constantly being rediscovered
by Hollywood, will have plenty to choose from in the next few
months.
</P>
<P>
   Opening on June 18 is ``The Thomas Crown Affair,'' a remake of
the 1968 Steve McQueen-Faye Dunaway romance about a cool bank
robber and an insurance investigator, starring Rene Russo and
Pierce Brosnan. On June 18, Miramax will release ``An Ideal
Husband,'' an adaptation of the Oscar Wilde romantic comedy,
starring Cate Blanchett, Rupert Everett, Julianne Moore, Minnie
Driver and Jeremy Northam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same time slot as `Mrs. Brown,' which worked
successfully for us the year `Lost World' opened,'' said Marcy
Granata, the executive vice president of marketing and publicity at
Miramax. ``It's worked for us in films like `Emma,' and `Il
Postino' and `Smoke.' If you counterprogram art-house films, you
can do very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Fox, which is releasing the Lucas film, is providing a film
for the art-house crowd, ``A Midsummer Night's Dream,''' at roughly
the same time, releasing it on May 14. Set in Tuscany at the end of
the 19th century, it stars, among others, Michelle Pfeiffer, Kevin
Kline, Stanley Tucci, Rupert Everett and Calista Flockhart and was
directed by Michael Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``America has got to see some other movie beside `Star Wars,'''
said Lindsay Law, president of Fox Searchlight. ``The parents will
go only once to see `Star Wars.' The kids will go seven times. So
what's a parent to do but see another film?''
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers, of course, are just as uneasy about the impact of
``Star Wars'' as studio executives are. Jan De Bont (``Twister'')
said that the July 23 release date for his new film, ``The
Haunting,'' with Liam Neeson and Lili Taylor, was selected by
Dreamworks because of the success last year of another film
released on that weekend, ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The film is geared toward an older audience,'' De Bont said of
``The Haunting,'' which is based on the Shirley Jackson horror tale
``The Haunting of Hill House.'' ``It's a very adult psychological
horror movie that I hope is in the same vein as films like `The
Exorcist,' `The Omen' and `Rosemary's Baby.'''
</P>
<P>
   In a similar situation is Jon Turteltaub, the director of
Disney's ``Instinct,'' in which Hopkins plays a seemingly deranged
man who has been living in Rwanda among gorillas and Gooding
portrays his psychiatrist. Turteltaub said that because his film
would appeal to adult audiences, it would have a chance to do well
even though it is opening only two weeks after ``Star Wars.''
``There's no question that it will be like a bulldozer,'' he said
of the Lucas movie. ``But people will want to see other movies _ I
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Also among the smattering of mainstream adult films that will be
released by studios this summer are John Sayles's drama ``Limbo,''
about various people struggling to reinvent themselves in Alaska
(June 4); ``The General's Daughter,'' starring John Travolta as an
investigator looking into a murder on an Army post, directed by
Simon West (June 11), and Spike Lee's ``Summer of Sam,'' which is
about New York in 1977, when the city was in a panic over the
serial killer whom the tabloids called Son of Sam (July 30).
</P>
<P>
   The most anticipated film in this category is Stanley Kubrick's
``Eyes Wide Shut'' (July 16), a psychological thriller about sexual
obsession starring Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman. Shrewdly, Kubrick,
shortly before his death, gave distributors a peek at a sexy scene
between the two stars that stirred strong interest in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Surely at least a couple of these movies will turn out to be
hits, but the overriding question facing Hollywood in this odd
summer dominated by one film remains: Will rival studios be helped
or hurt by the mega-hit ``Star Wars''? That is, will their
counterprogramming work?
</P>
<P>
   As for the theater owners, they can rest easier: even if other
movies do simply normal business, the theaters are going to benefit
from the invasion of ``Star Wars.'' Asked if he had any worries
about the summer of '99, Patrick, the president of Carmike, thought
for a long moment, then said, ``We might melt a popcorn machine
here and there, but I see no problems at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
