<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6492 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVUELTAS-MUSIC-2TAKE     04-28 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVUELTAS-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 MARIACHI MEMORIES OF A '30s TONE POET   (af)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the calendar of saints, the last day of the year belongs to
St. Sylvester, and it was on that day in the last year of the 1800s
that the Mexican composer Silvestre Revueltas was born.
</P>
<P>
   Now, several months before his centenary, Sony Classical has
released an exhilarating Revueltas album, with Esa-Pekka Salonen
conducting the Los Angeles Philharmonic and its New Music Group,
and other new releases round out the picture.
</P>
<P>
   American music, in the fullest sense of the term, had its first
great period in the 1930s, and Revueltas, nearly all of whose works
date from that decade, merits a place with such contemporaries as
Aaron Copland, Duke Ellington, Henry Cowell, Amadeo Roldan, Louis
Armstrong, Roger Sessions and George Gershwin, all born within the
same few years around the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Revueltas wrote in an autobiographical sketch that his mother
had dreamed of having an artist son who could express everything
she admired and loved in nature and life. ``This probably
explains,'' he added, ``why I was born with a regrettable
inclination towards music and loafing and an unquenchable yearning
for new horizons.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of his pieces have to do with travel: ``Itinerarios''
and ``Caminos'' are among his several short tone poems, and from a
score for a film about the Baja California railroad he created
``Musica Para Charlar'' (``Chitchat Music''). The piece rattles
with the regular rhythms of train wheels, between episodes in which
it breaks off to look at the view, including one remarkable passage
of smooth low strings and rippling upper instruments to represent
sand and water. Such music came from a life of journeys and
participatory observation.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Revueltas was emphatically a musician of his
home country. Into his ears as a child had gone the sounds of
street bands and mariachis, and out came that music again, recalled
in tight, bright motifs, spirited and unsentimental, often with two
or three dance rhythms going on at the same time, quite frequently
with a caustic contrast of wind instruments high (piccolo, E flat
clarinet) and low (bassoon, tuba), and nearly always with jump-cuts
from one texture to another, juxtaposed like strips of vibrant
color on a rug.
</P>
<P>
   ``My rhythms are booming, dynamic, tactile, visual,'' he wrote.
``I think in images that are melodic strains, that move
dynamically.'' All that is true, and makes his music a Mexican
parallel to the ethnic works of Stravinsky, Bartok and Janacek.
</P>
<P>
   Like those composers, Revueltas cherished the rough edges of
folk music _ the cues for abrasive sounds and dissonant harmonies _
as well as the immediacy. What separates him from the Europeans of
his time, and most of the Americans, is his happiness, which may be
both undercut and reinforced by the sly irony that enlivened his
music as much as his prose.
</P>
<P>
   His tone poem ``Janitzio'' provides examples, in itself and in
what he said about it. ``Janitzio is an island of fishermen, gently
rocked by the lake of Patzcuaro,'' he wrote of a well-known beauty
spot. ``The lake of Patzcuaro is ugly. Romantic and sentimental
travelers have embellished it with postcard kisses and music. Not
to be left out, I have made my own small contribution, in an
infinite yearning for fame and renown. Posterity will no doubt be
thankful for these efforts on behalf of tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Santiago Papasquiaro, in the western Sierra Madre,
Revueltas apparently had violin lessons as a boy in the provincial
capital of Durango and in Mexico City before his father, evidently
just as encouraging as his mother, sent him and his brother to St.
Edward College across the border in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He also studied at the Chicago Musical College between the ages
of 18 and 20, and seems to have remained in the United States for
several years. But in 1929 Carlos Chavez, whose centenary also
falls this year, recalled him to help in the work of invigorating
the Mexico Symphony and the National Conservatory.
</P>
<P>
   He broke with Chavez in 1935 and, in 1937, spent several months
in Europe. By now a committed socialist, he wanted to lend support
to the Republican side in the Spanish Civil War, which he did, and
visit the Soviet Union, which he was unable to do. He also stayed a
while in Paris. Once back in Mexico City, he threw himself into
writing film scores, a ballet _ ``La Coronela'' (``The Colonel's
Wife'') _ and other pieces, and died of exhaustion, pneumonia and
alcoholism at 40.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time thereafter his fame rested on two scores for
large orchestra, ``Sensemaya'' and ``La Noche de los Mayos,'' both
of which are included on the new Sony CD (SK 60676-2).
``Sensemaya'' is indeed his best piece of a certain kind.
</P>
<P>
   Audibly indebted to ``Le Sacre du Printemps,'' it is music of
persistent repetitions, big sonorities, and melodies as short as
signals, and it does its job of powerfully evoking a ritual:
specifically, the ritual described in a poem by the Afro-Cuban poet
Nicolas Guillen, whose refrain of ``mayombe, bombe, mayombe''
Revueltas translated into his most continuous and thumping
ostinato. Salonen takes the piece slowly and delivers its
immensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Noche de los Mayos'' is a sort of four-movement primitive
symphony, created by the Mexican conductor Jose Yves Limantour 20
years after Revueltas's death out of 36 sequences he had written
for a film. (You have to read the Spanish version of the booklet
notes to learn this.) The reworking may account for a certain
looseness in the form as well as a banality in the scoring, where
Revueltas on his own was always so exact and fresh; though the
conch trumpet makes a great noise in the last movement, this is not
a score anyone will want to hear too often.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But it is hard not to keep playing the smaller pieces on this
record again and again, for they represent Revueltas at his most
inventive, humorous and lovable. ``Ocho por Radio'' is a comic,
trumpet-led mosaic of simultaneous and successive quick dances
around a slow section that is almost a ``Bachiana Mexicana.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Homenaje a Federico Garcia Lorca'' was certainly written out
of respect for the assassinated poet, but it remembers his vitality
more than his death, again with helter-skelter dances around a
quiet, watchful, nocturnelike elegy, and again with trumpet
prominent. The two ``Little Serious Pieces'' for Stravinskian wind
ensembles are little but not at all serious, except in that all
play is so.
</P>
<P>
   This new recording effectively replaces a compilation of mixed
conductors in much the same program on BMG Catalyst, the
performances being at once livelier and more robust. But the older
disk is useful for three otherwise unavailable selections from the
chamber-orchestra repertory in which the best of Revueltas is to be
found: the ``Toccata Without a Fugue,'' spiky with piccolo,
clarinets and violins; ``Alcancias,'' where no harmonic holds are
barred at the end of the slow movement, and ``Planos''
(``Layers'').
</P>
<P>
   Revueltas described this last piece as a set of math equations
that he had solved in notes, and when he orchestrated the music, he
changed the title to ``Danza Geometrica.'' As usual in anything
concerning his life or his music, he was being half-humorous, but
``Planos'' does have less local color than usual, and in its chain
of contrasts and allusions it gets beyond the two formal types
Revueltas was rather stuck on: the fast-slow-fast model and growth
by accumulation.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders whether Varese was remembering its striking opening,
for piano and percussion with wind pedal tone, when he started his
``Deserts.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other recent CDs, one conducted by Gisele Ben-Dor offers
the late ``Coronela'' together with two tone poems: ``Itinerarios''
and ``Colorines'' (Koch 3-7421-2H1). ``La Coronela'' is a problem
piece, put in shape, like ``La Noche de las Mayas,'' after the
composer's death.
</P>
<P>
   Whether for that reason or not, the zest is spread rather thin.
The performance is lively, and the tone poems are well worth
hearing, but anyone whose appetite for more Revueltas is whetted by
the Sony release would do better to go on to a beautifully
performed and presented recording of smaller-scale pieces by the
Camerata de las Americas under Enrique Arturo Diemecke (Dorian DOR
90244).
</P>
<P>
   This includes an early version of ``Sensemaya'' for chamber
ensemble, in which form the music works surprisingly well: Diemecke
makes it faster as well as slimmer. Also here are several songs
with highly characterful instrumental accompaniments. ``Ranas''
(``Frogs''), for instance, uses characteristic hiccups between
piccolo and low wind to amusing illustrative ends.
</P>
<P>
   Revueltas's model for such pieces must have been Stravinsky, and
it is hard to think of any other composer anywhere who was
following that road in 1932 so easily and effectively.
</P>
<P>
   The same marvelous record includes earlier pieces that show
Revueltas's individuality already well developed, and a wonderful
dance score, ``Troka,'' full of typical weird textures, bright
tunes and ideas broken off or lost in the exuberance, soulfulness
and comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The third Revueltas collection to hear is the Cuarteto
Latinoamericano's recording of the complete string quartets (New
Albion NA 062), an album that quickly conveys the composer's good
humor and magic.
</P>
<P>
   All four works are short (the longest lasting just 13 minutes):
a quality that should, along with the music's delightfulness,
recommend them to performers. The Second Quartet is curious in that
its second movement is a digest of its first; the Third has more of
the mystery that balances gaiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silvestre,'' Octavio Paz once wrote, ``like all real people,
was a battlefield. Inside Silvestre lived numerous interlocutors,
many passions, many capabilities, weaknesses as well as
refinement.'' One can hear that in the best of his music, in pieces
like ``Homenaje a Federico Garcia Lorca'' or ``Troka.'' But all the
people he was seem to be having a terrific time together.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
