<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6534 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPIRITUAL-AUTOBIOGRAP     04-28 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPIRITUAL-AUTOBIOGRAPHY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME BOOKS THAT MAY CHALLENGE AND CHANGE THE READER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    As the school year winds down, I look forward to summer reading.
There's nothing like getting lost in a good book while relaxing on
the porch swing or at the beach. Summer provides an excuse to catch
up on books I want to read.
 &HT;    This year, I started summer reading earlier than usual and have
been reading spiritual autobiographies.
 &HT;    Maybe I'm just nosy, but I love memoirs. I first became
acquainted with the genre of spiritual autobiography while a
college student. Since then, I have read hundreds, ranging from St.
Augustine's ``Confessions'' and St. Teresa of Avila's
``Autobiography'' to C.S. Lewis's ``Surprised by Joy'' and Thomas
Merton's ``Seven Story Mountain.''
 &HT;    However worthy these classics, this year I decided to limit my
reading to contemporary spiritual autobiographies.
 &HT;    Every time I visit the local bookstore I find two or three new
spiritual-journey books. As a fan of the classics, I admit to
having been a bit skeptical regarding the current publishing craze.
Over the months, however, I bought a couple dozen interesting
titles and finally dedicated myself to reading them. Many are
intelligent and insightful renderings of vital spirituality. I have
been challenged and, in some cases, changed by reading these books.
 &HT;    Here are some suggestions for a spiritual summer reading list:
 &HT;    More than any other writer, Kathleen Norris has mastered this
genre. Her best-selling books testify to her grace and insight.
``Cloister Walk'' and ``Amazing Grace'' are thoughtful
interpretations of traditional Christianity. However, do not miss
her first and less well-known book, ``Dakota.'' Its spare and
poetic prose communicates spirituality in small community better
than any book I have ever read.
 &HT;    ``Ordinary Time'' by Nancy Mairs could not be a greater contrast
to Norris. She writes crisply and bluntly: ``Religious belief is
something like masturbation: You may do it -- and it won't even
make you crazy or give you warts if you do -- but it's the sort of
thing you keep to yourself.'' Mairs is not for the spiritually
timid.
 &HT;    Gary Dorsey's ``Congregation'' narrates a single year at First
Church in Windsor, Connecticut. Dorsey, a journalist, begins by
reporting on church life. Within months, however, the line between
reporter and parishioner blurs. This is a funny book -- with a
complete cast of crusty New England characters and New Age
baby-boomer seekers. More like a novel than non-fiction, I had to
keep reminding myself it was true!
 &HT;    ``Encountering God'' by Harvard professor Diana Eck recounts her
journey from her Methodist childhood in Bozeman, Montana to being
transformed while studying Hinduism in India. Well-written and
theologically sophisticated, Eck explores the issues surrounding
American religious pluralism. This book is deeply Christian and
completely inclusive -- a model of religious dialogue and a good
introduction to Hinduism.
 &HT;    A new book, ``The Ironic Christian's Companion'' by Patrick
Henry, pushes Christians to embrace doubt as a way to God. Henry
knits together church history, contemporary events and his own life
experience and points out that God may be found in the
least-expected places -- such as a classroom at Swarthmore College,
the feminist Re-Imagining Conference, and in divorce and death.
Although the author is not ordained, I wished every minister in
America was as pastoral as Henry.
 &HT;    Two books by gay men address the issues facing Christian
homosexuals. John McNeill's ``Both Feet Firmly Planted in Midair''
and Mel White's ``Stranger at the Gate'' helped me, as a
heterosexual wife and mother, understand the painful struggle of my
gay and lesbian friends regarding faith and identity. McNeill, a
liberal Roman Catholic, and White, a conservative evangelical, come
to the point of self- and divine acceptance from opposite sides of
the theological fence. But they wind up in remarkably the same
place. I found these books profoundly human -- and should not be
limited in readership to the homosexual community.
 &HT;    Julius Lester's ``Lovesong'' recounts his conversion from
Methodism to Judaism. Lester, an African-American and son of a
southern Methodist minister, struggles with a lifetime of exclusion
until he meets God in Judaism. There, ``exclusion'' melts into
finding meaning through a distinctive community. ``Being a Jew,''
he writes, ``is more than loving Judaism; it is also belonging to a
people.''
 &HT;    ``Things Seen and Unseen'' by Nora Gallagher is another year at
church -- this time Trinity Episcopal in Santa Barbara. Her book
captures the ethos of contemporary Episcopalianism: contemplative
and activist. She takes the reader into the secret places of
Christian community as the people pray, serve the poor, minister to
one another, and struggle with the big issues of the day --
including having a gay priest.
 &HT;    Enjoy!
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
