<SLUG> BC-CIR-BIRD-NESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRDS OF THE WORLD WIDE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For birds, spring is the season to build nests, lay eggs and
poke a constant supply of fish and insects into the mouths of
ever-hungry chicks. It is also the season when birds play a
starring role on the Internet, their domestic lives shown on dozens
of live video Web sites where the public can keep abreast of every
flutter.
</P>
<P>
   Birds are filmed from cameras installed before their arrival at
regular nesting sites high in tree branches, inside birdhouses and
on office ledges. The birds seem to be none the wiser about their
global audience and go about rearing chicks as they have since long
before the Web was created.
</P>
<P>
   In photographs that are updated via a Web camera, or Webcam, as
often as every 15 seconds, birds can be seen furnishing nests with
feathers, laying eggs and returning home with lizards in their
beaks. At other times, the view can be dull as parents sit
motionless on their eggs or leave the nest unattended.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more interesting nest cams on the Web is focused on a
pair of peregrine falcons that roost in a box 400 feet up a power
plant smokestack in Oak Park Heights, Minn. The female, named Mae,
who is sitting on four eggs that are expected to hatch at any time,
has returned to this site for nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unprecedented look into the life of an endangered
species,'' said Paul Adelmann, a spokesman for Northern States
Power Co., which has included Mae and her mate on its Web site
(www.nspco.com/nspbird.htm) as a public relations (and educational)
tool since 1996. ``Boy, when those babies hatch, it's always fun to
watch. They're really furry.''
</P>
<P>
   Live images of Mae are generally available from mid-April to
early June, from the time the parents prepare their nest to when
their hatchlings fly away.
</P>
<P>
   During most of the birds' stay, the camera is focused on the
nest. But for the last two weeks, the camera is directed toward a
wooden flight deck where the young stand and stretch their wings
for a few days before throwing themselves into the air high above
the St. Croix River.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what species of bird, watching the hatchlings break
through their eggshells is an especially coveted event on the Web.
Of course, catching a glimpse of it requires luck. The process can
be relatively fast, is sometimes blocked from view by a parent and
can happen at night when there is no light to see.
</P>
<P>
   Of all nest cam Web sites, peregrine falcons and bald eagles
appear to be the most popular species in terms of numbers. Other
birds include storks, ospreys and geese.
</P>
<P>
   The nests featured on the Web are found around the world, though
given the limited panoramas of most of the cameras, the photographs
could be coming from anywhere. They are run by universities,
companies and amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites have audio samples of birds chirping. There is
frequently background information about the birds, including what
they eat, whether the parents are paired for life and how long
their eggs take to hatch.
</P>
<P>
   A family of kestrels may be seen at the www.jps.net/dnaprice
site, from Arizona. Two bald eagles in Tennessee are at
www.eaglewatch.com. The nest of a family of Carolina chickadees can
be found at www.ornith.cornell.edu. And one of the most extensive
links to several different bird cams is at www.pitt.edu/dziadosz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
