<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6547 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-NEWS-BY-COMPUTER-     04-28 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NEWS-BY-COMPUTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE YEARS INTO A MARRIAGE OF CONVENIENCE, TRUE LOVE BLOSSOMS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By EMILY PRAGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My computer is sick and I'm worried. The screen is yellow. It
won't print. When I called a techie and told him the symptoms, he
laughed devilishly and refused to help me over the phone. I don't
like this. I feel as if my lifeline is fraying and I'm about to be
set adrift. I think I have post-traumatic Web syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, I didn't even have a computer. I had an
electronic typewriter and a television, and I was happy. I got a
computer primarily because I was forced to. My book editor laid
down the law. Correcting my manuscripts by cutting and pasting, a
creative act I miss to this day, was no longer acceptable. I had to
join the technology revolution.
</P>
<P>
   So I threw away my white-out and bought a Mac in December 1994,
thinking of it as a secretarial tool and a bottomless file cabinet.
In fact, all I knew about computers was their storage and
correction capabilities. I had no idea that a computer would change
my life completely. I had never heard the term cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   My television had always been my connection to the world. I was,
for example, a devotee of live television events. From the Kennedy
assassination on, I don't think I missed a great happening in the
world. I saw the moon landing from start to finish, the 1972
Olympics, the last flight out of Vietnam, the Watergate hearings
and on and on _ and yes, Chernobyl, the day Ronald Reagan was shot,
Iran-contra, Bork, the O.J. Simpson chase. Through my television, I
felt that I was part of some worldwide family of watchers, and I
was loyal to the group. I thought of it as a great informational
tool, and it indeed taught me a lot.
</P>
<P>
   I became a parent about the same time that I got a computer, and
parenthood changed my relationship to television, too. I was no
longer free to watch anything I liked at any time I liked, and one
thing I had to stop watching completely was my favorite thing, the
nightly news. As network news became more lurid, it was too
unpredictable, too often wildly unsuitable for children. For
solace, I turned to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, my Internet service provider was in a
rudimentary state, and it was not easy to get out of its world and
onto the Web. That was all right because I didn't really know the
difference between the two.
</P>
<P>
   I was just delighted when I found that by plugging my phone cord
into my modem, I could get access to an entire newsstand's worth of
newspapers and magazines, seemingly for free. So after a long day
of baby care, I started sitting down at the computer and reading
the news. And in the process of doing that, one night I
inadvertently got onto the Web.
</P>
<P>
   I believe that I was seeking the front page of the main
newspaper in Jakarta, Indonesia. I clicked on something I had
clicked on many times before, and suddenly there were strange
rippling movements on the screen and a new kind of page appeared,
with a bar at the top that I instantly dubbed ``the www thing.''
Presto, I was on the Web. Reading a newspaper on the other side of
the world while watching my sleeping baby at home _ the whole event
gave life to the term futuristic.
</P>
<P>
   Then one night when I was reading the news, a news flash
suddenly appeared on the screen. I had not realized before that the
Web was ``live'' in that way. I was thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   In those two moments, I felt an entirely new connection to the
world; I was a member of a new group more informed than ever
before. Our information was as up to the minute as was
technologically possible. At last I felt solidarity with my
computer. It became not only my favorite but also my most trusted
machine.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, five years later, my computer has never let me
down. I have become more and more accustomed to it and, perhaps,
most important, I no longer fear it. At first, I was terribly
intimidated by URL's (Uniform Resource Locators, or Web page
addresses). But that was because I thought I had to understand
them. Now I know I only have to use them, and I feel much better.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that's true of the whole computer system. Once I
realized that I will never understand its workings as I understood
the typewriter _ that understanding the computer is beyond my
capability and something not expected of me, that I could simply be
a drone and that was OK _ I began to love going on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the Web remains a fantastical construct and perhaps
always will. I see it as a vast spider's web woven globally across
the world with little sites, like bound-up houseflies, caught
within its silken thread. The U.R.L.'s take me to these sites,
which are manned, I fantasize, by different humans of other lands,
in distant homes and offices decorated with foreign home
furnishings. The home pages are like huge billboards for these
sites, visible out there in cyberspace, where there is, at present,
still no gravity.
</P>
<P>
   I recently consulted the Chinese yellow pages for a phone number
in rural China, and I found it! I cannot think now of going on a
trip without using my e-mail to connect me to my home. Every day I
E-mote to friends who have moved to London, Los Angeles and rural
China. Our friendships are up to date now, reconnected through
cyberspace, never to be lost again.
</P>
<P>
   I am in the first generation of writers who no longer use paper
and at first, it was terribly wrenching. But now I send all pieces
via e-mail and I don't have to worry about pages getting lost or
bent or mashed and paper being everywhere in my office and
yellowing from age.
</P>
<P>
   It's a relief, actually. That my overhead has gone from the cost
of a pencil and paper to the cost of a computer plus supplies irks
me, but I wouldn't change back, not for anything.
</P>
<P>
   Now I watch television only rarely _ when ``The Sopranos'' is
on, or when I want to take a really good look at something. I have
switched both my mental and physical allegiance to cyberspace,
something I would never have predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the techie finally found time for me and came over.
There's nothing, thank God, wrong with my computer. The screen was
yellow because a wire was loose, so my computer guru told me to
tape it. It was sluggish because the hard drive was, as he put it,
``full of garbage.'' Its problems were the result of my neglect.
</P>
<P>
   I am terribly embarrassed and somewhat amazed. I didn't realize
that it was bad for the computer not to throw out old applications
and obsolete software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of it as a car,'' the techie kept saying, but I never
will. I think of my computer as a miniature version of Hal in
``2001,'' a sentient machine that is my escort into the 21st
century. If it needs a little maid service in return for the entree
it gives me, I'll be happy to comply.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1609EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
