<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER YOUR PREPARATION, IT'S TIME TO BUILD THE STAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Howto drawing is being sent to NYT photo and NYT graphics
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Building a simple set of stairs is not difficult, but it does
require taking accurate measurements, making a few calculations and
taking care to lay out the figures carefully on the carriage
boards. When you have taken all the required measurements, you can
estimate how much lumber you need for the project. If possible, buy
extra lengths. This will allow you some latitude if you have to cut
out sections that have knots or cracks.
</P>
<P>
   The carriages provide the support for the steps, so it is
important to cut them from lumber that is sound and relatively free
of defects. If possible, go to the lumber yard and hand-pick the
boards yourself. The stock does not have to be perfectly clear
(free of knots). A few knots or cracks near the edge may be
acceptable if you can cut them away when you cut the pattern for
the steps.
</P>
<P>
   Carriage boards should be wide; they must be at lease 3 inches
wider than the riser height. If your risers are 7 inches deep, the
carriages will have to be at least 10 inches wide.
</P>
<P>
   To lay out the step pattern on the carriage start about six
inches from the end and mark off the width of the first tread, then
draw a line, perpendicular to the first, for the riser. Marking off
the tread/riser lines is demanding because lines must be straight,
they must always be the same respective lengths, and they must join
at a perfect right, that is 90 degree, angles. This, however, is
easy if you use a framing square with a pair of stair gauges. Stair
gauges are small screw clamps. They are sold in pairs at most home
centers and hardware stores for about $5.
</P>
<P>
   Locate the riser measurement on the short arm of the square and
lock one gauge at this point. Move to the adjacent arm of the
square and lock the other gauge at the tread measurement. To mark
off the steps, position the square on the board so both gauges butt
against the edge. Draw lines along the square arms.
</P>
<P>
   Reposition the square for the next step and draw new lines. All
the lines will be consistent, and they will always form a right
angle. At the end of the step pattern, draw the final riser line.
Finish the stair pattern by drawing a base line. It will be
parallel to the last tread and connect with the end of the last
riser.
</P>
<P>
   After laying out the step pattern, check to make sure that it
matches on both carriage boards. Then use a circular saw to cut
through the lines. Cut along the layout lines, but stop cutting at
the intersection. Use a handsaw or saber saw to complete the cuts.
Cutting beyond the lines can weaken the carriages.
</P>
<P>
   Next cut the lumber to make the risers and treads. Start by
ripping (cutting through the length) the boards to the right width.
Then cut them to length. For example, assume that your stairs will
be 32 inches wide, with 6 risers and 5 treads. The risers will be 7
inches wide and the treads 10 inches. Rip the riser boards to 7
inches wide, then cut six 32-inch lengths. Rip the tread stock to a
10-inch width, then cut five 32-inch lengths.
</P>
<P>
   At this point you may want to nail all the pieces together, then
attach the assembled stairs to the deck. This way you can see how
the stairs will look before they are mounted on the deck. The
problem with this method is that the stairs are apt to be heavy and
difficult to maneuver into place. Most professional carpenters,
therefore, prefer to attach the carriage boards onto the deck then
nail the steps in place. In this way they can easily adjust the
carriages to get the proper pitch for the steps. If you choose to
mount the carriage boards before attaching the steps, first nail 2
by 4s to the boards to brace them at the proper width.
</P>
<P>
   The method you use to attach the stairs to the deck will depend
on the deck structure. Probably the easiest way to attach the
stairs is with stair hangers. The hangers are simply three lengths
of 2 by 4s that run vertically from the carriages to the rim joist
on the deck. You will need a nailing surface on the carriages to
attach the hangers. Make this by nailing a 2 by 4 brace across the
top of the carriages so it is parallel to the top riser.
</P>
<P>
   If the joists on your deck run perpendicular to the steps, you
can install mounting blocks to attach the carriages. These blocks
can be cut from 2 by 8s and nailed between the joists. Nail the
carriages directly to the blocks with 10-penny nails.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
