<SLUG> BC-CIR-GESTURE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK, MA, NO KEYBOARD: IT'S ALL IN THE FINGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ga.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computers continue to shrink successfully, but not their
keyboards. On the tiny keyboards of handheld computers, efficient
touch typing remains a distant dream.
</P>
<P>
   Now a Stanford University professor has a possible solution.
Both real and virtual keyboards may one day be replaced with an
ingenious, one-handed sign language that is the ultimate in touch
typing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it thumbing,'' said the inventor, Vaughan R. Pratt, 55,
a computer scientist at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Using Pratt's method, the computer user would type not just with
the hand, but on it, using the thumb and a variety of finger
positions. Pratt, who specializes in wearable computers, is
designing a glove and other devices to transmit the signals to a
computer.
</P>
<P>
   He has already shrunk a PC with a 340-megabyte hard drive for a
wearable computer to four cubic inches and a Web server to one
cubic inch (described at wearables.stanford.edu). ``I like
equipment you can slip into your pocket without a bulge,'' Pratt
said.
</P>
<P>
   His keyboardless typing system, which he calls thumbcode, is
designed to work with the matchbox-size computer one day. It
depends on a single hand _ not clapping, but quietly tapping with
the thumb on the other four fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``To develop wearable computers, all the components must shrink
together, keyboard included,'' Pratt said. ``We achieved
scalability by using the hand itself as the keyboard, rather than
any particular device.''
</P>
<P>
   If thumbcode catches on, joggers may someday be able to answer
their e-mail as they trot along, and pedestrians will be able to
get in a few paragraphs of the great American novel as they wait
for traffic lights to change.
</P>
<P>
   To use the language, a person combines touching the thumb to the
top, middle or base of the index, middle, ring and pinky fingers
with changes in finger position _ from all open to all closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are using the 12 sections of the fingers _ tip, middle and
base of each of four fingers _ as though they formed a 3-by-4
keypad,'' Pratt explained. Holding some fingers together and some
apart expands the character set from 12 characters to 96.
</P>
<P>
   For example, to spell the word tea, a person holds the fingers
apart, then the thumb taps the tip of the ring finger (t), the tip
of the middle finger (e) and the tip of the index finger (a).
</P>
<P>
   Each position in thumbcode corresponds to a character in ASCII,
the plain vanilla language familiar to users of e-mail. ASCII is
designed so all machines in a network, from the simplest to the
most complex, can understand its stripped-down notations for such
essentials as carriage returns, backspaces, the Enter command, the
letters of the alphabet and numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes thumbcode digital,'' Pratt said,
distinguishing between his signing language and American Sign
Language. ``Thumbcode is a keyboard replacement and is purely
character-oriented.'' Thumbcode accounts for all 128 seven-bit
ASCII characters as well as other standard computer functions, like
the cursor and the Alt key.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Sign Language is designed to be recognized by people,
not computers,'' Pratt said. ``ASL uses finger spelling for
uncommon words and about 6,000 gestures for common words. It's
complicated to explain gestures to computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Thumbcode requires explaining only the 12 positions on the
fingers and the three gaps between fingers. ``This is the sort of
yes-no information computers can handle right now,'' Pratt added.
</P>
<P>
   Thad Starner, a professor at the Georgia Institute of Technology
who has worked on a wearable computer capable of understanding ASL,
agrees. ``A.S.L. is complex,'' he said. ``It presents challenges to
the computer as complicated as those posed by speech recognition.
Thumbcode is a lot simpler.''
</P>
<P>
   Pratt said the characters in thumbcode were quite easy to learn.
And unlike pen-based systems, thumbcode lets you look up while
you're entering data. Pratt estimated that top speed would be about
30 words per minute.
</P>
<P>
   To make thumbcode work as rapidly as possible, the most commonly
used letters have been assigned to easier positions, like the tips
of the fingers. Touching the base of the fingers is slightly more
difficult, Pratt said, so that maneuver is saved for letters used
more infrequently.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-to-execute finger positions are modified in other ways. For
instance, the pinky is moved toward the palm rather than trying to
separate it upright from the ring finger, a gesture that is
difficult for some people.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt is busy perfecting his matchbox computer right now, so he
has postponed work on the data glove that will transmit thumbcode,
at least for this semester. He emphasized, however, that he had not
designed thumbcode with a particular mechanism for transmitting it
in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I designed it around the hand, not a device,'' he said.
``There are many ways to identify the thumb's location _ a
touch-sensitive glove or a camera perhaps. The beauty of the scheme
is that the basic concept is independent of the hardware you use
for recognition to the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, many people who want to communicate with their
wearable computers use a device called a Handykey Twiddler
(www.handykey.com), a keyboard that fits into the hand. To use the
Twiddler, one or more keys are pressed to form a character, word or
phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Starner wrote his entire PhD dissertation using a Twiddler. ``By
now I'm up to 60 words a minute,'' he said. ``But I have many, many
hours of practice and lots of macros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pratt's system of dispensing with the keyboard and using the
hand itself may, like the Twiddler, be better for the body. With a
desktop keyboard, you are bending your wrist, leading to all sorts
of injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Mann, a professor at the University of Toronto and a
pioneer in the field of wearable computers, has different ideas for
the keyboardless future. ``Why not interact with things directly?''
he asked. ``For instance, you can look at something as a means of
selecting it. Keyboards force us to think in terms of syntax.
Visual thinking is more powerful. I would call into question the
entire metaphor of the keyboard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
