u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2     04-28 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMILE! IT'S DIGITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a recent visit to an amusement park in Florida, where he was
supposed to be having fun, poor little Taylor was in agony.
``Taylor, take a bite of your hot dog,'' his father coached.
``Smile! That's it! Taylor, turn around and walk toward the roller
coaster. No, walk the other way. Taylor, look over here. Over here!
Wave to your grandpa. Say, `Hi, Grandpa!' Show him your new
T-shirt. Come on, Taylor, smile!''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's father had a video camcorder attached to his face and
was determined, apparently, to let no moment of this vacation go
undocumented. Taylor riding the carousel. Taylor drinking from a
fountain. Taylor looking miserable as he is hugged by some garishly
costumed theme park employee.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Taylor, his father did not have access to one of
Sony's new Digital 8 Handycam camcorders with up to 10 hours of
battery life and the capability to shoot video in the dark.
Otherwise, his entire day might have been directed and
choreographed by his video-crazed dad.
</P>
<P>
   The new Handycam, in the right hands, is actually a delightful
piece of technology. It has many of the best features of digital
camcorders, including superior picture quality, near CD-quality
sound, the ability to snap digital still photographs, to make exact
digital copies of tapes, to add special effects and to transfer
images easily to a personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   It can also record on and play back from older, less expensive
and more widely available 8-mm and Hi-8 video cassettes. Most
digital camcorders use a special digital video (DV) cassette, which
is smaller than an 8-mm cassette, and of course they are
incompatible.
</P>
<P>
   So the new Handycam is an ideal bridge between digital and
analog video cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Sony also makes DV-only camcorders, for those who are willing to
make a clean break with the past. But the new line of Digital 8
video cameras _ three models ranging from $699 to $1,399 (suggested
retail prices), offer a smart compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason to get a digital video camera is picture
quality. With a horizontal resolution of more than 500 lines, a
digital video camera can create very sharp pictures, much better
than analogue camcorders. By contrast, Super VHS and Hi-8 formats
record 400 lines, standard television is 330 lines, and
8-millimeter and VHS camcorders record only 250 lines.
</P>
<P>
   I've been testing the top-of-the-line Digital 8 model, the
DCR-TRV510. It is larger and heavier than most DV camcorders, but
about the same size and heft as analog 8-mm cameras. Although it
records onto Hi-8 tapes with exactly the same high resolution and
clarity of digital camcorders that use DV tape, it does so at the
expense of recording time.
</P>
<P>
   A 120-minute Hi-8 tape in a Digital 8 camcorder yields just 60
minutes of recorded video, while a 120-minute DV tape in a DV
digital camcorder yields the full two hours.
</P>
<P>
   At $1,399, the DCR-TRV510 is more expensive than most 8-mm
camcorders, yet less expensive than some DV models, which charge a
premium for miniaturization. Still, it comes loaded with digital
camera features.
</P>
<P>
   The DCR-TRV510 has a color viewfinder and a flip-out, four-inch
color display screen that is among the best I've seen. The screen
image still washes out in bright sunlight, as they all seem to do,
but it is impressive indoors.
</P>
<P>
   All of the Sony Digital 8 models come with a 20X optical zoom
lens that can be boosted to 360X magnification via digital zooming.
Digital zooming is overrated. It does not add anything to picture
quality, but merely enlarges the size of the digital picture
elements (pixels) in the center of the image.
</P>
<P>
   Zooming in too tightly creates a blocky, mosaic effect that one
often sees on television when one of Jerry Springer's guests
decides to reveal an intimate tattoo.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The camera is also equipped with image stabilization technology
that reduces the normal shakes and jitters that plague hand-held
cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The camera has video and audio ports, which means that it can be
hooked up to an older video camera, a VCR or a television set to
make digital copies of older analog tapes or even TV broadcasts.
With analog tapes, every time a copy is made, the picture is
degraded just a little. When both the image and the soundtrack are
made of 1s and 0s, digital copies are identical to the original.
</P>
<P>
   Some people may want to transfer their older analog tapes to
newer digital tapes, to preserve picture quality and memories for
the future.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more intriguing features of the DCR-TRV510 is called
I-Link, which is Sony's brand name for an IEEE 1394 digital
interface. IEEE 1394, also known as Firewire, is a high-speed data
transfer port that is popular on newer personal computers and
digital peripherals.
</P>
<P>
   The I-Link port is bidirectional, which means that it can send
not only video to a PC _ because it is digital, there is no need
for a separate PC video capture board _ but also easily transfer
edited video from a PC back to the camcorder.
</P>
<P>
   Once the video is in the PC, a creative videographer might wish
to add a CD soundtrack, edit out the 99 percent of most videos that
are uninteresting except to parents and grandparents, and add fancy
scene transitions with fades, wipes, old-time movie and other
special effects.
</P>
<P>
   Another snazzy feature is Laser Link, which uses infrared waves
to transfer images. When an optional ($70) infrared receiver is
attached to a television, you can beam video directly to the
television set without wires, cables or gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   Infrared waves have other interesting properties, like the
ability to invisibly illuminate things at night. The Sony I tested
has a feature called Nightshot, which functions much like the night
vision scopes used by spies. It works over short distances in
almost complete darkness (zero lux), although the image is a
washed-out monochrome with an eerie green tint.
</P>
<P>
   Sony suggests that Nightshot is handy during camping trips,
perhaps for tracking and videotaping wily nocturnal creatures like
foxes or teen-agers. Another possible use, Sony suggests, is for
keeping an infrared eye on the baby at night without turning on the
lights.
</P>
<P>
   I have mixed feelings about using the video camera as a digital
still camera. The Sony can store hundreds of snapshots on a tape.
Its ability to capture both video and still images is a harbinger
of the eventual convergence of digital cameras with digital
camcorders. But transferring the pictures off the tape is somewhat
awkward, and I still prefer a true digital camera.
</P>
<P>
   But I liked the Sony's ability to capture a single frame from a
video tape. The image can be transferred to a PC and perhaps sent
as e-mail or posted to a Web site. The software to allow the PC to
receive and manipulate the images is included.
</P>
<P>
   Another clever touch is the use of an ``Info-Lithium'' battery.
Lithium ion batteries are far superior to the older nickel cadmium
batteries (NiCads), because they do not have the so-called memory
effect that required the owner to worry about discharging the
battery completely before recharging. Lithium batteries can be
recharged whenever the opportunity arises.
</P>
<P>
   The ``info'' part of the battery is very handy. It tells, via a
digital meter in the camera's viewfinder and on its side control
panel, exactly how many minutes are left before the battery goes
kaput.
</P>
<P>
   I rarely got 30 minutes of active use from the battery that came
with the camera. For $60 to $150 more, Sony offers optional Stamina
batteries that promise up to 10 hours of uninterrupted recording
time. Sorry, Taylor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1618EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6565 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SOLUTION-U.N.-     04-28 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SOLUTION-U.N.-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN WE WIN THE PEACE? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By RODRIC BRAITHWAITE  
 c.1999 Prospect Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Since the alternative is too horrible to contemplate, let us
assume that before long NATO succeeds in imposing its will on
President Milosevic, with or without the use of ground troops, and
that a kind of peace has descended on the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to remember is that it is not only Kosovars who
have suffered as a result of Milosevic's murderous drive for a
Greater Serbia. As a consequence of his policies, hundreds of
thousands of Serbs have also been expelled from lands which their
forefathers have occupied for centuries in Croatia, Bosnia and no
doubt now in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps these people will conclude, as the Germans did 50 years
ago, that they must pay the price for following a deluded leader,
and learn to live within diminished boundaries. But it is more
likely that they will conclude that once again they have been the
victims of a historic injustice, and that they will brood in
bitterness, waiting to launch yet another futile attempt to reverse
the verdict of history.
</P>
<P>
   And yet for the future tranquillity of the Balkans, the Serbs
will have to be brought back into the international community as
equal members.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the consequences go much wider than the Balkans
alone.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, NATO will be profoundly affected even in victory.
There were two main arguments about NATO enlargement. One argument
was that NATO would remain a purely defensive alliance, and that
those who remained outside had nothing to fear. The other was that
NATO would now acquire a new role: to promote human rights,
democracy, good government and market economics inside Europe.
</P>
<P>
   It was never clear how a military organization could promote
civilian objectives. But the ultimatum which NATO delivered to
Serbia _ and the war which has followed it _ means that it can no
longer be portrayed as a purely defensive alliance. And many are
wondering where it will stop.
</P>
<P>
   Russia could gain or lose. Before the crisis, most Russians were
as ignorant of what was happening in Kosovo as most Westerners. If
Prime Minister Primakov's bid to act as a broker in the peacemaking
succeeds, he will boost the prestige of Russia as well as of
himself. But many in the West regard Russia as an irritating
irrelevance. Relations between Russia and the West could spiral
downward.
</P>
<P>
   NATO members have been surprisingly united in support of
military action. Milosevic's policies left them no decent choice.
But NATO has turned out to be a very blunt instrument. Even if a
halfway decent settlement is now cobbled together for Kosovo, it
will be more difficult to get people to support a repetition of the
trick in another European crisis. And America is now likely to find
it harder to get European support for the idea that NATO should
extend itself beyond this continent, to help maintain the peace
wherever it is threatened, and punish villains wherever they are
found.
</P>
<P>
   This raises the biggest question of all: the nature and the
future of U.S. global power. Americans believe that they have a
duty to slay dragons. But the record _ in Vietnam, in Iraq, in
Iran, in Somalia, even in neighboring Cuba _ demonstrates that
there are severe practical limitations even to the most awesome
military power, especially when it is exercised in the belief that
technology can substitute for body bags.
</P>
<P>
   All our relationships are likely to be more edgy as a result of
what has happened. NATO's identity crisis and trans-Atlantic
recrimination are likely to intensify, even as the Europeans wonder
whether they will ever be able to organize a peaceful continent
without external assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Countries such as India or China, which do not share the U.S.
view of its own role, will become more inclined to join in
resisting U.S. demands. Sooner or later America too will have to
adapt to an imperfect world. But there is a danger of going too
far, and retreating into sullen isolationism.
</P>
<P>
   It is a glum prospect. Because there are no simple, cheap or
satisfying solutions, we will have to go for complex and boring
ones.
</P>
<P>
   NATO should abandon its wilder pretensions to set the rest of
the world on a right moral course. It should concentrate instead on
its basic function as a defensive alliance and expand its network
of partnerships with non-members. In Europe, the main, and most
successful body for the promotion of peace, prosperity and
democratic rights in Europe, is not NATO but the European Union. It
should give practical aid and political support to the countries
most immediately affected by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which
includes Russia, should become the main pan-European agency for the
resolution of political disputes between its members.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the much despised United Nations. Of course
the U.N. cannot solve all, perhaps not even many, of the world's
problems. Of course it provides no basis for starry-eyed optimism
about universal peace and world government. But despite its
numerous failures, it is the only comprehensive, law-based body
which exists for the purpose of settling political disputes among
its members.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief period at the end of the 1980s and the beginning of
the 1990s, while the Permanent Members of the Security Council
still took one another seriously, it functioned as its founders had
intended. The theory which has recently gained currency _ that if
the United Nations cannot agree then the United States and its
allies have the right and the duty to take action on their own _ is
arrogant, subversive of the rule of law, and unattractive to a lot
of people.
</P>
<P>
   However inconvenient, it is time for the Western powers to try
once more to make the United Nations work.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Rodric Braithwaite was foreign policy adviser to John Major,
the former prime minister of Great Britain.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
