<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEEP-BLUE-SEA-2TAKES-     04-28 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEEP-BLUE-SEA-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERFECTIONIST TRIES TO MAKE A FISH STORY TITANIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday May 2)  
(rk) 
 By BRUCE NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ He has spent the morning polishing his shark as if
he were someone detailing a car _ meticulously examining the
gleaming grillwork of its mouth, the coldness of its eyes, the
rakish tilt of its dorsal fin _ and now Renny Harlin must face the
music.
</P>
<P>
   Not the theme music that the shark in Steven Spielberg's
``Jaws'' was always humming. Dum-dum. Dum-dum. How did people in
the water not hear that? No, Harlin's shark movie is of a different
kind.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Deep Blue Sea,'' the director has assembled more than 300
tracks of recorded sounds, so that this essentially noiseless
creature can chew through metal and flesh _ and, with any luck, the
summer box office after the film's July 30 release _ in deafening
Dolby digital.
</P>
<P>
   It is actually possible to trace the evolution of the summer
action movie over the last quarter-century by examining the chum
line of plot contrivances and special effects that leads from
``Jaws'' to ``Deep Blue Sea.'' In his 1975 classic, Spielberg made
do with a single, peckish shark that was rarely seen and _ except
for the humming _ never heard.
</P>
<P>
   In Harlin's far frothier film, research scientists have
genetically altered the DNA of an entire fleet of mako sharks, and
are on the verge of finding a cure for Alzheimer's disease, when
something goes horribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the scientists are being stalked by their own coldblooded
creations, which have overrun the floating laboratory Aquatica, a
place that was considered the last word in mad-scientist housing
until it started to sink in a tropical storm so big, you half
expect to see cows flying through the air.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, just when you thought it was safe to go back in
the multiplex: ``Jurassic Shark.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has seen sharks in living rooms, bedrooms and kitchens
before,'' declares Harlin, to whom such auteurist flourishes just
seem to come naturally.
</P>
<P>
   On this morning, he has come to an editing room on the Warner
Brothers lot to study an action sequence, which lasts several
minutes and in which the longest speech delivered by anyone not
breathing through gills is ``Oh, my God!'' Harlin has used his own
boat to get the sound of an idling motor just right.
</P>
<P>
   ``You spend so much time making all these little decisions to
try to make it perfect,'' he says. ``And in the end, if the movie
doesn't work, if people watch it and say it wasn't any good, you
feel like, `What fools we were for all that work.' Because it just
means nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Any conversation with Harlin about his new water movie must
eventually wash up on ``Cutthroat Island,'' the submersible bomb
that nearly destroyed his career. When it detonated in 1995 _
``Cutthroat Island'' was the film industry's first $100 million
flop, making back only $10 million _ all he could think about were
the thousands of custom-made costumes, the hundreds of swords and
pistols whose details he had agonized over getting just right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depressed me, of course,'' he says of the debacle,
``because we had chosen every pirate hat and sword with great
care.''
</P>
<P>
   In the editing room, his eye is on the 25-foot, 8,000-pound
mechanical shark that the studio built for him. With its
thousand-horsepower hydraulic engine, the shark was capable of
doing 35 miles an hour, though speed was less the point than the
relentless need to keep moving forward, a need that it shares with
the director.
</P>
<P>
   During one scene in which the shark was making its way through a
half-flooded living room, a glitch in the beast's software suddenly
launched it straight up through the ceiling. ``It went through the
two-by-four beams there like they were cheese,'' Harlin says
proudly. ``It gave everybody a good idea of the power of the
shark.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a power Harlin knows very well, having spent the last
decade swimming with the sharks in Hollywood, before being nearly
devoured by them. In the early '90s, he quickly moved to the front
rank of action-movie directors with the consecutive box-office
successes ``Die Hard 2'' and ``Cliffhanger.'' Harlin is a
6-foot-4-inch Finn with flowing blond hair and a great bronze slab
of a face.
</P>
<P>
   When he was living large, Harlin took no prisoners, though every
night he was visited by the nightmares that have haunted him since
he was a little boy. ``It's always the same,'' he says. ``Being
chased, being guilty of something, losing everything. I'm in the
middle of a movie, and all of a sudden the police come and accuse
me of murder. They're taking me to jail and I'm looking at the set,
thinking: `Oh, my God, I've lost it all. It's over.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Harlin blinks. ``It does make for a life without very many happy
moments,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He had waited his whole life for happiness. Now he was hungry
for it, and at any price. When he married the Oscar-winning actress
Geena Davis in 1993, their guests' feet rarely touched the ground
during a wedding weekend of elephant and hot-air balloon rides.
Overhead, a skywriter painted interlocking hearts across the sky.
The budget for this diorama was reportedly $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ended up costing an insane amount of money, yes,'' Harlin
says. ``I was afraid to get married and have kids because I thought
it would ruin my career, so I had waited until I was 34. I took it
very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Was the wedding worth it? ``I don't know,'' he says. ``We just
tried to make it as beautiful and romantic and memorable as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that same impulse, oddly, that guided Harlin as he walked
down the plank on ``Cutthroat Island.'' That epic shipwreck became
emblematic of a kind of wretched excess associated with Hollywood
egos run amok, and Harlin's directorial swagger seemed particularly
evident in his determination to make his wife an action-movie star.
</P>
<P>
   He attempted it first on the pirate picture, though it cost him
the film's only bankable star, Michael Douglas. Douglas felt Ms.
Davis' role was being beefed up at the expense of his own, and quit
after Harlin declined to do anything about it. (The director
insists now that Douglas was merely ``exhausted'' and didn't want
to go to Malta for several months.)
</P>
<P>
   Then he cast Ms. Davis as a platinum blond assassin in ``The
Long Kiss Goodnight,'' which also failed to make money.
</P>
<P>
   He was reviled for all this. ``Hollywood people love to gossip
and snicker about other people's failure,'' he says. But the sin
for which Harlin suffered _ and for which he was willing to risk
everything _ was the pride that he obviously took in showing off
his wife to the world.
</P>
<P>
   Was he blinded by love? ``I can't deny that in some ways it
played a part in everything falling apart,'' he says. ``People
think: `Oh, this is too much, you're so in love and you're doing
everything together. It's unbearable. What do you think, that
you're going to be the king and queen of the world?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The royal pain of divorce came swiftly enough, in 1998, but
while it lasted their relationship seemed to be based not so much
on hubris as happiness.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Unaccustomed as he was to that, Harlin felt unfettered in a way
he never had, as if unconstrained by the normal rules.
</P>
<P>
   When he was hired in 1997 to make ``Deep Blue Sea,'' he was sent
to sprinkle himself in the same holy waters used by Hollywood's
last self-proclaimed king of the world: the 17 million-gallon tank
near Rosarito, Mexico, that was constructed for the making of
``Titanic'' by the director James Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   You might think that sending the only director in the history of
the film industry ever to lose $100 million on a water picture into
the tank used by the only director in history ever to make him look
like a piker doing it _ Cameron is believed to have spent closer to
$200 million _ would have given Lorenzo di Bonaventura, the Warner
Brothers production chief, pause. It did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to protect ourselves, and be certain that Renny
would be fiscally responsible, so I think we were careful about
getting into business with him,'' says di Bonaventura.
</P>
<P>
   The studio counted on Harlin's determination to prove he wasn't
a wild-eyed profligate. And it kept him on a very short leash, with
a budget of less than $80 million. ``We went through a long period
of analyzing every element in the movie with him,'' says di
Bonaventura. ``So in terms of what we were going to try to do and
how we were going to do it, we were 100 percent confident that he
would follow what essentially we had worked out as a partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   The studio brought in veteran writer and producer Akiva
Goldsman, possibly as its proxy in this ``partnership'' with
Harlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had heard tales galore,'' Goldsman says of the director. ``I
just heard that Renny drove forward with an intensity that was all
about getting the movie made without necessarily embracing the
emotions of the people making the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldsman pauses, probably exhausted. ``In our business, personal
growth is not a prerequisite,'' he adds, ``and it makes you really
admire those who do it. There's a force of imagination in remaking
one's life that dwarfs the imagination required to make a movie. I
had a sense that this was a man who decided he had to change. And
not just superficially.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Harlin is now able to view his life as
narrative, with its inevitable ups and downs. ``I was shy and
insecure when I first came from Finland,'' he says, ``and I tried
to cover that by being tough and strong. After `Cliffhanger,' I
thought I had really figured it out, that I had found the key.
Really, it was the Hollywood dream. It was just as one could have
imagined. Then I was humbled, and now I have sort of come full
circle, being who I am but able to listen to people more, and
relate to people in a better way. It's the most humbling thing to
totally fail.''
</P>
<P>
   In this summer's third reel, Harlin will find out if he is
heroically redeemed by success, or if he is the devil in ``Deep
Blue Sea.'' Either way, his passion for action impressed one of the
film's young stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``During his bad days and his good days, it's all about getting
the good stuff,'' says Thomas Jane, the virtual unknown Harlin cast
in the picture's biggest role, as the shark expert Carter Blake,
``making it a little scarier, a little faster, a little more
dangerous than you've seen before. He eats, breathes and sleeps
getting the good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he sleeps, Harlin still dreams that the good stuff
might all be taken away some day. ``The worst feeling is when the
film is completely finished and you're just on your own,'' he says.
``It's a very empty feeling, like you're completely unnecessary.
It's incredible to have all these people come to work and look at
you, and they'll do what you tell them to do. Pulling it all
together, making something happen.
</P>
<P>
   What could be better than that?''
</P>
<P>
   His voice gets very small, like a little boy's. ``The scariest
moments are when you are just with yourself,'' he says. ``Then you
don't know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Newman, a writer based in Venice, Calif., wrote most
recently for Arts and Leisure about the television show, ``It's
Like, You Know. ...''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
