<HEADLINE>
HOMELESS GET SHOPPING CARTS AS CITY MOVES AGAINST VAGRANCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ John White is homeless, but he is also the proud
owner of his very own shopping cart.
</P>
<P>
   White was one of five homeless people Tuesday to receive a cart,
along with a certification of ownership courtesy of the Homeless
Coalition and POOR magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But hours after White received his cart to tote around all his
wordly possessions, the San Francisco Shopping Cart Task Force
moved to make it tougher for homeless people to have carts.
</P>
<P>
   On an 8-3 vote, the task force sent to the Board of Supervisors
a proposal to require businesses to work to keep the carts on their
premises. It also would require businesses to attach signs to their
shopping carts identifying ownership.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation will be assigned to a Board of Supervisors'
committee before going before the full board for consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal by the task force, led by Supervisor Amos Brown,
and the shopping cart giveaway are the latest in a tension-filled
chess match between advocates for homeless people and the city.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown, who has become the homeless advocates' symbol for
what they say are mean-spirited objectives for dealing with
homelessness, said that this proposal reflected only his interest
in eliminating clutter on San Francisco streets. The proposal was
not aimed at homeless people, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sidewalks were made to walk on, not for storage of carts and
people's belongings,'' Brown said. The proposal, he said, is aimed
at removing unattended and empty shopping carts, ``the same as we'd
remove anything left that poses safety hazards.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mara Raider of the Homeless Coalition, also a member of the
task force, said proposals, such as Brown's latest, ``criminalize
homeless people.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the city has started a war on homelessness that
includes confiscating carts and possessions by the police and the
Department of Public Works, and rousting vagabonds from parks and
tourist spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a full frontal attack on homeless people, their
property and their rights,'' Raider said, referring in part to
crackdowns on homeless people in public places and on panhandlers
who use median strips and freeway ramps to beg for money.
</P>
<P>
   The shopping cart giveaway by the Homeless Coalition and the
magazine is an effort to break down the legal obstacles that stand
in the way of homeless people owning shopping carts, said Judy
Appel of the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   She promised that more free carts, which were donated to the
organization, would be given away.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown accused the homeless advocates of staging the
giveaway. ``They knew we were having a hearing tonight. So they
used props and strategies to dramatize,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, Raider proposed having the city establish a
program to give carts to homeless people.
</P>
<P>
   Raider also asked that people whose carts and possessions are to
be confiscated be given 24-hour notice and that a grievance
procedure be put in place for people who believe a cart was
confiscated unlawfully.
</P>
<P>
   Those proposals were defeated 7-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
