<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFIDELITY-1170(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFIDELITY COMES OUT OF THE CLOSET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Wash., N.C.)  (js) 
 By JOSEPH HOOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the course of his 12-year marriage, Bob M., a 40-year-old
executive from Annapolis, Md., had racked up a considerable
extramarital track record. One night in bed, his wife, Bernadette,
39, asked him whether he had ever strayed, and Bob, sick of the
deception, confirmed her worst suspicions. Two months later, their
marriage held together with prayer and Scotch tape, Bob and
Bernadette, who, to protect their privacy, spoke on the condition
that their full names not be used, went to their first session with
Frederick DiBlasio, a therapist and professor of social work at the
University of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look your spouse in the eye,'' Bob said, describing the
session, ``and you itemize everything you did. `I fornicated with
this woman. I had oral sex with that woman.' And then you ask for
forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to lie,'' Bernadette said. ``It was a
heart-piercing thing to hear. Infidelity takes away every ounce of
trust in a marriage. If I didn't have all the details addressed
early on, I would have thrown it back in his face. In order to
forgive, you need to know.''
</P>
<P>
   DiBlasio says he believes forgiveness can be asked for, and
received, in an instant. For people who have been on the receiving
end of infidelity, that may fly in the face of what they think they
know about the human heart. But it's just one, and probably the
most radical one, of many infidelity strategies and theories that
have begun making the therapeutic rounds.
</P>
<P>
   No reliable evidence exists that Americans are cheating more now
on their spouses than they ever did. A highly-regarded 1994
University of Chicago survey, Sex in America, conservatively put
the figure at 25 percent for men, 12 percent for women. But
whatever the actual incidence, most experts think it is unlikely
that infidelity is more popular today than it was in the 1950s and
1960s, when men often enjoyed the advantages of a sexual double
standard, or in the swinging '70s, when open marriage had its
vogue. But if psychologists and therapists have anything to say
about it, we are entering a Golden Age of thinking about
infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that the nation has learned more than it ever
wanted to know about its president's extramarital sex life,
therapists are churning out popular books about affairs and how to
survive them. The past two months alone saw two new volumes, ``When
Your Lover Is a Liar'' by Susan Forward (HarperCollins, $24) and
``Women Who Stay With Men Who Stray'' by Debbie Then (Hyperion,
$23.95). At the same time, therapists' counterparts in academia are
receiving grants to study how and why married people cheat and what
can be done to repair the damage. Infidelity, of all things, has
come out of the closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back when I started 20 years ago, you couldn't even find
infidelity mentioned in the classic family-therapy texts,'' said
Don-David Lusterman, a couples therapist in Baldwin, N.Y., and
author of ``Infidelity: A Survival Guide'' (New Harbinger
Publications, 1998, $12.95). Now, Neil Jacobson, a much-published
professor of psychology at the University of Washington, is
starting a pilot study, which he hopes to expand into
government-funded clinical trials. His goal: to find out who cheats
and why and what can be done in therapy to salvage their marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of eight studies of his own, Jacobson has found
that only half the married couples who go into marital therapy
derive any significant long-term benefit from it. Late last year,
at the annual convention of the Association for Advancement of
Behavior Therapy in Washington, he dared a packed hotel ballroom of
psychologists to put aside ``techniques for taking out the
garbage'' in order to address ``a primitive, dark underbelly'' of
couple relationships. ``We're going to make rapid progress,'' he
declared. ``Long live extramarital-affair research.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone can agree, however, what direction that research
should take. Jacobson and most of his colleagues see themselves as
scrupulous scientists of the unrulier passions. But the new
interest in infidelity has opened the door for academic mavericks
who believe that morality and spirituality have a role, a
scientifically measurable role, in treating troubled couples.
DiBlasio travels the couples-therapy conference circuit challenging
the therapeutic wisdom that a betrayed spouse must traverse a long,
torturous path to forgive the betrayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The knee-jerk reaction is, you can't do it in a day,''
DiBlasio said. He counters the skeptics with a double faith: a
Christian belief in the power of forgiveness and a cognitive
therapist's confidence in the power of the directed mind to
overrule emotional impulse. ``For years, the research has shown
that expressing anger doesn't cure it,'' he said. ``What cures it
is finding a connection with faith, inner peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidentally, Bob and Bernadette share DiBlasio's
Christian belief _ in fact, credit it as the ultimate guarantor of
their marital salvation. But the therapist says that his approach
isn't only for Christians. He says that forgiveness as something
given and not earned is common to many of the world's religions.
</P>
<P>
   During their first session with DiBlasio, a couple will also
draw up a contract of behavior designed to prevent future
infidelities, and the offending partner may sign up a same-sex
``accountability'' partner, like an Alcoholics Anonymous sponsor,
to help him or her live up to the terms. Not even DiBlasio believes
that one session cures all unhappiness, but, he argues, the initial
commitment to forgive takes much of the sting, and the longevity,
out of the recrimination that inevitably follows the discovery of
an affair. He is now putting these ideas to the secular test in an
ambitious study that compares outcomes in a large group of couples
receiving his forgiveness therapy with a group receiving more
standard couples counseling and a control group that gets no help
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson has heard enough about forgiveness for one lifetime.
``It makes me cringe,'' he said from his Seattle office. ``Why
should we assume that the person who needs forgiveness is the
perpetrator of the extramarital affair?'' he said. (Actually, most
therapists would make that assumption, but Jacobson is being
provocatively neutral.)
</P>
<P>
   The cornerstone of his ``acceptance based'' therapy model is the
idea, untested, that opportunity has more to do with affairs than
moral values. ``It's easy for a 300-pound man to say he's never had
an affair in 30 years of marriage, but how much has he been
tested?'' Jacobson said.
</P>
<P>
   As for forgiveness, Jacobson says he thinks it may indeed occur
after an infidelity but only according to its own logic and
timetable. The best thing the therapist can do, he argues, is to
provide a safe haven for the angry betrayed spouse and the guilty
betraying spouse to work through their emotions. ``For a
relationship to survive an affair,'' he said, ``a perpetrator has
to accept the possibility that he may never be forgiven.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
