<HEADLINE>
TOUR TIME: SPRING BECOMES THE NORTHEAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Conn., Pa., Mass., R.I.)   (bl)  
 By SHELLY FREIERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From an 1811 farmhouse in Doylestown, Pa., to ocean-front
gardens in Rye, N.Y., to a Park Avenue duplex, show houses and
house and garden tours are preparing for visitors in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   All of the tours are self-guided unless otherwise indicated.
Here is a selection in six states.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK CITY
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Hill, Brooklyn, Sunday _ A mix of 19th-century houses
will be open for a tour from noon to 5 p.m. They include a house
with a central oak staircase and a renovated 1870s carriage house
that was once a restaurant and is now a residence, decorated with
contemporary art. The tour will also include the studios of 30
local artists in converted industrial buildings. Tickets, $15, at
the Caroline Ladd Pratt House, 229 Clinton Ave., near DeKalb
Avenue. Information: (718) 855-7090.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn Heights, May 8 _ Five residences will be open for a
tour from 1 to 5 p.m. They include an 1880s row house with
interiors painted in persimmon, cranberry and yellow and decorated
with Biedermeier furniture and Kosta Boda glassware, and a duplex
apartment in an 1840s brownstone with contemporary furnishings,
custom fireplaces and views of lower Manhattan. No children under
13 except infants in front packs. Tickets on day of tour, $25, at
122 Pierrepont St., near Clinton Street. Information: (718)
858-9193.
</P>
<P>
   Park Slope, Brooklyn, May 16 _ The 40th-annual Park Slope Civic
Council House Tour, featuring 10 houses, some with gardens, will be
from noon to 5 p.m. Highlights will include collections of artwork
from Bali and Thailand, murals, drawings for opera and ballet
productions and a roof garden. No children under 10. Tickets in
advance, $10, and information: (718) 832-8227. Tickets on day of
tour, $15, at Dizzy's Diner, Eighth Avenue at Ninth Street.
</P>
<P>
   Upper East Side, Manhattan, May 18 _ Six residences will be open
from 6 to 9 p.m. for a tour to benefit United Cerebral Palsy of New
York City. They include a duplex formed from five apartments and a
Park Avenue apartment decorated with French and English Regency
antiques, lacquer objects and contemporary art. Tickets, $75, by
mail in advance only, 105 Madison Ave., New York 10016.
Information: (212) 683-6700, ext. 217.
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea, Manhattan, June 5 _ A guided tour of six to eight
private gardens will start at 4 p.m., followed by a reception.
Proceeds from tickets, $30, will benefit Public School 11. Tickets
in advance at the Chelsea Garden Center, Ninth Avenue at 22nd
Street; on day of tour, at Clement Moore Park, 10th Avenue at 22nd
Street. Information: (212) 496-4520.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton Heights, Manhattan, June 5 and 6 _ Architectural
historian Michael Henry Adams will lead a walking tour June 5, noon
to 2 p.m. Tickets, $10, on June 5 at Hamilton Grange, Convent
Avenue at 141st Street. A tour of 12 houses, including those in
Romanesque, Beaux-Arts and Italian Renaissance Revival styles, will
be June 6. Proceeds will benefit the Hamilton Grange Branch of the
New York Public Library and the Hamilton Heights Preservation Fund.
Tickets in advance, $12, for June 6 and information: (212)
281-4442. Tickets on June 6, $18, at the Grange.
</P>
<P>
   Prospect Lefferts Gardens, Brooklyn, June 6 _ Brownstones and
limestone row houses will be open for a tour from noon to 5 p.m.
They include a row house with a stained-glass skylight, made with
glass recovered from churches and synagogues, and a flower garden
with pond. A brick house built by a shipbuilder in the early 1900s
has a Mission-style fireplace and floor-to-ceiling wainscoting.
Tickets in advance, $10, and information: (718) 284-6210 or (718)
462-0024. Tickets on day of tour, $15, Mike's International
Restaurant, 552 Flatbush Ave., near Lincoln Road.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Hill, Fort Greene and Prospect Heights, Brooklyn, June 6
_ Sixteen private gardens will be included on a tour from 11 a.m.
to 5 p.m., along with community gardens, the sculpture garden at
the Pratt Institute and the garden at St. Joseph's College.
Proceeds from tickets and an herb and plant sale will benefit Argus
Community, a social services group. Tickets in advance, $8, and
information: (718) 855-7090. Tickets on day of tour: Tillie's
coffeehouse, DeKalb and Vanderbilt Avenues in Clinton Hill;
Brooklyn Music School, 126 Felix St., near Lafayette Avenue, in
Fort Greene, and Muddy Waters Coffee Bar, 669 Vanderbilt Ave., near
Prospect Place, in Prospect Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Heights, Queens, June 12 and 13 _ Eight private gardens
will be open June 12, from noon to 4 p.m. A free lecture on the
neighborhood's history will be offered at 10:45 a.m. and 12:15 p.m.
at Community United Methodist Church, 35th Avenue at 82nd Street,
where there will also be an exhibition of historic photographs. On
June 13, guided walking tours will start at noon in front of the
church. Tickets, either tour, $8; both tours, $12. Information:
(212) 439-8784.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Morris Park, Manhattan, June 13 _ Ten private houses and
two or three churches will be open for a tour from 11 a.m. to 4
p.m. A guided tour will be offered at 1 and 3 p.m. Tickets in
advance, $12, and information: (212) 369-4241. Tickets on day of
tour, $15, at the Pelham Fritz Community Center, 18 Mount Morris
Park West, at 122nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   LONG ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   Huntington, through June 27 _ A show house at Oheka, a French
chateau, on East Gate Drive off Route 25, features 35 designers.
Open Tuesday through Friday, 10:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.; Saturday and
Sunday, 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. (closed May 23 and June 20). Admission is
$18; those 62 and older, $16; those 10 to 16, $5. Information:
(516) 367-2600.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Cliff, May 16 _ An 1890 ornate Victorian house, with 18
rooms and gas lighting fixtures and woodwork, will be one of seven
houses on a tour from noon to 4 p.m. Tickets in advance, $12, and
information: (516) 733-0013. Tickets on day of tour, $15, at the
village green, Sea Cliff Avenue at Central Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Roslyn, June 5 _ Twelve buildings, including a Queen Anne
Revival-style house and the 1824 home of the author William Cullen
Bryant, will be open for a tour from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Tickets in
advance, $15, and information: (516) 625-4363. Tickets on day of
tour, $18, in front of Roslyn Savings Bank, Old Northern Boulevard
at East Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   WESTCHESTER COUNTY, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Yorktown, May 23 _ Seven houses will be open from noon to 5
p.m., to benefit the Foundation for Excellence in Yorktown
Education. No one under 16 will be admitted. Tickets in advance,
$25, and information: (914) 245-3087. Tickets on day of tour, $30,
at French Hill Elementary School, Baldwin Road near Route 202.
</P>
<P>
   Rye (and Greenwich, Conn.), June 7 _ Five houses overlooking
Long Island Sound will be included on an art and architecture tour
to benefit the Neuberger Museum of Art. The houses, open from 10
a.m. to 4 p.m., will include a Colonial-style house decorated with
paintings by Robert Motherwell, Frank Stella and Louis Nevelson,
and another house highlighting the owner's majolica, porcelains and
paintings by David Hockney and Rene Magritte. No one under 16 will
be admitted. Tickets before May 27, $80 (members, $65), or on day
of tour, $90 (members, $75), at the museum, 735 Anderson Hill Road.
Information: (914) 251-6115.
</P>
<P>
   ORANGE COUNTY, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Newburgh, June 12 and 13 _ A house-and-garden weekend on the
theme of adapting historic structures starts on June 12, 10 a.m. to
4 p.m., with a series of talks and workshops on topics like
restoring stained glass and decorative finishes. On June 13, from
noon to 5 p.m., there will be a tour of 15 properties, including a
garden shed being used as an artist's studio, a former residence
serving as a school and a 19th-century mill converted into a house.
Tickets, for June 12, $15, and for June 13, $20, from the
Historical Society of Newburgh Bay and the Highlands, Crawford
House, 189 Montgomery St., at Clinton Street. Information: (914)
561-2585.
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY
</P>
<P>
   Princeton, through May 22 _ Regent's Mead, a 35-room field-stone
house built in 1929 is the site of a show house by 40 designers to
benefit the Junior League of Greater Princeton. Open Tuesday
through Thursday, 10 a.m. to 3 p.m.; Friday, noon to 8 p.m.;
Saturday, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m., and Sunday, noon to 5 p.m. No children
under 12. Tickets, $18; those 62 and older, $15, at the show house,
Drakes Corner Road and the Great Road. Information: (609) 771-0525.
</P>
<P>
   Morristown, Sunday through May 31 _ Ten landscape architects and
33 designers are participating in a show house at Knox Hill, an
Tudor-style house with 25 rooms, leaded glass windows, mahogany
woodwork, courtyards and terraces. Open Monday through Saturday, 10
a.m. to 3 p.m.; Wednesday evening, 6 to 8; Sunday, noon to 4 p.m.
Tickets, to benefit Morristown Memorial Hospital, $20; those 62 and
older, $15. Parking and shuttle service at Sussex Avenue and
Kahdena Road. Information: (973) 538-5011.
</P>
<P>
   Montclair, May 14 through 23 _ The Van Vleck House and Gardens,
a Mediterranean-style villa, with 55-year old wisteria, hybrid
rhododendrons and beds planted with blueberry bushes, will be the
site of a showcase of 15 garden areas. Open Monday through Friday,
10 a.m. to 7 p.m.; Saturday and Sunday, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Tickets,
$15; students and those 65 and older, $10; children under 12, $5,
at 21 Van Vleck Street near Upper Mountain Avenue. Information:
(973) 744-0837.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bank, Rumson, Navesink and Oceanport, June 5 and 6 _ Six
estate gardens will be open on June 5, from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m.,
including the Borden estate, with a vegetable garden, perennial
beds and fish pond. An antiques show will be June 5, 10 a.m. to 7
p.m., and June 6, 11:30 a.m. to 7:30 p.m. All events will benefit
the Jacqueline M. Wilentz Comprehensive Breast Center of the
Monmouth Health Foundation. Tickets in advance for the tour and
show, $25, and information: (732) 923-6886. Tickets on June 5, $30;
those 65 and older, $20, at the show, Rumson Country Day School, 35
Bellevue Avenue, near Ridge Road. Tickets for antiques show only,
$10, at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Summit, Short Hills and New Providence, June 11 and 12 _ Six
private gardens, including a small cottage rose garden and formal
gardens with island beds of perennials surrounded by lawn, will be
open both days from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. On June 11 at 6:30 p.m., the
tour and a supper and auction will benefit the Reeves-Reed
Arboretum in Summit. Tickets in advance, by May 18, $60 for all
events; for the supper and auction only, $50; for the tour only,
$15. After May 18, tour tickets only, $20, at the arboretum, 165
Hobart Ave., near Route 24. Information: (908) 273-8787.
</P>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT
</P>
<P>
   Guilford, June 12 _ Ten private gardens, including seven in
Sachem's Head, an enclave bordering Long Island Sound, will be open
from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. to benefit Guilford A B C, a nonprofit
education organization. Four historic properties will also be open.
Tickets in advance, $12, and information: (203) 453-0069. Tickets
on day of tour, $15, on the Guilford village green at Whitfield and
Broad Streets.
</P>
<P>
   Lyme, Hadlyme and Old Lyme, June 18 and 19 _ Six private gardens
will be open each day, from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Proceeds will benefit
the Child and Family Agency of Southeastern Connecticut. Tickets in
advance, $18, and information: (860) 442-2797, ext. 420. Tickets on
day of tour, $20, at the Old Lyme Pharmacy, 90 Halls Road, near
exit 70 on Interstate 95.
</P>
<P>
   RHODE ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   Providence, June 11 and 12 _ A candlelight tour will be held on
both days from 6 to 10 p.m., and a house and garden tour will be
held on June 12 from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m., as part of the 20th annual
Festival of Historic Houses. Proceeds will benefit the Providence
Preservation Society. Tickets in advance, $20 a tour, are
recommended. Information: (401) 831-8587. Tickets on day of tour,
$20 a tour: for candlelight tour, Central Congregational Church,
296 Angell Street, near North Main Street; for house and garden
tour, Brown University Thayer Street Quad, 101 Thayer St., near
Hope Street.
</P>
<P>
   Newport, June 18 through 20 _ Fifteen private gardens will be
open for a tour to benefit the Benefactors of the Arts, on June 18
and 20, noon to 4 p.m., and June 19, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. There will
also be a plant sale. On June 19, a garden symposium will be held
($75, tickets in advance recommended). Tickets for the tour, $20,
at 33 Washington Street, near Goat Island Causeway. Information:
(401) 847-0514.
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS
</P>
<P>
   Newton, May 23 _ Nine houses, including a concrete house built
around 1900 by F.E. and F.O. Stanley, the brothers who made the
Stanley Steamer engine, will be open from noon to 5 p.m. to benefit
the Jackson Homestead Museum. Tickets in advance, $15, and
information: (617) 552-7238. Tickets on day of tour, $20, at the
museum, 527 Washington Street, near Jackson Road.
</P>
<P>
   Lenox and Lee, July 10 _ Six houses and their gardens will be
open from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. to benefit the Lenox Garden Club. They
include a 14-room Georgian house with formal gardens; a hilltop
house with a shade garden and view of the Berkshires, and a cottage
with a garden planted with hollyhocks, lilies, black-eyed Susans
and roses, Tickets before July 2, $25, and information: (413)
298-3089. Tickets on day of tour, $30, at Lilac Park, Main and
Sunset Streets in Lenox.
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, through May 16 _ The 21st annual Philadelphia Open
House features bus tours, garden tours and self-guided and guided
walking tours, including a self-guided tour on Saturday in Queen
Village, an area of older houses and converted commercial buildings
south of South Street, and a boat ride on May 13 on the Delaware
River to Fort Mifflin, a Revolutionary War site. Tickets from $20
to $75. Information: (215) 928-1188.
</P>
<P>
   Doylestown, Sunday through May 30 _ Glen Echo Farm, built in
1811 with additions since then and featuring six fireplaces and a
pine-paneled library, will be the site of a show house by 40
interior and landscape designers to benefit Doylestown Hospital and
the Village Improvement Association of Doylestown. Open Monday
through Saturday, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m.; Tuesday through Friday, 6:30
to 8:30 p.m.; Sunday, noon to 4 p.m. Tickets, $15, at the show
house, 360 Old Dublin Pike, near Easton Road. Information: (215)
345-2191.
</P>
<P>
   Newtown Square, May 8 through 31 _ The 33rd annual show house to
benefit the Philadelphia Vassar Club's scholarship fund will be at
Montparnasse, an 1896 stone house with intricate woodwork, stained
glass and a two-story library. Open Monday through Friday, 10 a.m.
to 3 p.m.; Tuesday through Friday, 6 to 8:30 p.m.; Saturday and
Sunday, noon to 4 p.m. Tickets, $18, at 800 Goshen Road, near
Darby-Paoli Road. Information: (610) 527-9717.
</P>
