<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6584 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAURUABUSH-COX     04-28 3433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAURUABUSH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What Laura Bush wants
 &HT;    EDITORS: WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Julie Bonnin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There's a speech Laura Bush has been giving
around Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The popular Texas first lady, a former schoolteacher and
children's librarian, begins by recounting letters from a class of
fourth-graders about what they have learned.
</P>
<P>
   `Nine-year-old Josh learned that you don't give a goldfish milk.
</P>
<P>
   `Jacob learned that when you have four girlfriends, you get 28
phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   `Megan learned that when you get a new baby in the house, you
get no attention.''
</P>
<P>
   And `Craig learned that there are usually disadvantages in
advantages.''
</P>
<P>
   There's something to Craig's theory.
</P>
<P>
   When you're first lady of Texas, people pay attention to
projects you care about; money gets channeled to libraries, to
literacy programs and to kids.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever you go, whether it's a poor El Paso neighborhood or the
country club, the waters part when you appear. People pay attention
to what you have to say; someone even paints your name on a
Harley-Davidson, emblazoning it alongside the state of Texas and of
course, bluebonnets.
</P>
<P>
   But when you're the wife of a presidential candidate, the media
throng gets thicker; the questions get meaner. On a brisk spring
day, the wind is blowing through the shade trees on the lawn at the
Governor's Mansion and you are sitting next to your husband,
beaming in a mint-green suit.
</P>
<P>
   From the horseshoe-shaped swarm of reporters and photographers
that surrounds the two of you, someone yells out: `Are there
skeletons in your closet?'' Friends from around the country
occasionally call to report rumors about your husband that they've
heard.
</P>
<P>
   Warm, but straightforward and no-nonsense, like your favorite
grade-school teacher, dressed and polished like the future U.S.
first lady she may yet be, Laura Bush has acknowledged there are
disadvantages as well as advantages to being married to a probable
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   `I know what the ugly side of politics is,'' she says. `The '92
race (then-President George Bush's unsuccessful re-election bid)
was miserable. It's very difficult to have bad things said about
the people you love.''
</P>
<P>
   The Woman Who Dared to be Publicly Hesitant is roundly described
by friends and family as someone with inner strength, someone who
takes things in stride.
</P>
<P>
   `Rock of Gibraltar,'' says her father-in-law .
</P>
<P>
   Unflappable, says mother-in-law Barbara Bush, `in contrast to
our family, which is anything but calm.''
</P>
<P>
   In troubling times, this Texas first lady has been known to cope
by putting things in order, particularly the books she so loves. In
the coming months, as the national media circus pokes and prods her
family onto center stage, one imagines her firm presence -- rooms
full of exceedingly tidy bookshelves in her wake. Fear of lack of
freedom
</P>
<P>
   She'd been warned the creek was high.
</P>
<P>
   But Laura Bush had plans to visit El Paso writers Lee and Bobby
Byrd at Paisano Ranch in southwest Travis County, where Lee Byrd
was on fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   And when she came face to face with the swirling waters of a
swollen Barton Creek, she `may have hesitated for about three
seconds,'' says friend Adair Margo, who was with her.
</P>
<P>
   `Then it was like, plop. All the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Your Texas first lady had plunged into the creek, a big grin on
her face. Just behind her, a panicked Department of Public Safety
officer in charge of protecting her was struggling to keep up and
to keep his gun dry.
</P>
<P>
   Unprogrammed, unscheduled moments are getting to be more and
more of a rarity in Laura Bush's already busy life.
</P>
<P>
   When she talks about why she wasn't the first to dive into her
husband's all-but-officially-announced presidential bid, losing
`the freedom of being able to move around without starting up a
motorcade'' is at the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   Though her anonymity is waning, she can still go for lunch at
Las Manitas without attracting a lot of attention. She can, on a
moment's notice, hop in a car with a long-time friend to see what
people are doing to their homes in Travis Heights or other Austin
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, there she was in the checkout line at Wal-Mart
(yes, Wal-Mart), with her twin daughters. The woman she was
chatting with, so sure she'd met this nice lady somewhere before,
finally had to say, no, sorry, her name just did not ring a bell.
</P>
<P>
   Only recently, she says, are folks starting to recognize her
when she flies around the state on Southwest Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake, the company she keeps is rarefied.
</P>
<P>
   There are those in-laws -- the former president and one of the
nation's most beloved first ladies.
</P>
<P>
   The woman behind the popular Texas Book Festival not only has
helped to raise nearly $600,000 for Texas libraries, she's been
able to meet dozens of famous authors, a bibliophile's dream. Lyle
Lovett, a favorite musician, entertained at a Christmas party at
the mansion.
</P>
<P>
   And during a spring break getaway to New York City with her
daughters, she took in the St. Patrick's Day parade with the
archbishop of New York , and met Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   At a clinic in a downtown El Paso neighborhood, Laura Bush
sweeps into the crowded lobby followed by a trail of television
cameras. An elderly woman, watching, says of her, `Muy bien. She
thinks and cares about the poor.'' Someone else says, `I want to
see if she's as beautiful as she is on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, balloons and banners decorate a parking lot adjoining
the clinic where Laura Bush and Texas Commissioner of Health
William cq''Reyn'' Archer talk about the importance of childhood
immunizations.
</P>
<P>
   This is the biggest advantage of being Texas' first lady, she
says.
</P>
<P>
   `I've had the opportunity to champion causes that I'm interested
in, I've had an opportunity to make an impact in our state.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Laura Bush has been asking people to support programs
that focus on nurturing kids from birth to age 3. ``We want to
level the playing field so that every child arrives (at school)
ready to learn,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   At the country club luncheon that follows her clinic visit,
women whose husbands are affiliated with factories on either side
of the border have gathered at dozens of tables to hear her speak.
</P>
<P>
   A woman in a salmon-colored suit nods approvingly at the notion
of Laura Bush as the nation's first lady .
</P>
<P>
   `Hillary's problem,'' she snips, `was getting involved in sticky
issues like abortion and a national health plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush's focus on literacy and children may be a safe bet
politically, but her interest comes naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Kenna Ramirez, the wife of El Paso's Democratic Mayor Carlos
Ramirez, became a fan after seeing the former teacher linger in
classrooms at a school she was visiting, long after the TV cameras
had left.
</P>
<P>
   `She was there for two hours. The media was gone. Her schedule
was tight, but she still took the time.''
</P>
<P>
   And Laura Bush is a book club member, an avid reader who always
has a book or two at her bedside -- last month she finished books
by two University of Texas professors: Jim Magnuson's `Windfall''
and Laura Furman's `Tuxedo Park.'' As a girl, she loved `Little
Women'' and `Little House on the Prairie,'' with its brown-haired
heroine named Laura. A fix-up with George W.
</P>
<P>
   An only child, she started school in Midland with all the
advantages she wishes for other children.
</P>
<P>
   Father Harold Welch, who died in 1995, was a homebuilder. Her
mother Jenna, who still lives in Midland, kept the books.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' future first lady, now 52, crossed paths for years with
the man she'd eventually marry. They attended different elementary
schools in Midland, but went to the same junior high for a year. In
the '60s, when she was a teacher and he was flying fighter jets for
the Texas Air National Guard, they lived in the same apartment
complex in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until 1977, when she was working as the librarian
at Dawson Elementary School in Austin, that friends Jan and Joey
O'Neill got the two of them together at a barbecue in Midland when
Laura was home visiting her parents.
</P>
<P>
   They'd been trying to do it for some time, recalls Jan O'Neill.
Laura, who'd had plenty of boyfriends, `wasn't particularly anxious
to be fixed up,'' says O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   `I thought he was someone who was interested in politics and
that he would be someone I wouldn't be interested in because I was
so uninterested in politics at that time,'' Laura Bush says.
</P>
<P>
   They fell in love anyway.
</P>
<P>
   `I think I was struck by her beauty and her charm,'' Gov. George
W. Bush says. `She was an intriguing personality to me. . . . We
had a whirlwind courtship and it stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   Their romance came on the heels of that period which has invited
so much speculation about the governor's past. It's as if his life
is split neatly in two sections, with the pre-Laura Bush era
comprising the years when, as Bush has said, he was `young and
irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Was she the good woman who tamed him, as so many have suggested?
</P>
<P>
   `Barbara and I were talking about that yesterday,'' says the
senior George Bush. `We don't remember George as this kind of wild
thing. I don't understand the needless speculation that he needed
somebody to quiet him down.
</P>
<P>
   `On the other hand,'' he concedes, `Laura has been a very
stabilizing influence on our whole family.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bush says: `He may have been a playboy and had a lot of
fun. . . . She laughed at his jokes. He has enormous admiration for
her.''
</P>
<P>
   And from Gov. Bush: `I think marriage and children settle people
down, particularly if you take your vows seriously. I did.''
</P>
<P>
   They were both 31. They married three months after they met.
</P>
<P>
   And Laura Bush immediately met two challenges: campaigning
across the Panhandle with her husband, who was making his first run
for office (he lost a race for Congress); and fitting into the
extended Bush family.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime friend Regan Gammon recalls talking with Laura Bush
about the turn her life had taken.
</P>
<P>
   `We discussed the fact that his father was thinking about
running for president and what that might mean,'' she says. `How
bizarre that was. . . . It seemed a little unreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush never seemed intimidated by her new extended family,
Gammon says.
</P>
<P>
   But the family she was marrying into was a huge, competitive
clan (she had no siblings and only two first cousins). The elder
George Bush's mother, in particular, was perhaps `the most athletic
human being living,'' Barbara Bush says.
</P>
<P>
   One day, inevitably, the matriarch asked the future Laura Bush,
`'What do you do?''' To which she replied, `I read.''
</P>
<P>
   `Mrs. Bush couldn't believe her ears,'' Barbara Bush recalls.
Trouble with the twins
</P>
<P>
   They were a family first, before they became a public entity,
before everyone from The New York Times to Vogue wanted to tell
their story.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge he and Laura have faced, George W. Bush
says, was not the '94 governor's race nobody thought he would win.
It was the birth of their children, after Laura was ordered to bed
with toxemia late in her pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   He was in Midland and she was hospitalized in Dallas when he got
the call from her doctor: `Your children will be born tomorrow;
either that or your wife's kidneys will fail.''
</P>
<P>
   He got on a plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loves our daughters more than anything,'' he says, `would
lay her life down for them. And nearly did at birth. . . . She was
absolutely determined to do whatever she could to make sure those
little girls came into the world healthy and safe. And she did.''
</P>
<P>
   He returns to the story later.
</P>
<P>
   `That was Laura at her best, kind of hanging on with the
girls.''
</P>
<P>
   She has warm memories of their early years as a family in
Midland, of wheeling the twin baby girls around in a stroller on
hot summer afternoons as the cicadas trilled loudly.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara and Jenna, 17, are juniors at Austin High School now,
and Laura Bush talks a little wistfully about the days when she
could throw her arms around them so easily. Now they're busy
teen-agers with their own agendas.
</P>
<P>
   `It is very natural for them at this age to want to spread their
wings, and George and I are certainly aware of that,'' she says.
`We are aware of how much less relevant we are in our children's
lives each day as they grow up and want to be with their own
friends and are starting to think about where they want to go to
college and where they want to be when they move away.''-
</P>
<P>
   A normal life in the public eye
</P>
<P>
   She says her daughters are not overly concerned with their
father's political plans.
</P>
<P>
   `Just like every teen-ager, they are mainly concerned about what
they're going to be doing this weekend. At the same time they are
very proud of their dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout their lives, when their grandfather was
vice-president, then president, and when their father first became
governor in 1994, the Bushes have `tried to make a normal life for
our daughters,'' Laura Bush says. They keep evening events to a
minimum, and despite their schedules, one or the other tries to be
home by 4 p.m. each day, she says. They all have dinner together
most nights.
</P>
<P>
   In the event of a presidential campaign, Laura Bush says she
plans to follow the lead of her in-laws, who always reserved
Sundays for family.
</P>
<P>
   Both the former president and Barbara Bush say they're feeling a
protective surge as Texas' first family moves into the national
political arena. But neither has offered any guidance on how to
survive a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   `Of course I awaken every morning with advice,'' Barbara Bush
jokes, `but I don't give it.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about how his candidacy might affect their daughters
(they would be in college if Bush took office) worry George W. and
Laura Bush. They say they appreciate the hands-off policy of the
Texas press and are encouraged by the way the national media have
treated Chelsea Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some things the girls can't be shielded from. At
the last Texas Book Festival, hecklers shouted down former
President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   `Jenna walked out of (there) and burst into tears,'' Laura Bush
says. `It's hard for a teen-ager when they yell mean things at your
grandfather.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult, too, to hear things said about your husband.
</P>
<P>
   `I feel like that's what I dread the most, the criticism, but
also the totally unfounded rumors which we've heard,'' Laura Bush
says.
</P>
<P>
   `Friends will call us from somewhere, and tell us something
they've heard somewhere. There's no way to refute it because
they're so totally made up.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, not known for keeping his cool when his father
was the target of criticism during his last presidential race, says
he is also concerned about what his wife may have to endure.
</P>
<P>
   `It's a lot easier to be the candidate where people say ugly
things about you than the person who loves the person about which
ugly things are said. I know first-hand,'' he says, pausing. `I
know first-hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Just three months ago, Laura Bush sat beside her husband at a
press conference and said she was `reluctant, absolutely,'' to get
involved in a presidential race. about the prospect of becoming
engaged in a presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Now she says she is simply a realist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone today knows that any person who was considering this
job would have certain reservations,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   TRANS. And that's been Laura Bush's role throughout their
marriage, to be her husband's sounding board on issues big and
small. Their contrasting personalities -- his high-energy
temperament and her laid-back style -- have provided `a good check
and balance,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   She's always been `a very positive influence on me . . . in
terms of forcing me to ask the right questions,'' Bush says.
</P>
<P>
   `On the occasions where I drank too much she reminded me I was
drinking too much. And I listened.''
</P>
<P>
   And in 1994, when everyone else was urging him to run for
governor, Laura Bush was one of the last people to get behind the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   She reminded him he was `living a dream'' as an owner of the
Texas Rangers, he says. Both of them had enjoyed their time
together watching games, the Florida Gulf Coast vacations that
centered on spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laura's not the first to say, Oh boy, let's go do that, sort
of shovin' me into the limelight,'' the governor says.
</P>
<P>
   `She's the opposite of that. She says, Wait a minute, buddy, are
you sure? Are you sure you're going to ask our family to make a
life change? Are you sure that this is something you really want to
do?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the decision about a presidential campaign has all but
been made, the candidate is putting a positive spin on how a heated
political campaign might affect their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   `We grew close during the baseball games because of the amount
of time we spent with each other,'' Bush says. `We could think
about things and talk. We grew very close during the (1994)
campaign because it was like we were in combat to a certain extent,
fellow warriors.
</P>
<P>
   `I don't really fear failure, and one of the reasons I don't
fear failure is because I know that I've got a wife who loves me.
And she doesn't fear failure either.'' Her politic decision
</P>
<P>
   When somebody asks me about life with George W. Bush I have to
resist using that old clich: There is never a dull moment.
</P>
<P>
   I have to resist being sentimental and saying that when I was in
class in elementary school I never dreamed that there was a boy
named George Bush who was also sitting in class across town at our
rival school, and that one day I would grow up to marry him . . .
</P>
<P>
   I have to resist saying that according to my children, life with
their dad is like being a private under the direct command of a
general. And that according to George, war is hell.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, when someone asks me about George W. Bush I say
marrying him apparently was the smartest political move I ever
made. Not bad for somebody who knows nothing about politics.'' --
Laura Bush, introducing her husband at the Texas Women's Hall of
Fame gala.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' first lady never planned to give speeches.
</P>
<P>
   `I always think of myself as basically reserved and shy,'' she
says. `I wouldn't have thought of this before I started giving
speeches, but reading over the top of a book like I did millions of
time as a children's librarian is great practice.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman who put off meeting her future husband because of his
political aspirations has said the idea of occupying the White
House is `sort of a stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   `I could just as soon, you know, hang around and work in the
yard,'' she told The New York Times Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Advantages. Disadvantages.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush `is in a life that I don't think she ever
envisioned,'' George W. Bush says. `But she has seized the
opportunity and made a difference in people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   She is, Barbara Bush says, `a sort of catalyst in our family.
She brings out the best in us.''
</P>
<P>
   And from the elder George Bush: `When she greets Barbara and me,
when we come over to the house, there she is with her arms open for
a hug.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush can't throw her arms around all the children of
Texas, but that's her goal, figuratively speaking.
</P>
<P>
   `I would most like to be known as an advocate for children,''
she says. `I would like to help parents be very informed so they
can make great decisions for their young children. I think being a
parent is the most important job any of us will ever have and our
relationships with our families and our children are our most
important relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   And her work to empower other families would be expanded if her
own were to occupy the White House. Barbara Bush can see her there,
reveling in the history and `majesty'' of her former home at 1600
Pennsylvania Avenue, the self-assured successor to lightning rod
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   `She's a good little nester,'' her mother-in-law says.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever a campaign brings, family ties will bind them, the
Bushes say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say that like any other family George and I have had
our share of fun and frustration in our 22 years of marriage.
Overall, though, I think we are both pleased with our success.
We've managed to raise two smart daughters and a half-dozen of
their animals. I consider myself doubly blessed to be a part of his
family and a partner of his in life. Ladies and gentlemen, my
husband, Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Bonnin is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman. jbonnin(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
