<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are considering
for Page 1, Thursday, April 29. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Sam Weiss; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ Yugoslavia's deputy prime minister,
Vuk Draskovic, a staunch and vocal opponent of his government's
policy on Kosovo, was sacked Wednesday by Prime Minister Momir
Bulatovic. The action by Bulatovic, who is close to President
Slobodan Milosevic, effectively squelched Draskovic's calls for a
U.N. peacekeeping force in Kosovo. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TOWN (Surdulica) _ The town where about 20 civilians,
including children, were killed in NATO attack that hit a
residential area, destroying or damaging many houses. An interview
with a man whose wife, son, daughter-in-law and two grandchildren
were killed. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ In its first full debate since
air strikes began against Yugoslavia, a divided House voted to
block financing for the deployment of American ground troops in the
Balkan conflict unless President Clinton first gains the approval
of Congress. The Senate is expected to vote on the legislation in
early P.M. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO-ASSESS (Washignton) _ White House officials, faced
with three unpalatable choices _ an open-ended and probably
unsuccessful air campaign, the dispatch of ground troops and a
diplomatic resolution _ ses a diplomatic solution as the most
promising. Therefore, the Clinton administration is forging ahead
with using Russia, whose views it spurned at the outset, to help
find a diplomatic alternative. News Analysis. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-SANCTIONS (Washington) _ Pressed by large corporations
and farm-state lawmakers, the Clinton Administration announced that
it had decided to ease its sanctions policy and permit the sale of
food and medical supplies to Iran, Libya, Sudan and other nations
that are considered adversaries of the United States. By Philip
Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING. (Littleton , Colo.) _ The Jefferson County
Sheriff is to have a briefing at 6 P.M. EST in which he is expected
to clear up assorted big issues. Are the three kids who were
pictured with their hands up suspects? Is there a videotape of the
shootings that is significant? He has given various answers in last
couple of days. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PROFILING-MOTELS (Trenton) _ The New Jersey State Police have
quietly enlisted workers at dozens of motels to tip them off about
suspicious guests who, for instance, pay for their rooms in cash,
receive a flurry of telephone calls or, in some cases, simply speak
Spanish, according to participants. By David Kocieniewski.
</P>
