<HEADER>
A6588 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHORS-ENGLANDER-SPI     04-28 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHORS-ENGLANDER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORTHODOX JEWISH WORLD FROM A FRESH, YOUNG VOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REGINA HACKETT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nathan Englander shrugs when asked to account for his celebrity
status. Even with amber curls framing his head in shining
abundance, he looks momentarily old.
</P>
<P>
   On tour following the publication of his first book of short
stories, ``For the Relief of Unbearable Urges,'' (Alfred A. Knopf,
205 pages, $22), he seems for a second tired of trying to charm the
latest in a long line of interviewing strangers who greet him armed
with microphone and camera, pen and notepad.
</P>
<P>
   Although he's too polite to say so, a flash of light in his
large brown eyes and a slight tightening of his generous mouth
suggests he's not pleased by the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absurd,'' he said. ``I'm thrilled, of course, and
startled. I feel as if people are thinking, `He's a sly one, that
Englander boy.' As if I were sitting on a gold mine when I was
staying home without a job to write short, literary fiction about
Orthodox Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   A barely published writer of short fiction is lucky to see a
first collection printed at all, but Englander's stories won him an
unprecedented advance of $350,000, which includes a 30,000-book
first printing and a commitment to publish a yet unfinished novel.
Before ``Unbearable Urges,'' he had published only four short
stories, three in Story magazine and one in The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone moving quickly from obscurity to fame risks a backlash,
and this is especially true of a short-story writer. The market is
tight to the point of constriction. Most of the best can't make
even a modest living from sales. They teach, lecture, rely on
spouses, luck, stints of manual labor, grants and stipends.
</P>
<P>
   Englander, 29, won't be needing to teach any time soon and won't
be seeing a backlash from his peers. They love him. They compare
him to Chekhov and Singer, and not without reason. His work is
transparently lucid, with the profundity and ambition of an elder
and the jaunty wit of a youth. Lois Rosenthal, editor of Story
magazine, gave him the label everybody likes: ``Isaac Bashevis
Singer on crack.''
</P>
<P>
   Plaudits pour in, causing him to feel a mixture of elation and
dread. As a woman in ``The Wig'' observes to a friend, ``I can't
face Nava now. I'm too weak for her compliments. She'll praise me
into the grave today.''
</P>
<P>
   The quality of his work is the first reason for his amazing
debut, but he's willing to admit there are other reasons having
nothing to do with talent.
</P>
<P>
   Youth and good looks don't hurt, and he's got both. More
importantly in an age of identity politics, he's a strong new voice
from the world of Orthodox Judaism, growing up as an insider and
achieving distance as a secular adult. To invent characters and
place them in environments, detachment is essential. The insider
who can, like Englander, see his world as outsiders see it is free
to make art from personal experience.
</P>
<P>
   Englander raises his hands, as if in surrender, and says he
doesn't spend time pondering why he is where he is. ``I'm doing my
best to maintain my place in the food chain,'' he says. ``My job is
to find the rhythms and phrasings to create characters in the
stories that are right for them. Talking about myself or selling
books is not my job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is I'm playing catch-up,'' he continues. ``I'm
poorly educated. Comparisons with great writers scare me.''
</P>
<P>
   Englander grew up in an Orthodox community on Long Island,
receiving what he calls a ``right-wing, xenophobic,
anti-intellectual, fire-and-brimstone, free-thought-free,
shtetl-mentality, substandard education.''
</P>
<P>
   His questioning mind, for which he credits his mother, was
constantly thwarted. ``My mother loved art. She dropped out of
school at 18 to get married. When I wanted to be a writer, she
encouraged me. That was vital. It's hard enough to do it without
people at home calling you a bum.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as ``The Pugilist at Rest'' is Thom Jones' masterpiece
short story, ``The Twenty-seventh Man'' is Englander's. He got the
idea when he was 19 and thought, someone should write that story.
``I didn't think I would, but it stayed with me and eventually I
began to try.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was 23, a friend whose mother was a children's book
editor _ Deborah Brodie _ asked to see a story. The only one he had
was ``The Twenty-seventh Man,'' in a far different form from its
present one. ``From her I learned that there was hope, if I kept
working I'd find a story in my material.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodie talked him into applying for the Iowa Writer's Workshop,
where he continued to revise his story and start others. ``Writers
were always coming through,'' he says. ``Meeting them and seeing
that they were human beings was huge for me. I had two years to
write in a community in which there is nothing more important than
writing. If you're asked why you weren't at your brother's funeral
and you say, `I was writing,' it's an acceptable excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, he also made the contacts that led to being published,
including Rosenthal of Story magazine. Two years ago, he moved to
Jerusalem to forge his new identity as a secular Jew and learn to
speak Hebrew. ``You'd think I would have learned Hebrew from an
Orthodox school, but no. What can I tell you? They failed us. I got
the Hebrew prize and knew nothing. I have no bone to pick with
anybody, but a school has a contract with children to teach them
and not waste their time.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he believe in God? ``It isn't the right question,'' he
says. ``Most of my characters believe in God. God exists in my
book.''
</P>
<P>
   Englander writes in drafts, endlessly revising. When does he
know he's finished? ``When someone pries a story out of my
fingers,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Twenty-seventh Man'' describes the last days of a group of
Jewish writers rounded up at Stalin's orders to be shot, because as
Jews they were thought insufficiently loyal to the State.
</P>
<P>
   Surely a grim theme, but each writer in the story has his own
light, his own despair or delusion, his own purity and humor. If we
are flies to the gods who kill us for their sport, we are in
Englander's story flies capable of making urgent and necessary art
even in our last hours.
</P>
<P>
   Englander hesitates when asked why he moved to Jerusalem.
``Nothing I can say sounds right. I visited and came back. Now I've
made myself part of something very complicated. Living there has
made me a flag-waving fan of democracy. I ask people, do you
believe in equal rights for all citizens? If they even pause, I
know I'll have a problem. We're closer to tragedy in Israel. We
feel it and know its possibilities. There's nothing remote about
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he's surprised when people assume his Orthodox family
must have shunned him. ``Not even close to the truth. My family
keeps me honest. They and the community at home support me.'' Their
lives, abstracted into fiction, are the basis of his work, and
sometimes they make suggestions that result in stories.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting his sister, one of her friends teasingly suggested his
bountiful locks would make a good wig. Hence, ``The Wig'' starring
his hair, which becomes a symbol of lost sexual power for a
middle-age woman willing to pay to get it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a mane of curls the color of toasted bamboo that runs
down to the middle of his back and ends in a deep, blunt ridge. The
curls are singular, full and moist, and they stack well. A head of
hair with personality. She is obsessed, she knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Listening to the passage, he blushes. ``I wasn't describing my
own hair,'' he protests weakly. ``It isn't that direct.'' Clearly
it is. An artist can use anything, even what he sees in the mirror.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
