<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6591 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-LASER-DISCS-NYT &LR;      04-28 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-LASER-DISCS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BITTERSWEET TIMES FOR COLLECTORS OF LASERDISC MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When they outgrew the shelves, he put them in crates, and
finally in stacks on the floor of his home. Bill Griffin estimates
that he has amassed about 4,000 titles since he began collecting
movies in 1983. ``I generally have a sense of what I own,'' he
said, ``but locating it is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Videotapes? Hardly. Griffin, of Ridgewood, N.J., is part of a
small but proud group, the faithful followers of a technology that
has been the quiet state of the art in home theater for two
decades: the laserdisc.
</P>
<P>
   ``My absolute worst addiction is for the Disney laserdiscs,'' he
said. ``I champ at the bit for those.'' He rhapsodizes about a
boxed set of ``Alice in Wonderland'' with television show excerpts,
radio broadcasts on the audio track and hundreds of animation
stills. ``You could sit there for hours and become absolutely
immersed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   True, few Americans have ever bought a laserdisc player, or even
held one of the thin, 12-inch laserdisc platters, with their
silvery, iridescent sheen. Their owners have been limited to a
niche that is about 2 percent of the size of the VHS market; they
are the movie buffs who are willing to pay a little more for the
best picture available without a projector.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other worthy but outfoxed technologies, like Betamax, the
laserdisc has remained in the background for 20 years, supported by
fanatics with a yen for the director's cut of ``Brazil'' or a boxed
set of D.W. Griffith's early films.
</P>
<P>
   But these are bittersweet times for collectors. With DVD being
hailed as a conquering hero by the entertainment industry, the big
laserdiscs may be closed to spinning their last movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``DVD has pushed it out of all the local stores here,'' said
Robert Niland, of Fort Collins, Colo., who has written about
laserdiscs and maintains on his Web site a
frequently-asked-questions page on the technology,
www.frii.com/rjn/laser/default.htm. He predicts that the production
of laserdiscs will stop within a year. ``As nice as it was, it's
history,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Laser video first came on the retail market in 1978. It is a
cousin to the audio compact disc, with the data for the picture
image recorded as a series of pits on a reflective layer (usually
aluminum) in the disk, but unlike CDs and DVDs, which are digital,
the laserdisc is an analog system, with the data for the picture
image recorded as a series of pits on  reflective layer (usually
aluminum) in the disc. A laser reads the pits (about 30 billion of
them) as the disc spins in the player at up to 1,800 rpm. Because
only laser light comes in contact with the disc surface, it
theoretically does not wear out. Niland said it could provide a
picture as clear as 16-mm film.
</P>
<P>
   So why did VHS win out? The first laserdisc players cost about
$200 more than VCRs, and the VCR's ability to record turned out to
be a big draw with consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Laserdiscs were also the victims of poor marketing. They got a
bad name from a competing videodisc system, Selectavision, marketed
around the same time by RCA. Selectavision used a stylus-in-groove
format, similar to a record; it died in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   More than once, observers declared that laserdiscs would make a
resurgence, prompted by the popularity of big-screen televisions
and audio compact discs. But even at its height in the 1990s, it
never reached more than 2 million players in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   DVD is a touchy subject on the alt.video.laserdisc newsgroup,
where flame wars have broken out between DVD and laserdisc
adherents. ``Your LD players will officially become boat anchors,''
one visitor taunted. But laserdisc stalwarts are skeptical that DVD
will provide the range of titles and extras they have grown
accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of people that I observe buying DVD are really
into showing off their system: `Look how big my subwoofer is,'''
Griffin said. ``It becomes less a focus on the movie itself and
more `look at the great explosion, feel how the house rumbles.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know too many people that are raging that you have to
see `Casablanca' on DVD,'' he said. ``They're like, `You have to
see `Lost in Space.'''
</P>
<P>
   That's sour grapes, said John Higdon, a collector from San Jose,
Calif. ``That is standard whenever a new technology comes out,'' he
said. ``You always have people who just can't possibly move on.''
He has already supplemented his 2,000 laserdiscs with several
hundred DVDs.
</P>
<P>
   Another collector, Dan Balogh, admits that his ``Music Man'' DVD
is sharper than his laserdisc version, but he still has
reservations. ``It's like a Sunday morning cartoon,'' he said. ``I
can see that it is a sound stage. I thought, Do I really want to
see how fake the set looks?'' He likened it to the restoration of
the Sistine Chapel. ``People were questioning whether Michelangelo
wanted the colors to be so bright,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The laserdisc's glossy packaging with sometimes lavish cover art
and liner notes evokes nostalgia in some, ``especially people in
their 40s, who grew up with long-playing records,'' said Mon Ayash,
a collector from Fall River, Mass. Laserdiscs look like an LP gone
platinum, while DVDs are the size of CDs. ``DVD,'' he said, ``is
dinky.''
</P>
<P>
   The nit-picking is endless, but laserdisc fans were the first on
the waiting list to order DVD players. Pioneer Electronics, the
only remaining manufacturer of laserdisc players, expects many
collectors to hedge their bets by purchasing its combi-players,
which play both DVDs and laserdiscs. It said it would stop
producing players for laserdiscs alone in one to two years.
</P>
<P>
   Some may say laserdiscs are following the ignoble footsteps of
the eight-track tape, but Ayash pointed to a laserdisc legacy.
Manufacturers kept digging deeper into the movie vaults to find
more obscure titles, unseen footage and the best film prints for
transfers to laserdiscs, which set a higher standard. Laserdiscs,
like DVDs, tend to offer much more than the average videotape, like
actors' biographies, directors' commentaries and outtakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never saw wide-screen videotapes,'' said Ayash, until
laserdiscs began to present movies in the same width-to-height
ratio as on the theater screen, using a technique called
letterboxing. ``They remastered the films, they fixed the picture
quality, they fixed the sound. The laserdisc gave a little more
impetus to the archeologists of film to get the best quality of
prints.''
</P>
<P>
   Balogh, who runs a laserdisc boxed-set tribute page,
www.openix.com/danb/lds/boxsets.shtml, said he wondered if that
attention to detail would fade as DVD aimed for the mainstream
market. ``Most people really don't care about the correct aspect
ratio,'' he said. ``Most people don't care about horizontal lines
of resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   While prices seem to be dropping on most used discs, rare discs
are fetching higher prices. Griffin is optimistic that there will
always be a collector out there to trade with because ``these discs
are probably going to outlast us all.'' Hundreds are auctioned on
the Internet each day, he added.
</P>
<P>
   And there is always Japan, where an estimated 10 percent of
homes have laserdisc players and DVDs have been slow to catch on.
With the right connections, and a bank that does international
money transfers, you can find yourself the proud owner of a Pioneer
HLD-X9 player and a complete season of the ``X-Files'' in a boxed
set, with Japanese subtitles. (American television shows are
popular laserdisc productions overseas.)
</P>
<P>
   Griffin, at least, is not planning to give up his laser
collection anytime soon, not unless all 11 of his players break
down. ``You mourn the passing,'' he said, ``but you celebrate the
life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
