<HEADER>
A6594 &Cx1f; tab-z
r c &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     04-28 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV16-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., MAY 16, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: The double hung windows in my house leak badly, so I was
thinking of having completely new replacement windows installed _
until I found out what this would cost. A friend told me that I
could leave the old window frame in place and buy special kits that
would include new double-pane window sash and matching vinyl tracks
that come complete with weather stripping; then these can be
installed inside the existing window frames. I was also told that a
handy homeowner could install these himself, thus cutting costs
even further. What do you think of this idea?
</P>
<P>
   A: These kits do work. They come with complete instructions, and
can be installed by a do-it-yourselfer if he is handy and familiar
with using tools. You leave the old window frames in place, so you
will still have to paint and maintain the trim, but there is no
doubt that when properly installed the new sash and weather
stripping will definitely be a lot more efficient and energy saving
than old wooden windows are.
</P>
<P>
   Q. My basement walls are brick, and there is considerable
seepage in very wet weather, although there are no actual puddles
forming on the floor. Is there some kind of waterproofing paint I
can apply that will stop this seepage?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are a number of ``waterproofing'' paints available that
are claimed to effectively seal masonry basement walls. They will
stop minor seepage through poured concrete and cement block
foundation walls, but I am not sure how effective they will be on a
brick basement wall, especially if the seepage is due to defective
mortar joints. At any rate, before applying such a coating I would
strongly recommend checking all mortar joints and replacing any
mortar that seems to be crumbling or is cracked.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A couple of years ago I had insulation blown into the outside
walls to cut down on heating costs. This year the outside paint
started blistering and peeling. I was told that this is because
there is no vapor barrier in the walls with this insulation. Is
this true, and what can I do to add a vapor barrier without having
to rip the walls open?
</P>
<P>
   A: Adding blown-in insulation into the walls sometimes does
cause condensation problems which can lead to peeling of paint
because moisture vapor from inside the house gets partially trapped
by the insulation. Condensation then forms on the back of the
exterior siding, causing the paint to peel. To solve this problem
you need to install a vapor barrier on the warm side of the
insulation in order to keep moisture vapor from penetrating. You
can accomplish this with a coat of vapor barrier paint (such as
Insul-Aid, made by Glidden) applied to each wall inside the house
or by hanging a vinyl wallcovering that will also serve as a vapor
barrier to prevent moisture vapor from inside the house entering
the hollow spaces inside the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We removed the carpet from our hardwood floor after 12 years.
However, we found that the padding under the rug is sticking to the
wood flooring and practically falls apart when we try to pull it
up. How can we get this padding off without damaging the beautiful
parquet floor underneath?
</P>
<P>
   A: It sounds as though an adhesive was used to cement the pad to
the floor, or it may have simply deteriorated and is now sticking
to the wood floor's old finish. The only way to remove this now is
to start by first scraping off as much as you can, using a
long-handled scraper or stiff putty knife. Then you will have to
sand the floor to clean off any residue that remains. Before
sanding, however, make sure the parquet is solid wood, not just a
veneer (sanding could damage the veneer).
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``NEW WINDOW TRACKS'' goes with this
column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: New window sashes come with matching vinyl tracks that
can be installed inside existing window frames.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
