<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLIPCOVERS-ART-1000(2     04-28 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLIPCOVERS-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAMING THAT ONE-SIZE-FITS-ALL SLIPCOVER 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Pa., Ohio, N.Y.)  (EDS: Optional sidebar in 2nd take.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By STEVEN J. STARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The slipcover probably made its appearance during
prehistoric times, when a cave dweller threw an animal skin over a
rock. Even back then, the slipcover slipped. Frescoes show that
recumbent Romans preferred to cover their pallets with layers of
cloth, which puddled on the mosaic floors. (Tailoring was hardly
expected.)
</P>
<P>
   In the 18th century, Europeans resolved the slipcover conundrum
with tapestry coverings made in two parts, to fit over the backs
and seats of chairs. (Anyone who had tapestries also had teams of
servants to keep the covers neatly in place.)
</P>
<P>
   Americans, during the 1930s and '40s, rose to the slip-off
challenge with custom-made coverups for old chairs. In the early
'90s, slipcover sales surged with the advent of the ``English
country-house'' look _ a loose cover made in universal-fit sizes
and sold to the masses.
</P>
<P>
   The universal-fit slipcover market grew to what today is an $80
million a year business, said Warren Shoulberg, the editor of Home
Textiles Today, a Manhattan-based trade publication. But returns
were high, he said, around 30 percent in the early '90s. Universal
slipcovers have, in fact, a universal tendency to slip off and
bunch up.
</P>
<P>
   That was why Paula Riley, 50, invented Fitting Pretty, which
promised to keep slipcovers in place without constant retucking.
She hoped that her device _ plastic holding rods and clips _ would
take advantage of a niche that was becoming increasingly popular.
Unfortunately, her rivals had the same idea.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Ms. Riley, a business consultant in fashion and
retailing in New York, enlisted Ken Stevens, a New York industrial
designer, to design her product. She envisioned ribbed, V-shaped
plastic rods, the size of windshield wipers, that when pushed
around the seat cushions would keep slipcovers from sliding. It was
the equivalent of shoulder pads in a woman's dress _ something to
stabilize the fit _ and it hit stores just as consumers were
returning their slipcovers in droves. The rods were packaged with a
tucking tool and clips for pleating _ $30 for a sofa, $25 for a
love seat and $20 for a chair.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Riley applied for a patent in July of 1994 and the kits
began turning up in catalogs six months later. Domestications, a
home furnishings catalog company in Weehawken, N.J., initially
ordered 600 kits, said Gunter Siemon, a senior buyer for the
catalog, and sold all 600 within two days. Domestications ordered
15,000 more. Not bad for a one-woman company run out of a
two-bedroom apartment on West 57th Street in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Early on in Fitting Pretty history, Ms. Riley sought a tie-in
with a slipcover manufacturer. Who better, she thought, than Sure
Fit Inc. of Allentown, Pa., the largest manufacturer in the
country. ``It seemed so hand-in-glove,'' she said, sitting in her
home office.
</P>
<P>
   In August of 1994, Ms. Riley met with Bert Shlensky, the
president of Sure Fit, at his Manhattan office. From 1991 through
1994, Sure Fit sold $80 million to $90 million worth of slipcovers.
But, Shlensky explained recently, the company suffered the same
plight as the rest of the industry _ high returns.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Riley said Shlensky signed a confidentiality agreement
saying he would not reveal information about Fitting Pretty _
including making or selling any version of it. But after examining
her product and being told how it worked, Shlensky said that Sure
Fit wasn't interested. So, Ms. Riley decided to go it alone.
</P>
<P>
   That might have been the last she saw of Sure Fit executives,
except that in April, 1995, she and her designer, Stevens, ducked
into a Bed, Bath and Beyond at 18th Street and Sixth Avenue in
Manhattan and discovered a product like their own being marketed by
Sure Fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't breathe for a second,'' she said, describing
her reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Ms. Riley and Stevens were on their way to her
patent attorney's office to sign a patent application for another
component of Fitting Pretty, the pleating clips. Their attorney
fired off a letter to Sure Fit reminding the company of its
confidentiality agreement. Sure Fit's lawyers replied, denying that
it had copied her invention. In August of 1996, when Ms. Riley's
patent on Fitting Pretty was approved, her lawyer notified Sure Fit
of the patent infringement. Sure Fit didn't budge.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Riley's lawsuit was filed in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan on Oct. 7, 1996. According to her suit, Sure Fit declined
to license her invention, then knocked it off with what it called
Stayputs, plastic slipcover stabilizers similar to Ms. Riley's
product.
</P>
<P>
   It was a David and Goliath clash between Ms. Riley (annual sales
of $195,000) and Sure Fit (annual sales of about $50 million).
Although Sure Fit's lawyers would not comment on the lawsuit, court
papers show the company denied Ms. Riley's accusations, but agreed
to stop selling their product while it continued. As it dragged on,
Sure Fit went through a series of corporate mergers that saw it
acquired by Pillowtex as a part of Fieldcrest Cannon, and then spun
off to private investors in March of last year.
</P>
<P>
   On May 1, 1998 _ Ms. Riley's 50th birthday _ the two sides
settled without assessing blame. The settlement is confidential,
and both sides agreed to destroy all documents related to it. Ms.
Riley said only that her settlement was at least $1 million over
the cost of the lawsuit and that her legal bills totaled about $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Sure Fit no longer sells its Stayputs. Shlensky,
while he would not talk about the lawsuit, did say that Sure Fit
now sells a one-piece slipcover that looks like a big shower cap,
and does not need anchors. ``It's not form-fitting, so it will
move, but it generally stays in place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the settlement, Ms. Riley has signed an agreement with
Value Quest, a distributor in Canton, Ohio, to sell Fitting Pretty
to American retail chains. ``We have not found any product remotely
similar,'' said Mike Clark, the vice president for marketing of
Value Quest. ``It almost defies logic why it works, but it really
does.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This month, distribution of Fitting Pretty began in Europe. And
Ms. Riley has gone into partnership with Pottery Barn, which is
selling her product in the store's new catalog as the Loose-Fit
Tailoring Set.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Alber, the vice president of the Pottery Barn Catalog
Division, said the device ``enhances slipcovers and allows the
customers to achieve the look we have in the catalog.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you sit on the sofa,'' she said, ``it stays tucked in.
They do exactly what they say they will do. It's cut down on
returns of loose-fit slipcovers substantially.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL SIDEBAR BEGINS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   When people started having babies, that's when everyone began
buying slipcovers,'' said Nana Colgrove, a television producer in
New York with two small children. But universal-fit slipcovers have
to be constantly retucked, especially after Arnie the Airedale has
slept on the sofa and the children have used it as a trampoline.
Paula Riley's Fitting Pretty kit of plastic rods and clips ($30)
promises to keep ``casual slipcovers secure and looking picture
perfect.'' Do they?
</P>
<P>
   ``Picture perfect'' may be aiming a little high, but the device
does help. The target sofa, a chocolate-brown velvet number that
had already endured one child, needed some serious freshening for
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Two novice slipcoverers tackled two do-it-yourself cover-ups,
one a luxurious cotton velvet from Classic Slipcovers (about $300),
the other a washable cotton and polyester slipcover by
Fieldcrest/Sure Fit from Bed, Bath and Beyond ($129.99). The
Fieldcrest slipcover was meant to stay in place with an elastic
band that runs under the cushions. Wrestling it on was a two-person
job, and although it looked satisfactory, especially after the
corner straps were tied, the fit was hardly tailored. (Does anyone
seriously believe one size fits all?)
</P>
<P>
   So, it was on to the Fitting Pretty plastic rods, which were
easy to install. (Pushing the rods deep into the crevice around the
seating area seemed to do the trick.) Thankfully, none of the
accompanying fancy clips and elastic bands were needed; using them
seemed to require the perseverance of a committed decorator. With
the Fitting Pretty Tuck-Once Grips the fit was more crisp and
tailored. Over an active weekend, nothing required retucking.
</P>
<P>
   The fit of the luxe Classic slipcover, made without the elastic
band under the cushions, was actually quite good. But even here,
the plastic Fitting Pretty grips added tension, making for a
cleaner edge. The cover looked almost custom-made and would have
been a keeper, if it hadn't clashed with the walls.
</P>
<P>
   _ LINDA LEE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
