<HEADER>
A6605 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAG29-COX     04-28 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAG29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GLENN ACCEPTS 'MISSION' OF OPPOSING FLAG DESECRATION AMENDMENT
 &HT;    640&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Making his first visit to Capitol Hill since his
retirement from the Senate, John Glenn urged his former colleagues
Wednesday to reject a constitutional amendment giving Congress the
power to outlaw flag desecration.
</P>
<P>
   Such an amendment would ``protect the symbol while risking
chipping away at the freedoms it symbolizes,'' Glenn warned the
Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   A Marine pilot in World War II before he became an astronaut and
politician, Glenn appeared along with current senators united by
their distinguished combat records. But the senators, even members
of the same party, differed dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Among Democrats, Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, who lost a foot and
earned a Medal of Honor in the Vietnam War, spoke against the
amendment. But Max Cleland of Georgia, who lost his legs in the
Vietnam War, is a co-sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans, John Chafee of Rhode Island, a combat veteran
of World War II and the Korean War, was passionate in his
disapproval, while John McCain of Arizona, who survived years
torture as a prisoner of war in North Vietnamese, was eloquent in
his defense.
</P>
<P>
   The only senator who saw combat in Vietnam as an enlisted
soldier, Nebraska Republican Chuck Hagel, conceded that ``there are
legitimate questions about this,'' but said he would vote for the
amendment. ``Freedom of speech is not unlimited,'' he said.
``Symbolism is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Supported by most Americans in public opinion polls and by
powerful veterans groups, the proposed amendment would give
Congress ``the power to prohibit'' any ``physical desecration'' of
the American flag.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has ruled that state and federal statutes
outlawing burning or otherwise abusing the flag are
unconstitutional abridgements to the right of free expression
guaranteed by the First Amendment. Thus, supporters have concluded
that an constitutional amendment is needed to give Congress
authority to pass a flag protection measure.
</P>
<P>
   The House has approved the amendment twice before and is
expected to do so again in this Congress. Even opponents believe
that the Senate is nearing the two-thirds majority needed to
approve it as well.
</P>
<P>
   The president has no say in the matter, and if the measure
clears Congress, more than the required three-fourths of the state
legislatures have made clear they would quickly ratify it as the
28th amendment to the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very close, ... two votes one way or the other'' in the
Senate, said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., who asked Glenn to testify
before the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy said the former Democratic senator from Ohio _ the first
American to orbit the Earth and a ``mythic figure'' in the space
program who undertook a shuttle mission at the age of 77 _ is still
revered in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank him for accepting this latest mission'' of testifying
against the popular amendment, said Leahy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all love the flag and are dedicated to it and to what it
stands for,'' Glenn told the committee. But it would ``tear the
fabric of the country'' to ``retreat from the principles that our
flag stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   There is hardly an epidemic of flag desecration, he pointed out,
and asked, ``is this really a solution looking for a problem?''
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, McCain told how one of his comrades in the POW
camp stitched the Stars and Stripes on the inside of his prison
garb. With this shirt stuck to the wall, the Americans would say
the pledge of allegiance to the flag each day.
</P>
<P>
   But their captors discovered the flag and severely beat its
creator, McCain recalled. Afterward, while still bruised and
bleeding, the punished POW was back sewing another flag from scraps
of cloth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into a constitutional debate,'' McCain
said quietly. ``I feel very strongly about the flag.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Chafee told the panel, ``I strongly oppose the amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It trivializes the Constitution,'' he said. Would the law
punish college professors for burning a flag in protest, he asked,
but not Boy Scouts for reverently burning a worn or soiled flag,
the recommended means of disposal? What about someone who burned a
worn or soiled flag in protest?
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear that the unintended consequences (of the measure) will
be far worse'' than ``the isolated instances of desecration,'' said
Kerrey. ``Real patriotism cannot be coerced.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cleland said the flag is ``the one unifying symbol of our
country'' and deserves protection. Soldiers have been awarded the
Medal of Honor, often posthumously, for protecting the flag, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's opposition to the amendment was
explained by Randolph Moss, acting assistant attorney general in
the office of legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amendment, if passed, would for the first time in our
history limit the individual freedoms protected by the Bill of
Rights, adopted over two centuries ago,'' Moss testified.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, however, the opponents were criticized by
Butch Miller, the national commander of the American Legion, a
veterans group with 2.8 million members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Various polls conducted over 10 years have shown consistently
that 80 percent of the American people support the amendment.
Forty-nine state legislatures have passed resolutions supporting
the amendment,'' Miller said in a prepared statement. ``It is time
for those we have elected to represent us in Washington to do the
right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
