<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEATLODGE-JAIL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLACE FOR TRADITION: INMATES BUILD SWEAT LODGE IN COMANCHE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMANCHE, Texas _ The sight of a sweat lodge in Comanche County
probably wouldn't have been unusual back in the 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   But since few Native Americans are left in the region, and its
location is inside the grounds of the Comanche County Jail, the
lodge now is a little out of the ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Located behind the jail's auto repair shop and surrounded by the
barren soil that is a byproduct of a recent jail expansion, the
sweat lodge is surrounded by a chain-link fence and razor wire. But
it is sacred to the eight Native American inmates from Wisconsin
who were allowed to build and use it in Comanche County after being
denied the right while they were housed in other Texas jails.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all thought it was kind of ironic that we would end up in a
town named Comanche,'' said Randy Denny, 42, who spent most of his
life on the Oneida Reservation in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of joke about it, that the Indians have returned,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a town where high school mascot is ``The Indians'' and the
annual arts and crafts festival is called a ``Pow Wow,'' the
inmates have been a little surprised at their reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're a little bit of a novelty, but we've been
well-received'' said Denny, who is serving time on an arson
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed the county was procrastinating for a while but we
got it built and we've been treated well here,'' Denny said. ``We
call it the mom-and-pop jail because it's so laid-back around
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Comanche County Sheriff Billy Works said the sweat lodge
ceremonies have posed no problems and have helped morale in the
jail, 100 miles southwest of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of what they've done here,'' said Works, who
acknowledged that it took a while to find a site for the sweat
lodge. ``Every time we picked a site we had a county commissioner
saying we couldn't build it there,'' he said. ``But I think
everyone's happy with the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   One Saturday a month, stones are heated in a pit and the inmates
_ two Oneidas, two Menominis, two Chippewas, one Ponca and one
Aztec _ shed their clothes and crawl into the sweat lodge to begin
their prayers and songs. Two remain outside, heating stones in a
fire pit.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony, which is for purification, lasts about three
hours. It includes four sessions, with seven hot stones used for
each stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The door faces east, representing rebirth,'' Denny said. ``If
my mother or sister were giving birth, for example, we would pray
for the newborns.''
</P>
<P>
   The men then pray to the west, north and south, which represent
the stages of life. There are ribbons, which signify each
direction, and the ends of the ribbons are filled with a mixture of
tobacco, cedar, sage and sweet grass.
</P>
<P>
   Between the lodge's entrance and the pit where stones are heated
is a staff topped with feathers and deer antlers, representing
birds and hooved animals.
</P>
<P>
   Though they are satisfied that they finally have a sweat lodge,
Denny said the Native American inmates were frustrated by the
amount of time it took for it to be completed.
</P>
<P>
   They are among 740 Wisconsin inmates housed in eight Texas
jails. In other Texas counties, the inmates said, they felt they
were never taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never a priority,'' Denny said. ``We were made fun of
and taunted for our faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Hood County Sheriff Rodney Jeanis, head of Wis-Tex, the
company that finds jail space for Wisconsin inmates, said he
immediately thought of Comanche County as the place for the Native
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their religion is different than anything some people have
been around _ that's one of the reasons I thought of Comanche,''
Jeanis said. ``It was Indian country. I don't think they liked the
idea initially, but they got behind it. The support this has
received from the community has been unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   To show their appreciation, the inmates have made Indian crafts
and given them to guards and residents who helped them obtain
materials for the sweat lodge. Now that the lodge is built, Works
hopes the Indian crafts made by the inmates can be sold at a flea
market outside the jail.
</P>
<P>
   The inmates also are planning a Ghost Feast for June 12, where
they will honor their ancestors with a daylong celebration of
drumming, singing and dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll try and have some traditional foods but, who knows, we
may end up having hot dogs,'' Denny said. ``It just kind of depends
on what kind of support and donations come in. We hope we'll get
the support and attention of other Indian groups in Texas to help
us out.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
