<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6621 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-MAKING-CARDS-3TAK     04-28 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MAKING-CARDS-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE FOR CREATING GREETING CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Alice Keim, a teacher, is the technology coordinator for the Horace
Mann Lower School in the Bronx.  
 By ALICE KEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've never been a big fan of store-bought greeting cards. I've
always preferred to pull out some markers or watercolors and create
my own disaster. I like my cards to sound like me, not like a
Hallmark professional.
</P>
<P>
   But I am marrying into a family of big-time card givers so I
have started going to card stores in search of thoughts or feelings
to send to my fiance's relatives. I have discovered, however, that
I can spend hours and never find a true expression of myself.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it doesn't matter whether you like card stores or
not: Mother's Day is around the corner, and the pressure is on. One
answer is software that allows you to combine your personal style
with computer-assisted production: graphics, phrases and more.
</P>
<P>
   The programs allow you to be as creative or inventive as you
wish, providing preformatted options for the timid and creative
tools for the bold.
</P>
<P>
   Most home-publishing products have a card option. There are
also, however, many programs that are specifically geared toward
cards and other simple printed products for the consumer who does
not want all the publishing options.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Microsoft Graphics Studio Home Publishing 99 is a
comprehensive publishing program, but Microsoft's Greetings 99
includes everything you need for cards and other small projects.
Similarly, Sierra Home's Print Artist Platinum is a wonderful
program, but if you just want to make some cards and invitations,
Print Artist Cards Plus is more than enough.
</P>
<P>
   The packages of most home publishing programs promote huge
collections of clip art, phrases and more. The numbers are truly
remarkable _ 14,000 designs, 6,000 greeting cards, 80,000 graphics
_ but also relatively unimportant when choosing a program.
</P>
<P>
   If a program, no matter how large, doesn't include the type and
style you want, then it's a waste of money. I was amazed by the
collection of 5,000 quotations in one product, yet disappointed by
the 6,000 greeting cards available in another program. While there
may be a huge number of cards, they may not correspond to your
style and needs, and you probably won't know that until you open
the box.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the programs also offer different project types and
often include calendar reminders that help keep you informed of
forthcoming holidays and other celebrations that might warrant a
card. Most have electronic greetings that allow you to send cards,
often animated, through a Web site or e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Some products are geared to children, but I was disappointed by
them. For example, I looked at IBM's Crayola Print Factory, for
ages 5 to 10. The tools were easy to understand but hard to use.
The graphics were cute, but most children _ certainly the ones I
teach _ would expect a bigger and better selection.
</P>
<P>
   For children, a general classic art program, like Broderbund's
Kid Pix or Art Dabbler by Metacreations, is a better bet than the
programs specifically for cards. Many adult programs are friendly
enough for children to use with just a little help. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRINT ARTIST CARDS PLUS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sierra Home; $29.95; Windows 95 and 98.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cards Plus is in many ways the solution to basic card-making
needs. Graphically appealing and simple to use, it caters to the
user who wants to make cards, things like scrapbooks and calendars,
and little else.
</P>
<P>
   The interface is familiar and comfortable, similar to most word
processing programs but with slightly different buttons and
functions. The opening screen offers 11 different project types,
each represented by a picture button. There are several different
types of cards as well as stationery, scrapbooks, banners,
calendars and party and gift sets to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   Clicking on Holiday Cards brought up another picture window that
let me choose a season of the year or other options. After I picked
Spring, I was able to select from holidays ranging from National
Nurse Day to Easter. The design choices vary by format; I found a
simple flower card.
</P>
<P>
   Before making my final decision, I was able to preview the
inside and back of the card in addition to the front design. After
I made my selection, the card appeared on the screen with an
editing button bar.
</P>
<P>
   At this point in the program, you can alter the card. I changed
the background colors on the front cover, then moved inside and
clicked on a button with a picture of a camera to get access to a
library of compatible graphics.
</P>
<P>
   The program allows you to search by keyword or by category, an
essential function when searching through 20,000 pictures. The
search pulls up related subject matter, not just graphics with
matching titles. For example, using the keyword ``mom'' pulled up
graphics titled Family 1 and Mother With Baby. For a picture of a
flower, I could search by category in either the Flora or the
Flowers and Plants categories, or I could type in the name of my
mother's favorite flower.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Once you select a graphic, it appears on your editing screen
with handles. I moved it around, made it bigger and rotated it to
an appealing angle.
</P>
<P>
   When I clicked on the Insert Text Object button, a screen
appeared where I could either write my own message or choose from a
catalog of quotations. This is a remarkable section that includes
words of wisdom, philosophy and humor from most every source you
can think of, like Dr. Spock, Phyllis Diller and Friedrich
Nietzsche. A selection of 300 fonts also provides wonderful
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   If you are happy with this program's graphics collection and are
looking for a program that is easy to use, Cards Plus is an
excellent choice. But the program does not do a good job of
importing the user's own graphics or artwork. That requires a more
sophisticated program. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COREL PRINT HOUSE MAGIC 4 PREMIUM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Corel; $39; Windows 95 and later.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While I try to stay away from programs that seem too ambitious,
I truly enjoyed using Print House Magic 4. It is a a sophisticated
program designed for the novice user, thanks to a wonderful
built-in tutorial.
</P>
<P>
   The opening screen is a simple interface with a blank page to
the right and options to the left: no cute icons or enticing
sounds. You can choose to work from a ``sample,'' from ``scratch''
or from a saved document.
</P>
<P>
   I also liked the ability to jump immediately from the opening
screen to the last project you worked on. Clicking on Sample or
Scratch calls up project types to choose from. There are banners,
brochures, calendars, certificates, cards and others.
</P>
<P>
   To choose cards, I selected Birthday as my occasion and Family
as my recipient. A list appeared with sample birthday cards to
various family members. I also looked in the humor section but, as
is the case in just about every card store, I wasn't too thrilled
by the selection. All the cards can be previewed while you are
considering the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The program comes with six CDs. It is both a blessing and a
nuisance to have such a large selection of photos, phrases, borders
and clip art. There are two CDs labeled Photos, two labeled Clip
Art Images, more clip art images combined with picture frames and
borders on another CD and the main program CD, which offers a
sample of everything.
</P>
<P>
   I found myself switching CDs in search of an image from the
instruction book or an image that would complement my project. The
program will tell you if you make an error by inserting a CD that
doesn't contain what you are looking for, but it does not specify
which is the correct disk to use.
</P>
<P>
   I changed my card by switching the message and adding a
personalized opening. Then I decided to import a photo. It is in
this area that Corel excels beyond the other home publishing
products. Print House Premium includes a copy of Photo House 3,
which offers many tools similar to those offered by Adobe Workshop.
It is easy to toggle between the programs to create a fantastic
personalized card.
</P>
<P>
   I opened a family photograph from my desktop folder and started
to play with Photo House 3. I was able to repair red eye, adjust
the color and contrast and replace colors in my photograph. I took
a photograph with poor lighting and shadows and made it
presentable. I was particularly impressed by the program's ability
to let a user take several steps backward when a mistake is made.
</P>
<P>
   Another useful inclusion is the cloning tool, which lets you
copy one part of a photo into another. I took a picture of my
2-year-old nephew, cut him out, pasted him into a jungle scene and
then cloned the bushes to make the setting seem natural. The
drawing tools are also impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Photo House 3 also has unusual special effects that allow you to
warp and swirl your photograph and add texture. It combines the
sophistication of Photoshop with the user-friendly tools of Kai's
Power Goo. If you want to import your own images into your cards,
the results with this program are wonderful. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN GREETINGS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CREATE-A-CARD GOLD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mindscape; $49.99; Windows 95 and 98.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of this program is its simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the opening screen, the program features a
graphics-based interface with friendly icons and limited choices.
This program will not answer every home publishing need, but it
provides an easy way to create some home print projects.
</P>
<P>
   To create a Mother's Day card, I started simply. The screen let
me narrow my search by picking from specific People and Format
categories. For example, I could have chosen ``flowery thoughts,''
which steers you to an extensive collection of sentimental cards,
or ``new mother.'' I chose ``for grandmother.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The next screen shows a mock-up of the actual cards and a check
box for you to select a tone for your card.
</P>
<P>
   The choices were disappointing. For a funny card for my
grandmother, I had only one option. Double clicking brought the
card to full size, and additional tools appeared on the screen.
From here, you can preview the different front covers available and
select from a few other messages that go with the same card design.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a Change Text option that allows the user to
personalize the message. I changed Grandma to Grammy and
substituted in my name where appropriate. On the back of the card,
I gave myself creative credit right above the large American
Greetings logo.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, I could have printed the card and called it done.
Instead, however, I chose to click the Creative Workshop link to
personalize my card further. This section provides more phrases and
drawing tools and the ability to add photos or art from the file. I
was able to find words more appropriate for my own grandmother and
add a few graphics to spice up the card.
</P>
<P>
   The graphics selection is enormous and a bit overwhelming. I
found myself scrolling through the pages trying to remember where I
had seen certain pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The print menu allowed me to choose a paper format and provided
helpful animated instructions for how to fold your card once it is
printed. It also provided ways to create a self-mailer or an
envelope. The card can be sent via e-mail, or if you send the card
to American Greetings through e-mail, it will print and mail it for
you for a small fee.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good program to use with your children. You can enable
a child guard, which makes potentially inappropriate adult-oriented
material available only to users with the correct password.
</P>
<P>
   Any child who knows how to use computers could create a card _
or invitations, announcements, multimedia cards, signs,
certificates, stickers, stationery and more. The program includes a
calendar, which can be personalized to help remind you of occasions
for sending cards, and a special screen saver program. The software
comes with locked files containing additional graphic collections
that can be opened for additional fees.
</P>
<P>
   But I would not recommend this program for people with extensive
experience with desktop publishing or photo editing. While the
tools are adequate for the novice, they will prove frustrating for
more experienced users.
</P>
<P>
   The drawing and painting tools are extremely limited so it's a
poor program for those wanting to create original artwork. You
could create the artwork in another program and import it as you
would a photo, but that would seem to speak volumes about the
inadequacy of this program for such uses. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT GRAPHICS STUDIO GREETINGS 99 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Microsoft; $29.95; Windows 95 and 98.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you want to design the card of your dreams on a Microsoft
program, you face a decision. Microsoft Graphics Studio Home
Publishing 99 has card-making components. The Greetings 99 program
includes Hallmark materials.
</P>
<P>
   If you just want to make cards, the Greetings program makes the
most sense. The program is user-friendly and allows you to choose
from sections called Paper Projects, E-Mail Projects, Occasions and
Blank Projects (for starting from scratch).
</P>
<P>
   I found that I could make a Mother's Day card in any of these
areas. On the Paper menu, I could choose from seven options,
including Greeting Cards, Stationery and Announcements. When I
clicked on Greeting Cards, the computer prompted me to either use
one of the predesigned cards or start with a blank page.
</P>
<P>
   The first option includes thumbnails of card designs and lets
you pick a mood: cute, funny or serious. I found it frustrating
that I was able to see only one mood at a time. After choosing a
card, you can edit, add and alter to your heart's content.
</P>
<P>
   I changed the border, altered the colors, added some clip art
and came up with a fairly original card with the Hallmark look, yet
my own personal touch. I was impressed by the selection of art and
phrases but frustrated by the way it was organized.
</P>
<P>
   The images are divided into 51 subject areas with 60 pictures in
each section. These sections are rather overwhelming. The program
does, however, have a search engine. I typed in ``chicken'' and was
shown an astounding 24 images and borders either showing or
relating to chickens.
</P>
<P>
   I next tried to make a photo card using a photograph that I had
saved from the modified version of the program Picture It Express,
which comes with the Greetings program. But if you are serious
about photos, I would suggest purchasing the full version of
Picture It or going with a different card program. This
mini-version is fun and useful but just did not do enough.
</P>
<P>
   The most useful aspect of this program is that it enables you to
reduce red eye with a click of a button. The program also allows
you to alter the color, brightness and contrast of any photo and
includes a cropping tool that cuts out a piece of the picture in
cookie-cutter shapes.
</P>
<P>
   The editing is very limited, however, so you will be most
successful if you start off with a high-quality photo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
