<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6634 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIANI-AT&AMP;T-NYT &LR;      04-28 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIANI-AT&AMP;T-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUND DESIGN: SMOG GETS IN YOUR EARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 BY PHILIP NOBEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suzanne Ciani lives in seclusion at the end of a dirt road in
Marin County, Calif., but her most famous piece of music is heard
about 280 million times every day. In 1988, balancing commercial
work with her career as a composer, she created what may be the
world's best-known audio signature: the miniature chordal flourish
that introduces every AT&AMP;T call.
</P>
<P>
   Known within the company as the sparkle tone, that one-second
chime was the first concerted foray into sonic branding in what
might be called, with apologies to the Internet, ``phonespace.''
After that humble beginning, the deluge.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by the competition, the wires are now clogged with audio
logos and announcements for new services and pay-per-use features.
If a line is busy in the Bell Atlantic calling area, for instance,
a voice will intrude for a moment to offer the company's new
call-back service. If you use AT&AMP;T to call another time zone from
your home phone, you may hear their new feature: a quick ``It's
(insert time here) where you're calling'' before the ringing
starts.
</P>
<P>
   If you are lucky enough to find a working Bell Atlantic pay
phone in the New York subway, you then have to wait out an
interminable commercial greeting: ``Thank you for riding New York
Transit.'' Similar messages accost you when you make pay calls at
Marriott or Hilton hotels. And AT&AMP;T has entered what seems like
very dangerous terrain, injecting promotional messages about
discounts and frequent flier miles, at the beginning of some
overseas calls.
</P>
<P>
   All of this new line noise naturally raises the specter of
disenchanted customers. And as in the real world, the quality of
the design determines the quality of the experience. When Bell
Atlantic introduced its new information service, it came with a
bassy greeting by James Earl Jones: ``Welcome to Bell Atlantic
local and national four-one-one.'' To keep people from pulling out
their hair during the almost four seconds it took the message to
run, designers condensed it digitally by 20 percent. Jim Smith, a
Bell Atlantic spokesman, said: ``You want to brand the service, but
you don't want to annoy the customers, and you sure as heck don't
want to slow them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound designers at AT&AMP;T are also quick to point out that their
chimes and stamps won't cause delays. Because they take place
during the few seconds it still takes to connect a call, it is
really a sort of found promotional space. Brad Burns, a spokesman
for MCI Worldcom, was just as quick to claim that his company's
``seamless'' network didn't offer even that tiny window of
opportunity. ``When it comes to these types of messages,'' he said
haughtily, ``we've found that less is more.''
</P>
<P>
   David Shenk, the author of ``Data Smog: Surviving the
Information Glut'' (Harper San Francisco, 1997), sees parallels
between telephone branding and the digital overload he decried in
his book. More information, he points out, always comes at a cost:
``You have to ask, `What are we giving up?' '' But he is hopeful
that the once pristine phonescape can be reclaimed. ``Generally
speaking, the people who make this mess can be counted on to clean
it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Those people include Jim Farber and his team of sound designers
at AT&AMP;T Labs in Florham Park, N.J. One of their current projects is
to improve the audio cues that callers encounter as they navigate
through modern communication's least loved bramble: automated
answering services. The team has recently developed a palette of 12
two-note tones _ fuller melodies, they say, flunked the focus
groups _ that could be used to identify specific ``locations'' in a
complex system. Callers will learn that each sound designates a
certain spot in the menu. ``To make it good and attractive requires
the kind of production skills that a small radio drama would,''
Farber said.
</P>
<P>
   Thoughtful design may be able to keep people from getting lost
in phonespace, but it is unlikely to make the commercials go away.
The future may be the Free For All Phone Club, a service that takes
on-phone advertising to its logical conclusion: free long-distance
calls in exchange for the pleasure of having your conversations
interrupted every few minutes by sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   So, with all this money about to change hands, where is Suzanne
Ciani, whose elegant chime first raised the bar for telephone audio
design? She asked herself the same thing. ``Believe me, I tried to
get a royalty,'' she said. ``All I wanted was about one-billionth
of a cent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
