<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6639 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-ORLEANS-JAZZ-ART-     04-28 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ORLEANS-JAZZ-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS IN AMERICA: TIME AND AGAIN, THAT SPUTTERING BEAT GOES MARCHIN'
IN
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ A lone sousaphone, unamplified, was all it took to
rock the house at the Maple Leaf, a New Orleans club that was
packed at 2:30 a.m. Wednesday. With the Rebirth Brass Band onstage,
the tin-ceilinged room was full of happy feet, dancing to Rebirth's
euphoric, recklessly improvisational medleys of its own rowdy
call-and-response chants and songs from Marvin Gaye and TLC. The
chunky stomp of funk was married to a rolling, sputtering
carnival-parade backbeat that's at least a century old; the band
played and sang without microphones. All the crowd cared about was
that it made them dance.
</P>
<P>
   Rebirth's set, like countless performances in and around the New
Orleans Jazz and Heritage Festival over the last week, wasn't a
self-conscious fusion trying to prove some thesis about musical
history. It was simply bar-band business as usual in a city where
that history is a common language, a lexicon of tunes and rhythms
and inflections that's maintained, mostly, because it feels good.
</P>
<P>
   The survival of old styles, which are cherished not as creaky
old relics but as sure things, is a homegrown musical miracle. And
while that persistence seems absolutely natural to local musicians,
it's still no more likely than finding a metropolis where men still
regularly wear hats and women have not only held on to their
flapper dresses but feel free to wear them with running shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, New Orleans music is different because New Orleans
has been different. West African slaves held on to drumming
traditions with regular gatherings in Congo Square and found New
World guises for old parade traditions in Mardi Gras. Under French
and Spanish rule, and then as a major port, the city took in
cosmopolitan influences, while its natural moat _ the Mississippi
on one side, Lake Pontchartrain on the other _ isolated it from the
rest of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz innovators found regular work in the red-light district of
Storyville, inaugurating an enduring fondness for live music. The
city's distinctive racial history, from Creolization through Jim
Crow through integration, has also left traces. Yet New Orleans
isn't isolated anymore; like any other American city, it has cable
television and chain stores. But somehow _ through stubbornness,
through memory, through institutions like the Jazz and Heritage
Festival and through some mysterious grace _ its music hasn't
assimilated.
</P>
<P>
   In New Orleans, musicians can make careers playing sousaphone or
clarinet; elsewhere those instruments are hardly heard outside high
school bands. In New Orleans young musicians don't feel corny
playing ``When the Saints Go Marching In'' or ``Basin Street
Blues,'' while audiences happily sing along with songs like ``Iko
Iko'' or ``I'm Walking.'' It's not nostalgia or some kind of cute
revival, because the music was never lost or forgotten. Musicians
love to swing, but they wear T-shirts not vintage suits.
</P>
<P>
   Purism doesn't appeal to Louisiana musicians. Brass bands and
zydeco bands (which arrived in New Orleans from the neighboring
Cajun and Creole bayous) not only find regular club engagements,
but freely combine the old instrumentation with tactics lifted from
rock, modern jazz and, in self-described ``brass-hop'' bands like
Coolbone and All That, from hip-hop. Lil' Band o' Gold, a band of
bayou rockers that performed at the festival and in clubs, knocks
together rockabilly guitar, country pedal steel guitar, Cajun
accordion and a rhythm-and-blues saxophone section that happened to
include Richard Landry of the Philip Glass Ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   Working primarily for live audiences _ instead of trying to hone
potential hits for an invisible mass public _ New Orleans musicians
survive by performing. Many musicians are members of two or three
or four groups at once, piecing together a living from club fees
and tips. The better ones work so often that they don't have to
leave town to get by. Yet even if New Orleans musicians didn't make
a virtue of necessity, they would probably pride themselves on
their versatility.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know who's going to be on the other end of that
phone call,'' said Roger Lewis between club sets by the Dirty Dozen
Brass Band, which revolutionized brass-band music in the 1970s by
adapting be-bop tunes, funk and anything else it wanted. Lewis can
anchor the band or play dizzying swirls of modern jazz; last
Thursday and Sunday, he also punched out brawny baritone-saxophone
riffs as part of Fats Domino's horn section.
</P>
<P>
   Working in multiple contexts, New Orleans musicians recharge old
connections. As the music moves through generation after generation
and hybrid after hybrid, some features keep coming back, the way
great-grandpa's nose is still recognizable on a distant nephew. The
second-line parade beat, one of the wellsprings of 20th-century
music, turns up in gospel, jazz and rhythm-and-blues; the
instrumentation of traditional jazz bands echoes through later
styles.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night the Jazz and Heritage Festival's annual Dew
Drop Inn Revisited concert _ a tribute to New Orleans' equivalent
of the Cotton Club _ brought together four rhythm-and-blues singers
in a memorial to Johnny Adams, a hero to local singers. Big Al
Carson sounded like a trombone; Marva Wright's gospelly belting
could have come from a trumpet; Irma Thomas was an urbane alto
saxophone, and Aaron Neville had the delicacy of a clarinet.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans jazz musicians aren't too serious to dip into
traditional jazz or to sing. Kermit Ruffins, who leads one of the
city's most popular jazz groups, alternates genial trumpet solos
with homey vocals on songs like ``Ain't Misbehavin''' or his own
``Hide the Reefer.'' At club dates, he also cooks barbecue for his
fans.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't hurt that New Orleans is a tourist delight, drawing
people who want to experience the city's legendary music in its old
forms. But the city's musicians regularly give ignorant (or
drunken) audiences more nuance and passion than they necessarily
appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   The virtuoso guitarist and singer Snooks Eaglin, who rarely
leaves New Orleans, honored a request for ``Happy Birthday'' when
he played late on Monday night at the Mid-City Lanes bowling alley
with a jocular, rolling treatment that harked back to the heyday of
New Orleans rhythm-and-blues. His scratchy voice sounded like a wry
reflection on getting older, with raffish personality and vivid
roots; every hip in the room was swaying.
</P>
<P>
   From a distance _ perhaps when the birthday boy leaves town _ it
could seem like a magnificent, improbable mirage. But in New
Orleans, it's just another night's work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
