<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6645 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAMA-ELECTIONS-$ADV     04-28 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-ELECTIONS-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PANAMA'S PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES MILK FAME OF WELL-KNOWN
RELATIONS
 &HT;    875&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With PANAMA-BOX-$ADV01.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., May 1 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Even from the grave, Panama's cigar-chomping former
dictator, Gen. Omar Torrijos, surely must be smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Torrijos had called the U.S. presence in Panama a ``colonialist
tumor'' before negotiating the Panama Canal treaties with his
friend, former President Jimmy Carter, in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Now his son, Martin Torrijos, 35, has a good shot at winning
Panama's presidential election on Sunday(5/2) and leading the
country as it takes official custody of the 50-mile-long waterway
at high noon on Dec. 31 under the terms of those treaties.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it would be a remarkable twist of fate for the young
Torrijos to preside over the fulfillment of his father's dream.
</P>
<P>
   But his political ascension is far from being a sure thing as
several polls this week predict a neck-and-neck contest with the
leader of Panama's largest opposition party, Mireya Moscoso.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, both candidates have played up their
famous relations more than their stands on domestic issues such as
jobs and education.
</P>
<P>
   Omar Torrijos headed a military coup that deposed former
President Arnulfo Arias 11 days after he took office in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   The colorful general remained in power until he died in a 1981
airplane crash.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Moscoso is the widow of Arias, a famous three-time
president and the country's most popular civilian politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin is obviously getting a lift from Omar's continued
popularity,'' said Robert Pastor, a Latin America expert at
Atlanta's Emory University who helped negotiate the Panama Canal
treaties.
</P>
<P>
   Running third in Sunday's race is Alberto Vallarino, chief
executive of one of Panama's leading banks. A political newcomer,
he lacks the big party support of the two leading candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Although Omar Torrijos has been criticized for ushering in 21
years of military rule, he still has a massive following of ardent
supporters who praise him for providing housing and employment for
the poor.
</P>
<P>
   To this day the former strongman is viewed as a national hero by
many of his countrymen for negotiating the return of the Panama
Canal, which for decades had been a Yankee thorn in the side of
Panama's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Torrijos was a mere 14 years old when the canal treaties
were negotiated, and was 18 when his father died.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Torrijos graduated from Texas A&AMP;M University with degrees
in economics and political science, and his first job was slinging
hamburgers at a McDonald's restaurant in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   He has vowed to oversee a kinder, gentler government that's in
touch with the needs of all segments of the population.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have found him to be very intelligent and very charismatic,
just like his father was,'' said Ambler Moss, former U.S.
ambassador to Panama. ``I think he'd be a good leader and represent
continuity in the U.S.-Panama relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso, 54, is a left-leaning populist who has opposed many of
the government's economic reforms -- including privatizations of
state-owned businesses -- worrying some business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But she is a tireless campaigner who made a surprisingly strong
showing in the 1994 election, when she was narrowly defeated by
President Ernesto Perez Balladares.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has seen with her own eyes the poverty that neo-liberal
economic policies have brought to Panama,'' said Guillermo Endara,
a former president who supports Moscoso.
</P>
<P>
   Panama struggles with widespread poverty and a high unemployment
rate of 12.8 percent, despite $100 million in profits annually from
canal tolls and another $300 million derived from the U.S. military
presence in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Besides blasting his economic policies, Moscoso and other
critics have often accused Balladares, as well as his party, the
Democratic Revolutionary Party, of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   That party, founded by Omar Torrijos, today supports Martin
Torrijos.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the criticism has hurt Martin Torrijos, who has
served the last four years as a deputy minister in the Balladares
administration, which is also viewed by many in Panama as being
riddled with nepotism.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, voters expressed their dissatisfaction with
Balladares by overwhelmingly defeating a referendum to change the
constitution allowing Balladares to run for a second consecutive
five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, since neither of the two leading candidates has a lot
of government experience under their belts, it's the names of their
well-known relations they often invoke when stumping for votes.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Torrijos' campaign headquarters is blanketed with posters
of his father, and even his campaign's theme song is an
enthusiastic tribute to the former dictator entitled ``Omar
Lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso, who dresses casually and is praised for her ``common
touch,'' leads a party that's named for her late husband -- the
Arnulfista Party.
</P>
<P>
   But Pastor insists that Martin Torrijos has a certain charisma
all his own.
</P>
<P>
   He points out that he defeated two opponents with the same
famous last name in last year's presidential primary: his
half-brother, Omar Torrijos Jr., and his cousin, Hugo Torrijos.
</P>
<P>
   But even with all the charisma in the world, Martin Torrijos
faces a major challenge if elected: He must ensure the canal runs
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, critics in the United States have expressed
misgivings that a small country of only 2.8 million people with no
military can successfully manage one of the world's most important
transportation lanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think there will be mismanagement of the canal,''
said John Sweeney, an analyst at the Heritage Foundation, a
conservative think tank in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the government will be tempted to milk the canal for
resources because the economy will take a big hit when the U.S.
military leaves,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of the U.S. troops will cost Panama's economy some $300
million a year, or up to 15 percent of the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   Panamanian government officials say they will more than make up
for that, though, with an expected boom in tourism and new
business.
</P>
<P>
   All the candidates promise to run the canal professionally and
to maintain good relations with the United States following the
canal's transfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be very symbolic if Martin Torrijos wins and oversees
the canal's return, but it will also be a challenge for whoever
wins,'' said Jennifer McCoy, director of the Atlanta-based Carter
Center's Latin America and Caribbean Program. ``All eyes are going
to be on Panama as it takes over the canal.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
