<SLUG> BC-CIR-PLANE-PARACHUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CASE THINGS GO VERY WRONG, A PARACHUTE FOR THE PLANE ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Minn.)   (af)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It works for pilots and passengers, so why not for whole
airplanes? Next month, a company in Duluth, Minn., plans to market
a single-engine plane with a parachute for the plane itself.
</P>
<P>
   The SR-20, from the Cirrus Design Corp., is one of only two new
American designs for single-engine private planes approved by the
Federal Aviation Administration in the past 15 years and will be
the first plane to have a parachute as standard equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The parachute is stowed on the roof; when an occupant pulls an
overhead handle, the parachute is deployed by a rocket that shoots
toward the tail.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how good you are as a pilot,'' said Chris L. Maddy,
a spokesman for the company, ``there are some circumstances, like a
midair collision, or where the pilot becomes incapacitated, or
you're flying over the woods of northern Minnesota at night and you
can't see the runway to land, and you're going to pull the chute.''
</P>
<P>
   Parachutes have already been included in ultralights and hang
gliders. The company that builds parachutes for Cirrus, Ballistic
Recovery Systems of St. Paul, Minn., also designed one as an add-on
for two small Cessnas, but they did not catch on.
</P>
<P>
   Maddy said his company had orders for 272 planes, which cost
$165,000 to $175,000 each _ $10,000 of that for the parachute. But
an owner might recoup some of that cost if insurance companies see
a reduction in claims as a result of the parachute.
</P>
<P>
   The parachute attaches at the plane's center of gravity and thus
can hold it level and give it a steady rate of descent, but using
the parachute would still be an act of desperation. The plane is
likely to be damaged beyond repair by the impact, the company said,
but the occupants will be able to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a bumpy ride and not going to be any fun,''
Maddy said, ``but you're going to walk away from it, most likely.''
The extent of injuries could also depend on whether the plane came
down in a flat spot or in the trees.
</P>
<P>
   Although the parachute is a dramatic feature, the airplane, one
of the few models developed after microchips became commonplace,
also makes heavy use of computers. The cockpit is equipped with
full-color flat-panel computer displays, something found only on
newer jets. These show the function of various aircraft systems and
navigation information, incorporating data from the Global
Positioning System.
</P>
<P>
   The plane has several other innovations intended to make it
simpler to fly. One is a lever that adjusts both the throttle and
the angle at which the propeller blades dig into the air. On most
planes those controls are separate.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cirrus has not had smooth sailing. The first one off the
production line crashed on March 23, killing the pilot, Maj. Scott
Anderson of the Minnesota Air National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who had 1,000 hours of experience in F-16s, may have
had control problems. The accident is still under investigation by
the National Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   The plane Anderson was flying did not have a parachute, which
was not available when it was built.
</P>
</TEXT>
