<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV06-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDING OVER THE HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Thursday, May 6)  
(mk) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We just sold our house in Florida, an unassuming ranch on a
woodsy lot in Plant City that my husband and I moved into when I
was six months pregnant with our first baby.
</P>
<P>
   Since our family has lived in our new home in suburban Atlanta
for nearly eight months, I was relieved that we now have only one
mortgage payment and one place to hang our hats.
</P>
<P>
   But my first question, since we did the closing long distance,
was to ask my husband, ``So, do they have any children?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said Jim, who is often puzzled when
information is requested that is neither relevant nor essential to
the transaction at hand. ``Does it matter?''
</P>
<P>
   Myself, I'm of the ``everything matters, if only in some
tangential, ephemeral, metaphysical way'' school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of COURSE it matters,'' I say. ``You didn't ASK?''
</P>
<P>
   So I called the realtor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, do you know if the couple who's buying our house has
kids?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee, no, I don't, I didn't think to ask,'' she said, blowing
my theory that all women would consider this not only interesting,
but also vital information. ``I can find out for you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, great. And I'd like to know how many and how old they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Um, sure,'' she said, sounding increasingly hesitant.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, Adam, our 8-year-old, would like to write a letter to
their kids, if they're old enough, to tell them some cool stuff
about the house and the woods and the neighborhood and school,
stuff like that,'' I explained.
</P>
<P>
   But, in all honesty, this was only part of my reason for asking.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, I wanted to know more about these people who would be
moving into the place we called home for close to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Were they bibliophiles who would appreciate our built-in,
floor-to-ceiling bookshelves in the fireplace room?
</P>
<P>
   Would they understand the magic of the huge, wooden ``Gate to
Adventure'' in the back yard that Jim had built for Adam when he
was 4 and could go exploring in the woods?
</P>
<P>
   Did they have young kids who could clamber over the swingset we
left because its feet were buried in concrete so it wouldn't shake?
</P>
<P>
   Can these newcomers sense the memories contained inside those
block walls?
</P>
<P>
   The first night home with our son, when he lay blindfolded in an
ultraviolet light box, too sleepy from the jaundice to cry, and we
put up a sign that said, ``Adam's tanning salon.''
</P>
<P>
   Or Sarah's arrival, with much fanfare, when her older brother
gladly moved from the pale yellow nursery to his ``big boy room''
filled with dinosaur posters and Star Wars figurines.
</P>
<P>
   So much of our life played out in those six rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Our realtor told us not to worry about attending the closing,
that all the papers could be mailed up to us and we could overnight
them back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do most people believe that they have to fly back for the
closing, then?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, just tradition,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But I think I know.
</P>
<P>
   They want to pass on the home with a handshake. Show them where
the sprinklers turn on. Mention the great produce stand just up the
road. And size up their replacements.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland, Fla., Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
