<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back Button On the Blink?
</P>
<P>
   Q. When I was surfing the Web, I noticed that the Back button on
my browser was ``grayed out,'' and when I closed that window, I saw
that several more windows were open underneath. Is something wrong
with my software?
</P>
<P>
   A. Nothing is wrong with your browser _ it's just doing what it
is told by the HTML code in some of the Web pages you have been
looking at. As you click on a link you wish to see, the new window
may seem to be replacing the previous one, but in fact, the new
window is opening right on top of the old one.
</P>
<P>
   So why are some pages encoded with instructions to open a new
browser window on top of your first one? Usually it is because the
Web page you have just looked at wants to keep you there, even
while showing you a page from a link it has. Many online merchants
use this tactic, which can be helpful if you just want to take a
quick look at a product and then click on the main page to return
to it. The Back button on the second window is grayed out because
the browser considers it a new window and thinks there is no place
to go back to.
</P>
<P>
   On some pages, however, the extra windows can be highly
annoying, especially the smaller pop-up windows that are there to
display only advertising. If you've had enough of the
interruptions, check your favorite shareware archive for a browser
utility that can help filter out Web page excesses, like the
freeware program called Pop Off, at www.davecentral.com/7670.html.
Or try the $20 program at www.intermute.com that promises to help
stop the popping.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
