r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EASYMEALS-2ndTake-TEX     04-28 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EASYMEALS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    _ AUTHENTIC ETHNIC FARE, VIA THE INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
 
ARLINGTON, Texas: $3 drink.'' 
 &HT;    Noe has been on the money with his read of consumer habits for
more than a decade. In 1998, 108 million Americans, or 47 percent
of the population, drank espresso, cappuccino, latte or a cold
coffee drink during the year. In 1997, it was 35 percent.
 &HT;    Hazelnut creme was a speciality coffee when Noe opened in the
1980s. Today, that flavor is one of 7-Eleven's regular offerings.
 &HT;    But it's not just the product that is appealing to consumers. It
appears that coffeehouses may become THE meeting places in the next
decade.
 &HT;    ``Coffee bars have become friendly places to hang out,'' Noe
says. ``We'll sometimes have 10 people at one of our big tables
going over blueprints. At a coffee bar, you can tie up a table for
an hour or two and no one will get upset. You do that in a
restaurant and you're expected to buy a meal. We even get families
in here who in another time would have been meeting over the dinner
table.''
 &HT;    Noe does not expect to see the coffee craze die. The only thing
he sees cooling off in the future is the temperature of the coffee.
 &HT;    ``Ten years ago we couldn't give away iced or frozen coffee
drinks,'' Noe says. ``Today those drinks are a very important part
of our overall business. Even people who don't drink coffee like
frozen drinks like our Eskimocha.''
 &HT;    And those iced and frozen drinks will further fuel the growth of
the coffee market.
 &HT;    ``When it's 140 degrees outside, that African heat, people are
going to skip their afternoon coffee,'' Noe says. ``But they will
buy an iced coffee drink.''By JUNE NAYLOR RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHLAKE, Texas _ Scarcely two months since opening her
business, Inga Bowyer suspects she may have struck gold. And the
thing is, her idea is both brilliant and simple.
</P>
<P>
   Bowyer, a Southlake resident who spent much of her formative
years in Germany, has opened an online German grocery store. Anyone
lusting for a package of teewurst, Bavarian potato dumplings or
sauerbraten gravy just has to log onto www.GermanDeli.com.
</P>
<P>
   She and her sister, Gina Green, knew there were thousands of
military brats like themselves who hungered for the rich foods of
their childhood. Deciding to forsake their event
management/promotion business, they put their energy and resources
into their passion _ German food.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at what wasn't being served and decided it was just
too hard to drive to this deli and that one and not find the foods
we wanted,'' Bowyer says. ``So we set up shop on the Internet, and
people are finding us in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   Once their site was carried by larger search engines like
Yahoo!, the e-mail inquiries began flooding in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of Germans who came to the United States for
their jobs, and they're looking for ingredients, for instance, for
baking,'' Bowyer says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll find the mixes they want, or the ready-made tart
bottoms, and then they'll discover the `brat herings' (pickled,
fried herrings) and `blutwurst' (blood sausage), too.''
</P>
<P>
   One customer in Cuba called the GermanDeli.com toll-free number
and offered to trade cigars for German sausages, but Bowyer decided
to steer clear of that deal.
</P>
<P>
   Customers going to the GermanDeli.com site find a home page
simply decorated with the yellow, red and black colors of the
German flag. Down the left margin are more than two dozen
selections, ranging from baking aids, dairy, chocolates and
liverwurst to pates, soups and teas. Want a jar of Lowensenf hot
mustard? A large one is $3.49. How about a half-pound package of
``greisinger schinkenspeck'' (paper-thin sliced, smoked pork leg)?
That's $7.49.
</P>
<P>
   GermanDeli.com shoppers can even click on ``U.S. Military
Brats'' and order T-shirts or ``greeting cards,'' and add pretty
cards written in German for birthdays, Mother's Day, weddings and
anniversaries to their virtual shopping carts.
</P>
<P>
   Bowyer _ noting that ``Germans love convenience'' _ says most
customers order online, using the secure system. Orders are shipped
within hours, Bowyer says, and the perishable items are shipped in
ice packs for one- or two-day delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Right now there's just a staff of two, working out of a small
Southlake office that has a storage room with food-laden shelves,
refrigerators and freezers. Bowyer says they want to grow slowly,
adding staff and opening a warehouse as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so many pages we want to add to the site, featuring
old photos of Germany, for instance,'' Bowyer says. ``The objective
is to become the largest Internet German food store in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Info box
</P>
<P>
   GermanDeli.com can be reached toll-free at (877) GERMANY
(437-6269), and locally at (817) 410-9955. E-mail address is
sales(at)germandeli.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail
to bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
