<HEADLINE>
THREE ENTREPRENEURS ARE ADDRESSING AMERICANS' APPETITES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 &HT;    It's no longer your grandmother's grocery list.
 &HT;    As the century ends, we're just as likely to find our meals via
fax, computer or telephone. And nourishment is no longer simply
meat and two vegetables. We want exotic food, we want premium
coffee, we want convenience. And we don't want the hassle of
trekking through football-field-size supermarkets.
 &HT;    Three entrepreneurs are hearing your needs and jumping into the
fray. One is cooking up premium meals to go and delivering them to
where harried mothers and fathers congregate: preschools. Another
is pampering us with gourmet java. And a third is offering Old
World food in a new world venue: the Internet.
 &HT;    _ AFTERSCHOOL SPECIALS PARENTS WILL LOVE 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It never fails. The air conditioning has
gone out in the car, the traffic leaving work in north Dallas is
awful, and Junior awaits chauffeur service.
</P>
<P>
   And when you finally make it to the preschool, what are the Next
Generation's words of greeting?
</P>
<P>
   ``What's for dinner, Mom?''
</P>
<P>
   If Mom is lucky, Junior's preschool is on one of the routes
serviced by Easy Street.
</P>
<P>
   This nascent home-meal replacement operation, based in Fort
Worth, cooks meals like Mom would make if Mom had the time. But
instead of delivering the meals individually, a la Domino's, the
firm delivers weekly to each of 49 preschools.
</P>
<P>
   The company is the brainchild of Fred Kirby, the former
president of Mrs. Crockett's Kitchens, a refrigerated-food
manufacturer that makes all the refrigerated potato salad sold at
Sam's and the potato salad served nationwide at KFC.
</P>
<P>
   But this time around, Kirby's food is more eatZi's than
McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making the kind of food you'd make at home if you only
had the time,'' says Kirby. ``When we came up with this idea, we
wanted to have high-quality food with real convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   And convenient it is. Easy Street provides each of the
preschools with a menu for the month. One week's offerings may
include beef burgundy with noodles, chicken con queso, chicken
piccata, and spaghetti and meatballs. As parents sign their child
in for school, they also see the month's Easy Street options.
</P>
<P>
   The order forms are faxed to Easy Street, along with the
parents' names, and the food is delivered to the schools for
pickup. It's one-stop shopping _ pick up dinner and your child at
the same time. A traditional family meal around the kitchen table
is just a microwave away.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the selections feed a family of four and range from
green beans and new potatoes with herb butter for $5 to a 2-pound
chuck roast with mashed potatoes for $14. Some of the items are
definitely targeted toward children (cheeseburger macaroni is $5,
macaroni and cheese is $4), while others are more adult
(herb-crusted pork roast sauced with apricots and a hint of
habanero peppers is $10).
</P>
<P>
   In business since January, Easy Street is selling about 1,000
entrees a week. Kirby expects that amount to quadruple within the
next few months. He's also working on deals to open kiosks in
downtown office buildings so workers can pick up dinner to go as
they head for their cars and home.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's convenient.
</P>
<P>
   You can find Easy Street on the Internet at
www.easystreetfoods.com or phone it at (817) 232-3563.
</P>
<P>
   _ COFFEEHOUSE CHAIN KNOWS VALUE OF TURNING DAILY GRIND INTO A
TREAT &QL; 
By BEVERLY BUNDY &QC; 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ If there were a contest to name the
definitive food of the 1990s, a lot of votes would have to go to
coffee.
</P>
<P>
   According to industry figures, there were fewer than 500
coffeehouses in 1991. In 1998, there were nearly 7,000. By 2000,
there could be almost 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Don Noe was doing coffee before coffee was cool. Or iced or
frozen, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, before Starbucks became the Sears of the java world,
Noe opened the Coffee Haus in Arlington's Lincoln Square. Noe
morphed that hill of roasted beans into an empire, including
locations in Sundance Square and one near Southern Methodist
University in Dallas. Tack that on to six locations at Dallas/Fort
Worth Airport and we're talking about a perking enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   And for every coffeehouse, there appears to be a different sort
of customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we opened,'' says Noe, ``I thought the profile of our
customers was predominantly female, middle-aged, white-collar,
probably a Junior Leaguer. But, guess what, the profile is
incredibly broad. We're just as likely to have someone drive up in
a beaten-up Chevrolet and run in to buy a pound of kona for $20.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coffee is a luxury that everyone can afford. You might not
have the money to buy a new yacht, but you can drink great coffee
at home. It's a very affordable way to pamper yourself,'' Noe says.
``Or you can give yourself a perk, no pun intended, with a $3
drink.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
