<HEADER>
A6673 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIT-PULITZER-TEX     04-28 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIT-PULITZER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TEACHER AND THE PULITZER: READ IT AND WEEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 602nd-bestselling book among the 2 million offered by
Internet bookstore Amazon.com is currently out of stock; anyone who
wants to buy Margaret Edson's ``Wit'' is warned it will take up to
five weeks to get one.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Faber and Faber, publishers of the $12 paperback,
printed only a few thousand copies. Play scripts recycled as books
never sell particularly well, and, until the middle of April,
``Wit'' was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pulitzer Prize for drama changed that; so did subsequent
media coverage of Edson, a 37-year-old Atlanta kindergarten teacher
who never wrote a play before ``Wit'' and who insists she isn't
going to write one after it, either. She got word of her Pulitzer
win while cleaning up her classroom after a messy lecture on bugs;
after ordering a pizza to celebrate, she went back to working on
lesson plans.
</P>
<P>
   But it required a unique playwright to craft a unique play.
Currently running at New York's Union Square Theatre, in a low-rent
area politely termed ``off-Broadway,'' ``Wit'' is a fascinating
study of one woman's confrontation with terminal illness. College
professor Vivian Bearing, 50, is dying of ovarian cancer. Her
doctor has asked her to undertake excruciating chemotherapy
treatments which, though they won't save her life, might offer some
informative results to shape future treatment of others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not my intention to give away the plot,'' Vivian informs
the audience soon after the curtain rises. ``But I think I die at
the end.'' She does, in horrible pain. Though ``Wit'' offers its
share of laughter, there are a lot more tears. Vivian, whose chief
accomplishment in life has been writing a series of books about the
works of John Donne, can't wisecrack her way past death _ but she
tries.
</P>
<P>
   Before its Pulitzer laurels, ``Wit'' struggled. Edson wrote the
play in 1991 after a stint volunteering as a hospital clerk/social
worker. Her play received the same attention most plays by unknown
authors get: No theater company was interested in producing it.
Finally, in 1995, South Coast Repertory Theater in Costa Mesa,
Calif., brought Vivian from the printed page to the boards. The
national theater community took gradual notice. By 1997, ``Wit''
was being produced in Connecticut. From there, it moved to
``off-off Broadway,'' and finally just ``off,'' a designation
meaning any theater within walking distance of the Great White Way.
</P>
<P>
   New York critics loved ``Wit'' so much that a few weeks before
the Pulitzer announcements, Playbill magazine's Web site was
describing ``Wit'' as ``certainly a front-runner, if not a foregone
conclusion for the award.'' Even after its big moment, ``Wit''
retains its modest dimensions; tickets are available at Union
Square Theatre, priced from $20 to $49.50. A few blocks away on
Broadway, it costs $80 to see ``The Lion King'' and $100 to enjoy
Kevin Spacey in Eugene O'Neill's ``The Iceman Cometh.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who can't get to New York will have to settle for reading
the script; Faber and Faber's skinny paperback is just 80 pages.
Scripts, of course, are written to be heard rather than read.
Italicized stage directions detract from the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the book/script is undeniably moving. Without other written
work for use in comparison, it's impossible to tell whether Edson
is a word wizard in the traditional sense. There are no long
descriptive passages to showcase her skills with adjectives and
adverbs. What is very clear from ``Wit,'' however, is the
playwright's rock-solid sense of dialogue. Her characters talk like
real people, especially a hospital resident who once took Vivian's
college class and hated it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I survived Bearing's course,'' he tells a nurse. ``No problem.
Heh. Yeah, John Donne, those metaphysical poets, that metaphysical
wit. Hardest poetry in the English department. Like to see ``them''
try biochemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   It's far too early to tell if ``Wit'' will become one of those
rare theatrical icons like ``Death of a Salesman'' or ``The
Mousetrap,'' to name two that apparently will be produced forever
and ever. Edson is currently getting as much attention as her play;
if she changes her mind and writes a second script, it will be hard
to top her first.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Wit'' will be enough all by itself; clumsy as scripts are
when published as books, this one still made me cry a little. I
suspect it will have the same effect on just about everyone else.
It's so sad, but it's so ``good.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
