<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6675 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-MONTICELLO02-COX     04-28 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-MONTICELLO02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At Monticello, the delicious ironies of America's first foodie
come to life
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 2.
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey Illustrations by Walter Cumming
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. _ When Thomas Jefferson returned from Paris
after five years as envoy, his fellow Virginian Patrick Henry
scoffed that he was ``so Frenchified that he abjured his native
victuals.'' Though more than two centuries have passed, the
Jeffersons haven't forgotten the slight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick Henry,'' says the man with the long strawberry locks
and fair, freckled complexion. ``I believe he liked to go out in
the woods and eat bear meat.''
</P>
<P>
   No one would ever accuse Rob Coles of abjuring his native
victuals. A fifth great-grandson of Jefferson, through his daughter
Martha, the 47-year-old actor grew up eating hot dogs and prefers
Brunswick stew and corn bread to fancy Continental cooking. Like
his famous forebear, whom he impersonates in 150 appearances a
year, Coles eats his vegetables. But there are limits to his
enthusiasm. ``Jefferson grew 16 varieties of peas,'' he says. ``I
love peas, but, I mean, come on.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jefferson is many things to many people: president,
author of the Declaration of Independence, architect, naturalist,
farmer, slaveholder. To anyone who loves food and wine, he is
another kind of founding father as well. He was America's first
great gourmet. ``I want to improve the tastes of my countrymen,''
he wrote. (Had he envisioned weiner-scarfing progeny, he might have
added, ``All palates are not created equal.'')
</P>
<P>
   In food as in other matters, Jefferson poses contradictions. As
epicurious as he was, he apparently did not cook. Though he was a
tireless champion of the New World, he fell for French cuisine as
hard as any tourist sipping wine for the first time at a sidewalk
cafe on the Champs Elysees.
</P>
<P>
   The ironies take shape at Monticello, the neoclassical mansion
he built atop a small mountain on the edge of Virginia's Blue Ridge
country. Everyone who visits these days wants to hear about Sally
Hemings, the comely slave who is said to have been Jefferson's
concubine. Guides openly discuss the relationship and the latest
DNA evidence, which very nearly proves the old rumor that she bore
children by her widowed master. But tourists rarely ask about
another Hemings, Sally's brother James, who toiled in the service
of another Jeffersonian passion. He was a cook.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson took James Hemings along to Paris and instructed him
to learn everything he could about French cooking. They returned to
Virginia with a wealth of European delights: vanilla, almonds,
pomegranates, Lombardy rice, a Dutch waffle iron, an Italian pasta
maker, a French ice cream churn. Some had never before been seen in
America. One of Jefferson's dinner guests mistook a strange new
dish for a pie made of shallots; he'd never encountered macaroni.
</P>
<P>
   Two meals a day were served at Monticello: breakfast at 9 and
dinner at 4, followed by wine. Unfortunately, no menus survive, and
the only known cookbook _ including eight recipes in Jefferson's
hand _ is frustratingly incomplete. Much of what is known about his
gastronomical explorations comes from the garden journal he kept
for six decades, recording the 170 fruits and 250 vegetables from
both sides of the Atlantic that he planted over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like an Ellis Island for immigrant plants,'' says Peter
J. Hatch, the bushy-haired director of gardens and grounds at
Monticello.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson clearly cherished his vegetables. He stored seeds in a
cabinet in his study, with his precious books. And he secured the
garden, a long terrace carved into the side of the mountain, with a
wooden fence and locked gate.
</P>
<P>
   On the slope below the garden, Jefferson cultivated a fruit
orchard and two vineyards where he attempted, with little success,
to transplant grapes from France and Italy. The vineyards are
flourishing today and until recently were pressed for wine. There
was just one problem: Monticello doesn't have a license to produce
commercial quantities of alcoholic beverage, and state authorities
got wind of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made us pour out 700 bottles like it was moonshine,''
Hatch laments.
</P>
<P>
   According to slave accounts, Jefferson himself would get his
hands dirty working the garden. There is no evidence, however, that
he ever shelled peas, chopped carrots or otherwise prepared his
food. The kitchen was for ``servants,'' as he euphemistically
called slaves, and his design for Monticello kept most of their
scullery work out of sight. The kitchen, smokehouse and wine cellar
are located beneath promenades that flank the main house and are
joined below it by a tunnel. Bottles were lifted by dumbwaiter from
the subterranean quarters into the dining room, and food was
delivered through a revolving door with shelves that allowed
service with a minimum of interruption. Jefferson didn't like
servants hanging around while he conversed with guests; he thought
it fed gossip.
</P>
<P>
   For the past five years, the private foundation that runs
Monticello has undertaken an oral history project to record the
stories of the plantation's slave descendants. Cooks have figured
prominently.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson freed James Hemings on the condition that he train
someone else to become chef. Out on his own, Hemings traveled
widely and took a job cooking at a Baltimore tavern. He died a
young man in 1801.
</P>
<P>
   ``He appears to have committed suicide,'' says Lucia Stanton,
Monticello's senior research historian. ``We think he had a
drinking problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemings trained his younger brother Peter as his replacement. He
was joined in the kitchen by Edith Fossett, who went to the White
House with Jefferson and returned to Monticello after he retired.
She was still there when he died on July 4, 1826, and was sold,
along with eight of her children, at an estate auction.
</P>
<P>
   There's a happier postscript. The Fossetts eventually purchased
their freedom and moved west to Cincinnati, where they assisted
runaway slaves on the Underground Railroad. One of those eight
children, Peter Fossett, became a caterer and minister who helped
found the black Baptist church in Ohio. Many years later, on his
85th birthday, his congregation asked him if there was any gift he
longed for. There was; he wanted to visit Monticello. Despite
everything, he still regarded it as home.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, more than 100 descendants of Jefferson's slaves
gathered for a reunion at Monticello. There was no dinner on the
grounds; they had to go off-site to a restaurant for lunch. The
only foods to be had at Monticello these days are gift shop snacks.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, on Jefferson's 256th birthday, Monticello observed
the occasion with the usual wreath-laying ceremony at his grave
under a shady grove on the side of the mountain. The real
celebration took place that night down the road at the Clifton Inn,
a 1790s house that once belonged to Jefferson's son-in-law. Chef
Rachel Greenberg prepared a five-course Jeffersonian feast with
paired Virginia wines that had one couple blithely singing ``happy
birthday, dear Thomas'' over dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Before dinner, there was a surprise. ``Ladies and gentlemen,''
Greenberg announced, ``I give you Thomas Jefferson.'' And in walked
his kinsman Coles, looking as bright as a spring morning with his
red hair, white ruffled shirt and green frock coat with gold
piping.
</P>
<P>
   The actor's soliloquy included an anecdote that could have come
from the papers of Jerry Clower. Jefferson recalls a boyhood meal
for eight at which nine pork chops were served. Everyone had a pork
chop, leaving one in the middle of the table. No one dared take it;
they all begged off, saying they were full. Just then, the candles
flickered and young Thomas reached for the chop and felt the
stabbing of eight forks.
</P>
<P>
   The anecdote didn't taste right. Jefferson always told people
that he ate meat sparingly, usually as a condiment to flavor
vegetables. He doesn't seem a pork chop kind of guy.
</P>
<P>
   Coles readily confessed. ``My great uncle used to tell that
story. It never happened to Jefferson. I just like to tell it. I'd
rather be entertaining than authentic.''
</P>
<P>
   A Virginia ham, this Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
