<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6697 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUGS-MEDIA29-COX     04-28 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-MEDIA29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUBSTANCE ABUSE COMMON IN MOVIES AND MUSIC, STUDY FINDS
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Drug agencies reported Wednesday that the nation's
teens are being exposed to high levels of drug and substance use in
movies and music.
</P>
<P>
   In 200 popular movies and 1,000 popular songs from 1996 and
1997, investigators found that 98 percent of the movies and 27
percent of the songs contained references to use of tobacco,
alcohol, illegal drugs or medicines.
</P>
<P>
   The study, the first to precisely quantify such references, was
conducted by the White House Office of National Drug Control Policy
and the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services' Substance
Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entertainment media can have an enormous impact on
society, and the findings show that drug references and messages
are part of our children's lives,'' said Nelba Chavez,
administrator of the substance abuse agency.
</P>
<P>
   The study focused on how often movies and songs depicted the use
of illegal drugs, alcohol, tobacco, and over-the-counter and
prescription medicines. The study looked at what substances were
used, who used them, how often the substances were used or
mentioned and the consequences of the use.
</P>
<P>
   Persons age 12 to 20 make up 26 percent of movie admissions, and
63 percent of children ages 9 to 17 watch at least one rented video
per week. The music industry estimates that teens listen to music
an average of four to five hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   According to the drug policy office, use of illicit drugs among
10th graders has doubled since 1992, to 23.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While there's no clear evidence that entertainment content is
linked to drug use, ``our children's rate of exposure to substance
use has increased,'' said Barry McCaffrey, director of the office.
</P>
<P>
   The study of the entertainment industry found that alcohol was
depicted in 93 percent of the movies studied, tobacco was shown in
89 percent, and illicit drugs in 22 percent. The study also showed
that consequences of substance use were portrayed in only 49
percent of the movies studied.
</P>
<P>
   In movies rated G, the study found, tobacco use was depicted in
79 percent and alcohol use in 76 percent. No G- or PG-rated movies
showed illicit drug use. Of PG-13 movies, tobacco was depicted in
82 percent, alcohol use in 97 percent, and illicit drugs in 17
percent. In R-rated selections, tobacco use was found in 92
percent, alcohol use in 94 percent, and illicit drug use in 20
percent. Only five movies out of the 200 studied depicted no
substance use.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Roberts, a professor of communication at Stanford
University and a researcher for the study, noted that ``with the
exception of hard drugs, there was no difference between the rated
movies.''
</P>
<P>
   The study also showed that illicit drug use was depicted in 18
percent of dramas, in 13 percent of the comedies, and only in 10
percent of the action adventure movies.
</P>
<P>
   In musical lyrics, the study showed, 17 percent referred to
alcohol use, 3 percent to tobacco use, and 18 percent to illicit
drugs. Only 19 percent of song lyrics depicted the consequences of
substance use.
</P>
<P>
   Among various musical genres, rap music most often referred to
substance use. Illicit drugs were mentioned in 63 percent of rap
songs and alcohol use in 47 percent. Country and Western music had
the lowest levels, with illicit drug use mentioned in 1 percent of
the songs and alcohol use in 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some good news to report,'' said McCaffrey. ``The
entertainment industry is already working on a variety of fronts,
with government and private organizations to develop
solution-orientated initiatives and programs with more accurate
messages and images.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey said government and private agencies have met with
groups in the film industry and the music industry to discuss some
changes. Some of the suggestions offered by McCaffrey and others
were to stop portraying drug use humorously, to show realistic
consequences of substance use and to remember that drug use is
abnormal.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
