<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-PIRATES29 _ ATLANTA _ Braves vs. Pirates game story.
(Stinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 13.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: First pitch is at 7:40 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-NOTES29 _ ATLANTA _ Braves notebook. (Stinson/Rosen,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-REDSOX-HOBSON _ JUPITER, Fla. _ Butch Hobson sat behind a
desk in the visiting manager's office Monday afternoon at Roger
Dean Stadium wearing a Red Sox T-shirt. Yeah, Butch Hobson. Yeah, a
manager's office. Yeah, a Red Sox T-shirt. OK, so he's with the
Class A Sarasota Red Sox of the Florida State League and not the
Boston Red Sox of the American League, for whom he once played and
later managed. It's a long way from those glory days _ Hobson
slugged 30 homers and drove in 112 runs as Boston's regular third
baseman in 1977 _ and an even longer way from the glory days when
he was Bear Bryant's quarterback at Alabama. But that's how it goes
when a guy is 47 years old and has seen his life almost
disintegrate. (Stoda, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL
</P>
<P>
   FBC-AUBURN _ AUBURN, Ala. _Tommy Tuberville's first spring as
Auburn's head coach has not been an easy one. The former Ole Miss
coach has pushed his players through the most physically-demanding
period they have ever experienced. Tuberville has admitted to
friends that he pushed Auburn's players to find out how many of
them really wanted to stay in the program. It's the kind of
discipline that will be necessary, said Tuberville, if Auburn wants
to get back in the hunt for the SEC's Western Division anytime
soon. (Barnhart, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HORSE RACING
</P>
<P>
   RAC-BISHER-DERBY _ On the 100th birthday of the Kentucky Derby,
23 horses were allowed to squeeze into the starting gate. Anybody
who owned anything with four legs that could whinny wanted to get
his animal on the track. Ten horses spilled over into the betting
field _ that's for those commoners not considered threat enough to
have their own betting slot _ and one of them finished second. It
was more a stampede than a race, and amazing that through all that
traffic a favorite named Cannonade was able to find a way to the
finish line first. Not since the Kentucky Racing Commission limited
the starting slots to 20 has there been a cast more befuddling than
the one going into the gate this weekend. (Bisher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-ARCHDEACON-DERBY _ LOUISVILLE _ Akiko Gothard is most
colorful trainer at the Kentucky Derby. She's a grandmotherly
68-year-old Japanese woman who is the trainer for K One King. Only
eight other women in 125 years of the Kentucky Derby have trained a
Derby horse. None have won. Gothard was born in Tokyo during the
war. Her neighnorhood was bombed. She eventually earned a degree in
English literature, married a U.S. serviceman and moved to
Kentucky. She earned a masters in Psychology at the University of
Kentucky and later served as an interpretor for Japanese horse
buyers who came to Kentucky to buy race horses. In 1976 she bought
yearling John Henry for $1,100. She sold him, but the horse went on
to win $6.6 million. Four years ago she began to train horses.
(Archdeacon, Dayton Daily News). 30.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
