<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOK: NOT BY ITS COVER, BUT BY ITS TITLE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you walked into a bookstore and saw the title ``Trimalchio in
West Egg'' would you be seduced into grabbing it off the shelf? How
about ``The High-Bouncing Lover''? Perhaps a bit more alluring and
at least fathomable. Or ``Gold-Hatted Gatsby.'' Closer maybe, but
it doesn't sing.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after much anguish, it became ``The Great Gatsby.'' But
according to a book about book titles, ``Now All We Need Is a
Title'' (W.W. Norton) by Andre Bernard, Fitzgerald was still
lamenting after ``Gatsby'' was published that he had allowed
himself to be talked out of ``Trimalchio'' (borrowed from
Petronius' ``Cena Trimalchionis,'' a satire about a man of newly
acquired wealth and his vulgar displays of it).
</P>
<P>
   The example shows that of all the tyrannical problems that go
into writing a book, often the one that most hectors the author is
contriving the fitting title. How important is the title anyhow? It
is certainly a consequential part of the sales and marketing
package required to publish a book successfully.
</P>
<P>
   Nan Graham, editor in chief of Scribner, said, ``I'm perfectly
capable of buying a book because it has a great title.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that really ups the stake beyond marketing. Still, there is
no formula for that great title that will reach out from the
bookstalls and bewitch the browser. Generally a title for a
nonfiction book should be as clear as the tapping of a fingernail
on a table top. ``The Majors'' (Little, Brown), the title of John
Feinstein's best seller on golf's four major tournaments, says it
all, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   But fiction, particularly literary fiction, has no rules that
anyone adheres to. Sometimes poetry alone carries the day. What,
for instance, does ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' (Harcourt Brace, by
David Guterson) mean or ``Cold Mountain'' (Atlantic Monthly Press,
by Charles Frazier)? Nothing really. There's a poetry and an
atmosphere about the first and a starkness about the second that's
rather like a punch in the stomach. Both titles evoked a certain
classiness, and both books were huge best sellers, though neither
title indicated much of what was going on between the book's
covers.
</P>
<P>
   Bewildering titles. How about ``An Instance of the Fingerpost''
(Riverhead), Iain Pears' murder mystery set in the 17th century? It
too was a best seller. Hindsight or great creative gamble? Julie
Grau, co-editorial director of Riverhead, said that the title was
``so odd and mysterious that we thought it actually was a selling
point.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if people didn't get it all, they got enough of it,'' she
said. ``It was part of the intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a calculated risk. The idea is to get a title that piques
interest, whether it's ironic, alluringly mysterious, funny, or
musical. After it works, you're a genius.''
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't, it's a quick journey to nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   David Rosenthal, publisher of Simon &AMP; Schuster's trade division,
said ``the title should be memorable and descriptive. As sharp as a
headline; as direct as possible, with as few words as possible. It
can mean the difference between a book being reviewed and bought
and a book you're going to find on the remainder table.'' Still,
who knows if a book failed because its title didn't allow it a
chance? Did the title send the wrong signal? Was it too sad, too
vague?
</P>
<P>
   The naming of a book is often a collaborative effort, starting
with the author but including the editor, the publisher and the
agent. The ``sales rep'' _ that is, the person who must sell the
book to the bookstores _ at times has a say. Unhappy sales reps
make for authors' bad dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Esther Newburg, a literary agent, said that even writers of
``commercial books gravitate toward literary titles. But the best
title is one in which you know exactly what it means.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, she cited ``Difficult Conversations: How to
Discuss What Matters Most,'' saying: ``When the book was being
sold, all the publishers involved not only loved the proposal, but
the title also and that made it so much easier to sell. The sales
rep going into the store with 30 books liked this one.'' (Ms.
Newburg sold the book, by Douglas F. Stone, Bruce Patton and Sheila
Heen, to Viking.)
</P>
<P>
   Generally there is no copyright on a title, so books can have
very similar titles _ something no one wants _ and when there is a
dispute over a title the author usually prevails, particularly with
literary fiction. As Ms. Graham said: ``You can't publish a book
with a title the author doesn't like. You can't start making the
author miserable with this _ there are too many other opportunities
for the author to be made miserable.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal says he tries to use ``gentle persuasion'' to get a
title change, ``but if that fails you bring in the marketing person
who tells the author, `Everything's great about the book but the
title, and that will cost you 20,000 copies.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's a tough and precarious business tampering with an author's
title. Many writers look upon the titling of their book as they do
the naming of a child. The title defines the book for its life and,
unlike a child's name, cannot be changed.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Lemann (``The Fiery Pantheon,'' Scribner), who is now
working on her fifth novel, ``Malaise,'' said that she settles on a
title right from the beginning. ``It sets the tone for the book
from the start, so it is important for me to have the title in my
head.'' She said she gets feedback from her editor and her agent
and from some friends because ``in the title lies the whole point
of the book; it wraps up the mood.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, other authors look upon titles differently. E.L.
Doctorow, for instance, has what he calls ``working titles. They
usually get used up during the course of the book.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that these temporary titles give his work ``a propulsive
capacity. They supply little bursts of inspiration and excitement.
They exhaust themselves and are replaced by others. The last one is
the one that works.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctorow will deliver a new novel to Random House in June, but
he declined to reveal its last driving force.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Hamlet, Prince of Denmark' is really a lousy title, so I
don't speculate anymore on titles,'' Doctorow said.
</P>
<P>
   But let us speculate. What if their covers read, ``Prejudice and
Pride,'' ``Sensibility and Sense,'' ``Peace and War.'' Would they
be as well read this way as vice versa?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1730EDT &QL; 
