<SLUG> BC-KUNDUN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IN SEARCH OF KUNDUN WITH MARTIN SCORSESE': PROFILING THE DALAI
LAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm not one for causes unless it's film preservation,'' Martin
Scorsese observes dryly near the end of Michael Henry Wilson's
documentary film, ``In Search of Kundun With Martin Scorsese.''
Then he hesitantly adds: ``But compassion and love are the only way
to go. The other way is violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The director's remarks illustrate the degree to which the making
of ``Kundun,'' his empathetic biography of the early life of the
14th Dalai Lama, was a labor of devotion and perhaps a kind of
atonement for some of the more brutal imagery in movies like ``Mean
Streets'' and ``Goodfellas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Search of Kundun'' is a valuable and informative footnote
to ``Kundun,'' a visually enthralling film of few words and many
magnificent images conveying the color, mood and spirit of Tibetan
Buddhism. The documentary clarifies the aim of Scorsese's film,
which was not to be a historical epic but to try to capture the
Dalai Lama's spirit of kindness and nonviolence in the face of his
exile and the continuing destruction of Tibetan culture by the
Chinese absorption of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary, which includes interviews with several of the
creative participants in the earlier film (notably missing is
composer Philip Glass), reveals the nuts and bolts of a project
that was filmed in Morocco on some of the same locations Scorsese
used for ``The Last Temptation of Christ,'' with matte background
drawings of the Himalayas evoking the mountainous terrain.
Interspersed with scenes of Scorsese at work are comments by the
Dalai Lama, filmed at his residence in India, and by several
Tibetan cast members.
</P>
<P>
   The film is unapologetically puffy, both in its portrait of the
director as a twinkly avuncular presence on the set and in its
portrait of the Dalai Lama as a kind of living saint. Speaking the
film's final words, the Dalai Lama expresses his wish that people
embrace ``humanity rather than my nation or our nation.'' Yes, but.
. . .
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `IN SEARCH OF KUNDUN WITH MARTIN SCORSESE'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Michael Henry Wilson; directors of
photography, Jean-Jacques Flori and Frederic Vassort; edited by
Rick Blue; music by Ken Lauber; produced by T. Celal, Jean Labib,
Dale Ann Stieber and Wilson; released by In Pictures and
Hollywoodn't Independent Film Distribution.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 84 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: The Dalai Lama, Martin Scorsese, Roger Deakins, Dante
Ferretti, Tenzin Chodon Gyalpo, Lobsang Lhalungpa and Melissa
Mathison.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1733EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
