<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUICE-TASTE-TESTERS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROPICANA PRODUCTS TASTE TESTERS; NO EXPERIENCE REQUIRED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MATTHEW SAUER   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRADENTON, Fla. _ So they've made the juice, now what do they
do?
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Tropicana Products Inc., they bring in a bunch of
people to taste it.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Tropicana recruited its first panel of tasters
from outside the company. Before that, the juice producer ran
various blends and new products by its employees. That contribution
proved too taxing on some employees with other duties, so Tropicana
reached out to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Through newspaper advertising and canvassing area events, the
company found nearly 80 applicants who were then put through a
screening process. The company, which is based in Bradenton, was
interested in how well applicants could taste things, how well they
communicated and how much time they had available.
</P>
<P>
   The company ended up with a group of 13 women and two men who
come in about four times a week and taste juice for two hours at a
time. The pay is modest _ one panelist said he uses the cash to
take his wife out to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Most have become adept at identifying particular flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Stafford, 61, a retired high school social studies teacher
from Cooperstown, N.Y., has learned to taste for different
attributes on different parts of his tongue: sweetness with the tip
and sourness with the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Stafford, whose wife works for Tropicana, said his confidence in
his tasting abilities has grown over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have self-doubt as I try to apply the standards. I think
everyone in the group does,'' Stafford said. ``You debate a lot
with yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   All but one member of the group live in Bradenton and, not
surprisingly for a retirement area, most are over 50. The age of
the tasters was originally thought to be problematic because older
people tend to have reduced senses of smell and taste, but testing
proved that most members of the group have average or
better-than-average tasting capabilities, said Jennifer DiCicco,
the sensory scientist in charge of the tasting panel.
</P>
<P>
   Over two months, panel members got more than 80 hours of
training on how to be tasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them couldn't believe that it could take 80 hours of
training,'' DiCicco said. ``But really, 80 hours isn't enough
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The tasters identify 21 attributes of juice _ such as sweetness,
bitterness or a cooked taste _ and make observations on a scaled
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to teach them how to taste analytically and describe
the flavors in a uniform manner,'' DiCicco said. ``We needed to
make sure they all are using the same words.''
</P>
<P>
   The tasters are not sampling juices to make sure a batch
produced in Tropicana's mammoth plant meets quality standards. That
is accomplished by a separate quality control division.
</P>
<P>
   The panelists taste new blends and formulations such as
Tropicana Pure Premium Tropical Orange, the company's
vitamin-enriched products and Tropicana Twister. The batches are
generally produced at a ``pilot plant'' in Tropicana's technical
center, where juice can be formulated and mixed in small batches
without affecting overall production.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, the taste testers sample ``Brand X,'' meaning
Coca-Cola Co.-owned Minute Maid, the No. 2 juice company behind
Tropicana.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the panel's work coincides with larger samplings
performed by the company in national tastings. But ``the taste
panel can break it down further'' than the national studies,
DiCicco said.
</P>
<P>
   Much like a jury, Tropicana wants impartial and objective
reporting from each member of the panel. ``We wanted people that
were outgoing but not overbearing where they started influencing
other members of the group,'' DiCicco said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no give-and-take between panelists as they taste.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists taste about a dozen 3-ounce samples over two hours. So
the most any particular panelist consumes would be 36 ounces of
juice _ the equivalent of more than four 8-ounce glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Some panelists choose to spit out the juice after a tasting,
much like a wine taster.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists file into a tasting area in half-hour sessions. The
individual juice cups are labeled with numbers. The tasters enter
their findings in a computer system.
</P>
<P>
   After a half-hour of tasting, panelists take a 30-minute break,
during which they may cleanse their palates with unsalted crackers
and water.
</P>
<P>
   That's similar to what wine tasters do when they seek to keep
their palates sensitive to the more than 98 attributes of wine,
including one called ``wet dog,'' said Kristine Nickel, a Tropicana
spokeswoman and wine connoisseur.
</P>
<P>
   Before they come in at either 9:30 or 10 a.m. for a tasting
session, panelists are asked not to use colognes or brush their
teeth an hour before they arrive. Smoking, which deadens taste, is
not an issue because smokers were eliminated from the initial
applicants.
</P>
<P>
   (Matthew Sauer writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
