<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, April 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   So far, 35 inches of snow have fallen in Flagstaff, Ariz.,
during April, which is about 25 inches above normal for the month.
The snowy trend will continue at Flagstaff and the adjacent
mountains of northern Arizona and Nevada on Thursday as a sluggish
low pressure system and its associated cool pocket of air aloft
traverse the region.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a strong pressure difference between the Nevada low
and high pressure over the eastern Pacific will promote gusty winds
over much of the West on Thursday. Indeed, winds will exceed 30
miles an hour in many locations across California and Oregon. At
the same time, strengthening breezes from the southeast will
transport moist air northward though the western Plains and Front
Range of the Rockies, setting the stage for numerous showers and
isolated thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   The ascending air currents associated with a jet stream
disturbance will cause a cold area of rain to fall over the
southern Appalachians and Southeast coast Thursday. Daytime
temperatures will average more than 20 degrees below normal beneath
the thick cloud cover and precipitation. Brisk winds from the east
will add to the day's chill. Farther south, Florida will remain
partly sunny and humid with isolated thunderstorms erupting in the
sultry air.
</P>
<P>
   A large high pressure system over Ontario, Canada, will promote
dry and sunny weather over the Great Lakes and Northeast on
Thursday. An exception will be over eastern New England where moist
air spiraling westward around low pressure near Nova Scotia
produces scattered clouds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Breaking Away
</P>
<P>
   Huge chunks of ice threatened to break away from the shores of
northeastern Alaska on Thursday. This potentially dangerous
situation was caused by strong and persistent winds from the east
associated with the clockwise circulation of air around a high
pressure system building into northwestern Alaska. Such ``polar
easterlies'' are a common feature of the system of winds that blow
over high latitudes. These winds owe their existence to recurrent
high pressure systems that form over the Arctic in response to
heavy cold air near the earth's surface and the weighty convergence
of air overhead. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6720 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-FUNDING-0429-COX     04-28 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-FUNDING-0429-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARTS AND HUMANITIES FUNDING FINDS MORE PATRONS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Peace broke out Wednesday in the culture wars of
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   After chatting amiably with the folksy new chairmen of the
national endowments of the arts and humanities, Republican members
of a key House subcommittee seemed willing to not only continue
funding the agencies but to also boost their budgets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should all be encouraged by the progress that has obviously
been made,'' said Rep. Zach Wamp, R-Tenn., at a hearing of the
Appropriations Subcommittee on the Interior.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, conservative critics have sought to abolish the
National Endowment for the Arts and the National Endowment for the
Humanities. The agencies were haunted politically by their support
for a handful of controversial projects and attacked by legislators
philosophically opposed to taxpayers funding the arts and
humanities. In their third decade of existence, the agencies' very
survival has been at stake in the Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   However, President Clinton has diffused much of the opposition
with his appointments of two folklorists from the heartland to head
the agencies, which critics long contended were elitist and out of
touch with mainstream values.
</P>
<P>
   William Ivey, former director of the Country Music Foundation in
Nashville, has been chairman of the National Endowment for the Arts
for 11 months. William Ferris, former director of the Center for
the Study of Southern Culture at the University of Mississippi, was
named chairman of the National Endowment for the Humanities in late
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The ``two Bills'' were warmly received by the subcommittee that
has the initial review of their requested budget increases from
about $100 million apiece this year to $150 million for each agency
in fiscal year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe that we have unfairly cut their agencies back
and they need to have some growth,'' said Rep. Norman Dicks,
D-Wash. A budget increase ``is overdue for the two endowments,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ivey and Ferris said the endowments' programs have
suffered since their budgets were cut by over a third in 1996 and
kept at about that same level since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the wake of that reduction, the (humanities) endowment was
forced to close down many of its core grant programs, lay off a
quarter of its employees and downsize many of the agency's
functions,'' Ferris testified.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by Congress, the National Endowment for the Arts has
made dramatic changes, said Ivey. Grants are more equitably
distributed among the states. Grants to individual artists have
been largely stopped. Seasonal support and subgrants were also
eliminated to give the National Endowment for the Arts control of
exactly what performances and artists the agency funded.
</P>
<P>
   Ivey said he hoped to move the agency ``to a place of strong
bipartisan support.''
</P>
<P>
   The new policies -- and budget cuts -- have resulted in the
average National Endowment for the Arts grant decreasing from
around $59,000 three years ago to about $28,000 this year, Ivey
said.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   Rather than having to defend their budget requests against a
hostile panel, the chairmen on Wednesday fielded softball questions
and engaged in conversations about Studs Terkel, blues music, cable
TV's History Channel and the need for a museum about First Ladies
-- a project of the wife of subcommittee chairman Ralph Regula,
R-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Wamp even offered advice on how he wanted to be lobbied. ``I'd
rather hear from a dobro player or a quiltmaker than from a
Hollywood star,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the new era of good feelings, though, Congress is
restrained by spending caps, Regula cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   The chairmen said they have contingency plans for continuing
flat budgets or smaller increases than they have requested.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
