<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-GREENFIELD02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Town meeting called on Colorado tragedy
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CNN's Jeff Greenfield was on vacation when the shots rang out in
Columbine High School, but he was far from removed. He's the single
father of a 16-year-old son, David.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really relieved when I went in to see how he was doing
and he was playing the new Major League Baseball (computer) game,''
Greenfield says. ``I think any parent is aware. My son is not the
sort who wanders around in black dressed as a Goth, (but) I'm more
conscious of what he's up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield, CNN's senior analyst, will moderate a 90-minute town
meeting tonight in Champaign-Urbana, Ill. He was chosen not because
he has an adolescent son, but because he's CNN's go-to guy in
situations like this, a pundit who can think on his feet and avoids
easy answers. Champaign-Urbana was chosen not only because it's
home to the University of Illinois (the alma mater of CNN-U.S.
President Richard Kaplan), but because it was not Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Columbine has been done,'' Greenfield says. ``Champaign-Urbana
is not a place where anything has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea, he says, was to get away from the specifics of
Columbine and to get away from the parade of experts who have been
all over television in the last 10 days. Instead, the town meeting
will focus on teenagers and their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 10 days since it happened,'' Greenfield says. ``Now that
there's a certain amount of calm, let's see if we can just talk
with some adolescents and hear what they have to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're talking about a broader kind of conversation.
Anybody who's been through adolescence knows it can be a tough
time. Maybe some parents can share with us if they managed to break
through that distance that, particularly, young boys establish with
their parents.''
</P>
<P>
   The town meeting will feature teen-on-teen interviews from CNN's
Student Bureau, a recent venture by CNN that allows promising young
people to learn reporting. (Little usually ends up on CNN, but it
does happen.)
</P>
<P>
   While the 90-minute show won't be completely expert-free,
Greenfield says, ``the idea is to get away from the usual
suspects.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Listening After Littleton''
</P>
<P>
   7:30 tonight on CNN
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
