<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBUCHI PREPARES FOR U.S. VISIT THAT WILL INCLUDE POLITICS AND
BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi prepared Wednesday for a
meeting with President Clinton, working on his economic policy and
on his pitching arm.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi, who is to leave on Thursday for the first official visit
by a Japanese prime minister to the United States in 12 years, is
expected to throw out the first ball at a Cubs game at Wrigley
Field in Chicago on Saturday. So Obuchi, 61, who said he last threw
a pitch about 50 years ago, spent part of the afternoon in his
backyard with a baseball glove and a former pro pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really worried whether the ball will reach home plate or
not,'' Obuchi said.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the practice session, which Obuchi good-naturedly
allowed reporters to watch, he has good form but not much
consistency. All in all, he seems to have a strong chance of
getting the ball to home plate _ at least by the third bounce.
</P>
<P>
   Other prime ministers have made working trips to Washington, but
this is a more formal official visit and includes stays in Los
Angeles on Thursday night and in Chicago on Friday and Saturday
nights. Then Obuchi is to travel to Washington for talks on Monday
with President Clinton and a White House dinner that evening.
</P>
<P>
   This is a time of relative harmony in American-Japanese
relations, and officials say the main purpose of the summit meeting
is to reaffirm and strengthen the relationship rather than to
resolve any particular disputes. But the backdrop will be Japan's
faltering economy and American insistence that Japan do more to
revive it.
</P>
<P>
   The Group of Seven major industrial nations issued a communique
on Monday calling on Japan to ``implement stimulus measures until
growth is restored, using all available tools.'' But in a meeting
Wednesday with American reporters, Obuchi did not seem to take the
hint; he suggested that Japan has already taken enough action for
now and needs to allow time for results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've adopted numerous measures,'' he said, pointing to
various economic legislation passed in the last year. ``I trust
that favorable effects will emerge.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked specifically whether Japan would consider a supplementary
budget to provide a stronger fiscal stimulus if current steps
proved inadequate, Obuchi poured cold water on the idea, saying,
``At this stage, we have no intention of drawing up a supplementary
budget.''
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized that government spending is only a modest part of
the economy and suggested that there may be only so much that he or
any official can do to revive the economy, which has been in an
on-again-off-again slump since the early 1990s. He noted that the
greatest part of the economy is private consumption, and added,
``We are somewhat concerned that personal consumption so far has
not yet shown a rising curve.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there are some areas where the government can help, like
promoting the housing industry and deregulating the economy. But he
gave no indication that he was planning any dramatic program.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi and Clinton are also to discuss American military bases
on Okinawa, where bases are concentrated and the opposition to them
has traditionally been strongest. But the anti-bases movement in
Japan has lost steam in the last few years, and public support for
the bases and for the military alliance with the United States now
seems stronger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our relations with the United States are the very foundation
of Japanese foreign policy,'' Obuchi said Wednesday. ``My own
perception of Japan-U.S. relations is that they are at their best
and most stable since Japan opened its doors to the outside
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi has long been friendly to America, and Wednesday he
recounted how as a college student in 1963, he visited the United
States for the first time, staying in Washington at the YMCA. The
son of a member of Parliament, Obuchi won a meeting with Robert F.
Kennedy, who was then attorney general, and was given a 1960
Kennedy-for-President tie clip showing a PT-109, the boat John F.
Kennedy commanded when fighting Japan in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by that example, Obuchi said, he has used tie clips in
his own campaigns in Japan. He said he was thinking about wearing
the PT-109 clip on this trip but was afraid he might lose it.
</P>
<P>
   On this trip to Washington, Obuchi will enjoy fancier
accommodation, at Blair House, the official guest residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in those days, the YMCA was the cheapest place in
Washington, $1.50 a night,'' Obuchi said. ``But this time will be
even cheaper. Blair House _ no charge!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
