<SLUG> BC-CIR-DHARMA-HOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNICAL ADVICE IS EASY TO FIND WHEN THE ROAD BECKONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long-Term travelers can easily get information about gaining
access to the Internet and posting their travels from the road.
There are probably hundreds of travelogues on line, and at least
one guidebook publisher, Lonely Planet, also maintains an extensive
message board, the Thorn Tree, at its site (www.lonelyplanet.com).
</P>
<P>
   Many seasoned travelers also like the broad range of information
that is offered at sites like www.travel-library.com, and the
www.roadnews.com site is geared toward people traveling with
laptops. Many people who post tales of their journeys on Web sites
include a ``how we did it'' section that lists technological
information. For a list of Internet cafes abroad, see the
www.netcafeguide.com site.
</P>
<P>
   A site called www.photo.net is useful for both improving photo
skills and building personal Web pages. Another site at
www.microship.com/technomads is filled with travelogues.
</P>
<P>
   What about lugging a computer on the road? Marc Brosius, a
former long-term traveler who runs the popular Round-the-World
Guide on line (www.travel-library &QC; .com/rtw/html), recommends that
travelers stick to a laptop that weighs no more than two or three
pounds, like the Sony Vaio.
</P>
<P>
   While smaller machines can often run on AA batteries, travelers
who want to use a digital camera and edit their photos should
choose machines with relatively large screens, of at least 10
inches, to insure that they can see enough of each picture to edit
properly, Brosius said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other long-term travelers, Brosius recommends taking a
digital camera on the road, to avoid photo development hassles on
the road and to be able to post pictures quickly and easily at Web
sites. To avoid problems like blurry action shots, he recommends
that travelers stick to machines with at least one million pixels
of resolution.
</P>
<P>
   What about software? Brosius advises that beginners, in
particular, should keep it simple. For travelers who want to write
Web pages with interesting layouts and who do not want to have to
do their own HTML coding _ the common computer language of the Web
_ he recommends sticking to a product like Adobe's Page Mill. He
likes Photodeluxe, also made by Adobe, for photo editing.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone hardware abroad is still a problem. Travelers still
complain about ancient phone lines and phones that are hard-wired
to the wall without phone jacks. Many travelers carry adapter kits
like those made by Road Warrior International (www.warrior.com) or
Teleadapt (www.teleadapt.com).
</P>
<P>
   Internet access from around the world has improved significantly
lately, as companies like America Online and International Business
Machines have set up global networks. AOL offers access in more
than 100 countries, while IBM offers access in 53 countries,
through more than 1,300 access numbers.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 of those numbers operate at modem speeds of 56K,
unlike the 33K speeds that are more common through other Internet
service providers, a company spokesman said. Most AOL numbers, a
spokeswoman said, operate at 56K.
</P>
<P>
   A company in Mountain View, Calif., called iPass says it has
some 3,200 access points in 150 countries (www.ipass.com). The
iPass company tries to provide Internet access through local
telephone calls wherever possible. But travelers have to sign up
with an ISP to get access to iPass.
</P>
<P>
   The iPass service is not available in Vietnam or North Korea,
and some travelers have reported access problems in countries like
Thailand and France.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Chakmakian, an iPass co-founder, said her company was
trying to iron out access problems, especially in Thailand, China
and India. Some computer users may have modems that are
incompatible with some countries' phone systems, Ms. Chakmakian
said, and iPass, like many ISPs, is trying to alert its users to
potential modem problems. A 56K modem, for example, may not connect
through a slower access number.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius recommends thorough planning for a trip. ``I see a lot
of people who at the last minute buy their equipment and who have
no idea of the full range of it,'' he said. ``Also, you have to
work the bugs out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
