<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-CLUSTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AGENCY ACCUSED OF WITHHOLDING VITAL INFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Armed with a public-records request, an
anti-nuclear group recently began sifting through file cabinets of
the state Department of Health Services.
</P>
<P>
   What the group found has created a fissure between the
Legislature and state health officials, who are being accused of
conspiring with corporate interests and withholding crucial health
information from the public.
</P>
<P>
   The Committee to Bridge the Gap uncovered a survey showing
higher-than-normal rates of lung cancer in an area around a
Rocketdyne Corp. plant near Simi Valley outside Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Rocketdyne builds propulsion systems for NASA space shuttles,
and has been under intense scrutiny over health issues.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery of the cancer study, which health officials dismissed
as incomplete and flawed, has nevertheless enraged some lawmakers
and added fuel to another debate over whether Health Services tried
to manipulate the Legislature on a tobacco-related issue.
</P>
<P>
   The National Smokers Alliance, which is funded mainly by the
cigarette industry, is wondering why a Field Poll commissioned by
Health Services was kept secret as the Legislature was debating a
ban on smoking in bars.
</P>
<P>
   Health Services paid $80,000 for two March 1998 polls from the
respected, San Francisco-based Field Research Corp. But state
officials released only the poll showing overwhelming public
support for the bar smoking ban.
</P>
<P>
   The second, less-favorable poll of bar owners and workers was
not released _ until it was accidentally mailed to the
Virginia-based National Smokers Alliance, which quickly cranked up
its public relations machine after reading it.
</P>
<P>
   The two controversies have prompted an investigation by the
Joint Legislative Audit Committee and spurred the administration of
Gov. Gray Davis to appoint Ed Lowry, director of Toxic Substances
Control, to examine the allegations about Rocketdyne.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are just more examples of what we perceive to be a real
problem within the department,'' said Assemblyman Scott Wildman,
D-Los Angeles, chairman of the audit committee, ``a department that
has put more obstacles in the way of making legislation rather than
making it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Four months after his inauguration, Davis still hasn't appointed
a director for the Department of Health Services, one of the
state's largest agencies.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the governor said Davis was interviewing
candidates but had no date set for an appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Career health officials have been left to defend their
department and practices that took shape under two Republican
governors. They say they're under fire from two special interests
trying to influence policies within the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``One group is saying we've been too cozy with Rocketdyne and
have not gone after them and the other side is saying we've been
far too tough on a legitimate business, the tobacco industry,''
said Dr. Jim Stratton, deputy director for prevention. ``The
Department of Health Services plays it straight down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Legislature isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Lou Papan, D-Millbrae, said he wanted an
investigation into whether Health Services deliberately withheld
the critical tobacco poll and released the more favorable one just
two days before a legislative hearing last year on overturning the
ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned if we have state agencies that are not being
objective,'' said Papan, who supports giving bars the choice of
whether to ban smoking.
</P>
<P>
   But Stratton and Donald Lyman, chief of the chronic diseases
division, said the poll of bar and tavern owners was for internal
use, so field workers and health officials could better understand
their views as they explained the new law.
</P>
<P>
   Lyman said releasing the first poll came in connection with a
new series of television advertising promoting the law, which
coincidentally, he said, came the same day of the legislative
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of stuff we do,'' Lyman said. ``There are piles
and piles of data, and we release in a formal sense a small part of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the more comprehensive Rocketdyne investigation, the audit
committee will look at more than just the shelved cancer study.
</P>
<P>
   Recently released electronic mail messages and memos suggest
that Rocketdyne was trying to influence the make-up of an advisory
panel created in the early 1990s to examine worker safety at its
plant.
</P>
<P>
   Health Services officials say they wanted to start looking at
potential health problems in the community, not just among workers,
and they began talking with Rocketdyne about which scientists and
community members should be on the reconstructed board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recommended that DHS form a new group of limited scope and
time duration,'' Rocketdyne consultant Susan Santos wrote in a Dec.
18, 1997, memo that recommends the state play a leadership role in
any future studies and not use the old advisory board, which had a
contentious relationship with Rocketdyne.
</P>
<P>
   Santos, who works for Massachusetts-based Focus Group, suggested
contacting local homeowners associations that might want to
nominate someone to the advisory panel and inviting people to a
Rocketdyne-sponsored workshop on environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   Health Services officials admit wanting to control the
scientific review and budget of any future health studies, as it
did in a previous Rocketdyne study.
</P>
<P>
   But officials said they want to add better-suited scientists to
the advisory panel, specialists in water tables and air quality,
not kick off the old members.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no evidence uncovered showing a direct response,
favorable or otherwise, from Health Services to Rocketdyne
regarding the Santos memo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them verbally, `Thank you for your opinion,' and
that's it,'' said Dr. Raymond Neutra, chief of the department's
Environmental and Occupational Disease Control division.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Assemblywoman Sheila Kuehl, D-Santa Monica, and members of
the advisory board believe the department and Rocketdyne have a
suspiciously cozy relationship. Kuehl wants three top Health
Services officials fired because of their handling of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Rocketdyne, for example, was given copies of two comprehensive
studies conducted by the University of California at Los Angeles on
illness and cancer rates near its Simi Hills plant. When the most
recent study was released two weeks ago, the company was prepared
that day with a detailed rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   And Kuehl said she phoned Davis' secretary of Health and
Welfare, Grantland Johnson, two weeks ago and told him she was
about to release the cancer study uncovered by the anti-nuclear
group in Emeryville. The next day, during her press conference,
Rocketdyne again was ready with a response, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Kuehl said the department should have been alarmed at
the cancer study that was filed away in Emeryville. Although
everyone involved believes it wasn't substantial enough to reach
any conclusions, it contained one red flag.
</P>
<P>
   Lung cancer rates were going up, according to the review, but
bladder cancer rates were not, suggesting something other than
tobacco was causing the spike in lung cancer. (Studies have shown
that lung cancer caused by tobacco is often associated with bladder
cancer.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of the evidence points to a kind of collusion
between DHS and Rocketdyne,'' Kuehl said.
</P>
<P>
   Neutra, however, said the cancer study wasn't worth pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was based on about six hours worth of work and didn't
take into account smoking rates or other data from the community
besides who has cancer and where they live.
</P>
<P>
   And Stratton said it was common practice for state agencies to
share scientific studies. Indeed, the state auditor always lets
groups or individuals under scrutiny review its reports and offer
rebuttal letters. Stratton said it helps make the science better,
but that Health Services is never under any obligation to change
anything.
</P>
</TEXT>
