<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TONY-AWARDS-ART-2NDTA     04-28 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONY-AWARDS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: beyond reproach.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ashton Springer, who produced ``T.O.B.A.,'' said he was baffled
by the committee's decision not to consider his show about the
heyday of black vaudeville, which closed three days after its
petition was rejected. ``Cabaret'' was ruled eligible in the same
theater last season, the Kit Kat Klub, formerly Henry Miller's
Theater, on West 43rd Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make up new rules as they go along,'' Springer said. ``If
it's something they want to do, it will happen. If it's something
they don't want to do, it won't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony officials said the reason for the ``T.O.B.A.'' decision was
that the Kit Kat Klub failed to apply for Tony status in the year
since ``Cabaret.'' They said that the Roundabout, producer of
``Cabaret,'' simply used the Kit Kat Klub for its authentic
nightclub environment, although it has a Tony-eligible theater of
its own, Stage Right at the Criterion Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the right decision,'' Somlyo said. ``On the surface it
looks horrendous. But you have to go just a quarter of an inch
deeper.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ``Wit'' petition, Hughes argued that the producers tried
hard to find a home on Broadway last fall and had raised a million
dollars for such a move yet were rebuffed because the play deals
with a woman dying of ovarian cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found ourselves with more than adequate capitalization, a
sheaf of unanimous raves and the doors to every available Broadway
theater slamming in our faces as we listened to a refrain of `Too
depressing,''' Hughes wrote in the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Gabay, the general manager of ``Wit,'' said he knew the deck
was stacked against the show when he and Hughes faced the
administration committee. ``Why would the majority of people in
that room, who had other plays represented on Broadway that would
be in direct competition, want `Wit' to be eligible?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The committee includes producers with competing shows and
members of the Actors' Equity Association. There are also people
like Stone, who left the room when the committee voted on
eligibility for his rewrite of ``Annie Get Your Gun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tony rules specify that committee members must abstain from
votes in which they have an interest, although they may participate
in discussions of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Several committee members said personal concerns were set aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee, despite having agenda after agenda, has
functioned fairly well,'' said Emanuel Azenberg, one of the
producers of ``The Iceman Cometh.'' ``They vote almost always with
some logic.''
</P>
<P>
   The logic at work in the case of ``Wit,'' several committee
members said, was clear-cut: Only Broadway shows are eligible, and
``Wit'' is off-Broadway, at the Union Square Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Robert Whitehead, a longtime producer, the administration
committee is scheduled to meet Thursday to consider his proposal to
give ``Wit'' a special commendation at the Tony ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   But others in the theater say ``Wit'' is no special case. Other
acclaimed off-Broadway plays have been ineligible for Tony
consideration, like ``How I Learned to Drive'' and ``Three Tall
Women,'' both of which won Pulitzers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of shows that can't find Broadway theaters,''
said Jed Bernstein, executive director of the league. ``So the idea
that you would be eligible for Tonys because you  &UR; want &LR;  to be on
Broadway, that seems sort of odd.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether off-Broadway productions should be included for Tony
consideration raises questions about the cost to off-Broadway
producers and the logistical difficulty of having Tony voters see
all the shows. Some off-Broadway producers have argued against
their own inclusion on grounds that already meager potential
profits would be considerably reduced if they had to pay union
scale or give free seats to Tony voters.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the administration committee said they might
someday consider the possibility of creating a special Tony Award
for off-Broadway, the way they created one for regional theater in
1976.
</P>
<P>
   But others are adamant about keeping off-Broadway out of the
Tony mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very expensive to mount a Broadway musical; it
might cost $10 million,'' said Rocco Landesman president of
Jujamcyn Theaters who sits on the administration committee and
unsuccessfully argued against the Roundabout becoming Tony eligible
in 1991. ``I don't see why someone who puts up a musical for $1.98
gets the same privileges automatically. We've been handing out Tony
eligibility like candy, and as far as I'm concerned it has to
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Another question has to do with Tony Award voters themselves.
More than 800 producers, general managers, theater owners and
others are eligible to vote. Many of them have not been active in
the theater for years, yet as long as they pay dues to the league,
$1,000 a year, they retain their voting status. Proponents of
stricter membership rules call it the cheapest theater subscription
in town, given that each voter gets two tickets to every show on
Broadway: a $5,000 value, one producer estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Azenberg said it was costing him $150,00 in free tickets for
``Iceman'' alone. ``You have to maintain the qualifications,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Voters sign their ballots pledging to have voted only for plays
after having seen all the nominees in a given category, but many in
the theater are skeptical. ``What it is is a freebie list,'' said
one producer.
</P>
<P>
   Azenberg said the management committee was considering more
stringent criteria for voter eligibility, although this could cut
into the membership fees that support the league.
</P>
</TEXT>
