<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6759 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV0     04-28 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV02-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GORE PROBLEM: WARTIME VICTORY DOES NOT PRODUCE TRIUMPH AT POLLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 2)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Armed conflict in the Balkans has compounded the
problems that Vice President Al Gore faces in seeking to become
Bill Clinton's White House successor.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not simply his risk in being loyal to a president
and a policy that could be in disrepute with a majority of
Americans by the time voters journey to the polls in November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it the danger that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
will outlast the determination of the NATO allies and emerge
victorious from the confrontation over Kosovo, thus boosting the
presidential hopes of such Republicans as Dan Quayle, Patrick
Buchanan and Malcolm S. ``Steve'' Forbes, who have been fiercely
critical of Clinton's Balkans policy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's most dangerous curse may be his service to a president in
a time of armed conflict abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Whether America and NATO win or lose in their drive to provide a
safe haven for hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo,
the Democrat who seeks to follow Clinton as president must overcome
a powerful 20th century precedent.
</P>
<P>
   Simply stated, it is that war _ with two major exceptions _ has
not benefited the political party of the presidents who have
presided over lengthy military engagements abroad.
</P>
<P>
   One exception came in the aftermath of World War II. Franklin D.
Roosevelt was at the beginning of his fourth term, and victory over
Nazi Germany was at hand when he died at Warm Springs, Ga., in
April 1945.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, the Democrats lost control of Congress. But
FDR's successor, Harry Truman, in serving three years and nine
months of Roosevelt's unexpired four-year term, had stamped his own
brand on the presidency and in 1948 won the most amazing upset
victory in the history of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The other exception came in 1972, when President Richard Nixon,
who had expanded the Vietnam War into Cambodia and Laos, won
re-election by carrying 49 of the 50 states over Democrat George
McGovern.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the party of the president prosecuting a war has lost
the White House in the succeeding election.
</P>
<P>
   The latest victim of that trend was Republican George Bush, who
had poll ratings of around 90 percent early in 1991 when U.S.-led
allied forces routed Iraq's Saddam Hussein in the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Bush should have been helped also by the fact that he was in the
Oval Office when the Cold War, which had occupied every president
from Truman to Ronald Reagan, finally ended with the collapse of
communist regimes in Poland, East Germany, Czechoslovakia, Romania
and even the Soviet Union itself.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his enlightened leadership in foreign affairs, Bush
lost his 1992 reelection bid to Clinton. The Democrat understood
that old-fashioned bread-and-butter issues still were vital to
Americans, and he focused his campaign on criticizing Bush for the
faltering economy.
</P>
<P>
   An additional problem for Gore is that millions of Americans
find it difficult to see him as anything other than a No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Bush in 1988 was the first candidate since Martin Van Buren in
1836 to be elected president directly from the vice presidency, and
his success may have owed more to the feeble campaign run by
Democrat Michael Dukakis than to Bush's own efforts.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that Nixon served as vice president before becoming
president. But he failed in his first try in 1960 and had to wait
eight years to achieve his goal.
</P>
<P>
   The political parties that controlled the White House in World
War I, the early part of the Vietnam War and the conflicts in Korea
and the Persian Gulf all lost the presidency either while
hostilities were in progress or after they had ceased. It made
little difference that in some instances, the defeated candidate
was more qualified for the presidency than his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   A week before World War I ended victoriously for America and its
allies in November 1918, voters rejected President Woodrow Wilson's
public appeal for reelection of a Democratic Senate, which would
determine the fate of agreements emanating from the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they handed the GOP a one-vote margin in that body.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Wilson sailed to Europe to take part in the peace
negotiations that produced the Treaty of Versailles and Wilson's
most treasured dream, the League of Nations. After returning to
America, the president embarked on a nationwide speaking campaign
on behalf of the League. But he was felled by a paralytic stroke
and eventually witnessed the defeat of the League in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In 1920, voters elected Ohio Republican Sen. Warren G. Harding
to the presidency over Ohio Democratic Gov. James Cox, who
supported American participation in the League.
</P>
<P>
   When the 1952 presidential election rolled around, Truman was
ending his presidential tenure, and Americans were in the midst of
the Korean conflict. Although peace talks were under way, the
fighting had not ended and the Democratic presidential nominee,
Adlai Stevenson, was overwhelmingly defeated by the GOP standard
bearer, Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower, a beloved World War II hero.
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnam situation in 1968 was similar for the Democrats.
Like Truman, Lyndon Johnson had taken himself out of the
presidential race and launched negotiations to end the war. But the
nation was bitterly divided over the continuing conflict, and Nixon
defeated Johnson's vice president, Hubert Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Nixon finally withdrew American combat troops from
Vietnam in 1973, the war did not end until North Vietnam overran
South Vietnam in 1975. Nixon, meanwhile, had resigned in 1974,
disgraced by the Watergate scandal. Vice President Gerald Ford, who
succeeded him as president, pardoned him for his Watergate
offenses. Then, a year after America's loss in Vietnam, Ford was
defeated by Democrat Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Vietnam had been a U.S. triumph, Ford might have lost
anyway. As other presidents learned, winning has to be the goal in
waging war against a foreign foe, but victory on the battlefield
does not guarantee victory for the wartime party the next time
voters go the polls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
