<SLUG> BC-GUNS-REACTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS, LEGAL EXPERTS QUESTION CLINTON'S GUN PROPOSALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH E. IGOE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   One week after the Colorado high school
shootings, President Clinton proposed gun-control legislation that
would hold negligent parents liable when their children commit
crimes with guns.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But Clinton's suggestion brought questions and criticism in
Kansas and Missouri among prosecutors, politicians and law
professors. Legislatures in both states have no plans to pursue
similar state laws.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his omnibus crime package announced Tuesday, Clinton
pushed numerous proposals, including mandatory prison sentences of
three to 10 years and $10,000 fines for adults, including parents,
who allow children access to guns.
</P>
<P>
   The adult could be held liable whenever a juvenile crime was
committed and the adult ``knowingly or recklessly allowed it to
occur,'' a White House spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's parental liability proposal amounts to a
``political gesture'' and a knee-jerk response to a high-profile
crime, said Johnson County District Attorney Paul Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal judicial system is already overwhelmed,'' he said.
``It's hard for me to imagine they'll be able to handle a lot of
those cases.''
</P>
<P>
   In such cases, prosecutors face a high burden of proof, Morrison
said. ``The raging negligent parent is what you'd be looking for,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Compassion for the shooter's parents combined with that high
legal standard would make prosecutors hesitant to file cases, said
University of Kansas law professor Roscoe Howard, a former federal
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be hard for cops and prosecutors to walk in there and
say: `You're under indictment,' '' Howard said. ``In this
situation, everyone seems like a victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than drafting laws that blame parents, Jackson County
Prosecutor Bob Beaird said, the focus should be on violence
prevention programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be getting to kids before they reach this point,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The legal system already can penalize parents of lawbreakers.
Civil law provides ways to make parents pay damages or fines when
their children commit crimes, said Mary Kisthardt, a law professor
at the University of Missouri-Kansas City. Civil cases are easier
to prove than criminal ones, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Constitutional questions also surround a proposal that could
jail people for a crime someone else committed, Kisthardt said. The
proposal ``might satisfy politicians and the public, but it might
not be held up by the courts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides addressing parental responsibility, the president's
proposal would raise the legal age for possession of a handgun from
18 to 21 and treat sales of explosives, such as dynamite and
blasting caps, the same as guns under the Brady law.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Democratic leaders are counting on outrage over last
week's shooting rampage at Columbine High School that left 15 dead
to help push the proposal through this year.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri and Kansas, state lawmakers have shown little
interest this year in passing bills similar to the president's
suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Key Kansas lawmakers said no measure like Clinton's had been
introduced or considered. With only days left in this year's
legislative session, they said, it is doubtful the issue will even
come up.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Tim Emert, an Independence Republican,
said passing such legislation would be ``extremely difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tim Carmody, an Overland Park Republican and vice chairman
of the House Judiciary Committee, said criminal law was based on
intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the bare fact of giving a gun to a child shouldn't be
criminal,'' he said. ``Intent is everything. To say that someone
else should be criminally responsible for the evil act of another
is kind of scary.''
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, legislation was introduced earlier that would have
allowed prosecutors to charge gun owners with a felony if a minor
obtained the gun and killed or seriously injured someone. That
proposal got little support at a public hearing and has languished
in committee since February.
</P>
<P>
   Although a home environment is often the easiest place to point
fingers after a child commits an unthinkable crime, it isn't the
parents who pulled the trigger, Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to make your children even-tempered people. But you
are kind of scared, because your kids are their own people. They
make decisions on their own,'' said Howard, himself the father of
two young boys. ``But folks now want some kind of punishment. They
are all grabbing for their pound of flesh.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
