<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6769 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELDERLY-DRIVERS-KAN &LR;      04-28 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-DRIVERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETENCE OF OLDER DRIVERS A TOUCHY ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Evelyn White, 84, had driven her car for 68 years without an
accident _ until one chilly day last December when she hit a pickup
truck.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a minor fender bender. But the crash jolted her into
reassessing her own driving skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I couldn't hear so good anymore and, well, little
things are going wrong with my body,'' she said. ``It's time for me
to stop driving.''
</P>
<P>
   She won't renew her license when it expires in June.
</P>
<P>
   Although White decided to stop driving on her own, many of this
country's aging drivers stay behind the wheel long after it's safe.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with the problem, Missouri in January enacted a new law
that is being hailed as a national model for how to tackle this
sensitive safety issue.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's law, which relies on impairment rather than age, has
won support from advocates for the elderly, from AARP to the
Alzheimer's Association.
</P>
<P>
   Other states, which may have been reluctant to yank the licenses
of impaired drivers whose skills have deteriorated over the years,
have contacted Missouri about its new law.
</P>
<P>
   Under Missouri's law, anyone can confidentially report an
impaired driver and the state will determine whether they should
keep driving. Those who file reports are also granted immunity from
prosecution, and the law provides penalties for fraudulent reports.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, 293 Missourians have filled out the forms, now
available at all driver's license offices.
</P>
<P>
   Once a claim is filed, the state can require the driver to
re-take the driver's license exam, including the road test. Drivers
who fail the test can opt to retake it later.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, residents can write the state a letter about an
impaired driver, then a doctor must determine whether a person is
competent to drive. But doctors are sometimes loath to report a
patient because they are not shielded from prosecution, according
to some advocates for the elderly.  &LR; brk:Numbers growing  &LR; tx:Getting
unsafe older drivers to give up their licenses has long been a
delicate subject. And the ranks of older drivers will only grow in
coming years. Within the next two decades, the number of licensed
drivers age 75 or older will zoom from 17 million to 50 million,
according to the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, traffic fatalities increase sharply after age 70,
and drivers age 75 years or older are involved in more fatal
crashes per mile driven than any other age group except teens,
according to a 1996 study by the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   As persons age, their vision and hearing often dim. Reflexes
slow. Arthritis can make looking over the shoulder a painful
experience. The rate of metabolism decreases, extending the effects
of many medications. All of these problems can make driving more
precarious.
</P>
<P>
   Some senior drivers aren't aware of the physical changes. Some
suffer dementia and other mental illnesses that affect their
judgment. For those people, driving could be a death sentence for
themselves or anyone they encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, family members could do little except take away
the car keys from a loved one or dismantle the car itself. Just
bringing up the topic to a spouse, a parent or grandparent can be
painful for families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Driving is often people's last bit of independence,'' said Kim
Collins, executive director of the Alzheimer's Association
Heartland Chapter in Kansas City. ``It's especially hard for a man
to give up his license. Families don't want to be evil or mean, but
they go through torture worrying about what could happen, and what
they should do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Missouri enacted its law, doctors were reluctant to
report a patient because of possible repercussions, said Martin
Zehr, a neuropsychologist at Research Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some doctors were also afraid they'd be sued for libel,'' he
said. ``With the old law, when doctors did call about a patient,
they'd get the local Department of Revenue's assurances that it
would do something and it would promise to follow up. But the
patients would usually keep driving.''
</P>
<P>
   With the new law, the forms are confidential. Zehr, who helped
lobby for the Missouri bill, reported a difficult patient with
dementia in February. Within days, his patient was notified to
retake his driving test. After failing the test twice, the patient
decided on his own to give up driving. His family was ecstatic,
Zehr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In dementia cases, doctors always try to reason first with
their patient and then with the family,'' he said. ``But that
doesn't work in hard cases where the patient sees nothing wrong
with themselves. I feel better now about seeing the information on
paper and I know it's being followed up. Plus, a doctor can now
help the family by being the `bad guy,' without fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon and Karen Suroff pushed for the Missouri law after their
son died in a 1993 wreck caused by a 91-year-old man with senile
dementia.
</P>
<P>
   The man had driven the wrong way down Interstate 70. When police
caught up with him some 250 miles later, he and his wife were
sitting on the roadside, with no memory of the accident.  &LR; brk:More
than just age  &LR; tx:The Missouri law has won support from AARP
because people can't lose their driving privileges based on age.
Age advocates praise the law for giving people the chance to regain
their licenses if their medical condition improves or if they learn
how to compensate for it.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at the Rehabilitation Institute in Kansas City
therapists find adaptive driving devices like a left-foot
accelerator pedal or a hand-control on a steering wheel to help
people with visual, physical or cognitive impairments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes as people age they start having more medical
complications like strokes or amputations, but that doesn't mean
they have to stop driving,'' said Mary Schwartz, an occupational
therapist at the institute.
</P>
<P>
   The real difficulty with curbing any at-risk driver is that
states do not have adequate driving tests, said Audrey Straight of
AARP.
</P>
<P>
   License testing only screens the most obvious problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, on the vision tests, people with 200 eyesight
won't pass, but if they have some sort of problem with peripheral
vision or depth perception the tests won't necessarily pick that
up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And fewer states do on-the-road testing for renewals, she said,
to save money and shorten lines in the license bureaus. In
Missouri, people renew their licenses every three years _ and the
state may decide before May 14 to extend that to every six years.
Kansans renew their licenses every six years.  &LR; brk:Classes
available  &LR; tx:Seniors can learn to compensate for diminishing
abilities through driving refresher courses, like AARP's ``55
Alive//Mature Driving'' program. The class costs $8 and can earn
graduates a lower rate from their insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent class in Sugar Creek, instructor Ed Moran talked to
33 seniors about seat belts and airbags, grandchildren and
left-turns, and how to set limits on driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of things we did in our younger years that's not
logical to attempt today,'' he said to the class. ``But you can
still keep driving if you know your limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday there will be a time when you'll decide it's time to
quit,'' he continued. ``Start making plans now, so you'll be
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Evelyn White did. She gathered information on bus
routes and carpools and talked to her family about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a hard decision to stop and I'm sure that I'm
going to miss it,'' she admitted. ``But I'm doing it before I
actually have to, so that my son won't have to go through that
worry.''
SIDEBAR Driving tips for seniors
</P>
<P>
   Michael Seaton, of Washington D.C., and the creator of AARP's
``55-Alive/Mature Driving'' class offers the following suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   Take a driver re-training or refresher class. Driving laws have
changed quite a bit since most seniors first became licensed to
drive.
</P>
<P>
   See an eye doctor regularly. If night vision is a problem, limit
driving to daytime only.
</P>
<P>
   Because age cause declining depth perception and peripheral
vision, make left hand turns and lane changes a group project.
</P>
<P>
   Plan your route ahead of time to avoid confusion; drivers
frequently have less than a one-half second to avoid a collision.
</P>
<P>
   Buy a bigger car. Size offers more protection in accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Always wear your seatbelt, and remember that grandchildren in
carseats sit in the back.
</P>
<P>
   Check with your doctor of pharmacist to determine side-effects
of medications. If you are taking more than one prescription or
even an over-the-counter drug, make sure your doctor knows about
all of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
