<HEADER>
A6786 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-2TAKES     04-28 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALCULATORS THAT OFFER MORE THAN THE SOLUTION 
WHEN THE MODEM HOGS THE PHONE LINE 
IF YOU CAN STAND THE ADS, THE VOICE MAIL IS FREE  
GAME MAKERS ON THE DEFENSIVE 
LATEST HANDHELD ELECTRONIC ORGANIZER
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As soon as handheld calculators appeared in classrooms,
educators warned that the devices would undermine the learning of
mathematics. Now at least one major calculator maker, Casio,
acknowledges that the doomsayers were right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calculators in general have become a crutch,'' said Jim Gross,
director of marketing for Casio's educational products unit. ``Some
students are just spitting out answers but not getting a grasp of
the concepts behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Casio's proposal for solving the problem is, well, a
calculator. The Casio Algebra FX 2.0 promises to teach while it is
crunching numbers by offering two types of tutoring. The first uses
graphs to display each of the calculations the machine is making to
solve the algebraic problem punched into its keyboard. The other
allows students to work out the solution step by step and corrects
their efforts along the way.
</P>
<P>
   While the calculator, which costs $149, is designed for students
in grades 7 to 12, Gross said he expected that it would also be
welcomed by mathematically challenged parents who were not able to
help with their children's homework.
</P>
<P>
   _ IAN AUSTEN
</P>
<P>
   Answering Calls Online
</P>
<P>
   Each Internet user with a single telephone line is always
plagued by the suspicion that an important caller is trying to get
through while the modem is hogging the phone connection. Now such
surfers can develop a special form of multitasking anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Call Manager _ a service developed by Infointeractive,
based in Halifax, Nova Scotia _ is offering a pop-up menu that
identifies incoming callers and offers a chance to complete the
voice connection through the Net itself.
</P>
<P>
   The service, which costs between $4 and $7 a month, diverts
incoming voice calls to a special Internet server that in turn
sends caller ID messages to the user's computer screen. A user can
then instruct the server to ignore the call, take a voice-mail
message or disconnect the modem and put the caller through to a
conventional phone almost instantly.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Infointeractive introduced a fourth option:
Recipients can take calls over the Net, using the speakers and
microphones on their computers. Given the problems that plague
voice transmission over Internet calls through dial-up PC modems,
Infointeractive's president, Bill McMullin, isn't promising much.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that most people will still revert to the
phone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ IAN AUSTEN
</P>
<P>
   Patience Rewarded
</P>
<P>
   A free voice-mail system is now available to anyone with the
patience to listen to advertising spots over the phone. The system,
called Echobuzz, is aimed at teen-agers _ a market that just might
be willing to endure the advertising in exchange for a place to
leave messages that can't be heard by Mom or Dad.
</P>
<P>
   People who want to register for the service go to
www.echobuzz.com, where they fill out forms asking for contact
information and details about their favorite music, sports and
hobbies. The advertisements _ which last from two to 10 seconds _
will be tailored to users' interests. ``A guy, for example, won't
get an ad for the newest, coolest shade of lipstick,'' said
Kimberly Goolsby, an Echobuzz spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   After signing up for Echobuzz, users will receive e-mail
messages containing personal identification numbers that give them
access to their accounts. To leave or receive messages, members
must dial in to the toll-free number _ (877) 324-6289. Messages may
be left only for other Echobuzz members.
</P>
<P>
   A start-up company called Blue Diamond Software, based in
Irvine, Calif., developed Echobuzz. Although the system is designed
to earn revenue from advertisers, it was also developed to be a way
to test Blue Diamond's speech-recognition software, said the
company's president and chief executive, Blaine Ung.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
<P>
   In the Aftermath of Littleton
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the killings of 12 students and a teacher in
Littleton, Colo., last week, many commentators and some parents are
wondering aloud about what influence _ if any _ video games may
have had on the actions of the two gunmen, Eric Harris and Dylan
Klebold. Not surprisingly, video game manufacturers are reluctant
to be drawn into the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no comment on it at all,'' said John Carmack, the
co-founder of Id Software, which makes the games Quake and Doom, in
which the object is to use an array of weapons to kill and blow up
as many enemies as possible. Harris was known not only to play Doom
but to program levels for it. A profile Harris may have written for
his America Online account lists Doom as one of his hobbies. And on
a Web site attributed to him, a diatribe ends with the ominous
words, ``Doom will become reality!''
</P>
<P>
   Other game makers and industry observers said video games should
not be held responsible for violence. Rob Legg, marketing manager
for Ion Storm, a company started by John Romero, the co-creator of
Doom, said the game industry was getting a bad rap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play these games and they do not make me take a sawed-off
shotgun to somebody,'' Legg said, adding that Ion Storm also
planned to make vivid first-person shooter games.
</P>
<P>
   While game industry observers have said Doom is being unfairly
blamed for the Colorado incident, one did acknowledge an eerie
similarity between the attack last week and the game play itself,
which puts the player in the role of a first-person shooter on a
rampant attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that when that guy is there going down the hall with
a gun, it looks pretty much like the view he has when he's playing
Doom or Quake,'' said Vince Broady, the editorial director of
Gamespot, an online gaming publication based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   _ MATT RICHTEL
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Aiming at the Younger Set
</P>
<P>
   The success of high-end handheld devices like the Palm
organizers and the various flavors of Windows CE has inspired a
number of imitators. The latest, and the one most likely to have an
impact outside the world of business gadget freaks, is the Helio
from Vtech. If the name Vtech doesn't register, go to any toy store
and look at the electronic toys in the educational section. Vtech
makes 60 percent of all the electronic devices for children sold in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Helio, which was introduced last week is aimed at those who
lust after a Palm V or a Compaq Aero but can't afford the $500
price tag. The company will start shipping it on June 15. The Helio
sells for $199 and is only available, for now, on Vtech's Web site
(thunder.kelly.com/vtech.storefront). Taking a cue from the success
of the Apple iMac, the Helio comes in a rainbow of eight colors.
</P>
<P>
   Vtech culled the best from the Palm and Windows CE devices; it
has all the standard functions of both the Palms and CE _ phone
book, calendar, to-do list, memo pad, calculator and an e-mail
reader. It has a Windows personal information manager that allows
you to enter data on the PC and then synchronize it with the Helio
via a cradle, which is supplied. For handwriting recognition, it
uses Jot from Communication Intelligence Corp.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that the Helio doesn't have yet is the support of
large numbers of third-party developers who are writing programs
for the device. If teen-agers start buying the Helio, that will
change.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEPHEN C. MILLER
</P>
<P>
   Encyclopedia Prequel
</P>
<P>
   In another example of the Internet turning academic publishing
on its head, MacMillan Reference is pre-releasing parts of its
massive Encyclopedia of Life Sciences on the Web. The encyclopedia
won't be completed until 2001, but in September 1999, MacMillan
will begin previewing more than 700 articles in an electronic
version, the Embryonic ELS (www.macmillan-reference.co.uk). That
will let academics and scientists participate in the evolution of
what MacMillan is calling ``the most ambitious reference source
ever to be published in the biological sciences.''
</P>
<P>
   Aiming Higher
</P>
<P>
   Is technology education in decline in the United States? It
might seem so after a glance at a recent report from the American
Electronics Association that found a 5 percent drop in the number
of math, physics, engineering and computer science degrees from
1990 to 1996. A closer look, however, reveals many signs of good
health. Most of the decline is due to a drop in associate and
bachelor degrees: Master's degrees are up 10 percent and Ph.D.s up
29 percent. The report also found an increase in the number of
advanced high school technology courses. So what happened to those
undergraduate dropouts? The report didn't speculate, but a few of
them may be software millionaires by now.
</P>
</TEXT>
