<HEADER>
A6796 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APACHE-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      04-28 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APACHE-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OFFICIALS SEEK TO LOWER EXPECTATIONS FOR APACHE HELICOPTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the much-touted Apache helicopter gunships
poised for action against Yugoslav forces Wednesday, military
officials and members of Congress sought to lower public
expectations that the high-tech aircraft would rapidly produce
dramatic war-ending results.
</P>
<P>
   After more than three weeks of anticipation, 24 Apaches, each
armed with as many as 16 tank-killing Hellfire missiles, 70mm
rockets and a 30mm cannon that can fire 625 rounds per minute,
arrived in northern Albania from bases in Germany ready for combat
in the embattled province of Kosovo. One of the gunships crashed
Monday in a training accident.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the soaring expectations for the Apaches have been
inspired by remarks by British Prime Minister Tony Blair's defense
staff and NATO spokesman Jamie Shea.
</P>
<P>
   But Defense Secretary William Cohen has warned earlier this week
that ``the role of the Apaches should not be overestimated,''
adding, ``Do not look for the Apache to be some sort of a miracle
solution or a silver bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't try to exaggerate ... what it can do in terms of
carrying out its missions,'' said Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Sen. Carl Levin, senior Democrat on the Senate Armed
Services Committee, said the American public shouldn't be led to
believe ``that there's going to be a sudden shift in the war
because the Apaches are arriving.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Before they can operate in large areas in Kosovo, the Apaches
must proceed on a gradual basis,'' said Levin. ``To put it bluntly,
do not expect substantial results from the Apaches for quite some
time, perhaps months,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Even as NATO officials asserted Wednesday that Apache missions
against Yugoslav forces were imminent, U.S. air crews faced a
formidable air defense system still in place around Yugoslavia _
despite more than a month of air attacks.
</P>
<P>
   One of NATO's top officials, German Gen. Klaus Naumann, head of
the alliance's military committee, said Yugoslavia's air defense
network of anti-aircraft guns, surface-to-air missiles and hundreds
of shoulder-fired missiles is prompting the alliance to move slowly
before dispatching the Apache gunships.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem we have to cope with is we still have a rather
dense air defense environment,'' Naumann said. ``That is presumably
the reason why they are very, very cautiously approaching the
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their armaments, the gunships are capable of
surprise attacks against enemy targets because of their ability to
fly only a few feet off the ground and suddenly appear from behind
trees or hills.
</P>
<P>
   But the helicopter's low-altitude operations also make it
vulnerable to air defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Michael O'Hanlon, a defense analyst with the independent
Brookings Institution in Washington, D.C., said another advantage
of the Apache is that it can attack in bad weather, unlike NATO's
high-flying jets that are hampered by cloud cover.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said O'Hanlon, simple math suggests that the relatively
small number of Apaches in the Balkans won't be able to rapidly
destroy 300-plus well-hidden and dug-in Yugoslav tanks and hundreds
of artillery pieces and armored personnel carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the Apaches can attack armor maybe twice as many days as
fixed-wing aircraft at high altitude _ that's not a big deal,
especially when you're adding 24 to 48 Apaches to a force that's
already numbering 700 planes,'' O'Hanlon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just no reason to think the Apaches are going to be a
decisive difference,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of Army Gen. Wesley Clark, the top NATO
commander, President Clinton on April 3 approved the deployment of
the Apaches to Albania. But it wasn't until Monday that the
aircraft arrived in Tirana, Albania, where they are protected and
maintained by 5,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   As the air campaign against Yugoslavia enters a second month
with no sign that President Slobodan Milosevic plans to withdraw
his forces from Kosovo, expectations for the Apaches were fueled
over the weekend when NATO spokesman Shea boasted that the
firepower of the Apaches, coupled with ground-based Multiple Launch
Rocket Systems to suppress enemy fire, would quickly cause
Milosevic to cry uncle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the Serbs, with their armor, in Kosovo to feel the
heat, quite frankly, to come under the kind of intensive pressure
which will give them absolutely no option but to pack up and leave
as rapidly as they possibly can, because we don't want this to go
on indefinitely,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to end this as quickly as we can,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, the British prime minister, expected ``big results'' from
the Apaches, according to the Times of London, quoting members of
Blair's national security team.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper reported, ``There was a conviction (among Blair's
inner circle) that the American Apache attack helicopters that
arrived in Albania will cause such devastation among the Serb
forces in Kosovo that after four or five weeks of close-quarter
action, NATO ground troops would be able to move in and occupy
territory in the province with the minimum of opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Telegraph of London editorialized that Blair
``continues to expect too much of high-tech weaponry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
