<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHAW, ARCHER OFFER GOP SOCIAL SECURITY PLAN
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bucking the reluctance of their own congressional
leaders to tackle the Social Security issue, two key Republicans
offered a plan Wednesday to save the retirement program through
private investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe strongly that we can work in a bipartisan manner to
save Social Security now, in this Congress,'' said Rep. Bill
Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee and
prime sponsor of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., a Florida Republican who chairs the
Social Security subcommittee and drafted the plan with Archer, said
Social Security must be reformed now. ``It can't be allowed to go
on the ash heap of indecision and political chicanery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, House GOP leaders disputed reports that they planned
to abandon Social Security reform before the 2000 elections, but on
Sunday, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said he didn't expect
reforms to be considered during this Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Both House Democrats and conservative groups gave the new
proposal a cool reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Archer-Shaw plan may be cloaked in the rhetoric of reform,
but a closer look reveals a risky scheme that would end Social
Security and put millions of American seniors in jeopardy,'' said
Rep. Rosa DeLauro, D-Conn. ``Ultimately, the Archer-Shaw proposal
would eliminate all surpluses, force the federal government to
increase taxes, and cut spending elsewhere in the budget. It's
irresponsible and unworkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Tanner of the Cato Institute, a libertarian research
center, called the proposal ``seriously flawed and deeply
disappointing. ... This is not a serious attempt to reform Social
Security, it is simply an attempt to bail out the current system
using taxpayer money.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House response was muted. Spokesman Joe Lockhart said,
``We've always been willing to work with those who want to work
constructively to get a solution to this, and that remains the
same.'' Clinton has proposed creating private investment accounts
in addition to _ rather than in place of _ current Social Security
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The Archer-Shaw proposal would use the projected federal surplus
to finance a 2 percent tax credit on wages subject to Social
Security payroll taxes. This year, the maximum credit would be
$1,452 on income of $72,600 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Workers would be required to invest the money in one of about 50
funds _ made up 60 percent of stocks and 40 percent of bonds _
approved by the government but selected by the worker.
</P>
<P>
   Workers and employers also would continue paying the 12.4
percent Social Security payroll tax. Archer said that tax could be
reduced in the future.
</P>
<P>
   When a worker decided to retire, the money in the investment
account would be paid out as an annuity, based on actuarial
estimates of the worker's remaining lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   If the amount in the account was enough to pay benefits at least
as high as what Social Security would pay under current law, the
benefit would come solely from the investment account. That would
relieve financial pressure on Social Security, which is expected to
run out of reserves by 2034.
</P>
<P>
   If the amount in the account was not enough to match the level
of benefits under current law, the difference would be paid from
reserves in the Social Security trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said the plan would guarantee existing benefits to current
retirees and at least that amount _ and likely more _ to future
retirees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to defuse what is actually a ticking time bomb
that will go off in the lifetime of our grandchildren,'' Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Schultz of The Palm Beach Post contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
