<HEADER>
A6798 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIPS-DECORATOR-ART-2T     04-28 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIPS-DECORATOR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTROSPECTION IS THIS YEAR'S STYLE AMONG INTERIOR DESIGNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A pair of monumental wire columns filled with oranges
stand sentry at the Kips Bay Boys and Girls Club Decorator Show
House. They are the latest indication that the American home has
become a place for navel-gazing.
</P>
<P>
   It's show house time again, that riotous seasonal decorating
ritual in which angst takes a holiday and rooms by decorators and
architects _ over half of them new to the show house _ reveal the
annual ``state of the nation'' of interior design.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Kips Bay's traditional cast of stodgy chintz-loving
characters had been supplanted by a jaunty group of young Turks.
This year, they're at it again. The show house, which opens on
Tuesday at 2 E. 82nd Street in Manhattan includes confident young
alumni from the offices of Parish-Hadley, Peter Marino, Mario
Buatta and Ralph Lauren, as well as the daughters of two Kips Bay
stalwarts, Janet Ackerley and the late Mark Hampton. Like their
mentors, they throw around the word ``timeless'' a bit too much but
nevertheless seem poised for the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   This year, darling, it's Nietzsche: this is doubtlessly the
first show house in history with two rooms inspired by Nietzsche
and Proust _ grab those Cliffs Notes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the earnest Dakota Jackson actually recited Chapter 3
of Proust's novel ``Jean Santeuil.'' Jackson described his room,
which is filled with art, music, books and objects from his own
home, as ``a reflection of my relationship with my wife.'' While
there are nearly as many themes as design firms in the show house
(17), there was a general feeling of introspection. The froufrou
index is at an all-time low. At the end of the century, Jackson
said, ``it's a moment of self-renewal, of coming clean.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the only designer obsessed with cleanliness. It is
also the year of the tub potato, of gargantuan Roman bathrooms for
stressed-out Spartacuses.
</P>
<P>
   It was a direction that might be thought of as fusion design,
the traditional functions of rooms morphing to form new hybrids _ a
bathroom-library-media room, for instance, and a living
room-conference center. The once-discrete disciplines of decoration
and architecture have converged.
</P>
<P>
   New materials, including silicon sheeting, cotton-and-rubber
weaves and titanium-dipped glass, have been enlisted for the cause.
Lucite is the new Lalique. It is no coincidence that the
five-story, 12,000-square-foot town house contains only one
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas O'Brien of Aero Studios designed a soothing and elegant
white-tiled sanctuary in two parts: a sitting room with a tiled
daybed and a bathroom with a double shower large enough for
shampooing a baby elephant.
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs the circus was Roman. Eric D.W. Cohler calls the
bathtub ``the New Age hearth.'' His is raised on a stepped
limestone platform set off by mosaics. He's surrounded the tub with
walnut bookshelves holding weighty tomes encased in plastic and
overhead, a study by John Singer Sargent. ``In the original
millennium, as men evolved from the ape, people sat around the
fire,'' Cohler said. Now, they can exfoliate while reading the
stock tables.
</P>
<P>
   The most powerful metaphor of the new spatial fluidity may be a
pivoting steel screen on casters, wrapped in sheets of stretched
silicon, in a salon by Catherine S. Kim and Leyden Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Designed with rotating art collections in mind, the screen
recalls the movement of a sail that can come about when the owner's
tastes change course. The silicon screen captures light like
alabaster: a contemporary shoji screen for the Silicon Valley era.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, the furniture designer and former magician, uses
theatrical scrims set in brushed aluminum frames to manipulate
light. Arranged along two walls like a backlighted cityscape, the
screens are an ingenious solution to the problem of unsightly
views. Venetian plaster walls with a subtle colored-pencil grid
inspired by Agnes Martin, soften the urban feeling of the room.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has perfected the art of curating himself:
autobiographical details abound, from galleys of a new book by his
wife, Roselee Goldberg, to suspiciously unfolksy family
photographs, which upon closer inspection turn out to have been
taken by his friend Arthur Elgort, a fashion photographer.
Furniture by his heroes, including Frank Lloyd Wright and Pierre
Chareau, are joined by his own, like a macho ebony desk-for-success
that dominates the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much the way my wife and I live,'' Jackson
explained, with art by his friends Robert Longo, Cindy Sherman and
Lou Reed. ``It's about two people, as Proust said, `surrounded by
the instruments of their pleasures.'''
</P>
<P>
   For Jennifer Post, the muse is Nietzsche. A laser-printed
quotation, taken from her college philosophy textbook, is
prominently displayed in a white-on-white home office. ``It's about
believing each person can be his own hero,'' she said _ the perfect
attitude for nesting entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kips Bay is always a mirror of contemporary fantasies,
the biggest fantasy this year may be the dream of a quiet corner.
Ms. Post, whose clients include Matt Lauer, the ``Today'' show
host, fulfills that wish in a deeply calming space that includes
aural therapy: a murmuring water sculpture by Archie Held.
</P>
<P>
   The small room is alive with textures, from a bluish panel of
opaque glass dipped in titanium above a desk to walls covered in a
shimmery reptilian vinyl. Ms. Post also plays with scale, keeping
her Lucite-handled furniture low to the ground at a noncorporate 18
inches high.
</P>
<P>
   The show house was full of references to modernism, but the best
designers avoided slavish imitations, treating history like a rest
area, pausing to refresh but then moving on down the highway.
</P>
<P>
   This irreverent spirit was captured on Douglas Wilson's stairway
walls. Acting on every boy's desire, Wilson took colored pencils
and drew freehand along the town house's proper classical moldings.
He glamorized his swirls with convex rearview mirrors purchased at
Jack's 99-Cent Store.
</P>
<P>
   In a proper drawing room, the designer Mariette Himes Gomez
subtly defies conventional expectations of town house architecture.
Where once a crystal chandelier dripping with prisms would have
hung, there is a simple 1950s brass fixture with paper shades.
</P>
<P>
   Where gilt mirrors would have decorated the walls, there are
ethereal and mysterious Cibachrome photographs on plexiglass, fuzzy
room interiors by Seton Smith that animate the space. Beneath them,
where the gilt bombe chests would have been, fanciful gnarled root
consoles tweak the room.
</P>
<P>
   James Rixner recalls steamship interiors and 1920s cabinetry
without copying either. At the center of his handsome upstairs
landing is a faceted zebrawood fireplace, its horizontal and
vertical veneers juxtaposed for contrast. Light from a handblown
Venetian chandelier bounces off gold-leaf squares on the ceiling,
some tinted copper and green, enveloping the space with a luminous
sense of artisanry.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Peter Vaughn takes his cue from the Lucite stacking cubes and
backgammon sets by Baron Alessandro Albrizzi, the late interior
designer and photographer whose work Vaughn reintroduced last year.
Fearlessly chartreuse, with ocelot-print cotton curtains, Vaughn's
room is like a bite into a lime.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces de resistance are perforated white screens made of 24
rubber doormats. ``You get creative when you get desperate,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reinvention is the name of the game at Kips Bay. This year's
most brazen attempt may be the one by Stephen Miller Siegel and
Nannette Brown, who designed George Stephanopoulos' New York
apartment and are now striving, as they put it, to ``recreate a new
Hillary.'' Stephanopoulos has obviously taught them something about
spin.
</P>
<P>
   For a future Senator Clinton's New York apartment, they aim for
urbane sophistication, with a whip-stitched blanketlike rug of
brown and gray wool felt and men's pin-striped suiting on the walls
and banquettes. The designers picture Mrs. Clinton living in
harmony in New York with the former president. How thick the walls
would be, they didn't say.
</P>
<P>
   Also spotted around the show house:
</P>
<P>
   _ Best economic indicator: the herringbone leather floor in
Lewis' and Ms. Kim's salon.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most obsessive detail: a tie between the toothpaste tube with
classical lettering in Aero Studios' bathroom and the artfully
arranged French baguette slices in the toaster in Christopher
Peacock's kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``Rethink This Idea in the Morning'' Award: The canvas
shower curtain that would need to be laundered weekly (Aero).
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``it'' plant: Contorted bamboo, $100 a stem (for both
Jackson and Vaughn, by the David Browne Flower Shop).
</P>
<P>
   _ Cognitive Dissonance Award: Aero's Zen bathroom abutting Ralph
Harvard's ode to Monticello.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Sweet Excess Award: Scott Salvator's topiary doors,
decorated with moss, artichokes, ostrich feathers and speckled
eggs.
</P>
<P>
   _ The last word on decorating and the influence of the stock
market: ``Everyone wants it finished quickly before something
horrible happens,'' Harvard said.
</P>
</TEXT>
