<HEADLINE>
BEIJING TOUGHENS ITS POSITION IN WORLD TRADE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ China appears to have toughened its stance in
talks aimed at gaining entry to the World Trade Organization,
making U.S. negotiators pay for President Clinton's decision
earlier this month to delay a final deal.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest turn in China's long and complex path toward
membership in the group that makes the rules for global commerce,
Chinese negotiators have accused U.S. officials of making excessive
demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some negotiators are reaching out for a yard after taking in
an inch,'' said Wu Yi, a state councillor and senior trade
official, in Beijing. ``They are demanding too high conditions that
are impractical and unacceptable for China.''
</P>
<P>
   China also seems to be trying to use international leverage with
European trade officials to put pressure on the United States to
agree to a WTO deal more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese negotiators Wednesday met for a third consecutive day in
Beijing with negotiators from the European Union, in preparation
for a visit by European Trade Commissioner Leon Brittan, who is
scheduled to arrive in Beijing on May 5 and is expected to announce
an agreement that China should finally be allowed into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   Two separate groups of negotiators met about tariffs and on
trading services, the New China News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Long Yongtu, China's chief negotiator, was quoted by the agency
as saying that China was prepared to make extensive efforts to push
forward the negotiations, apparently appealing for international
support to counter U.S. demands in its trade talks with China.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Prime Minister Zhu Rongji's trip to the United
States early this month, China made a broad array of concessions
aimed at overcoming United States opposition for Chinese entry to
the WTO, which China has sought for 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   China agreed to import more American beef, citrus products and
wheat, and to allow more openness in the telecommunications,
financial services and entertainment fields. Clinton rejected a
proposed agreement, though, apparently judging the anti-China mood
in Washington to be too strong to accept an accord.
</P>
<P>
   After vigorous protests from U.S. business leaders that a good
deal had been within reach, the Clinton administration authorized a
fresh round of negotiations aimed at preserving the momentum that
had been achieved.
</P>
<P>
   With the Americans on the defensive for what is widely seen to
have been a lost opportunity during Zhu's visit, Chinese
negotiators seem to want to take advantage of a suddenly
strengthened negotiating position.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials now say that their latest round of talks with
China, held last weekend, focused on financial services, an area
where they say the most obstacles remain. They have demanded full
rights for foreign banks operating in China to conduct business in
local and foreign currencies and to serve both local and foreign
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. negotiators say that China is insisting on too many
restrictions on U.S. banks, insurers and other financial companies
that want to enter the country. In response, Chinese officials
argue that equalizing market access for Chinese and foreign banks
could be disastrous for domestic banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excessive growth of nonbank financial institutions could lead
to a financial crisis,'' The China Economic Times reported, quoting
a position paper from the State Development and Planning
Commission. ``Foreign-invested firms, supported by their banks,
could easily take over sectors of the market and monopolize
industries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
