<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIMLER-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIMLERCHRYSLER CITES STRONG EARNINGS GAIN FOR QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Fueled by strong vehicle sales in the United States
and healthy heavy-truck sales, DaimlerChrysler AG on Wednesday
reported first-quarter profits increased by 23 percent, exceeding
some analysts' forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Net profits totaled 1.6 billion euros, or $1.75 billion; the
equivalent of $1.64 euros, or about $1.79 a share, vs. 1.43 euros,
or about $1.56 a share, for the same period in 1998. Revenues rose
10 percent to 35 billion euros, or about $38.28 billion. Profits
and revenues were up in every category in which DaimlerChrysler
competes.
</P>
<P>
   These comparisons, provided by DaimlerChrysler, are based on the
combined totals of Daimler-Benz AG and Chrysler Corp., which merged
in November.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler is riding the wave of strong U.S. vehicle sales,
which ran 10 percent above a year ago during the first quarter at a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of nearly 17 million vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler products, such as the new Jeep Grand Cherokee and the
Dodge Durango sport utility, have been well received as Chrysler
has increased its market share. Profits from the sale of Chrysler
vehicles rose 12 percent to $1.5 billion in the quarter. More than
half of DaimlerChrysler's 2.8 billion euros, or $3.06 billion in
operating profits came from Chrysler, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chrysler is selling what people want and selling what people
are willing to pay a premium for,'' said James Collins, an
automotive industry analyst with the London office of Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. ``Chrysler's revenues were up slightly, but its
operating margins improved from 9 percent to 9.6 percent. It's
clearly a matter of the mix of vehicles Chrysler is selling.''
</P>
<P>
   Income from the sale of Mercedes-Benz and Smart vehicles, the
second largest contributor to DaimlerChrysler's operating profits,
rose 4 percent. Mercedes is being dragged down by slow sales of the
Smart car, a new minicar sold in Europe. Sluggish sales have led
the automaker to cut production by a third.
</P>
<P>
   ``'Mercedes saw a good quarter, but it was slightly hidden under
the continuing problems with the Smart car,'' said Collins. ``The
recent news of Smart sales has been better, but it's difficult to
see longer term if the car will be viable. In the meantime, the
Smart car is hurting the margins at Mercedes.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins predicts the Mercedes margins will be hurt only
temporarily. The expected high profit margins of Mercedes' new
top-of-the-line S-Class, introduced in Europe late last year and on
sale since March in the United States, have yet to have an impact
on DaimlerChrysler's balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Strong sales of Freightliner heavy trucks helped profits in the
commercial-truck segment increase by 12 percent to 1.63 billion
euros, or $1.78 billion. Profits from the company's aerospace unit
more than doubled, and income from financial services operations
also rose.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler's strong first-quarter results suggest increased
revenues for the rest of the year, which now are expected to
surpass its initial revenue target of 137 billion euros, or $149.84
billion, said DaimlerChrysler chairman Jurgen Schrempp in a
statement. Strength in the United States should offset a possible
slowdown in sales in Europe during the second half of the year and
continued economic problems in Asia and Latin America, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock closed at $99.125, down $2.1875. European
auto stocks declined after Volkswagen AG reported
lower-than-expected profits, raising concerns about sales on the
continent.
</P>
<P>
   Created by the $36 billion takeover of Chrysler by Germany's
Daimler-Benz AG, DaimlerChrysler, now the world's fifth largest
automaker, also continues cost-cutting that will help increase
operating profits at a rate greater than revenues over the year.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call, DaimlerChrysler executives told auto
analysts that the cost-cutting benefits from the merger were
minimal in the first quarter but would total $1.4 billion in
savings for the full year.
</P>
</TEXT>
