<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO ACKNOWLEDGES MISSILE MISSED TARGET, HIT CIVILIAN HOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO acknowledged Wednesday that at least
one laser-guided bomb missed its intended military target Tuesday
afternoon and exploded in a neighborhood of civilian houses in
southern Serbia. Yugoslav authorities, who reported the incident
Tuesday night, said 20 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can confirm that one bomb went astray and impacted in an
area where there were civilians,'' a spokesman for the allied
military command, Brig. Gen. Giuseppe Marani of Italy, said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He said the attack had been aimed at a military garrison 200 to
300 yards away in the town of Surdulica, although reports from the
scene said that the barracks was at least 500 yards away. NATO
officials gave no estimate of their own of the number houses
destroyed or people killed. And they did not say what exactly had
caused the bomb to stray, though they have emphasized in the past
that bad weather or malfunction can send the weapons off target.
</P>
<P>
   Marani also indicated that more than one bomb may have missed
its target on Tuesday, and journalists who visited the site in
Yugoslavia on Wednesday reported seeing a second bomb crater.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot exclude that another bomb could have been in the
same conditions and caused some collateral damage,'' the general
said, using the NATO military term for unintended destruction of
civilian life or property.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's swift if incomplete acknowledgment that Tuesday's
attack went wrong contrasted with the confusion of its initial
responses earlier this month to reports from Serbian officials that
about 70 people were killed when NATO bombs hit a column of ethnic
Albanian civilians near the town of Djakovica. It took days then
for the command to determine that allied planes had indeed fired on
the convoy, believing it contained only military vehicles, and then
explain the mistake publicly.
</P>
<P>
   This time, NATO officials reacted so quickly that when the
alliance's top civilian leader, Javier Solana, appeared before
reporters Wednesday afternoon he was not even asked about the
incident, and said nothing about it.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, British Defense Minister George Robertson said in
London that Tuesday's attack destroyed the military barracks it was
aimed at and apologized in London for civilian casualties, which
NATO commanders say they are trying to keep to an absolute minimum
by picking targets carefully and using precision-guided bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to express our regrets about any civilian casualties
which may have resulted from NATO's attack yesterday on the
Yugoslav Army training center at Surdulica,'' Robertson said. The
command here did not say which country's forces had carried out the
attack. Marani said NATO had no independent knowledge of how many
civilians might have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   As the bombing continued into its 36th day Wednesday, Marani
said that NATO planes had bombed anti-aircraft weapons sites,
fuel-storage areas, and roads and railways throughout Serbia. The
allies also tried to keep up pressure on the Serbian police and
military forces carrying out attacks against ethnic Albanian
civilians and soldiers of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army inside
the province, striking a multiple rocket launcher system, armored
vehicles, storage areas, and a police command post, Marani said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the top allied commander, Gen. Wesley K. Clark, said at
a news briefing here that five weeks of bombing and bad weather had
not prevented the Serb forces from reinforcing and continuing
sweeps that have driven hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians &UR;  &LR; 
from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's command said Wednesday that reinforcements that had kept
Serb military and police forces in the province at a strength of
about 40,000 since the bombing started were actually signs that the
allied air campaign was hurting the Serb forces in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been some misinterpretation of this reinforcement,''
Marani said. ``Let me clarify its significance. It in fact
demonstrates two key points. First, the Serb military cannot make
good the losses the air campaign has inflicted on their forces in
Kosovo. The Serbs are unable to reconstitute their forces in Kosovo
and must rely on reinforcement with new units from outside
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, Marani said, the reinforcements showed that Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic had made a major miscalculation about
the length of time his forces would need to eliminate the Kosovo
Liberation Army and its challenge to Serbian rule over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought he could defeat the KLA with his existing forces on
the ground in a short five-to-seven-day operation,'' Marani said.
``This, as the reinforcement and duration of these operations in
Kosovo show, was completely wrong, and is further testimony to the
success of the air campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The command reported Wednesday that, despite the bombing, Serb
forces were continuing attacks against the rebels in three general
areas around the province, southwest of Podujevo north of the
provincial capital of Pristina, east of Globocica near the border
with Macedonia, and northeast of the town of Suva Reka, near
Prizren in the south.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrilla forces, Clark said Tuesday, had not been defeated
and were still able to put up stiff resistance to the Serbs. NATO
spokesman Jamie P. Shea said Wednesday that the rebels still had at
least 12,000 fighters inside Kosovo, although NATO has denied
having any contact with the KLA in the field and Shea did not give
any indication of the source of his estimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying also to create two corridors from Albania into
Kosovo, which can be used of course not only as resupply circuits
but for the evacuation of refugees and displaced persons in the
safest circumstances,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb military and heavily armed police units fighting
against the rebels are also trying to cut their supply lines from
Albania along the western border of Kosovo near Djakovica,
according to the command.
</P>
</TEXT>
