<HEADER>
A6808 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WITCH-DOCTORATE-ART-N     04-28 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WITCH-DOCTORATE-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 WITCH COMES OUT OF THE CLOSET, GOES INTO THE CLASSROOM  (ART ADV:
Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BARRY BORTNICK   
 Santa Barbara (Calif.) News-Press   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ Nancy Ramsey is out of the ``broom
closet,'' as she puts it, and studying witchcraft at the University
of California at Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   The 39-year-old Florida native is a practicing witch and a
second-degree priestess in the Wicca faith, who believes in spirits
and spreading good magic. She is working on a Ph.D. at the
university's religious studies department.
</P>
<P>
   Her field of research centers on Wicca, a pagan religion
practiced by modern witches. The research focuses on how witches
view themselves and how that self-image is affected by the way
others, such as the media, fundamentalist Christians and Hollywood,
treat the ancient faith.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey and others in the department say little is known about
neo-paganism. Her work may shed light on an otherwise vague topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her research will yield some very interesting information,''
said UCSB religious studies professor Wade Clark Roof, who serves
as Ramsey's Ph.D. adviser. ``She will find out a great deal more
about who contemporary pagans and witches are. She will find out
about their networks and their views, their practices and beliefs.
All that will let us understand modern paganism a lot better than
we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey is well suited to the task because she's felt a spiritual
link to the pagan culture since childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not raised with a religious tradition,'' Ramsey said in
an interview at her Ventura home. ``But my father grew up in
Appalachia and his family believed in ghosts and spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey encountered a reappearing spirit she called ``the blue
lady'' during her youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``She watched over me. She was the spirit I was most familiar
with,'' Ramsey said of the apparition.
</P>
<P>
   The mystic heritage made Ramsey a popular figure in grade
school. She traded amulets with friends and performed dream
interpretation for schoolmates.
</P>
<P>
   Other families in her Daytona, Fla., neighborhood worried about
the young girl's strange ways and urged her to attend their church,
so Ramsey grew curious about religion at a very early age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been interested in how people make sense of the
world, and religion is a way we have done that from the
beginning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As one would expect, Ramsey's quaint home is loaded with various
totems. There's a wreath and a pentagram over the doorway that
leads to Ramsey's kitchen; a Buddha and a Ganesha, the Hindu deity
of learning, stand in her hallway. A knife, its blade side facing
upward for good luck, hangs over the front door. A statue of a
Chinese god of wealth adorns her living room. She also keeps a deck
of tarot cards on hand in case someone needs advice.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey is a witch who embraces all forms of religious energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a religious studies student, so I collect lots of
things,'' she said while her infant daughter, Dana, slept in a
nearby crib.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the tarot cards, which Ramsey consulted to select a
doctoral dissertation, there is nothing particularly unusual about
the Ph.D. student's life or academic pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, it is like being in an office with anyone else,''
said Josephine McMullen, a fellow religious studies scholar who
shares space with Ramsey at UCSB. ``She is a nice, friendly person.
I only found out a few months ago that she was a witch. She is just
like everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is the point Ramsey wants people to understand. Though
Hollywood often treats witches with contempt _ remember the
terrifying flying monkeys of the ``Wizard of Oz'' and their evil
mistress, the Wicked Witch of the West _ Ramsey's Ph.D. work seeks
to expose the ordinary face of modern pagans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pagans come to the religion because they like magic and loved
fantasy as children,'' Ramsey said. ``They are people who saw
themselves as outsiders, who found a community that celebrates
their uniqueness. We are like the Uncola, or the Unchristians.''
</P>
<P>
   That uniqueness has kept a lot of pagans ``in the broom
closet,'' Ramsey said.
</P>
<P>
   Her research indicates that there are a lot more witches about
than most people think.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for a lot of them to come out because many people
don't understand paganism,'' Ramsey said. ``Some people think we
are satanists who drink babies' blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey described Wicca as a European-based religion that
predates Christianity. Modern witches have a magical world view and
believe they can influence events with positive thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea behind magic is that you can affect things,'' she
said. ``You might do a spell to get a job, but the spell is mostly
a way to generate positive thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Ramsey, there is no such thing as a wicked witch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Witches are healers who work to keep their lives in harmony
with nature,'' she said. ``They work for good and not harm. We are
ordinary people who believe in a serious and ethical religion.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Barbara, Calif., News-Press is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
