<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-SLAYING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DECIDES TO MOVE DRAGGING DEATH TRIAL OUT OF JASPER AREA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The capital murder trial of the second of three
white men accused in the brutal dragging death of a black man will
be moved out of Jasper County, a judge ruled Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Monte Lawlis said he will issue a ruling by
May 14 naming where the trial of Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr., 32,
of Sulphur Springs, will be. He said he must discuss details of how
to handle the move with officials of other counties before deciding
just where the trial will be held. He said he expects to begin
picking a jury by July 6.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and defense lawyers had earlier considered
Georgetown, just north of Austin, as a site for the trial. Jasper
County District Attorney Guy James Gray said Wednesday that several
cities are being considered. He would not name the possible sites,
but Corpus Christi, Galveston, Kerrville and New Braunfels had
earlier been discussed as possible sites.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's order came less than a week after Lawlis had denied
a change of venue request by Brewer's lawyers. He said he granted
the change Wednesday after both sides agreed to it.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said he still believes that a Jasper County jury could give
Brewer, accused in the June 7 dragging death of 49-year-old James
Byrd Jr., a fair trial. He said the venue issue is the only matter
in the case he expects to offer any possible grounds for appeal,
and he didn't want to have to be repeatedly defending that issue in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, he didn't want the venue issue to become a
major part of the lengthy process of picking a jury for Brewer's
trial. ``I didn't want it to be turned into a side show,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Barlow, Brewer's court-appointed attorney, said that
while prospective jurors in Jasper County may think they were being
fair, comments made after co-defendant John William King was
convicted and sentenced to death made it clear that many in Jasper
think guilty convictions help the reputation of their community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't care where it goes, just so it's outside of Jasper
County,'' Barlow said.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said it is significant that defense attorneys claim a white
defendant accused of the racial killing of a black man can't get a
fair trial in East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have had 150 years with no Klansman having ever been
convicted of killing a black man in East Texas and then you have
Bill King being convicted in Jasper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today you have a Klansman who says he can't get a fair trial
in Jasper.''
</P>
<P>
   King and Brewer, who served prison sentences together in a Texas
prison, were identified as being members of a Ku Klux Klan offshoot
group.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's order specifies only that the trial will be moved
beyond an adjoining county. Gray said he thinks it's important to
move the trial beyond the Beaumont media market.
</P>
<P>
   While many Jasper residents have said they wanted all three
trials held in their county, Gray said most have said they realize
that spending more money to move the trial would be better than to
risk having to try Brewer again.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney for the third suspect, Shawn Allen Berry, 24, of
Jasper, has said he wants to keep his trial in Jasper. That trial
will probably begin next fall.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said moving Brewer's trial might cost the county $50,000
more than having it in Jasper. So far Jasper County has spent more
than $283,000 on the court cases related to Byrd's murder _ most of
it on King's trial.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with those trials and several other unrelated and
unexpected capital murder cases, Jasper County Commissioners
increased the county tax rate by 2 cents per $100 valuation. The
increase was expected to last for two or three years. Gray said
moving Brewer's trial may mean the increase will be in effect for
one additional year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
