<HEADLINE>
U.N. RIGHTS COMMISSION VOTE CALLS FOR WORLDWIDE MORATORIUM ON
EXECUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The U.N. Human Rights Commission voted overwhelmingly
Wednesday in favor of a worldwide moratorium on executions over the
objections of fewer than a dozen countries, including the United
States, China, Rwanda and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, sponsored by the European Union, is viewed by
human rights advocates as a step towards abolishing the death
penalty around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   The 53-member commission voted 30-11 in favor of the measure,
with 12 countries abstaining. Both the United States and China,
accused by human rights groups as the most frequent users of
capital punishment, voted against the resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the American delegation, Nancy Rubin, defended the
practice in the United States, where 38 of the 50 states permit the
death penalty. ``A noticeable majority of our citizens support the
death penalty for particularly heinous crimes and our laws support
this,'' she told delegates attending the commission's annual
session.
</P>
<P>
   If the American public changes its view, Ms. Rubin said, ``there
is little question our laws will follow suit.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, American officials recognize that ``a
significant number of countries have abolished the death penalty,''
she noted. A report by the U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to the
commission found that 65 countries, including France and Germany,
have abolished capital punishment, while 88 countries retain it.
</P>
<P>
   The American vote put it in the company of Bangladesh, Botswana,
Indonesia, Japan, Pakistan, South Korea, and Qatar as well as
Rwanda, China and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Although the commission voted in favor of similar resolutions in
past years, this is the first time the European Union as a whole
had sponsored a resolution on the topic. The EU text urged
countries ``to progressively restrict the number of offenses for
which the death penalty may be imposed and to establish a
moratorium on executions, with a view to completely abolishing the
death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the resolution asked countries not to permit
executions ``for any but the most serious crimes'' and then only
when a ``final judgment'' is ``rendered by an independent and
impartial competent court.'' The resolution also called on
governments not to execute anyone who was under 18 when the crime
was committed, pregnant women, or whenever any legal proceeding is
pending.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the resolution urged barring the execution of
people with ``any form of mental disorder'' and the extradition of
suspects who would face capital punishment in another country.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, Italy has spearheaded the drive against the death
penalty. Capital punishment became a very public issue in Italy
last year when the country refused to extradite the Kurdish rebel
leader, Abdullah Ocalan, because Turkey has the death penalty for
convicted terrorists. Ocalan left Italy in January, and was
captured by Turkish commandoes in Kenya in February and is now
awaiting trial on charges of treason in Turkey. Prosecutors have
asked for the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Germany introduced the resolution, arguing that its passage was
essential because ``there is the possibility of judicial error
anywhere.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Human rights groups have made abolishing capital punishment a
top priority. Amnesty International said that the United States had
executed more than 500 people since it reinstated the death penalty
in 1977. According to its latest statistics, more than 2,375 people
were executed in 40 countries in 1997, and 3,700 sentenced to death
in 69 countries.
</P>
<P>
   By far the greatest number of executions were carried out in
China _ approximately 1,644 in 1997, with Iran and Saudi Arabia
trailing with about 143 and 122 respectively. The United States had
74 executions that year. The London-based rights group said that it
had also received reports of hundreds of executions in Iraq that
year that it was unable to confirm.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 countries bar execution for juvenile offenders,
which is also prohibited under international human rights treaties.
However, six countries are known to have executed prisoners under
18 since 1990, including Iran, Nigeria, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, the
United States and Yemen, Amnesty International said.
</P>
<P>
   The country with the highest number of of such executions was
the United States, where six juvenile offenders have been put to
death since 1990, the advocacy group said.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the U.N. special investigator on such executions urged
that they be abolished. Her predecessor, Waly Bacre Ndiaye, issued
a report in 1997, based on an 18-day trip to the United States,
that said the death penalty was applied in an unfair,
discriminatory and arbitrary manner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
