<HEADER>
A6838 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-SIDEWALK-SIT     04-28 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-SIDEWALK-SITTERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERVENT FANS IN LINE WEEKS BEFORE `STAR WARS' TICKETS GO ON SALE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ A long time ago, in a galaxy far, far away, there
might have been something like it. But even Mann's Chinese Theater,
the gaudy ground-zero of movie fandom, has never seen anything
quite like the global village that is snaking along its scarred old
sidewalk in the heart of Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   They have been here for nearly three weeks now, this shifting
band of 30 hardy souls, camped in pup tents and equipped with
laptops, cell phones, digital video cameras and an Internet
connection that broadcasts their vigil live to the world. They have
just three more weeks until ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom
Menace'' opens on the Chinese's big screen, and they are determined
to be first in line. The Force is clearly with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first saw ``Star Wars,'' it was like a life-defining
moment,'' said Cecil Seaskull, 29, an aspiring singer-songwriter
and children's book author who collects vintage ``Star Wars''
action figures (especially broken ones) and now waits on the
sidewalk virtually 24 hours a day, 7 days a week. ``It was the
first time I was conscious of stories and that they could be
powerful and that that's what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Seaskull's story is echoed by a dozen Gen-Xers up and down
the line, many others among them born too late to see the first
``Star Wars'' in theaters in 1977, or even its sequels, ``The
Empire Strikes Back'' (1980) and ``Return of the Jedi'' (1983),
until all three were reissued in a 20th anniversary tour two years
ago. But they have watched the trilogy over and over on
videocassettes and have found in George Lucas' epic saga of good
and evil something like their system of belief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beyond appeal, it's a cultural icon for us,'' said
Lincoln Gasking, a 22-year-old entrepreneur from Melbourne,
Australia, who organized the line here and others around the
country (including one scheduled to begin forming at the Ziegfeld
Theater in New York on May 1) on his Web site,
www.countingdown.com. Gasking continues to run his apartment rental
business over the Internet from a sidewalk computer. ``For a lot of
people here, it was one of the most enjoyable times in their
childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Gasking is nothing if not organized. He obtained a permit from
the city and liability insurance to cover 250 sitters. He cadged
free computers and cell phones from corporations, borrowed power
from a neighboring souvenir stand and established general
headquarters across the street at the Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel,
the site of the first Academy Awards ceremony, where members of the
group take turns showering. He has arranged for line-sitters to
enlist sponsors who pay at least 25 cents for each hour spent in
line, with the proceeds going to the Starlight Children's
Foundation, which grants wishes for ill children and is a favorite
charity of actor Mark Hamill, ``Luke Skywalker'' himself.
</P>
<P>
   Self-governance prevails on the street. Steve Cote, 28, a
freelance camera assistant in the movie business who comes down
from his home in the suburban San Fernando Valley to wait, oversees
a system in which sitters accumulate points on a sliding scale
depending on when they arrived and how many 4-hour shifts they sit,
with the first shifts April 7 worth 100 points and those in the
final week worth 5. Those with the most points will get first
chance at tickets whenever they go on sale, perhaps May 12, a week
before the nationwide opening May 19.
</P>
<P>
   Among the minutes of a recent meeting posted on a tent was this
injunction: ``Sleeping in hotel, watching a movie at the Chinese,
shower breaks longer than 1/2 hour and sit-down eating in a
restaurant are things that need to be signed out for.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this is a bit too bureaucratic for Daniel Alter, 17, a
recent high school graduate and aspiring film student who calls
``Star Wars'' ``modern American mythology that transcends every
race, religion, generation, class.'' Alter came from his home in
suburban Tarzana to set up a folding chair outside Mann's Village
Theater in the Westwood section of Los Angeles, a few miles miles,
on April 7, and dismisses Gasking as a self-promoter. He said some
of Gasking's troops at the Village had given up and joined his more
ad-hoc line.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't want to wear name tags or have sign-in sheets or
get sponsors,'' said Alter, who has been plotting his own mission
for three years and is first in line for his favorite, acoustically
perfect seat at the Village, P107. ``They defected to us.''
</P>
<P>
   It is all the sort of publicity a studio cannot buy, but Tom
Sherak, chairman of the 20th Century Fox Domestic Film Group, which
is releasing the movie, said the studio had stayed away from the
line-sitters because it did not want to be accused of hyping a
grass-roots effort. ``This is their thing, not ours,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sherak has paid a couple of incognito visits to the lines
and called them ``an amazing phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the things that makes us so special as a people, I
believe,'' Sherak said, ``the fact that we can come together with
strangers for something like this.'' He said the studio was
considering how to do something to honor the line-sitters as the
release date approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't figured it out yet,'' he said. ``Maybe in a couple
of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kurt Volk, 25, an art student who quit his job as a bike
messenger in Chicago to come to the Chinese on April 8 with his
friend Chris Hrasky, 25, a graduate student in film at the
University of Texas, the line has been the source of firm new
friendships with people like Ms. Seaskull. ``I'll charge the whole
damn thing on my credit card,'' he said. ``I don't care. I'm going
back to Chicago financially ruined, but I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the movie opens, Gasking said, his gang plans a celebratory
trip to Disneyland, and then he is off to Sydney, London and Paris
for ``Star Wars'' premieres there. Will the group have reunions
when they're old and gray?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Volk said, noting that Lucas envisions at
least two more ``Star Wars'' tales. ``We'll probably just come back
for the next one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
