<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOODMED-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICINAL PROPERTIES OF FOOD TOUTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - If Americans need proof that medical professionals in
this country don't recognize the link between food and health, they
need only check out ``the abysmal foods served in hospitals,'' says
Andrew Weil, physician, author and guru of alternative medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Weil appeared on a panel discussing the use of food as medicine
at the annual conference of the International Association of
Culinary Professionals held in Phoenix earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with Weil were cookbook author and authority on Chinese
cuisine Nina Simonds, and Madhur Jaffrey, cookbook author and
expert on Indian cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   Asian cultures long have recognized the health benefits of
eating certain foods, eating foods in the right seasons, and
treating and preventing illness with food, the panelists said.
Western medicine lags behind, leaving health professionals ignorant
of nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has not changed substantially since I was out of medical
school,'' said Weil, a graduate of Harvard Medical School, who has
written such books as ``Spontaneous Healing'' and has hosted
television specials recommending ways to prevent disease through
diet.
</P>
<P>
   He is the director of interactive medicine at the University of
Arizona's College of Medicine in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   In America, distinctions still are made between food and
medicine, Weil said, while the lines have blurred in Asia. Yet he
maintains that many foods have medicinal properties.
</P>
<P>
   Powdered ginger, for instance, can ``neutralize bad energies''
as a powerful anti-inflammatory agent. It also soothes the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   The spice turmeric also has anti-inflammatory properties.
</P>
<P>
   Lycopene, a pigment found in tomatoes, can help prevent some
forms of cancer, he said. Research finds it works best when the
tomatoes are cooked and accompanied by fat.
</P>
<P>
   Essential fatty acids, such as Omega-3, found in fish oils and
walnuts, help build cell membranes in the brain. Failing to eat
enough of these oils early in life may lead to such diseases as
Alzheimer's and Lou Gehrig's disease later in life, Weil said.
</P>
<P>
   A healthful diet needn't be a Spartan one, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eating healthy doesn't mean giving up everything you enjoy,''
he said, dismayed recently when his pre-ordered airline vegetarian
meal was bland and had no dessert.
</P>
<P>
   The airline chefs seemed to believe, he said, that ``anyone who
orders a healthy meal doesn't want anything pleasureful.''
</P>
<P>
   But the public is confused, he said, by seemingly conflicting
reports about which foods are beneficial and which are harmful. So
they turn to the adage of ``everything in moderation.''
</P>
<P>
   Weil insists that there are ``good'' and ``bad'' foods, and the
bad ones _ such as certain fats _ are to be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of eating well to stay well is a topic that ``goes
beyond folk remedies,'' said Simonds, the Chinese cuisine
authority. In Asian philosophy, it involves the balance of yin and
yang, opposing yet complementary aspects of the universe. Food
plays a role in that balance.
</P>
<P>
   Women tend to be yin, while men tend to be yang. Foods, too, are
classified as yin and yang.
</P>
<P>
   Yin foods have a calming effect, Simonds said. They include raw
fruits and vegetables and seafood. Yang foods, which energize and
stimulate the body, include eggs, meats and spicy foods. Neutral
foods include rice, peanuts and breads.
</P>
<P>
   Simonds details much of this information in her just-published
cookbook, ``A Spoonful of Ginger.''
</P>
<P>
   She expects those notions to appeal to adults eager to enhance
their health through diet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby boomers are reaching an age when we want to prevent
disease,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffrey, who grew up in India, says Indians are raised with a
subliminal knowledge of food and its healing powers.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers pass along to their children advice for aiding
digestion: Chew food carefully, drink ginger juice and take a short
walk _ even 100 steps _ after eating.
</P>
<P>
   Eat opposite of the seasons _ cold foods in summer, hot foods in
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Disease often comes as the seasons are changing, Jaffrey said.
Getting a massage at that time can relax the body and help ward off
illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to follow a whole way of life to bring balance to the
body,'' Jaffrey said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
