r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARTNERS-EXERCISE-AZR     04-28 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTNERS-EXERCISE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXERCISING WITH OTHERS PAYS OFF IN MOTIVATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS ROPP  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Chic Older works out alone so people won't see him
cry.
</P>
<P>
   However, Older, who is executive director of the Arizona Medical
Association, admits there are significant advantages to working out
with others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The single greatest benefit I'm aware of is it's the best way
I know to get your butt out the door when you don't want to,''
Older said. ``Secondly, there's a rhythm to working out, and often
it's enhanced by two people.''
</P>
<P>
   Health experts believe motivation is the single most important
reason for working out with others. Most people, they say, do not
have the discipline to work out solo over a long period. That, in
part, accounts for the success of health clubs and specialty
organizations where people with like interests get together to
bike, run or even walk.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Ann Taylor, owner of The Walking Connection, said the need
for motivation is what brings new members to her 2,000-member
Valley club, which specializes in the mental, skeletal, muscular
and aerobic benefits of walking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walkers tend to want to walk with others,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, a former runner-turned-power walker, is also more
inclined to work out with a partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when I can't depend on myself to exercise,''
Taylor said. ``In the summer when it's 110 degrees, you have to get
up real early in the morning to work out. If you have a friend on
the corner waiting for you at 5 a.m., you don't think twice. You
get up.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Steingard, an orthopedic surgeon trained in sports
medicine, believes working out with a partner is best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely better to work out with other people, provided
your goals are the same,'' Steingard said. ``I think just the peer
pressure alone will make you do the exercises, because it's hard to
say no to someone else who has the same goals.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Russell Chick of Phoenix said there are also benefits of
exercising alone. Chick, a runner and orthopedic surgeon, said many
people prefer to jog alone so they can go at their own pace and in
their own time frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people like to run certain distances, and they don't want
to worry about a partner not being able to run as far,'' Chick
said. ``Plus, I think a lot of people enjoy the privacy of being by
themselves so they can think and have that peace of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Older, of the Arizona Medical Association, agrees. A bicyclist
and weightlifter, he prefers going it on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to pace myself at exactly my speed,'' Older said. ``I
don't want to feel like I'm either holding someone up or I have to
do what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Chick said some people have a negative body image, which compels
them to work out away from others.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're embarrassed,'' Chick said. ``They don't think they're
very fit or look that good, so they buy those videotapes and work
out at home.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the problem with workout tapes is they often require
another person to help explain the details on how to do a
particular move in an exercise, Chick said.
</P>
<P>
   Steingard, the orthopedic surgeon, prefers that his patients
work out with a group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I side with the camp that team efforts are better than
individual,'' Steingard said. ``If I go out and jog, my speed will
increase if I'm jogging with someone else. I also see fewer
injuries when people are looking out for each other, especially in
weight training. You just did 20 pounds and you're thinking of
trying 60. A partner will put it in perspective, tell you don't be
ridiculous. That's too much of an increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Steingard also believes partners are crucial if you're involved
in serious training. He relates it to playing the piano.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter offers an objective point of view when I'm hitting
the keys too hard. So I make adjustments based on her objectivity.
The results are bigger gains.''
</P>
<P>
   The experts say there are no definitive studies on health and
workout partners. Unless you're the kind of person who won't work
out without a partner, there is no right or wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the nice thing about working out,'' said Chick, the
orthopedic surgeon. ``You can tailor it to whatever your
personality dictates.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as Older of the medical association puts it, hope to heck
someone is around when you can't lift that 90-pound barbell from
your neck. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
