<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6846 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0429-     04-28 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0429-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW KOSOVAR REFUGEE WAVES REPORT KILLINGS, EVICTIONS OF ENTIRE
VILLAGES
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINA BORDER POINT, Albania _ New bouts of ethnic cleansing
sent entire towns of refugees on the run out of Kosovo Wednesday,
bringing with them tales of killings and beatings and the targeting
of ethnic Albanian men.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions were so bad in Macedonia, where more than 4,000
refugees arrived Wednesday, that food fights broke out as people
scrambled to get loaves of bread.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Albania, relief workers were hustling to put up more
tents for more than 2,500 new arrivals, scores of whom were still
sitting and waiting on roadsides and at the town square in Kukes by
7 p.m. (local time).
</P>
<P>
   After a week of relative calm, in which only a few hundred
refugees a day crossed out of Kosovo, Serb forces were said to be
clearing out and torching villages again.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, military activity here along Albania's
northern border with Kosovo was intensifying. More than a dozen
Yugoslav shells were lobbed close to two Albanian towns northwest
of here overnight, and planes believed to be NATO bombers were
heard circling above this border crossing area all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Around 1:15 p.m. a boom sounded and a dense black cloud of smoke
arose on the Yugoslav side. It could have been as close as 10 miles
from the border.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovar Albanians fleeing into Macedonia reported harassment and
beatings, and the BBC radio said a group of about 50 refugees ran
into a minefield as they tried to escape their homeland. It said
five of them died in explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Many refugees who crossed into Albania Wednesday said men
between 15 and 50 years of age had been separated from tractor
convoys and beaten, then allowed to continue. Most reported being
forced to give up money and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Families from the town of Hade said they had been trapped for at
least two weeks by Serb-led Yugoslav forces circling their village,
until Serb police arrived Wednesday morning at 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came quarter by quarter. The Serbs put us on buses,''
said Alim Grajqevci, 67. Several villagers said 15 buses were
brought to take away the people, three of them driving to Albania
and the remainder to Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Three other families from the town said four men had been
incinerated a week ago after paramilitary forces made an assault on
the village. The burned remains of two of them were found under the
charred body of a dead cow, said Aslan Merena, 61, who said he was
a distant relative of the dead men. More than half a dozen
villagers identified the people killed as belonging to the Merena
family.
</P>
<P>
   More refugees repeated variations of the story first heard late
Tuesday of 200 or more dead bodies seen in a field off the road at
a village called Meje, near the regional center of Dakovice.
</P>
<P>
   A group of women who arrived before this story was heard said
that about 300 men with them had been separated and taken by the
Serbs to sit in a field at the village of Meje. This happened in
late morning Tuesday, said Zenije Pajaziti, 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police were around them in a circle. They had their guns
on them,'' she said. When interviewed in Kukes on Wednesday
morning, she said her family still had no idea what happened to the
men taken away.
</P>
<P>
   Later arrivals reported seeing a concentration of dead men, and
refugees crossing the border Wednesday gave similar accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Two cousins who had been heading on foot toward Albania came
over the border in tears Wednesday and told that they saw a group
of men around 12:30 p.m. Tuesday who appeared to be squatting in a
field off the road at Meje.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we left them 10 meters behind, the police stopped us and
asked for gold jewelry and money,'' said Valdeta Rama, 22. The
young women said they gave what they had, then were allowed to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard a lot of shots. We turned our heads a little and we
saw they fell face down. Their faces were covered with blood,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Wilkinson, spokesman for the United Nations refugee agency,
said similar reports had been repeated by refugees who had come in
the early morning hours Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks very ominous. The reports seem consistent,'' he said.
If it is found to be true, he said, this would be among the worst
massacres of the Kosovo ethnic cleansing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson said that some of the women also reported they were
detained by the Serbs for several hours. They said younger women
were taken away for between 1 1/2 to 2 hours, and that they ``had
been touched'' by the Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Later Wednesday, scores of people in cars and tractors arrived
from Meje, saying they had been ousted from their homes on Tuesday
night. Some reported seeing such a group of dead bodies, but others
did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the town is leaving,'' said Gjon Prishi of Meje, who had
just driven a tractor over the border Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   He and his son said they saw 80 to 100 mostly young men laying
dead in a field as they pulled out of town Tuesday evening. They
spent the night in a nearby village, then moved on toward the
border.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
