</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, April 29. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Showcasing the profound divisions
over the escalating NATO engagement in Kosovo, the House votes to
block President Clinton from widening the conflict to include
ground troops without prior approval from Congress. The bill,
approved 249-180, was the only measure to survive a day of
sometimes anguished debate over what several lawmakers described as
a set of bad choices on how to handle a deployment that has not run
according to plan. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-SANCTIONS (Washington) _ The Clinton administration
announces that it has decided to ease its sanctions policy to
permit the sale of food and medical supplies to Iran, Libya, Sudan
and other nations alleged to support terrorists. The new policy,
which had long been sought by farm-land lawmakers and lobbyists for
several large corporations, will make a general exemption for food
and medicine whenever trade sanctions are placed on countries
considered adversaries of the United States. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Littleton , Colo.) _ Developments. The
Jefferson County sheriff's briefing. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-BIRTHS (Washington) _ The teen-age birth rate, which has
been dropping steadily for six years, has dipped so sharply that it
has helped push the nation's overall birth rate to the lowest point
since the government began keeping records in 1909, according to
data by the National Center for Health Statistics. By Sheryl Gay
Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PROFILING-MOTELS (Trenton, N.J.) _ The New Jersey State
Police have quietly enlisted workers at dozens of motels to tip
them off about suspicious guests who, for instance, pay for their
rooms in cash, receive a flurry of telephone calls or, in some
cases, simply speak Spanish, according to participants. By David
Kocieniewski.
</P>
<P>
   of motels to tip them off about suspicious guests who, for
instance, pay for their rooms in cash, receive a flurry of
telephone calls or, in some cases, simply speak Spanish, according
to participants. By David Kocieniewski.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
