<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-MANSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARILYN MANSON CURTAILS TOUR IN RESPONSE TO SCHOOL MASSACRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Nev., Ariz., Iowa, Minn., Mass.)   (bl)  
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Marilyn Manson, the dark, cross-dressing rock
musician, said he was canceling the last five dates on a two-month
concert tour because of last week's shooting spree in Littleton,
Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Manson, who is frequently criticized for the nihilistic strains
in his shock-rock music, described the cancellations as a show of
respect for those killed, but he also lashed out at the media for
suggesting in any way that his provocative music, or his fans,
incite violence.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have linked his music to the ``Goth'' rock culture
that some have claimed was favored by the two students who killed
13 people at Columbine High School last week. There were some
demonstrators at Manson's recent concert in Minneapolis, but no
hard evidence has emerged that the killers knew his music well or
were motivated by it.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, Manson has been accused _ largely by the
Christian right and other conservative groups, but also by
politicians like Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn. _ of depravity and
conveying negative messages in his songs. For instance, his 1994
album, ``Portrait of an American Family,'' has songs with names
like ``Cake and Sodomy,'' ``Dope Hat'' and ``Misery Machine.'' And
in concerts in past years, which were far more incendiary than the
current tour, he has led fans in chants like, ``We hate love. We
love hate.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement announcing the suspension of his tour, Manson,
whose real name is Brian Warner, rejected assertions that his songs
or any other music had incited the tragic violence. His current
concerts, based on his latest album, ``Mechanical Animals,'' is
more in the glam rock tradition of the 1970s and is not as
sepulchral as some of his previous music. He acknowledged, though,
that it would be a show of respect to put off further performances
of his brand of hard rock for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a great atmosphere to be out playing rock 'n' roll
shows, for us or the fans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``The media has unfairly scapegoated the music
industry and so-called Goth kids, and has speculated, with no basis
in truth, that artists like myself are in some way to blame. This
tragedy was a product of ignorance, hatred and an access to guns. I
hope the media's irresponsible finger-pointing doesn't create more
discrimination against kids who look different.''
</P>
<P>
   Manson planned to proceed with a concert scheduled for Wednesday
night in Cedar Rapids, Iowa, said his record company,
Nothing/Interscope. Then he will cancel scheduled stops in Reno,
Nev.; Fresno, Calif.; Las Vegas; Phoenix, Ariz., and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, a radio station in Denver, KBPI, canceled a concert
scheduled for April 30 at which Manson's band was one of several
scheduled to play.
</P>
<P>
   Even some First Amendment groups supported the cancellations.
Nina Crowley, the director of Massmic, a group in Massachusetts
that fights music censorship, said she recently attended one of
Manson's concerts and that it was hardly the sort of shocking music
for which he had been known in years past. She added, ``From a
First Amendment perspective, I think he should go on. But I think
the cancellations are respectful. It acknowledges that he cares
about his fans and he realizes what the parents and the kids must
be going through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
