<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGAL FEE CLAIM IN TOBACCO DEAL MAY LEAD TO CORNYN-MORALES
FACE-OFF 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Attorney General John Cornyn on Wednesday asked
for a possible courtroom face-off with his predecessor, Dan
Morales, over a claim by a Morales friend for about $260 million in
legal fees in the tobacco case.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn told U.S. District Judge David Folsom of Texarkana that
the court could dismiss Houston lawyer Marc Murr's claim without
calling witnesses in a hearing scheduled for May 6.
</P>
<P>
   But if Murr is allowed to testify, Cornyn asked that Folsom also
allow the state to question Morales and Morales' former first
assistant, Jorge Vega, about the scope of Murr's work on the
tobacco suit.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn opposes Murr's claim for fees and is investigating his
involvement in the tobacco litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Morales negotiated a $17.3 billion settlement from cigarette
makers last year, but the agreement also sparked a lengthy dispute
over fees paid to outside lawyers who also represented the state.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco companies have agreed to pay $3.3 billion to five other
private lawyers hired by Morales on a contingency contract. Murr
had a separate agreement with Morales, and cigarette makers have
resisted paying him because other lawyers on both sides of the suit
have contended Murr did little work on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, who left office Dec. 31, was unavailable for comment
Wednesday. But he has repeatedly said Murr was an important adviser
who played a crucial role in planning and developing the tobacco
suit.
</P>
<P>
   The national arbitration panel awarded Murr only $1 million, and
that is all the tobacco industry is obligated to pay him under the
Texas settlement.
</P>
<P>
   A separate state arbitration panel of three retired judges
appointed by Murr and Morales awarded Murr $260 million last fall.
The difference between that amount and the $1 million awarded by
the national arbitrators represents a potential claim against the
state, but it must be enforced by Folsom.
</P>
<P>
   Folsom ordered the May 6 hearing for Murr to ``show cause'' why
the state panel's $260 million award should not be nullified.
</P>
<P>
   Folsom said Murr and Morales had failed to comply with his order
for one of the three state arbitrators to be appointed by the
judge.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Folsom, Murr's lawyer, Roy Minton of Austin,
defended the selection of the state arbitrators. Minton said he
didn't believe testimony was necessary but said Murr and other
witnesses, including former Texas Supreme Court Justice Bob
Gammage, one of the state arbitrators, would be available to
testify if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   First Assistant Attorney General Andy Taylor, in a separate
letter to Folsom, pressed the state's motion to dismiss Murr's
claim outright. Cornyn contends that Murr's claim amounts to a suit
against the state, which is barred by the 11th Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn's position was supported by Austin attorney Pete
Schenkkan, who represents several state legislators in the case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
