<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6864 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUOMO-POVERTY-HNS &LR;      04-28 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUOMO-POVERTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUOMO CALLS FOR FOCUS ON REGIONS, CITIES ECONOMY LEFT BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Americans have no right to gloat over the vibrant
U.S. economy while hard-luck cities and regions still suffer
unemployment, poverty and population drain, Housing Secretary
Andrew Cuomo said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not a success with your Dow-Jones breaking 10,000 if
one in five children sleeps in poverty tonight,'' he said in a
speech at the National Press Club here.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo, who heads the Department of Housing and Urban
Development, invoked an updated brand of liberalism with roots in
the philosophy of his father, former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, and
his late father-in-law, former U.S. Attorney General and Sen.
Robert F. Kennedy, D-N.Y..
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said record low unemployment and high-flying gains on Wall
Street can never be the measure of economic strength as long as the
depressed areas remain.
</P>
<P>
   He called the poverty in the midst of plenty ``the great
American paradox.'' While major cities such as New York and San
Francisco are riding the wave of prosperity, places like East St.
Louis, Ill.; Buffalo, N.Y.; Texas City, Texas, and Chico, Calif.,
have been left behind, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   The HUD secretary released a report on the plight of 539 central
cities that found:
</P>
<P>
   _ Seventeen percent _ one in six _ have unemployment rates 50
percent or more above the national rate of 4.2 percent. Although
their rates are lower than they were during the recession of the
early 1990s, these areas have not seen the dramatic job growth of
other regions, he said. Yuma, Ariz., for instance, has an
unemployment rate of 18.8 percent. In Madera, Calif., it is 18.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fifty-seven cities have lost at least 10 percent of their
population since 1980. East St. Louis lost more than 30 percent;
Gary, Ind., 27 percent, and Youngstown, Ohio, 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Thirty-two percent of the cities _ one in three _ have
persistently high poverty rates. Based on HUD's own estimates and
school system figures for free and reduced-price school lunches to
impoverished students, the report put the rate for Laredo, Texas,
at 36 percent and that of New Orleans at 34 percent. Rates were
also high in parts of the Appalachian Mountains stretching from
Kentucky through West Virginia. Hazard, Ky., for instance, has a
poverty rate of 27 percent. In some cities, poverty went up for a
couple of years even as the economy improved. In Beaumont, Texas,
for instance, the poverty rate went from 21.5 percent in 1993 to
22.4 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The ``worst conditions,'' Cuomo said, are on Indian
reservations. The high school dropout rate among the Oglala Sioux
in Pine Ridge, S.D., is 70 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo did not call for massive new government spending. Rather,
he said the solution lies partly in informing the American people
about conditions in these places. ``They don't see it on the way to
work; that's not where they live,'' he said. ``We have to expose
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington must convince people that government is not the enemy
and a number of government programs such as Medicare and Social
Security do work, he said, adding that government must learn from
the mistakes of past antipoverty programs.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, he said, government tried to insulate poor people
from the market place by substituting what he termed a ``government
subsistence market.'' With welfare, public housing and food stamps,
government inadvertently divorced poor people from the mainstream
economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo insisted that HUD _ an agency with a long record of
mismanagement _ finally has cleaned up its act.
</P>
<P>
   He said it is spearheading an effort to link troubled areas with
the mainstream economy. Under HUD's $25.5 billion budget, the
agency is overseeing a $3.5 billion loan-guarantee program to
attract business to inner cities. So far, Cuomo said, there have
been ``no defaults that called for Uncle Sam to pay one dollar.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
