<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6867 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS &LR;      04-28 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHER UNVEILS INVESTMENT PLAN TO SHORE UP SOCIAL SECURITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite waning interest by the GOP leadership in
tackling Social Security, House Ways and Means Committee Chairman
Bill Archer unveiled Wednesday the broad outlines of an
investment-based plan to shore up the retirement system.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's plan would essentially divert a portion of the income
tax to create individual retirement accounts that would be invested
in a mix of stocks and bonds. Upon retirement, the accounts would
be paid out monthly, guaranteeing retirees a minimum income for the
rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Ways and Means staff members said that for most people, the
income from the private accounts would likely have to be
supplemented with Social Security funds to reach current benefit
levels.
</P>
<P>
   However, they noted that without the private accounts, Social
Security benefits are expected to drop eventually to about three
quarters of current levels because of the aging public's demands on
the system.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, R-Texas, acknowledged the growing resistance to dealing
with the complex problem this year both from inside and outside the
GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately there are plenty of politicians from both
parties who don't want to touch Social Security for all the wrong
reasons,'' he said. ``Our challenge is to put politics aside and
save Social Security for all the right reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer said he called President Clinton on Tuesday &UR;  &LR; to tell him
about the plan and ask for a meeting to discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   The president has proposed devoting most of the budget surplus
to shoring up the system. The White House proposal also calls for
government investment of Social Security funds in the private
market. It would create individual investment accounts for people
below certain incomes.
</P>
<P>
   There was little indication that the Archer plan would soon be
moving through the legislative process. The plan has not yet been
fleshed out in legislative language, nor have any hearings been set
to consider the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   It also has not yet received the blessing of the House
leadership, including Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Some GOP leaders fear that getting too far out front on Social
Security will only come back to haunt them in the 2000 election.
They distrust President Clinton's vows that he wants to work with
them to shore up the system and believe Democrats will demagogue
them on an issue regardless of what they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view it as a trap,'' said an aide to a House GOP leader.
Republicans also are not convinced that privatizing Social Security
is a winner with the voters. A recent Republican poll found
skepticism for private investment except among young adults.
Disapproval of such investments were particularly strong among
women over 45, the poll found.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being chairman of an influential committee, Archer's
proposal was not being treated as particularly special by the
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it going to be something that will be voted on the House
floor, I doubt it,'' the leadership aide said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also came under fire from conservatives and liberals.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democratic lawmakers questioned the wisdom of letting
individuals invest in the market if only a few people would reap
more benefits than they now get.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Earl Pomeroy, D-N.D. described the plan's winners as ``high
fliers and early diers.''
</P>
<P>
   He argued that the more affluent and the families of those who
died before retirement age would come out ahead. Under Archer's
plan the accounts could be transferred to an individual's heirs if
that person died before reaching retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives also criticized the proposal, saying it did not
truly privatize the system since the individual accounts would be
transferred into the Social Security system once an individual
reached retirement age rather than turned over to the beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is simply using the income tax revenue to bail out the
current system,'' said Michael Tanner, a Social Security
privitization advocate at the libertarian Cato Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner echoed Democrats' contention that the plan was not worth
the headaches it would take to administer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are are going to muck around with Social Security system
and in the end they are not going to give anybody anything they
don't have today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The contributions to the retirement accounts would come from a
tax credit that amounted to 2 percent of wages up to $77,000 _ the
income limit to which Social Security payroll taxes are applied.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals could choose from a variety of government approved
funds, which would have a mix of 60 percent stocks and 40 percent
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The plan assumes that the return for the funds would be about
5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Upon retirement the individual would receive monthly payments
from their funds. If those funds did not at least amount to the
benefit level now set for beneficiaries, beneficiaries would get
additional money from the Social Security trust fund. Social
Security would still collect the 12 percent payroll tax from
employees and employers. However, Ways and Means officials estimate
that eventually the payroll tax could be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
