<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Thursday, April 29. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
STARTOYS (Phoenix) - Lucasfilm is fending off reporters by the
dozen. The Internet is buzzing with rumors. Fans are plotting to be
first in line. And we aren't talking about the movie.
Frighteningly, this is just about the toys. At 12:01 a.m. Monday,
the Star Wars: Episode I playthings will descend upon the country
with a nearly deafening marketing roar. Retailers across the
country are planning to take advantage of the first minute of the
first date the embargo is lifted. Here's a sneak peek, mostly due
to two folks: local collector Oliver Huish, who found a naughty
Chandler K-Mart that sold toys early, and Dallas Web junkie Philip
Wise, who found his own Star Wars toy manufacturing sources in Hong
Kong. The big news: The toys can talk to each other.By JAIMEE ROSE.
Story will move in the ``A'' and ``E'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PARTNERS (Phoenix) - Chic Older works out alone so people won't see
him cry. However, Older, who is executive director of the Arizona
Medical Association, admits there are significant advantages to
working out with others.
</P>
<P>
   Health experts believe motivation is the single most important
reason for working out with others. Most people, they say, do not
have the discipline to work out solo over a long period. That, in
part, accounts for the success of health clubs and specialty
organizations where people with like interests get together to
bike, run or even walk. By THOMAS ROPP. Story moved in the ``L'
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Phoenix) - It's 12:36 a.m., my eyes fly wide open
and I find myself gasping for breath. I look at the clock and
realize that it's only been three minutes since the last time I've
blown my nose. I find my tissue and blow until I hear my ears pop.
I'm not sick. I have allergies. By LAURI NOTARO. Story moved in the
``L'' category. &QL;  &QL; 
FOODMED (Phoenix) - If Americans need proof that medical
professionals in this country don't recognize the link between food
and health, they need only check out ``the abysmal foods served in
hospitals,'' says Andrew Weil, physician, author and guru of
alternative medicine. Weil appeared on a panel discussing the use
of food as medicine at the annual conference of the International
Association of Culinary Professionals held in Phoenix earlier this
month. By BARBARA YOST. Story will move int he ``L'' category.
llrybarbara yose  &QL; 
VITAMIN COCKTAIL (Phoenix) - Ruth Kawasaki has a cocktail every
morning before work.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Tanqueray and vermouth in a seductive glass, Kawasaki
chugs a dozen vitamins and supplements with a water chaser.
Although there is no information on the number of people who take
double-figure dietary supplements daily, surveys show that more
than half of the U.S. population uses dietary supplements and
spends nearly $10 billion on them annually.
</P>
<P>
   But do they really make us healthier? And is more better? With
PHOTO. By THOMAS ROPP. Story moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) - Fire gets our attention. All heat and
light. But then the flames subside and the smoke dissipates. The
embers cool. Ashes crumble to dust and scatter in the wind. And we
forget. The name Jermaine ``J.R.'' Miguel Jr. means nothing. By
E.J. MONTINI Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL; 
