<HEADLINE>
THE SUMMER JOB FRONT 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By MOLLY FRISINGER 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer is almost here, and financially challenged teens
everywhere are looking for jobs. But even with the great job
opportunities out there lately, it is hard for kids under age 16 to
find jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Child labor laws for younger workers cause so many problems that
employers do not like to hire 14 and 15-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Figure out how to work for your mom,'' suggests high school
student Marcela Evans, 15. ``She is the only one who will hire
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the difficulties, some young teens find summer jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already had three jobs,'' said 15-year-old high school
student Lindsay Hoying.
</P>
<P>
   The most wanted jobs are at stores with great employee
discounts. Jobs at the mall and secretarial work are scarce. Most
teens end up working in grocery stores or at telemarketing
companies or fast-food places.
</P>
<P>
   The key to getting that perfect job is confidence. Filling out
the application neatly and dressing nicely for the interview help
also.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get a note from your parents saying you can work late,''
suggests Lindsay.
</P>
<P>
   With just one month left until summer, anything to get an
advantage might mean the difference between an allowance and a
paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
