<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:TEENSTALK-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVICE ABOUT GRADUATION, TATTOOS 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR TeensTalk: I'm a senior this year and getting ready to
graduate. But I missed the boat on signing up for caps and gowns.
When they came around, I didn't sign up for them because I didn't
think walking across the stage was a big deal. My mom started
crying and said I disappointed her. She said she waited her whole
life to see me graduate. Now I want to get a cap and gown, but the
school said it was too late. What should I do? _ Graduation.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR Graduation: This is a party you don't want to miss. Many
kids do not understand the importance of participating in their
graduation ceremony. This is your moment of glory. You worked 12
years to complete your education. You and your family deserve to
celebrate your accomplishment of graduating from high school.
</P>
<P>
   So check with the school and get a number from the company that
orders the graduation caps, gowns and the invitations. They have
late orders and will help you get the stuff you need.
Congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR TeensTalk: I went with some friends to a tattoo shop just
to see what it was like. I wound up getting one. I got one with a
skeleton with a drink in one hand and a cigarette in the other.
When I got home, I showed it to my parents. I didn't think they'd
mind, but they said it was embarrassing and disgusting. They said I
should have checked with them first, but this is my body and my
choice. They have grounded me for six weeks. I don't think it's
fair. What can I do? Tattoo.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR Tattoo: Your parents are in shock. They can't change what
has happened, but they can let you know that they don't approve.
And by grounding you, they are letting you know that they want you
to think before you make decisions like this in the future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do you have a problem or concern that needs an answer? The Class
Acts Teenstalk panel _ headed by Kathy Pope, a counselor at a Texas
junior college _ is comprised of teenage students who care about
other students. Write to: Teenstalk, c/o Class Acts, The New York
Times Syndicate, 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
