<HEADLINE>
A BRIEF LOOK AT THE NEWS 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 c. 1999 Compiled from reports by The Associated Press and Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEENS GUN DOWN CLASSMATES
</P>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Hurling bombs and blasting away with guns,
two students in black trench coats killed 12 schoolmates and a
teacher last Tuesday at Columbine High School, in one of the
deadliest school massacres in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen, Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, both were
members of a group of outcasts called the ``Trenchcoat Mafia.''
They killed themselves after gunning down the students and teacher.
</P>
<P>
   The pair was apparently enraged by what they considered taunts
and insults from classmates. Investigators said that the boys also
wanted to kill at least 500 others, attack nearby homes and then
hijack a plane and crash it into New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush ordered flags in Texas lowered to half
staff in response to the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so tragic is not only the loss of life but the fact
that there are people in our society who disregard human life to
the point where they will act out their fantasies and aggressions
with weaponry,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, many officials wondered how to stop violence
in schools.
</P>
<P>
   COPING WITH TRAGEDY
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For teens interested in how young people can cope
with such problems, a new interactive Web site gives kids a safe
and trustworthy place to share fears and concerns with each other.
It also offers resources to help resolve teen problems before they
get out of hand. It's at TeenCentral.Net. The site was developed by
KidsPeace, a part of the National Center for Kids Overcoming
Crisis.
</P>
<P>
   GOODBYE GREAT ONE
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wayne Gretzky, known as the best hockey player ever,
retired from hockey after two unforgettable decades on the ice,
walking away from the game he loves, despite pleas from friends and
family not to go.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old ``Great One'' said goodbye in last week's season
finale against Pittsburgh at Madison Square Garden. The New York
Rangers lost 2-1 in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this game,'' Gretzky said. ``No matter what happens,
I'm going to miss it more than anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   HELPING CHILDREN OF WAR
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Houston Rockets basketball star Hakeem Olajuwon is
trying to get children involved with relief efforts for refugees
from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon has agreed to help the Houston office of UNICEF raise
$250,000 to support children in Kosovo. He and Houston Mayor Lee
Brown met last week with students who have developed fund-raising
projects for refugee kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel privileged and am willing to play my role and help
encourage people to step up and do something _ to take
responsibility,'' Olajuwon said.
</P>
<P>
   ON A WING AND A PRAYER
</P>
<P>
   John Travolta is planning to fly around the world to welcome the
year 2000. The plan is to race across the world's time zones on the
last day of 1999, and although he plans to bring along wife Kelly
Preston, he left her at home for a recent test flight across the
Pacific in his new Boeing 707. He took off into the wild blue
yonder with some fellow flyboys.
</P>
