<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6936 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VITAMIN-COCKTAIL-AZR &LR;      04-28 2132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAMIN-COCKTAIL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SWEAR BY VITAMIN COCKTAIL AS A DAY STARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been moved to nytns photo clients)  
 (ADV: CHARTABLE MATERIAL ON DIET SUPPLEMENTS, MINERALS, HERBS, FOOD
SUPPLEMENTS  AND REGULATIONS APPEARS AT END OF ARTICLE)  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS ROPP  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Ruth Kawasaki has a cocktail every morning before
work.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Tanqueray and vermouth in a seductive glass, Kawasaki
chugs a dozen vitamins and supplements with a water chaser.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nicoletti and his wife, Lisa, do much the same. Joe tosses
down a whopping 56 pills, Lisa a dozen.
</P>
<P>
   Kawasaki and the Nicolettis, all Phoenix residents, are among
the burgeoning number of Americans who start each day with vitamin
cocktails, a practice also known as stacking, in which a dozen or
more vitamins, herbals, minerals or food supplements are taken
together as a talisman against poor health.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no information on the number of people who
take double-figure dietary supplements daily, surveys show that
more than half of the U.S. population uses dietary supplements and
spends nearly $10 billion on them annually.
</P>
<P>
   But do they really make us healthier? And is more better?
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and clinical nutritionists often refuse to endorse
dietary supplements, pointing out that many of their manufacturers'
claims to better health never have stood up under rigid, scientific
testing. Besides, they say, if most people simply ate the right
foods in the first place, they wouldn't need vitamin cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   Those who advocate alternative medicines or sell dietary
supplements agree that eating better is beneficial, but they say
the bottom line is that people don't eat what they should or they
don't eat the appropriate quantities. Some go further to say that
even if you did eat all the right foods, you'd still be lacking
certain nutrients because of the way food is processed for
large-volume sales.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the controversy is a nonplused public.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Amardeep Majhail, an inter nal-medicine specialist who
practices in the Horizon Medical Clinic in Sun City West, is not
impressed with most dietary supplements, with the exception of St.
John's wort for depression and saw palmetto for prostate problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think their popularity is due to people thinking they're
missing out on something,'' Majhail said. ``Everyone wants that
magic bullet, even though there is no scientific basis for all
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Claims made by herbal manufacturers are especially outlandish,
Majhail said.
</P>
<P>
   He cites the very popular herbal medicines echinacea and ginkgo
biloba as examples:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ginkgo has been widely touted to improve memory, but there's
been only one brave scientific study about it, and that study
showed its benefits were minute for most people,'' Majhail said.
``Same for echinacea. There's absolutely no scientific proof that
it improves immunity, yet people feel a cold coming on and that's
what they take now.''
</P>
<P>
   Kawasaki, a Phoenix family counselor, has no problem including
echinacea in her vitamin-cocktail mix when she feels a cold coming
on. She also takes vitamins A, C and E; multiple vitamins; ginseng;
fruit and vegetable supplements; a digestive aid; and whole
enzymes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know these things work because of my energy level, and I
don't get sick very often,'' Kawasaki said.
</P>
<P>
   Nicoletti, an ABCO employee, said he's spending about $100 a
month on his habit of taking 56 dietary supplements a day. He began
taking them last September. Included in his pill troupe are
stomach-acid stimulators, St. John's wort, multivitamins, calcium,
magnesium and co-enzymes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I eat a lot of fast food,'' Nicoletti said, ``so I've always
taken vitamins, just never in this extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   He began his current massive dietary-supplement program after
talking to a nutritionist who analyzed his nutrient deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   An older-brother pharmacist also guided him.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all I know, this could be hogwash,'' Nicoletti admitted.
``But I do feel better. I had a problem with being exhausted all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Francis, a staff pharmacist for CIGNA HealthCare, also
takes echinacea for colds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does work,'' Francis said. ``Instead of having a cold for
seven days, I'll only have it for four when I take echinacea.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis, who has a special interest in alternative medicines,
especially herbs, is convinced echinacea is more than just a
placebo, as some medical experts insist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a situation where I expected it to work,'' Francis
said. ``I was very skeptical.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis, like Majhail, believes food is the best source for
obtaining nutrients, but feels dietary supplements are also
beneficial if used appropriately. She is not an advocate of
stacking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the approach where you individualize it,'' Francis
said. ``If I'm a post-menopausal woman worrying about osteoporosis,
I'm going to have a different need than if I'm diabetic. Just to
take a (multi) vitamin that has a little bit of everything in it is
not a good idea. Our bodies are made to take what they need to
maintain health, and anything else is excess.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Lessman, owner of the Winning Combination, a
nutritional-supplement manufacturer in Henderson, Nev., said mixing
dietary supplements is normally not harmful. He and his products
are regularly featured on the Home Shopping Network.
</P>
<P>
   Lessman, a former biochemistry and medical-school student, takes
issue with Majhail and other physicians who condemn dietary
supplements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The medical community, by and large, does not have the benefit
of a great deal of information and education in this area,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lessman said he's been putting folic acid in his products for 20
years and was told by doctors that he was foolish. It wasn't until
January of this year that the U.S. Public Health Service announced
that folic-acid supplements are beneficial for pregnant women. It
reported that during the first weeks of pregnancy folic-acid
supplements can cut by 50 to 70 percent a woman's risk of having a
baby with a neural-tube defect, in which the brain and spinal cord
form improperly.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration now requires food manufacturers
to fortify grain products with folic acid.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the gap between physicians and patients seeking
alternative medications has given rise to a new niche in the
medical field: the intermediary nutritional consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Zachow of Scottsdale is an independent distributor for a
large dietary-supplement manufacturer, Body Wise International,
based in Tulsa. She's also the wife of Valley physician William E.
Zachow. Recently, she launched a program called PPIP _ Putting
Prevention Into Practice _ in which she consults with doctors on
behalf of patients who would like to take nutritional supplements.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of patients are going to their doctors and saying,
`Look, there are so many products out there. What works, what
doesn't? Can you help me?' I work hand in hand with physicians in
letting them know what is available and the research behind the
products.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many physicians are reluctant to endorse dietary
supplements for reasons that go beyond whether the supplements
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we see is that patients sometimes focus so
much on their dietary supplements that they forget to take their
prescription medications, which really help them,'' Majhail said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, despite their gentle nature, there still can be risks in
mixing certain combinations of minerals and vitamins. He tells a
story from his own practice of a woman who had chronic diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't understand why,'' Majhail said. ``When we found
out she was taking all these vitamins and supplements, we had her
stop them, and the diarrhea immediately disappeared.''
</P>
<P>
   Vitamins A and D are quite notorious for causing toxicities,
Majhail said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vitamin K can neutralize a lot of medicines, like blood
thinners,'' Majhail said. ``Patients who have a propensity for
developing kidney stones, if they keep taking calcium and vitamin
D, they will be causing themselves more harm than good.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis, the CIGNA pharmacist, said vitamins adversely can
affect certain antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've found that calcium, iron and magnesium will bind up a
new group of antibiotics for upper-respiratory problems so they're
not absorbed into your body,'' Francis said. ``If you're taking a
multivitamin, don't take it with an antibiotic. Wait a couple
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale allergist Dr. Michael Manning sees his share of
patients who are allergic to certain medicinal herbs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Francis points out that alternative medicines, and
Chinese medicine in particular, have been around a lot longer than
modern medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``So there's something to it,'' Francis said. ``And as a
pharmacist, I see the side effects of the modern medications I
dispense. They're not free of risks, either.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Popular dietary supplements &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Common uses:  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vitamins &QL; 
A _ For skin, immune system and eyes. &QL; 
B _ For general metabolism; pernicious anemia; Alzheimer's
disease. &QL; 
C _ For general metabolism; prevention of colds. &QL; 
D _ For stronger bones. &QL; 
E _ For the nervous system; antioxidant for cancer; may enhance
sexual performance. &QL; 
K _ For bleeding disorders; promotes stronger tissues and bones. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Minerals &QL; 
 &QL; 
CALCIUM _ To help prevent osteoporosis. &QL; 
IRON _ For iron-deficiency anemia; stimulates bone-marrow
production of hemoglobin.  &QL; 
POTASSIUM _ Promotes regular heartbeat; maintains water balance in
body tissues and cells. ZINC _ Maintains normal taste and sense of
smell. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Herbal supplements &QL; 
 &QL; 
ECHINACEA _ May relieve symptoms of cold and flu. &QL; 
DONG QUAI _ May relieve menstrual pain. &QL; 
GARLIC _ May protect against infection; relieves indigestion. &QL; 
GINKGO BILOBA _ May aid in treatment of memory loss associated with
Alzheimer's disease; increases circulation to the brain and lower
extremities. &QL; 
GINGER _ For nausea and vomiting; for motion sickness. &QL; 
GINSENG _ May improve appetite and digestion; reduce stress;
stimulate brain, heart and blood vessels. &QL; 
KAVA KAVA _ May reduce anxiety. &QL; 
ST. JOHN'S WORT _ May reduce depressive moods. &QL; 
SAW PALMETTO _ Used to treat symptoms of enlarged prostate. &QL; 
VALERIAN _ For insomnia. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Food supplements &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEE POLLEN _ May decrease allergy symptoms. &QL; 
CREATINE _ Popularized by Mark McGwire, promotes weight gain; may
improve strength. &QL; 
MELATONIN _ For fatigue; may slow aging. &QL; 
WHEAT GERM _ Nutritional source; may improve physical stamina. &QL; 
Sources: ``Vitamins, Herbs, Minerals &AMP; Supplements'' (Fisher Books)
by Dr. H. Winter Griffith and ``The Over-The-Counter Drug Book''
(Pocket Books) by Dr. Michael B. Brodin.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
2) CAUTIONS &QL; 
Negative reactions &QL; 
Dietary supplements and various medicines may have negative
interactions. Never guess if taking medications and supplements at
the same time. Ask your doctor or pharmacist about potential
conflicts. &QL; 
Known negative interactions include: &QL; 
- Vitamin K and blood-thinning medications may decrease the
effectiveness of the blood-thinning medication.  &QL; 
- Certain antibiotics and multivitamins can prevent antibiotics
from working. &QL; 
- Vitamin D and antacids with magnesium may cause too much
magnesium in blood, especially in people suffering kidney failure. &QL; 
- Vitamin D and diuretics increase risk of hypercalcemia (too much
calcium in the blood). &QL; 
- Mixing certain supplements together also can cause problems. The
most common negative reaction is one supplement preventing another
from being absorbed. Some reactions can be more serious. Potassium
and calcium, for instance, increase the possibility of heartbeat
irregularities. Supplements alone also can have bad reactions in
people allergic to them. Adverse reactions include:  &QL; 
- Bee pollen may cause itching. &QL; 
- Echinacea may cause dermatitis.  &QL; 
- Kava kava may cause drowsiness. &QL; 
- Ginkgo biloba may cause diarrhea or headaches. &QL; 
- Magnesium may cause abdominal pain or appetite loss. &QL; 
- Vitamin A may cause hair loss or bone-joint pain. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
3) REGULATIONS &QC; 
Dietary supplements &QL; 
In 1994, the Dietary Supplement Health and Education Act was
established for Food and Drug Administration regulation of dietary
supplements. Effective in March, the following information must
appear on the labels of dietary supplements: - Statement of
identity (for example, ginseng). &QL; 
- Net quantity of contents (for example, 60 tablets). &QL; 
- Purpose for using product with the disclaimer that it has not
been evaluated by the Food and Drug Administration. &QL; 
- Directions for use. &QL; 
- Facts panel (serving size, amount and active ingredients). &QL; 
- Other ingredients in descending order of prominence. &QL; 
- Name and place of business of manufacturer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
