<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6941 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERPUBIC-MULLEN-BOS     04-28 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERPUBIC-MULLEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MULLEN SELLS MAJORITY STAKE TO INTERPUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Mullen, the third largest ad agency in New England and
the region's largest independent agency, has sold a majority stake
of its business to a unit of the Interpublic Group of Cos., the New
York conglomerate that last year bought Boston ad agency Hill,
Holliday, Connors, Cosmopulos.
</P>
<P>
   In the rapidly consolidating ad industry, Mullen is the third
big ad agency to be purchased by an outside-the-region
communications company in the last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal announced Wednesday, Mullen will keep its
autonomy; founder Jim Mullen will remain chief executive of the
Wenham agency for the next few years and there will be no layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Said Mullen: ``I want to stabilize the future of this company.
This was an opportunity to preserve our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullen's clients include L.L. Bean, Swiss Army Brands, and
Polartec. Mullen was recently hailed as the region's ad agency of
the year by Adweek New England, a trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed, but ad agencies have
generally been selling for 1 to 1.5 times annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Given that independent ad agencies are becoming increasingly
scarce, Mullen may have fetched a premium price, said Adweek New
England editor Judy Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen had revenues of about $38 million last year, and IPG's
Lowe Group division is buying a 70 percent equity position in
Mullen, according to sources. That would mean the deal could be
worth from $27 million to $40 million in cash and IPG stock.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors are driving consolidation in the ad industry.
</P>
<P>
   First, many agency founders are nearing retirement. For Mullen,
58, the sale is a way to cash out his investment.
</P>
<P>
   A similar dynamic partly prompted Ed Eskandarian to sell Arnold
Communications to Snyder Communications of Maryland last year and
Jack Connors to sell Hill Holliday to IPG.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many client businesses are looking to hire agencies
with global reach, ones that can offer a wide range of services
including public relations and Internet marketing. Today a regional
ad agency may be too small to handle the marketing chores of a big
multinational corporation like Gillette Co.
</P>
<P>
   To address the needs of global giants, publicly traded
communications conglomerates have sprung up. Buoyed by a bull
market, these companies have used their rising stock shares to help
finance strings of acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, firms such as IPG, Omnicom Group, and True
North Communications have bought ad agencies, PR firms, and
direct-marketing shops as they seek to put together portfolios of
communications companies that can provide soup-to-nuts marketing
services to even the largest of clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a steady stream of acquisitions for the last 10
years,'' said William Blair &AMP; Co. analyst Anthia Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Under those circumstances, it was almost inevitable that Mullen
would be snapped up, and founder Mullen said he had talked with
many suitors in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   In other industries, acquisitions generally mean that two
companies are blended into one, with the smaller company often
losing its identity and some of its work force as efficiencies are
sought. But acquisitions are different in the ad industry.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from its creativity, an ad agency's most valuable assets
are its paying clients. If an acquisition causes some clients to
defect, the acquisition loses some of its value.
</P>
<P>
   What would cause a client to defect? Suppose two ad agencies
represented two rival banks. If the two ad agencies joined forces,
one of the banks would almost surely leave, fearing that
proprietary information might be leaked to its competitor.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent client defections, a company such as IPG keeps the ad
agencies it buys separate and autonomous. As a result, it's not
unusual for two ad agencies owned by the same holding company to
compete against each other for a prospective client's business.
</P>
<P>
   So even though Mullen and Hill Holliday are now part of the same
New York company, don't expect them to be mingled.
</P>
<P>
   With this acquisition, Ingalls of Boston becomes the region's
largest independent ad agency. Ingalls had capitalized billings of
$141 million in 1998. That compares with Mullen's $254 million,
Hill Holliday's $707 million, and Arnold's $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   What impact will the sale of local ad agencies to outsiders have
on the region? That's not immediately clear. On one hand,
acquisitions often accelerate growth at the purchased ad agency and
create more local jobs, Adweek's Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The downside is less tangible'' and unlikely to be apparent
until the ad agencies' founders step down, something not expected
to happen for another few years, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But as an agency evolves from an independent privately owned
shop to part of a publicly traded company, at which the goal is to
maximize profitability, the contributions and pro bono work local
agencies do for local charities could decrease, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades ago, Boston was a branch office for big New York
ad agencies, said Skip Pile of Pile and Co., a Boston consulting
firm. Then several young men, notably Mullen and Connors, decided
to help open their own local agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've now gone through a 30-year cycle,'' Pile said.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, IPG shares fell 2 5/16 to 78
after hitting a 52-week high earlier in the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
