<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-WILSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILSON PUTS IT ALL TOGETHER WITH THE BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Landon Wilson insists it was not his formal
introduction as a bona fide National Hockey Leaguer. Dave Karpa
certainly would disagree _ if he could remember anything about the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson turned the Carolina defenseman into a virtual hologram
with a calamitous check that forced a giveaway and set up the
Bruins' first goal Monday night at the FleetCenter. No matter that
Boston went on to lose the game, 3-2, and trailed in the
best-of-seven Eastern Conference quarterfinal, 2-1, when the teams
took the ice Wednesday. Wilson couldn't be blamed _ for a pleasant
change.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that the 6-foot-2-inch, 215-pound right wing was one
of the Bruins' few effective forwards through the first three
games, throwing around his weight _ and Hurricanes _ with abandon.
The Karpa pancake was merely Exhibit A.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his fourth pro season with his third organization,
it seems that Wilson finally has fit together the pieces of a game
that had been a Rubik's Cube for him since Toronto chose him with
the 19th pick in the 1993 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a reflection of the way the team is playing, the
way my linemates (Sergei Samsonov and Joe Thornton) are playing,''
said Wilson. ``We're playing well together.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there are differences of opinion as to why the
24-year-old is emerging as a force after a maddening shuttle
between the minors and the NHL with Colorado, which acquired him
from the Maple Leafs in 1994, and Boston, which sent a first-round
draft pick to the Avalanche to get him on Nov. 22, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who played just 22 regular-season games with Boston in
1998-99, believes his development is the inevitable result of
increased playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more ice you get, the more confidence you get,'' said
Wilson. ``When I was up before, I was playing on the fourth line,
getting maybe five shifts a game. I was up for injury purposes. I
knew I wasn't here to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns sees the equation in reverse: The extended
activity is the product of Wilson's belated development, which
Burns has been awaiting since he was coaching Toronto when the
Leafs drafted the University of North Dakota star.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was with Toronto,'' said Burns, ``I was told about all
the things we're seeing now _ a big, strong player.''
</P>
<P>
   What Burns really means is that Wilson finally is playing big
and strong. That wasn't consistently the case in the past; hence,
Wilson's failure to stick in the majors, regardless of his
revisionist history about lack of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The maturity part is coming into play,'' said Burns. ``That's
the big thing. He wasn't always sure what he wanted to do (in terms
of playing style). People say, `Why don't you tell the player what
he has to do?' Well, you do tell him. But you can talk to him all
you want. It has to come from within the player. When you talk to
him enough, sometimes you say, `If you want to be that way, then go
ahead down.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That kept Wilson on the commuter track to Providence amid a
series of unsuccessful flings with Boston. This season he
established himself at the AHL level, earning first-team All-Star
honors despite playing just 48 games between recalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing my game consistently in Providence, night in and
night out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The question was whether he ever would figure out how to do that
at the top level. Burns, who could see the tantalizing traces of
potential, had begun to wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping he was going to mature during this lifetime of
hockey,'' said the coach.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more perplexing, Wilson comes from a hockey
pedigree _ two uncles played in the NHL and his father, Rick, is an
NHL veteran who now serves as an assistant coach in Dallas. Yet
Wilson still wasn't getting it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to his father a little,'' said Burns. ``And I talked
to Landon a lot. I think he's one of those guys who needs
(guidance).''
</P>
<P>
   Burns always has felt it was worth the effort. ``I liked Wilson
in Toronto,'' he said. ``When you get a big, strong player like
that, you've got a player for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Which seems to have arrived for Wilson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
