<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS HAVE TO BE THEIR OWN BEST FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Well, yes, you want to win because that's the basic
object of the exercise, isn't it? You win, and then you advance to
another seven-game series, and then another, and the next thing you
know you're playing for the championship and if you win that you
get to skate around holding up The Cup and Jeremy Jacobs might even
dismount his golden throne and shake your hand, presuming, of
course, that he can even tell his Swedes from his Russians from his
Ukranians from his Canadians from his Americans from the Crunch and
Munch Man.
</P>
<P>
   You play to win; that's a given. But _ and this is not exactly a
major news bulletin _ the 1999 Boston Bruins aren't really playing
to win the Stanley Cup. That's in the realm of fantasy for many of
the participants, not including the Senators and Mighty Ducks, each
of whom have already cleaned out their lockers following
first-round sweeps. Anyway, who doesn't know that the Stanley Cup
winner is coming out of the West?
</P>
<P>
   That said, there is still a lot to play for, particularly if you
are Pat Burns and what your team basically consists of is a lead
dog and a bunch of pups. There is no George Allen thing going on
here. The future for this hockey club most assuredly is not now. He
is trying to build something here, and the primary gauge of a
successful 1998-99 season is for his team to win a series. Not win
the Cup. Win one series. Anything after that, frankly, will be
gravy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important for this team to win a series,'' asserts
38-year-old resident legend Raymond Bourque, the obvious lead dog
on this sled. ``We have a lot of young guys and we need to take the
next step so they can experience the feeling. Last year they got a
taste of what it's all about by getting into the playoffs. Now if
we can win a series it will be an important step in their growth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year our goal was to get into the playoffs,'' confirms
Burns. ``This year the goal was to get into the playoffs and
advance. We're not going to build Rome in two years.''
</P>
<P>
   The youth of this team is truly astonishing. Burns suited up 18
non-goaltenders for Wednesday's Game 4 against the Carolina
Hurricanes, and 12 of them were 25 years of age or younger.
Combined winning playoff series of the 11: zero (0).
</P>
<P>
   (itals)What could Ray Bourque possibly have in common with these
kids? He remembers 45s. He probably saw the Beatles on Ed Sullivan.
He stumbled through an entire childhood without Velcro.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting,'' maintains Burns. ``Having a team this young
is exciting for the organization and for the city. But I do have to
maintain a different frustration level.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids.
</P>
<P>
   There are 25-year-olds (Hal Gill, Darren Van Impe, Mattias
Timander). There are 24-year-olds (Anson Carter, Landon Wilson, Ken
Belanger). There are 23-year-olds (Jason Allison, P.J. Axelsson,
Shawn Bates). There is a 21-year-old (Kyle McLaren). There is a
20-year-old (Sergei Samsonov). And there is a 19-year-old (Joe
Thornton).
</P>
<P>
   Kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things that can't be taught by a coach,'' Burns
says. ``They have to be experienced. You can talk to these young
players all you want, but in order for them to absorb certain
things they have to live it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of all this youth there is one very intriguing
individual. ``I'm tired of losing,'' declares that wily old veteran
McLaren.
</P>
<P>
   Surely McLaren must be an exception here to this youth thing.
C'mon, coach, doesn't a guy with 264 games combined regular-season
and playoff experience qualify as a ``veteran,'' even though he
won't turn 22 until June 18?
</P>
<P>
   Burns shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a `veteran' if you go by seniority,'' says the mentor,
``but he's still learning. He has to be shaken up every now and
then. He has to learn that if you want to win you have to come to
practice prepared to work every day and that you can't be running
around out there wildly, that you've always got to be in control of
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that McLaren feels like a weary veteran when it
comes to this playoff business. He engaged in his first playoff
series as an 18-year-old rookie three years ago. The Bruins went
down in five games to the Florida Panthers, and it certainly made
an impression on him. ``I looked around the locker room and there
was no emotion on the faces of the veterans,'' McLaren recalls.
``You could hear a pin drop in that room. That was a team people
thought was good enough to go all the way at the start of the
season and no one was ready to go out in the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't even get in the playoffs two years ago. Last year the
Bruins re-entered the Stanley Cup process, but lost out to the
Washington Capitals in six games. This year he'd like to stick
around. After all, he hasn't really won anything in, oh, seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to think back to my hometown (Humboldt,
Saskatchewan),'' he says. ``It was a great feeling to win the
Western Canada championship when I was 14. But this is 10 times
bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   At least.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win because I want to win, not just to get a taste
of playoff success,'' says Allison. ``But it would definitely be a
big step for us. It would help us down the road to know what it
feels like. I've won two World Juniors and a Calder Cup, so I have
something to relate to, but it's not the same as winning something
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Ray Bourque remembers when Don Cherry was a coach, not a
national institution. Ray Bourque predates SUVs. Ray Bourque grew
up using a dial phone. Ray Bourque played with Cashie, Cheesie,
Doakie, Schmautzie, and Nifty, not to mention Gentleman Jean
Ratelle and Brad Paaahk.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting,'' Burns repeats. ``It's important for these
kids to go through all the emotions _ the highs and the lows.''
</P>
<P>
   They already know about the lows. Now they must provide
themselves with a high.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
