<HEADLINE>
EPA CHIEF BOOSTS FEDERAL OPEN-SPACE PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Warning that Americans' quality of life is under siege
from sprawling development and traffic jams, President Clinton's
top environmental official came to Boston Wednesday to promote new
federal programs that would protect open space and help create
neighborhoods where people can walk to the corner store.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Browner, administrator of the US Environmental Protection
Agency, said that 1,200 acres of open space are developed in New
England every week, while traffic congestion costs people scores of
hours a year in wasted time.
</P>
<P>
   Browner said Clinton wants to help local and state governments
turn the tide, and has proposed a $10 billion no-interest bond fund
to protect land and $1.6 billion to reduce road congestion and
boost mass transit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our cities, towns, and communities . . . need help if they are
to be vibrant in the century to come,'' said Browner, speaking in a
Ford Hall Forum lecture at the Boston Center for Adult Education.
``The president's livability agenda is giving them the tools they
need to get that job done.''
</P>
<P>
   This Clinton agenda, a favorite of Vice President Al Gore, is
aimed at national anxiety over such trends as development that
creates long commercial strips at the expense of downtowns and a
burgeoning suburban population that must drive practically
everywhere they go.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, voters confronted a record 240 environmental ballot
initiatives, approving $7.5 billion in state and local spending
mainly to preserve land from development. In Massachusetts, Cape
Cod residents approved a 3 percent surcharge on their property
taxes to preserve land.
</P>
<P>
   In response, EPA has promoted redevelopment of former industrial
land in cities, and held a conference on sprawl in Boston this year
that was attended by nearly 1,000 people. In addition, Clinton
proposed his Better America Bonds to buy land in his state of the
union speech.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives have attacked Clinton's livability plans, doubting
that there is a role for the federal government in such local
matters as highway planning and oversight of development.
</P>
<P>
   But Browner said there is a national interest in creating
``livable'' communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a human cost here. Studies say we lose two full
working weeks a year, or more, stuck in traffic,'' said Browner. In
addition, she said the economy loses $74 billion a year in lost
work and wasted fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Browner said she envisioned an America where
``families won't have to burn a quart of gas to get a quart of
milk. Parks will sprout on abandoned industrial sites that are now
unsafe for children. And stands of trees, protected from
development, will protect rivers and creeks for the wildlife that
need them and the families that want to enjoy them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 1940EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6950 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      04-28 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLIT PERFORMANCE LEAVES MARKET FLAT, ANALYSTS CONFUSED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chemical, paper and other stocks sensitive to the
business cycle turned in another strong performance Wednesday while
technology and other longtime market leaders sagged.
</P>
<P>
   The sharply split performance, which resulted in a flat market
overall, left analysts struggling to figure the significance of
this month's sudden but erratic revival of cyclical stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market doesn't have a well-organized, broad-based economic
theme to support itself anymore,'' said Christine Callies, chief
investment strategist at Credit Suisse First Boston. ``It's
confusing. The market goes in several different directions at
once.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, driven by cyclical stocks,
sailed above the 10,900 mark for the first time but swooned late in
the session and managed to hang on to only 13.74 points of a gain
that had swelled to more than 103 points. Still, the one-tenth of a
percent rise, to 10,845.45, was a new high.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, meanwhile, lost 52.04 points, or 2
percent, to 2,550.37, as software and computer stocks slumped, led
by Amazon.com, which fell 12 3/8, to 193 1/2. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index fell 11.89 points, or nine-tenths of a percent, to
1,350.91.
</P>
<P>
   All of the top-performing blue-chip stocks from Wednesday stand
to benefit from stepped-up global economic growth. Alcoa added 6
5/8, to 62; Dupont rose 4 3/8, to 73 1/2; Minnesota Mining and
Manufacturing climbed 3 11/16, to 84 1/2; Exxon increased 3 1/4, to
81 1/2, and Allied Signal was up 3 1/16, to 59 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest drags on the Dow were IBM, down 7, to 205, and
American Express, down 5 11/16, to 133 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing continued rotation away from consumer stocks,
particularly pharmaceuticals, into industrial companies and oils,''
said Timothy Woolston, a portfolio manager at Boston Advisors.
Merck fell 2 13/16, to 70 3/4, and Johnson &AMP; Johnson dropped 2
7/16, to 99 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Vernon Winters, chief investment officer at Mellon Private Asset
Management, called America's large-capitalization growth stocks
``perhaps the most overpriced asset'' in the world. Money should
flee them, he said, and ``flow to the broader universe of stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Dow Chemical jumped 8 1/2, to 126 1/2, to lead a strong showing
by chemical companies. The paper group featured Mead, up 4 3/4, to
43 5/16, with the aid of a recommendation by Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter; Bowater rose 5 7/8, to 52, after earnings fell less than
expected, and Georgia-Pacific increased 4 1/16, to 94 1/8. Its gain
is now above 60 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The most actively traded issue, McKesson HBOC, the biggest drug
wholesaler, was one of the biggest casualties. It plunged 31 1/4,
to 34 1/2, after restating earnings because of improperly recorded
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna joined the long list of big companies that beat Wall
Street's expectations this spring and its shares soared 10 1/8, to
92. But America Online, whose report after the close on Tuesday did
little better than match forecasts, dropped 10, to 143, still more
than eight times its price on Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq, which fell for a second consecutive day after five
advances, reflected losses in its dominant high-technology sector,
with Microsoft, down 1 7/8, to 82 1/8, having the biggest effect.
Next were Cisco, which was down 3 5/16, to 111 3/4; Dell, which
fell 1 9/16, to 41 5/8, and Amazon.com. Ebay skidded 16 11/16, to
192 9/16, and Yahoo fell 11, to 173 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   The Morgan Stanley Cyclical index jumped 2.6 percent, its
biggest gain since April 15, and lifted its gain for the month to
more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, volume was a moderately heavy
951.79 million shares as 1,753 stocks rose and 1,279 fell. New
52-week highs were made by 82 issues compared with 28 new lows.
</P>
</TEXT>
