<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: UNMASKING POVERTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Calif., Ill., Ariz., Mich., N.Y.)  (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cities have not been in the news much lately. Crime is down,
unemployment is down and the ghettos are not burning down. What's
to cover?
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Monica and impeachment, the war in the Balkans,
high school massacres and Hillary's quest for fulfillment, the
status of daily life in places like Rochester, N.Y., or Flint,
Mich., is _ to most people _ not worth thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   But now comes Andrew Cuomo to awaken us from our urban snooze.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a booming national economy and the creation of millions
of jobs, many American cities still face a bewildering array of
very serious problems. In an important new report called ``Now Is
the Time: Places Left Behind in the New Economy,'' Cuomo, the
secretary of housing and urban development, argues that the current
economic environment ``offers the best opportunity in a generation
to effectively address these problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Feel-good stories about the economy are waved in our faces like
pompoms, making it easy to miss the astonishing fact (to cite just
one example) that the poverty rate for the city of Miami is 42.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   That should be unacceptable, and a big story. But it's not even
part of the national consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Most cities are doing reasonably well. But Cuomo's report,
released Wednesday in Washington, says that one in three central
cities are struggling with persistently high poverty rates, one in
five are experiencing steady population losses and one in six are
faced with chronically high unemployment rates.
</P>
<P>
   The problems are pervasive. According to the report, ``The
comparatively high unemployment areas, most of which are small or
mid-sized cities, are found throughout the nation, from farm cities
to former industrial giants, from timber towns to former mining
centers: Yuma, Ariz., saw its unemployment rate fall modestly, from
19 percent in 1992 (pre-recovery) to 18.8 percent in 1998; Madera,
Calif.'s rate fell more than 5 percent over the last six years but
remains high at 18.3 percent; North Chicago, Ill., saw a modest
drop from 10.7 percent in 1992 to 10.3 percent last year; and
unemployment in Yakima, Wash., has declined from 13.7 percent to
10.2 percent, still more than twice the national average in 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   The jobless rate in Madera, Calif., or Yakima, Wash., is not
high on the list of most Americans' concerns. They are out of sight
and far out of mind. And even in big cities like New York and
Chicago, the ugly pockets of poverty and joblessness lie hidden and
neglected in the shadows that surround the glittering economic
successes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This economy is in some ways deceptive,'' said Cuomo. ``It is
so strong that it has generated almost an economic euphoria. But
when you look at the numbers underneath, you see a widespread group
of cities and counties which are lagging behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Because most of the country is doing well, and because of the
residential and employment patterns that have emerged in the last
few decades, most Americans never see the areas of extreme economic
distress, and don't encounter their fellow citizens who are
struggling.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said that as he traveled the country talking about these
problems, the reaction he frequently got was surprise. ``You have
to expose it because people don't see it anymore,'' he said.
``They're surprised that it still exists.''
</P>
<P>
   The report lists what it describes as the economic successes of
the Clinton administration, including the creation of 18 million
jobs, the lowest peacetime unemployment rates in decades, decreases
in poverty rates among blacks and Hispanics, and a record rate of
home ownership.
</P>
<P>
   But despite those successes, the report says in its conclusion,
``The great project of our nation _ extending opportunity to all _
remains incomplete.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems of America's cities are not limited to the cities.
They have bled into the suburbs and they are evident in many areas
of chronic economic distress, including Appalachia, the Mississippi
Delta region and many of the nation's Indian reservations _ places
Cuomo refers to as ``economic flatliners.''
</P>
<P>
   If those problems are not forcefully addressed when the national
economy is strong and budget surpluses are huge, said Cuomo, then
when?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
