<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS LOOK TO KHRISTICH'S SCORING KNACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In search of . . . Dmitri Khristich.
</P>
<P>
   Headed into Game 4 of the Bruins-Hurricanes Eastern Conference
quarterfinal series Wednesday, Boston coach Pat Burns went
sleuthing for his top-scoring right wing. Khristich disappeared in
the first three games, totaling only one shot across 197 minutes,
and it didn't take an ex-cop, with a summa cum laude in street
sense, to figure out that Khristich was the key to the Bruins
getting back in the series.
</P>
<P>
   When Burns found Khristich, he delivered the obvious message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him this morning, `Deemer, you're frustrating me, and
I'm frustrating you,' '' Burns said following a workout at the
FleetCenter, where the Bruins were looking to even the seven-game
series at two wins apiece. ``He's frustrating his teammates, and
they're frustrating him. He's got to get his head up and get
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Burns dismissed any temptation he might have had to
sit out Khristich or reduce the enigmatic winger's ice time for
Game 4. In fact, he eschewed a kick in the derriere and instead
went with a vote of confidence. Rarely seen on the ice in the late
stages of Game 3, Khristich was penciled in to be back on a line
with Jason Allison and Sergei Samsonov, setting him up for ample
ice time and a chance to play himself back into good graces.
</P>
<P>
   Does that line sound familiar? It should. For the better part of
two seasons, the trio has formed Boston's top performing line.
After three games in which the Bruins barely scratched together an
offense against the scrappy 'Canes, it was Burns's attempt _
perhaps his only remaining hope _ to find a way back into the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Look, Deemer, I've been a good supporter of you,'
'' said Burns. ``But I also said, `Now I want something back.'
Heck, we need his goals.''
</P>
<P>
   No Bruin scored more goals than Khristich during the regular
season. He potted 29, most of them when riding with Samsonov and
Allison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the line combinations the last two years,'' said
Allison, thinking ahead to the night's reuniting, ``no one's played
as well as us. If we can find that again, we'll be a tough team to
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Headed into the postseason, the Bruins were confident that they
had a bonafide two-line attack, with Allison skating much of the
time with Steve Heinze and Anson Carter. Jumbo Joe Thornton
finished the regular season with Khristich and Samsonov, in part
because Allison was nursing a sore wrist in the final weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But when Game 1 opened, Thornton was sidelined (strained
sternum), leaving Samsonov and Khristich with Randy Robitaille, a
loaner from the Baby B's of Providence. Allison remained with
Carter and Heinze. In short, nothing clicked. Rob DiMaio and Ken
Belanger had the Game 1 goals, a 2-0 Boston victory. But in Games 2
and 3, with Thornton back, the Bruins dropped to a 2-1 series
deficit in large part because they couldn't establish any first- or
second-line presence.
</P>
<P>
   Khristich, in particular, looked lost. It's one thing to take
shots and miss, or get stoned by the goalie. But Khristich wasn't
even in the play. He skated aimlessly, shift after shift, returning
to the bench zombie-like, his gaze fixed to the floor until it was
again his time to roll over the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through these things before, too, and it's tough,''
said Allison, reflecting on Khristich's cold spell. ``I went
through it when I was in Washington and, hey, I went through it for
25 or 30 games this year _ a stretch when I wasn't playing well at
all. It's not as if you're not trying, but it's like, no matter
what you do out there, it doesn't accomplish anything. It's hard to
describe.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond wanting the obvious, such as a handful of goals, Burns
was looking for the Allison-Khristich-Samsonov trio to play a
smart, simple game. To wit: Allison and Khristich had to commit
themselves to grinding the puck low in the offensive end and
Samsonov, if not leading the play across the blue line, could swoop
in as an effective trailing shooter. Samsonov, emphasized Burns,
could not concern himself with making fancy plays, a trademark,
though crowd-pleasing at times, that too often can lead to costly
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confidence is such a big part of coming out of something like
this,'' said Allison. ``But you can't just say, `Hey, I'm
confident.' It's not that easy. You just have to keep playing until
you get into a zone, or a flow, and then you're all right. Even if
he's not scoring, Deemer's still good in our end. There are some
guys, all they can do is score. Otherwise, they're no good to you
at all. In fact, they hurt you. But Deemer's good defensively, he
can play the penalty kill _ he can do a lot more than score
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   All true. All vital. Every team needs quality, complete players,
and Khristich has been that for most of his two years in Boston.
But for the first three games in the spring of '99, he showed up
with a noticeable chunk missing from his repertoire. He wasn't
skating. He wasn't shooting. He wasn't even noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than send him to the dungeon, Burns chose to boost him
back to the No. 1 line. Did he have a choice? Not really. He could
have slipped Cameron Mann or Ken Baumgartner into the equation, but
Burns didn't see that as addition by subtraction.
</P>
<P>
   Game 4 was Khristich's chance to come back to the dance. And
everyone waited to see if heard the music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
