A6956 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-0429C     04-28 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-0429COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE VOTES TO RESTRICT ANY GROUND WAR
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (i) international categories
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A divided House of Representatives voted Wednesday
to restrict President Clinton's power to wage a ground offensive
against Yugoslavia, but stopped short of ordering him to withdraw
U.S. forces from the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   In their first formal response to the five-week-old air war, the
lawmakers voted 249-180 to deny funding for ground troops unless
the president wins authorization from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The House rejected a measure to require Clinton to bring home
the U.S. forces involved in the NATO operation, 290 to 139. It also
trounced a proposal, with only two ``yes'' votes, to make a formal
declaration of war against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The practical effect of the action on ground troops was
uncertain, since the Senate would have to pass a similar bill,
which could then be vetoed by the president. Moreover, several
senators have introduced a proposal that would extend the
president's authority to use ``all means necessary,'' including
ground troops, in the Balkan struggle.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, the emotional daylong debate aired long simmering
disputes over the the U.S. role in the Balkans, the
administration's conduct of the war, and whether Congress has a
constitutional duty to play a role in the decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not even be in the Balkans,'' said House Armed
Services Chairman Floyd D. Spence, R-S.C. ``The national security
of the United States is not at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the mission countered that Americans had an
obligation to stop the assaults on ethnic Albanians by the forces
of Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosovic. ``The voices of
appeasement and isolationism are reverberating in these halls,''
said Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., who fled the Nazis during World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   Other members complained that there were no good options. Rep.
Herbert H. Bateman, D-Va., said the Balkan conflict offered ``one
of the most dismal range of policy choices this House has ever been
asked to make.''
</P>
<P>
   The president had attempted to preempt the House action by
reassuring lawmakers in person and through a letter in which he
wrote the would seek their consent before deciding to wage a ground
war. In remarks outside of the White House during the House debate,
the president said he was asking the lawmakers to follow the
example of unity set by the NATO summit last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stressed that the 19 NATO allies are speaking with a single
voice,'' he said. ``America must continue to speak with a single
voice as well.''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., told his
colleagues that it was unnecessary to pass a law requiring
authorization to expand the air assault into a land operation.
``The president said he would not as a practical matter ask for an
introduction of ground troops without coming here and taking the
time to ask us for a vote,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That assurance was not enough for some members. Rep. Lindsey
Graham, R-S.C., one of the managers who conducted the impeachment
trial in the Senate against Clinton, told his colleagues: ``I do
not have the confidence'' that Clinton will seek a vote before
ordering troops into ground action, he said. ``Now's the time to
speak, more than less, sooner rather than later, before we get a
lot of people killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the House refused to go along with a resolution by Rep.
Tom Campbell, R-Calif., to withdraw the troops from the conflict.
Using the provisions of the War Powers Act of 1973, Campbell had
single-handedly forced the House leadership to schedule the debate
on the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment that we never had in Vietnam we now have,'' he told
his colleagues. ``We have a chance to stop it before we get in too
deep.''
</P>
<P>
   Until this week, the congressional leadership had shied away
from a public debate over the conflict, and the White House had
strongly discouraged it. Minority Leader Gephardt told his
colleagues, ``Mr. Milosevic will be listening carefully to what is
being said here today.''
</P>
<P>
   But once the issue was joined, critics opened up on the Clinton
policy. House Majority Whip Tom Delay, R-Texas, called for pulling
out now. ``Was it worth it in Vietnam?'' he asked. ``In Lebanon,
(President) Ronald Reagan cut his losses and withdrew the troops''
after a barracks was bombed. ``We should do the same thing before
the body bags start coming home. What good have we done? None.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the members chose a more middle of the road
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``No military action should have been initiated in the Balkans
without prior approval of Congress,'' said Rep. Lloyd Doggett,
D-Texas. ``But with this conflict already underway, it would be
folly not to consider the facts on the ground. An immediate exit
would send the wrong message to Milosevic and to other petty
tyrants around the world from Iraq to North Korea, and it could
defeat our goal of ensuring peace and
</P>
<P>
   stability in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
