<HEADER>
A6978 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WOMEN-BOYCOTT-NYT     04-28 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WOMEN-BOYCOTT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVENPORT: WOMEN READY TO BOYCOTT THREE SLAMS OVER LACK OF PARITY
IN PRIZES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Grand Slams don't pay, they won't play. Tired of
receiving second-class treatment on the payrolls of three of the
sport's four Grand Slams, the women who make their living from
professional tennis may resort to a boycott to bite the hand that
feeds them _ but feeds the men more _ if the three shallow-pocketed
Slams don't make a millennial motion toward equality.
</P>
<P>
   Billie Jean King calls it a potential ``girl-cott.'' Bart
McGuire, the WTA Tour's chief executive officer, calls it a
militant maneuver he hopes his troops won't deploy. Lindsay
Davenport, who sits on the tour's Player Council, calls it a
possible future payback for past and present slights.
</P>
<P>
   If Wimbledon, currently the most chauvinist of the Slams in its
pay scale, doesn't announce a raise Thursday for this year's event,
don't look for many female players at Wimbledon next year: they
just may have other plans for that particular fortnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't actually spoken to any of the players about
boycotting, but I think the players need to be ready for it,'' said
Davenport, who earned a record $700,000, the same as the men's
champion Patrick Rafter, for her 1998 U.S. Open title. ``Obviously
we can't expect to see total equality this year, but we need to see
some goals set for it to happen soon.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the money debate began in January with a plaintive
piece of rhetoric from Venus Williams and some unanimous advice to
the tour from the four business advisers on its council.
</P>
<P>
   Williams surveyed the year's first Grand Slam, the Australian
Open, and came away unconvinced that the bigwigs behind the
tournament couldn't find a way to ante up the measly $200,000 that
separates the men and women from fiscal equality on its $10 million
payroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you even want to play in a place that doesn't give
you equal prize money with the men?'' asked the 18-year-old
Williams. The answer is that the women don't want to. And if things
don't change at the Australian Open, French Open and Wimbledon, all
of which ignore the U.S. Open's 25-year tradition of awarding equal
prize money, perhaps the women won't play them until the concept of
equal remuneration becomes universal. ``The ladies need to get
together on this one,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Nudged along by the four business advisors, who urged the
council's eight player members to make gender equity on the Grand
Slam payrolls a top priority for 1999, some of the players did get
together.
</P>
<P>
   This month, they assembled their discontent into a petition that
demands equal pay at the Grand Slams, a document decorated with
signatures from the top-ranked player Martina Hingis and No. 2
Davenport (Steffi Graf is the only top player uninterested in the
issue) as well as 50 others.
</P>
<P>
   They supported McGuire, in a series of strongly worded documents
and orations to the chairmen of all three Grand Slams, and added
the petition as further ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   They were mildly approving when the French Open, citing the
increased entertainment value provided by the women's game, bumped
up their prize money to within 90 percent of what the men receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French moved about a third of the way in the right
direction,'' McGuire said. He also noted the Australian Open, which
in 1995 reneged on its decade-old policy of equal pay, gave the
women a slightly larger raise than the men this year. But a 6
percent discrepancy persists, which is why Martina Hingis collected
$529,600 while Yevgeny Kafelnikov received $563,200.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one that hurts us the most is the one where we had equal
prize money and then they took it away,'' Davenport said about the
Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Tobin, president of the International Tennis Federation,
commiserated. ``In recent years, the Australian Open has moved from
prize money parity,'' he said, ``which is a pity, but I hope will
be redressed soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the players are waiting to see what happens Thursday
at Wimbledon, when the All England Club will announce its 1999
prize money. Last year, they shortchanged the women by 20 percent.
Pete Sampras took in $717,750 with his title, while Jana Novotna
settled for $645,975.
</P>
<P>
   McGuire is aware that players are judging his performance _
under scrutiny as well for the tour's trouble in landing a title
sponsor _ on the response his pleas for parity inspire from
Wimbledon. In his own defense, McGuire pointed out that the three
Slams in question ``are played in countries where there's nothing
comparable to Title IX in the legal system or in the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   But McGuire made it clear that now is not the time for the
players to be threatening boycotts. ``Strikes and boycotts are the
atomic bombs of dispute resolution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not even King is comfortable slinging a word like boycott
around. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This probably isn't the right time to go for the girl-cott,''
said King, who was a willing party to the one that got women's
professional tennis off the ground 30 years ago. ``But if the Slams
don't come through with something like a three-year plan to put
things on an equal level, then the boycott becomes an option. My
take on this is that first you do things diplomatically; then you
fight.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
