<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE DEVILS DON'T DARE LOOK AHEAD
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the Devils' road to what they hope will be the Stanley Cup,
they are not only trapped in a backup at a toll booth, but they
also know the highway is even more jammed beyond the next exit.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Devils win their opening round playoff series with
the Pittsburgh Penguins, which resumes Friday night in the
Meadowlands, their next opponent is already established: the
Buffalo Sabres, alias Dominik Hasek, hockey's most dreaded
goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Devils are looking past the Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' coach Robbie Ftorek said. ``We've got to
play Tom Barrasso and the Penguins.''
</P>
<P>
   What else would any coach say? One of sports' oldest
commandments is: never look ahead. But left wing Dave Andreychuk,
who was once Hasek's teammate in Buffalo and still lives there in
the off-season, acknowledged thinking about the Sabres' goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told the people at my golf course not to let him on,''
Andreychuk said, joking. ``The Sabres have 10 days off now. That's
a long time to stay sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the Devils, at least publicly, don't dare look past the
Penguins, it is only because they don't want to see what they know
is there: Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   While the Devils were squaring their best-of-seven-game series
with the Penguins at 2-2 with a 4-2 victory in Pittsburgh on
Tuesday night, Hasek and the seventh-seeded Sabres were sweeping
the second-seeded Ottawa Senators, the Northeast Division
champions, out of the Eastern Conference playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Over the four games that included a 30-minute overtime, Hasek
allowed only six goals, a 1.33 goals-against average. With 156
saves, his save percentage was .963, even better than his
league-leading .937 during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek again proved the value of a ``hot goaltender'' in the
playoffs. Although the Sabres have never been good enough as a team
to win the Stanley Cup, he lifted them to the conference final last
year. And the Devils know he is capable of ending their cup hopes
this year _ if they survive the Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek is a candidate to be the NHL's first-team All-Star
goaltender for the fifth time in the last six seasons and he could
win his fifth Vezina trophy. He earned the Hart trophy as the
league's most valuable player the previous two seasons. During last
year's Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan, he dominated the Czech
Republic's gold-medal victory.
</P>
<P>
   During the recent season, the Devils had a 1-1-1 record against
Hasek, who permitted only five goals in those three games, but four
occurred in a rare 7-4 shootout in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   All the Devils who played in the 1994 opening round playoff
remember Hasek from the sixth game, the Sabres' four-overtime, 1-0
victory as he made 70, count 'em, 70 saves, before Dave Hannan's
goal shortly before 2 o'clock in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils won the seventh game, 2-1, then eliminated Boston
before losing to the Rangers in seven games in the conference
final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hasek's amazing,'' Andreychuk said. ``In practice once, we had
to send him off the ice because we couldn't get the puck past him.
He made you lose your confidence. When we asked him how he did it,
he didn't have an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   But another reason the Devils can't worry about Hasek yet is
because they are quietly worrying about their own goaltender.
Martin Brodeur, with a 2.52 goals against average and a shaky .877
save percentage in the Penguins series, hasn't been as consistent
at making the big save as he was when the Devils won the 1995
Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a more intense effort Tuesday night that limited the
Penguins to 18 shots, the Devils weren't dominant in their two-goal
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to play with the same heart and passion,''
defenseman Ken Daneyko said. ``If we let up, we're not going to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   And Friday night Jaromir Jagr, the league's leading scorer with
127 points, is expected to be in uniform for the Penguins after
having missed three games with a groin injury. Look for the Devils
to pound him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the opportunity is there, you've got to take the body,''
Daneyko said. ``Jagr is a big guy, the best player in the league.
You've got to match his size and strength. If you don't, you're
going to get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Devils won't get to go against Dominik Hasek in the next
series. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
