A6981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUG-INFORMER-NYT &LR;      04-28 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-INFORMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAINTED INFORMER FOR U.S. IN DRUG CASE COULD GET $10 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Mexico, Colombia)  (bl) 
 By TIM GOLDEN with CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As federal prosecutors went to trial here against
a group of Mexican bankers and accused drug traffickers implicated
in the biggest investigation ever into the laundering of illegal
drug money, their evidence seemed overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the suspects had been caught on hidden cameras as they
negotiated with undercover U.S. Customs agents about how to hide
millions of dollars in illicit funds. A half-dozen defendants had
pleaded guilty rather than face a jury, and several of them agreed
to testify against their former associates.
</P>
<P>
   But now a crack has appeared in the government's case as defense
lawyers have focused on a mysterious Colombian-born informer who
was at the center of the undercover operation _ and who could
receive almost $10 million for his help.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether the prosecution will be weakened
seriously by disclosures about the informer, a former emerald
dealer named Fred Mendoza. But the trial has already focused new
attention on how law-enforcement agencies use informants in the
money laundering investigations that have become a central part of
the fight against the drug trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the trial hinged on his testimony, we might be in big
trouble,'' one senior customs official said of Mendoza. ``But
without this guy or somebody else like him, we never would have
made a case like this in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the first of four scheduled trials in connection with the
customs investigation known as Operation Casablanca, law
enforcement officials said Mendoza had been recruited in part
because he had no criminal record and was not wanted for any crime
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   While they acknowledged that his value as an informer stemmed
from the contacts he had developed in the drug underworld, they
also insisted that he was a brave and honest man who was motivated
by more than just money he might make.
</P>
<P>
   But as Mendoza prepared to begin testifying last week against a
first group of six Mexican defendants, one customs official
acknowledged in court that the informer's earnings could reach
perhaps 10 percent of the $101 million that the government has
frozen or seized in the case. And even then, law-enforcement
officials said, Mendoza would not become the most highly paid
informer federal law-enforcement agencies have ever employed.
</P>
<P>
   What may be more damaging to Mendoza's credibility, though, are
allegations disclosed to the defense by prosecutors indicating that
their star witness may have been considerably more involved in drug
trafficking than at least most of the government officials involved
in the case had known.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza, a boyish looking man in his 40s, was known to the
bankers and accused traffickers in the case as ``Javier Ramirez.''
The Mexicans, having been introduced to Mendoza by drug traffickers
associated with the Cali cartel in Colombia, believed him to be the
boss of a big Colombian money laundering operation run out of
warehouse offices in an industrial suburb of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza's bona fides in the underworld were in fact quite good _
and far better than Customs officials acknowledged before the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning in court and in his confidential debriefings
by customs agents, Mendoza said he was drawn into the drug trade in
1989, when, as a gem dealer in Los Angeles, he sold $150,000 worth
of emeralds to a new customer from Colombia. The customer turned
out to be a reputed drug trafficker named Luis Enrique Puentes, and
he quickly discovered that he had been sold a cache of emeralds
worth only about one-third of what he paid.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza said that after he told the trafficker he had already
spent most of the money, he was forced to work off his debt as a
drug money courier, making seven or eight deliveries of cash to
storefronts and offices in the jewelry district of downtown Los
Angeles. Although Mendoza's activities eventually brought him under
the scrutiny of federal agents who were then pursuing another huge
money laundering investigation, he was never arrested.
</P>
<P>
   According to a confidential customs report based on the
debriefing of an FBI informant in Houston on March 23, Mendoza also
had a hand in arranging for one or more cocaine flights into Mexico
in the early 1990s. A copy of the report was obtained by The New
York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials said some of the Houston informant's claims
were patently false: He asserted, for instance, that Mendoza had
been an associate of Amado Carrillo Fuentes, the late Mexican
trafficker against whom Operation Casablanca was directed.
</P>
<P>
   But Mendoza did admit in court to having helped with the
arrangements for a flight of 1,320 pounds of cocaine into Mexico in
1992, and said he became a customs informant in 1995 only after he
was kidnapped and held for 18 days by traffickers demanding payment
on a debt owed by his brother, a drug trafficker already working
for customs.
</P>
<P>
   The federal judge presiding over the trial, Lourdes Baird,
barred lawyers from introducing the Houston report about Mendoza as
evidence. But she allowed defense lawyers to draw from it in
cross-examining Mendoza, and one of them, Michael Pancer, used the
information to suggest that he had been less than candid with his
customs handlers and less than noble in his past activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were willing to profit on the misery that that drug gives
people?'' Pancer asked, referring to cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir,'' Mendoza finally said.
</P>
<P>
   Under contracts with the Customs Service, the officials said,
Mendoza could receive as much as $7.5 million in rewards, in
addition to slightly more than $2 million that he has already
received in commissions on the money he helped to launder, other
fees and the reimbursement of his expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law-enforcement agencies generally cap their payments to
informers at one-fourth the value of the assets seized in an
operation, or no more than $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Customs Service, however, has been especially liberal in
circumventing those limits with contracts like the ``personal
service agreements'' that Mendoza signed. Customs agents say it has
often helped them to recruit better informants than those of the
FBI or the Drug Enforcement Administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
