<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KATZENBERG TESTIFIES DISNEY RENEGED ON BONUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jeffrey Katzenberg, testifying over the last two
days about his angry relationship with his former employer, Walt
Disney Co., said his 10 years at the studio had proved to be ``a
lie'' because of a dispute with Michael Eisner, the Disney
chairman, over a huge bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg's testimony came in the second phase of a trial in
which the former studio chief contends that Disney owes him at
least $250 million, based on an agreement that was to have given
him 2 percent of the profits on films including ``The Lion King,''
``Beauty and the Beast,'' ``Aladdin'' and ``The Little Mermaid,''
and spinoffs from them.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's general counsel, Louis Meisinger, who spoke scathingly
to Katzenberg, has argued, essentially, that while Katzenberg was
owed some bonus money, the former studio chief was not defrauded or
duped by Eisner. ``The purpose of all this is to embarrass Disney,
and not focus on the valuation,'' Meisinger said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Meisinger, in questioning Katzenberg, contended
that the former studio chief had endured numerous flops in 1994 _
when Disney's film division, under Katzenberg, had an operating
loss of $231 million. At the same time he depicted Katzenberg as a
shrewd negotiator _ one who would not have allowed any ambiguity in
his own contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is being presided over by a retired Los Angeles
Superior Court judge, Paul Breckinridge.
</P>
<P>
   It is highly unusual for two such powerful and high-profile
Hollywood moguls to bare not only their public anger at one
another, but also details about compensation.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Katzenberg testified that as early as 1984, after he
joined Disney, the company offered him a 2 percent share of the
profits from films and television shows placed in production or
acquired for distribution during his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, he said, Eisner and Frank Wells, the
president of Disney, offered him a seven-year deal to extend his
contract to 1997. They offered, among other things, a base salary
of $750,000 a year, an option on 500,000 shares of Disney stock, a
$1.5 million ``cash flow safety net'' over and above his salary and
a beach house that the company would buy. But they wanted
Katzenberg to give up his 2 percent bonus. He rejected the deal,
saying of the bonus, ``It was the most important element of my
original deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg said that a new deal was signed in 1988, allowing him
to leave the company as early as 1994, three and a half years into
his contract, without forfeiting the bonus. But Katzenberg said he
was informed by a Disney lawyer in 1993 that, if he left the
company early, he might forfeit his bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, Katzenberg said, his attorney, Arthur Emil, was
told by Wells to ``read the contract.'' Katzenberg said he phoned
Wells to say ``that I didn't understand why a game is being played
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg said he told Wells, ``If I worked for this company
for 10 years under a lie, I couldn't possibly stay another day. I
was furious.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells replied that he would speak to Eisner about the matter,
Katzenberg said, adding that Wells was ``the peacemaker'' and ``the
person who kept Michael and I working together.''
</P>
<P>
   In April 1994, Wells was killed in a helicopter crash, and
Katzenberg left within months. He said Eisner ``told me he did not
want me to stay with the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, Katzenberg said, he had two meetings with Eisner,
one in which the company chairman came to his home and another at
the Disney offices, but the bonus issue remained unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg, whose lawyer at the trial is Bertram Fields, left
Disney officially in September 1994, and sued in April 1996. Eisner
is expected to testify next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
