</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-AID-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: WORDS IN NEED OF ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin's proposal for reforming
international financial institutions, announced on the eve of this
week's gathering of the world's finance officials in Washington,
was greeted mostly with yawns. His ideas were described as modest
or cautious _ mere tinkering in a financially hazardous world that
cries out for bold architectural overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem with Rubin's proposal, some prominent economists
say, lies not with its cautious ideas. Professor Barry Eichengreen
of the University of California at Berkeley argues that modest
reforms are what are needed. ``The problem with Rubin's policy
announcement,'' he said, ``is too little follow-through.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hufbauer of the Institute for International Economics
agrees. ``Rubin failed to outline concrete steps that would
translate pleasant words into effective action.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial crisis struck Asia hard in the summer of 1997, spread
to Russia and Brazil last year and continues to threaten Japan and
China. The International Monetary Fund intervened but could not
prevent steep recessions in any of the countries. The question that
lingers is how to stop currency crises before they spread.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin would discourage the use of pegged exchange rates _ rates
that are temporarily linked to the dollar but easily abandoned
during crises. Countries inevitably run out of dollars to prop up
their currency, accelerating the flight of investors and
precipitating a currency crisis. ``At the center of each recent
crisis,'' Rubin argues, ``has been a rigid exchange-rate regime
that proved ultimately unsustainable.''
</P>
<P>
   To discourage the practice, Rubin would, with caveats, deny
large bailouts to countries that peg their currencies. That could
persuade most developing countries to adopt floating rates or
currency boards, which bind the value of a currency to the dollar
with no easy way to opt out.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin also proposed that creditors bear more of the cost of
bailing out insolvent governments. And he wants developing
countries to accept fewer short-term loans, the kind that cause
creditors to flee at the first whiff of financial trouble. That
prescription might encourage developing countries to adopt measures
that the industrialized powers have historically opposed, including
taxes on short-term capital loans.
</P>
<P>
   Economists point out that it takes more than hortatory language
to achieve Rubin's goals.
</P>
<P>
   To force creditors to bear some of the cost of bailing out
insolvent governments requires rewriting contracts that govern the
issuing of their bonds. Those contracts would need to allow a
majority of creditors to renegotiate on behalf of all bond holders
rather than require unanimous consent. The bond contracts would
also need to require creditors that sue delinquent governments to
share settlements with all bond holders. Only then could creditors
as a group accept lower interest payments rather than driving the
debtor government into default.
</P>
<P>
   But, Eichengreen points out, no developing country can rewrite
bond contracts on its own. If Ecuador tried to write anti-creditor
provisions into its contracts, creditors would take their money
elsewhere. There is, however, one country that could proceed with
impunity. Eichengreen says that Rubin could have announced that the
United States would take the lead and incorporate majority voting
and settlement-sharing provisions into its bond offerings, giving
cover for other countries to mimic.
</P>
<P>
   Hufbauer makes a similar point about Rubin's call for steering
developing countries away from short-term loans. Rubin could have
made headway had he proposed, for example, that the banking
authorities in the United States impose higher reserve requirements
on banks that make such loans. Rubin calls instead for
international guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Hufbauer and Eichengreen are more supportive of Rubin's decision
to avoid the many grandiose ideas that have been proposed to solve
the international financial crisis. Some want to create an
international ``lender of last resort'' _ an international central
bank that would make loans to distressed governments, just as the
Federal Reserve does to distressed banks in the United States.
Others call for an international agency, modeled on Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp., to insure foreign loans. The idea would be to
reassure skittish investors that their loans were safe so they need
not bolt at the first signs of financial stress.
</P>
<P>
   But Eichengreen exposes the flaws of ambitious institution
building in a book published earlier this year. International
pledges to insolvent governments encourage investors to take
unwarranted risks.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, international authorities cannot provide unlimited
loans or insurance to individual governments or banks without the
right to halt activities that threaten solvency _ an invasion of
sovereignty that no proponent of these new institutions has yet to
tackle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
