<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6988 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-SOCSEC-NYT &LR;      04-28 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-SOCSEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO HOUSE REPUBLICANS UNVEIL SOCIAL SECURITY PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to breathe life into the dying effort to
shore up Social Security, two pivotal House Republicans laid out a
plan Wednesday that they said would assure the retirement system's
long-term health without cutting benefits or raising taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would plug the projected hole in Social Security's
balance sheet by taking trillions of dollars in government revenues
in coming decades and giving the money to individuals in the form
of tax rebates. Workers would then have to invest that money in the
stock and bond markets through individual accounts, with the
proceeds going to help finance their retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Although the proposal is similar to the approach advocated by
most Republicans, it has been shunned by the party's leaders, in
part to avoid what they fear would be a losing political fight with
Congressional Democrats and President Clinton. As a result, the
plan has virtually no chance of passage, and some members of both
parties said Social Security was all but dead as a substantive
issue until after the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan's Republican authors, Reps. Bill Archer of Texas,
chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee, and Clay Shaw of
Florida, chairman of the Ways and Means subcommittee on Social
Security, said they intended to push ahead anyway, in the hope that
they could create momentum for bipartisan negotiations this year.
</P>
<P>
   Insuring that Social Security can weather the impending
retirement of the vast baby-boom generation and be there for future
generations should be a matter of ``principle over politics,'' said
Archer, who is retiring from Congress at the end of this term.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides said he believed that a deal was still possible.
The president is to plot his next move in a strategy session with
his advisers on Thursday, and administration officials said they
were not considering any dramatic new proposals.
</P>
<P>
   But they said they would look for ways to make a gesture to
Archer and other Republicans. Among the options on the table are
technical changes in the way Clinton's current plan would use the
surplus to help Social Security. Also being considered is an effort
to convince Republicans that Clinton's proposal for a new type of
individual retirement account outside of Social Security could be
part of a package to strengthen the system.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to nurture the remnants of bipartisan good will on the
issue, White House officials gave the Archer-Shaw plan a gentle
reception Wednesday, saying they objected to some of its components
but appreciated Archer's willingness to tackle a subject that many
Republicans have been loathe to touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This looks like a serious attempt to engage in a very
important debate,'' said Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Although many House Democrats attacked the plan, others,
including Rep. Charles B. Rangel of New York, the senior Democrat
on the Ways and Means Committee, muted their criticism. After being
briefed on the plan by Archer and Shaw on Wednesday afternoon, some
Democrats on the Ways and Means Committee said the plan, while
deeply flawed, could be the basis for negotiation if the Republican
leadership is willing to engage on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Without any changes, Social Security will run short of money
needed to pay promised benefits starting in 2034, after the
retirement of the baby boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's approach relies largely on using the projected budget
surplus to bolster Social Security's finances and allowing the
government to invest a portion of the retirement system's reserves
in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The Archer-Shaw plan uses the same basic tools but in very
different ways. All workers would receive a tax credit from the
federal government each year equal to 2 percent of the 12.4 percent
payroll tax that finances Social Security benefits. Because the
payroll tax currently is only levied on the first $72,600 of wages
(the amount is adjusted each year for inflation), the maximum
annual credit would be $1,452.
</P>
<P>
   The money would automatically be deposited in a Social Security
account in the worker's name. The worker would then choose from
among a variety of mutual funds, all of which would be required to
hold 60 percent of their assets in stock indexes and 40 percent in
high-grade corporate bonds. Any gains in the account would
accumulate tax free.
</P>
<P>
   At retirement, the money in the account would be used to help
finance the worker's Social Security benefit. All workers would
receive at least as much as promised under the current system,
regardless of how well their investments do. Those workers whose
accounts do particularly well would come out ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the plan has two major flaws. It relies on
federal budget surpluses to finance the tax credit, and the surplus
is likely to be exhausted sometime in the next several decades,
they said. And it creates what Democrats said would be an unwieldy
system of more than 100 million individual accounts that would be
very expensive to administer.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was also unpopular among conservatives, who said it did
not go nearly far enough to give individuals control over the new
retirement accounts and did not allow them to reap enough of the
benefits at retirement.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While the chances of reigniting serious bipartisan negotiations
this year remain dim, some members of both parties said there may
be an opportunity now to look at other compromise proposals,
including one being developed by Rep. Benjamin L. Cardin, D-Md.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to the Republican desire to shift more control to
individuals, Cardin's plan would establish savings accounts within
Social Security but would have them supplement the current system
rather than replace part of it. In an attempt to appeal to
Democrats, Cardin's plan would also allow the government to invest
a portion of the system's money on Wall Street, but only under
restrictions that would limit political meddling in the investment
decisions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
