<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6989 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTERPIECES-VIDEO-$A     04-28 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTERPIECES-VIDEO-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADD EGG YOLKS AND VOILA! ART!  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DEBORAH SOLOMON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `MAKING MASTERPIECES'
</P>
<P>
   A three-video set written and presented by Neil MacGregor. Home
Vision Arts. $79.95. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Should you happen to be in the mood to paint your own
Renaissance-style altarpiece, I know the perfect video for you.
``Making Masterpieces'' takes you into the conservation lab of the
National Gallery in London and shows you how artists achieve their
special effects.
</P>
<P>
   Neil MacGregor, the museum's director, is a man in love with
artists' materials, and here he offers step-by-step instructions on
such fascinating if not exactly timely techniques as hammering
Florentine coins into gold leaf (you will need it for your halos)
and creating a rare shade of vermilion paint from a substance
excreted by Polish insects.
</P>
<P>
   Originally televised in six segments on the BBC in London, the
video adds up to a sly revisionist argument. MacGregor believes
that stylistic revolutions in art owe less to their creators than
to the materials they favored, from the lapis lazuli stones of the
Middle Ages to the cadmium colors invented by 19th-century
chemists.
</P>
<P>
   Angst, draftsmanly genius, an obsession with one-point
perspective, Cezanne's radical geometry: all the standard
explanations for masterworks are blithely pushed aside here.
Ingredients get the starring role. Artists are merely the servants
who use them.
</P>
<P>
   As MacGregor sees it, the great turning point in art history
occurred in the Netherlands in the 15th century, with the invention
of oil paint. Artists had previously bound their pigments in egg
yolks, an imperfect medium, in part because yolk dries with a
dullish matte finish (just think of an eggy plate left too long on
the breakfast table).
</P>
<P>
   Oil paint, by comparison, is a greasy miracle. It can capture
the sparkle of sunlight and, conversely, the murk of shadow. It
prepared the way for Caravaggio, Rembrandt and other Old Masters,
whose fabled use of light-dark contrasts imbued their pictures with
a drama and psychological inwardness that could not be achieved in
egg.
</P>
<P>
   A second turning point came in 1841, when John Rand, an American
painter living in London, invented the collapsible metal paint
tube. This meant, in effect, that artists could suddenly take their
materials anywhere _ that they no longer had to stay in their
studios, grinding pigment with linseed oil and storing it in pigs'
bladders, which worked fine for centuries but was a bit of a
headache for artists not fond of jabbing organs.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of the paint tube brought on a vogue for plein-air
painting; among its practitioners was Vincent van Gogh, whose
pigment-laden landscapes are evidence, according to MacGregor,
``not of a tortured personality but of a flourishing paint
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   One presumes the comment was intended as a joke, but even so, it
hints at the reductive approach that ultimately mars the video.
Seeing MacGregor at a table, chirping away as he cracks an egg into
a bowl and whips up a batch of tempera paint, you begin to feel as
if you are watching Julia Childs in the kitchen. He fails to
acknowledge that it takes more than the right ingredients to make a
great supper, not to mention Leonardo's ``Last Supper.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
