<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-TWINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAPP SNAPS SOX LOSING SKID IN CONFIDENCE BUILDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
Red Sox9, Twins4 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The pieces Wednesday started to fit for Pat Rapp.
And it couldn't have come at a better time for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Rapp's sixth-inning contribution to a 9-4 rout of the Minnesota
Twins did more than snap a two-game skid against a team Boston
should be able to handle. It went a long way in restoring the
club's confidence in the big righthander who had been impressive in
spring training but struggled in his first three starts, all Red
Sox losses.
</P>
<P>
   With the status of Bret Saberhagen a question mark, it is vital
that one of the other starters be ready to step up. If it's not
Mark Portugal, who couldn't hold a four-run lead in a 6-4 loss
Tuesday night, it has to Rapp, a veteran who was 12-13 for the
Kansas City Royals a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight day, the Sox took a 4-0 lead. But Rapp
refused to cave in to the pesky Twins, limiting them to six hits
and one run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been messing with my mechanics since spring training,''
Rapp said when asked how it turned things around Wednesday. ``And I
was trying to find a happy medium where I wasn't off balance and
out of synch. Today, I just tried to slow everything down. Last
week I felt like I was throwing the ball 200 miles per hour. When I
do that, it takes away from my location and my speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the game went on, I was able to work my sinker in there a
little more, use my changeup and try to hit my spots. It turned out
a lot better than my last three games. The long ball has been
killing me. I've given up six. So I just tried to stay calm, pitch
down in the zone all day, and try to get some double-play balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Rapp got two double plays and didn't yield a homer.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had been outhustled Tuesday night, but not Wednesday. In
the third inning, Boston took advantage of wildness by Twins
starter Mike Lincoln, who gave up a single to Darren Lewis and the
first of three walks that were issued to Trot Nixon. A wild pitch
allowed both runners to advance into scoring position. One run came
in on a sacrifice fly by Jose Offerman, a second on a ground out by
John Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Boston built the lead to 4-0 as Lincoln again had
trouble finding the plate. Brian Daubach, making a rare start at
first, led off with a double to right-center and advanced to third
on a wild pitch. Daubach then was caught off the bag on a grounder
to second by Jason Varitek, but Varitek was able to reach second
during the rundown. After Nixon's second walk, Offerman came
through with a two-run triple.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln left after the fourth, and the Sox jumped on his
replacement, Joe Mays, for four runs in the sixth. Nixon hit a solo
home run in the seventh, his second of the season, and scored four
runs on the day. Not bad for a guy hitting .105.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more patient today and more relaxed,'' said Nixon, who
couldn't remember a game in which he had three walks. ``With my new
stance I feel very comfortable. By cutting out all the extra
movement, I can see the ball better.''
</P>
<P>
   All the Red Sox saw the ball better judging by the 11-hit output
against four Minnesota pitchers. Boston stranded six more runners,
but it is not a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have base runners,'' said manager Jim Williams, ``the
opportunities are there. Even though we have left some bodies on
base in a couple of games, I'd rather do that than not have anybody
on.
</P>
<P>
   Of Nixon, Williams said, ``If the kid takes a walk three times,
it just shows his patience at the plate. You never know what will
happen when you give young players an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he was especially pleased with Rapp's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real good competitor for me,'' said Williams. ``He made
some pitches when he had to and he made some double plays. Offerman
and Nomar (Garciaparra) really had outstanding games. They made
some nice plays, including both double plays and several other
stops up the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Garciaparra and Jose played a great game today,'' said Rapp.
``They were catching everything in the hole, double plays left and
right. It kept us in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox simply can't afford to take things for granted on
offense or defense, said Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we'd get on a pitcher early, score some runs, and
that was it,'' Garciaparra said. ``Today, we jumped on the pitcher
and just kept going. That's nice. That's what we have to do. You
can't always assume the game is under control. That's not always
the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did get busy out there today. But that's all part of it.
You've got to play on both sides of the ball. If the pitcher feels
comfortable on the mound and in control of their game, that's
important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
