A6995 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMBLING-COMMISSION-A     04-28 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-COMMISSION-ART-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PANEL TO SEEK MORATORIUM ON EXPANSION OF GAMBLING INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV 13 : Photo is being sent to NYT 14  photo clients.
Non-subscribers 15  can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BRETT PULLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal commission is preparing to send Congress
and the president sweeping recommendations for the gambling
industry, including a moratorium on expansion and some form of
government regulation of the giant casinos on Indian reservations.
</P>
<P>
   But after two years of studying the economic and social effects
of gambling, the National Gambling Impact Study Commission is
likely to issue a report that, as expected, leaves major commercial
casino operators free of federal regulation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the moratorium, the commission, meeting here for
two days this week, is likely to recommend that all forms of
Internet gambling be prohibited, that state lotteries curtail
advertising and that states sponsoring lotteries be required to
contribute some of their revenue to the treatment of problem
gamblers. Although the nine-member commission _ comprised of
gambling opponents and proponents alike _ is not expected to
advocate any federal taxes or regulation of the casino industry, it
appears that more federal oversight of casinos operated by
Native-American tribes will be recommended.
</P>
<P>
   The commission was formed in 1996 and at the time casino
operators were fearful that it would lead to federal policies that
could stifle business and impose taxes and layers of regulation.
But after vigorous lobbying by the casino industry, the major
changes that are expected to be recommended to Congress are aimed
mostly at other forms of gambling, and even many of those
recommendations are expected to face vigorous fights in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle over the commission and the hearings have educated
the American people about the money and power'' that the casino
industry has, said Rep. Frank R. Wolf, a Virginia Republican who
sponsored the legislation leading to the formation of the
commission. Wolf, an immovable opponent of gambling, said he was
pleased, nonetheless, that the commission was ``putting the
spotlight'' on the industry. ``There will be a lot of information
and data in the report,'' he said. ``You had to have the commission
report to take these guys on.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which is facing a June 18 deadline, is currently
debating the final report, which will be delivered to Congress, the
president and tribal governments. Although no drafts have been made
public, it has become apparent during commission meetings that
while there is unanimous agreement on some issues, like raising the
minimum age for gambling to 21 and banning Internet gambling,
commission members remain divided over other major issues, like the
extent of compulsive gambling in the country, and whether the
social costs of the growth in legalized gambling outweighs the
economic benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those who like to emphasize the costs and those who
like to emphasize the benefits,'' said Kay C. James, the chairman
of the commission who resigned this week as a dean at Regent
University in Virginia. ``Although there is now a great deal of
consensus, on some issues that just won't happen.'' For instance,
Ms. James noted that while there is no disagreement over the
existence of pathological gambling, ``the disagreement is over the
numbers and how much of a problem it is.''
</P>
<P>
   With some form of gambling now legal in 47 states, commission
members are expected to express concern in their report about how
quickly gambling has spread since the last federal study in 1976.
One of the most heated issues of debate here on Wednesday concerned
whether a moratorium should be imposed on the expansion of
gambling. Some commissioners contended that such a move would give
local governments a chance to evaluate the effect of their gambling
operations before adding more.
</P>
<P>
   But others, including J. Terrence Lanni, the chairman and chief
executive of the MGM casinos, said a moratorium was not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people hear the word moratorium, they think, `That's it.
They want to end it,' '' Lani warned. After a majority of
commissioners voted to recommend a moratorium, Lani warned that he
might draft a minority report if the issue is not resolved before
the final report is submitted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
