<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-SMOKING-ADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBE WON'T BAR TOBACCO ADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The New York Times announced says it will no longer
accept cigarette and tobacco advertising in its pages, effective
Saturday. The decision by the Times, whose parent company owns The
Boston Globe and 20 other newspapers, does not apply to those
publications.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe will continue to accept advertising for tobacco
products, but strict guidelines that were put in place last month
will be applied in selecting the ads for publication, a spokesman
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Richard P. Gulla, director of public relations at the Globe,
said revenue from tobacco advertising accounts for a fraction of
the newspaper's overall advertising volume and revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not go out and seek this type of product or this kind of
advertising business, but if an ad comes to us and it meets certain
guidelines then we will accept it for publication,'' Gulla said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tobacco is still a legal product regardless of how one views
it,'' he added. ``Censorship, whether of a news story or an
advertisement, is something we look at closely every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post, USA Today, The Wall Street Journal, and the
Los Angeles Times are among several newspapers around the country
that accept advertising for tobacco products, though revenue from
such ads is small.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, cigarette and tobacco advertising has decreased
sharply in recent years, dropping to just over $11 million today
from $21 million in 1995, The Wall Street Journal reported this
week. By contrast, $500 million is spent on tobacco advertising in
the United States each year.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Nielsen, a spokeswoman for The New York Times Co., said
Wednesday that tobacco ads represented less than 1 percent of the
newspaper's advertising revenue. She told reporters this week that
a ban is being instituted because the paper ``does not want to
expose readers to advertising that is harmful to health or
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   But Neilsen stressed that the decision applied only to the
Times, and not to the Globe or the other newspapers the Times Co.
owns. ``All of our properties have the autonomy to make their own
decisions about the advertising they accept,'' she said. ``In fact,
I think our properties were caught by surprise. We did not tell
them in advance that we were going to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Globe's advertising policy, the newspaper will not
accept cigarette ads that are targeted at children or teenagers,
ads that contain cartoon characters, or ads in which the text or
images suggest that smoking and good health are related or that
smoking could lead to a better life.
</P>
<P>
   The policy also prohibits placement of the ads in newspaper
sections designed for children or teenagers, and it bans
distribution of tobacco products through the Globe's product
sampling programs.
</P>
<P>
   Gulla said all tobacco advertising copy must be submitted in
advance. He added that freestanding inserts and advertising copy
are also expected to meet the standards outlined in the Globe's
policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6997 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMBLING-COMMISSION-A     04-28 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-COMMISSION-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: is submitted.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Besides the content of the report, commission members are also
wrestling with its tone. ``What's missing in my view is an explicit
recognition of the fact that the American people love to gamble,''
said John W. Wilhelm, president of the Hotel Employees and
Restaurant Employees International Union, which represents 75,000
casino employees. ``While I don't think it's the only thing to say,
I certainly don't think it should be ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission, established in 1996 by Congress and the
president at a cost of $5 million, the commission has traveled
around the country to explore the consequences of gambling's rapid
expansion, and it has also financed several studies to help reach
its conclusions. One study found that more than 5 million Americans
are considered problem or pathological gamblers, and an additional
15 million are at risk. Another study found that an estimated 1.8
million American adults and 1.1 million young people 12 to 17 years
of age exhibit severe, or ``pathological'' gambling behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But gambling advocates on the commission contended that the
language on compulsive gambling was misleading and intended to
exaggerate the dangers. For example, they said it was unfair to say
that all of the 15 million people who have gambled at least one
time to relieve uncomfortable feelings should be classified as ``at
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they said they were displeased that one study found
that the economic cost of gambling addictions is about $5 billion a
year _ for things like legal fees for divorce, court and jail
costs, bankruptcies and lost wages _ much less than opponents of
gambling had previously estimated.
</P>
<P>
   While it does not appear that the commission will take any
action that will severely effect the large casinos, some members
want to ensure that the report reflects a concern about the
dominate role the casino industry now plays in society.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time gambling was rare and considered exceptional,''
said Richard C. Leone, a former state treasurer of New Jersey and
currently president of the New York-based Century Fund. Gambling is
now ``common and unexceptional,'' Leone said.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the minimum legal age for all forms of gambling could
effect race tracks, which in many states allow 18-year-olds to
wager. States with legalized casinos already have set the minimum
age at 21, but the commission agreed that stricter enforcement is
needed.
</P>
<P>
   The final report is expected to be highly critical of the
lottery industry. At one point, some commissioners favored
referring to politicians as ``addicted to the revenue'' that comes
from state-sponsored gambling. Ultimately, they agreed to change
the language, but they were still expected to call for independent
boards to oversee the regulation of lotteries, and they were also
likely to recommend that states disassociate themselves from the
video lottery business.
</P>
<P>
   One study financed by the commission found that about 5 percent
of lottery players purchase more than half of the tickets sold and
that poor people spend a greater portion of their income on lottery
tickets than other players. The commissioners agreed that a portion
of the revenue from lotteries should go toward the treatment of
compulsive gamblers. Although most large casino companies already
finance research and treatment for such problems, state lotteries
are not required to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is expected to be extremely, the commission appeared
to be unanimous in its desire to stop the highly lucrative online
gambling companies.
</P>
<P>
   Should a complete ban on online gambling prove impossible to
implement and enforce, one proposal under consideration by the
commission would make it illegal to use credit cards to gamble with
the offshore Internet casinos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
