<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PLEA IS IN THE MAIL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Bill Chapin &LR;  forwarded these results of his personal study of
the phenomenon of fund-raising requests. From Jan. 1, 1998, to Dec.
31, 1998, Chapin kept records of 666 requests that he received by
mail:
</P>
<P>
   _ The total amount requested was $2,221,024.44, computed by
adding up the maximum amount options on each request.
</P>
<P>
   _ The University of California School of Medicine requested the
most money, a total of $1,998,000; the smallest request was from
the North Shore Animal League, for $2.50.
</P>
<P>
   _ There were 24 requests from Amnesty International and 34 from
various cancer organizations.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Chicken Program for Bosnia requested $36, ``all that is
needed to provide seeds, tools and chickens to four Bosnian
farmers. Can you spare at least this amount?''
</P>
<P>
   Chapin's favorite: the Heifer Project International. ``For
varying amounts,'' he writes, ``I could donate to needy people a
heifer, a water buffalo, a llama, a goat, a sheep, a pig, trees, a
rabbit, honeybees, a flock of chickens, a flock of ducks, a flock
of geese, or _ for $5,000 _ an entire (expletive deleted) ark.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ On her way from Weight Watchers promotions in San Francisco to
Weight Watchers promotions in Kansas City on Tuesday, the
 &UR; Duchess of York &LR;  took advantage of a two-hour layover in Denver to
lay flowers at the memorial site in Littleton, Colo. ``I feel very
strongly that the American people need to know they're supported in
Europe and all over the world, too,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Florida,  &UR; Burt Reynolds' &LR;  defunct Carousel Jupiter Theatre
is about to become Christ's Church of the Palm Beaches, in
preparation for which church administrators are holding an auction
of stuff Reynolds left behind. Among the souvenirs are pictures
autographed to Reynolds by  &UR; Woody Allen &LR; ,  &UR; Jackie Gleason &LR;  and  &UR; Mae
West &LR; , and a photograph of Reynolds with the  &UR; pope &LR; . ``People will
pay good money for this stuff, said  &UR; D. Cooper &LR; 
 &UR; Getschal &LR; , director of worship. ``We're counting on it.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Cybill Shepherd &LR; , 49, complains in Mode magazine that her
sitcom ``Cybill'' was not renewed, although ``it was the No. 1 CBS
sitcom for women. `The Nanny' was picked up, and we tied `The
Nanny' in ratings. Think about it. In one year, `Murphy Brown,'
`Ellen,' `Roseanne' and `Cybill' all went off the air. They took
all the women in their 40s off the air. I mean, when you're a woman
in your 40s, where are you represented in this culture?''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Francis Moonan &LR;  forwards a  &UR; Joseph Epstein &LR;  essay reprinted
in the Hudson Review, in which Epstein reveals a lifelong ambition
to coin a word.
</P>
<P>
   One of his suggestions: Bayarrea, ``too much talk about the
delights of living in or near San Francisco. Much of this talk is
about good living, food and wine and fine views _ and I find I soon
get a snootful of it, which makes me want to heave sun-dried
tomatoes at anyone engaging in it.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Tito Guizar &LR; , 91-year-old Mexican troubadour and actor, will
be honored for his contributions to the Latino community when he
receives the 1999 Nosotros Golden Eagle Award in Los Angeles on
July 30. Guizar, who starred on radio and in movies of the '30s,
'40s and '50s, and made more than 1,500 recordings, had announced
his retirement in San Francisco in 1983. Nonetheless, he is
appearing in Spanish-language TV soap operas broadcast in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT YOU DIDN'T LEARN IN HIGH SCHOOL HISTORY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A letter to the editor of Harper's magazine, printed in the May
issue, states:
</P>
<P>
   ``An interesting postscript to  &UR; David Samuels &LR; ' chronicle of
greyhound racing is that  &UR; O.P. Smith &LR; , the inventor of the
mechanical rabbit, was directly responsible for the imprisonment of
 &UR; Al Capone &LR;  for income-tax evasion. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``O.P. Smith was my mother's uncle, and the rabbit was just one
of his inventions. Another was a toothpick dispenser that used to
be seen in almost every restaurant in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately, I've gotten into a horrible habit I'm ashamed of:
Playing solitaire on the computer. It's a full-blown addiction, but
that's how I gather my thoughts. It's a Zen thing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Teri Garr in More magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
