<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7005 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-HNS &LR;      04-28 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE SEEKS TO LIMIT CLINTON'S ABILITY TO DEPLOY TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House defied Clinton administration pleas
Wednesday and approved a measure that would restrict the
president's ability to deploy ground forces in Yugoslavia without
first consulting Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The 249 to 180 vote signaled that Congress seeks to assert a
larger role in U.S. policy toward the conflict with Yugoslavia,
more than a month after the United States and its NATO partners
launched an aerial campaign to force Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to end his assault on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, sponsored by Rep. William Goodling, R-Pa.,
would ban the use of federal money to deploy ``ground elements''
unless Congress first authorizes it. The Senate is working on
similar legislation and could consider it before the end of the
week.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton has said he would consult Congress if he
decides to move beyond the bombing campaign and send troops into
Yugoslavia, Republicans said the legislation gives Congress a
vehicle to assert its power to declare war and would force Clinton
to keep his promise.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats argued that Goodling's bill was vaguely written
and could be misinterpreted to mean that the current use of U.S.
Apache helicopters over Kosovo would be banned.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Clinton said ``America must continue to speak with a
single voice'' in dealing with Yugoslavia. And senior
administration officials, in a letter to Republican congressional
leaders, said the Goodling bill would ``unacceptably restrict the
president's ability to carry our his responsibilities as commander
in chief and to conduct foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., said the bill would have no effect
on the ongoing air campaign and said the intent of the legislation
``is to preclude a large'' deployment of land forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill does not tie the president's hand,'' she said. ``It
will not impair the use of Apache helicopters or small numbers of
forces ... for intelligence gathering.''
</P>
<P>
   But House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., said the
resolution on ground forces was unnecessary because Clinton has
promised to consult Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said Clinton reiterated that promise Wednesday to
lawmakers who attended a White House meeting on the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization operation that began on March 24. Clinton has
repeatedly said he does not expect to use combat forces and expects
the air campaign to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a change of policy by NATO or ground troops
(become necessary) then it must be debated by Congress and a vote
must be taken by Congress,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Richard Armey, R-Texas, said he hoped the
measure would reverse the trend of presidents deploying air or
ground forces before consulting Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship with Congress comes before our relationship
with our NATO allies,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that if Clinton had consulted Congress before
starting the air war, the U.S. would have been able to send a
strong, united message to Milosevic. ``We can do this if we do it
together Mr. President,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   The debate on Kosovo policy was forced by Rep. Tom Campbell,
R-Calif., who submitted two resolutions earlier this month aimed at
forcing Congress to take a firm position on the U.S. role in the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the verge of ground troops and I don't think anybody
should be mistaken about that,'' Campbell said. ``We are at
war...we have a constitutional obligation to fulfill.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Campbell's resolutions called for Congress to declare war
against Yugoslavia and the other called on Clinton to withdraw U.S.
forces from the NATO air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The House rejected voted 427 to 2 against the declaration of
war; the resolution to withdraw American personnel was defeated 290
to 139.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO campaign is designed to prod Milosevic to end his
assault on the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, a province of Serbia
that once enjoyed relative autonomy. Serbia, the dominant republic
of Yugoslavia, sees Kosovo as an invaluable part of its history.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders unsuccessfully tried to get Campbell to
withdraw his resolutions. Instead, Republican leaders offered
Goodling's legislation and a Democratic alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The House also debated a Democratic-backed resolution expressing
support of the current air campaign, but it failed to pass late
Thursday in a 213 to 213 vote. The resolution, which was adopted by
the Senate before last month's air campaign began, authorizes
Clinton to conduct such an operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
