<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7007 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-PROFILING-MOTEL-2N     04-28 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-PROFILING-MOTEL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TRENTON, N.J.: Hotel-Motel Unit. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although it is a common, and widely accepted, investigative
technique for detectives to develop sources within the community
they police, the state troopers' Hotel-Motel Program is unusually
aggressive because it uses an entire hotel or motel staff to to
scrutiinzie guests during their entire stay. That fact has made the
program very effective, Geleta said, although he declined to say
how many arrests the unit has made in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But it has also raised privacy concerns from some civil rights
advocates and members of the tourism and hospitality industry.
</P>
<P>
   Lenora Lapidus, legal director for the New Jersey chapter of the
American Civil Liberties Union, said she was shocked that the state
police and some hotels had been so cavalier about intruding on the
privacy of hotel guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the state police to be looking through people's credit
cards receipts and registration forms, and from what I understand,
conducting surveillance on some of them, is just a gross invasion
of privacy,'' Ms. Lapidus said.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Larsen, president of the New Jersey Hotel and Motel
Association, said he had never heard of the program and the
organization has never been asked to take a formal position on the
matter. But Larsen said he would not allow the hotel he manages to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't allow the police to look through our records
without a subpoena, period,'' said Larsen, manager of the East
Brunswick Hilton. ``We have an obligation to protect people's
privacy. I would think there's a civil liability if we start giving
out information.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fields, owner of the Days Inn near Newark Airport, said
he refused to participate in the program because he thought it
violated his guests' right to privacy. Fields said that in 1997,
his general manager was pressured by state police to join the
program, but felt that it would be intrusive to grant the troopers'
requests to arbitrarily search through ``the bucket'' where
registration cards and credit card imprints are stored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a tactic out of some dictatorship,'' said Fields.
``When a person checks into a hotel, he or she has a reasonable
assumption that the place of business will protect their privacy,
not treat them like a criminal.'' Many criminal defense lawyers
were stunned to learn of the existence of the informers and said
the program might also raise concerns about whether troopers
testified truthfully in court hearings about arrests that were
initiated by hotel employees.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lapidus said the she may file court papers to force state
police to turn over records of all arrests made by all troopers
involved in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certainly search and seizure issues here,'' said Ms.
Lapidus. ``The Constitution guarantees that every defendant knows
all the evidence against them and all the witnesses against them,
so if we find that that hasn't been happening, it's certainly
something we'd be interested in pursuing.''
</P>
<P>
   If criminal defendants can prove that officers testified
untruthfully about the circumstances leading up to a search, they
can ask a judge to throw out their search and overturn their
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   But Geleta said that his detectives are responsible enough to
handle the job the without violating either the law or police
procedure. The vast majority of the arrests made by the unit ended
with guilty pleas long before trial, he said. And if the cases went
to trial, he said, the detectives were trained to conceal their
informers identities without lying during court hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have ways of handling that,'' he said, but declined to
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel managers who participated in the program differed in their
assessments of whether race played a role in it. Fred Hartman,
manager of the Ramada Inn near Newark Airport, said he was
convinced that guests were scrutinized only on their behavior, and
not on their race.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no profiling whatsoever,'' said Hartman, who
acknowledged that he never attended one of the troopers' training
sessions. He said he had no qualms about allowing troopers to check
credit card receipts and registration forms because ``they're good
guys, and we want to co-operate with them whenever we can.''
</P>
<P>
   But even some hotel managers who support the program said that
state troopers had told them that the intent was to catch West
Indians or Hispanic people, particularly South Americans, involved
in the drug trade. Chip Woodell, general manager of the Hampton Inn
near Newark Airport, said he agreed to let the state police address
his employees last month because troopers convinced him that they
were interested in catching international drug smugglers rather
than guests who may have used narcotics themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me they weren't interested in catching someone
smoking a joint in their room,'' said Woodell, who noted that he
had allowed troopers to check his registration records about twice
a week. ``What they want is some guy from Colombia, who swallowed a
kilo of cocaine wrapped in balloons, who was trying to sneak it
through the airport.''
</P>
<P>
   David Chertoff, the former manager of the Howard Johnson near
Newark Airport, said he supported the program because he trusted
the troopers' judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the state police had their own criteria in
deciding who to look for, and it was a very detailed, complex
thing,'' said Chertoff. ``Race was one small part of it. But I will
tell you, it was not a function solely of race. If a Jamaican came
in, or someone with dreadlocks, it's not like they were
automatically targeted. A lot of our clientele and employees were
minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   State police officials would not discuss the size of the program
or its origins, and asserted that any publicity about the hotel
employees' involvement in the plan might endanger those employees.
But when he was pressed to describe how publicity could pose a risk
to informers if they were not identified in news accounts, Geleta
conceded, ``Well, maybe it would endanger the program, because the
drug dealers would know what we're up to.''
</P>
<P>
   One member of the unit said that a training film shown to all
members of the unit stated that the program was based on a similar
initiative by the Los Angeles Police Department and some federal
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The trooper, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that
although officers were never trained to target Hispanic or West
Indian people, they were frequently reminded that much of the
illegal narcotics in the area was shipped from South and Central
America and the Caribbean. They were also pressured by their
superiors to make as many arrests and seizures as possible, the
trooper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone could turn it into profiling, pretty easily,'' the
trooper said, although he insisted he never took race into account
when carrying out his duties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
