<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC ABRUPTLY FIRES OPPOSITION GADFLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ A Yugoslav deputy prime minister who had
threatened street demonstrations against the government over press
freedom went quietly Wednesday evening after being fired by fax.
</P>
<P>
   The minister, Vuk Draskovic, the outspoken and liberal
window-dressing for President Slobodan Milosevic's government, was
informed of his dismissal by Prime Minister Momir Bulatovic just 30
minutes before it was announced on Serbian state television,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Bulatovic, a close ally of Milosevic, said Draskovic, a writer
who turned to politics in the late 1980s and has always been
something of a maverick, had been dismissed ``because of his public
statements against government positions, and for damaging the
government's prestige.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO officials had interpreted Draskovic's stand as a
sign of dissent born of the air war. But Draskovic is not an
insider and there are few signs that the ruling circle around
Milosevic and his wife is cracking.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief news conference Wednesday evening, Draskovic issued
no direct challenge to Milosevic. He said he supported the united
fight of the Serbian people against NATO and would continue to urge
a negotiated settlement for Kosovo, adding, ``I hope Milosevic
wants the same things I want.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days the garrulous Draskovic had called on the
government to ``stop lying'' about the war and to negotiate a peace
that would be monitored by armed United Nations troops.
</P>
<P>
   But more threatening than these suggestions, senior Yugoslav
officials and analysts said, were his repeated criticisms of the
political parties of Milosevic and his influential wife, Mirjana
Markovic. Draskovic said the couple had taken advantage of the war
to further their own political aims.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stepped over some line with Milosevic,'' a senior Serbian
journalist said Wednesday night. Senior Draskovic aides were upset
by the dismissal, having urged him in recent days to tone down his
criticism and limit his interviews. ``He got carried away with
everyone slapping him on the back,'' one aide said.
</P>
<P>
   In statements carried Wednesday night on Studio B, the
television station that his Serbian Renewal Movement controls,
Draskovic was supportive and careful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that my country is a victim of aggression,'' he said, ``I
am one of the millions of Serbs who are soldiers of their
fatherland. We sometimes disagree about the ways and means of
defending ourselves, but we are united and uncompromising in the
decision to defend our sovereignty and territorial integrity. There
is no crack here and there will not be one.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbian state television also announced Wednesday night an
agreement between Ibrahim Rugova, an ethnic Albanian leader in
Kosovo, and Serbian President Milan Milutinovic to work on a
political settlement for Kosovo, a province in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova actually addressed the camera in Pristina, the capital of
Kosovo, speaking in Serbian and emphasizing ``an atmosphere of
mutual confidence.'' Rugova, whom NATO regards effectively as a
prisoner and unable to speak freely, looked relaxed as he said:
``The most important thing is this mutual trust that we have built
and the world will salute.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had ``successfully cooperated'' with Serbian
officials, including Milosevic and Milutinovic, ``and we shall
continue in that manner until we reach a solution and we create
organs and institutions in Kosovo for all nationalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Previously Rugova could be seen but not heard, with his views
being summarized, accurately or not, by an announcer.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, he and Milutinovic agreed to form a new,
temporary government for the province; resume talks immediately on
giving Kosovo ``wide self-rule'' within Serbia and Yugoslavia, and
invite some foreigners ``as guests'' to attend the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, a leader of anti-Milosevic protests in 1996 and 97,
had joined the government in January saying both that he wanted to
strengthen it during a time of crisis over Kosovo and that he
wanted to change it from within.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday evening, Draskovic said that a military censor had
taken over Studio B, an assertion denied by the military and later
by the station itself, and that he would lead street demonstrations
if military control over programming continued.
</P>
<P>
   He also complained bitterly about spending cuts for Belgrade
city, which his party governs, while the Serbian government faced
few cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Wednesday evening, the executive committee of
Milosevic's Socialist Party said: ``We shall not allow anyone to
weaken our people's resolve by diverting attention to any other
issues than defense of the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic had earned most attention from the West for his
statements that Yugoslavia was practically alone in its war over
Kosovo, that NATO was not cracking and that he thought Milosevic
would permit an armed United Nations force in Kosovo after
hostilities ended.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials say the same, although the government position
remains that only unarmed civilian observers from non-NATO
countries will be allowed into Kosovo _ nowhere close to the
allies' demand that an armed ``international security force,'' with
NATO troops as its core, go in to give ethnic Albanians the
confidence to return home.
</P>
<P>
   Three ministers from Draskovic's party resigned in protest
Wednesday is evening. They were he Information Milan Komnenic; he
Domestic Trade Slobodan Nenadovic, and Milan Bozic, a minister
without portfolio who is also deputy mayor of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   While Komnenic helped foreign journalists come to Yugoslavia to
cover the war, the resignations will have little effect on the real
power structure, which is controlled by Milosevic and his wife.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
