<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Thursday, April
29, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Bob
Schenet at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   SANCTIONS-FOOD (Washington) _ The Clinton administration lifts a
ban on the sale of food and medicine to three countries sanctioned
for being terrorist states, paving the way for Northwest farmers to
sell wheat to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (Story will move in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   RAMSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ No economist is suggesting it will
take East Asia 10 years to recover from the Crash of '97. Our own
Depression, however, lasted for a full decade, and economists have
never agreed why. A new view is offered by economists Harold Cole
and Lee Ohanian for the Quarterly Review of the Federal Reserve
Bank of Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   By Bruce Ramsey. (Story has moved in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   AUTHORS-ENGLANDER (Undated) _ Nathan Englander shrugs when asked
to account for his celebrity status. Even with amber curls framing
his head in shining abundance, he looks momentarily old. On tour
following the publication of his first book of short stories, ``For
the Relief of Unbearable Urges,'' he seems for a second tired of
trying to charm the latest in a long line of interviewing strangers
who greet him armed with microphone and camera, pen and notepad.
</P>
<P>
   By Regina Hackett. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SONICS (Portland) _ Seattle SuperSonics play at Portland.
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Tillery. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Seattle) _ Seattle Mariners host Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   By Tyler Kepner. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
