<HEADLINE>
OECD PROPOSES GLOBAL CODE OF CORPORATE CONDUCT 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Corporations around the world will be encouraged to
offer employees stock-ownership plans and other profit-sharing
incentives under a new code of good corporate conduct that finance
ministers from 29 industrial countries are expected to endorse in
May.
</P>
<P>
   The code was drawn up by the Paris-based Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development at the request of member
governments last year after the financial meltdown in Asia. The
OECD said the crisis highlighted what it called the need for better
standards of business behavior in that region of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing the code Wednesday, OECD secretary-general Donald
Johnston called it a ``cornerstone for attracting foreign
investment into the developing world.''
</P>
<P>
   He described the code as complementary to the efforts of the
International Monetary Fund and World Bank, which are holding their
annual spring meetings in Washington, to strengthen the
international financial system after the crises in Asia and Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Asian crisis highlighted the weakness in transparency, in
regulation and in overall good governance in the corporate sector
in a number of countries,'' Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   The new code, which will be approved at a meeting in Paris on
May 26, comes a few months after the organization banned corporate
bribery and after ratification by 12 governments including the
United States, Germany, Japan and Britain. Johnston said France is
expected to ratify this summer.
</P>
<P>
   This prohibition on bribery, which closely follows existing U.S.
law, requires ratifying countries to introduce domestic legislation
making it a criminal offense for their corporations to bribe
foreign officials in order to win business contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Although the new corporate governance code is voluntary, Johnson
said the World Bank and the IMF could insist that governments
encourage companies to follow its prescriptions as a condition for
loans they offer.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the code's provisions are already accepted practice in
the Western industrialized world.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The recommendation that corporations offer profit-sharing plans
to employees comes in the section dealing with ``the role of
stakeholders in corporate governance'' which calls for ``active
cooperation'' between businesses and all those with a stake in
their success, such as workers and suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Other sections of the code define the rights of shareholders and
provide for their equitable treatment. The code also lays down
general principals for corporate disclosure of finances and
management and defines the responsibilities of a board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting of the joint development committee of the World
Bank and the IMF, which deals with poorer nations and those
recovering from conflicts, World Bank president James Wolfensohn
said Wednesday that he expected the number of Kosovar refugees to
rise from 600,000 at present to 950,000.
</P>
<P>
   Within 30 days, he said, the World Bank and the European Union
plan to establish a jointly financed relief operation and to start
planning for the refugees' eventual return as well as for the
reconstruction of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the longer the bombing lasts in Yugoslavia,
the greater the economic damage to surrounding countries like
Macedonia, Bosnia- Herzegovina, Albania and Romania, which are
suffering trade and investment losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
