u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUISIANA-DUKE-NYT &LR;      04-28 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUISIANA-DUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RACE IN LOUISIANA FOR THE REPUBLICAN RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   METAIRIE, La. _ On the surface, the special election to be held
here Saturday is about who will replace Bob Livingston, the veteran
congressman who admitted an affair and abruptly resigned last year
as he was about to become speaker of the House.
</P>
<P>
   But the undercurrent, as has been the case in Louisiana politics
in the last decade, is whether this will be the race that finally
cures the state, and the national Republican Party, of the angst
generated by David Duke, the former Ku Klux Klan leader.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, 48 and graying, is among the seven Republicans and two
Democrats competing to succeed Livingston in the deeply
conservative, reliably Republican 1st Congressional District, a
swath of suburbs and farmland north of New Orleans. And for those
who would like Duke simply to disappear, he offers this bit of
encouragement: if he loses, he has no plans to run again.
</P>
<P>
   With Duke drawing only 12 percent in his 1996 race for the U.S.
Senate, many political analysts doubt he can finish first or second
in Saturday's open primary and advance to an all-but-certain runoff
May 29. They believe he has been marginalized by a field that is so
conservative that one of its more moderate members, front-runner
David Treen, advocates the public execution of drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The issues that once set Duke apart, like affirmative action,
immigration and welfare, have been appropriated by mainstream
Republicans. His rants about black inferiority and Jewish power
have worn thin, and their appeal has been diluted by declining
joblessness and crime rates.
</P>
<P>
   But some strategists say that strange things can happen in a
race with such a large field, and that history demonstrates that
Duke should not be underestimated. That message has not been lost
on the national Republican leaders who must protect the party's
narrow congressional majority in next year's elections. If Duke
wins, they acknowledge, every Republican candidate in 2000 can
expect Democratic advertisements that meld their faces into that of
a white-hooded klansman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will become our Y2KKK problem,'' said Rep. W.J. ``Billy''
Tauzin, the Republican dean of Louisiana's congressional
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Such fears help explain why a number of prominent Republicans
have tried, with only partial success, to forge a consensus around
the 70-year-old Treen. Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority
leader, has joined Livingston and Tauzin in backing Treen, a former
governor and congressman. Playing on the district's concern about
the loss of Livingston's 21 years of seniority, House Speaker
Dennis Hastert has declared that he would try to give Treen credit
for his previous seven years in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's outcome, therefore, should provide clues about how
far to the right the rightest of the Republican South is leaning at
a time when the party's presidential candidates are beginning to
hunt for traction.
</P>
<P>
   It also may speak to the state of racial politics in Louisiana.
Voting was deeply polarized along racial lines in the 1995
gubernatorial election, when M.J. ``Mike'' Foster, a white
Republican businessman, defeated Cleo Fields, a black Democratic
congressman. Foster is expected to have an equally easy re-election
campaign this year against Rep. William Jefferson, a black liberal
Democrat from New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The glass ceiling for black politicians in Louisiana, where 68
percent of registered voters are white, is sufficiently low that
the popular black mayor of New Orleans, Marc Morial, is exploring
the possibility of amending the city charter so he can run for a
third term. ``He has no place else to go,'' said Susan Howell, a
political scientist at the University of New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Treen, the first Louisiana Republican since Reconstruction to be
elected to Congress or the governorship, is widely favored to
finish first Saturday, but without the majority needed to avoid a
runoff. The other Republicans vying for a spot are Monica Monica, a
free-spending ophthalmologist who says her father loved her so much
that he named her twice; David Vitter, a telegenic young state
legislator and Rhodes Scholar; Rob Couhig, the owner of the New
Orleans Zephyrs minor league baseball team, and Duke.
</P>
<P>
   The only serious Democratic candidate in the race is Bill
Strain, a state representative who is considered as conservative as
his Republican counterparts. The list of less viable candidates
includes Patrick Landry, an electrician who is campaigning as a
33-year-old virgin, an interesting approach given that Livingston
forfeited the speakership when Hustler magazine threatened to
expose his extramarital affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Monica and Vitter are considered leading contenders for the
second runoff spot, and the two have thrown a barrage of negative
advertisements at each other. She has pumped nearly $1 million into
her campaign, and has outspent Vitter and Treen by more than 2 to
1.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates are ideologically similar, but Treen's age has
pushed the issue of term limits to the fore. Vitter was the author
of Louisiana's 1995 law that limits legislators to three four-year
terms, but refuses to take a voluntary pledge to restrict his stay
in Congress. Dr. Monica has pledged to serve only three terms and
has criticized Vitter as a term-limits hypocrite. Vitter counters
that he is the only leading contender who can build the kind of
seniority enjoyed by Livingston. Dr. Monica, he said, has limited
her own tenure while Treen may be ``limited biologically.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Duke critics believe that the warfare between Dr. Monica
and Vitter may hurt both candidates, and therefore help Duke. While
many national Republican leaders have denounced Duke, they note
that Foster and a number of other leading Louisiana Republicans
refuse to do so. Indeed, Couhig is the only candidate who has made
a public show of repudiating Duke's views.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in the back booth of a Mandeville Waffle House,
where Duke devoured a late lunch of four fried eggs, grits and
toast, the candidate said that the 1st District has ``perfect
demographics'' for him. Eighty-five percent of the district's
registered voters are white, and Duke won well over half of the
white vote in his unsuccessful races for the U.S. Senate in 1990
and for governor in 1991. His biggest electoral success came in the
heart of the district, Metarie, which elected him its state
representative in a 1989 a race against Treen's brother.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's candidacy coincides with the release of his
self-published book, ``My Awakening,'' a 736-page tract that calls
for an Aryan resurgence and the establishment of ``optional
separate homelands'' for minorities. His television advertisements
criticize the depiction of Malcolm X on a postage stamp, the recent
change of the name of a New Orleans elementary school from George
Washington to that of a black doctor, and prohibitions against
singing Christmas carols in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas is out, Kwanza is in,'' Duke says in one
advertisement. ``We're clearly in a fight for our heritage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7027 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATGUARD29-COX     04-28 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATGUARD29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's doubtful they'll get the call, but these civilians say
`Let's go!'
 &HT;    By Richard Whitt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT STEWART, Ga. _ Gunner Jeff ``Bear'' Martin relaxes with a
cup of cold cocoa while mechanics try to repair the turret of his
Bradley Fighting Vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Though his trigger finger is itchy, Bear knows how to hibernate
in the classic military hurry-up-and-wait sense. The 13-year Marine
Corps member, who served in Desert Storm, knows how to fight, too.
</P>
<P>
   Broad-shouldered and barrel-chested, the Gainesville native
didn't say how he got his nickname, but it fits him. He likes the
moniker. It's on his business card from St. Ives Coffee Roasters,
where he works as a sales manager.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the citizen soldiers of the Georgia National
Guard's 48th Infantry Brigade (Mechanized), Martin is at Fort
Stewart preparing for a conflict that now seems far away. The 48th
is a desert-trained outfit and not likely to be called early even
if the fighting in Kosovo escalates.
</P>
<P>
   The 48th's annual training started Saturday at the base near
Hinesville. Scheduled for more than a year, it is unrelated to
events in Kosovo. Yet the conflict there lends a heightened
awareness for these soldiers that they are always a phone call away
for deployment. Everyone in the 48th Brigade knows situations can
change quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Under the watchful eye of regular Army advisors, they are
conducting field operations, planning attacks on ``enemy''
positions and setting up mock field hospitals to care for
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   During three weeks of training, more than 4,000 citizen soldiers
of the 48th Infantry will rotate through this 280,000-acre Army
base.
</P>
<P>
   They will operate awesome M1A1 tanks and deadly Bradleys, the
most sophisticated fighting machines ever built. They will blow
holes in moving targets and blast craters in the sandy hills of
Fort Stewart's artillery range with huge howitzers and powerful
rockets.
</P>
<P>
   They will come away from the experience not ready to fight, but
a little better prepared, said brigade Deputy Commander Tommy
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   If the standard for training soldiers to fight is 90 days, the
intent of this training is to get a head start, perhaps knocking 15
days off the necessary preparations.
</P>
<P>
   Headquartered in Macon, the 48th Infantry is the largest unit in
the Georgia National Guard. It is made up of units from 40
communities throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteer soldiers' reasons for serving in the Guard are as
varied as their careers outside the military. Some love the
military lifestyle. Some just like the extra money.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Don Carpenter, a mess sergeant with 29 years of service in
the Army and Guard, works for the Savannah Water Department.
</P>
<P>
   Cook Gloria Sutton of Hinesville, a veteran of desert warfare in
the Desert Storm and Desert Shield operations, cleans homes for a
living and hopes for better.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Ray Reid of Snellville commands an M1A1 tank for
Canton-based Delta Company.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you pull the trigger, it's a lot of fun,'' said Reid, a
Guardsman for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like playing a video game,'' said gunner Gerard Link,
``except you don't have to put in quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of these men and women of the 48th were left behind when
other units deployed to fight in Desert Storm. And they're still
feeling the stigma of being labeled ``unready'' to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us still have a bad taste in our mouths, but we don't
blame the army. A lot of it was politics,'' said Capt. Paul
Schmutzler, the Bravo Company commander.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of those in summer training here, Schmutzler doesn't
relish the idea of going to war.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``I would love for us to get the opportunity to go
and do what we are trained to do.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
