<SLUG> BC-NBC-AFFILIATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC OFFERS BUYOUTS TO SOME EMPLOYEES AS AFFILIATES FACE PRESSURE
FROM NETWORKS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC &UR;  &LR; is offering financial buyouts to all 20 members of its
affiliate relations department, a move network executives said was
part of a long-term strategy to redefine NBC's relationship with
its affiliated stations.
</P>
<P>
   The NBC executives said the buyouts were also meant to achieve
budget reduction goals set by the network.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, which is owned by General Electric, &UR;  &LR; is not eliminating the
affiliate department, Bob Wright, the president of NBC, emphasized,
and the network does not expect all 20 employees to accept the
buyout. NBC executives would not say how many executives they
expect to accept the offer.
</P>
<P>
   But Edward Scanlon, the executive vice president for employee
relations for NBC, said, ``If not as many as we expect take the
buyout, there will be some layoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The move comes as the networks, struggling to be profitable, are
trying to adjust their relationships to the affiliates. Walt
Disney's ABC &UR;  &LR; angered its affiliates when it announced plans to
start a soap opera cable channel using programs previously
available exclusively to its affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a subsidiary of News Corp., &UR;  &LR; enraged its affiliates when it
announced plans to reclaim for its own use more than 20 percent of
the commercial time the stations had previously sold.
</P>
<P>
   Fox executives met in New York Wednesday with executives from
several of its biggest station group owners, including Tribune
Broadcasting, Sinclair Broadcasting and Meredith Broadcasting,
trying to work out a deal that might put its switch in commercial
time into affect without the input of any of the smaller stations.
</P>
<P>
   Fox stations have openly discussed some alternatives if Fox goes
through with its plans, even leaving Fox for some other network.
The two new and smaller networks, Time Warner's WB and UPN, which
is owned by Viacom and Chris-Craft, have been actively courting
disaffected Fox affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   Scanlon said NBC's decision to reduce its affiliate relations
department was connected to the network's conviction that
``affiliation is going to be done in a different way in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright said that NBC's decision to pare down its affiliate
relations department was mainly part of the network's continuing
effort ``to try to reduce our costs.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also said that the network-affiliate relationship was in
the midst of an overhaul at every network which would leave the
system significantly changed in the next two to five years. The
current contracts between networks and affiliates will be ending
over that period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes NBC is aiming for is reduction or elimination
of the fees, called compensation, that the network pays to stations
for carrying its shows. Wright said that only the smallest stations
truly needed compensation to help their profits and yet large
stations received the most money. ``Compensation is like social
security,'' Wright said. ``Some people need it but other don't.
It's an entitlement without necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   On the larger question of how all of these changes might affect
network-affiliate relationships, Wright said most of the stations
``have no place to go.'' He said that unlike a few years ago, when
many stations jumped networks, few stations were likely to find it
attractive to switch networks now.
</P>
<P>
   `'I think it's unlikely that our affiliates will go somewhere
else, just as it's unlikely most Fox affiliates will join UPN,''
Wright said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
