<HEADER>
A7030 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCKESSON-AUDIT-MARKET     04-28 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCKESSON-AUDIT-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: CARNAGE AT MCKESSON HBOC 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In what is sure to become fodder for shareholder
groups who oppose frequent mergers, McKesson HBOC Inc., the
nation's largest drug wholesaler, announced Wednesday that it would
restate earnings for the last four quarters after discovering
improperly recorded sales from its recently acquired software
business.
</P>
<P>
   Investors promptly dropped the stock. Shares of McKesson plunged
47.5 percent, or $31.25, on Wednesday, to $34.50, a new 52-week
low. Some investors had suspected that McKesson had troubles and in
the last few weeks had been buying up huge volumes of put options,
or bets that the stock would decline.
</P>
<P>
   While stock analysts had expressed some reservations about
McKesson's $13.9 billion acquisition in January of HBO and Co., the
largest supplier of patient monitoring systems, the carnage
Wednesday caught them by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   While ratcheting down its fourth-quarter earnings, McKesson also
shaved 16.6 percent from its per-share earnings goal for fiscal
2000 and announced that further revisions were possible as the
company's audit progressed. McKesson now expects to earn $2.50 a
share in 2000, far below analysts' consensus of $2.94, according to
First Call Corp., which tracks corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly happened at McKesson HBOC may take months to
unravel fully. The company said Wednesday that it had discovered
$26.2 million in transactions during the fourth quarter and another
$16 million in the other three quarters that had been booked as
sales when they had not been fully completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``HBO put so much pressure on their sales people,'' said Kenneth
Abramowitz, an analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein. ``They may have
been stretched for results. I'm sure they had agreements with these
accounts. The sales here on some of these may just be delayed by
six to nine months.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the sales contracts that McKesson discounted were
over simple problems. A typical situation would have a client's
chief information officer making a deal that had to be approved by
the company's board, said Larry Kurtz, a spokesman for McKesson. If
the board had yet to approve the contract, the sale was reversed.
</P>
<P>
   The setback was enough for McKesson to lower its fourth-quarter
earnings per diluted share Wednesday to a 27-cent loss and earnings
for fiscal 1999 of 75 cents. This came less than a week after
McKesson announced a fourth-quarter loss of $60.4 million, or 22
cents per diluted share. For the year, McKesson had net income of
$237.1 million, or 84 cents per diluted share.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the discovery of McKesson's unearned sales raised more
troubling questions. Analysts feared that when the audit was fully
completed, McKesson, which is based in San Francisco, would have to
lower its earnings in several more quarters. But a company
spokesman said this was unlikely because the audit is only for four
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to that worry, it was especially troubling to have the
sales error involve HBO. That some of HBO's sales could have been
inflated, even accidentally, made analysts worry that McKesson may
have paid too much for the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wonder with this accounting procedure in place
since December '98, if this could not have been uncovered sooner,''
said Christopher McFadden, an analyst with First Union Capital
Markets. ``There has been a lot of negative sentiment about the
McKesson and HBO acquisition. HBO was so aggressive in their
acquisitions. There was some speculation whether they had done all
their homework.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unusual for companies to restate earnings for periods
longer than several quarters. CUC International Inc. uncovered fake
sales on its books last year after it had merged with HFS Inc., a
hotel franchiser. The combined company, Cendant Corp., was forced
to restate earnings back to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson appears to have detected the sales discrepancies during
its routine year-end audit. According to analysts, McKesson's
accounting firm, Deloitte &AMP; Touche, mailed a survey to several
clients asking for the amount they had actually purchased from the
company. Several of the amounts returned by clients did not match
what HBO had recorded.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Deloitte &AMP; Touche declined to comment about
McKesson's audit. A spokesman for Arthur Andersen &AMP; Co., HBO's
auditor, also declined to comment but said the accounting giant was
cooperating.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were especially interested in the chronology of the
audit. While the volume of puts traded for McKesson had been thin
during the months before Wednesday's announcement of the restated
earnings, huge volumes were traded within the last six weeks. On
March 15, for example, 500 put contracts were traded and on April
16, another 1,424 contracts were traded. A put investor is betting
that McKesson's stock will fall.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Wednesday if McKesson's accounting error would
invite scrutiny from federal investigators. The Security and
Exchange Commission declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, more trouble appears to be imminent. One New York law firm,
Wolf Haldenstein Adler Freeman &AMP; Herz, announced Wednesday that it
was filing a class action lawsuit in U.S. District Court for the
Northern District of California for shareholders of McKesson HBOC.
The lawsuit seeks to recoup damages from McKesson's fallen stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
