<SLUG> BC-MA-DOCTOR-PROFILING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL GROUP SETS STANDARDS FOR `PHYSICIAN PROFILING' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Growing enthusiasm for ``physician profiling'' _
measuring doctors' performance _ has got the Massachusetts Medical
Society worried.
</P>
<P>
   The 17,000-member group Wednesday published a set of criteria it
says should govern what kind of data are collected on physicians'
quality of care, and how it should be shared with the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public release issue is huge,'' the Medical Society said
in its 40-page report.
</P>
<P>
   The Medical Society has no power to enforce its proposed
standards. Officials of the group said they hope to get health
plans, insurers, hospitals, employer groups and others interested
in profiling doctors' performance to agree voluntarily to adopt its
criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Stason, a cardiologist who led the effort, said it
is not an attempt to block public disclosure of physician
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we release information, it's got to be thoroughly
justified in terms of its accuracy and statistical significance,
because physicians will object to the release of information that
is not well-founded,'' Stason said. ``But you can't hide behind a
shield.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The public should receive reports that are relevant to
choosing a physician, health plan, or hospital,'' the Medical
Society report said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the report said, consumers might be told of
doctors' performance in controlling high blood pressure, preventing
post-surgical wound infections, patients' timely access to needed
care, and patients' satisfaction with the quality of care.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the Medical Society's nine ``principles'' on physician
profiling pertain to disclosure of the results.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the report asserts that data released to the
public must meet ``especially high standards of accuracy, validity,
relevance, and clarity.'' There should also be ample opportunity
for doctors to screen public reports before their release, the
Medical Society said.
</P>
<P>
   Reports on individual doctors' performance should be distributed
only on a ``need to know'' basis, the report says, but adds ``a
clear definition of this phrase. . .is elusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Often individual physicians do not have enough cases to allow
statistically meaningful conclusions about their performance, he
said. But when they do, or when groups of physicians have
sufficient cases, ``I personally see no reason to embargo those
data,'' Stason said.
</P>
<P>
   Stason said the emphasis on high-quality data and review should
not become an excuse to block or delay information that helps
consumers choose a physician or a health plan. ``We need to apply
the best the current state of the art permits but not hide behind
perfection,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
