<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TOPGUNS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women pilots, like men, are ready with an 'attack mind-set'
 &HT;    By Richard Whitt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTER ARMY AIRFIELD, Ga. _ Sitting in the front seat of her
Apache attack helicopter, U.S. Army 1st Lt. Marla Bradbury looks
this way and that through an infrared monocle attached to her
helmet.
</P>
<P>
   A computer-controlled 30 mm cannon mounted on the chopper's
belly follows her head movements. It is aimed and ready.
</P>
<P>
   When she spots an ``enemy,'' the 5-foot-2-inch Boston University
graduate can unleash an awesome arsenal _ enough to annihilate an
entire company of enemy tanks or level a couple of city blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four Apache helicopters have been deployed to the Balkans
for combat in the Kosovo crisis. The technology they represent has
taken the brute out of ``brute force.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mostly a buttons game,'' said the 24-year-old
Californian.
</P>
<P>
   But pushing the buttons has devastating results. In practice
firing, entire boulders disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exhilarating,'' Bradbury admitted. ``I get a burst of
energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradbury and Chief Warrant Officer-2 Catherine R. Jung are the
only two women pilots assigned to the 3rd Infantry Regiment at
Hunter Army Airfield near Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   Both women fly the front seat of the two-seat Apaches, and
although they can fly the aircraft from that position, they are
primarily responsible for locating targets and firing weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Their physical size and strength are not an issue, their
commanders said. At 5 feet 5 inches, Jung is about the same stature
as her battalion executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Women have been allowed to fly in combat roles only since 1992.
They still cannot participate in ground combat roles.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches that Bradbury and Jung fly are designed primarily to
support ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its cannon, each Apache carries 38 rockets that can hit
a target from four miles away. But the helicopters' biggest weapons
are 16 laser-guided Hellfire missiles. The Hellfire is an anti-tank
missile that proved itself in the 1991 war for Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   The two women pilots, the first in this unit's history, compare
the high-tech point-and-shoot practice to video games they played
as children _ except that you can feel the power of these weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes you aback,'' Jung said. ``You feel the recoil of the
gun. It's a pretty awesome sight at night because you can see the
muzzle fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Jung was aiming for ``top gun'' honors in a recent training
exercise, but lost on the final night. She came in third out of 24
chopper pilots in the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Bradbury was in the middle of the pack. Some defective rockets,
she suspected, held down her score.
</P>
<P>
   The women said they have few problems getting along with the
male pilots. There's competition, sure, but it's friendly and they
are as gung-ho as their male counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speak for other women, but I don't think we're any
different than any of the men,'' said the 28-year-old Jung.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, being female offers them no advantages in the
Army either, the women said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradbury is thinking of leaving the Army because she can't get
enough flying time: There are more senior men pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Jung and Bradbury haven't flown combat missions, and their unit
probably won't be sent to the Balkans unless things escalate
rapidly over there. But both women said they're ready and would
have no problem pushing the buttons against live targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mission, just like any other job,'' said Jung.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wants to be involved in a shooting war, Bradbury said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But (if) I got over there, I'm going to kill them before they
kill me,'' she said. ``I just have an attack mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
