<HEADER>
A7037 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-BOOKS-LADN     04-28 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-BOOKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD READ OFFERS GLOBAL WARNINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH MARTIN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Few writers have capably painted the issue of
global environment. Some sketch in a few trees, but journalist Mark
Hertsgaard has crafted a veritable masterpiece from comprehensive
research during travels to 19 nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earth Odyssey'' (Broadway Books; $26) is a trek around the
world to witness the problems in developed countries and developing
nations alike. He frames the issues cohesively, tying in growth
with environmental devastation, connecting the woes of rich and
poor with global warming. That he sometimes takes leaps of faith to
present dire predictions of what might happen is nearly forgivable
given the sweep of the book and powerful, irresistible journalistic
storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   Hertsgaard's visits to ground zero of devastation are
beautifully rendered; one can almost smell the stench of
industrializing China and cringe at nuclear accident-prone Russia.
</P>
<P>
   It's like getting a bucket of cold _ and polluted _ water thrown
in your face. Deforestation in Brazil. Population explosions in
India. Poverty, tainted water, desertification, war and government
corruption in Africa. Overconsumption and addiction to the
automobile in North America, Europe and Japan. Food shortages in
many third-world counties. And, of course, the grim warnings about
global warming.
</P>
<P>
   While none can doubt the reality of the problems presented, the
conclusions Hertsgaard reaches are debatable.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset of the 372-page book, the Washington, D.C., author
ponders whether humankind will survive the next hundred years.
Except for the obvious danger of nuclear catastrophe, it's hard to
see how even a combination of disasters would result in extinction.
The more likely scenario is a series of terrible plagues that would
devastate parts of Africa and perhaps Asia. Population growth,
flooding, shrinking coastlines, food shortages _ a combination
could wipe out whole areas. Rich countries with a better handle on
such difficulties will be less impacted.
</P>
<P>
   The book offers opinion, makes readers think and stirs emotion,
and those are the ingredients of a good read. Our rating: { &QL; 
X X X
</P>
<P>
   Legends like river runner Buzz Holmstrom are the focus of great
yarns destined to be regaled around campfires for decades to come.
And, like many legends, many of those tales are just smoke.
</P>
<P>
   There are probably as many diverging stories about Holmstrom as
there are tributaries of the Colorado _ a river the Coquille, Ore.,
native conquered as a solo boater in 1937, the first time the
navigation feat had been accomplished. Like Glen and Bessie Hyde _
honeymooners who rode the Colorado and only their boat was found _
he has achieved cult status among the fraternity of river runners.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on Holmstrom's diaries, letters and remembrances of
people who knew him well helps unravel the mysterious character in
``The Doing of the Thing: The Brief Brilliant Whitewater Career of
Buzz Holmstrom'' (Fretwater Press; $20) by Vince Welch, Cort Conley
and Brad Dimock.
</P>
<P>
   A wealthy widow hired him in 1939 to take her the length of the
continent via waterways; he joined two boats that followed the
Columbia, Snake, Yellowstone, Missouri, Mississippi, Ohio,
Allegheny, Erie Canal and Hudson. Then he killed himself in 1946 at
the age of 37, shocking his friends and family members. For many
years, wild theories held sway _ he argued with a cook, who shot
him, or died as a result of a terrible accident.
</P>
<P>
   The 290-page book shows a darker side of Holmstrom. He loved
challenging rivers but returned back home frustrated and restless,
always planning his next adventure. After looking upon the Colorado
``like a friend, a companion'' and believing that the river claimed
a part of him, he confessed ``everything seems kind of empty.'' The
authors describe his reaction as ``withdrawal from the incredible
elation of the River.'' It's no great surprise that the tedium of
work could not match his river treks.
</P>
<P>
   The virtue of the title is that it tells the story with little
intrusion. Our rating:
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
