<HEADER>
A7038 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAYLE29-COX     04-28 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quayle wary of new gun laws
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Former Vice President Dan Quayle, in Atlanta to raise
money for his presidential campaign, said Wednesday that President
Clinton is ``playing politics'' by proposing new gun control laws
in response to the massacre at a Colorado high school.
</P>
<P>
   Aiming for the support of social conservatives, Quayle said
anti-gun measures are simple answers to a complex problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really think this is primarily an issue about guns or
primarily about values?'' Quayle asked the nonpartisan Georgia
Public Policy Foundation. Quayle made it clear he would choose the
latter.
</P>
<P>
   In a later interview, he emphasized his doubts about the
efficacy of enacting new gun control laws, saying that Dylan
Klebold and Eric Harris, the two gunmen at Columbine High School,
broke 17 laws in their murderous attack on schoolmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are a few more laws out there going to make a difference?''
Quayle said. ``I'm not sure they will.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Quayle said he would be open to a law that prohibited
kids who commit firearms violations from ever owning a gun.
</P>
<P>
   And asked about a federal proposal to limit purchasers of
handguns to one a month, Quayle said, ``I'd have to think about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, who is struggling to distinguish himself from a
half-dozen GOP candidates, issued a strong statement following the
high school shootings that warned gun control advocates not to try
to take advantage of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Quayle has talked about parental involvement and
responsibility, although it is unclear what kind of relationship
Klebold and Harris had with their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the teen-age years of his children, Quayle said he and
his wife, Marilyn, imposed curfews. ``Literally, you've got to get
in their face a little bit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle spoke to 200 people at the foundation luncheon, one in a
series featuring presidential candidates. He also held a private
fund-raising reception.
</P>
<P>
   Former Georgia Sen. Mack Mattingly, a fellow Indiana native and
national co-chairman of Quayle's campaign, introduced the former
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   On Kosovo, Quayle drew scattered applause when he criticized
Clinton for getting the United States involved in what he called a
civil war in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle has called for a negotiated settlement, which he defended
as the only way out of a situation in which U.S. vital security
interests are not at stake.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian treatment of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo is
``outrageous,'' Quayle said. ``But does that mean you're going to
get involved in a civil war? I would say no.''
</P>
<P>
   He also tried to point up his experience in foreign affairs,
saying the country cannot afford another president who needs
``on-the-job training.''
</P>
<P>
   That line apparently referred to the leading Republican
candidate, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle spoke more directly about Bush in the interview when he
joked, ``He's got to come out of Texas sometime. Sometime this
year, I presume.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
