<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7039 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      04-28 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRING OF DEPUTY LEADER BLURS SIGNALS FROM YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Yugoslavia's deputy prime minister, who publicly
criticized Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic over the weekend
for not telling his people the truth about the war in Kosovo, was
fired Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My voice of reason has now been put out,'' said Vuk Draskovic,
who was once the leader of Yugoslavia's main nationalist opposition
party.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic had said on Serbian television that Milosevic should
tell his people victory over NATO was impossible and that the
Yugoslav president should accept a UN security force to enforce a
peace.
</P>
<P>
   His words were widely seen either as an indirect peace
initiative by Milosevic or as a sign of a fissure within his
regime. Draskovic's dismissal Wednesday tended to dampen both
interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said Belgrade's
position on ``the key points'' has not changed enough ``to justify
any overwhelming optimism or any optimism at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin quoted several political figures in Serbia, mainly
opposition party officials who have spoken out against Milosevic in
recent days. However, he said, ``Whether that will signal a change
in his policies . . . is anybody's guess.''
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   --Several countries stepped up diplomatic efforts to settle the
conflict, most notably Russia. Viktor Chernomyrdin, Russia's envoy
to the Balkans, is expected in Belgrade Thursday. Foreign Minister
Igor Ivanov said the discussions will focus on what kind of
international force should enforce a peace settlement inside
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   US Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, traveling in
Berlin, said NATO and Russia were close to an agreement on this
issue. But he added, ``We have not heard anything from Belgrade''
that Milosevic might go along with it.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic alliance insists that NATO be ``at the core'' of
such a force, even if troops from non-NATO countries are also
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia's Foreign Ministry spokesman, Nebojse Vujevic, said
Wednesday that a peacekeeping mission must be ``nonarmed'' and
``under United Nations protection.'' He also said NATO must
withdraw its forces from Kosovo's borders before any such mission
moved in. NATO officials have dismissed both ideas as unacceptable,
noting that Kosovar refugees would not come back unless they were
protected by NATO arms.
</P>
<P>
   --White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said President Clinton does
not support the Rev. Jesse Jackson's trip to Yugoslavia to try and
free the three US soldiers who were captured March 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``We run the risk when Milosevic hears from multiple voices that
the message is not clear,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   National security adviser Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger met with
Jackson Wednesday, to reinforce the point that ``this is a private
mission'' and is ``not one we support,'' Lockhart said. Jackson
left Wednesday night, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The three prisoners, who had recent visits from International
Red Cross officials, were allowed to fax messages to their families
for the first time Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   --Clinton, speaking in the Rose Garden, reiterated that NATO's
airstrikes will continue as long as necessary. With the impending
arrival of extra warplanes in the region, he said, ``We will be
flying arond the clock, at lower altitudes, from all directions.''
He also said the weather should be getting better, allowing for
more persistent bombing. ``The weather is better in May than in
April, better in June than in May, better in July than in June,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also restated, in a White House meeting with
congressional leaders, that the air campaign alone would accomplish
NATO's goals. Senator John F. Kerry said after the meeting that
Clinton assured them that if US ground troops ever were sent in, he
would first ask Congress for approval, just as President Bush did
before sending troops to push Iraqi troops out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told reporters he saw some signs that Milosevic might be
losing his grip, citing the much-reported disagreements within
Yugoslavia, then adding, ``There are some things that we know that
I think I should not comment on.''
</P>
<P>
   --In a further expansion of the air war's resources, Bulgaria,
which borders Serbia, formally agreed to let NATO warplanes use its
air space in exchange for NATO guarantees of Bulgarian security.
</P>
<P>
   --Two grenades were tossed from a moving car into a NATO supply
depot manned by French troops near Skopje, Macedonia, early
Wednesday morning. Nobody was hurt, but the action heightened
concerns about Western soldiers' security and the possibility of
the conflict expanding outside Kosovo's borders.
</P>
<P>
   --Ethnic Albanian refugees continued to stream across the Kosovo
border, raising the total to well over a half-million.
</P>
<P>
   J. Brian Atwood, Clinton's humanitarian aid coordinator,
expressed concern that Milosevic might push all the remaining
Albanians out of Kosovo in the coming weeks, which would add
another 800,000 people to the flow.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the overcrowding in Albanian and Macedonian refugee
camps has ``reached a breaking point,'' the UN High Commissioner
for Refugees declared in a public statement. ``Tensions are on the
rise'' and the ``health and sanitation situation is quickly
deteriorating, leading to fears of the oubreak of epidemics'' once
warmer weather arrives. Measles, respiratory infections, and other
diseases are already breaking out at a rate that emergency vaccine
programs can barely cope with.
</P>
<P>
   Over 22,000 of the refugees have been evacuated to other
countries, mainly in Europe. The 20,000 to be accepted in the
United States should be leaving in the next few weeks. However,
Atwood said he was ``not satisfied'' that other countries are
fulfilling their commitment to accept another 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Five or six refugees were killed, and another seven were injured
Wednesday when they strayed into a minefield while approaching the
Macedonian border.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials acknowledged that a stray GBU-10 laser-guided
bomb, dropped Monday by an F-15, slammed into a residential area in
the Serbian town of Surdulica. Belgrade authorities, calling the
attack ``barbaric,'' said 16 civilian Serbs were killed. They also
said 400 have been killed, and 4,000 injured, through the five
weeks of NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea, while regretting the incident, said
these numbers could not be confirmed. Given that NATO attack planes
have flown 4,500 sorties to date, Shea said, the number of errant
bombs has been phenomenally low.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said the cause of the
mistake was unclear. However, it is well known that clouds, smoke,
or fog can diffuse, refract, or otherwise distort a laser beam.
Since the bomb follows the beam, such conditions could cause the
bomb to go astray. According to some reports, the stray weapon was
the third bomb dropped on the target and may have been deflected by
the smoke sent up by the two earlier explosions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Mary Leonard of the Globe staff contributed to this article. Wire
service material was used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
