<HEADLINE>
KRAFT HAS MANY OUTS TO HARTFORD DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Connecticut, eager to lure the New England Patriots to
Hartford last year, gave team owner Robert Kraft many conditions
under which he could walk away from the $374 million stadium deal
without paying a penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The escape clauses, negotiated by Kraft into the 300-plus page
contract, take on crucial importance now that Massachusetts
lawmakers have agreed to a plan that has a shot at keeping the team
in Foxborough, even though it is significantly less lucrative than
Hartford's.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the Connecticut deal, Kraft would have to
formally break off negotiations with Connecticut to consider the
Bay State bid. According to a review of the publicly available
contract signed by Gov. John G. Rowland and Kraft, that won't be
hard. Or expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Until May 2 there is only one penalty included in the accored _
a maximum $2 million fine _ that is Connecticut's ``sole and
exclusive right and remedy'' for any potential breach of contract.
After that date, penalties would increase depending on how much the
state has expended on the project.
</P>
<P>
   Before May 2, Kraft would have to pay only if he failed to honor
his agreement to negotiate exclusively with Connecticut or did not
show ``good faith'' in trying to complete details of the proposed
stadium deal.
</P>
<P>
   But because of delays in assembling the Hartford stadium site,
and serious questions about the state's ability to clean up the
property and deliver it on time and on budget, Kraft appears to
have ample grounds to bow out.
</P>
<P>
   Under the contact, the Patriots can terminate the agreement
without any penalty if, in the team's ``sole and absolute
discretion,'' the state's interim report, delivered last month,
fails to ``demonstrate sufficient progress'' in moving the steam
plant currently located the proposed stadium site.
</P>
<P>
   The May 2 deadline also allows the team to call it quits if the
report ``does not provide sufficient assurances that the site,
scope, cost, timing or funding'' of the project, and necessary
infrastructure improvements, can be completed in time for the team
to move into the stadium by August 2002.
</P>
<P>
   All of these issues have dogged Connecticut from the start.
Connecticut has not yet reached a final agreement on moving the
steam plant, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Key soil tests began just days ago, and results won't be
available for weeks, making it hard to determine whether the state
can clean up the site in time and on budget by the 2002 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   There are also questions about the project's infrastructure
budget. Construction experts, for example, are concerned that the
state may not be able to hang a portion of the 68,000-seat stadium
over a highway as planned without going over budget. And a change
in stadium design would also cause further delays.
</P>
<P>
   The state also has not negotiated the required sublease with the
University of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The May 2 deadline is the most obvious window of opportunity,
although the contract is littered with other ``escape hatches''
with varying deadlines. The later exit dates come with varying
degress of risk, however, and carry damages that would be decided
in a Connecitcut court.
</P>
<P>
   In the next two months or so, there are a number of other things
Connecticut must do, almost none of which have been completed.
These items include plans for:
</P>
<P>
   -- Preliminary stadium design agreements
</P>
<P>
   -- A project timetable and master coordination plan
</P>
<P>
   -- A site survey
</P>
<P>
   -- Site clean up and preparation
</P>
<P>
   -- Relocation of sewer and utility lines
</P>
<P>
   -- Stadium project budget
</P>
<P>
   -- Infrastructure improvements
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are also protected if the other NFL owners refuse
to approve the team's proposed move from Foxborough to Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft has formally submitted his application for the move, but
team owners are expected to approve it only if Massachusetts fails
to deliver an alternative proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
