<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN SOCIETY OF MAGAZINE EDITORS HANDS OUT ITS AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss.) (rk) 
 By   ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To borrow a phrase from the world of psychotherapy, at
Wednesday's National Magazine Awards it seemed at times that the
magazine world was trying to reach closure on the issue that
dominated magazine covers over the last year: the presidential
intern.
</P>
<P>
   While the lunch opened with a pair of Broadway actors singing
Monica Lewinsky-specific ditties, the tone later turned sober. The
American Society of Magazine Editors gave Newsweek the award for
reporting, for three articles about the intern and President
Clinton _ ``Clinton and the Intern,'' ``The Secret War'' and ``The
Tripp Trap?'' _ by the reporter Michael Isikoff and the Washington
editor, Evan Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen B. Shepard, the editor in chief of Business Week
magazine, was inducted into the Society's Hall of Fame _ along with
longtime former Scientific American editor Dennis Flanagan _ and
made pointed remarks about the culture of ``buzz'' and how
magazines can potentially sink to the ``lowest common
denominator.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in an age when it is fashionable to trash the media,''
Shepard said. However, he added, ``in an era of Matt Drudge, it is
possible to be provocative and successful without being trivial and
trashy.''
</P>
<P>
   The awards luncheon, sponsored by the magazine society and
administered by the Columbia University Graduate School of
Journalism, hosted a record attendance of almost 1,500 guests. At
the ceremony at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel, images from the scandal
_ like Ms. Lewinsky's Vanity Fair photo spread and a provocative
New Yorker cover featuring a presidential lower half surrounded by
microphones _ flitted across the video screens.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the winners _ and losers _ were notable. The New Yorker,
which had been nominated for eight awards, received none. Saveur
and Esquire, both nominated for three awards, and GQ, nominated for
one, did not win any.
</P>
<P>
   In the feature writing category, The American Scholar _ a
quarterly with a circulation of under 100,000 published by the Phi
Beta Kappa Society in Washington _ beat out GQ, Esquire and The New
Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxford American _ a cultural bimonthly magazine published in
Oxford, Miss. (the magazine's publisher is John Grisham, the
thriller writer) _ beat competitors like The New Yorker and
Business Week for the award of best single-category issue.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the ASME gave an award for General
Excellence in New Media: the online version of Cigar Aficionado
beat TheStreet.com, Slate, People Online and TheStandard.com, the
online version of The Industry Standard.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a complete list of National Magazine Award winners: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   General Excellence, over 1,000,000: Vanity Fair.
</P>
<P>
   General Excellence, 400,000 to 1,000,000: Conde Nast Traveler.
</P>
<P>
   General Excellence, 100,000 to 400,000: Fast Company.
</P>
<P>
   General Excellence, 100,000 and under: I.D. Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Personal Service: Good Housekeeping for three stories on colon
cancer: ``Katie's Crusade'' by Joanna Powell; ``The Stories of
Families Left Behind'' by Sondra Forsyth, ``The Preventable
Cancer'' by Lisa Collier Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Special Interest: PC Computing for ``Undocumented Internet
Secrets'' by the editors.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting: Newsweek for three stories by Michael Isikoff and
Evan Thomas: ``Clinton and the Intern,'' ``The Secret War'' and
``The Tripp Trap?''
</P>
<P>
   Feature Writing: The American Scholar for ``Exiting Nirvana'' by
Clara Claiborne Park.
</P>
<P>
   Public Interest: Time for a three-part series by Donald L.
Barlett and James B. Steele: ``Corporate Welfare,'' ``Paying a
Price for Polluters'' and ``the Empire of the Pigs.''
</P>
<P>
   Single-Topic Issue: The Oxford American, for its ``Second Annual
Double-Issue on Southern Music.''
</P>
<P>
   Design: ESPN The Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Photography: Martha Stewart. Living
</P>
<P>
   Fiction: Harper's Magazine for stories by Richard Russo, Lorrie
Moore and Michael Chabon.
</P>
<P>
   Essays and Criticism: The Atlantic Monthly for ``Hymn'' by Emily
Hiestand.
</P>
<P>
   General Excellence in New Media: Cigar Aficionado.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
