<HEADER>
A7045 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-WRAPUP-LADN     04-28 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-WRAPUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFLECTING UPON THE TROUT OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAMMOTH LAKES, Calif. _ A few observations from the opening
weekend of trout fishing in the Eastern Sierra:
</P>
<P>
   Mystery solved: He registered for trout derbies in Bishop and
Toms Place as ``Uncle Bill's Barber Shop.'' So when calls were
placed to tournament headquarters late Saturday evening to inquire
the name of the angler who took the 10.35-pound brown trout at
Bridgeport Reservoir that was the opening-day's second largest
fish, all that newspapers could report was ``angler unidentified.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Tuesday that confirmation was made that the
mystery angler was Bill Kinzy, whose Bishop haircutting business on
Main Street was closed through Monday with a sign that read, ``Gone
fishing! Be back Tuesday. Uncle Bill''; the word ``Tuesday'' was
crossed out. Apparently he thought he would push his luck a little
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Not for anglers only: The trout opener also can be a pleasure
for Eastern Sierra residents who are working and rarely get a
chance to fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like seeing the guys from the year before,'' said Lee McCoy,
proprietor of Falling Rock Marina situated on Bridgeport
Reservoir's east side. ``And my son (Lee of Gardnerville, Nev.)
comes and works with me opening weekend, and that's important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the period of a couple of days, 300 guys will call you by
your first name. It feels good. That's neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny stories: Deborah Paules of Simi Valley got some second
looks at her pink fishing rod and reel. ``Isn't it hideous?'' she
observed while bank-fishing at Upper Twin Lake out of Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Ron, bought it for her, but said: ``If she goes for
a drink and a fish hits, I won't touch it. Any self-respecting man
won't touch a pink fishing rod.''
</P>
<P>
   At least they don't get their fishing tackle mixed up.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a family was still chatting about a fishing pole that
was lost hours earlier when an overzealous trout took hook, line
and sinker; the outfit was caught a short time later by another
angler... with the offending trout still hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first guy was crying the blues,'' said Ron Paules, who
witnessed the sequence of events. ``Ten minutes later his buddy
says, `Guess what? I've got your pole and the fish is still on
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Paules wasn't so lucky last year; he lost a rod and reel
under similar conditions while fishing the same lake from a boat.
</P>
<P>
   Opener blastoff: At Crowley Lake, the most popular of
opening-day destinations, fireworks were set off at 5:10 a.m. to
signal the season's start in Mono County, replacing the traditional
pre-dawn flare.
</P>
<P>
   Second's best: Often overlooked by the opening-day's big fish at
Crowley Lake is the top catch of Day 2, which, in this case, was a
half-pound heavier than the first day's trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Yamasaki of Torrance on Sunday fooled a 6-pound, 5-ounce
rainbow at Sandy Point using a worm.
</P>
<P>
   Cold cuts: Anglers at Crowley on Saturday were subjected to
periods of snow that occasionally was blown sideways by gusts of
wind estimated at 25 mph or greater.
</P>
<P>
   Those gathering data at fish-cleaning stations near Crowley's
marina noticed that the cold weather might actually have
contributed to anglers attaining their five-trout limits as early
as 8:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't picking and choosing their fish as much,'' said
Curtis Milliron, as associated fishery biologist with the
Department of Fish and Game's office in Bishop. In other words, he
explained, anglers weren't as apt to throw back smaller fish in
hopes of catching larger ones... so they could get out of the
elements faster and into their trucks, car and campers.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: Meanwhile at Crowley, Milliron crunched the
statistics that are gathered and analyzed for his annual
opening-weekend studies. The results from 423 rainbow trout
measured:
</P>
<P>
   Average length: 14.0 inches _ an inch longer than the norm, as
predicted, thanks to a mild winter that allowed the 300,000
rainbows planted in August and September to feed more actively
during the closed season.
</P>
<P>
   Average weight: 1.07 pounds, slightly above the long-term
average. Milliron had predicted even heavier fish _ 1.1 to 1.2
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Percent of carryovers: 17.5. The long-term average of trout
caught after surviving one or more fishing seasons is about 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Percent of brown trout in catch: 1; the biologist usually
expects 2 to 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other results:
</P>
<P>
   Catch rates: 1.23 trout per hour Saturday for 574 anglers
interviewed. That means a five-fish limit was taken in 4.07 hours,
quicker than the average limit in 4.7 to 4.9 hours. Fishing was
even more productive Sunday, when 315 anglers caught 1.39 trout an
hour, or a limit in 3.6 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The DFG's goal is a trout an hour, or a limit in five hours.
However, depending on the mildness or harshness of the winter,
respectively, limits have been taken in as short as 3.13 hours (at
1.6 trout per hour in 1992) and as long as 15.6 hours (at .32 trout
per hour following the late, late thaw of 1993, there weren't
enough hours of daylight to catch a limit).
</P>
<P>
   Lakewide catch estimates: 7,034 trout on Saturday, 6,355 Sunday,
for a two-day total of 13,389 fish _ 14,326 pounds or 7.16 tons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
