<SLUG> BC-SANCTIONS-FOOD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION LIFTS BAN ON FOOD, MEDICINE SALES TO THREE
COUNTRIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration Wednesday lifted a ban
on the sale of food and medicine to three countries sanctioned for
being terrorist states, paving the way for Northwest farmers to
sell wheat to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Iran, the action also makes sales of food and
medicine possible to Libya and Sudan. In the future, President
Clinton wants to exclude food and medicine sanctions against any
country unless they are at war with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Agriculture Department estimates that U.S.
exporters could sell as much as $500 million worth of goods,
primarily wheat, corn and rice annually to sanctioned countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The national security and foreign policy concerns that led to
the original decisions to impose comprehensive sanctions on those
countries still pertain,'' said Undersecretary of State Stuart
Eizenstat. ``(But) sales of food, medicine and other human
necessities do not generally enhance a nation's military
capabilities or support terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat said the decision was driven by the administration's
decision to reform sanctions policy, and not by any particular
political concerns. But U.S.-Iranian relations have warmed somewhat
in recent months, and Libya recently complied with a longstanding
U.S. demand that it turn over to Scotland two suspects in the
bombing of Pan Am Flight 103.
</P>
<P>
   Iran was a huge market for Northwest wheat prior to the Iranian
revolution of 1979. Northwest wheat growers had 53 percent of the
Iranian wheat market _ a percentage that would be worth $176
million annually today, according to Glen Squires of the Washington
Wheat Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But when the U.S. imposed sanctions, the Iranian wheat market
was snapped up by countries such as Canada and Australia. Now the
United States must compete with those countries to win back Iranian
market share.
</P>
<P>
   Libya and Sudan are less significant potential markets for
Washington state growers.
</P>
<P>
   The development is the second bit of good news in recent weeks
for wheat farmers, who have been struggling to survive with low
prices. The Clinton administration recently persuaded China to drop
its longstanding ban on the importation of Northwest wheat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great news, and shows that common sense is finally
catching up with the silliness of unilateral sanctions,'' said
state Agriculture Director Jim Jesernig. ``It's another step toward
eliminating a tool that only hurts Washington farmers.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not open the door to unrestricted sales of food and
medicine to Iran, Libya and Sudan, but rather granted the federal
bureaucracy permission to consider sales on a case by case basis.
But administration officials said the presumption now is that sales
will be allowed to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Iran has already placed an order with a trading company called
Niki to purchase grain from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a constructive move, and very helpful to U.S.
agriculture,'' said Richard Bliss, president of Niki. ``From the
Iranian point of view, having us as a competitor in the grain
market is very positive, because our absence from the market gave
the Iranian trade to other countries and probably resulted in
higher prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss said the first sale to Iran, which has yet to be approved
by the administration, would probably involve several types of
wheat, including the white wheat grown in the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential is fabulous,'' said Rep. George Nethercutt,
R-Wash., whose eastern Washington district is home to much of the
state's wheat acreage. ``We hope we get a chunk of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shahriar Afshar, the president of the Iranian Trade Association,
a U.S. organization pushing for a lifting of sanctions against
Iran, welcomed Wednesday's development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ecstatic,'' he said. ``This will be of tremendous
benefit to American exporters ... and is a real positive step in
U.S.-Iran engagement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
