</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-CONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO SHOOTING EXPOSES CRACKS IN GUN CONTROL MOVEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gun control groups have seized on the mass shooting at Columbine
High School as a new opportunity to gain command of the nation's
firearms debate, but the massacre has also intensified long-running
divisions among the allies over the best way to reduce deaths from
firearms.
</P>
<P>
   From whether to punish the parents of children who use guns in
crimes to the effectiveness of safety locks, the groups are often
at odds, their differences often reflecting their political
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   While moderate organizations like Handgun Control Inc., based in
Washington, applauded the broad package of gun control measures
announced on Tuesday by President Clinton, an official of the
Violence Policy Center, a small activist group in Washington that
favors a ban on handgun sales, said the package's only worthwhile
proposal was to ban sales at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nothing more than a collection of knick-knacks and
doo-dads that focus on the gun seller and gun user but does not
focus on the gun industry,'' said the group's director of federal
policy, Kristen Rand.
</P>
<P>
   The spokeswoman for Handgun Control, Naomi Paiss, said the group
does not favor a such a ban. But she also said that groups in the
firearms control movement shared many of the same objectives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't a lot of players in gun control,'' Ms. Paiss
said. ``And divisions, such as they are, are nothing compared to
the other fratricide on the other side of this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun groups like the National Rifle Association also often find
themselves disagreeing with other gun interests, such as
manufacturers, on policies and strategies to follow.
</P>
<P>
   But some gun control advocates have even challenged data used by
others in the movement to lobby for new laws. In the past decade,
for example, Handgun Control, the nation's biggest gun-control
group, has helped pass laws in 16 states that would make parents
liable if they failed to store guns safely. In advocating that
approach, the group has pointed to a 1997 study in the Journal of
the American Medical Association that found that states that had
enacted such bills had seen a 23 percent reduction in the number of
accidental shootings of children.
</P>
<P>
   But in an editorial published Thursday in the British Medical
Journal, Stephen P. Teret, director of the Johns Hopkins University
Center for Gun Policy and Research, said that the study is flawed
because its conclusions were overly influenced by findings in just
one state, Florida, which passed the nation's first safe storage
bill in 1989. With the Florida results removed, an unpublished
analysis of the JAMA data performed by Johns Hopkins researchers
suggests that the laws have little or no impact.
</P>
<P>
   Teret said in a telephone interview Wednesday that because the
JAMA study was the only one on the issue he had no idea whether the
laws work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my reservations,'' said Teret, who is an advocate of
``smart'' technology that would limit a weapon's use to one person.
``People buy guns because they want them available for immediate
protection, and it may be not be realistic to expect people to lock
them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Paiss said that Handgun Control believes that the Johns
Hopkins review had failed to account for factors like how
vigorously the safe storage laws have been prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do agree that more research is needed,'' Ms. Paiss said.
``But we are confident that strong, well-publicized child access
laws will have an effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Cummings, a doctor at the Harborview Injury Prevention
and Research Center in Seattle and the lead author of the 1997 JAMA
article, could not be reached Wednesday for comment. But in an
recent interview he said that he was collecting more data on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Along with other steps, the proposals announced by the president
on Tuesday would restrict the purchase of handguns to one a month
and restore a waiting period before any handgun purchase. It also
would raise the minimum age for possessing a handgun to 21 from 18
and impose felony penalties on adults who knowingly or recklessly
allow a child access to a gun that is used to commit a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Horowitz, a lawyer with the Coalition to Stop Handgun
Violence, in Washington, said the group backed the initiatives
cited by Clinton but did not believe they went far enough. Among
the group's goals: a tough licensing and registration system on all
firearms as well on limits on those who could buy handguns.
Horowitz added there were ``honest differences'' within the
firearms movement over the effectiveness of measures like safety
locks for weapons and the smart technology championed by Teret.
</P>
<P>
   Those favoring mandatory safety locks say that they are a cheap
and simple way to prevent children from shooting either themselves
or friends, or using the guns to commit crimes. Requiring companies
to include the safety locks with firearms is a good way to remind
parents and others to store guns safely, those advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   But other gun control groups say that locks are little more than
a feel-good measure. Responsible gun owners are already safely
storing their weapons, they say, and giving a lock to those who
leave guns lying around or to those bent on violence won't mean
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think to make the argument that trigger locks would be a
deterrent to two kids capable of making hundreds of bombs is
ludicrous on its face,'' said Ms. Rand of the Violence Policy
Center.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A number of companies including Colt's Manufacturing, Sig Arms
and O.F. Mossberg &AMP; Sons Inc., are developing firearms that
incorporate technologies in which only an authorized user can fire
the weapon, officials in the firearms industry said. And Teret says
that widespread use of such technology could have reduced gun
problems ranging from accidental shootings to the use of guns in
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But some gun control advocates have their doubts. Ms. Rand said
that the number of deaths that could be prevented by such guns
might be offset, because people who might not otherwise buy a
firearm might buy a smart weapon. As a result, she said, a
homeowner might try to use such a weapon in defense against an
attacker and get shot.
</P>
<P>
   While Handgun Control backs the development of the smart
technology, Horowitz of the Coalition to Stop Handgun Violence,
said that his group is hedging its bets.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one side they will save lives and on the other side they
will increase gun sales, which may lead to more shootings,''
Horowitz said. ``Right now, it's unclear what the effect will be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
