<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: NO QUICK SOLUTION TO KOSOVO CONFLICT IN SIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With KOSOVO-CONGRESS) 
(sw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Five weeks into the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia, the
Clinton administration is faced with three choices on the war in
Kosovo, all disagreeable: an open-ended air campaign, the dispatch
of ground troops, or compromise in a diplomatic solution.
</P>
<P>
   None of the options offers a quick solution. President Clinton
suggested on Wednesday that bombing could last into the summer;
preparing for an armed invasion could take months, and a negotiated
resolution would have to span a yawning chasm between NATO and
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia on the shape of a
negotiated settlement.
</P>
<P>
   With mounting eagerness, the administration appears to be
focusing on a diplomatic strategy and using Russia, whose opinion
it spurned at the outset of the conflict, to help find an exit out
of an increasingly difficult situation. After a telephone call from
President Boris Yeltsin to Clinton on Sunday, Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott made a one-day visit to Moscow to explore the
potential of Russian mediation.
</P>
<P>
   The potential use of Russia as a mediator turned into an option,
administration and European officials said, as the military outlook
of the Kosovo conflict became less certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration is throwing a `Hail Mary' to the
Russians,'' said an adviser to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Though Clinton and other NATO leaders confidently proclaimed at
their recent summit that the air campaign is eroding Milosevic's
strength, one of NATO's senior soldiers, Gen. Klaus Naumann, said
publicly on Monday that the exclusive use of air power had never
achieved victory in the history of military campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The military alternative, an invasion by land, appeared less and
less likely after the administration choked off discussion of
ground troops at the NATO summit.
</P>
<P>
   Among factors that the White House is taking into consideration
are polls that show that less than 50 percent of the American
public support ground troops in Kosovo if that means American
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomatic alternative also raises problems. One is whether
the Russians will really argue for NATO's five conditions, which
include an international military force with NATO troops at its
core. Another is whether NATO is prepared to compromise on the
conditions, after insisting that it will not _ a compromise that
would require some tricky explanations from NATO and the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials seemed confident that if this path was
chosen, Clinton would find a way to sell it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is a better communicator than anyone else,'' said a
senior administration official. ``Once Clinton decides that's what
he's going to do, he'll sell it. If Nixon could sell the the fall
of Saigon as peace with honor, Clinton can sell this.`
</P>
<P>
   But ``this'' _ a diplomatic solution based on a compromise _ may
be no more of a quick fix than the path of a stepped up air
campaign that the administration has chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has given any estimate yet how long the bombing could
last, and Clinton suggested on Wednesday that it could go at least
into July.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's military commander, Gen. Wesley K. Clark, noted in a
briefing Tuesday that despite the intensive air assaults to date,
Milosevic had as many forces inside Kosovo now than he did six
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   To some officials in Washington, the general's assessment looked
like a plea in disguise for ground troops, but that option was not
on the table, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The British prime minister, Tony Blair, failed to persuade
Clinton of the wisdom of preparing for ground troops during a
meeting at the White House before the NATO summit opening. The
French president, Jacques Chirac, who had been expected to argue
for ground troops, failed to do so. And elsewhere in Europe,
particularly Germany and Italy, there was considerable political
opposition to ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   While a diplomatic solution was looking better and better, at
this point it still seemed a long stretch, administration officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have insisted that they are not willing to be only
a ``postman'' for NATO, as Foreign Secretary Igor Ivanov put it.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the administration and NATO insist for now that
they will stick to their five conditions. The most contentious of
these is the composition of the international security force that
would take Albanian refugees back to Kosovo and the character of an
international protectorate that the administration has said it
favors carving out in Kosovo .
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Milosevic appeared to be holding firm to his
opposition to the presence of NATO troops on Kosovo soil. His
stubbornness was demonstrated Tuesday evening when he fired Deputy
Prime Minister Vuk Draskovic for suggesting that foreign
peacekeeping troops under U.N. control should be allowed in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   With such a large gap between what the administration can
apparently tolerate and what Milosevic will agree to, there seemed
to be much diplomatic work to be done, administration and European
officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
