u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-IMF-840&AMP;ADD-NY     04-28 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMF-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF TO RESUME LENDING TO RUSSIA, PENDING REFORMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The International Monetary Fund announced a
preliminary agreement Wednesday night to lend Russia $4.5 billion
over the next 18 months, the first resumption of loans since the
country defaulted on its debts and devalued its currency last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   But in a little noticed and highly unusual element of the deal,
the money will never actually be sent to Moscow. Instead, at the
insistence of the U.S. Treasury and some European nations, the
loans will essentially be transferred from one of the Monetary
Fund's accounts to another _ allowing Russia to avoid default on
money it owes the IMF this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   The Western allies feared that if the loan was made in the usual
way, with the money transferred directly to Russia's central bank,
the cash could disappear in days. That is what happened last July,
when the fund sent $4.8 billion to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The deal enables Russia to make it through elections in the year
2000 without a default to the IMF that would undercut whatever
strands of credibility the country has with private investors.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations over the loan had sputtered along for months, as
the fund had sought to extract commitments from Russia over its
spending policies, reluctance to collect taxes, and failure to
reform a collapsing banking system. But the renewed drive by the
West to complete the deal reflected a wish to avoid another nasty
dispute with the Russians at a moment when Moscow has been courted
extensively to play the role of mediator in the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to make sure that Russia does not feel even more
alienated from the West,'' one senior official involved in the
talks said earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Wednesday night about the loan
agreement, IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus said, ``I am
pleased that we have agreed with the Russian authorities on an
economic program for Russia that I hope to be able to recommend to
the Executive Board in support of a new Stand-by Arrangement as a
new step in the cooperation between the IMF and Russia. There are
still a few technical elements to be settled in the next few
days.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Russia also had agreed to provide the IMF with an
explanation of how earlier loans had been used, a veiled reference
to widespread suspicions that past loans had been funneled to
benefit some of Russia's wealthy oligarchs or secretly sent abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The refusal to send the new loans to Moscow reflected some
behind-the-scenes pressure from Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin
and finance ministers from other European nations, who had argued
that any credible new loan program for Russia must include
safeguards to prevent a repeat of last summer's embarrassment. In
mid-March, Rubin told a congressional panel that much of the $4.8
billion pumped into Moscow's foreign exchange reserves at that time
``may have been siphoned off improperly.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin was referring to investigations showing that when the IMF
money briefly propped up the value of the ruble, the country's
richest oligarchs raced to convert their cash into dollars at a
favorable exchange rate. More than $4 billion flowed out of Russia
nearly immediately, much of it headed for Swiss bank accounts and
other safe havens.
</P>
<P>
   This time, officials say, Rubin's aides made it clear to the IMF
that the United States would seek to block any effort to resume
loans to Russia unless the IMF retained direct control over the
money at all times. And that means the aid amounts to little more
than rescheduling Russia's payments to the fund. It owes more than
$5 billion to the IMF over the next 18 months, and nearly $2.5
billion by the end of June. So even with the tentative agreement
reached Wednesday, Russia's new loans will total less than its
repayments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that the IMF will get a bit more from
Russia than Russia gets from the fund,'' one senior official
involved in the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's finance minister, Mikhail Zadornov, who has been in
Washington all week holding talks with the IMF and the World Bank,
had hinted earlier Wednesday that an agreement was close, saying
``we do not have any special problems.'' The governor of Russia's
central bank, Viktor Gerashchenko, had hoped to borrow about $4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But the agreement alone will not get Russia the money it has
sought for so long. Before the board of the IMF formally approves
any accord, the IMF is insisting that the Russian Parliament pass
several bills to remake Russia's bankruptcy laws, strengthen the
tax-collection system and overhaul the banking system. Last year
the IMF transferred money to Russia before the Parliament acted _
only to discover that the Communist-led body failed to fulfill
several commitments made by the government of President Boris
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   A senior European official who had been briefed on the
negotiations said Wednesday that ``the way the agreement is now set
not a dollar will actually enter Russia, so the risk is very
small.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There is something else the IMF's board has demanded: A report
by Price Waterhouse on the operations of Fimaco, an offshore
company based in Britain's Channel Islands, where the Russian
Central Bank was secretly sending a portion of its foreign
reserves. The fund was never informed by Russian officials that
they were moving some of the reserves _ presumably including some
cash loaned by the IMF _ outside of Russian territory.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, Russia has yet to provide a convincing explanation
of why the money was sent to the offshore haven, exactly who had
control over it, and who may have benefited from management fees or
investment proceeds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
