</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PREXY-ART-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TALKS OF KOSOVO CAMPAIGN LASTING MANY MONTHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By   JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton warned Wednesday that NATO's
bombardment and economic pressure on Yugoslavia would persist for
many more months and called on Congress to quickly pass his request
for $6 billion in emergency funds to pay the mounting costs of the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each day, our military campaign takes a toll on Serbia's
machinery of repression,'' Clinton said in a Rose Garden statement
after a meeting on the Balkan conflict with 46 members of Congress.
``The Serbian leadership has failed to divide us and will not
outlast us. The combined military might and moral determination of
Europe and North America will endure.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said that additional air power was arriving in the
region and allied pilots were beginning to fly around the clock on
missions to destroy Serb troops who are terrorizing the the ethnic
Albanian population of Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia. The Serbs
have already driven hundreds of thousands of Kosovo's people out of
the province.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that the air campaign, now at the end of its fifth
week, had been hampered by rain and clouds and said the pace would
now pick up as the skies clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, the weather is better in May than in April,
better in June than in May, better in July than in June,'' Clinton
said in a clear sign that he intends to continue the air war for
months. ``And I feel very strongly that we should stay with and be
very strong in determination to pursue our strategy, as well as the
very important decisions we made at the NATO conference to
intensify the economic pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said that signs of dissension were beginning to
appear in Belgrade, including public criticism by senior officials
of Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Olympia J. Snowe, R-Maine, said that Clinton pleaded for
forbearance from lawmakers during their meeting, saying they had to
give air power time to work to undermine Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But she said that the administration's ``gradualism and
incrementalism'' were frustrating many in Congress, who want
quicker consideration of the use of ground troops to end the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said absolutely we have to be patient,'' Ms. Snowe said.
``But he gave no indication how long it would last.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Snowe and other members of Congress who attended Wednesday's
session with the president said he repeated his determination not
to dispatch ground troops to fight in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the contrary,'' said Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass. ``He
indicated that he intended a stepped-up prosecution of the air war
and the blockade of oil supplies.''
</P>
<P>
   But other members said that Clinton's aims _ the removal of Serb
forces from Kosovo and the return of hundreds of thousands of
ethnic Albanian refugees _ could not be achieved with air power
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala., said that the administration had
been sending confusing signals about the the goals of the war, its
costs and the administration's plans for relocating refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The messages coming out of the White House have a great deal
of ambiguity,'' Callahan said. ``But it's very obvious to me that
this is going to be a prolonged and costly endeavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged the lawmakers to move quickly on his funding
request, which would provide money to replace munitions already
used and to build weapon stockpiles for a lengthy air campaign. The
administration's $6 billion package also includes about $1 billion
for food and shelter for refugees displaced by the fighting in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The president said that Congress should resist the temptation to
attach to the legislation money for unrelated activities, no matter
how worthy, because it would slow the bill's progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must get a Kosovo funding measure passed and to my desk
now,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Draft proposals in the Senate and the House would add $6 billion
to $7 billion in Pentagon programs, bringing the emergency spending
bill requested by Clinton to roughly $12 billion to $13 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional add-ons include projects arguably unconnected
to NATO's operations in the Balkans. For example, the House bill
would spend hundreds of millions of dollars on construction
programs sought by the military to increase soldiers' morale and
efficiency, such as refurbishing 50-year-old barracks, building car
washes and garages, and paving parking lots at bases in Germany.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many Republicans are eager to approve them as a show of support
for the military, and to bolster their argument that Clinton has
starved the Pentagon. But the emergency money must come from
surplus Social Security revenues, which both parties have pledged
to keep their hands off.
</P>
<P>
   At least five Republican senators, loath to break their vows of
fiscal abstinence, are ready to break with their colleagues instead
of supporting a $12 billion emergency bill, according to senior
aides. They want the spending limited to what the president has
requested. Others want to see even more money added to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Given the intensity of the internal debate, it will be at least
two weeks before any money is approved.
</P>
<P>
   In his White House remarks, Clinton said that the terror in
Kosovo was the product of a ``meticulously planned'' campaign by
Milosevic's Serb troops to drive the ethnic Albanian majority out
of the province. ``A campaign organized by the government of
Belgrade for a specific political purpose _ to maintain its grip
over Kosovo by ridding the land of its people,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the expulsions began, ethnic Albanians made up about 90
percent of Kosovo's population of two million.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cited continuing reports of atrocities, including one
unconfirmed report brought to him by Brian Atwood, the
administration's humanitarian coordinator for the region. Atwood,
who just returned from Albania, said he had been told of one
village in Kosovo where most of the men were rounded up, tied
together and burned alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind of story that would be too horrible to believe
if it were not so consistent with what so many refugees have been
saying,'' the president said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
