<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS BARS USE OF GROUND TROOPS WITHOUT APPROVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A wary Congress waded into the politics of war
Wednesday, as the House rejected calling home US forces from the
Balkans but voted to prohibit President Clinton from sending ground
troops into Kosovo without congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   The House also overwhelmingly rejected a resolution to declare
war on Yugoslavia, marking the first time since World War II that
Congress has voted on a declaration of war.
</P>
<P>
   In a debate with potential implications for individual members
and their parties in the 2000 elections, lawmakers summoned the
conflicting images of the US experience in Vietnam and the triumph
over fascism in World War II before they voted, 249-180, to require
congressional approval for the use of ground forces in NATO's
battle against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The vote threw open a window on the deep divisions within
Congress over the US role in the NATO campaign, as 45 Democrats,
including four from Massachusetts, supported the measure despite
Clinton's warning that ``America must continue to speak with a
single voice.'' The president has said he opposes a ground war in
the Balkans but believes he should retain the power to deploy US
forces without prior approval.
</P>
<P>
   A related skirmish roiled over Clinton's request for $6 billion
to fund the Kosovo operation through September and a rival plan by
House and Senate Republican leaders to spend $13 billion on Kosovo
activities and other Pentagon needs, including a pay raise for the
military.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, lawmakers faced the prospect of linking themselves
and their parties to a potentially unpopular military conflict, as
they weighed the US role in the Balkans with an eye toward the next
election.
</P>
<P>
   At times, subtlety all but dissolved as lawmakers reminded each
other of the personal consequences. In pushing for the House to
declare war on Yugoslavia rather than pursue the ``half-hearted''
policies that led to the US defeat in Vietnam, Representative Gene
Taylor, a Mississippi Democrat, scanned the chamber and told his
colleagues, ``You aren't willing to risk your careers, but you're
willing to risk those kids' lives.''
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor stood nearly alone in supporting the war resolution,
which was defeated, 427-2. The only other supporter was
Represetantive Joe Barton, a Texas Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's chief sponsor, California Republican Tom Campbell,
even voted against it. Campbell said he had pushed the legislation
to force reluctant House leaders to bring the Kosovo issue to the
floor for a debate.
</P>
<P>
   Criticizing the Vietnam-era Congress for lacking the courage to
declare war on Vietnam or end US involvement there, Campbell said
of the Kosovo conflict, ``We have a chance to stop this now, to say
no before we get in too deep.''
</P>
<P>
   Foes called the proposed declaration of war a highly provocative
step with potentially disastrous consequences for world stability.
</P>
<P>
   The House also killed a measure that would have ended US
involvement in the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative, based on the Vietnam-era War Powers Act, would
have required the White House to limit the military campaign to 60
days unless it obtained congressional authorization. The measure
was defeated, 290-139, after Clinton's handling of the Kosovo
crisis was roundly criticized by many members of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Only 12 Democrats broke with Clinton on the measure. And only
two New Englanders supported it: New Hampshire Republicans Charles
F. Bass and John E. Sununu.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was the vote to require congressional approval for
ground troops in Kosovo that Republican leaders hailed as a
triumph. The measure faces a likely filibuster in the Senate and a
possible veto by Clinton, who had assured congressional leaders
before the vote that he would consult them before he deployed
ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Yet GOP leaders said they wanted to hold Clinton to his word and
press him to communicate US objectives in the mission more clearly.
``It is important that the American people be heard, through their
elected representatives, before ground troops are committed in this
hostile situation by the president,'' said House Speaker J. Dennis
Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert said Clinton should consider the contentious House
debate ``a signal that he should better explain the goals, the cost
and the long-term strategy of why we are there.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Democrats accused GOP leaders of trying to use the war
to their political advantage. ``I think the Republican idea is to
make this Clinton's war,'' said Representative J. Joseph Moakley of
South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to develop a strategy where if this operation
should prove to be unsuccessful, they will be in a position to
criticize,'' said Representative William D. Delahunt, a
Massachusetts Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The four Massachusetts Democrats who voted to require
congressional approval for ground troops were Barney Frank, Edward
J. Markey, James P. McGovern and John F. Tierney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we should be very cautious about getting ourselves
into a ground war in the Balkans,'' Markey said. ``We should recall
the lessons of the Gulf of Tonkin resolution and not pass a Gulf of
the Adriatic resolution that provides an open-ended and
unconditional authorization for the use of ground forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Senator Jesse Helms, chairman of the Foreign
Relations Committee, scheduled a hearing Thursday to vote on a
measure that would authorize Clinton to use ``all means
necessary,'' including ground troops, to prosecute the war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
