A7061 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOODOO-SFCHRON &LR;      04-28 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOODOO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Upstart Sticks Pin in Voodoo   By David Einstein 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
A race car explodes in a ball of flames following a 100-mph
collision. Tiger Woods raises a clenched fist after sinking a
birdie putt. The Empire strikes back and shatters your spaceship
into smithereens.
</P>
<P>
   Video games have gotten awfully realistic, thanks mostly to 3-D
chips on special circuit boards that go into personal computers.
And now the competition is heating up, with two Silicon Valley
rivals introducing the most powerful technology yet.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose's 3Dfx Interactive, the perennial market leader in
high-end PC graphics, recently introduced the Voodoo3, the latest
in its popular line of 3-D Voodoo chips.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming weeks, Santa Clara's Nvidia will unveil its new
Riva TNT2 chip, which it says will outperform the Voodoo3.
</P>
<P>
   Early reviews in trade publications tend to back up some of the
claims, suggesting that 3Dfx's undisputed reign may be ending. &UR;  &LR; ``A
lot of people expect the TNT2 to be the high-end product of the
year,'' said analyst George Iwanyc of Dataquest.
</P>
<P>
   3Dfx is selling three versions of Voodoo3 video boards under its
own brand name, priced at $129, $179 and $249. Boards based on
Nvidia's TNT2 should start shipping next month from Diamond
Multimedia, Creative Labs and other vendors in similar price
ranges.
</P>
<P>
   (Like every other computer component or peripheral, video boards
have been dropping in price, and the arrival of new technology is
making older products even cheaper. A Voodoo2 board that cost $299
a year ago can now be had for $100.)
</P>
<P>
   The technology coming out of 3Dfx and Nvidia already has turned
the PC into a gaming platform that offers clearer images and faster
action than you can get now on a dedicated game console such as the
Sony PlayStation or the Nintendo 64.
</P>
<P>
   As high-speed Internet access becomes widely available, 3-D
chips also will enhance multimedia on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Most new PCs come with 3-D video _ the biggest provider is ATI
Technologies, a Canadian company that specializes in selling
graphics systems to PC-makers. But the 3-D built into PCs usually
is not top-notch.
</P>
<P>
   For a better picture, you have to install a video board with a
chip from 3Dfx, Nvidia or even ATI, which also has some pretty good
retail products.
</P>
<P>
   Video boards featuring Voodoo chips have been among the most
popular upgrades for PCs, and as a result, 3Dfx has been one of the
most successful computer hardware companies. Founded just four
years ago, it had revenues of $202.6 million and income of $21.7
million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Nvidia, which went public in January, also has prospered. In
fiscal 1998, sales of video chips earned it $4.1 million and
generated revenue of $158.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   With TNT2, Nvidia has sent a signal that it no longer intends to
settle for second place. ``We truly believe that it will provide a
stunning level of visual realism, for the first time, to the
mainstream PC user,'' said Nvidia spokesman Derek Perez.
</P>
<P>
   From a purely technical standpoint, Nvidia indeed may have the
edge. The TNT2 can display 32-bit color at high screen resolutions
versus just 16 bits for Voodoo3. That can translate into clearer
images and sharper color definition. Nvidia also says its chip is
faster than Voodoo3, with better image textures and smoother
action.
</P>
<P>
   3Dfx officials argue that Nvidia's chip takes a performance hit
because it's too busy trying to display vibrant colors. As a
result, action can become jerky.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our competitors are talking about 32-bit rendering, the
thing they never tell you is that along with that goes lousy
performance,'' said Peter Wicher, director of consumer products for
3Dfx.
</P>
<P>
   Voodoo3, says Wicher, provides a superior ``overall quality for
the gaming experience.''
</P>
<P>
   3Dfx also says more games are compatible with its chips than
with Nvidia's _ partly that's because some games are written to
work best with 3Dfx's own software standard, called Glide. Most
popular games, however, should work well with either chip.
</P>
<P>
   The question of who has the technical edge may be a moot point
with the average user, because with most current games there's not
much difference in actual performance between TNT2 and Voodoo3.
Both can run full-motion video as well as graphics without breaking
a sweat, and both significantly enhance the performance of sports
games, shoot-em-ups and fast-paced adventure games.
</P>
<P>
   None of today's games can take the new chips to their limits.
But games optimized for them will soon start to appear, and then
we'll get a better idea of how the TNT2 stacks up against Voodoo3.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the claims of the companies about technology
effectively cancel each other out, the only key issue left will be
price. If TNT2-based boards fetch less at retail than their Voodoo3
counterparts, analysts say Nvidia could win wide acceptance for its
brand and take market share from 3Dfx.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most likely it will come down to which one can hit the right
price point and get the buzz generating around it,'' said
Dataquest's Iwanyc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
