<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7063 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON &LR;      04-28 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Charismatic Editor Steps Aside at S.F. Business Monthly
Upside  Media 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Dan Fost &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Inside Upside, changes are afoot.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Brandt, the charismatic editor of the monthly business
magazine, has stepped aside. He's still with Upside Media, but is
seeking funding for a new Internet media business.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Macworld editor Adrian Mello is the new
editor-in-chief, overseeing the magazine, Web site and book
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The personnel moves come as the company, late of San Mateo,
settles into its new home on San Francisco's Market Street, just
four floors below Mother Jones' headquarters. That's San Francisco
for you: A magazine aimed at the captains of the technology
industry under the same roof as a nonprofit magazine that keeps
capitalism under fire. Framed pictures are still on the floor in
chief executive David Bunnell's corner office, waiting to be hung
on the wall, and Bunnell is upbeat as he talks about Upside.
</P>
<P>
   He started out as an investor in the company _ which was founded
by Tony Perkins, now the CEO and editor-in-chief of competing
magazine Red Herring, and Rich Karlgaard, now publisher of Forbes _
and became CEO two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, circulation has ``more than tripled,'' he said, to
200,000 _ 20 percent of it paid, but 60 percent of it going to
corporate board members.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, he's expanding. ``Now we're a magazine and an online
business, and a robust conference business and a book division,''
he said. ``We're becoming a true media company. But we're not going
to change the name to Upside.com.''
</P>
<P>
   He could have a change of heart if he decides to take the
company public. ``Dot com'' is the magic phrase in the stock
market. ``We're looking at an exit strategy,'' he said with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to spend more time promoting his 70-person company,
Bunnell also elevated Gini Talmadge, who joined the company in
January, to president and publisher, overseeing sales, marketing,
circulation, finance and administration.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the impression one might have from Upside's name,
Bunnell said the magazine is anything but boosterish. The latest
cover is a good example. It's a photo of people holding picket
signs with such slogans as ``Tax the Net'' and ``Ban Internet
Welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We question why it is that the Net is tax free for three
years,'' Bunnell said. ``It seems awfully strange: We're creating
all these billionaires, and giving them tax breaks....
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't read this article in any other magazine,'' he said
proudly. ``All they do is suck up to whatever technology believes
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunnell, 49, has an impressive media pedigree. He is the founder
of PC Magazine, PC World, Macworld and New Media magazines, as well
as a biotechnology newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Mello, 43, worked with Bunnell in the early days of PC Magazine,
when its offices were spread throughout the Sunset District. He
ultimately rose to become editor-in-chief of Macworld, leaving in
1997 when that magazine went through a restructuring related to the
turmoil afflicting Apple Computer.
</P>
<P>
   He becomes the fourth editor in Upside's 10-year history,
following Perkins, Eric Nee (now with Fortune) and Brandt. He
starts work Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Brandt, who joined Upside in 1995 after 14 years with
Business Week, heads to New York next week to meet with venture
capitalists he hopes will fund his next business.
</P>
<P>
   Until it's funded, he won't say what it is _ and he's not
leaving Upside. ``I can't just quit,'' said Brandt, 43. ``I need
some income.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ZDNET ZOOMS &LR; : Shedding the muzzle of the ``quiet period,'' ZDNet
chief executive Dan Rosensweig sounded like a happy man Tuesday as
he talked about his company's earnings and the state of online
media.
</P>
<P>
   You know ZDNet: It's the San Francisco online division of
computer magazine publishing giant Ziff-Davis. Ziff sold tracking
stock in ZDNet to cash in on the Internet stock craze, and it paid
off beyond anyone's dreams: Its market value is $2.6 billion, more
than the $1.7 billion value of the parent company.
</P>
<P>
   The first public earnings report revealed that ZDNet lost
$186,000 in the three months that ended March 31, but its revenues
nearly doubled since last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Rosensweig also noted ZDNet's increasing traffic numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ZDNet puts up content from Ziff magazines, but it also employs
300 people _ half in San Francisco _ creating original content.
It's become a formidable competitor for Cnet, the San Francisco
online media powerhouse. Cnet once ridiculed Ziff in ads showing a
bulked-up bodybuilder with skinny legs; the ads said the upper body
was Ziff-Davis in print, and the scrawny lower body was Ziff-Davis
online.
</P>
<P>
   Representing Ziff online, Rosensweig says: ``That's my upper
body in the picture.'' Having bulked up, ZDNet will keep growing.
</P>
<P>
   One factor that will help foster that growth is ZDNet's stock,
which Rosensweig said ``creates a currency for all the reasons we'd
need a currency, from employee retention to potential
acquisitions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; PRIZE SURPRISE: &LR;  Right up there with Tina Brown, David Remnick,
Martha Stewart and other magazine luminaries at New York's
Waldorf-Astoria yesterday were Paul Somerson and Greg Mason, editor
and publisher of San Francisco's PC Computing magazine, hauling off
a prestigious National Magazine Award.
</P>
<P>
   They beat out a diverse group _ Saveur, Conde Nast's Women's
Sports and Fitness, and Field and Stream _ with a package from last
November, ``Undocumented Internet Secrets,'' giving the Ziff-Davis
magazine's 1 million subscribers tips on searching the Net without
headaches.
</P>
<P>
   The award ``says San Francisco is a real publishing hub,''
Somerson said. ``And computer magazines have come up into the
mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   In a different, regional contest, Bay Area &UR;  &LR; technology and
business pubs brought home a lot more hardware. The Western
Publications Association bestowed the Maggie Awards to Upside (two
awards), Business 2.0 (not only best new mag, and not only best
special interest mag, but best consumer mag), Macworld in print and
online, Publish, New Media, InfoWorld and PC World.
</P>
<P>
   Shed a tear for the Industry Standard, which celebrated its
first birthday with four Maggie nominations, but didn't win any.
</P>
<P>
