<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Increasing Storage Capacity
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By David Einstein &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I'd like to add a second hard drive to increase the
storage capacity of my PC (my original drive holds 2 gigabytes, and
I'm looking at adding one that holds 10 gigs). Is this something I
can do myself, and if so, how hard is it?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  It's actually pretty simple. Your PC case should have
a space called a bay inside it for an extra hard drive. But you
should open the case and make sure that's the case (is that
clear?). Anyway, here's how to install the new hard drive:
</P>
<P>
   _Set the switch on the back of the drive to the ``slave''
position. Also, make sure that your original drive is set to the
``master'' position. That way, the computer will boot using the
original drive, which contains your operating system.
</P>
<P>
   _Slide the new drive into the empty bay and secure it with
screws on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   _Your original drive is connected to the motherboard with a flat
ribbon cable. In the middle of the cable there should be a black
connector that's not being used for anything. Connect it to the
back of your new hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   _Connect the drive to one of the free plugs that extend out of
the computer's power supply.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. Now close the case, fire up the computer and follow
the instructions that came with your new drive to format it and get
it ready.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging E-Mail
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I get an acknowledgment when someone gets the e-mail
I've sent them? I'm sure I figured out how to do it once, but I
can't seem to find my way there again.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Both Microsoft Outlook and Netscape Communicator let you
request receipts for when mail is received, and when it's read.
</P>
<P>
   To request receipts for all messages that you send in Outlook
98, choose Options from the Tools menu, then tab to Preferences and
click E-Mail Options. In the dialog box that appears, click
Tracking Options, then select ``Tell me when all messages have been
delivered'' and/or ``Tell me when all messages have been read.''
</P>
<P>
   You can also track an individual message. Open a new e-mail
message window and click Options on the toolbar. In the Voting and
Tracking Options area, check the boxes for the receipt options you
want.
</P>
<P>
   To request receipts for all messages, open your Inbox, then
choose Preferences from the Edit menu. In the Preferences dialog
box, go to the Mail &AMP; Newsgroups category on the left and choose
Return Receipts. Then choose your receipt preferences.
</P>
<P>
   To track an individual Netscape message, open a new message
window, click Options on the toolbar and check the box for Return
Receipt. There doesn't seem to be an option for finding out if an
individual message has been read as well as received.
</P>
<P>
   Banish Your Buddies
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm 79 and very much a neophyte as far as computers are
concerned. I use America Online as my ISP and whenever I access, it
I get a ``Buddies Online'' window in the top right-hand corner. I
couldn't care less about it and need to deluun it. Help!
</P>
<P>
   A: Irritating, isn't it? But fear not, you can banish your
buddies with a few quick mouse strokes. Just click the Setup icon
in the Buddies Online window, then click Buddy List Preferences.
Now remove the check (by clicking it) from the box labeled ``Show
my my Buddy List(s) immediately after I sign onto AOL.`` Next time
you sign on, the buddy window will be gone. You're welcome.
</P>
<P>
   So Sorry
</P>
<P>
   Q: Three years ago, I bought a Macintosh clone _ a Power
Computing PowerCurve 601/120. Loved it. But now the motherboard has
burned out. Can I buy a replacement motherboard now that Power
Computing no longer exists? Or am I just stuck?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: You're just stuck. The motherboard for your machine is no
longer being made, and an Apple expert tells me that there probably
isn't a current board that would be compatible with your system.
Best bet: Get yourself a new tangerine-color iMac.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  If you download a lot of programs, why not create a folder on
your desktop to hold them all. That way, you won't have lots of
icons cluttering up the desktop, and you'll always know where your
programs are. To create a new folder, right click on any unused
area of the desktop, point to New and choose Folder from the list
of options. Immediately type a name for the folder, then hit Enter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to  &LR; computers(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;
</P>
