u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-N     04-28 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT QUESTIONS DELAY IN NETSCAPE-AOL DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A lawyer for Microsoft Corp. tried Wednesday to
show that Netscape Communications Corp. and America Online delayed
the announcement of their merger for several weeks last fall,
apparently because they feared that earlier disclosure of it might
hurt the government's antitrust case against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to suggest a plot between the two companies and
the government to keep their intentions from Microsoft's legal
team, the lawyer, Michael Lacovara, questioned Peter Currie, a
senior vice president for Netscape, for more than two hours. The
deposition was the first of several that will be taken to prepare
rebuttal arguments for the trial, which is in recess.
</P>
<P>
   All but about 10 minutes of the deposition was taken in public,
as the result of a suit filed by 13 news organizations, including
The New York Times, under a 1913 law intended to make antitrust
cases subject to public scrutiny. During the final few minutes of
the deposition, the lawyers discussed what they described as
confidential business information, and the public was asked to
leave the room.
</P>
<P>
   But during the public portion, a small gathering of reporters
and other onlookers at a Washington hotel watched as Currie, in
response to questions from Lacovara, said discussions of the deal
between the two companies were quite active last August and
September, ``but then they went into hiatus for weeks and weeks _
until mid-November.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on Nov. 23, America Online announced that it was buying
Netscape for $4.2 billion, while also forming an alliance with Sun
Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   In his questions, Lacovara said nothing about why he thought the
``hiatus'' had occurred. But Microsoft is basing the major portion
of its rebuttal case on the thesis that the Netscape-America Online
deal changes the competitive landscape of the software industry,
seriously undermining the government's charge that Microsoft is a
bullying monopolist with the power to cow the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   In support of that notion, Lacovara quoted from an underwriter's
report on the proposed deal presented to the Netscape board last
fall, which called the acquisition ``an industry-defining
transaction.'' Currie scoffed at that, saying, ``it sounds like the
kind of thing they might have said.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and government lawyers both completed presenting their
principal cases at the end of February, when the antitrust trial
went into recess. It is currently expected to resume in late May,
when both sides offer three rebuttal witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   During the earlier part of the trial, in October, James
Barksdale, Netscape's former chairman, and David Colburn, a senior
America Online executive, testified for the government. This was
during the hiatus in the merger talks. At the time of their
testimony, no hint of the discussions came out in court.
Presumably, had Microsoft known of the proposed deal, the company
could have made the argument earlier that it undermined the
government's case and could have questioned executives of the two
companies about it.
</P>
<P>
   Currie said he heard no significant discussions within Netscape
last fall about how the proposed deal might affect the antitrust
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a very brief discussion _ will this have an
impact,'' he said. ``But mainly we were looking at the business
issues. There were only a very few people at Netscape worrying
about the trial. And remember, at that time we had no deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacovara also suggested that Netscape informed the Justice
Department about the proposed deal in September. On Wednesday,
David Boies, the government's lead lawyer in the case, said the
government was not informed until mid-November. But Microsoft has
subpoenaed thousands of pages of documents from Netscape, and
Lacovara said: ``I would not ask a question like that unless I had
a good faith basis for believing it is true.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the September revelation would prove even if true,
Lacovara said only, ``Let us shake the case out, and then we'll
tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   After the deposition had ended, Boies called the
Netscape-America Online issue ``a sideshow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is about what Microsoft did, despite Microsoft's
effort to change the subject to what other people did,'' he said.
``I don't think this witness was very helpful for Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   Colburn of America Online testified last October that his
company had ended its relationship with Netscape and had chosen
Microsoft's Internet Explorer as the default browser for its
service because Microsoft had promised America Online a prominent
advertisement in all copies of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft argued in court that America Online had chosen
Internet Explorer because it was technically superior; it offered
specific features that Microsoft valued that Netscape could not
match. Microsoft also argued that Netscape never did produce a
version of its browser including those features.
</P>
<P>
   But Currie said Netscape's main interaction with America Online
in September and October was Netscape's effort to persuade America
Online to adopt a new version of the Netscape browser that did
include the specific features the company wanted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
