<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7068 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEDGE-FUNDS-800&AMP;ADD-N     04-28 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGE-FUNDS-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION TO SEEK GREATER OVERSIGHT OVER INVESTMENT BANKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Worried that Wall Street will soon forget its brush with
financial meltdown six months ago, federal regulators will take
steps and seek new powers to further regulate the trading practices
of investment banks and examine the books of private investment
funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, acting on a government report, plans
to introduce legislation soon that, while not calling for direct
regulation of the investment pools for the wealthy known as hedge
funds, will give the Securities and Exchange Commission and the
Commodities Futures Trading Commission enhanced powers to examine
the dealings of Wall Street trading firms.
</P>
<P>
   They will also seek congressional backing for rules that require
hedge funds to disclose more information about their borrowing and
trading practices even if that drives some such funds out of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The long-awaited report is the product of an investigation into
Wall Street practices that began after the government-brokered
rescue of Long-Term Capital Management last September. Although it
falls short of recommending direct regulation of hedge funds, which
would have provoked strong opposition within the financial
industry, the authorities do plan to adopt fresh powers over
investment banks, which were among the biggest lenders to Long-Term
Capital. The measure would make the Wall Street houses subject to
some of the same controls that commercial banks face.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations are part of a long study on financial
borrowing prepared by the nation's top financial regulators, led by
Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin and Alan Greenspan, the chairman
of the Federal Reserve. The report was obtained by The New York
Times and is expected to be released on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Though Long-Term Capital's near collapse happened only six
months ago, it is no longer a pressing concern on Wall Street,
where companies are profiting handsomely from buoyant stock and
bond markets. Long-Term Capital was rescued by 14 Wall Street
companies, which injected $3.6 billion at the height of the crisis.
The hedge fund has since posted solid returns and generated profits
for its new owners.
</P>
<P>
   But the bailout of Long-Term Capital was orchestrated by the
Federal Reserve, the nation's central bank, and regulators said at
the time that the hedge fund's failure might have prompted a
worldwide financial crisis. Officials now argue that the lessons of
that brush with disaster would be lost unless they adopted new
measures designed to limit the risks that financial companies take.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators called the amount of money that Long-Term Capital
borrowed ``extraordinary'' and complained that many of the best
known banks and securities companies adopted ``excessively
liberal'' lending policies. But they said the problem went well
beyond Long-Term Capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The LTCM episode illustrates the need for all participants in
our financial system, not only hedge funds, to face constraints in
the amount of leverage they can assume,'' the report says. ``Some
of the same weaknesses that permitted LTCM to achieve its
extraordinary market leverage were evident in other market
participants.''
</P>
<P>
   The report uses strong language to describe the increasing
tendency of financial companies to leverage their bets on financial
markets with borrowed money. It says, for example, that leading
securities firms use even more borrowed money relative to their
capital than Long-Term Capital did. The ratios of borrowed money to
capital at the top five investment banks average 27 to 1, the
report says, a bit higher than Long-Term Capital.
</P>
<P>
   The securities companies may not be much better able to
withstand a sharp downturn in financial markets than that hedge
fund was, the report says. A collapse of a major Wall Street firm
is widely dreaded because it could have ripple effects on financial
markets everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But regulators did not propose legal limits on borrowing.
Instead, they expressed hope that public scrutiny of borrowing and
trading practices would prompt financial companies to reduce their
risk levels voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   If they do not, however, the authorities are threatening much
sterner measures. These include imposing tight capital requirements
on investment banks, not unlike those imposed on banks. The
government is also considering direct regulation of both hedge
funds and derivatives dealers, which are now largely free of
oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these steps don't work to reduce the leverage in the
system, then there are other options we can take,'' said one member
of the President's Working Group on Financial Markets, the
regulatory committee that studied the Long-Term Capital fallout.
``These would be likely to raise a great deal of noise from the
industry, and we are hoping that it will not be necessary to take
these steps.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The report mainly recommends that:
</P>
<P>
   _ Bank and securities regulators insure that financial companies
adopt better risk management practices, saying that the risk
management system ``broke down'' when companies allowed Long-Term
Capital to borrow so much money.
</P>
<P>
   _ Banks and brokerages houses provide a more detailed summary of
their lending to individual borrowers so that both regulators and
other financial companies can spot excessive risk building up.
</P>
<P>
   - Federal authorities take action to insure that other
countries, and particular popular offshore financial centers like
the Cayman Islands, toughen their regulatory policies in tandem
with the strengthened U.S. rules.
</P>
<P>
   _ Congress speed passage of updated bankruptcy laws that would
make it easier for financial companies to allow a hedge fund like
Long-Term Capital to collapse without upsetting the entire
financial system.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street executives contacted on Wednesday said they had no
read the report, and most declined to comment. But the proposals on
the whole seem unlikely to prompt a strong protest from banks and
brokerages houses. Many traditionally secretive hedge funds seem
likely to bristle at the demand for more disclosure. But they are
not viewed as a strong industry lobbying group and many already
operate from offshore bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hedge fund industry will object to disclosing more than
they do now. They won't like it,'' said Roy Smith, a professor of
finance at New York University. ``But it's a nuisance they brought
on themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the requirements on banks and brokerage firms, Smith said
they sounded moderate. He reflected the views of many in the
financial industry who argue that the Fed may have overreacted to
the Long-Term Capital crisis and that no radical changes are needed
in the way they do business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not appear to be a major overhaul in the way things
work now,'' he said. ``That's a wise conclusion for the committee
to reach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
