<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BB&AMP;T to buy First Liberty
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shares of First Liberty Financial Corp. jumped 34
percent and reached a 52-week high Wednesday on news that the
Macon-based bank holding company is being acquired for $500 million
by BB&AMP;T Corp., a bank holding company based in Winston-Salem, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   First Liberty closed Wednesday at $31.06 1/4, up $7.81 1/4,
after hitting a 52-week high of $32.25. BB&AMP;T shares closed at $39,
down 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The Macon bank has $1.7 billion in assets and 39 branches in
South and Central Georgia. Its net income has nearly doubled since
1995. During the 1990s, it has made several acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   BB&AMP;T has a 580-bank network in North Carolina, South Carolina,
Virginia, Maryland and the District of Columbia. The company was
founded in 1872.
</P>
<P>
   Its stock price has been on an upswing since 1992. It is now the
fourth-largest bank based in North Carolina and is doing business
in fields such as accounts receivable, insurance, venture capital
and investment banking, spokesman Robert Denham said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great deal for First Liberty shareholders,'' said
John Pandtle, bank analyst at Robinson-Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will involve a stock swap. A First Liberty stockholder
will receive BB&AMP;T shares based on an exchange ratio tied to BB&AMP;T's
stock price at some point before closing. Shareholders of the Macon
bank can expect to receive about 0.85 shares of BB&AMP;T stock for each
First Liberty share they hold. Closing is expected to be in the
fourth quarter, said Richard A. Hills Jr., First Liberty's general
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hatcher, First Liberty's chief executive, will be
president of BB&AMP;T's Georgia operations.
</P>
<P>
   Pandtle and other analysts expect those to continue to grow.
BB&AMP;T's assets were $37.8 billion at the end of March. In January,
it agreed to buy First Citizens Corp. of Newnan for $126 million in
stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they are doing in Georgia is consistent with how they
have built a sizable franchise elsewhere in the Southeast,'' said
Pandtle. ``And there are plenty of opportunities for them to build
a franchise here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
