</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magazine sees return of old-line stocks
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The bull on Wall Street has long since reached the
status of senior citizen, but it still shows no signs of retiring.
If anything, says Business Week (May 3), the stock market might get
a shot of adrenaline, thanks to the shift of investor interest
toward old-line, blue chip industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next phase, we may see what you might call the wiser
bull _ a market that provides a more comprehensive view of the
economy's overall potential, and not just the extraordinary
expectations for a few leaders,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, Business Week sees the market's leading
stocks shifting from companies such as America Online, IBM,
Microsoft and Sun Microsystems to Alcoa, Caterpillar, International
Paper and Ingersoll-Rand.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean investor interest will wane for the recently
highflying Internet and other high-tech stocks. ``Technology still
has the greatest profit promise, well ahead of other industries,''
says the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But the new buying pattern will broaden the market's base, even
including the stocks of smaller companies at some point.
</P>
<P>
   In the same edition, Business Week makes a case that the Federal
Reserve under Chairman Alan Greenspan is shifting its focus from
inflation _ which is under control _ to productivity in domestic
policy, and a more global view of finance outside the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Little guys get a chance
</P>
<P>
   Everybody yearns to get in on the ground floor of a hot new
stock when a company goes public with an initial public offering.
But individual investors rarely get a chance to do this because the
brokerages that underwrite stock offerings hog the initial shares
for themselves and friends _ especially if it is a hot prospect.
</P>
<P>
   But Individual Investor (May) reports that a Silicon Valley
investment banker, William R. Hambrecht, is trying to level the IPO
playing field by offering on the Web the shares of the IPOs his
company underwrites.
</P>
<P>
   In breaking from the ranks of most Wall Street firms, Hambrecht
has been branded as ``a traitor.'' Others suggest that only
desperate companies will do business with his company, W.R.
Hambrecht &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Nobel laureate Milton Friedman pontificates on his inflation
theories in a challenging Forbes (May 3) interview. Calling
inflation the century's dominant economic problem, he says Asia's
recovery may cause more problems for the United States than the
recessions that Asian nations have suffered.
</P>
<P>
   _ Investors looking for stocks worth buying should keep an eye
on companies that buy back their own shares, Kiplinger's Personal
Finance Magazine (May) suggests. It's not a sure-fire signal of
undervalued stocks. But one research project showed that stocks of
companies that buy their own shares rose an average of 12 points in
the year after a buyback.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
