</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HOMEDEPOT29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot fans meet chairman at book signing
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bernie Marcus is likely nursing a sore right hand
today.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman and co-founder of Home Depot spent several hours on
Wednesday signing his new tell-all book at a Chapter 11 bookstore.
About 200 people lined up at 7:30 a.m. to get autographed copies of
``Built from Scratch,'' a gritty look back into the making of the
$30 billion company. Written with co-founder and Chief Executive
Arthur Blank, the book tells the tale of two ``regular guys'' who
built a retail empire with scrappy determination.
</P>
<P>
   The book was written for Home Depot employees, Marcus said.
``Every time I visit a store, they want to know how we did it,''
Marcus said during a break. ``Once we started putting the book
together, the memories just poured out.''
</P>
<P>
   Several anecdotes are particularly notable, such as how Ross
Perot came close to being the majority owner of Home Depot during a
desperate search for financing. And then there's the one about the
banker who risked his career to give the company a $3.5 million
loan it needed to survive. In all, it's 300 pages of Home Depot
machismo, sprinkled with profanity and wild drinking parties.
</P>
<P>
   About 700 copies of the book sold Wednesday, said Chapter 11
President Barbara Babbit Kaufman. Home Depot stores are also
carrying the book, which sells for $24.95. Royalties will be
donated to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those at the book signing were Home Depot employees or
other business people. Customers and shareholders also showed up to
rub elbows with Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spend a lot of time in the stores, so I just wanted to meet
Bernie,'' said Jim Cooke, who owns a real estate investment
company. ``I asked him when the stock would split, but he wouldn't
tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Williamson had an additional motive. ``I want to get a
job with the company,'' said Williamson, who was sharply dressed in
an olive-colored suit.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson arrived at 7:45 a.m., planning to chat with Marcus
until he saw the throng. ``I could've have been here at 7 o'clock,
but I didn't want to pounce on the man.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
