</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring plans campaign to increase brand awareness
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta-based MindSpring Enterprises plans to add more
content to its Web site (www.mindspring.net) and increase its
advertising and marketing spending to boost national brand
awareness.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call Wednesday morning, MindSpring Chairman and
Chief Executive Officer Charles Brewer told Wall Street analysts
the company would either make the investment itself or seek
partnerships with media companies so it can leverage its portal
presence and turn it into a money-maker. MindSpring has 1.2 million
subscribers, which is a lot of potential eyeballs logging onto its
home page.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer said the company's growth meant that there were ``a lot
of things we can do on the portal side.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can create a much more in-depth portal. ... It's certainly
worthy of more effort from our company.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Operating Officer Michael McQuary also said the company
would be ramping up its advertising and marketing efforts,
including a foray into television advertising at year's end.
</P>
<P>
   However, Brewer still won't comment on plans for the $430
million raised in a recent stock offering. Weeks ago, Brewer told a
group of investors at the Robinson-Humphrey conference he would be
interested in acquiring the Microsoft Network of dial-up
subscribers. Brewer also declined to get into specifics about the
proposed MediaOne/AT&AMP;T acquisition. He restated his position on the
cable industry's need to open lines to competition if it plans to
offer other services, including cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cable industry is trying to have us believe that because
they developed a cable service in the past, the rules don't apply
to them. The law says that if you want to provide other services,
the rules do apply.''
</P>
<P>
   While Brewer dismissed any notion that MindSpring might be
carried on MediaOne, McQuary did say the company was talking with a
number of small cable operators about providing MindSpring service
over their wires. He didn't name any.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer also urged analysts to ``stay the course'' with 1999
earnings estimates. First Call estimates for fiscal 1999 are for a
profit of 88 cents a share, including quarterly earnings of 20
cents, 25 cents and 29 cents a share for the second, third and
fourth quarters, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
