<SLUG> BC-CANADA-SHOOTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO STUDENTS SHOT BY TRENCHCOAT WEARER, 14 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ In a school gun assault with eerie parallels with
last week's murders in Colorado, a 14-year-old student Wednesday
shot two older boys in the hallway of an Alberta high school,
killing one and critically wounding the other.
</P>
<P>
   The ninth grader, who reportedly wore a blue trenchcoat, was
arrested by Royal Canadian Mounted Police. There was no clear
motive for the violence except that the assailant was widely
regarded as ``depressed'' and ``unpopular,'' and had reportedly
been regularly taunted by his peers.
</P>
<P>
   Both of his victims were in the 11th grade, and reportedly were
only vaguely acquainted with the younger boy.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians, who often consider themselves immune from the gun
violence plaguing their southern neighbor, were stunned by the
incident at C. W. Myers High School in the small farming community
of Taber, about 50 miles north of the border with Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 14-year-old male has shot two 17-year-old males at the
school,'' said Cpl. James Johnston of the Royal Canadian Mounted
Police. ``A suspect was taken into custody at the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Police refused to divulge the names of either the victims or the
suspect. Fellow students described the shooter as a loner who had
few friends and had recently stopped attending classes at W. R.
Myers, which has only 440 students. He was reportedly in a home
instruction program for troubled students.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a crisis and a catastrophe that no one could even have
imagined occurring in small town Canada,'' said Sharon Holtman, a
member of the school board in the community of 8,000. ``It's like a
bad dream. Only we can't wake up.''
</P>
<P>
   The shooter reportedly offered no resistence when he was taken
into custody by an off-duty police officer working at the school.
The shootings occurred after he entereed the school at lunch hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked out of the classroom, I saw his gun right
there,'' Regan Valgardson, a 11th grade student, told CTV News. ``I
asked the guy what he was doing. He told me to get lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Canadian news reports said the boy wore a blue trenchcoat. It
was unclear whether his gun was a rifle or handgun, or whether he
intentionally singled out the two victims or whether they were shot
at random.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the regional hospital in nearby Lethbridge,
Alberta, said that the second shooting victim was still in surgery
Wednesday night. The first victim was pronounced dead at a smaller
medical facility in Taber.
</P>
<P>
   The Taber shootings occurred eight days after two students
killed 12 classmates and a teacher before turning their guns on
themselves in Littleton, Colordao. The horrific incident was widely
covered in Canada, although many Canadians seemed to view it as
less of a storm warning for their own schools than an indictment of
the United States, whre violent crime is far more prevalent than in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not immune to something like this,'' said Toronto
lawyer Eric Roher, an authority on teen crime. ``Violence also
afflicts our society.''
</P>
<P>
   The shooting at the Alberta high school occurred in the early
afternoon, Rocky Mountain time, according to Canadian news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the two students were shot, the principal of the
school ordered all students to report to the auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   There were conflicting reports on the chronology of events.
According to one student, the armed ninth grader first held a gun
to the head of a feamale teacher, screaming ``this is not a joke,''
before stalking into the hallway and shooting the two older
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrifying, all this week all we'd been talking about is
what happened in Littleton,'' said student Valgardson. ``None of us
could imagine such a thing coming to our little town.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
