<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7079 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SHO-ADVANCE-HNS &LR;      04-28 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SHO-ADVANCE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
THE WOODLANDS _ In the car business, if you sell Cadillacs, you
don't put a Mercedes-Benz logo on the hood ornament. If you deal in
Jaguars, you don't borrow engine parts from Lexus.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In golf, it's supposed to be the same way. If your course is
lined with trees and filled with forced carries over water and
sand, common sense dictates that the greens be somewhat more spongy
and receptive to approach shots than the nearest freeway overpass.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't always been the case this year on the PGA Tour. Too
often, the world's best golfers have been subjected to U.S.
Open-like conditions. Too often, well-played shots have ended up in
bad shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we tell the PGA Tour,'' Payne Stewart said Wednesday,
``is that we'd like to have the courses set up tough, but fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are places this year that they have lost the `fair'
part of that scenario. Some places have been growing rough so high
that it's like we're playing the U.S. Open every week. I don't
think fans get a lot out of that. And it starts testing our
patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting today, the $2.5 million Shell Houston Open will curb
the frustration and offer a return to normalcy.
</P>
<P>
   They call this tournament the SHO. It may also be a SHO-case for
the skills of golf's best before the week is done.
</P>
<P>
   With manageable rough and a little help from Mother Nature, the
Tournament Players Course at The Woodlands should provide the
perfect stage for low scoring this week. Monday's rain softened up
the course and made the greens like dartboards.
</P>
<P>
   If the warm, dry weather of the past two days continues, the
course will dry out and the proverbial ``ideal scoring conditions''
should rule.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a delight to the playing field, if that's the case.
Golfers are no different than other athletes.
</P>
<P>
   They want the chance to make good shots and have those shots
rewarded. They don't like seeing a sand wedge shot take two big
bounces and then roll off the back of the green when the same shot
on the same green last year backed up eight feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it, when somebody runs a 100-yard race in
nine seconds, they don't say that it's too fast and now everybody
has to run 103-yard races,'' said Peter Jacobsen. ``But they try to
do that in golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody shoots a low score, everybody worries that
conditions are too easy. But usually, it's only one guy who shoots
that score. It doesn't mean you have to start doing things to the
course or start putting pins on the collar of the green next to a
bunker.''
</P>
<P>
   The TPC at The Woodlands has been blessed with a layout that has
played tough without an abundance of trickery. And with the rough a
couple inches shorter than last year, the birdies should start
flying today and the scores ought to be lower than the 72-hole
total of 12-under 276 that has won the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said, ``By the start of the week, we usually know what
the scores are going to be like. At The Players, I knew even-par
was going to be a good score for the week.''
</P>
<P>
   And this week?
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see scores well in the red,'' Stewart said. ``This
course is in very good shape, and the greens are so good. The rough
is penal, but it isn't too high. You have to think your way out of
it. But the scores will be lower.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is a good thing compared to the hardship the players have
faced at some courses this year. The Phoenix Open, Bay Hill and The
Players Championship all featured rock-hard greens.
</P>
<P>
   Fans who thrill at approach shots that suck up close to the hole
have all too often been left disappointed when even short-iron
shots bounded hard off the putting surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sport has a wonderful identity with the fans, but if we
continue to be tested with hard, fast greens surrounded by
five-inch rough, we will lose our patience,'' Stewart said. ``We
will lose our professionalism as athletes, and fans are not going
to want to see that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a steady diet of that gets real old in a hurry. I
think fans would rather see us making birdies than us chopping out
shots from thick rough around the green and making bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take The Players Championship (last month). David Duval was
leading the tournament and shot 2-over-par over the last two rounds
and still won. I don't think fans want to see that every week. They
want to see some shots that show how good players out here really
are. You want to get those `oohs' that come with great
shot-making.''
</P>
<P>
   As Jacobsen said: ``The silliest thing is when they've got four
or five inches of rough around the greens. When you see that, you
might as well take Seve Ballesteros and Tom Watson and guys like
that out of the record books. Part of the reason they were so great
is they were so good with their games around the green.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, there will be no such problems around the green. What
is uncertain is whom the conditions will favor.
</P>
<P>
   Duval enters as the pre-tournament favorite, as he does in every
event he plays. But with birdie opportunities throughout the
course, anybody who gets a hot putter will be a threat.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart is coming off a second-place finish at the MCI Classic
two weeks ago, when he lost in a playoff. It was the 25th runner-up
finish of his pro career to go with 10 victories. Other than Tom
Kite, no active player on the regular tour has more second-place
finishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know how other people view it,'' Stewart said
of his flair for near misses. ``But I feel like it's a sign that I
get myself into position a lot. And that's why I'm out here _ to
compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I couldn't go out there and defend Glen Day's putt (to
win on the first playoff hole at the MCI two weeks ago). I was
looking at a putt to win the tournament, then he makes his and I'm
looking at my putt now just to stay in it. There's not much you can
do about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Except come back firing again this week. And the targets should
be a little easier to hit than at some tour stops this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
