<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIP-HACKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY THAT DETECTED COMPUTER SECURITY FLAW IS UNDER FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When privacy advocates first sounded alarms in
January about a serial number that Intel Corp. had embedded in its
new Pentium III processor, the company quickly responded by
distributing software that enabled owners of Pentium III computers
to hide the number. But it now appears that the problem is not
solved and is not about to fade away.
</P>
<P>
   Recently a researcher at a small Canadian software company found
a way to make the hidden serial number hidden visible again to
prying eyes _ and without the owner's realizing it. Acting in what
it says is the public interest, the company, Zero-Knowledge Systems
of Montreal, placed a program on its Web site demonstrating the
vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Intel is responding more aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, an Intel executive called executives at
Symantec Corp., maker of the popular Norton anti-virus software,
and told them that the demonstration program was ``hostile code.''
</P>
<P>
   Symantec agreed that the program fit its definition of a type of
malicious program known as a Trojan horse, so it included the
software in its continually updated list of dangerous programs,
which include viruses, that cause warnings to pop up on its
customers' computers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, users of the Norton anti-virus software who visit the
Zero-Knowledge site get a warning that they are about to download a
virus.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, one man's virus is another's diagnostic tool.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Zero-Knowledge said they were being unfairly
portrayed as outlaws by Intel. Zero-Knowledge, which employs about
40 people, develops software that enables Web surfers to protect
their identity on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't a virus,'' said Austin Hill, president
Zero-Knowledge. ``It was simply a demonstration of a software
flaw.''
</P>
<P>
   He also disputed Intel's assertion that the demonstration
program, which locks up a computer and forces the user to reboot,
was destructive software. And unlike typical authors of virus
software, the company clearly identified itself with a digital
signature embedded in the program, a type of Windows-specific
software known as an Active-X control.
</P>
<P>
   The serial number is a volatile issue for Intel. The
introduction of the feature, which Intel said was designed to
increase computer security, touched off a boycott against the
company by some privacy groups, which not only insisted that the
serial number would fail to protect security but warned that it
enabled direct marketers, data-mining companies and others to track
the paths of Web surfers more easily.
</P>
<P>
   After the controversy erupted earlier this year, Intel, which
makes about 85 percent of the world's microprocessors, the nerve
center of personal computers, responded by saying that it would
work with computer makers to insure that the serial number was
switched off by default when personal computers were shipped to
stores or customers. A computer user could then turn the number on
if it was needed for a particular application.
</P>
<P>
   Intel executive vice president Paul Otellini said corporate
customers were demanding the feature, but that the company was
still evaluating the consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   The software that secretly turns on the Intel serial number was
demonstrated by Ian Goldberg, chief scientist at Zero-Knowledge.
Goldberg, a graduate student in computer science at the University
of California at Berkeley, is a member of an advocacy group of
computer security researchers who assert that network security is
enhanced by publicly demonstrating the shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg says it is virtually impossible to permanently switch
off Intel's serial number. Zero-Knowledge's software turns it back
on by inserting a command in the computer's basic input/output
system, or BIOS, chip. The BIOS hold a computer's most basic
instructions, the ones that tell it to look for disk drives and an
operating system, for example, when the computer is turned on.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to switching the serial number on, the software
recalculates a protection feature known as a checksum, making it
extremely difficult to detect the tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Intel spokesman Mike Sullivan acknowledged that there was no
perfect way to keep the number hidden, he but insisted that the
company was acting prudently to work with the industry to build
stronger defenses against tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has been discussing the vulnerability with Zero-Knowledge,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Sullivan, the Intel executive who called Symantec, said he
did so because the Zero-Knowledge program left a copy of the serial
number from the user's processor on the company's Web site and
because it caused the user's computer to crash.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Intel had worked with Symantec before to combat
viruses and had engaged Zero-Knowledge in a discussion about the
problem almost immediately after notifying Symantec.
</P>
<P>
   Symantec executives said they were standing by their
determination that the Zero-Knowledge demonstration was a dangerous
program because it made the user's computer crash.
</P>
<P>
   And though Zero-Knowledge warns users that their machines will
freeze up, Enrique Salem, vice president for Symantec's security
business, said: ``If someone has work that hasn't been saved, it
will be lost as a result of running the demonstration. I really
want to make sure that we do things to protect our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Zero-Knowledge digitally signed the program, he
said, did not protect users from potential abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Zero-Knowledge said its brand had been damaged unfairly by
Symantec's characterizing the demonstration as a virus.
</P>
<P>
   One annoyed user sent an e-mail to Zero-Knowledge saying: ``My
Norton AV detected a trojan virus when I clicked on the breaking
news link. If you can't even manage your own site, there's no way
I'm going to do business with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the anger its demonstration has engendered,
Zero-Knowledge insists that the bottom line is that Intel chose the
wrong way to protect user security.
</P>
<P>
   ``A serial number is a bad way to protect someone,'' Hill said.
``It can be stolen or it can be spoofed, and it links
authentication to a computer and not a person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
