<SLUG> BC-FILM-NAVYYARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE NIRO AND MIRAMAX PLAN A FILM STUDIO FOR THE BROOKLYN NAVY YARD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.J.)  (rk) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Actor Robert De Niro and Miramax Films plan to
announce a tentative deal with city officials to build a $150
million Hollywood-style film studio at the Brooklyn Navy Yard, the
sprawling complex where tens of thousands of workers once built and
launched warships and tankers.
</P>
<P>
   According to executives on both sides of the negotiations, the
proposed movie studio would include 12 sound stages in three
buildings on a 15-acre site within the Navy Yard and would employ
thousands of people. It would be used by De Niro's TriBeCa
Productions, Miramax Films and other companies in the industry,
which have overrun New York in recent years, spending $2.6 billion
last year alone on crews, equipment, supplies and services.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the $150 million plan faces major obstacles, particularly
regarding its financing and questions about the long-term viability
of such a venture. The project's backers are investing $35 million;
they have already raised an additional $35 million from city
government sources, and will need another $80 million in financing,
people involved in the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the growth of film and television production in New
York, the plan to develop the Navy Yard into film studios has had a
tortured history ever since it was first suggested last June. But
De Niro, Harvey Weinstein, co-chairman of Miramax, and another
partner in the venture, Steven Roth, chairman of Vornado Realty
Trust, are expected to take an important step at the Navy Yard
Monday by signing a nonbinding letter of intent to go ahead with
the project.
</P>
<P>
   Even as recently as last week, the negotiations nearly unraveled
over a rent dispute between officials at the Navy Yard and the
studio group. After frantic meetings over the weekend, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani met with De Niro and Weinstein on Monday at Gracie
Mansion and put the deal back on track. The meetings were first
reported Wednesday in The New York Observer.
</P>
<P>
   The studio group, which is led by De Niro, has been hampered by
insufficient financing. A week ago, however, Union Labor Life
Insurance Co., a union-supported pension fund that has invested in
New York real estate projects, notified the group and the city that
it is considering whether to finance or invest in the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking a hard look at it,'' said Michael Steed, senior
vice president for investments at Union Life in Washington. ``It's
clear that New York doesn't have enough studios to handle both the
television and film production that could take place there. What's
unclear to us is exactly what types of studios should be there _
film or television _ and where they should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the tentative deal, the city would provide a
$25 million, low-interest loan and the city's Brooklyn Navy Yard
Development Corp., which oversees the industrial park there, would
contribute up to $10 million in cash. The rent would rise from
almost nothing to market rates over the term of a 50-year lease.
</P>
<P>
   Another recent participant in the talks has been the Fisher real
estate family, a major Manhattan landlord. The Fishers would
oversee construction and, possibly, become a partner in the
project.
</P>
<P>
   A deal would not only rejuvenate an area that was long a main
source of the city's economic muscle, but would also provide growth
space for the city's booming film industry. The number of feature
films shot in New York City soared to 221 last year, up from 69 in
1993. During the same period, the number of television production
shooting days jumped to 7,680, from 3,598. But most of the
post-production work is done elsewhere and many companies prefer to
shoot interior shots in Toronto or Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of small sound stages in New York already,
including Chelsea Piers, home to ``Law and Order'' and ``Spin
City,'' and Kaufman Astoria Studios in Queens, where ``Sesame
Street'' and the ``Cosby Show'' are recorded. But a number of
proposed projects have had difficulty finding financial support
because the stages, which require a large investment, are generally
at the mercy of filmmakers who do not want to pay a lot of money
for short periods of work.
</P>
<P>
   Union Life had planned to finance Hudson River Studios, a
proposed $120 television sound stage atop the St. John's Center, at
Houston and West Streets on the West Side of Manhattan. But when
the developer ran into delays in acquiring additional financing,
Union Life withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Shooting Gallery, an independent film production
company, announced plans to build a $75 million movie lot in the
metropolitan area in Harrison, N.J. In the end, the company scaled
back its plans for 15 sound stages and opened a $5 million
production center in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very tough, very fluid business that's hard to keep
going,'' said Hal G. Rosenbluth, president of Kaufman Astoria
Studios. ``If Harry and Bob can fill the studio with their own work
then they're way ahead of the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
