u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-HARTFORD-BOS     04-28 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-HARTFORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT TURNABOUT WOULD BE A WORLD RECORD, ROWLAND SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ This buttoned-down capital, long a
minor-league way station &UR;  &LR; between Boston and New York, is counting
on elemental economics to preserve its ticket to the big leagues:
Bob Kraft knows a sweet deal when he sees one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Kraft does (leave) it'll go down in the Guinness Book of
World Records as one of the more interesting turnabouts,'' Governor
John Rowland said in an interview with the Globe Wednesday. ``Why
would someone walk away from a $374 million publicly financed deal
to go build your own facility on your own dime?''
</P>
<P>
   As officials in Boston celebrated an 11th-hour, $70 million deal
designed to stop Kraft and the New England Patriots from moving to
a riverfront site here, the architects of one of the nation's most
generous publicly financed stadium deals pronounced Massachusetts'
efforts stingy by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium boosters, including state government leaders and many
business executives, insist Kraft will stick with the deal he
hammered out in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a signed agreement with Kraft,'' Thomas Ritter, the
former Democratic speaker of Connecticut's House of Representatives
and a staunch stadium supporter, said. ``I don't care how many
meetings there are in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   The news of a deal in Boston lit up the lines on the city's
talk-show circuit and prompted Rowland to emerge from his office,
greeting reporters with buckets of rhetorical cold water. Logic and
reason, he said, lean toward Hartford, not Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no butterflies in my stomach,'' the Republican governor
said later in a shirtsleeve interview in his capitol office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two or three discussions among some political leaders do not
make for a very sophisticated proposal to accommodate an NFL
franchise and all the things that go into it,'' Rowland said. ``We
have thousands and thousands of hours invested in this. We have
millions and millions of dollars invested in this. And we're
actually working with the owner.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said he last spoke with Kraft about a week ago, and the
team owner told him his commitment to Hartford is absolute.
Hartford has already spent over $2 million on the stadium
initiative, including paying for soil tests for architectural
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's he going back to?'' Rowland asked. ``It's not an
emotional issue. It's a financial issue. He's got to be able to
afford his team. I mean the bottom line is that to be able to
afford NFL franchises these days, and pay the players what you have
to and all the rest, yes, you do need a good media market. But you
also have to have the revenues to support it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is those revenues that enraged some Connecticut conservatives
who argued that Rowland and other stadium supporters were duped by
Kraft, blinded by the glitter that accompanies modern major-league
sports. The deal Rowland signed with Kraft not only calls for
taxpayers to foot the bill for stadium construction, it also
promises the owner revenues from luxury box seats, concessions, and
parking, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Connecticut plan Wednesday rooted for a Kraft
double-reverse that would land him back in Foxborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal was a bad deal to begin with and, frankly, I hope
they stay in Boston because of the cost to the state. It's too much
for the taxpayers to bear.'' said State Senator Edith G. Prague, a
Democrat from Columbia who had opposed the deal. ``Now the NFL is
saying that they may contribute to the cost of the stadium in
Massachusetts, and they're not contributing a dime here. Let them
stay in Foxborough. I will shed no tears and neither will the
taxpayers who are praying that this deal falls apart. We simply
cannot afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   Radio talk-show host Tom Scott of New Haven said the
negotiations in Boston confirmed his suspicions Kraft was just
using Connecticut to get the best deal in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Kraft should be careful not to let the door to the state
border hit him in the backside on his way out of Connecticut,''
said Scott, a former Republican state senator. ``His arrogance and
contempt for the taxpayers of Connecticut is something that hasn't
been seen around here in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   For Patriot fans, like 39-year-old John X. Smith, the Boston
deal would bring frustration after the enormous excitement the
advent of the Patriots had stirred up here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kraft is going to stick it to Hartford. I really do,''
Smith said Wednesday in a downtown park. ``I think he's going to
stay put. And I was really looking forward to watching the games
here until this last-minute deal came up.''
</P>
<P>
   But most fans were more sanguine. Money, they said, talks. And
if there's anything that a businessman like Kraft understands, it's
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a real sweet deal here,'' said Wesley Stewart, 64, a
retiree who lives near the stadium site. ``I think he's going to
come. I don't think that Boston can top that deal that he has. No
way. Kraft is a wheeler-dealer and he wheeled and dealed this deal.
The state will be dishing out a lot of money for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
