<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7084 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-NYT     04-28 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE BARS GROUND TROOPS IN KOSOVO WITHOUT CONGRESSIONAL OK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mb) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a heated and sometimes anguished debate, the
House voted On Wednesday to bar President Clinton from sending
ground troops to Yugoslavia without congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed 249-180 as lawmakers weighed how to respond to a
policy in the Balkans that many called flawed and others defended
as a just cause. Forty-five Democrats and one independent joined
203 Republicans to support the bill. Sixteen Republicans and 164
Democrats opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   In an an even stronger sign of the sharp division over Kosovo,
on Wednesday evening the House defeated in a 213-213 tie a
Democratic resolution supporting the president's policy of NATO air
strikes. In this case, 31 Republicans broke with the majority of
their party to support the air campaign, and 26 Democrats voted
against it.
</P>
<P>
   The all-day session marked the first formal congressional debate
since NATO began its bombing campaign on March 24 in an effort to
drive the forces of Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic out of
Kosovo. The Senate had voted on March 23 to approve the air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois said after the vote on ground
forces, ``I would hope that the president would take this diverse
debate as a signal that he should better explain the goals, the
costs and the long-term strategy of why we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, the two party leaders were working behind the
scenes to see if they could draft bipartisan compromise language on
Kosovo looking toward a vote as early as Friday. Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., who was a prisoner of war during the Vietnam conflict and
is now seeking his party's presidential nomination, has introduced
his own resolution authorizing Clinton to use ''all necessary
force'' to win in the Balkans, but Sen. Trent Lott, the majority
leader, has objected to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting with lawmakers at the White House on Wednesday,
President Clinton once again said he had no plans for ground troops
and vowed that he would seek congressional ``support'' if he
changed that stance. But he would not seek congressional approval,
his spokesman Joe Lockhart said, arguing that such a step would
raise a host of constitutional questions. While Lockhart stopped
short of a veto threat, Democrats in the House said the president
would veto any measure requiring such approval of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the long day of debate, some House members invoked
the quagmire of Vietnam to call for America to withdraw from the
Balkans. Others drew comparisons with World War II and the
Holocaust to argue for the air campaign to go on. And Rep. Gene
Taylor, D-Miss., urged the rare step of a full declaration of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that in voting for war I will share the responsibility
for those young Americans who may die,'' Taylor said. ``But to do
anything else is much worse. The best course of action for this
nation is to use the overwhelming military might we have at our
disposal to end this war swiftly and quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House had tried in the past to discourage such open
debate in Congress about the Kosovo conflict in the hopes of
sending a united message to Yugoslavia and to present a unified
voice of support for the troops. Until now, the Republican
leadership had also shied away from such a debate, with some senior
Republicans calculating that their party would be best served by
distancing itself from the conflict and letting President Clinton
take any blame for involvement in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Defense Secretary
William Cohen argued in a letter to Hastert that a prohibition on
ground troops ``could be misinterpreted as a U.S. retrenchment''
from its solidarity with NATO, and would impede the president in
his role as commander in chief. But the Administration's effort to
influence the House vote was low key and the White House was not
demanding party-line support.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's debates were forced by Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif.,
who used his prerogatives under the Vietnam-era War Powers
resolution to force votes on what he has called an unconstitutional
war, undeclared by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes we're at war,'' said Campbell, who is a law professor.
We're on the verge of ground troops. The framers were quite clear
that war was too important to be decided by one individual. Ground
troops are very seriously being considered. Therefore we must
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Working its way through an array of proposals, the House
overwhelmingly rejected the measure to issue a formal declaration
of war against Yugoslavia by a vote of 2-427. The House also
declined, by a vote of 139-290, to call for an immediate withdrawal
of all American forces from the region.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans poured out their reservations about a conflict
they said had ill-defined goals and was not in the nation's vital
interest. ``Was it worth it to stay in Vietnam to save face?''
asked Rep. Tom DeLay, the majority whip. Sharply criticizing the
NATO bombing campaign, DeLay said, ``What good has been
accomplished so far? Absolutely nothing. What long term goal will
be accomplished by having our troops there? None unless you're
willing to occupy all of Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich, of Ohio and another of the many Republicans
seeking his party's presidential nomination, said, ``The fact is
the civil war in Kosovo has been raging since 1389.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasich added, ``The fact is our intervening in the middle of an
ethnic civil war that has been going on for six centuries is not
likely to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Charles Norwood, R-Ga., predicted that if Congress did
not act, the President ``will commit our grandchildren to policing
the Balkans. Not because we are threatened. Not because we are
under attack. But simply to enforce a new world order.''
</P>
<P>
   The many Democrats who rallied around Clinton invoked memories
of the Holocaust to cry out for help for ethnic Albanians. They
said the ban on ground troops without authorization would hamstring
NATO commanders, force the courts to decide what constituted ground
troops and sent the wrong message to Milosevic. Some said the
bill's restrictions on what it termed ``ground elements'' were so
vague that they could be interpreted as banning financing for the
support troops already in Albania and the Balkan region with the
Apache helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really want to say to him today, `we don't know what
we're doing, we probably won't be for ground troops?''' implored
Rep. Dick Gephardt, the minority leader, ``You want to take that
option off the table? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Bonior, the Democratic whip said, ``Some say the
suffering Kosovars are not America's responsibility. That the gang
rapes, the burned villages, the mass graves are not our problem.''
He added ``We are a superpower at the peak of our prosperity and
strength. What is America supposed to do? Look the other way?''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the Democrats agreed. ``We cannot win peace through
war,'' said Rep. Dennis Kucinich of Ohio. ``The failure of the
bombing campaign is proof.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
