<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7089 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOSPITAL-MISDIAGNOSE-     04-28 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-MISDIAGNOSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL ADMITS 19 CANCER DIAGNOSIS ERRORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE AND RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It began around the first of this year, when a biopsy report on
a patient at an Attleboro, Mass. hospital turned up positive for
prostate cancer, triggering doubts about a negative test three
years ago on the same patient.
</P>
<P>
   A review of 279 prostate tissue tests at the hospital confirmed
that the ones on that patient and 18 others had been misread, with
the patients being told they didn't have prostate cancer when they
did.
</P>
<P>
   Now officials at Sturdy Memorial are reviewing 6,000 additional
biopsies for conditions ranging from breast cancer to skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no reason to believe there are problems with any of
the others. But we wanted our patients and medical staff to have
confidence and rest easy about all the findings from that period''
about which questions were raised, which was from the start of 1995
through the end of 1997, Linda Shyavitz, Sturdy's president and
CEO, said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   The two pathologists who misread the tests, she added, have not
been on Sturdy's staff since 1997 and the errors have been reported
to the cancer patients or their families, as well as to the state
Department of Public Health and the Board of Registration in
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the 19 patients have died, ``but we are absolutely
certain that their deaths are not a result of misread biopsies.
They died from completely unrelated reasons,'' said Shyavitz. As
for the health of the remaining 17, she said, ``I have no knowledge
of that because of patient confidentiality. I have no answer to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The two issues involved in the Sturdy case have been big news
lately. Awareness of prostate cancer has been growing rapidly, in
part because it is so widespread; an estimated 179,000 men in
America are likely to be diagnosed with the disease this year and
37,000 are likely to die from it. Hospital errors also have been
shown to be pervasive, with more than 1 million occurring each year
in the United States, 100,000 of which are deadly.
</P>
<P>
   Sturdy has been at the forefront of efforts by Bay State
hospitals to uncover such errors, which health watchers say is why
the hospital responded so aggressively once it learned about the
problems in its pathology department from 1995 to 1997. The initial
misreading of a biopsy on a prostate cancer patient was uncovered
earlier this year by a urologist, who saw a positive test result
that contradicted a test from 1996. Further review confirmed that
the 1996 test also was positive, although it was misread as
negative by the Sturdy pathologist working on the case then.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 20 prostate tests on 19 patients were shown to have
been misread, and the patients or their next of kin were notified
in late March and early April, Shyavitz said Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sturdy declined to name the two doctors who performed the
erroneous biopsies, and state officials declined to comment on the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital did approximately 15,000 biopsies during the
1995-97 period, but it is reviewing only the 6,000 involving
conditions where the tests could have affected diagnoses. Ones
involving procedures such as knee replacements or hernias are done
as a matter of routine but even if they were misread the results
would not have affected the treatment, the CEO added.
</P>
<P>
   A doctor would order a biopsy of the prostate after suspicions
of possible cancer were raised by the results of two simpler tests.
One is the digital rectal exam, in which a doctor feels the surface
of the prostate: hardness, enlargement, or lumps might indicate a
tumor. The other is a screening test, the PSA or prostate-specific
antigen, which measures the level of a chemical in the bloodstream
that is produced by the prostate and is elevated in prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The biopsy is carried out by rectally inserting a probe that
fires a hollow needle into the prostate to remove a tiny core of
tissue. Normally, several cores are obtained in different parts of
the prostate to determine the extent of the cancer, if any.
</P>
<P>
   Misreading diagnostic tests is relatively common, although
erroneous biopsies are rarer, said Andrew C. Meyer Jr., a leading
medical malpractice lawyer in Boston. His office currently is
pursuing two cases of alleged misreading of prostate cancer
biopsies, neither of which was at the Attleboro hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Since most prostate cancer is slow-growing, the Sturdy patients
who received falsely negative biopsy results might not have been
significantly endangered by the delay in diagnosis, said Dr. Eric
Small, a urological cancer specialist at the University of
California at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   If the pathologist wrongly read the biopsies as normal, it might
be because the cancer cells were in early stages of malignancy, he
explained. If so, ``it's still not excusable, but there would be
less clinical impact'' than if the error involved a more advanced
stage of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably in the cases of the 19 men, the men's doctors would
have been faced with a puzzlingly negative biopsy reading after PSA
and digital exam findings that were suspicious. Actually, said
Small, ``that's not an unusual scenario'' because prostate cancers
detected by PSA readings may not be big enough to be caught by a
biopsy.
</P>
<P>
   But in such a situation, the oncologist added, ``the men
shouldn't have been told just to relax and not worry.'' Rather, the
doctor should have had the PSA test repeated in six months or a
year. And if the PSA reading continued to rise, he said, the doctor
would likely have ordered a repeat biopsy.
</P>
</TEXT>
