<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7093 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLORADO-SHOOTING-BOS     04-28 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLORADO-SHOOTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL GUNMEN WERE PREPARING FOR COLLEGE, MILITARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ At the same time Eric Harris and Dylan
Klebold were making elaborate plans to cut short the futures of
hundreds of their classmates, they were also preparing for their
own futures in college and the military.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps to appease their parents, one of the boys spent the
weeks before their April 20 massacre scouting a college campus,
while the other was impressing Marine Corps recruiters.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the details that have emerged about the pair, their
planning for the future was a bizarre contrast to the deadly scheme
they had spent months plotting.
</P>
<P>
   Harris's yearlong diary, which mapped a plan to execute 500
people and blow up Columbine High School, also laid out an escape
that would take the pair to an unnamed island. But the two also
agreed to kill themselves if it became clear that they would be
caught, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to go to Mexico, or find an island someplace to
get away from America,'' said Jefferson County Sheriff John Stone.
Another scenario offered by Harris was that the two might somehow
be able to hijack a plane to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   However implausible their escape plans, officials said, Klebold
and Harris did carry out the initial steps of their assault plan,
following logistics on timing and location.
</P>
<P>
   After gunning down 12 students and a teacher, the boys killed
themselves, each firing a single shotgun blast to his head. Police
speculate that Klebold's and Harris's escape attempt was foiled
when a police officer standing in an exit fired at one of the
gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   As police Wednesday continued to prepare a detailed timeline of
the events on April 20, officials Wednesday said that Klebold's
girlfriend and prom date, Robyn Anderson, purchased a rifle and two
sawed-off shotguns that were used in the shooting. On Tuesday,
officials had said she purchased two of the weapons.
</P>
<P>
   They reiterated that the 18-year-old Anderson has cooperated
with requests for interviews and that she is not a suspect. They
continue trying to determine whether she was aware the weapons
would be used in a deadly shooting spree. It is illegal for a
person to provide guns if the person knows the weapons will be used
for a crime.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials are reviewing a videotape from the surveillance
camera in the school's cafeteria, but Jefferson County law
enforcement officials said Wednesday they had no indication that a
third gunman, or accomplice, was on the tape.
</P>
<P>
   Several student witnesses have said they told police that a
third gunman, a former student and member of the Trenchcoat Mafia,
was inside the school Tuesday morning. Those witnesses said they
saw the teen running through the halls wielding a gun, but not
firing it.
</P>
<P>
   In response, officials said they continue to interview friends
and acquaintences of Klebod and Harris, but did not name any
suspects. ``Keep in mind, there are a lot of people, in our minds,
who have not been cleared yet,'' Sheriff's Department spokesman
Steve Davis said at an afternoon press conference.
</P>
<P>
   But he did say police had cleared three teenagers who were
arrested as they watched the chaos at the school April 20 from a
nearby hill in Clement Park.
</P>
<P>
   The three had raised suspicions because they arrived at their
vantage point so soon after the first shots rang out, and because
at least one of their jackets bore an emblem _ a crucifix with a
slash through it _ that members of the Trenchcoat Mafia sometimes
wore.
</P>
<P>
   But law enforcement officials now say that they do not consider
the three teens accomplices, and that the sheriff had misspoken
Tuesday night when he said the trio was the focus of the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators Wednesday also interviewed an employee at a
Littleton hardware store, according to a store manager and police.
Police say that the employee told them that he sold propane tanks,
nails, and duct tape to Harris and Klebold, and that he copied a
set of keys for the teens, although they were marked ``do not
duplicate.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said investigators have learned that a set of keys to the
schools are missing, and officials theorize the pair stole the keys
so they would have access to the school and be able to place as
many as 60 homemade explosives and a propane bomb before the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   But while they were laying out their deadly plan, Harris and
Klebold also appeared to be moving ahead with their lives. Five
days before the shootings, Harris, the son of a retired Air Force
pilot, was rejected by the Marine Corps because of his medical
history, military officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the teenager reportedly say Harris had been
prescribed a psychiatric drug.
</P>
<P>
   Marine First Lieutenant Jeff Sammons confirmed Wednesday that
Harris's name, along with other interested students, was provided
to recruiters by Columbine officials.
</P>
<P>
   On April 2, Harris was interviewed by telephone about his
grades, his family life, and his reasons for wanting to join the
Marines, Sammons said. After passing two initial screenings, Harris
was visited at his home April 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was during that screening process, on the 15th, that his
parents told us there was a medical disqualification,'' Sammons
said.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said Harris, who allegedly was filled with
hatred for the ``jocks'' and other who he said tormented him, was
the younger brother of a Columbine graduate who represented the
type of school pride Harris despised.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Harris sailed through high school, getting good grades and
winning respect as a tight end on the football team. Neighbors said
they recall the two brothers playing basketball in the family
driveway.
</P>
<P>
   The Harris family, like the Klebolds, have hired attorneys and
declined to comment beyond statements expressing their grief and
sympathy for the victims.
</P>
<P>
   While Harris was considering a military career, Klebold
accompanied his father to the University of Arizona and returned to
tell friends he had placed a deposit on a dormitory room there.
</P>
<P>
   The Klebolds have lived in Littleton longer than the Harrises,
who, typical of a military family, have moved several times.
</P>
<P>
   The community continued its mourning Wednesday, as the impromptu
shrine outside Columbine grew further, extending hundreds of yards.
It overflowed with notes, cards, and flowers, and drew people late
into the evening. Many said they were unsure what they would find
at the scene, but were hoping to find comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the grief, there was a sign that forgiveness may be
possible. Fifteen large wooden crosses have been erected in Clement
Park next to the high school, one for each of the people killed,
including Harris and Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   On Klebold's cross a simple message reads, ``We must forgive
before we can move on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
