<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, APRIL 29
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT (moved on Monday, Apr. 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Apr. 26,
about Ehud Barak, the Labor Party candidate for Prime Minister of
Israel, misstated a campaign goal of the incumbent, Benjamin
Netanyahu, in some copies. He is trying to push Mr. Barak's public
image to the left, not his own.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CHOCK-PURCHASE-NYT (moved on Friday, Apr. 23)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Apr. 23,
about recent purchases of stock by directors of Chock Full o'Nuts
referred incompletely to the circumstances under which a director,
Henry Salzhauer, sold shares he had purchased in August 1998, when
the board was considering a takeover offer from Sara Lee. Mr.
Salzhauer says his purchase resulted from a longstanding order,
placed in February 1997, to buy if the price fell to a certain
level. When Mr. Salzhauer learned that the order was automatically
carried out in August 1998, he told the company of the improper
purchase and sold the shares at a loss.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PATENTS-NYT (moved on Sunday, Apr. 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Apr. 25,
about the addition of images to some patents available through the
Patent and Trademark Office's Web site misstated the address of a
separate patents data base operated on the Web by I.B.M. It is
www.ibm.com/patents.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-CANAVAN-DISEASE-NYT (moved on Monday, Apr. 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Apr. 26,
about screening for Canavan Disease, an inherited neurological
disorder, misstated the risk of a child's contracting the illness
when both parents are carriers. The risk is 1 in 4, not 1 in 6,400.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NABOKOV-CENTENARY-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Apr. 20)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Apr. 20,
about the birth centennial of Vladimir Nabokov misstated the
position of his son, Dmitri, on ``The Origin of Laura,'' an
unfinished novel by the author. Dmitri Nabokov does not intend to
try to complete it.
</P>
</TEXT>
