<SLUG> BC-PROVIDENCE-FBI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI ARRESTS TWO PROVIDENCE TAX OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ Federal agents stormed Providence city hall
Wednesday, searching five city offices, and arrested two top tax
officials on charges that they participated in an expansive bribery
and money laundering scheme that included other officials.
</P>
<P>
   The raid came as staggering blow to the mayor, Vincent A.
``Buddy'' Cianci, who has tried to overcome his city's history of
public corruption, and his own troubled past. Twenty-one of his
underlings were convicted on corruption charges during the 1980s,
and Cianci himself was forced to resign after beating his estranged
wife's boyfriend with a fireplace log.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Cianci denied any involvement in wrongdoing in this case,
saying ``You won't find any stains on this jacket.''
</P>
<P>
   Culminating a year-long covert probe called Operation Plunder
Dome, 76-year-old Joseph Pannone, chairman of the Board of Tax
Assessment Review, and 57 year old Davie Eade, vice chairman, were
arrested at home Wednesday and arraigned in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-page complaint detailing the charges laid out a scenario
scripted for the movies _ with hidden video cameras, undercover
informants, and accusations of double crosses.
</P>
<P>
   Pannone and Eade were were each charged with three counts of
money laundering, bribery, and conspiracy. At the heart of the case
against Pannone and Eade are 100 hours of video- and audio-taped
transactions and conversations with the informant in which the two
detailed their system of phony invoices and sham soda machine
purchases, converting checks into cash for bribery or extortion
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Pannone and Eade were suspended immediately without pay
Wednesday. Each earns about $3,500 annually from their positions on
the review board, according to the City Solicitor, Charles R.
Mansolillo. If convicted, the two men could each receive a maximum
penalty of 20 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   But the probe is far from over, according to US Attorney
Margaret E. Curran.
</P>
<P>
   ``This investigation is delving deeply into city affairs,'' said
Curran, listing five city departments served with search warrants
Wednesday. In addition to the Tax Collector's and Tax Assessor's
office, they included the Planning Department, the Department of
Inspections and the School Finance Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``This investigation does not stop today,'' Curran said. ``If
you are out there, and you have information about corrupt conduct,
or are involved with corruption, the time to come forward is now.
Consider this a window of opportunity, but know that that window
will soon close.''
</P>
<P>
   Curran would not name any officials by name, or specify whether
anyone who came forward would be offered immunity in return for
their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   But Cianci insisted Wednesday that any problem was limited in
scope. Just hours after FBI agents scoured City Hall in search of
potentially incriminating documents, Cianci said he was saddened by
the day's events, but that ``I want to reassure the people of this
city, and especially the workers of this city, that the
overwhelming majority of workers here are decent, honest people.
This is a sad day for the city of Providence and we are going to
get to the bottom of this.``
</P>
<P>
   Barry W. Mawn, special agent in charge of the Federal Bureau of
Investigation, said Wednesday that the impetus for the
investigation began with the flurry of citizen complaints made to
the FBI over the past several years. But the probe into Pannone's
and Eade's activities began in earnest last April, after a private
businessman spurned from a city contract agreed to pose as a person
willing to do the bidding of corrupt officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person was in a position that he was aware of possible
corruption that was going on, and they obviously disturbed him,''
said Mawn, who added that the informant was not currently under
special protection.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing Curran, Mawn said the arrests were just the beginning of
a probe that would widen to include more city officials and almost
certainly lead to more arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Pannone and Eade are two of five members on the Tax Assessment
Review Board appointed by the mayor. The board considers appeals by
citizens on the amounts of property taxes determined by the tax
assessor, and has the power to change that assessment.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the investigation would lead to his office or to him,
Cianci replied, ``absolutely not.'' He sought to distance himself
from one of the suspects in particular, Pannone, saying he had
appointed him years ago and that, ``Frankly, he's a 78-year-old guy
that I haven't had a lot to do with him.``
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as he tried to reassure residents of his innocence and
his administration's willingness to would cooperate with the
investigation, Cianci seemed to downplay the issue, making
announcements about an upcoming city budget, an ongoing fued
between the city's police chief and the policeman's union, and even
telling reporters about his intention to go forward with plans for
his birthday party Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't spend my time checking to see whether soda was
delivered or not,'' said Cianci, referring to charges in the
federal complaint regarding a soda machine company owned by Eade,
Doris Vending Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
