<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7105 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-DOCUMENTS-N     04-28 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-DOCUMENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT PAPERS SHOW MICROSOFT'S WIDE-OPEN CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST, MICROSOFT-CALDERA) 
(mk) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In April 1995, long before the browser wars erupted, Microsoft
Corp. had recognized the challenge posed by the Internet. Its
strategic response, its top technology executive urged, should be
clear-cut: Control as much of the crucial technology as possible,
just as it does in the personal computer market with its
industry-standard Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue to be concerned about is the same issue we've
faced in the past _ proprietary standards coming from competing
software companies,'' wrote Nathan Myhrvold, Microsoft's chief
technology officer.
</P>
<P>
   In his e-mail to senior company executives, including Bill
Gates, the chairman, Myhrvold specifically cited Netscape
Communications Corp., the Internet browser pioneer, as one of the
challengers that would promote competing technology standards.
</P>
<P>
   His answer to the challenge was an early formulation of what
became Microsoft's ``embrace and extend'' strategy for Internet
software. ``As proprietary technology and protocols are used'' on
the Internet, Myhrvold wrote, ``we want them to be ours.''
</P>
<P>
   It is this kind of detail about Microsoft's Internet strategy
and the inner workings of the software powerhouse that are to be
found in the thousands of pages of deposition testimony from dozens
of witnesses in the Microsoft antitrust case released Wednesday.
The mountain of documents _ the depositions of 92 people, from
Microsoft and other companies as well as expert witnesses _ are
being made public as a result of a federal court ruling sought by
news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The most legally significant portions of the depositions,
including about eight of the 20 hours of Gates' videotaped
testimony, have already been presented in the long-running trial.
What is now being made public for the first time are essentially
outtakes _ the raw material not used by the Justice Department and
19 states suing Microsoft or by the company in its defense. ``If
you find anything in these pages that is not already in the trial,
we have not done our job,'' said David Boies, the lead trial lawyer
for the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Yet reading through several depositions, including those of some
of the 23 Microsoft executives questioned, does offer an intriguing
glimpse of the management style and corporate culture of the
world's leading software company.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft managers are apparently given a lot of freedom. For
example, the negotiations between Microsoft and Netscape in 1995
are a central chapter in the antitrust suit. The government
contends that Microsoft made an illegal offer to Netscape to divide
up the browser market, a charge Microsoft denies. When the talks
broke down, the browser wars began.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Rosen, a Microsoft manager, was in charge of the
negotiations with Netscape. When a Justice Department lawyer asked
him when he was authorized by his superiors to try to reach a deal
with Netscape, Rosen replied: ``That's a difficult question to
answer because that's sort of not the way the company explicitly
operates. My responsibilities were to some great degree formed by
myself and then later, you know, verified with others that that was
okay to be doing more than instructed to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, perhaps more than any other company, understands the
importance of shaping industry perceptions and expectations. That
process is clearly guided from the top. In an e-mail written on
July 20, 1995, when Microsoft trailed well behind Netscape in
Internet software, Gates wrote: ``We should make sure our goals for
Internet presence are low enough so that we can achieve them, but
also say that Netscape has lost control. As we achieve our goals,
people should start to question Netscape leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   From the testimony, it is striking how broad the communication
by e-mail is within Microsoft. For example, Rick Rashid, vice
president of Microsoft's research group, which mainly focuses on
long-range issues in computing, was weighing in on the fine points
of product specifications and software technology. He was joined by
senior product executives, like Paul Maritz, and young programmers
alike. Titles and hierarchy do not seem to matter much at
Microsoft; anyone with ideas can join the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one senior executive is curiously absent for the most
part: Steven Ballmer, currently Microsoft's president. His name is
mentioned only fleetingly in the Microsoft depositions, and unlike
Gates he is rarely included as a sender or recipient of the
thousands of e-mail messages that have been submitted as evidence
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft explanation is that he was a senior marketing and
sales executive during most of the period covered by the suit, yet
other Microsoft marketing executives are all over the case.
Ballmer, the long-time No. 2 executive at Microsoft, regarded as
Gates' alter ego, was never questioned by government prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the mind-numbing nitpicking of the deposition process _ a
kind of rhetorical arm-wrestling between the interrogator and the
witness _ there are occasional flashes of humor. A Justice
Department lawyer, for example, presented Brad Chase, a Microsoft
executive, with yet another piece of evidence saying, ``I'm now
marking government exhibit 962.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh boy,'' Chase replied, ``more exhibits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
