<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PLOT THICKENS . . . AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Remember that nitwit wearing the Patriot hard hat as
he voted from the floor of the Connecticut State Legislature last
December? Wonder how he's feeling today?
</P>
<P>
   More Patriot Games. Man, I just eat this up with a spoon. And
it's going to be juicy watching the stadium game unfold.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, we've got the Connecticut Yahoos, standing at
the platform at Yo Adriaen's Landing while the train pulls away
once again. They were willing to give Bob Kraft the world, but in
the end it's never enough because they are . . . Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Then we have Massachusetts Speaker of the House, Tom Finneran _
a Bob Kraft nemesis and guardian at the gate _ claiming victory in
his quest to protect taxpayers from the corporate welfare that
marks most modern stadium deals.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the NFL, flexing its considerable muscle and
reminding Kraft that he's going to have to play ball with them if
he wants to be a member in good standing. Nashville is bad enough.
But Hartford?
</P>
<P>
   And finally, there's the suddenly silent Kraft, who spends most
of his time pretending to be doing the opposite of what he is
actually doing.
</P>
<P>
   --On draft day, Kraft is in the war room pretending he's not
calling all the shots for Bobby Grier and Pete Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   --In Hartford, Kraft's pretending he's still interested in the
Love Canal site by the shores of the Connecticut River (was Homer
Simpson in charge of security at the steam plant? Can you just see
Homer tossing contaminated substances out of his car on his way
home from work on the Whitehead Highway?).
</P>
<P>
   --Best of all, we've got Kraft pretending he has no control over
the NFL's substantial efforts to keep the Patriots in New England.
Bob's pact with Connecticut prohibits him from negotiating any
non-Hartford proposals, but clearly the league would not be pushing
so hard if it didn't have a green light from silent Bob.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft's got to be careful. He's facing another alleged deadline
Sunday that would allow him to pull out of Hartford, but how can he
trust Massachusetts, which acts only under threat of defection? Bob
can't afford to bail out of Connecticut, then have Massachusetts
change its mind again.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran and Senate President Thomas Birmingham are saying that
they can get this bill passed by the time NFL owners would vote on
the Hartford proposal (May 24). Kraft needs approval from
three-quarters of the NFL owners to move.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran, suddenly the most influential NFL force since Pete
Rozelle, continues to state that there's nothing personal in his
dealings with Kraft, which is what Bill Parcells said right up
until he blew out of town.
</P>
<P>
   The Speaker didn't want to make a prediction on what Kraft might
do, but he did say, ``I think Hartford is falling apart on a number
of levels _ those being environmental, financial, and the legal
work that has to be done between them and the University of
Connecticut. But I think the league has made it clear that the
long-term interests of the franchise and the league are best served
with a Boston or Massachusetts site.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kraft, the economics are pretty simple. He has an
opportunity to go into a $374 million Hartford stadium at no cost,
or spend$225 million to $250 million of his own dough to rebuild in
Foxborough with $70 million of infrastructure help from the state.
Economically, there's no choice. But here in the Commonwealth,
we're counting on two things: 1. Hartford's inability to overcome
the contamination/financial/steam plant/deadline issues; and 2.
Kraft's concern with his legacy and need to be loved in his native
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be great watching Kraft try to make everyone happy
as this unfolds. No doubt when he bolts from Connecticut he'll
compose one of those disingenuous letters for the Hartford Courant:
(itals)We tried our best but the NFL wouldn't let us go or We tried
our best, but Connecticut was not able to meet its timetables. We
really love the Nutmeg State and hope you'll come to Foxborough to
support the New England Patriots.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   It matters not how it happens . . . contaminated soil . . .
steam plant problems . . . the lure of home . . . the NFL
television market . . . the Kraft family legacy . . .
</P>
<P>
   All that matters is that the Patriots aren't going anywhere.
They will never play a game in Hartford. They are the football
equivalent of Charlie on the MTA. They will play forever on the
fields of Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
