<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7113 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS &LR;      04-28 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ENGLAND KEPT GUESSING ABOUT PATRIOTS' FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Just about everyone had a prediction Wednesday on how
New England Patriots owner Robert Kraft would react to the
last-minute stadium plan to keep the New England Patriots in
Massachusetts. Everyone, that is, except Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   Muzzled by his contract with Connecticut, Kraft could not
discuss any option other than accepting its offer to build, with
taxpayer money, a 68,000-seat stadium in Hartford. A team spokesman
said Kraft, who was in Boston Wednesday, would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft is expected to meet with his consultants Thursday in an
effort to sort through the status of the Connecticut deal, which
has been dogged by environmental and logistical problems. Terms of
the contract signed earlier this year allow Kraft to cancel the
project _ without penalty _ if he decides by Sunday that the state
cannot deliver the stadium in time or on budget.
</P>
<P>
   In Hartford, Governor John G. Rowland called a news conference
at the Capitol to insist that the team would decamp from
Foxborough. ``Well, the Patriots are leaving,'' he declared.
``They're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   But among Bay State business and political leaders close to the
situation, there was unbridled optimism the team would remain in
Foxborough. Political leaders crowed about Tuesday's late-night
breakthrough, which provides $70 million in state money for
infrastructure improvements if Kraft agrees to build a new stadium
in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very optimistic this can keep the Patriots in
Massachusetts,'' said Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham, who
last year won agreement from Kraft for a plan similar to the one
hammered out Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   After speaking with National Football League commissioner Paul
Tagliabue on the telephone, Governor Paul Cellucci also was upbeat.
``Connecticut is much sweeter in terms of money, but the loyal fan
base is here, and this is the sixth largest media market,''
Cellucci said. ``I think that's something the other NFL owners and
Mr. Kraft care a lot about.''
</P>
<P>
   Even House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran, who many saw as the only
man stading in the way of a Masschusetts stadium agreement last
year, said the new deal is ``in the best interest of the taxpayers
and a good deal for the Patriots.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers stack up like this: The Nutmeg State has agreed to
spend $374 million in public money to build a stadium along the
banks of the Connecticut River in Hartford. In addition, it would
pick up the tab for any unsold luxury suites and seats for up to 30
years. Those guarantees alone are worth more than $1 billion,
sources familiar with the contract say.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Kraft would invest $75 million in a hotel, NFL
entertainment, and fitness complex as part of the city's Adriaen's
Landing development project.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Massachusetts plan, Kraft would finance a new stadium,
estimated at $225 million to $250 million, on his own, though under
recently approved rules the NFL can help with a low-interest loan.
It would also require Kraft to pay $1 million a year to the state
to compensate for some of its spending on roads, sewers, and other
infrastructure. The stadium would be built on land Kraft owns in
Foxborough, and the team would play at Foxboro Stadium until the
new facility was ready, in 2002 or 2003
</P>
<P>
   While the Massachusetts bid pales financially in comparison to
Hartford's, Boston business leaders all but predicted that Kraft
would opt to build a new home here.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is Robert Kraft is very much a hometown guy,'' said
former Democratic National Committee chairman Paul Kirk, who has
led the Bay State's bid to keep the team. ``I'm not sure he ever
wanted to leave to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert Kraft has a decision to make and it's not an easy
one,'' added advertising executive Jack Connors. ``But my guess is
he will end up coming home.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL issued a statement saying it was pleased with the
Massachusetts political agreement, reached after Cellucci,
Birmingham, Finneran, and NFL officials met for several hours over
two days this week.
</P>
<P>
   The league said the accord was a ``step in the right
direction,'' but stressed that long-term commitments by the
business community to luxury suites were essential to suceed in
keeping the team in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   In response, business leaders said they hoped to line up
commitments for up to $15 million luxury box suites over the next
two weeks. Luxury suites would sell from $75,000 to $325,000 for
the best 50-yard-line suites. Advance sales are essential to
financing a new privately funded stadium, and a strong response by
corporations would also be send a signal to Kraft that he can count
on their support at Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut has left the door open for Kraft to back out of the
stadium deal, considered the most lucrative for any NFL owner. It
has stumbled badly in its attempts to acquire and clean up the
proposed stadium site, and there are serious questions about
whether the state can deliver on its promise of 2002 opening date.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the NFL has said it prefers that the Patriots remain
in the Boston television market, the nation's six largest, where
games can generate much higher broadcast revenue than in Hartford,
which ranks just 27th. NFL owners, who split league TV money, are
scheduled to vote on the Connecticut move at their next meeting at
the end of May. It is not clear whether Kraft would decide before
that meeting between his competing offers, or wait to see if the
league approves or rejects Connecticut's.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all of my negotiations with the Patriots and Robert Kraft,
it was absolutely clear to me that given his preference Kraft
wanted to keep the team in Massachusetts,'' Birmingham said. ``The
NFL has made it incontrovertibly clear that the league's preference
is to have the Patriots remain in Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   But Connecticut remains adamant that the Massachusetts deal is
too little, too late. Jay Malcynsky, a lobbysist representing the
team in Connecticut, said he thought the team would still move to
Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert Kraft told me flat out, he's got the deal he want's and
it's in Hartford,'' said Malcynsky, who has close personal and
political ties to Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcynsky is so close to Rowland some say he's actually the
governor,'' said one person involved in the struggle for the
Patriots. ``It's not surprising he'd say something like that at
this point.... But even though it will cost him a lot of dough, the
smart money is on Kraft staying in Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
