<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7114 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MULLEN-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-28 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MULLEN-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING:   NEW ENGLAND'S BIGGEST INDEPENDENT AGENCY ACQUIRED BY
LOWE GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass., Va.) (rk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The largest remaining independent agency in New England remains
independent no longer.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen Advertising, a creatively focused shop in Wenham, Mass.,
said Wednesday that it had agreed to sell a majority equity stake
to Lowe Group in London, part of Interpublic Group of Cos. Under
the deal, announced after weeks of speculation, Mullen will operate
as an autonomous agency under its current name and management.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, expected to close in early June, is another reminder
of the relentless consolidation that is remaking the industry.
Mullen becomes the third big New England independent to be acquired
in little more than a year, coming after the purchase of Hill,
Holliday, Connors, Cosmopulos in Boston by Interpublic and the sale
of Arnold Communications in Boston to Snyder Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presumption is if you're not aligned with a bigger agency,
it's a better thing,'' said Jim Mullen, who continues as chief
executive at Mullen, which he founded in 1970, as he adds duties at
Lowe as a vice chairman offering strategic counsel for North
American operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this gives me comfort,'' Mullen said in a telephone
interview, ``because at 58, you have to understand that changes can
happen in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This agency is my life,'' he added, ``and to know if anything
would happen to me the agency would continue to operate with the
same culture, same leadership and same opportunities for people
that it has for 29 years is everything I've ever dreamed of.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate interview, Frank Lowe, chairman and chief
executive at Lowe, offered the perspective of the acquirer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mullen is a very, very good agency,'' Lowe said, ``and good
agencies are rather thin on the ground. So this is a great
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to be able to work with an international group,''
he added, referring to Mullen executives, who had not until now had
overseas capabilities, ``so they'll get something out of it as we
get something out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullen has 280 employees working on advertising, direct
marketing, public relations and digital marketing for accounts with
estimated billings of $255 million. Clients include L.L. Bean;
CompUSAnet.com, the online operation of CompUSA; the used-vehicle
and credit-card units of General Motors Corp.; MSNBC, a joint
venture of General Electric Co. and Microsoft Corp.; Money
magazine, part of the Time Inc. unit of Time Warner Inc.; the
Monster.com Internet employment service operated by TMP Worldwide;
Oxygen Media, a company being started by the media executive
Geraldine Laybourne, and the Stanley Works.
</P>
<P>
   Though financial terms of the deal were not disclosed, Muller
said that scores of Mullen employees will be enriched because
ownership of the agency is ``broadly shared among senior management
and the 150 members of our employee stock ownership program.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, an agency sells for an amount about equal to its
annual revenue; Mullen's revenue last year was $17.2 million. But
the trade publication Adweek reported that Interpublic paid $123
million for Hill, Holliday, well above its annual revenue of $80
million, and Snyder paid about $117 million for Arnold, which had
revenue of $91 million.
</P>
<P>
   In operating as a stand-alone unit of Lowe, Mullen will be
separate from the agencies under the Lowe &AMP; Partners Worldwide
banner that include Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS in New York and Lowe
Howard-Spink in London. Mullen joins such creatively focused
agencies that are autonomous units of Lowe as Goldberg Moser
O'Neill in San Francisco, which is majority-owned, and the Martin
Agency in Richmond, Va., which is wholly owned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mullen people spoke with GMO and Martin,'' Lowe said, and
were told ``that I am slightly hands-off. And I think they were
appreciative of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullen echoed his new boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been anybody we haven't talked with,'' Mullen
said, referring to the acquisitive top executives of the large
agencies, ``and when I met Frank Lowe, I used the term
`heaven-sent.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank leaves you completely alone,'' he added, ``and Fred
Goldberg at GMO said the most wonderful thing: `He leaves you too
much alone.' '' Lowe agencies have billings estimated at $4 billion
from clients like the Braun unit of Gillette Co., Coca-Cola Co.,
General Motors, Henkel KGaA and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   The Mullen deal is the second in a week for Lowe as Lowe MBAC in
Barcelona, Spain, part of Lowe &AMP; Partners, acquired a majority
stake in FMRG, another agency in Barcelona, for undisclosed terms.
FMRG is being merged with Lowe MBAC to form Lowe FMRG, with a staff
of 43 and estimated billings of $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisitions are a nice counterpoint to large accounts
recently lost by Lowe agencies like the Mercedes-Benz of North
America unit of DaimlerChrysler AG and the United Distillers and
Vintners unit of Diageo PLC.
</P>
<P>
   So which is the largest remaining independent agency in New
England now? The Titus Moody Advertising and Maple Syrup Co.?
Actually, it is Ingalls in Boston, with billings estimated at $141
million.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
