<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS AND KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, April 29: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prosecuting a war in consultation with Congress is not always
easy for the White House, but it is necessary under the
Constitution. Given the sensitive military and diplomatic ground in
Kosovo, the House is steering a reasonable if spendthrift course
this week in acting on several measures involving the war in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers were right Wednesday to insist that President Clinton
seek congressional approval if he decides to order ground troops
into combat. The measure was advanced by Republican leaders but
supported by 45 Democrats in a 249-to-180 vote that democratic
opponents mischaracterized as a message of weakness to Slobodan
Milosevic. Clinton says he has no intention of invading Kosovo or
Serbia, and NATO has made no preparations to do so, beyond the
drafting of contingency plans. If sentiment within the alliance
changes, Clinton would be well advised to start moving troops and
weapons to the Balkans to keep the option open and to increase the
pressure on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Congress should not limit Clinton's hand on such preparations.
But if the president chooses to send ground forces into battle, he
will need the full support of Congress and the American people.
Wednesday he assured the House he would seek congressional consent.
To act without it would invite the kind of division and political
unrest that developed during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   The House also properly rejected an appeal from Rep. Tom
Campbell of California to issue a formal declaration of war against
Yugoslavia. With diplomacy at a delicate stage, the act of
declaring war would escalate the conflict and harden Serbian
resistance to a political settlement. Diplomatic efforts are likely
to intensify now that Russia has taken a lead role in trying to
mediate the conflict. Kofi Annan, the U.N. secretary-general, plans
to travel to Moscow Thursday, following the visit there earlier
this week by Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott.
</P>
<P>
   The House has shown less restraint on defense spending. It
should quickly approve Clinton's $6 billion emergency request to
pay for the air war and assistance for hundreds of thousands of
ethnic Albanians driven from Kosovo by Serbian forces. Instead the
House is moving to provide more than double that amount, with
additional money for a military pay raise, construction projects
and other matters that should be considered as part of the normal
Pentagon budget. The Senate is likely to do the same. Using the war
to circumvent budget limitations is a misuse of congressional power
and will not help NATO prevail in Yugoslavia. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
