<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7116 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-2TAKES-N     04-28 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARTFORD WAKES UP TO FIND PATRIOTS MAY NEVER ARRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ The idea of luring a major league team like
the New England Patriots to this blighted insurance town between
the lights of New York and Boston had seemed so grand, so exciting,
so downright unlikely, that many Hartford boosters had feared that
they would wake up from their blissful dream.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, that seemed to be happening Wednesday morning, when
the wake-up television shows were dominated by shots of
Massachusetts Gov. Paul Cellucci, surrounded by legislative and
business leaders, declaring shortly before midnight that the Bay
State was putting aside years of bitter negotiations with the
Patriots' owner, Robert K. Kraft, and offering a package of state
subsidies for a new football stadium next to the one at Foxboro,
just south of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the stadium is far from decided; Kraft, in fact, has
taken no public position on the offer from his home state. But to
many people here, and to executives of the National Football League
itself, the momentum appeared to be moving rapidly away from
Hartford and toward Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In some quarters here, the stadium was even being discussed in
the past tense. ``We would have loved to have had it,'' said state
Rep. Annette W. Carter, a Democrat from Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL issued a statement saying, ``The Massachusetts political
leadership's agreement last night regarding a stadium proposal is a
step in the right direction towards a Patriots alternative in
Foxboro.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Connecticut are so concerned that the deal is
slipping away that they are working with a lawyer on a possible
class-action lawsuit against the NFL, which helped broker the
Massachusetts plan, charging ``tortious interference'' in the
state's contract with the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to sit by idly while our legal rights get
trampled,'' said George C. Jepsen, the Democratic majority leader
in the state Senate. ``We believe that a wide range of people,
including taxpayers and the trade unions that would have had all
these construction jobs, would have potential claims.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the stadium tug-of-war is likely to determine the
future face of Hartford, which had received a psychic lift from the
football frenzy. Losing the stadium would dash hopes for renewing
the city's downtown and could be expected to sink or at least stall
an ambitious hotel and convention center complex that was to be
built around the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Losing the deal would also be potentially devastating for Gov.
John G. Rowland, a second-term Republican who insisted that he had
``bonded'' with Kraft in their months of negotiations and who has
repeatedly said he would stake his legacy on the outcome of the
huge gamble on the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that people would like to see this fall apart _ it's
not going to fall apart,'' Rowland said Wednesday, looking a bit
rattled as he faced a huge pack of Boston and Connecticut
journalists keeping what he calls ``the death watch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I quote my critics, they say this is one of the best plans
in the country. Why would he walk away from this?'' Rowland said,
referring to Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, leaders of the Massachusetts bid said that if
Kraft resists their overture, they were prepared to make their case
directly to his fellow league owners, three-fourths of whom must
approve any move by a team. The Patriots' move is scheduled for a
vote at an owners' meeting May 25 and 26.
</P>
<P>
   The abrasive back-and-forth represents an escalation in the
stadium game of demanding owners who extract lavish offers from
eagerly competing cities. Now, it appears, a victorious city cannot
rest easily even after the contract is signed.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts offer came not just with the blessing of the
NFL, but at its instigation. An NFL executive first flew into
Boston on Jan. 6, three weeks after Connecticut had approved its
deal, and the league has been working ever since to promote an
alternative to the Patriots heading for Hartford, which would mean
disrupting the team's fans in order to move from the nation's
sixth-largest television market to the 27th.
</P>
<P>
   Media analysts said that sponsorships and naming rights would
carry a much lower price in Hartford, and said that the league
could expect an erosion of viewership in Boston if the team were
playing two hours away. ``Fans try to be loyal at first, but that
rarely lasts,'' said Terri L. Ritenour, a sports analyst for Paul
Kagan Associates, in Carmel, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland knew he was going to be accused of giving away the store
when he signed his stadium deal, knew the site was contaminated by
coal tar and toxins, and knew he was dealing with a canny owner who
was sure to wind up with the upper hand. But for all the hurdles
Rowland had faced, his aides say he was blindsided by the one that
now imperils his plan: the clout of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   According to people who have talked privately with Rowland, he
feels betrayed. NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue had called to
congratulate him the night he signed the deal with Kraft. Rowland
said Tagliabue later assured him that he was ``just listening'' to
the Boston officials _ that it was his responsibility to be sure
every avenue had been explored. The very next day, according to
people who were in the meetings, Tagliabue was aggressively
lobbying business and political leaders to offer a deal to Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to make a recommendation to the owners, he has to be
able to explore all alternatives,'' said NFL spokesman Greg Aiello.
``To develop an alternative you have to be aggressive. That's not
inconsistent.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, business and civic leaders were kicking off a
drive to sell skyboxes _ at prices running up to $325,000 a year _
in the stadium they were suddenly hoping to build.
</P>
<P>
   Among the leaders of the effort is the Rev. J. Donald Monan,
chancellor of Boston College, who said the city's leaders had
realized that retaining the Patriots ``wasn't just a matter of
sports.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a sport that was a business which has a tremendous
economic impact on the commonwealth, and we thought that it was a
real tragedy for the team to leave the state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots issued a statement saying the team was ``not
involved with any efforts to develop, or discussions pertaining to,
a new Massachusetts stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts group is proposing a new stadium on the site
of a former horse track at Foxboro that is now used for special
tailgate parties. Kraft would have to pay to build the $250 million
stadium, and the state would pay $70 million for related
improvements, including roads, parking lots, utilities and
landscaping. The offer includes a requirement that the team pay the
state $1 million each year for using the improvements. The state
also would receive a $400,000 annual fee from the stadium's
satellite parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut offer is a much better financial deal for Kraft.
The state would pay the entire $375 million cost of the stadium,
although he has agreed to invest $70 million in a hotel in the
development.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft has until Sunday to exercise one of several clauses in his
deal with Connecticut that would allow him to walk away from the
deal with no penalty. But the Boston leaders are banking on the
fact that he would accept the stingier deal in exchange for the
stability of home.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' lobbyist in Connecticut, Jay Malcynsky, who was a
senior adviser to Rowland's re-election campaign last year, said
the Massachusetts deal was similar to ones that Kraft had rejected
in the past, even without the lucrative Connecticut offer in his
back pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can put a tuxedo on a scarecrow, but it's still a
scarecrow,'' Malcynsky said. ``These are desperate people in
desperate times, scrambling to at least proffer the illusion that
there's a viable alternative in Boston.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
