<HEADER>
A7119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-SCHOOLS-NYT &LR;      04-28 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE WAR OF THE RUDYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, April 29:
</P>
<P>
   The latest battle between Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and schools
Chancellor Rudy Crew could not have come at a worse time. New York
City's students face tough new testing standards, and politicians
in Albany are squeezing funds from the city's schools. Cynics might
be forgiven for wondering whether the mayor and perhaps even the
chancellor are looking for a diversion.
</P>
<P>
   Crew says he is absolutely not searching for another job, but he
is at a point that often tempts reformers to decamp. New standards
and other changes have been put in place, but not for long enough
to judge how well they work. Giuliani asserts that his emphasis on
education is neither new nor an attempt to set the stage for a
Senate run. Even so, his strong words on vouchers, on Crew and the
board of education all make him sound like a politician trying to
make sure he does not get blamed for the school system's problems.
</P>
<P>
   New York City's schools have endless needs, but none more
critical than stable leadership. Crew has come up with ambitious
standards and initiatives. But because many of these steps are
underfinanced and far from fully realized, this is no time for him
to leave. As for the mayor, his chief focus should be on giving the
chancellor the support he needs, particularly when it comes to
lobbying Albany for promised aid that the governor wants to
withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani began his tenure by battling schools Chancellor Ramon
Cortines. Cortines was replaced by Crew, whose relationship with
Giuliani was what the mayor called ``a partnership of shared
principles.'' The state legislature then passed a major school
governance reform, giving the chancellor far more direct control
over local school boards. The board of education got a new chairman
and members with whom the mayor seemed able to work.
</P>
<P>
   Now, using language similar to his anti-Cortines campaign four
years ago, Giuliani is again calling for radical reform and
defending his comment that the system should be ``blown up,'' as he
put it so crudely last week. Although he has since tried to temper
his tone, the mayor also accused the chancellor of ``a rigid
defense of the status quo.'' That is also an exaggeration that
mocks the chancellor and others who have sincerely tried to change
the schools according to the Giuliani-Crew format.
</P>
<P>
   This page supported Giuliani's plan to abolish the school board.
We also agree with Crew that the mayor's obsession with school
vouchers is a useless distraction. But neither man can be allowed
to use these debates as a way to dodge his own responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Crew needs to calm down. Giuliani needs to acknowledge the
conflict between his call for greater mayoral control of the
schools and his advocacy of a voucher system that would deprive
them of money and public support. During the Cortines wars,
Giuliani was the radical reformer. Now he is a lame-duck mayor
whose political future will not be enhanced by running off an
effective chancellor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
