<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBYNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT ADDS FILLY TO THE MIX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The Kentucky Derby field took shape Wednesday,
and it's an ample, female shape.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert decided to enter Excellent Meeting, giving
Saturday's race two fillies and a total of 20 horses, the most of
either since 1984. That's the year the colt Swale won a 20-horse
Derby that included Life's Magic and Althea.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting and General Challenge, coupled for wagering
because both are owned by California's John and Betty Mabee, were
made joint 3-1 favorites, with Baffert-trained Prime Timber next on
the morning line at 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   But all of that could change in the next two days.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting, who joined the Florida filly Three Ring in
the Derby, is also entered in Friday's Kentucky Oaks for females,
which is where John Mabee would prefer to run her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'd say she will run in the Derby,'' said Baffert,
who apparently prevailed in a talk with Mabee. ``(Today), I may
show up at the barn and he (Mabee) may have changed his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Only three fillies in 124 years have won the Derby. But if
Excellent Meeting goes in the Oaks, she'll have to overcome
barnmate Silverbulletday.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting wound up with post position 6 for the Derby,
more favorable than Prime Timber's post 14 and General Challenge's
post 15. Churchill Downs, for the second year, catered to
television by having horses' connections ``draft'' starting spots
in an order determined by lot.
</P>
<P>
   Other contenders had even worse luck than Baffert's male
contingent: Florida Derby winner Vicar and Blue Grass Stakes winner
Menifee were stuck on the outside in posts 18 and 19, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Desert Hero trainer Richard Mandella, who drew the No. 1 pick,
chose ``lucky number'' post 7.
</P>
<P>
   Three Ring, who has as much early speed as any horse in the
field, will have to use it to keep a clear path from post 2.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert chose 14 and 15 even though 12 and 13 were available
when he drafted. He explained that he liked the idea of putting
Prime Timber in the last stall of the main starting gate and
General Challenge in the first stall of the auxiliary gate _ giving
each a few feet of extra room on one side at the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime Timber can get a little fidgety in the gate, so with 14
there's no one on his immediate right side,'' said Baffert, who's
shooting for a record third straight Derby victory. ``General
Challenge takes a step or two to get in gear, and there's open
space to his inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Posts 15 and 16 produced Derby winners Grindstone in '96 and
Thunder Gulch in '95.
</P>
<P>
   But 17 through 20 have produced only two winners in the century.
</P>
<P>
   A better way?: Baffert suggested the Derby hosts try yet another
way of assigning post positions _ by letting handlers draft in an
order determined not by luck but by their horses' earnings.
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas and Nick Zito quickly endorsed the idea, which
might guarantee the favorites good posts.
</P>
<P>
   It's good to be Sheikh: Is Dubai's Sheikh Mohammed al Maktoum a
hands-on horse owner? You bet.
</P>
<P>
   The Sheikh was scheduled to get to Churchill Downs in time for
Worldly Manner's and Aljibr's workouts this morning. The barn said
the workout distances will be determined after he arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Worldly Manner, the 1998 Del Mar Futurity winner, and Aljibr
will be the first Arab-based horses to run in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Memory test: Churchill Downs announcer Luke Kruytbosch, recently
of Hollywood Park, will be calling his first Kentucky Derby. He has
never called a race with more than 14 horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope I can look past the emotion, rattle off names and
call a solid race,'' said Kruytbosch, 36.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen TV crews have trooped through the booth this week to
interview Kruytbosch, whose job makes him a minor celebrity in
horse-oriented Kentucky. Asked how many L.A. stations showed such
interest in his three years at Hollywood Park, he gave the expected
answer: none.
</P>
<P>
   Early to rise: Lukas, named Tuesday to the thoroughbred racing
Hall of Fame, on how he celebrated: ``I didn't even leave my room.
I had some chocolate milk and I think I was in bed by 8:30.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
