<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GADEL29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Republicans, some Democrats slam war policy
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Georgia House Republicans marched in lock step
Wednesday in voting to require President Clinton to obtain
congressional approval before sending ground troops into
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual twist, Democratic Rep. Cynthia McKinney joined the
Republicans, charging that the president has ``taken us on the
slippery slope toward war.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote on the bill, which was co-sponsored by Rep. Saxby
Chambliss (R-Ga.), was seen by Georgia House Republicans as
necessary because of their growing distrust of the president's
actions in the war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't trust this president,'' Chambliss said. ``We are
saying, come to Congress before you get involved with ground
troops.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which passed the House 249-180, would cut off
Pentagon funding for the deployment of troops if Clinton does not
come to Congress for permission first.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation's two other Democrats, Rep. John Lewis and Rep.
Sanford Bishop, oposed the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think 535 members of Congress should try to conduct a
military action,'' Lewis said. ``We cannot stand by and see a
modern-day Holocaust occur.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if war conflicted with his view of fighting racism
through nonviolence, Lewis said, ``I think there comes a time when
things are so bad and evil that it requires action.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) said he wants Clinton to come before
Congress because he lacks faith in the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``This president has proven himself utterly untrustworthy
whether it's domestic policy or foreign affairs,'' said Barr, the
first House member to call for Clinton's removal from office, in
the fall of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   After a vote Wednesday to withdraw troops failed in the House
290-139 (Lewis, Bishop, Chambliss and Johnny Isakson were the only
delegation members to oppose it) and another to declare war failed
by 427-2 (no Georgians supported it), Barr decided to seek a remedy
in the courts to stop Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Barr wrote a letter to Rep. Tom Campbell (R-Calif.), offering to
join him in filing a lawsuit against Clinton for taking military
action without congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   The suit would ask the Supreme Court to decide whether Clinton
has violated the Constitution. Campbell had suggested the lawsuit
as an alternative if his resolutions seeking to end the military
conflict or declare war failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``American involvement in Kosovo is counterproductive,
detrimental to our national security, and probably
unconstitutional,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   After an emotional day of debate, the Georgia delegation
disagreed on how the country should proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Barr and McKinney, who have openly sparred with each other in
the past, are joining Republican Reps. John Linder, Jack Kingston,
Charlie Norwood, Mac Collins and Nathan Deal in calling for an end
to U.S. involvement in the NATO action and bringing home the troops
within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fixing to get everything out of there,'' said Norwood. ``I
think we are in the middle of the largest foreign policy disaster
of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   A second camp that includes Chambliss and Isakson says the
United States should finish what it has started and continue to
bomb until Yugoslavia's President Slobodan Milosevic is ``brought
to his knees,'' as Chambliss put it.
</P>
<P>
   And a third camp, Bishop and Lewis, think that Congress should
leave the war to the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the business of Congress to run a war from armchairs
on Capitol Hill,'' Bishop said. Over in the other chamber, Sen.
Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) said he would vote to require that the
president ask Congress for permission to send troops.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.) says he would vote against ground
troops for any reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot get drawn into a major war in the Balkans,'' Cleland
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
