<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSANDWICH29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schlotzsky's hopes cold sandwich fare will take off
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the Austin-Bergstrom International Airport opens
next month, visitors who don't have time to wait three minutes for
a hot Schlotzsky's sandwich will be able to grab a cold one.
Sandwich, that is.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin company, with more than 750 delis in 38 states and 13
counties, is known for its 15 hot muffuletta-style sandwiches. But
that may change. Schlotzsky's has been in the test kitchen cooking
up five new cold sandwiches for people on the run. Departing from
the company's trademark buns, which do not hold well in a cold deli
case, the sandwiches are built on artisan breads.
</P>
<P>
   Coming up cold will be:
</P>
<P>
   _ Roasted vegetables _ peppers, eggplant, tomatoes, onions and
mushrooms marinated in balsamic vinegar and oil _ on square
focaccia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Turkey on round rosemary focaccia bread, with mango chutney
and lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   _ Roast beef and cheddar on sliced loaf ciabatta bread with
creamy horseradish.
</P>
<P>
   _ Turkey on dark nutty health bread with Monterey Jack cheese
and lowfat mayo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ham and swiss on a round ciabatta bread with lowfat mayo or
spicy mustard, lettuce and tomato.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the airport opens, these sandwiches will be in place,''
says Lee Applbaum, Schlotzsky's marketing director.''
</P>
<P>
   The cold sandwiches, made on exotic breads and available with
horseradish sauces, gourmet mustards and spicy ranch dressing, are
a little more upscale than Schlotzsky's traditional hot ones. A
little costlier, too, ranging from $4.75 to $6.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to do sandwiches out of our artisan breads,''
says Schlotzsky's corporate baker Rebecca Rather. One of the
sandwiches is made on the popular health loaf from Schlotzsky's
Bread Alone. Another is layered on wood-baked focaccia. However,
for two of the cold sandwiches, Rather found she preferred the
ciabatta bread baked in convection ovens, with its softer crust, to
the crisper ciabatta from the wood-fired oven.
</P>
<P>
   Flavors, shapes, sizes, texture _ all these qualities figured
into the sandwich development. Then came the experiments with
dressings, mustards and other condiments (many of which will be
available separately) before the final five were determined. (Her
personal favorite of the new cold sandwiches: the roasted veggies
on focaccia.)
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Schlotzsky's has experimented with
cold sandwiches. A year ago, several selections, including a
similar turkey sandwich with peach chutney, were offered but
eventually discontinued. Under ideal conditions, the sandwiches
held up well, but in high volume, Schlotzsky's says they were not
satisfied with the product.
</P>
<P>
   It was back to the culinary drawing board for the new airport
offerings, which will be sold as grab-and-go sandwiches at
Schlotzsky's coffee and pastries counter in the Central Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   But, traditionalists, fear not. The original hot Schlotzsky's
will be on the airport menu, too, in the deli in the West Terminal.
Just allow three minutes in your schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
