<SLUG> BC-SONY-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONY POSTS DECLINE IN PROFIT AS PRODUCT DEMAND FALLS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In a sign of how Japan's faltering economy is hurting
even its healthiest businesses, Sony Corp. reported a nearly 20
percent decline in fiscal-year earnings Wednesday and a net loss in
the final quarter, its first quarterly loss in four years.
</P>
<P>
   The results largely reflected a fall in demand for Sony's
electronics products, which account for two-thirds of its sales.
</P>
<P>
   Sony, the inventor of the tiny transistor radio, the Walkman and
the Trinitron television, said consolidated profits for the year
ended March 31 were 179 billion yen, or $1.49 billion, down 19.4
percent from a record 222 billion yen the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth quarter, Sony lost 43.3 billion yen from
operations, compared with earnings of 58.9 billion yen in the
comparable quarter a year earlier and the first operating loss
since the quarter that ended in September 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Sony has hinted that business in the current quarter will also
suffer and that the poor performance will probably extend through
the summer. By then, analysts say, the company will have started to
profit from new products, such as its Vaio laptop computers and
digital camcorders that use a new kind of silicon chip.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the worst has probably passed for Sony, and
investors seem to be hopeful. The shares, which gained 140 yen
Wednesday, to 11,700 yen, have risen about 35 percent since March
1, largely on optimism about a planned revamping aimed at making
Sony a pioneer in the ability to link up technology, information
and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings results Wednesday were released after the stock
market had closed. Sony's American depositary receipts, traded on
the New York Stock Exchange, fell $2.9375 to $94.5625.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sony is trying to be a `dot com' company, supplying
networking, hardware and content,'' said Hitoshi Kuriyama, a
consumer technology analyst at Merrill Lynch Japan. ``People are
buying Sony because of its future dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said its performance for the year was shaken mainly
in the last half because of weaker economies in Asia and other
emerging markets. Another important factor was the rapid
appreciation of the yen last autumn, the season when sales are
usually strongest for the year. The sudden rise of the yen in early
October made it difficult for Sony and other exporters to offset
the impact of the currency move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sony has at least shown itself willing to take radical action
to position itself for the future,'' said Alan Bell, an electronics
analyst in London for Schroders Securities Ltd. ``Investors believe
that these are depressed earnings, and that too much concentration
on short-term earnings is to miss the bigger point.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some analysts caution against focusing too much on the
Sony dream, for much needs to happen before computers, televisions,
cellular phones and video games can all communicate with one
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sony is the only company with the ingredients to do that, but
implementation is the next stage,'' said Koichiro Chiwata, a
consumer electronics analyst at Nikko Salomon Smith Barney in
Tokyo. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
