<SLUG> BC-CHAT-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGINEERING FIRM FILES INTERNET CHAT SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: eBay in last graf is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet chatter is becoming a legal minefield.
</P>
<P>
   In a second major lawsuit by a Massachusetts company against
anonymous chatters on the Internet, Stone &AMP; Webster Inc. is seeking
damages against 20 people it charges made false statements about
the company or disclosed inside information online. Stone &AMP; Webster
believes at least some of the defendants are employees.
</P>
<P>
   Such cases are becoming more common as investors turn to the
World Wide Web for information. Raytheon Co. began a similar action
in February.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo Inc., the California-based Internet portal that operates
many financial chat boards, faces so many complaints from other
companies that it recently adopted a new disclaimer for its
financial message boards.
</P>
<P>
   Those services, Yahoo now stresses, are ``for entertainment
purposes only.''
</P>
<P>
   But many companies don't see the joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a responsible company you have a reponsibility to people
investing in the stock not to have irresponsbile information going
out,'' said William Zucker, a partner at the law firm of Gadsby &AMP;
Hannah, which represents Stone &AMP; Webster, the Boston engineering
and construction firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are starting to regard all this as material because
so many people log onto the chat rooms,'' said Charles L. Solomont,
law partner at Bingham, Dana who has pursued similar cases on
behalf of other clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people read negative things about their company that
appear truthful, it can hurt the value of the stock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Recent Supreme Court rulings have affirmed protections for
certain anonymous speech. In 1995, the high court called
unconstitutional an Ohio ban on anonymous leaflets distributed in
political campaigns; earlier this month, the court affirmed a
ruling that the 1996 Communications Decency Act does not prohibit
certain anonymous messages.
</P>
<P>
   But libel and slander are another matter, and even advocates of
protections for Internet users say that people who post on
electronic message boards should beware that passing on rumors
might come back to haunt them if the subject of the rumor takes
offense.
</P>
<P>
   In its suit, filed in Suffolk (Mass.) Superior Court last
Friday, Stone &AMP; Webster charges a group it calls ``John Does 1-10''
made false online statements in 1998 and 1999 intended to defame
the company.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, another 10 people the company calls ``Fred Roes''
and believes to be current or former employees, allegedly violated
company policies by disclosing confidential information on the same
message board.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Raytheon case, Stone &AMP; Webster has not yet cited
specific messages it considers improper or the screen names of the
authors who posted them.
</P>
<P>
   But like most of Yahoo's message boards devoted to publicly
traded stocks, musings on the Stone &AMP; Webster board run the gamut
from praise to criticism of the company and its chairman and chief
executive Kerner Smith. Recent comments often related to the
company's stock performance. Since January, shares have fallen from
their January high of $34 3/8. Wednesday they closed at $22 each.
</P>
<P>
   In one post dated April 1, for instance, an anonymous writer
described what was supposedly a confidential memo sent to the
company's top 100 managers regarding problems in Asia. ``The tone
of the letter is downright desperate,'' wrote the person, using the
screen name ``gignol.'' ``I suspect that Kerner will not be with us
very long.''
</P>
<P>
   Zucker declined to discuss specific posts, but said Stone &AMP;
Webster will say just what material it finds objectionable as it
pursues discovery against Yahoo to learn the names of the anonymous
authors. Yahoo is not named as a defendant.
</P>
<P>
   While employees might eventually be disciplined, he said, a
chief goal of the suit is to obtain an order prohiting them from
making further, allegedly defamatory, posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people would be posting this stuff if they put
it under their own name,'' Zucker said. ``There's a feeling of
having no responsibility for your actions and no ability to verify
whether what the person is saying is true.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is also seeking unspecified monetary damages. No
hearings have been scheduled in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In another lawsuit involving allegedly false statements on the
Internet, FedTrust Liquidations, a Washington car dealer, on
Tuesday sued a rival firm in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   FedTrust charges that officials of rival Specialty Car Sales
Inc. of Miami posed as disgruntled FedTrust customers and posted
criticisms of FedTrust on a message board at eBay, a popular
Internet auction site. The lawsuit filed in US District Court for
the District of Columbia says that six winning bidders cancelled
their auto purchases after reading the hostile messages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Staff reporter Hiawatha Bray and correspondent Sacha Pfeiffer
contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7134 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUIMA-DIALLO-LAWYERS     04-28 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-DIALLO-LAWYERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 PRIVATE LAWYERS SHADOW PROSECUTORS IN CASES AGAINST POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just hours after the four police officers accused of
killing Amadou Diallo were arraigned on murder charges in late
March, a team of lawyers convened before television cameras in
lower Manhattan and made their case against the officers.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the findings of what they called ``our pathologist,'' the
lawyers described how and where bullets had punctured Diallo's
body. They said Diallo had been lying on the floor for most of the
41-shot barrage in the vestibule of his Bronx apartment building.
And they attacked the ``blue wall of silence'' with which police
officers often shield their accused colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation had all the hallmarks of a closing argument by
prosecutors, but it was an opening salvo by a team of private
lawyers representing the Diallo family in the civil claim they say
they will eventually file.
</P>
<P>
   With that news conference, Johnnie Cochran, Barry Scheck and
Peter Neufeld served notice that they would go far beyond just
filing a lawsuit _ they would be shadowing the criminal
prosecution, demanding reforms in the Police Department and waging
a public-relations war. Friday, when wrangling over pretrial
motions in the criminal case begins in Bronx Supreme Court, they
will not be in the courtroom, but their presence will be felt.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the Diallo case the lawyers' only front. The three men,
who were at the epicenter of a national debate over race and police
with the California trial of O.J. Simpson, have now attached
themselves to a half-dozen headline-grabbing cases in New York and
New Jersey, all of which accuse law enforcement officers of
excessive force or abuse of authority.
</P>
<P>
   The people they represent include Abner Louima, the Haitian
immigrant who last year accused police officers in Brooklyn of
sodomizing him; two New Jersey men, one black, one Hispanic, shot
by state troopers on the turnpike last year after what was alleged
to be a race-based traffic stop, and the family of Thomas Pizzuto,
the Long Island man who died in January after, his family says,
guards at the Nassau County jail beat him and left him to languish.
</P>
<P>
   While all of these cases could yield sizable awards or
settlements, the lawyers say they have taken them on because of the
potential they offer for law enforcement reforms. The cases clearly
have their own momentum for reform, and many changes will likely
come long before the civil cases conclude. But the spotlight that
follows Cochran and his colleagues will help keep attention focused
on the issues the cases raise.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the lawyers' involvement is good for the prosecutors,
who have the narrower mission of pursuing the criminal case, is
less clear. The lawyers' expertise and the information they provide
in these cases may benefit prosecutors. But their high-profile
presence may also pose dangers, like creating the perception that
the private lawyers' agenda is driving the public prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Their visibility ``certainly has an effect on public opinion,''
said Gerald Lynch, a former prosecutor who teaches at Columbia Law
School. ``And to the extent that public opinion affects
prosecutors, judges and juries, then there is some impact to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Simpson case catapulted Cochran, Scheck and Neufeld to fame,
giving them reputations as formidable lawyers and high-priced hired
guns. That renown also provided them entree to many of these cases,
where they are working with local lawyers who were retained first.
And it gives them considerable access to prosecutors and public
officials.
</P>
<P>
   While it is unusual for criminal defense lawyers to suddenly
align themselves with prosecutors, there is a continuum of sorts:
the lawyers turned their defense of Simpson into an assault on the
Los Angeles Police Department, just as they are assailing law
enforcement now.
</P>
<P>
   And it did not start with Simpson. As an assistant district
attorney in Los Angeles, Cochran prosecuted police brutality cases,
and in private practice in California, he won millions of dollars
in judgments against law enforcement agencies in brutality cases.
</P>
<P>
   Neufeld and Scheck began their legal careers as Legal Aid
lawyers in the Bronx, and founded the Innocence Project, which has
used DNA testing to free more than 40 inmates wrongfully convicted
of crimes.
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon, legal experts say, for people who allege
that they were victimized by law enforcement officers to retain a
lawyer early in the process to prod prosecutors to pursue a
criminal case. But the impact on these cases of having lawyers with
such unusually high profiles is hard to predict.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, they can be useful to prosecutors. Scheck and
Neufeld wield considerable expertise in forensic evidence, and all
three are skilled at trial preparation. They have hired their own
investigators and say they will pass on to prosecutors what they
learn and will recommend experts.
</P>
<P>
   But as the civil lawyers marshal evidence and theories, it may
be hard for the actual prosecutors to avoid following in their
tracks. Those tensions were perhaps best displayed by the news
conference after the arraignment of the officers in the Diallo
case, at which the lawyers said they wanted to rebut ``trial
balloons'' floated by the defense lawyers about the circumstances
of Diallo's death. Neufeld decried as ``absurd'' the assertion by
one of the officers' lawyers that police had fired 41 shots because
Diallo did not fall down.
</P>
<P>
   Neufeld cited an autopsy the team had commissioned from Dr.
Cyril Wecht, a pathologist, to say that two bullets had perforated
Diallo's spine, which would have made it impossible for him to
remain standing, and that forensic evidence suggested those shots
had been fired early in the sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, such rebuttals would be made by prosecutors _ at
trial, which is months away. Prosecutors from Bronx District
Attorney Robert Johnson's office have avoided discussing evidence
in the case; they said they are not happy that the civil lawyers
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's good when evidence is discussed in the
newspaper, period, no matter who's discussing it,'' said Barry
Kluger, the chief assistant to Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The assertion also places prosecutors in a difficult position:
most criminal lawyers say it is exceedingly difficult for medical
examiners to determine the sequence of bullets hitting a body, and
people who have seen the official medical examiner's report in the
Diallo case say it draws no such conclusion. Yet by having these
lawyers advance with near-certainty such a sequence, the prosecutor
must either adopt the same theory _ or be in the awkward position
of disagreeing with the Diallo family's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Neufeld said that, as the family's representatives, his team was
obligated to rebut what they saw as false assertions.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson's office is going out of its way to demonstrate its
independence. Kluger, the chief assistant, said the prosecution had
not and would not share any evidence with the civil lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Neufeld and Scheck were also quick to stress the ``one-way''
nature of their relationship with prosecutors, saying that they
share information but get none in return.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say frequent contact between civil lawyers and
prosecutors is not uncommon, or even improper. ``There is probably
more interaction than is generally acknowledged,'' Monroe Freedman,
a professor of legal ethics at Hofstra University, said.
</P>
<P>
   What is important, for tactical reasons, is to maintain at least
a perception of distance. ``It's not a good idea for a prosecutor
to be seen as the pawn of a victim who's after a big judgment,''
Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers for the police officers on trial in the Louima
criminal case under way in Federal court in Brooklyn, for example,
say they plan to question Louima on whether he was prepared for the
criminal trial by his private lawyers. And potential jurors were
questioned about their perceptions of Louima's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   And in cases involving the police or other public entities,
Lynch said, a criminal case can be seen as too closely linked to a
broader reform, or symbolic, agenda. A judge, for example, may not
want his or her verdict to be interpreted as a rebuke of all police
officers or the Police Department's practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard enough for Bob Johnson,'' Lynch said. ``It can only
make it more complicated if the victim or the victim's lawyers are
also identified with an agenda of reform that you are not
identified with as a prosecutor.''
</P>
<P>
   But Neufeld says that, regardless of the impact on the criminal
case, it is this larger agenda that really interests him and his
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The New York cases, they said, will focus on the web of rules
and culture that protect police officers. They pointed to the
48-hour rule, which gives officers the right not to be questioned
for two days after an incident, and the power of the Patrolmen's
Benevolent Association, the police union, whose delegates often
insist that officers under suspicion not be questioned at all.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say litigation was a much more powerful reform
tool 10 or 20 years ago, when judges were willing to be more
activist. And often, they say, it is less what happens in court
than the publicity and political pressure resulting from a case
that matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to think about the courts as a mopping-up
operation,'' said Larry Kramer, a professor at New York University
School of Law. ``The Diallo case will do a lot more because of any
political reaction to it than any judgment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
