<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7140 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-B52S29-COX     04-28 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-B52S29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will the B-52's turn SunFest into a shimmying Love Shack?
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ B-52's vocalist Fred Schneider is
talking about Cher and her recent assault on the pop charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that something?'' a reporter asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' Schneider responds in his best devilish manner.
``Maybe Sonny will come back, too.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the B-52's in a nutshell, the group that turned a quirky
sense of humor and a thrift-store idea of fashion into a formula
for pop success. Not once, but twice _ in the late '70s, when they
broke big in the New Wave era with classics like ``Planet Claire''
and ``Rock Lobster,'' and again in the early '90s, when they scored
their biggest hits with ``Roam'' and ``Love Shack.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes yet another B-52's comeback a distinct
possibility. But for now, the band is lying low, coming off the
release last year of a greatest-hits compilation (``Time Capsule:
Songs for a Future Generation'') and heading on tour without
vocalist/percussionist Cindy Wilson. ``Cindy's having a baby, so
she's sort out of commission,'' Schneider explains.
</P>
<P>
   But at a time when rock seems to have categorized itself to
extremes _ alt-pop, trip-hop, you name it _ there's a niche clearly
waiting to be filled. Call it the rock-as-camp genre: The B-52's
created it, and they're bound to reclaim the throne one of these
days.
</P>
<P>
   Consider what's already come from the band: songs about dogs
named Quiche Lorraine and parties that never seem to end. To say
nothing of those beehive hairdos _ the name B-52's refers to them.
This was pop that begged not to take itself too seriously, but
wasn't pablum for the masses, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our songs are a little more complex than a lot of people
think,'' says Schneider, speaking by phone from his home outside
New York. ``They think we just write campy little tunes. I haven't
seen anyone write one as good as we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Take ``Rock Lobster,'' with its organ licks and whacked-out
lyrics. The original version ran more than six minutes _ hardly
what you'd call radio-friendly. Then again, as Schneider is quick
to note about one of the band's more party-oriented tunes, ``They
thought `Love Shack' was also too weird. It shows you how
progressive radio is.''
</P>
<P>
   Partying is indeed the predominant theme in the B-52's music.
But would you expect any less from a group that got its start one
night at a Chinese restaurant in Athens, Ga., before that city even
became known as a rock outpost? Original band members included
Schneider, Wilson, vocalist/keyboardist Kate Pierson,
guitarist/keyboardist Keith Strickland and guitarist Ricky Wilson
(Cindy's brother), who died of AIDS in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Among the five of them, musical experience was minimal at best:
Cindy sang in the shower to Petula Clark, Ricky learned to play
guitar from watching a show on public television. As for Schneider,
whose vocal style falls somewhere between singing and speech, he
says, ``I never even would sing around the campfire because I had
such a bad voice.''
</P>
<P>
   But the band's playful spirit prevailed. After that initial
restaurant meeting and a few basement rehearsals, they made their
debut at a friend's Valentine's Day party. ``We did the same set of
six songs twice,'' Schneider recalls. ``The rest just snowballed
into one party after another.''
</P>
<P>
   The group's fashion sensibility wasn't a conscious part of the
plan, Schneider insists. Band members shopped in thrift stores
because the clothes were cheap _ ``You could get shirts for a
quarter,'' Schneider says _ and they didn't have much money to
spare. The look just developed into its own funky thing.
</P>
<P>
   Musically speaking, what's the next step for the B-52's?
Schneider points out that the greatest-hits compilation did feature
a couple of new songs, ``Hallucinating Pluto'' and ``Debbie,'' that
follow in the band's dance-rock vein. But given Wilson's pregnancy,
he adds that he's not expecting to head back into the studio
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   As for future fashion statements, well, let's just say Schneider
is looking forward to his stint on jury duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it when they say, `Dress properly.' It's like, `Where's
my First Amendment rights?''' he concludes. ``I'm already planning
my outfits.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7141 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISAAC-HAYES29-COX     04-28 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISAAC-HAYES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From Stax to `Shaft' to `South Park,' he's still a soul man
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When Isaac Hayes talks, children listen.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's not the real Hayes _ that's Chef, the
kid-friendly, skirt-chasing cool cat of a cafeteria worker who's
one of the main characters in ``South Park,'' Comedy Central's
absurdist animated sitcom. Hayes provides the voice _ the writers
supply the comedy.
</P>
<P>
   So, when the unscripted, 56-year-old Hayes is on the other end
of the phone line, you're bound to do a double take. Should you
address him as Chef? Or as the composer of some of the most
inventive soul music known to man, the theme from ``Shaft''
included? The guy brings plenty of history to the table _ and
plenty of bass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will you forgive me for smacking in your ear while we talk?''
he says in that deep, luxuriant voice of his, apologizing for the
fact that he's grabbing a sandwich in the midst of another
interview-filled, 16-hour day. Hey, no problem, Isaac. We just want
to know what's on your mind.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, he's eager to talk music. ``It's not as
flamboyant as it used to be,'' he explains, referring to his
king-of-soul days in the '70s, when he had nearly an orchestra of
musicians behind him. ``Sometimes I'll do it with horns and
strings, but other times I'll do it via the synthesizer.''
</P>
<P>
   The vintage Isaac Hayes is a musician to be reckoned with. While
audiences may know him best for the ``Shaft'' soundtrack _ that
burst of electric funkiness that earned him an Oscar and a Grammy _
Hayes has countless other singles and albums to his credit. As one
of the session men with the famed Memphis-based Stax label, he
produced, composed and played on dozens of hits for artists like
Wilson Pickett, Lou Rawls and Sam &AMP; Dave: ``Hold On, I'm Coming,''
''Soul Man,'' ``B-A-B-Y,'' ``You Don't Know Like I Know'' are just
a few examples.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were like a big family,'' Hayes recalls of the Stax era.
``We worked and played. It was all fun. Nobody thought of the
longevity of the music or of writing a standard. We just wrote what
we felt.''
</P>
<P>
   He points to a humorous example. ``Hold On, I'm Coming'' was
actually the cry heard from the Stax bathroom by Hayes' songwriting
partner, David Porter. As Hayes tells it, ``I was playing on a
groove. I struck something and it sounded good. David said, `Hey
man, I gotta go to the restroom.' I called out, `David, hurry up
man, I got something.' He said, `Hold on, I'm coming.' He broke out
of the restroom, saying `That's it. That's the title' with his
pants down to his ankles. He was so excited he didn't care how he
looked. And we worked it out.''
</P>
<P>
   A more serious example from the Stax days, however, was Hayes'
1969 album, ``Hot Buttered Soul.'' At a time when rock bands were
beginning to explore the concept album, here was something more
rare _ an R&AMP;B concept album. The recording contained only four cuts
_ it was like a lengthy jam session captured on vinyl.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes admits he didn't see much commercial potential for the
project. ``It was a selfish thing on my part because I felt what I
had to say could not be said in two minutes and 30 seconds,'' he
recalls, commenting on the limitations of the singles format.
``Since I had already been a part of 26 albums, I felt no pressure.
I just wanted to do something that was artistically exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   He never thought that Stax execs would go for it. ``I put them
in the conference room and played it for them. As they sat there,
they listened intently. When the album stopped playing, they still
sat there, looking. I was getting worried,'' Hayes remembers.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they came forward. ``They said, `Isaac, we don't know
what this is. You might not get airplay. But this is a
masterpiece,'' Hayes said. Even through a phone line, you can see a
smile breaking on his face.
</P>
<P>
   To the record-buying public's credit, ``Hot Buttered Soul''
broke the top 100 and established Hayes as a new voice of black
cultural pride. It also paved the way for his biggest success _
namely, the score for the 1971 blaxploitation classic, ``Shaft,''
the soundtrack of which became a No. 1 album. As one critic said,
``It has held up much better than the film.''
</P>
<P>
   During this period, Hayes combined his music-making with his
bold ideas about style _ think chain vests and a shaved head. The
message of black power was unmistakable. ``I was trying to send an
image out of a black man standing tall, one who had overcome a lot
of suppression but one who was also was pouring his heart out and
sharing his personal experiences,'' he says. He makes no excuses
for his past extravagances: ``I believe in overkill. If people like
it, I want to feed it to them and give them enough so they know
they've been fed.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, musically speaking, Hayes is thinking more in terms
of collaboratingwith a younger generation of musicians,
particularly in hip hop. That is, when he's not having fun with
``South Park''-related projects like the platinum-selling ``Chef
Aid'' album and its unforgettable cuts, ``Chocolate Salty Balls
(P.S. I Love You)'' and ``Tonight Is Right for Love (with Meredith
Baxter Birney).''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, Hayes takes his sudden ``South Park'' fame in
stride. Although his celebrity status waned in the 25 years after
``Shaft,'' he went about making recordings without interruption. He
didn't expect, however, to become a cultural icon once again thanks
to a TV series that's guaranteed to offend everyone. Hayes' ``South
Park'' character has even managed to woo Kathy Lee Gifford to his
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I did the first episode, when I read it actually, I said
you guys got to be kidding,'' Hayes recalls. ``I was a little
reluctant, a little paranoid by it, but I eventually did it and had
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hayes is hardly as lust-driven as Chef. He spends his
days hosting a morning soul program on a New York radio station,
promoting education through his World Literacy Crusade and telling
the world the virtues of Scientology, his adopted religion (he
admits he thought it was a cultbefore he joined, but now finds it a
spiritual comfort).
</P>
<P>
   As for Chef and his antics, however, he thinks there's something
to be said for the man. ``I like his candor, the freedom of the
character. If he wants to make love, he wants to make love right
now,'' he concludes. ``There's a little Chef in all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
