<HEADLINE>
PIONEER SNOW RECOGNIZED BY DRAG RACING HALL
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gene Snow admittedly did not invent every cutting-edge part that
found its way onto his assortment of Funny Cars and Top Fuel
dragsters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But during a colorful and outspoken 40-year career that
continues today, the Fort Worth businessman/racer never has been
reluctant to bolt on, modify or fabricate a piece that might sling
him down the quarter-mile quicker and faster. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snow and fellow Texan Richard Tharp were among 14 members of the
class of 1999 who were inducted into the International Drag Racing
Hall of Fame last month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very nice deal,'' said Snow, who was presented by Joe
Amato, a five-time National Hot Rod Association Top Fuel champion,
during formal ceremonies in Gainesville, Fla. The hall is located
at the Museum of Drag Racing, founded by retired Top Fuel legend
``Big Daddy'' Don Garlits in Ocala, Fla. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor to be inducted into that hall of fame,'' said
Snow, who was presented a plaque and ring to commemorate his
achievements. ``A person that has put as many years into drag
racing as I have would be disappointed to have not gotten into it.
And like I told Don Garlits, thanks for putting me in while I can
still walk up there.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snow may have been the inspiration for the ``win on Sunday, sell
on Monday'' thinking that is the basis for factory participation in
all forms of motorsports. Snow began his drag-racing career with
muscle and high-performance cars he would repair, drive off his
used car lot and take to the local drag strip. A win over the
weekend more often than not would produce an eager buyer at Snow's
office the next morning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snow moved up the ranks into more exotic machinery but is best
remembered for his pioneering days in the Funny Car ranks. In 1965,
he built the first in a series of ``Rambunctious'' and ``Snowman''
Dodges. Using an injected, late-model Chrysler Hemi V-8, Snow's
first Dodge Dart featured fiberglass doors and front-end predating
the one-piece bodies that have become the norm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then classified by the NHRA as a Fuel Dragster, the car rang up
impressive numbers on gas or fuel, winning Comp and Super
Eliminator titles at NHRA events from 1966 through 1968. That year,
Snow also became the first NHRA Funny Car driver to crack the 200
mph barrier (200.88 mph). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snow is the only driver to have won national events in four
categories _ Top Fuel, Funny Car, Competition and Super Eliminator.
But his first love remains those exotic ``Rambunctious'' Funny
Cars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was trails we'd never been down before,'' said Snow, who
was among the first to experiment with high-gear, direct-drive
transmissions, rigid suspensions, turbocharging and air induction.
``Back then, we had something different every month that we were
trying. That's when it was fun.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snow also was a pioneer of the team concept, fielding a Top Fuel
car and three Funny Cars in 1972. He switched to Top Fuel in 1981
and racked up consecutive top-10 NHRA points finishes between 1983
and 1991. In October 1988, Snow became the first NHRA driver to
crack the 5-second barrier with a pass in 4.997 seconds at Houston
Raceway Park in Baytown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 61, Snow says that he is ``older than dirt.'' But the man who
made his money in the oil and gas business still is competing in
the NHRA's Federal Mogul Dragster division, as a Sportsman racer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an absolute hobby,'' Snow said between rounds at the
Castrol Nationals at the Texas Motorplex in Ennis last weekend.
``And I've got to be a realist. I don't want to spend what little
money I've put aside to retire on. And the odds eventually get you.
I've been pretty lucky not to have gotten hurt real bad. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'm not trying to blaze any trails, just get out and have a
good time. I don't have to answer to anybody that way.'' &QL; 
HAMLIN ADJUSTS TO EARNHARDT'S STYLE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Hamlin's first career victory as Dale Earnhardt's crew
chief in Sunday's DieHard 500 is proof that there is more than one
way to run a NASCAR Winston Cup race shop. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin joined Earnhardt's crew in June in the celebrated switch
of crew chiefs that also sent Larry McReynolds ``down the hill'' at
Richard Childress Racing and over to Mike Skinner's team. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds was diplomatic about the demotion. But Larry Mac
didn't hide the fact that he and Earnhardt clashed over the
seven-time champion's reluctance to spend time at the shop during
the week. McReynolds also suggested that Earnhardt had gotten a
little too comfortable with what had gotten him here, that he was
reluctant to try new ideas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds couldn't deal with all of the above during a tenure
that produced Earnhardt's emotional first victory in the 1998
season-opening Daytona 500. That was Earnhardt's only victory in
the previous 100 races heading into the Talladega (Ala.)
Superspeedway, where ``The Intimidator'' led his first laps of 1999
and gave Hamlin a new profile. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When it (the switch) all came about, it was like, `This isn't
what I want to do, Richard,' '' Hamlin said. ``I liked the
low-profile thing being with Mike Skinner and starting a team from
nothing and working up. Hopefully, Mike and I would get our first
win together. That's how I always envisioned it, and I really
wanted it to happen.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skinner and Hamlin did win a NASCAR exhibition road race in
Japan in November 1997. But Sunday's restrictor-plate gem produced
Earnhardt's 72nd career victory and took the heat off the crew of
his No. 3 GM Goodwrench Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media, people in the grandstands, everybody wants us to be
able to say: `What's wrong?' And there's not anything wrong,''
Hamlin said. ``Dale has the same desire he's always had to drive
and win races. The team is just as strong and pumped up as its ever
been. The competition level is just so great that one minor thing
is a major setback.''
</P>
<P>
   And just for the record, how often does Dale Earnhardt actually
show up at RCR to lay hands on his race car?
</P>
<P>
   ``Dale comes to the shop maybe once a month, or more, if
needed,'' Hamlin said. ``To me, it's no big deal.''
QUICK HITS
IRL RACE GAINS BACKER
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom has signed on as ``presenting sponsor'' for the Pep
Boys Indy Racing League's night event at Texas Motor Speedway in
Fort Worth on June 12. Formerly known as the True Value 500K, the
event is now the Longhorn 500 Presented by MCI WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive year, the IRL will share billing with
NASCAR's Craftsman Truck Series. The Pronto Auto Parts 400K is
scheduled for the night of June 11. PACE CARS ON THE BLOCK
</P>
<P>
   Two Indianapolis 500 pace cars, a 1982 Chevrolet Camaro Z/28 and
1986 Corvette, are among the inventory being offered in the Leake
Car Collectors Auction during the ``Star-Telegram'' AutoFest
featuring the Pate Swap Meet at TMS this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Show hours are 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. today through Saturday, and 8
a.m. to 3 p.m. Sunday. Admission is $6 for adults. NHRA rumors
flying
</P>
<P>
   Rumors surrounding the make-up of the 2000 National Hot Rod
Association season were circulating during the Castrol Nationals at
the Texas Motorplex in Ennis last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The rumored changes are that Houston Raceway Park in Baytown
will lose its spring race after 12 years, leaving it with a fall
date; Route 66 Raceway near Chicago will be granted a second date;
and Bruton Smith's Las Vegas Motor Speedway will get its first
national event.
</P>
<P>
   Those changes would bump the schedule to 23 events, not
including the nonpoints Winston Showdown at Smith's revamped
Bristol (Tenn.) Dragway. LITTLE AL PLANS RETURN
</P>
<P>
   Al Unser Jr., who suffered a fractured right ankle in the CART
FedEx season opener March 21 at Homestead, Fla., is planning to
return for the Bosch Spark Plug Grand Prix in Nazareth, Pa., this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Unser Jr. ran 49 miles of testing at Gateway International
Raceway near St. Louis on Monday, a session cut short by rain. As
an oval that requires a minimum of shifting, Nazareth is not
expected to overly test Unser's ankle-strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to watch two races from the sidelines and I'd rather not
make it three,'' said Unser, driver of the Marlboro Penske
Mercedes. IRL tunes up for Indy
</P>
<P>
   Indy Racing League teams get their last tune-up before the
Indianapolis 500 at the VisionAire 500 at Lowe's Motor Speedway in
Concord, N.C., on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   LMS is a 1.5-mile trioval banked at 24-degrees, a layout that
bears little resemblance to Indy's flat, 2.5-mile rectangle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indy is such a creature of its own, as far as setup and how
quickly the track changes,'' IRL regular Scott Sharp said. ``I
don't think your setup at Charlotte will help at Indy. However,
it's really critical that our series is in front of the fans more
often. Hopefully, this'll show the fans we're only a few weeks from
Indy, and these are the guys who will be comprising the field.''
LAST WORDS
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny. Driving a car is like sex. Everybody thinks
they're good at it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jay Leno, after practicing in the Chevrolet Monte Carlo Indy
500 pace car he will drive on May 30 nn
</P>
</TEXT>
