<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-PARKER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH ITS RICH RESOURCES, CALL LAKE PARKER PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEE VINING, Calif. _ Parker Lake is full of surprises, as a pair
of intrepid fishermen discovered during a recent foul-weather
camping trip to the postcard-worthy backcountry site in the Eastern
Sierra.
</P>
<P>
   Surprising in how close _ just 2.2 miles _ it is for anglers who
don't mind hike-in fishing holes.
</P>
<P>
   Surprising in how mellow the climb _ just 400 feet of elevation
gain.
</P>
<P>
   Surprising in how early the thaw _ at 8,318 feet, the lake is
ice-free.
</P>
<P>
   Surprising in how few anglers target it _ most anglers
 &UR; !ital! &LR; do &UR; !off! &LR;  mind hike-in fishing holes.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, surprising in how big and tough are the brown
trout.
</P>
<P>
   ``One in there has got my pole,'' said Doug Wildason of Wildomar
in Riverside County.
</P>
<P>
   His hiking buddy, Jeff Christiansen of Van Nuys, chuckled at the
recollection.
</P>
<P>
   Wildason had caught and released a 3-pound brown on his first
cast of Saturday's trout-season opener after awaking to a snowy,
windswept morning. The anglers favored Power Bait and inflated
night crawlers, but little was hitting after the initial hook-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sitting there relaxing and watching our poles because
they were motionless for the longest time,'' Wildason said. ``We
didn't have any bites for a while, but when the second one hit,
whack, phshh, my pole just flew off. We saw the fish jump but it
was hard to tell what size it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Their tough-luck story would only get worse, but more on that
later.
</P>
<P>
   Parker Lake is indeed home to bruiser browns, with some
measuring to 20 inches or longer; smaller browns and brook trout
reside in the outlet stream, Parker Creek. While the lake is
favored by bait-and-hardware types, it also sees plenty of
fly-anglers who often work their way up the creek to its source
using a mix of dry flies and nymph patterns on 3- to 5-weight rods.
</P>
<P>
   I carried a fly rod and a bait pole Sunday but was luckless on
the creek and blown off the lake by an unrelenting wind that put a
serious chill on the sun-drenched outing.
</P>
<P>
   While Parker Lake Trail offers one of the Eastern Sierra's
earliest backcountry fishing opportunities, it appears it was a
little too soon for much fly-fishing success in the creek. The
water remained cold and most of its fish were content to laze
around in deeper holes or under fallen trees, their cold-blooded
metabolisms not permitting any pursuit of the flies presented to
them even if they had the urge.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing worked, from the size No. 16 attractor patterns _ namely
royal stimulators and Sierra bright dots _ to deceivers such as an
Adams, mosquito imitations and emerger nymphs. You could blame my
fishing prowess, but no so fast; three fly-anglers in my group were
skunked on the day. One colorful brook was taken on a worm just
below the lake. The lake was worse; flies were useless in the wind,
and the lures got no attention.
</P>
<P>
   But like the locals say about the weather in the Eastern Sierra,
change comes very quickly, and the fish will undoubtedly be more
receptive when the climate warms.
</P>
<P>
   Braving snow flurries and strong winds a day earlier, Wildason
and Christiansen got a glimpse of what Parker Lake is like when
it's on. They landed several nice browns and Wildason took a
bruiser that he said measured from the ground to just above his
knee. (For reference, that distance is 24 inches on my leg.)
</P>
<P>
   But disaster struck again. ``I had it on the stringer sitting
there underneath my pole holder, and I went to adjust my pole
holder and it went vrooo with my stringer,'' said Wildason, who had
a witness in Christiansen but left his camera at camp. ``It was the
nicest one I ever caught, and it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't wish his luck on anyone. At least the anglers count
themselves fortunate for finding such a secluded spot, one that
they have visited several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get away from the crowds, this is the only way to do it
now,'' Christiansen said of such hike-in spots as Parker Lake,
which sits in an impressive basin surrounded by precipitous walls
of granite. ``It's the best scenery of the lakes in the (June Lake)
Loop.''
</P>
<P>
   And, just as fortunately, most anglers, hikers and campers will
have an easy time with the mild grade on the 4.4-mile round-trip
into the Inyo National Forest and Ansel Adams Wilderness. Waders
are a great benefit, and packing in a float tube shouldn't be too
much trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I took my young children _ Dillon, 3, and a baby,
Rebecca, in the backpack _ and Dillon was able to walk all the way
to the lake,'' said Donna Bertolina of Mammoth Lakes, manager of
the Mammoth Lakes Visitor Center. ``In the fall it's really pretty
because the aspen trees have orange and yellow leaves. It's one of
the best times to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The region is steeped in cultural _ and controversial _ history.
</P>
<P>
   Parker Lake was named after some early settlers in the Mono
Basin.
</P>
<P>
   For eons Parker Creek fed Mono Lake via Rush Creek. But for
nearly a half-century, Parker Creek was disconnected from Rush
Creek and Mono Lake by the Los Angeles Department of Water and
Power; its waters were diverted to the Los Angeles Aqueduct from
1941 to 1990, when the great Mono Lake debate came to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   The fishing-conservation group CalTrout and the Mono Lake
Committee successfully sued the DWP to rewater the creek in an
attempt to re-establish its fisheries and replenish Mono Lake. (The
litigation impacted the lowest stretches of Parker Creek, well
downstream from the lake and the portion of the creek profiled
here.)
</P>
<P>
   Anglers report the fishery upstream is as healthy as ever. Just
keep a sharp eye on your fishing rod and stringer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
