<HEADER>
A7148 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS29-ALT     04-28 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS29-ALTLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE DECLINES TO SUPPORT KOSOVO AIR STRIKES
 &HT;    Eds: This is an alternative lede for papers wishing to emphasize
the vote on air strikes.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (i) international categories
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House, in a 213-213 vote Wednesday night,
declined to support the U.S.-led NATO air strikes now under way
against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise vote came on a measure identical to one the Senate
had broadly supported last month. Some Democrats expressed outrage,
while the Clinton administration said it would proceed with the
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote was the last of several Wednesday on U.S.
participation in the five-week-old conflict, which is aimed at
returning ethnic Albanians to the province of Kosovo under the
protection of an international peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   Before splitting on air strikes, the House voted to require
President Clinton to seek Congress's approval before sending ground
troops into combat against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But the House refused either to order Clinton to withdraw U.S.
forces from the Balkans or to formally declare war against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote on air strikes came just hours after Clinton had
appeared outside the White House to request congressional support
for the war effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stressed that the 19 NATO allies are speaking with a single
voice,'' Clinton said. ``America must continue to speak with a
single voice as well.''
</P>
<P>
   But the House deadlocked on the resolution offered by Rep. Sam
Gejdenson, D-Conn., despite a supporting vote from Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a gratuitous authorization,'' Rep. Doug Bereuter,
R-Neb., said in the debate leading up to the vote. ``Bombing for
peace is wrong and it's not working.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Hastert said, ``The speaker has been telling the
president all along that he needs to make his case to the American
people and to the Congress. This vote shows how he has to continue
to make that case.''
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman said later, ``The House today voted no
on going forward, no on going back and they tied on standing
still,'' said White House spokesman Jake Siewert. ``We will
continue to prosecute the air campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., called the House vote an ``appalling
lack of judgment and an appalling abandonment of the troops in the
field. It is a day which this House will profoundly regret.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's series of votes marked the first formal House
response to the Yugoslavia fighting. They came only after Rep. Tom
Campbell, R-Calif., had single-handedly forced the House leadership
to schedule a debate on the war using the provisions of the War
Powers Act of 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers first voted 249-180 to deny funding for ground
troops unless the president wins authorization from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The practical effect of the action on ground troops was
uncertain, since the Senate would have to pass a similar bill,
which could then be vetoed by the president.
</P>
<P>
   The House then rejected a measure to require Clinton to bring
home the U.S. forces involved in the NATO operation, 290-139. It
also trounced a proposal, with only two ``yes'' votes, to make a
formal declaration of war against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, the emotional daylong debate aired long simmering
disputes over the the U.S. role in the Balkans, the
administration's conduct of the war, and whether Congress has a
constitutional duty to play a role in the decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not even be in the Balkans,'' said House Armed
Services Chairman Floyd D. Spence, R-S.C. ``The national security
of the United States is not at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the mission countered that Americans had an
obligation to stop the assaults on ethnic Albanians by the forces
of Yugoslavia's President Slobodan Milosevic. ``The voices of
appeasement and isolationism are reverberating in these halls,''
said Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., who fled the Nazis during World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   The president had attempted to pre-empt the House action by
reassuring lawmakers in person and in a letter stating that he
would seek their consent before deciding to wage a ground war.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., told his colleagues
that it was unnecessary to pass a law requiring authorization to
expand the air assault into a land operation. ``The president said
he would not as a practical matter ask for an introduction of
ground troops without coming here and taking the time to ask us for
a vote,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That assurance was not enough for some members. Rep. Lindsey
Graham, R-S.C., one of the managers who conducted the impeachment
trial in the Senate against Clinton, told his colleagues: ``I do
not have the confidence'' that Clinton will seek a vote before
ordering troops into ground action, he said. ``Now's the time to
speak, more than less, sooner rather than later, before we get a
lot of people killed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
