<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SENATE GIVES BLESSING TO SCHOOL FUNDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas Senate put its stamp of approval
Wednesday on a $2.6 billion school funding proposal designed to
raise teacher pay and help schools pay off debt while also
promising local property tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill represents the single largest infusion of new money
into public education in Texas history,'' said Education Committee
Chairman Sen. Teel Bivins, the chief author of Senate Bill 4.
</P>
<P>
   One of its key features is a $700 million set-aside for a new
funding formula that would help school districts retire existing
debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``School facilities are the most persistent issue this
Legislature has failed to address in the last 50 years,'' Bivins
said.
</P>
<P>
   The spending plan, however, is so delicate that a compromise
that could easily evaporate in the upper chamber if substantial
changes are made by the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we run the risk of losing a majority vote'' if the
House makes many changes, said Bivins, R-Amarillo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had Republicans that were dying to vote against the bill,''
he added. ``They said, `Go ahead and make one more amendment, and
we're going to go off the reservation.' And (some) Democrats felt
the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Approved unanimously on a voice vote by the Senate, the measure
now goes to the House, where Rep. Paul Sadler, D-Henderson and
chairman of the Public Education Committee, was quick to criticize
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't do the things that I think we should do,''
Sadler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to do are some very specific programs that improve
student learning,'' Sadler added. ``And I think that's what the
public wants. And so, we're going to have to find a way to fund
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've not had a surplus in almost a decade. We have a chance
to do some things that would really benefit our kids and our
education system, and we should do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the Senate bill's shortcomings, he said, are its failure
to guarantee every teacher a pay raise, failure to provide programs
such as mandatory kindergarten and others aimed at keeping high
school freshmen from dropping out. Earlier this week he laid out
his school funding plan, a substantially costlier proposal that
addresses all those matters.
</P>
<P>
   Although Senate Bill 4 would raise the minimum teacher pay scale
$4,000 for each of 20 steps, only about half of Texas teachers
would benefit from that provision. That's because most Texas school
districts use local tax funds to pay teachers more than the state
minimum. Only those teachers in districts paying the minimum or
slightly more would see substantial pay increases.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to guarantee that all teachers who already earn
more than the state base pay also get a pay raise, the Senate plan
would require that school districts put at least 60 percent of
their new funding into teacher pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   That pass-through provision, however, would amount to as little
as $400 or $500 a year in some districts, according to Bivins
spokeswoman Cathy Teague.
</P>
<P>
   Annette Cootes, spokeswoman for the Texas State Teacher
Association, however, said TSTA fears the pass-through provision
would allow districts to use all the pass-through money to raise
salaries of just a few teachers. For example, she said, a district
that wanted to attract science and math teachers might be able to
use all the new salary money to increase pay only for teachers in
those subject areas.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the preliminary Sadler plan would guarantee every
teacher a $3,000 pay raise, regardless of experience.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 4 also would put about $1 billion into facilities
funding and other measures that Bivins insists amount to a property
tax cut. Another $125 million has already been set aside in the
state budget to help districts with declining property values.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler has criticized Bivins' portrayal of Senate Bill 4 as
providing $1 billion in tax relief as a sham, contending that the
only real tax relief comes from a $700 million program aimed at
helping school districts pay off existing debt to build school
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins said such criticisms amount to splitting hairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is under this bill, the property taxpayers will
have a billion more dollars in their pocket,'' he said. ``I call
that a tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the consternation in Wednesday's nearly three-hour
debate came from those who wanted to put more money into teacher
pay raises and less into property tax cuts. They argued that an
additional $100 million that was put into facilities funding plans
under an amendment came from money that originally had been
earmarked for teacher pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   Texas teacher salaries have lagged behind the national average,
and teacher groups have been calling for a $6,000 across-the-board
increase to get classroom teachers to that level.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Eliot Shapleigh, D-El Paso, lost in his bid to amend Senate
Bill 4 so that it would put more money toward teacher salaries and
less toward facilities and tax cuts, and he suggested that Gov.
George W. Bush's presidential ambitions were driving the tax-cut
measures.
</P>
<P>
   During his re-election campaign, Bush pledged to seek $2 billion
in property tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suggest to you the only thing that has happened ... has been
New Hampshire,'' Shapleigh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heart of this compromise is the delicately crafted money
allocation balance between kids and tax cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the average Texas teacher salary was $32,000, while
the national average in 1996-97 was $38,000, said John Cole,
president of the Texas Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still going to be way below the national average and
everyone should understand that,'' Cole said. ``Still, (Senate Bill
4) is a step in the right direction, and we hope we're going to get
a better deal'' in the Texas House.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
