<HEADER>
A7152 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXLEGIS-TAXES-TEACHE     04-28 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXLEGIS-TAXES-TEACHERS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teacher raises weighed against Texas tax cut
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A ``delicate balance'' between $1.7 billion in
teacher pay raises and $1 billion in property tax cuts cleared the
Senate on Wednesday, but the Republican sponsor warned that
significant House changes could topple the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Teel Bivins, who had to rewrite the proposal more than once
just to get it out of the Senate, said he believes that the bill
has been changed as much as possible. But Rep. Paul Sadler, Bivins'
counterpart in the House, said the bill still needs work, adding
that House lawmakers have yet to go to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, University of Texas government Professor Bruce
Buchanan said the compromise away from Gov. George W. Bush's call
for $2 billion in property tax cuts doesn't appear threatening to
the governor, who's likely to run for the Republican presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any kind of tax cut at all, it seems Bush is in a
position to defend himself. The amount of tax cuts only becomes
important if he sticks to his number too long,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday, Bush's office said the governor remained
committed to his $2 billion even though legislative leaders like
Bivins and the Senate's chief budget-writer, Sen. Bill Ratliff
(R-Mount Pleasant), have said there's not enough money or support
for $2 billion in property tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said Bush will reach a point where he has to let go of
his proposal ``when everybody on his side says it's hopeless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't perceive that moment has arrived,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler (D-Henderson) said the House is considering changes to
the bill that will have to be ironed out with the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been compromising with themselves,'' Sadler said of
Senate members. ``Hello, there's another chamber. I think there are
some things that we need to do to benefit education.''
</P>
<P>
   Bivins said Senate Bill 4, which cleared the Senate on a voice
vote, contains $1.7 billion in new money for teacher compensation
and $1 billion to cut local school property taxes. Sadler has said
he believes the tax cuts add up to less than $1 billion and has
proposed a plan that has about $500 million in property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The gap between Bivins and Sadler had Bivins and others talking
about a special session, another wrinkle that could test Bush's
leadership before his expected bid for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could very easily run into serious resistance on one side
or the other if ... the mix changed substantially,'' Bivins said.
``It's a pretty delicate balance we've got here. If it's attempted
to be pushed very far one way or the other we run the risk of
losing a majority vote. Special sessions are always possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said if the House and Senate come close to a deal, Bush
could benefit from a special session because it would allow him to
show leadership on the issue and allow him to walk away with tax
cuts and teacher pay raises, another item on his legislative
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   If the chambers remain far apart on the pay raise-tax cut
matter, Bush might be better served by blaming the failure on
lawmakers than by trying unsuccessfully to broker a deal during a
closely watched special session.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding a special session, Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said
only that the governor will continue to work with lawmakers to
improve education funding and pass teacher pay raises and property
tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of the legislative process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The session ends May 31.
</P>
<P>
   While important to Bush's future, the bill also impacts the rest
of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Linda McNabb, a spokeswoman for the Association of Texas
Professional Educators, said the group is happy that more money has
been put toward teacher compensation ``but we would still like to
see raises be across the board.'' She said teachers and
administrators in her group are willing to pass up property tax
cuts in order to get pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   As it passed the Senate, the bill would guarantee at least
$4,000 pay raises for teachers paid the minimum allowed for their
experience level. That, however, covers less than half of the
state's 260,000 teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The bill requires all school districts to give 60 percent of new
money to teachers, so all of them will get some kind of raise, but
it won't be equal and could be very little for teachers in
districts that get very little state money.
</P>
<P>
   Property taxpayers also would get various levels of tax cuts
under the bill based in part on the amount of debt their districts
have related to school buildings. Much of the tax cutting efforts
in the bill are in programs to help pay for school buildings,
meaning that local taxes collected for that purpose can be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a perfect bill,'' Bivins said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
