 JACKSON PANEL BEGINS MISSION TO FREE 3 GIs  
(af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson and a dozen religious
leaders left Wednesday night for Belgrade to seek the release of
three American soldiers held captive by President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are convinced that our going will open up lines of
communication, and in the end we may be able to talk it out and not
just fight it out,'' Jackson said Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said they did not approve of
the trip and told Jackson that he did not have the authority to
negotiate on behalf of the administration and could not guarantee
his safety.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has stressed that the NATO conditions for a
cease-fire are not negotiable. Officials also said they were
concerned that Milosevic would exploit Jackson for propaganda
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always run the risk when Milosevic hears from multiple
voices, that the message is not clear,'' Joe Lockhart, President
Clinton's spokesman, said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel R. Berger,
met with Jackson and others for 45 minutes Wednesday afternoon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said after the meeting, ``Berger made it clear that if
he had his druthers, he'd rather we didn't go because it's
dangerous and he doesn't want Milosevic to get mixed messages.''
</P>
<P>
   The delegation was to include the Rev. Joan Campbell,
general-secretary of the National Council of Churches, the Rev.
Leonid Kishkovsky of the Orthodox Church in America, a Russian
Orthodox priest from New York, and Rabbi Steven B. Jacobs of Los
Angeles, a Reform rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   It also included Rep. Rod Blagojevich, D-Ill., and Landrum
Bolling, senior adviser of Conflict Management Group in Cambridge,
Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
