<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHROEDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAT SCHROEDER: OUT OF THE HOUSE, BUT STILL FOCUSED ON THE FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JANE GROSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Consider the following tableaux, circa 1956.
</P>
<P>
   It is Sunday night in suburbia, and Mom, Dad and the kids are
together around the TV. They are watching Ed Sullivan and the
featured guest is Elvis Presley. An intergenerational
misunderstanding ensues. In our day we had real music, says Mom. In
our day, we didn't wear tight jeans, says Dad. The kids roll their
eyes. Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Pat Schroeder, D-Colo., who fled what she called the
``food fight'' in Congress in 1996 and now runs the Association of
American Publishers, paints this picture, as dated as a Norman
Rockwell cover, as she sips coffee behind the New York Public
Library, under a canopy of budding green.
</P>
<P>
   She is musing on the recent school massacre in Colorado, asking
what had changed in the last 40-odd years to turn children of
upper-middle-class suburbia into mass murderers. ``How did we get
here?'' she asks. ``Times are good. What is the problem?''
</P>
<P>
   She answers her own question, at least in part, by imagining
today's upscale family. Mom and Dad are in the master suite of a
capacious home, with a movie on the VCR. The kids are in their
rooms, each with its own computer and TV. One is playing video
games. One watches MTV. Another surfs the Internet. Nobody is
arguing. Nobody is talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beautiful family of America living the American
dream,'' Ms. Schroeder says. ``But we need some ways to relate to
each other as human beings. We need to work on getting connected.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schroeder, 58, master of the irreverent sound bite, hems and
haws uncharacteristically. She has just finished a glib lecture to
library donors, who enjoyed all her old chestnuts, like the one
about having both a brain and a uterus.
</P>
<P>
   But afterward, Ms. Schroeder returns to the nagging questions of
Columbine High School in a suburban Denver district adjacent to the
one she represented for 24 years. She observes that technology can
be divisive, segregating adults and teen-agers as rock music and
drugs once did. And for misfit teen-agers the technology can be
dangerous, if they seek community in chat rooms where people sow
hatred.
</P>
<P>
   ``They no longer feel so isolated,'' she says. ``But they still
aren't looking anybody in the eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology has also changed our expectations of war, Ms.
Schroeder says, as she watches the conflict in the Balkans from the
sidelines, rather than from her seat on the House Armed Services
Committee. ``How accepting we've become with these 10,000-foot
aerial views,'' she says. ``Since the Gulf War, we've approached
this as a video game.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she balks at being viewed as a Luddite, despite fumbling
for change to make a telephone call while others at the cafe use
Startacs. After all, the trade association has recently pushed a
treaty through Congress that protects intellectual property in the
era of electronic publishing.
</P>
<P>
   But megabytes of information on the Internet are no substitute
for books. ``Knowledge is not wisdom,'' she says. Thus, her current
project is an advertising campaign encouraging 18- to 34-year-olds
to read. In this vein, she is a great fan of Oprah Winfrey's book
clubs and the coffee bars in Barnes &AMP; Noble.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are among the few civil institutions left,'' she says,
``Places to go to see other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schroeder's biography is a template for its time. She was a
gangly tomboy, a standout student at the University of Minnesota
and one of 15 women in a class of more than 500 at the Harvard Law
School. It was her husband, Jim, a devotee of Adlai Stevenson, who
pushed her into politics in 1972, the year of the Nixon landslide.
Like Stevenson, she expected to talk sense and lose. Instead, in an
upset worthy of Frank Capra, Ms. Schroeder, with two children in
tow, went to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   There she met with cruelty and condescension, and also great
success. Her legislative resume was heavy on family-friendly issues
long before they were trendy, like the Family and Medical Leave
Act, research on women's health and improved benefits for soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   She quit Congress in exasperation during the reign of Newt
Gingrich, in time to miss the impeachment shambles, and spent a
year teaching at Princeton University. Then she wrote a memoir.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Schroeder retired she said she was ``looking forward to
reading books, not bills.'' Still, running a staid association
seems an unexpected encore for a firebrand.
</P>
<P>
   She explains the move by saying that literacy and the First
Amendment are ``issues that have sung for me forever.'' She also
says she hated the commute from Princeton to Washington, where her
husband practices law. Plus, with offices in Washington and New
York City, the job allows her to visit her 32-year-old son, who
works at American Express, without ``hovering.'' She dodges a
question about other offers.
</P>
<P>
   The slower pace is timely, because Ms. Schroeder's parents, both
85, are ailing, her father with lung cancer and her mother with
Alzheimer's disease. Her brother lives with them in Florida, and
she visits each weekend.
</P>
<P>
   She describes her time there _ paying bills, buying groceries
and persuading her father he is too old to drive _ as ``a Salvador
Dali painting.'' This weekend, her 28-year-old daughter, a doctoral
student in England, will fly in to take her mother's place while
she attends a conference. It sounds like Ms. Schroeder's
congressional agenda incarnate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to reality,'' she says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
