<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-CALDERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT PAPERS CLAIM MICROSOFT PLOTTED AGAINST NOVELL  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah)  (See also MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST, MICROSOFT-DOCUMENTS) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To break the spirit of Novell Corp., its Utah-based archrival in
the network software market, Microsoft Corp. in 1994 considered a
recommendation that it lock up sales accounts at both the Church of
Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints and Brigham Young University,
documents filed Wednesday in federal court contend.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail message to Microsoft's chairman, Bill Gates, Mike
Murray, a high-ranking Microsoft executive, wrote that at a retreat
for company executives he had proposed that while the accounts were
not Novell's largest, they were important psychologically and
emotionally. ``The influence of the LDS church in the Utah economy
and culture is difficult to appreciate from a distance,'' Murray
wrote. ``I recommend we throw some significant weight at this
account.''
</P>
<P>
   The message was part of 188 pages of evidence filed in federal
court in Salt Lake City by Caldera, a software company that is
suing Microsoft for as much as $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail message added: ``In addition, it would be great for
Billg to make time for a trip to Salt Lake City to meet with church
leaders. It may be possible to leverage your mother's membership on
the KIRO board.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Mrs. Gates, who has since died, was on the board of
KIRO, a Seattle TV station owned by a church subsidiary, Bonneville
Communications. In the end, Gates never visited Salt Lake City for
this purpose and his mother never intervened, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Caldera contends that Microsoft set out to destroy public demand
for DR-DOS, an operating system that competed against Microsoft's
MS-DOS. Caldera was formed by Novell's former chairman, Ray Noorda,
who filed the lawsuit in July 1996 after acquiring DR-DOS.
</P>
<P>
   Caldera contends that Microsoft integrated MS-DOS with its
Windows graphical user interface in part to damage its competitors.
Microsoft's own filings contend that DR-DOS was a flawed product
and that its customers were provided with inadequate technical
support.
</P>
<P>
   The filings are aimed at defining the scope of claims that will
be allowed at a trial now scheduled to begin next January. Until
now, Microsoft has been successful at keeping much of the pretrial
evidence sealed under a broad court order.
</P>
<P>
   Caldera executives said they believe the evidence drawn from
more than 1.5 million pages of documents filed in the case
demonstrates that Microsoft used misleading product announcements
to dampen DR-DOS sales and that it made false and misleading
statements about DR-DOS to sow what Caldera called FUD _ for fear,
uncertainty and doubt _ in the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   Caldera also said the evidence showed that Microsoft developed
intentional incompatibilities to make it appear to be difficult for
DR-DOS to work with Windows and that it used ``per-processor'' and
other exclusionary licensing terms to block DR-DOS in the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't just random e-mails,'' said Bryan Sparks, chief
executive of Caldera. ``We think this material is significant, and
much of this has never been seen before because it's been under
protective order.''
</P>
<P>
   But a Microsoft spokesman said all accusations raised by the
company had previously been reviewed and rejected by the Justice
Department. ``This is an attempt by Caldera to rewrite the history
of the high-tech industry by pasting together these handpicked
excerpts,'' said Mark Murray, a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in many cases the Caldera document took the e-mail
comments of Microsoft executives out of context. For example, one
excerpt from an e-mail sent by James Allchin, the Microsoft
executive who now heads the company's Windows 2000 effort, states:
``If you're going to kill someone there isn't much reason to get
all worked up about it and angry _ you just pull the trigger. Any
discussions beforehand are a waste of time. We need to smile at
Novell while we pull the trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   But taken in context, Murray said, Allchin was writing an appeal
to instruct Microsoft executives to stop ``trash talking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was saying we should just compete in a way that is more
professional,'' he said. ``He was saying this is hurting us with
the customer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Caldera document asserts Microsoft integrated MS-DOS and
Windows in an effort to damage competitors' operating systems. The
document quotes Nathan Mhyrvold, Microsoft's chief technology
officer, as arguing for integrating the two products for a
strategic reason: ``We put a bullet in the head of our would-be
competitors on DOS, like DRI, Desqview, DOS extenders etc.'' DRI
was Digital Research Inc., the company that developed DR-DOS.
</P>
<P>
   The Caldera accusation is not supported by history, Murray said:
``This is them excerpting a small snippet of a memo and trying to
create a narrative that does not reflect the facts of the
situation. Even the Department of Justice has acknowledged that
Windows 95 is a completely new operating system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
