<HEADLINE>
ANY IMPROVEMENT BY VICAR SEEN AS PLUS
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Carl Nafzger has been commenting this week
that he expects Vicar, the 3-year-old he trains, to improve by five
lengths in Saturday's Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas has set his sights lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd settle for five inches,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, chosen Tuesday for induction into the National Racing
Hall of Fame, saddles Cat Thief and Charismatic in search of his
fourth Derby victory. Only two other trainers _ Dick Thompson and
Ben Jones _ have won that many.
</P>
<P>
   Cat Thief has frustrated Lukas with his penchant for near-wins.
</P>
<P>
   He lost the Fountain of Youth in February by a neck, and was
beaten only a half-length in the Florida Derby, both times by
Vicar. And in the Blue Grass Stakes three weeks ago, he finished 1
1/4 lengths behind Menifee.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas blamed some of Cat Thief's reluctance to win on an
obstinate personality inherited from close ancestors Alydar and
Storm Cat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a double dose of stupid,'' Lukas said. Valhol trainer
eating again Now that Valhol is safely in the field courtesy of an
Arkansas judge's decree, trainer Dallas Keen can enjoy his meals
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This hasn't been much fun,'' the Cameron native said
Wednesday. ``Food wasn't even tasting good. Maybe now I can put
some of this weight back on that I've lost the last two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Valhol will be the third Derby mount for jockey Willie Martinez,
who replaces embattled Billy Patin, accused of carrying an
electrical device in the gelding's surprise April 10 Arkansas Derby
victory. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Lemon Drop Kid was the lone Derby entrant to record an
official workout Wednesday. He went a half-mile in 48 1-5 seconds
under jockey Jose Santos.
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``dosage index'' is claimed by proponents to
mathematically calculate a 3-year-old's chances to win the Derby
based on pedigree, but Real Quiet foiled the system last year. Four
of this year's entrants are dosage non-qualifiers: Menifee,
Charismatic, First American and Worldly Manner.
</P>
<P>
   _ Getting knocked out of the Derby lineup by Excellent Meeting
is all part of the game, says Etbauer's owner, Hays Biggs of
Springdale, Ark. But Biggs was less philosophical about the judge's
ruling Tuesday that allowed Valhol into the Derby field, which also
contributed to Etbauer's exclusion. ``I'm not the least bit happy
with that business,'' Biggs said. ``But I don't want to comment
further.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
