NYT-04-28-99 2217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0461 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7164 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-DERBY-TEX     04-28 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT'S DERBY CHANCES BOOSTED BY FILLY'S ENTRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Bob Baffert spent much of Tuesday morning
biting his tongue and explaining why he probably wouldn't be
running Excellent Meeting in the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, he happily explained why he probably will.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert finally talked the owners of the filly into taking a
shot at Saturday's legendary race at Churchill Downs. He also has
two other entrants in the capacity 20-horse field, as he bids to
become the first trainer to win the Derby three consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This filly is doing great,'' Baffert said, ``and she's earned
her way into the Derby. She's good enough to win. Her last works
have been outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't run her in the Derby if I didn't think she had a
chance to win. She deserves the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting, to be ridden by Kent Desormeaux, will be part
of a betting entry with Santa Anita Derby winner General Challenge
and jockey Gary Stevens. Both horses are owned by John and Betty
Mabee of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert's third horse will be Prime Timber, ridden by David
Flores.
</P>
<P>
   The entry of filly Excellent Meeting and gelding General
Challenge was established as the 3-to-1 program favorite, even
though only three fillies have won the Derby in its 124-year
history, and geldings are 0-for-72 since 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Timber is the second favorite at 7-to-2.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive year, the televised Kentucky Derby
draw was conducted under a format in which owners and trainers of
the horses chose their own post positions in an order determined at
random. Unlike the first time, when a redraw was necessary,
Wednesday's procedure went without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting will start from post No. 6. Prime Timber has
No. 14 and General Challenge breaks from No. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Among Derby qualifiers, the extreme outside post positions went
to Lemon Drop Kid (No. 20) and Menifee (No. 19). But though they
are clearly disadvantaged, all hope is not lost for them. Clyde Van
Dusen, also the last gelding to win the Derby, scored from post 20
in 1929. And in the most recent 20-horse lineup, the 1984 Derby's
first four finishers started from posts 15, 19, 14 and 20.
</P>
<P>
   Valhol, the Arkansas Derby winner who made it into the race on a
judge's order, is one of four horses grouped in the mutuel field.
Other field horses are K One King, Ecton Park, Kimberlite Pipe and
Lemon Drop Kid.
</P>
<P>
   Making his first Churchill Downs appearance this week was Sheik
Mohammed al Maktoum of Dubai, who picked post No. 5 for Aljabr and
No. 12 for Wordly Manner.
</P>
<P>
   Another filly in the race is Three Ring from post No. 2. The
last time two fillies started in the same year was also 1984, when
the D. Wayne Lukas-trained duo of Life's Magic and Althea ran
eighth and 19th.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest losers in the entry process were Etbauer and Torrid
Sand, excluded from the field because of a lack of earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Etbauer was on the bubble until Wednesday morning's decision to
enter Excellent Meeting knocked him out of the race, which is
limited to the top 20 earners, according to track rules. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
