<SLUG> BC-LILCO-SEVERANCE-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLIONS IN LILCO SEVERANCE CANNOT BE CLAIMED BY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. _ The state attorney general's office has
determined that it is legally impossible to get back any of the $67
million in severance pay given last year to Dr. William J.
Catacosinos and 25 other top officials of Long Island Lighting Co.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Eliot L. Spitzer said Wednesday that although a
nearly yearlong investigation into the breakup of Lilco found that
Catacosinos had engaged in a ``pattern of deception'' in the size
of the severance package and under what circumstances it would be
paid, the severance agreement included ironclad protection against
any liability.
</P>
<P>
   And since the money for Catacosinos' severance pay did not come
out of the pockets of Lilco ratepayers, Spitzer said he decided to
conclude his investigation without taking any further action.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't just a golden parachute given to Catacosinos, but
a parachute encrusted with rubies and diamonds and pearls,'' said
Spitzer on releasing the results of the investigation, which was
initiated by his predecessor, Dennis C. Vacco.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I would love to go after Catacosinos, it wouldn't
do us any good because, unfortunately, he was not only greedy, but
smart,'' Spitzer said. The results of the investigation were first
reported in Wednesday's Newsday.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said the investigation determined that Catacosinos, the
former chief executive officer of Lilco, was protected by corporate
indemnification agreements and releases that kept him free from any
cost, liability or legal expense relating to his conduct as an
officer or director of Lilco when Lilco was partly taken over in
May 1998 by the Long Island Power Authority, a specially formed
state public benefit corporation.
</P>
<P>
   The state issued $2.5 billion in municipal bonds to complete the
transaction. Lilco's electrical generating and gas distribution
systems were merged with Brooklyn Union Gas in a company now called
Keyspan.
</P>
<P>
   Days after Lilco was disbanded, it was revealed that the company
had awarded its top executives severance packages totaling more
than $67 million, including $42 million to Catacosinos. The
payments were made even though Catacosinos and his fellow officers
were assured of similar positions with the new corporation.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 lawsuits were filed by former Lilco and Brooklyn
Union Gas shareholders protesting the severance payments. The
results of the attorney general's investigation were released
Wednesday at a hearing in state supreme court here, in support of a
proposed settlement that would pay shareholders $7.9 million to
resolve the suits.
</P>
<P>
   Franck Schellace, law secretary to Justice Ute Wolff Lally, said
the agreement had been worked out during the last several months,
including an agreement by Keyspan to pay $1.5 million to the state
attorney general's office. Spitzer said the money would be used to
cover the costs of the investigation by his office as well as
future programs for investor protection and education.
</P>
<P>
   Keyspan reimbursed the attorney general's office because, under
the merger agreement, it assumed all responsibility for legal fees
related to Catacosinos' employment.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Oestreich, the lead attorney for the class-action
plaintiffs, said the attorney general's report, in effect, ``put
the state's blessing on the settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary approval of the settlement was granted by Justice
Lally. She ordered that all former shareholders be notified of the
settlement, and set June 30 as the date for a hearing on final
approval. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Spitzer said the investigation concluded that Lilco's officers
and directors had failed to make full or timely disclosures to its
shareholders about the severance packages. He said the disclosures
were incomplete and obscure, and conflicted, in part, with the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Lilco's officers not only withheld information from
its board, but also that the board then failed to ask appropriate
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said Catacosinos ``intentionally concealed facts about
the packages'' from Lilco's board and Lilco's partners during the
state takeover transaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, Catacosinos and his cronies in Lilco had Long
Island residents paying the highest electric rates in the
country,'' Spitzer said. ``Then to add insult to injury, they had
the gall to rip off their shareholders for tens of millions of
dollars for all of their supposed `hard work.' About the only good
news to come from this sorry, sordid affair is that Lilco's
customers did not pay for this outrageous giveaway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
