<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENTUCKY DERBY UNDER CLOUD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ A minor scandal erupted Wednesday when the
local newspaper revealed that one of the entrants in this week's
race is diesel-powered.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the race is only the Kentucky Derby Festival's
Great Steamboat Race up the Mississippi River. And the entrant in
question is the Spirit of Jefferson, whose paddle wheel turns out
to be merely ornamental.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the Kentucky Derby itself is mixed up in scandal,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Normally you come to Churchill Downs in the spring to forget
about the seamy side of horse racing. To forget that a shot at big
money and instant glory can make people do stupid things with
syringes and miniature cattle prods. To forget there are cheap
little tracks where a horseman stands to rake in more money by
losing at an opportune time than by winning. To forget the image of
racing, burned into TV viewers' subconscious by a dozen detective
shows in the '70s and '80s, as a world full of drawling con men in
beat-up cowboy hats. To forget that the sport is founded on animal
exploitation _ however benignly intentioned _ and on gambling.
</P>
<P>
   To forget about shady affairs like the Arkansas Derby, won three
weeks ago by the upstart Valhol, whose jockey Billy Patin stands
accused of carrying an illegal electrical stimulating device in the
race.
</P>
<P>
   The Kentucky Derby is supposed to be above all that, to show
thoroughbred racing in its most delicate light.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, this week it's impossible to ignore the
not-at-all-grainy videotape that seems to show Patin dropping a
small object from his left hand in the precise area beyond the
Oaklawn Park finish line where a track employee later found a
buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible not to read about Valhol's owner having to go to
court to pry the $300,000 winner's purse away from the Arkansas
racing commission (which wanted to hold it pending an
investigation) and thus qualify for the Kentucky Derby field.
</P>
<P>
   And it's impossible not to wonder if something like this could
happen in Saturday's Kentucky Derby itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing isn't the greatest if you're Churchill Downs and
you're trying to promote the Derby,'' said Keith Chamblin, the
Hollywood Park marketing vice president who is moving into a
similar job with the National Thoroughbred Racing Association.
</P>
<P>
   Valhol's trainer, Dallas Keen, who will surely face official
questions about his own innocence in the matter, is reflective
enough to know ``it doesn't look good for racing.''
</P>
<P>
   But how bad does it have to look?
</P>
<P>
   The counterintuitive theory is that the Valhol incident and its
fallout could be a boon to racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody thinks it (that racetrack cheating is common),
then it's probably best if it comes out to a head and is dealt with
strictly,'' said jockey Kent Desormeaux, who rode 1998 Kentucky
Derby winner Real Quiet and was aboard Arkansas Derby runner-up
Certain.
</P>
<P>
   That is: If the guilty are punished appropriately, the sport
will show the skeptics that it demands integrity and fair play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can take a real negative incident into a positive
for horse racing ... if it's handled correctly,'' Chamblin said.
``People who know a little about our sport know how highly
regulated it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kentucky Derby itself will be run under the watchful eyes of
more than a dozen ABC-TV and racetrack patrol cameras, not to
mention state officials with binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a horse in this race could have a fly land on
him without somebody noticing,'' said NTRA spokesman Chip Tuttle.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble in the Arkansas situation is that it has not been
handled correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Oaklawn Park management went public with its request for a state
investigation before informing even Valhol's owner of the
suspicion. The track appeared spiteful, as if it was out to get the
people who had the audacity to win its biggest race with a maiden
gelding. The state commission ordered the purse withheld. In doing
so, it violated due process and its own regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they handled it lousy. That's a flat way of saying
it,'' said Carl Nafzger, trainer of Derby contender Vicar.
</P>
<P>
   And by allowing the first hearings to be delayed until four days
after the Kentucky Derby, the Arkansas commission leaves bettors to
wonder just what to make of Valhol's 30-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's a true race,'' Desormeaux said provocatively, ``this
horse will gallop (to victory) in the Kentucky Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Racing's spin controllers wish their sport weren't held to
different standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the captain of the Atlanta Falcons gets picked up for
soliciting a prostitute the night before the Super Bowl, nobody
says, `The Super Bowl is ruined,' '' Tuttle said.
</P>
<P>
   But they might say it if one of the teams was suspected of
cheating to win its conference-championship game. And if football
explicitly invited fans to bet on the game and expect an honest
result.
</P>
<P>
   When the Great Steamboat Race is touched by scandal, you laugh
and go on. When it's the Kentucky Derby, you can't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
