u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SHOOTING-CANADA-     04-28 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SHOOTING-CANADA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE DEAD, ONE WOUNDED IN CANADIAN SCHOOL SHOOTING; BOY, 14, IS
HELD
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 14-year-old boy shot two students, killing one, at a Canadian
high school Wednesday, the police said. It was the most serious of
a rash of incidents since the Littleton, Colo., massacre last week
in which young people have been charged with stockpiling weapons or
preparing to use them at their schools.
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn Wednesday, five boys were charged with conspiracy in
connection with compiling a list of victims to be killed during an
attack timed for the school's June 26 commencement.
</P>
<P>
   In Taber, Alberta, a town of about 8,000 about an hour's drive
north of Montana, the police took a 14-year-old boy into custody
after he shot two 11th-graders during lunchtime at the W.R. Myers
High School, The Canadian Broadcasting Corporation reported. The
CBC reported that some students said the gunman was a former
student who wore a blue trench coat Wednesday and carried a
.22-caliber rifle. The suspect's name was not released.
</P>
<P>
   The two suspects in the Littleton shooting were reportedly
members of a group called the ``trench coat mafia.''
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn, five male students, all 13, were arrested at
McKinley Junior High School after school when a student overheard
them discussing a bomb assault on the school, a New York police
spokesman said. A search of their bodies turned up instructions on
how to make bombs, as well as a list of people to be killed. The
teen-agers were charged with conspiracy. Their names were not
released because they are minors. A search of the school found no
bombs.
 &UR;  &LR;  In Oak Lawn, Ill., a suburb of Chicago, a 15-year-old boy was
arrested and charged Wednesday with assault and disorderly conduct
after an ax, knives, a rifle, shotguns, and 150 rounds of
ammunition were reportedly found in his home. A fellow student at
South Side Baptist Church School reported overhearing the suspect,
who had been suspended, making a threat to blow up the school.
</P>
<P>
   In the Central Valley of California, several schools received
threats. In Coalinga, a student was arrested for reportedly
threatening to burn down the middle school and another student for
allegedly threatening to blow up the high school. They were booked
on charges of making terrorist threats. And in Clovis, Calif., a
boy was arrested Wednesday for threatening a teacher at Alta Sierra
High School.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's arrests and threats follow a wave of similar
incidents in recent days that have struck around the country after
the Littleton shootings. For example, in Chicago a 15-year-old boy
was caught with a .22-caliber gun taped to his ankle, prompting
public demands to install metal detectors in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania officials reported at least 52 bomb scares and
other threats at schools in 22 counties. Near Philadelphia, a
16-year-old was reportedly turned in by his mother after he
threatened her with a reference to the Littleton tragedy. Law
enforcement officials later discovered a homemade videotape showing
the teen-ager building what appeared to be a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, about 12,600 high school students were evacuated
and missed at least part of the day's classes on Monday after an
unidentified caller said a bomb had been placed in one of the
city's 13 public high schools. There was a second wave of threats
on Tuesday but officials let each school decide whether to suspend
classes.
</P>
<P>
   In Longwood, in central Florida, a 13-year-old Rock Lake Middle
School student was arrested on Tuesday after officials said he
threatened to place a bomb at the school and kill eighth-graders
who had picked on him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
