<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUBURN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tuberville touts tough stance at Auburn helm
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Ala. _ Auburn's football players knew things were going
to be different in January when it came time for voluntary
offseason workouts.
</P>
<P>
   The first big change? The workouts weren't voluntary anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're motivated to do a lot of things when you're the age of
our players,'' new coach Tommy Tuberville said. ``Working out in
January ain't one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of sleeping in before the first class on those cold,
frosty mornings, the Tigers were enjoying sunrise services with
Kevin Yoxall, the new strength and conditioning coach. This guy,
the players said, could wilt a Marine drill instructor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three times a week at 6 o'clock in the morning,'' quarterback
Gabe Gross said. ``He would run us until we couldn't run any more.
And then we would.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I've never been through anything like it,'' offensive
guard Kendall Simmons said. ``There were guys on this team I
thought could run forever, and they are sucking wind. It was
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuberville, the former head coach at Mississippi, took over the
Auburn program Nov. 29. By the end of spring practice April 24 he
had put his stamp on it by significantly increasing the level of
physical conditioning and discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Go to class. You miss class and you earn an extra session with
Yoxall's Dawn Patrol. Be on time. Don't think you can be on time?
Try running the steps of Jordan-Hare Stadium in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Tuberville made it clear from day 1 who was in charge
and how it was going to be,'' Gross said. ``I saw guys look around
and say, `Man, this guy is serious!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to let them know exactly what our philosophy
was and get them all in the same boat,'' Tuberville said.
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly what happened.
</P>
<P>
   In the waning days of former coach Terry Bowden, Auburn was a
divided football team. The defense, which was pretty good, stayed
mad at the offense, which wasn't. The coaches of the respective
units weren't real chummy, either, and the animosity spread to the
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there was a lot of bickering going on,'' Simmons said.
``The defense was playing their game, and the offense was doing the
same. It was really frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a tough year to be an Auburn Tiger with the departure
of Bowden during the middle of last season, then Auburn's decision
to buy its way out of the opening game with Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   But Camp Tuberville has served the dual purpose of unifying the
players and getting them in excellent shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly what this football team needed,'' offensive
tackle Jeno James said. ``These guys have been through so much
negative stuff, and a lot of it didn't have anything to do with us.
We needed something to bring us together.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are better in the Auburn football family, but they are
far from perfect. Two players, running back Demontray Carter and
wide receiver Reggie Worthy, have been charged with misdemeanor
harassment of a female student. That followed a charge of
second-degree rape against wide receiver Clifton Robinson and the
arrest last spring of former wide receiver Robert Baker, who was
charged with cocaine trafficking. No decision has been made on
Carter, Worthy or Robinson. Baker has returned to school but is not
on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn will need all the unity it can get if the Tigers hope to
compete in the SEC West. The defense will be pretty good, with
eight returning starters led by end Leonardo Carson and tackle
Jimmy Brumbaugh.
</P>
<P>
   The offense still has serious problems. The unit struggled this
spring with Tuberville's new system. It has no real playmakers, and
only one guy who caught a pass last season, running back Markeith
Cooper, returns.
</P>
<P>
   To win, Auburn will have to rely on its defense and kicker Rob
Bironas, who will be busy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a long way to go before we're a good football team.
There's no doubt about that,'' Tuberville said. ``But when you try
to do what we've done, you've got to crawl before you can walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we wanted to do this spring was get our guys to
buy into what we're doing and believe in it. I think we did that.''
</P>
<P>
   The next step? Work 'em like crazy this summer and hit the
ground running Aug. 16, when the Tigers have their first practice
for the Sept. 4 opener with Appalachian State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some people don't think we'll be that good, but we're
going to fool them,'' Gross said. ``This team is hungry again, and
it wants to win. We've worked too hard for it not to pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
