<HEADLINE>
SKINNER NOT GETTING MUCH SHUT-EYE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the Los Angeles Clippers made Brian Skinner
the 22nd selection in the 1998 NBA Draft, a few talent sharpies
believed the 6-foot-9, 255-pound Baylor forward could be a
``sleeper'' pick.
</P>
<P>
   Nah. Well, not lately.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Skinner's wife, Rebecca, gave birth to seven-pound,
eight-ounce Avery Anne Alexes Skinner. Dad celebrated by scoring
nine points and grabbing seven rebounds in 19 minutes during the
Clips' near-miss comeback against San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   But Skinner, who said he'd slept a combined 10 hours over the
previous three nights, still isn't getting much shut-eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me? No, but they (mother and daughter) are asleep a lot,''
said Skinner, who didn't exactly need a wake-up call for his best
on-court performance of the season.
</P>
<P>
   His show of strength against San Antonio was good news for the
Clippers. Skinner's emergence could provide insurance for power
forward Maurice Taylor and center Michael Olowokandi in the event
that current low-post handyman Lorenzen Wright - who'll be a free
agent when the season ends - leaves for greener pastures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to contribute like I did,'' Skinner said. ``I think
I've learned a lot this year. I've learned what to do and not to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's learned there's no substitute for practical experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this league, you have to be on the court to really learn
how to play,'' he said. ``You have to play and figure out what to
do for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   As a first-round pick with two more years on his Clippers
contract, Skinner could figure prominently in their future.
</P>
<P>
   `Captain' comeback: Point guard Sherman Douglas, whose sprained
left ankle kept him in street clothes during the loss to San
Antonio, is listed as ``day to day'' for tonight's game at
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to play,'' Douglas said while making a quick,
sure-footed getaway from the Sports Arena after Wednesday's
workout.
</P>
<P>
   Filling in for Douglas, who turned the ankle in last Saturday's
victory over Vancouver, is Troy Hudson. Hudson played all 48
minutes in Monday's loss to the Spurs.
</P>
</TEXT>
