<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lopez not throwing away blame
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After leading all National League starting catchers
last season at throwing out potential base stealers, Javy Lopez
found himself in a strange routine Wednesday. He was on the field
long before the rest of the Braves, working on his throws down to
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we lost the game (Tuesday night), bad throws by
me,'' he said. ``Believe me, that was the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   After throwing out a career-high 33.8 percent of attempted
steals in 1998, Lopez has stopped just four of 16 thefts thus far,
a drop-off the coaching staff attributes to an old habit. Lopez has
habitually flipped the ball from his mitt to his right hand before
throwing, but when the transfer reaches six inches or more, the
margin for error is negligible.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always flipped it but there are degrees to flipping,''
said third-base coach Ned Yost, who worked with both Lopez and
Eddie Perez for 15 minutes. ``Sometimes he'll want to flip it from
here (holding his hands six inches apart). Whenever you do that,
everything's got to go perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez allowed Mike Benjamin to steal second in the eighth inning
Tuesday, just one of the elements to Pittsburgh's three-run burst
that decided the game. Always possessing above-average arm
strength, Lopez made his defensive strides last season with
improved technique. Wednesday was a refresher course.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year,'' he said, ``they're stealing my underwear.''
</P>
<P>
   Home is where the bat is
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most impressive about Brian Jordan's fast start with the
Braves is that April has traditionally been a poor month for him.
Over the last five years, he has hit .289 in the first month, his
lowest of the season, with a total of eight homers in 298 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   He entered Wednesday's play with six homers in his first 75
Atlanta at-bats while ranking in the top 10 in 11 NL offensive
categories. He was second in the league in RBI (21), multi-hit
games (10), runs (19), total bases (53), slugging percentage (.707)
and extra-base hits (14) as a leading player of the month
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox, for one, is not surprised, saying, ``He's a good RBI
guy. He's always able to get 'em in.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has several explanations. His offseason training regimen
with Bob Kersee has him in the best condition of his career. He is
completely over his back and wrist problems. And don't
underestimate the importance of finally playing in the city where
he has kept his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes away a lot of stress,'' Jordan said. ``When you're
away from your family, away from the kids, you're wondering about
what they're doing every day. Now that I'm home, it's fun. I can
relax.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan vs. LHP
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko made his second start of the year against a
left-hander in Pittsburgh's Chris Peters, having gone 2-for-5
against lefties thus far. His .400 start interrupted by two weeks
with a sore hamstring, Klesko is still recovering his swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen people come back after missing a month and start
raking,'' he said. ``I've been hitting in the cage but it's
different. You're not seeing breaking balls and change of speed in
the cage. It'll all come. I just have to get more at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
