<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-TRAINING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA PROGRAM TO SPEED TEACHER CREDENTIALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHARLINE CHIANG  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Teachers with emergency credentials will be able
to get fully certified in 18 months without ever stepping into a
classroom under a $5 million initiative announced Wednesday by Gov.
Gray Davis and California State University Chancellor Charles B.
Reed.
</P>
<P>
   California State University, Northridge, was one of five CSU
campuses that conducted the program last year on a pilot basis.
Under the direction of CSU faculty serving as mentors, participants
will earn credit through a distance-learning program based on
online courses and assignments via workbooks, audio and video
materials, and CD-ROMs.
</P>
<P>
   The program, christened CalStateTEACH, will begin Sept. 1 with
its first round of participants and is expected to draw 500
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an exciting program,'' Reed said Wednesday after
the announcement. ``They need access to the Internet, a video
recorder. That's it. They can do it early in the morning or late in
the evening, on their own time.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the only way a prospective teacher could get fully
certified in a relatively short amount of time -- 12 months -- is
by enrolling full-time for a year at a university. On average,
teachers working on emergency permits take four to five years to
get their credentials, Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   The program is based on the British Open University and is
intended to meet an exploding need for teachers. The designers
included an assessment component to ensure that teachers from the
new program are as prepared as those trained in the classroom, said
Delia Rudiger, assistant to the CSUN provost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reasonable question to ask,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said a teacher certified through the CalStateTEACH program
will be better prepared than their full-time counterparts due to
the increased mentoring and hands-on experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is even better,'' Reed said. ``They will be out in the
classroom and they will have the mentors working with them. One of
our faculty members will be assigned to every 20 participants.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 30,000 public elementary teachers in the state --
including 4,570 teachers in the Los Angeles Unified School District
-- are now working on emergency status.
</P>
<P>
   Education experts estimate California will need a total of
300,000 credentialed teachers from kindergarten through 12th grade
over the next decade due to teacher retirement, the push for
class-size reduction in all grades and increased student growth.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher students in groups of 18 to 20 will be assigned a
mentor, who will serve as an adviser, coach and evaluator. To be
eligible for the program, applicants must be teaching at the
kindergarten to sixth-grade level and should already have passed
the California Basic Education Skills Test. The cost of tuition for
the 38-credit program would be about $2,400.
</P>
<P>
   The $5 million will cover the cost to start up the program,
including expenses such as materials and salaries of mentors.
Afterward, the program is expected to be self-supported through
student fees.
</P>
<P>
   The second group will be admitted in September 2000, but
subsequent groups will be admitted every six months.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
