r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAS-OUT-LADN     04-28 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-OUT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL OFFICIALS DEFEND GAS PRICES TO CALIFORNIA LAWMAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TERRI HARDY AND RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- As some consumers prepare to boycott
gasoline stations Friday to protest high prices, oil company
executives told a state legislative hearing Wednesday prices are
unlikely to fall soon.
</P>
<P>
   Although short-term supply shortages did occur and drove up
prices, those problems have been resolved, the industry
representatives told lawmakers. But they offered no forecast of
when frustrated consumers might see lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``As competition continues in the street, (prices) will come
down further,'' said Chris Noble, senior vice president of retail
marketing for Atlantic Richfield Co. in an interview following the
hearing. ``We would advise consumers to shop around for where the
cheapest prices are.''
</P>
<P>
   Two senate committees jointly held the hearing to investigate
why gas prices spiked to historic levels this month. In Southern
California, the price rose more than 42 cents a gallon for
self-serve unleaded fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Los Angeles, the City Council voted 10-0 Wednesday
to go on record in support of the grass-roots ``gas out'' planned
for Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only way we, as consumers, can show our anger,''
Councilman Joel Wachs said.
</P>
<P>
   The one-day boycott has been promoted on the Internet by angry
consumers who also are trading information on gas stations with the
lowest prices. Councilwoman Laura Chick said the protest would send
a signal to the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a more powerful and effective way to get a
message to the oil companies,'' Chick said.
</P>
<P>
   In Sacramento, senators said the testimony from oil executives
-- who cited refinery fires and other production difficulties --
didn't fully explain why prices have been high for so long.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers pointed to data compiled by the California Energy
Commission that showed there had been enough gasoline to meet
consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, you raised prices because you could,'' said state
Sen. Debra Bowen, D-Redondo Beach, who chaired the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Oil company officials confirmed Energy Commission figures that
showed profits for refineries escalated dramatically during the
price hikes. Refineries received 70 cents for each gallon of gas in
April compared to 28 cents in February.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis DeCota, the executive director of the California Service
Station and Automotive Repair Association, disagreed that refinery
troubles and other manufacturing problems were to blame. Instead,
he said it was the lack of competition in the industry during an
era of bigger companies and mergers.
</P>
<P>
   Oil companies with refineries are able to force their service
stations to buy fuel only from them, instead of seeking out the
lowest priced gas, DeCota said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oil companies control gas prices in this state with an
iron fist,'' DeCota said.
</P>
<P>
   Exasperated lawmakers warned oil company officials that they
will need to loosen their grip or the state will make it illegal
for them to own gas stations.
</P>
<P>
   Already, legislation has been introduced by state Sen. Steve
Peace, D-La Mesa, that would allow gas station owners to buy their
fuel from other suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
