<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PIRATES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves rally, give Glavine first win
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The search for The Real Tom Glavine continues. And he
was believed to be nearby, judging by his pitching line. In the
meantime, the Braves committed an outright robbery Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the ninth down two runs, Atlanta rallied as Andruw
Jones sent a soft two-out single up the middle off reliever Mike
Williams, scoring Keith Lockhart with the game-winner in a 5-4
victory. Another small crowd of 29,615 was on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones delivered a critical two-run double off Jason
Christiansen, scoring Gerald Williams and Bret Boone to tie it 4-4.
After winning just two games last season when trailing after eight
innings, the Braves have done it three times in their first 20
games.
</P>
<P>
   The heroics made a winner of Glavine (1-3), who finished the
night by pitching seven shutout innings and avoided the first 0-4
start of his career. After being slapped around in the four-run
second, he delivered some of his best work of the season, limiting
the Pirates to two singles over the next six innings and retiring
10 straight during one stretch.
</P>
<P>
   With Chris Peters allowing one earned run over six innings, the
Braves labored to make up the deficit, stranding four men in
scoring position between the fourth and seventh innings alone.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko delivered his second RBI of the evening in the
fourth, when his sacrifice fly to center scored Brian Jordan to
close to the gap to 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta closed to 4-1 in the second inning, Javy Lopez drawing a
walk and taking third when third baseman Ed Sprague failed to
handle a high chopper by Andruw Jones and committed his seventh
error of the season. Klesko brought in Lopez with a ground-out to
second.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine was in trouble almost right away. He escaped the first
inning after yielding a pair of singles but was then raked for four
hits and a quick 4-0 disadvantage in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
