<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7345 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      04-28 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE DENIES SUPPORT FOR AIRSTRIKES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a setback for President Clinton, the
Republican-controlled House denied support for the ongoing NATO air
campaign against Yugoslavia and approved a measure requiring
congressional authorization before committing U.S. ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic-sponsored resolution of support for the NATO air
operation, which was approved by the Senate weeks ago, was defeated
on a vote of 213-213 and took both Democratic and Republican
leaders by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the House passed 249-180 a measure that would
withhold funding for a commitment of ground troops unless
specifically approved by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was only symbolic, the vote not to support the air
campaign angered a number of Democrats who contended that it was
incumbent on Congress to back the military operation as long as
U.S. forces are in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., said the votes represented an
``appalling lack of judgment and an appalling abandonment of the
troops in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a day which this House will profoundly regret,'' Obey
said, calling it ironic that Congress also defeated a measure
offered Wednesday calling for withdrawal of U.S. forces from the
NATO operation.
</P>
<P>
   He asked how the House on one hand could reject a resolution of
support for the NATO campaign while being on the verge of approving
an expanded emergency funding bill to help pay for the U.S. portion
of the allied operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never have I seen such confusion,'' Obey said.
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans, recalling the mistakes of Vietnam, called
the votes an honorable attempt by some lawmakers to prevent what
they believe could be a prolonged and costly U.S. commitment in the
Balkans and to ensure that Congress is involved in any decision to
expand the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may have been messy,'' observed Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas,
``but I am very proud that this House went on the record ... .''
</P>
<P>
   The votes, aimed at limiting Clinton's ability to widen the
offensive against Yugoslav forces, came despite his appeal that
lawmakers avoid a divisive debate on Kosovo that might be construed
by the Belgrade government as a lack of U.S. resolve to continue
the NATO bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to head off the debate, Clinton told lawmakers in
a meeting at the White House that he still believes ground troops
won't be needed. But if they are, he pledged in a letter to House
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., to seek the consent of Congress
before any ground invasion of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the House turned aside his appeal in an attempt to
force him to comply with the terms of the 1973 War Powers Act that
requires the president and Congress to agree when committing U.S.
forces to war.
</P>
<P>
   ``War is too important to be commenced by one person,'' said
Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., noting that presidents tend ``to act
... before bothering to consult'' with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bill prohibiting the commitment of ground troops
passed by a large margin, it must still win approval from the
Senate and be signed by the president before becoming law. The
Senate is expected to debate the possible commitment of ground
troops in a foreign relations committee hearing today. But the
measure the committee will consider would authorize the president
to use ``all necessary force'' to bring the Kosovo conflict to a
quick end.
</P>
<P>
   The air campaign resolution and the bill requiring congressional
approval for the use of ground troops were two of four measures
debated by the House on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The House defeated 427-2 a controversial measure declaring war
against Yugoslavia, offered by Campbell in an attempt to invoke the
War Powers Act.
</P>
<P>
   A second Campbell measure requiring withdrawal of all U.S.
forces from the NATO operation went down 290-139.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the chance to say no before we get in too deep. We
don't have to do this war,'' Campbell said, pleading with his
colleagues ``to have the courage'' to avoid another Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The debate Wednesday was rife with comparisons to the Vietnam
conflict, including expressions of concern about Americans
returning home from the Balkans in ``body bags'' or being caught
and held for years as prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   Rising to speak in opposition to U.S. military involvement in
the Balkans, Rep. Sam Johnson, R-Texas, referred to the nearly
seven years he spent as a POW in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer in Kosovo is not to waste American lives. The
answer is to stop the bombing and help the refugees. We don't need
another (Vietnam Memorial) wall,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Kosovo conflict as ``a Balkan quagmire,'' House
Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, said that the NATO air campaign
had accomplished nothing so far. He blamed the refugee crisis and
the intensified Serb offensive in Kosovo against ethnic Albanians
on the allied bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it worth it to stay in Vietnam just to save face?'' DeLay
asked his colleagues at one point, urging them to support the
withdrawal of U.S. forces from the NATO operation.``This is a
centuries-old civil war that we will become embroiled in
indefinitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Kevin Brady, R-Texas, suggested that the United States and
its NATO allies do not have ``the will to win'' because they have
refused to make killing Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic a key
objective of their campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've increased human suffering, not stopped it. We've
increased instability in the region,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But other Republicans, rising to express support for the NATO
campaign, cautioned their colleagues against any action that would
send ``the wrong message'' to Milosevic about U.S. resolve in
preventing him from displacing the ethnic Albanian population of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala., noted that Americans, by twice
electing Clinton as their commander-in-chief, had also granted him
the authority ``to do what he is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Still others pleaded with their colleagues not to turn their
backs on Kosovar Albanians who are being killed, raped and stripped
of their identity papers in their own homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard some refer to this as another Vietnam. But I see
Kosovo as another Cambodia or Rwanda ... Another killing field,''
said Rep. Tom Allen, D-Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Before the debate, Clinton met with 46 Republican and Democrat
lawmakers in hope of convincing them to speak with ``a single
voice'' on the Balkan conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The president also used his meeting to urge the quick approval
of a $6 billion emergency funding request he sent to Congress nine
days ago to finance the U.S. portion of the NATO operation.
Republicans in both the House and Senate are trying to double the
amount of the request by adding money for military programs that
the administration does not consider necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me stress that my request fully funds our military and
humanitarian needs in Kosovo,'' Clinton told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Both the House and Senate are expected to act on the funding
measure sometime next week. But some administration officials are
worried that it's being loaded up with ``pork barrel'' spending
designed to please defense lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
