<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
 ( rk )  
  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRADING BY HEDGE FUNDS MAY FACE TOUGHER SCRUTINY
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration plans to introduce legislation soon
that while not calling for direct regulation of the investment
pools for the wealthy known as hedge funds, will give the
Securities and Exchange Commission and the Commodities Futures
Trading Commission enhanced powers to examine the dealings of Wall
Street trading firms.
</P>
<P>
   They will also seek congressional backing for rules that require
hedge funds to disclose more information about their borrowing and
trading practices.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT IS SUED BY A RIVAL
</P>
<P>
   The software company Caldera is suing Microsoft for as much as
$1.6 billion, contending that Microsoft set out to destroy public
demand for DR-DOS, an operating system that competed against
Microsoft's MS-DOS.
</P>
<P>
   AETNA SHARES SOAR ON PROFIT REPORT
</P>
<P>
   First-quarter earnings at health insurer Aetna rose 15 percent,
as it raised premiums on employer health plans and shed
unprofitable Medicare business. Shares of Aetna rose $10.125, or
12.4 percent, to $92. The stock has risen more than 50 percent
since Aug. 31, when shares hit a 52-week low of $60.1875.
</P>
<P>
   DOW INDUSTRIALS SET ANOTHER RECORD
</P>
<P>
   Stocks sensitive to the business cycle turned in another strong
performance, while technology and other longtime market leaders
sagged. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 13.74 points, to
10,845.45, a new high. The Nasdaq composite index lost 52.04
points, or 2 percent, to 2,550.37, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index fell 11.89 points, to 1,350.91.
</P>
<P>
   SONY REPORTS A LOSS FOR THE QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   Sony reported a fourth-quarter net loss, and a decline of nearly
20 percent in fiscal-year earnings. Demand for its electronic
products fell, as Japan's economy faltered.
</P>
<P>
   BRITONS CONSIDER MISSILE VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   British Aerospace acknowledged that it was exploring a deal with
French and Italian companies to create a European missile industry
to challenge Raytheon.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA TOUGHENS TRADE STANCE
</P>
<P>
   China appears to have toughened its stance in talks aimed at
gaining entry to the World Trade Organization. It is using leverage
with European officials to press the United States for quicker
entry.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLERCHRYSLER PROFIT RISES 23 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by strong vehicle sales in the United States and healthy
heavy-truck sales, DaimlerChrysler reported that first-quarter
profits increased by 23 percent, exceeding analysts' forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN'S PLAN FOR GLOBAL REFORM
</P>
<P>
   Although Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin's proposals for
reforming international financial institutions have been described
as modest or cautious, the problem in the view of some prominent
economists is not that they don't go far enough but that Rubin
failed to outline concrete steps that would translate his ideas
into action.
</P>
<P>
   KATZENBERG TESTIFIES IN DISNEY SUIT
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Katzenberg, the former Walt Disney studio chief,
testified in court that his 10 years at the Disney Co. were ``a
lie'' because of a dispute with Michael D. Eisner, the Disney
chairman, over a huge bonus.
</P>
<P>
   DURABLE GOODS ORDERS UP IN MARCH
</P>
<P>
   Orders for big-ticket goods made in the United States rose a
stronger-than-expected 2 percent in March.
</P>
</TEXT>
