<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0482 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7359 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-MORGAN-NY     04-28 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-MORGAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN THE JOURNEYMAN, WITH EMPHASIS ON JOURNEY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Mike Morgan speaks as rapidly as he pitches,
firing one thought after another, rushing through conversation and
changing topics as quickly and seamlessly as he has changed teams.
</P>
<P>
   In one long, continuous answer to a question posed to him
Tuesday afternoon _ Why did he come back for his 22nd season in pro
ball? _ Morgan mentioned his two daughters, the business of
baseball and how he won't let it get to him, run support, his love
of team, friends, and in summation, his two daughters again.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan is 39 years old and has seemingly been in the wrong place
at the wrong time for most of his career, but he's not slowing
down, not now, not when he has found a place where his skills are
best suited. He is 4-0 for the Texas Rangers and will try to become
the American League's first five-game winner Thursday against the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still learning about this game, still trying to make
adjustments,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Manager Johnny Oates said: ``He's been a big plus for us.
He's kept us in every game he's pitched for us, be it starting or
relieving.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan is pitching for his 11th team, a record not just in
baseball but in major league sports, and he has a place in baseball
history, for sure, although his legacy is difficult to define.
</P>
<P>
   Going into this season, Morgan had the lowest winning percentage
(.416) of any pitcher with at least 275 decisions in his career,
according to Jim Henzler of Stats Inc.; Morgan has since climbed to
a .424 percentage (125-170), ahead of Pedro Ramos (.422).
</P>
<P>
   But it would be unfair to write Morgan off merely as someone who
lost a lot of games and played for a lot of teams. The first decade
of his career could be used as an example of how to mishandle a
young, talented pitcher, and Morgan always has been good enough and
earned enough respect to merit opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan was drafted out of high school in 1978 by Charlie Finley,
the owner of the Oakland Athletics, who had dismantled his
championship team rather than pay its free agents. With a bad team,
he sought methods of luring fans to the park. One way, he thought,
was to promote Morgan to the big leagues. Immediately. A week after
his high school graduation, Morgan made his debut, with absolutely
no idea how to pitch in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Morgan thought it was great. He and his friends
were thrilled with the idea that he was playing major league ball.
In retrospect, Morgan said, ``I should've been in rookie ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan floundered, predictably; before his first start, his
catcher, Jim Essian, told Morgan he would help nurse him through
the game by using all of his pitches. ``Don't worry,'' Morgan said,
``all I throw is a fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan has wondered occasionally how much the force-feeding
retarded his development. As with most players, he needed years in
the minors, in a low-pressure environment where he could learn.
Finley traded him to the Yankees, where the principal owner, George
Steinbrenner, was concerned about winning exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan floundered with the Yankees, predictably, and was traded
to Toronto and Seattle; everywhere Morgan went, everybody told him
what good stuff he had, that he should be better than he was, that
others with half his ability were winning. Morgan was losing a lot:
In his first 10 seasons in the big leagues, Morgan's highest
winning percentage was .500 _ he went 1-1 for Seattle in 1985.
Every other year, he had a losing record, his reputation growing.
</P>
<P>
   But after Morgan joined the Los Angeles Dodgers in 1989, he
said, he learned how to treat pitching as a profession. Ron
Perranoski, the Dodgers' pitching coach, shifted his position on
the mound, to take better advantage of the movement of Morgan's
fastball. His confidence grew, and ``finally, I began to see with
my own two eyes what everybody had been telling me'' _ that he
could be successful.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan had his first winning season in 1991, going 14-10 for the
Dodgers, and was 16-8 for the Cubs in 1992. Two years later, he
went on the disabled list three times _ he has been on the disabled
list 16 times in his career _ and he became a journeyman, bouncing
from one team to another.
</P>
<P>
   He moved from the Minnesota Twins to the Chicago Cubs last
season, and he surrendered Mark McGwire's 61st home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still got people out,'' said Morgan, who believed he would
have won more than four games last summer if he had been supported
by better defense and offense. ``I threw the ball better last year
than I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan was uncertain whether he would play in 1999, but once he
saw the way pitchers were coveted in the free-agent market, Morgan
hungered to get back. Many teams called in the off-season, he said,
but he was looking for the right situation, a club that could
provide ample run support and give him a chance to win when he
pitched into the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks before spring training, Morgan signed with the Texas
Rangers, who had perhaps the most dynamic offense in the league,
and for the first time in his career, he is 4-0. The other day, Joe
Girardi _ a teammate of Morgan in Chicago _ waved to him across the
field and held up four fingers. Four fingers for four victories.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan held a finger to his lips: Sshhh. With his history _ his
place in history _ it's something he doesn't want to expound upon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
