<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-DISPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SIGN OF DETENTE BETWEEN GIULIANI, SCHOOLS CHANCELLOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew said Wednesday that he
intended to keep working in New York despite tensions with Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, as the mayor repeatedly declined to say that he
still had confidence in him.
</P>
<P>
   Though Giuliani was instrumental in hiring Crew three and a half
years ago and has been one of his biggest boosters since then, the
deep chasm opened between them recently over school vouchers and
the structure of the Board of Education showed no signs of closing
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't work for the man, I work for the board,'' Crew said of
Giuliani after a meeting of the seven-member Board of Education
late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was going to resign over his dispute with the mayor,
Crew replied, in a jaunty, self-confident tone: ``No. Not at all.''
Asked if he was being pushed out of office by the mayor, he said
defiantly: ``No, I'm not being pushed.'' If anything, he added, he
was more determined than ever to stay on the job and continue his
efforts to improve city schools.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Giuliani refused to answer questions about whether
he continued to support the chancellor. But he said it would not be
his fault if Crew decided to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be responsible for it _ nope,'' Giuliani said,
bringing a sharper edge to his remarks after two days of
maintaining a subdued tone. ``People have to make their own
decisions about what jobs they want, what jobs they don't want. ''
</P>
<P>
   But both the chancellor and the mayor made it clear that they
would stand firm _ the mayor at City Hall, pressing his agenda for
what he called radical reform, and Crew at 110 Livingston St., the
school system headquarters in Brooklyn, defending his record. It
was a marked difference in a relationship that until two months ago
aides to both men had described as warm and personal.
</P>
<P>
   Although Crew and the mayor have had a strong working
partnership since Crew arrived in New York in October 1995, they
have been unable to reconcile their deep philosophical differences
over vouchers and control of the school system. Their battle
escalated last week, when Giuliani said the entire school system
was ``dysfunctional'' and ``should be blown up,'' and Crew reacted
by sending a passionate letter accusing Giuliani of ``reckless''
and ``destructive'' remarks that essentially wrote off the public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   While Giuliani has argued that vouchers that would send about
3,000 poor children to private and parochial schools would create
competition that would improve the school system, Crew has said the
vouchers would be a severe financial and moral blow to the system.
Under the mayor's plan, the vouchers would be paid for by taxpayer
money, and administered by City Hall. Crew has said he supports a
change in the structure of the Board of Education, but believes
that putting it under the direct control of the mayor would make it
too political.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
