<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-EWING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASKETBALL COLUMN: EWING OUGHT TO SIT, FOR SAKE OF THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before the New York Knicks played at Charlotte on
Monday night, Dave Checketts brought up a sensitive subject with
Jeff Van Gundy. He discussed the issue of whether the coach should
consider resting Patrick Ewing for the remainder of the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not giving up on the season when I say this by any
stretch, but Patrick needs a good off season when he's not sitting
at the bargaining table and he doesn't have that load on his
mind,'' Checketts said. ``He needs a good off season of
conditioning and getting ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``But saying all that, I still believe that if we can get him at
80 or 90 percent of what he's capable of doing and get a good
playoff position, there isn't anybody we can't beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Checketts has been taking the team's pulse since this three-game
road trip began Sunday in Miami, sitting with players on the team
plane, chatting with them after practice and essentially
determining what is salvageable from this disappointing season and
what is not.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the Madison Square Garden president seems to be
expanding his duties again. Since demoting Ernie Grunfeld last
week, he has already taken on the duality of social conscience and
general manager. Now, with Ewing, he is trying his hand at team
physician.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as the Knicks tried and failed to get their third straight
victory without Ewing on Wednesday night in their desperate march
toward the playoffs, losing to the Hawks, 76-73, it is reasonable
to wonder whether Ewing should play again this season.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, who may suit up again as early as tonight at home against
Philadelphia, might think the thought absurd. He would take it as a
blow to his ego and pride, and assume you believed he was a
detriment to a free-flowing offense.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the reason. If the Knicks ever want to win
anything of substance before Ewing retires after 2001, he needs to
be healthy. And if he is taking chances on a sore Achilles' tendon
in a season the Knicks need to write off as a learning experience,
the player who limps into the post-season is risking further injury
and hurting the Knicks in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts is paid to be a big-picture person, to see beyond
these comeback victories of late. He does need eight games at the
end of the season to confirm his worst fears about this franchise.
The first 42 games on television explained that to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy's fate may already be decided. Unless he culls
something extraordinary out of the post-season, his days in New
York may finally come to an end. Perhaps Checketts' decision to
spend this much time around the team of late is to let him gauge
what Van Gundy means to the Knicks before he decides his coach's
future.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, some things are obvious. This whole notion of giving
the Knicks a year to come together is not a great one. They need to
go after a point guard as soon as the season ends, giving up
anything they can to convince Seattle to part with the disenchanted
Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell, Charlie Ward and Chris Childs could be trade
bait, but whatever Checketts does, he needs to find someone with
the same court vision the franchise was supposed to have when it
made questionable decisions this past off season.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the past decade, the Knicks have used April and May
to turn the Garden into a noisy den of possibility and hope. And as
this current group of players appears to find its rhythm, that
feeling is beginning to build again.
</P>
<P>
   But this team has neither the personnel nor the heart to sustain
that momentum. Checketts can't admit that for obvious reasons, but
that is the hard and plain truth. And that is why Ewing should take
his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost threw it out there just to say, is it worthwhile just
resting him now,'' Checketts said. ``But I think in his view, and
in Patrick's view, if he can help us, if that one extra game can
make a difference _ or two extra games _ could mean a different
playoff seeding, I think we have to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing has missed 11 out of 46 games, nearly one-fourth of the
season. He would miss almost one-third of the season if he didn't
play the remaining four games. The team is already playing well
without him. Maybe, for once in a career, he should let his
teammates carry the piano upstairs. And play only when he is
healthy and ready.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
