<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRINCIPALS OVER POLITICS 
TIPTOEING THROUGH THE ALUMINUM 
SOME DVORAK FOR HAVEL
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON with ELISABETH BUMILLER AND DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maybe they both want to be a senator for six years,
but Hillary Rodham Clinton and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani will settle
for being principal for a day.
</P>
<P>
   Both will take charge of public schools in New York City on
Thursday, Mrs. Clinton at the Virgil I. Grissom Junior High School
226 in Ozone Park, Queens, and Giuliani at Public School 123 in
Williamsburg, Brooklyn, as part of a nationwide program that
encourages public officials, executives and celebrities to become
involved in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton and Giuliani are considering running for Senate
next year, so naturally, aides to both said Wednesday that politics
was the last thing on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor is in the schools all the time, not only when he's
running for office,'' said Cristyne Lategano, Giuliani's
communications director. ``This shouldn't be a political event, and
we hope that it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's spokeswoman, Marsha Berry, said much the same
thing. ``Mrs. Clinton has been interested in big public school
systems around the country for most of her adult life,'' Ms. Berry
said. ``This is a way for her to show her interest in a big public
school system.''
</P>
<P>
   And nothing else? ``Not from our point of view,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tulips for Sale on Park Avenue
</P>
<P>
   ``Tulips and the color red are my passion,'' the sculptor Edwina
Sandys said Tuesday, looking out at the three she had installed on
Park Avenue at 57th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Installed, not planted. She made these tulips herself out of
aluminum. They are 12 feet tall and overshadow the garden-variety
tulips that are planted every spring in the same median strip under
a bequest from the philanthropist Mary Lasker.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sandys, a granddaughter of Sir Winston Churchill, presided
at a kind of dedication ceremony inside the Alfred Dunhill store,
whose big plate glass windows face the tulips. Looking out from
inside were the Very Rev. James Parks Morton, the president of the
Interfaith Center of New York and the dean emeritus of the
Cathedral of St. John the Divine; the jewelry designer Kenneth Jay
Lane, and the novelist Barbara Taylor Bradford, who said: ``I'm a
huge admirer of her grandfather. I always mention him and quote him
in my books.''
</P>
<P>
   The parks commissioner, Henry Stern, called Mrs. Sandys' tulips
``first-rate sculpture.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the installation is for sale and added, ``If
anyone is good enough to buy it and give it to us, we'll find a
wonderful place for it.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused, then added, ``With the approval of the Art
Commission, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   This was apparently a reference to a lawsuit filed by Reba White
Williams, the former president of the commission, who accused Mayor
Giuliani of allowing Stern to install yardarms on flagpoles in
parks without the commission's approval.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the mayor, Stern, several other city officials and
a couple of celebrities went to Central Park to dedicate 2,000
trees that will be planted by the beginning of next year, which is,
of course, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Stern was as indefatigably earnest as ever, lecturing the crowd
of schoolchildren on red oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Then Nicholas Scoppetta, who heads the Administration for
Children's Services, stepped up to the microphone. ``I really don't
have anything to say,'' he said, ``but I couldn't pass up the
opportunity to be on the same bill and say I played Central Park
with Isabella Rossellini and Ron Silver.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound Czech
</P>
<P>
   What does the guy at at the Baldwin play when a VIP walks in?
Michael Garin, the pianist at Monkey Bar, a restaurant at 60 E.
54th St., tried ``O Lovely Moon'' by the Czech composer Antonin
Dvorak when Vaclav Havel, the president of the Czech Republic,
walked in on Tuesday with his wife, Dagmar, and the director Milos
Forman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four chords and Mrs. Havel went, `Yeah,' like, `You are not
asleep at the switch, man,''' Garin said.
</P>
<P>
   Later that same evening, Garin asked one of Havel's security
agents, who was hanging out at the piano, if there was anything he
wanted to hear. ``How about, `The Party's Over?''' the agent said.
</P>
</TEXT>
