<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PILLARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES PILLARD, 80; LED ELECTRICIANS UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles H. Pillard, the strong-willed president of the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers for two decades,
died April 26 in a hospital in Buffalo, N.Y. He was 80 and had
lived in Orchard Park, a suburb of Buffalo, since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Pillard, a native of Buffalo, graduated from high school, worked
for a time as an electrician, became an official of the IBEW and
rose steadily in its ranks. He was the union's president from 1968
until 1986, when he retired after a dispute with another union that
was on strike at the time.
</P>
<P>
   At his retirement the IBEW was the nation's sixth largest, with
869,000 members. The only unions with more members were the
International Brotherhood of Teamsters, the National Education
Association, the United Food and Commercial Workers, the United
Automobile Workers and the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees.
</P>
<P>
   During Pillard's presidency, his union's membership reached 1
million. It is now about 750,000.
</P>
<P>
   The union is the biggest of the electrical unions and represents
workers in utilities and in the broadcasting, railroad and
construction industries. When Pillard was president of the union,
he also was a vice president and a member of the executive council
of the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   Pillard could be contentious. In a letter to The Wall Street
Journal in 1984 he asserted, ``Blaming labor for the rising costs
of nuclear power plants is like placing the blame for the Johnstown
flood on a leaky faucet in Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also sometimes outspoken about politics. In 1982 he
declared that the Reagan administration had ``given new life to the
extremists of the right _ the very same forces that organized labor
threw out of the government 50 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   While Pillard was president, the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers won a lawsuit against the Nixon administration
about elements in the federal wage-control system that, the union
contended, penalized the working poor.
</P>
<P>
   Pillard retired after a rancorous dispute between his union and
the Communications Workers of America about negotiations on new
contracts with regional telephone companies and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Workers from the electrical workers union continued to work at
AT&AMP;T factories while the communications workers were on strike. The
CWA's president, Morton Bahr, later contended that Pillard's union
had committed ``fratricide'' in the labor movement. Bahr told
reporters that both unions could have gained more from AT&AMP;T if they
had presented a united front.
</P>
<P>
   Engineering News-Record, a McGraw-Hill publication, said in 1996
that before Pillard was succeeded as president by John J. Barry,
``few things better symbolized intransigence in the building trades
than Charles H. Pillard'' and his position on a labor issue
involving 10-hour work shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Pillard served in the Army in the Pacific and Europe in World
War II, rising to captain. He won awards from the Anti-Defamation
League of B'nai B'rith and other organizations, and served on
several federal panels, including a presidential advisory committee
for trade negotiations and a presidential committee on employment
of people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 55 years, the former Helen May
Bratten; two daughters, Jane Carollo of Orchard Park and Linda Voye
of Amherst, N.Y.; two brothers, Francis Bieber of Tonawanda, N.Y.,
and Jack Bieber of Cheektowaga, N.Y.; a sister, Gloria Cook of
Houston, five grandchildren and two great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
