<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-VALHOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALHOL SURVIVES FIGHT JUST TO ENTER KENTUCKY DERBY
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RAC-DERBY) 
 (rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Even if it took a court fight, the Valhol camp
is grateful that its horse is in the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Dallas Keen said Wednesday that his horse deserved the
ruling by an Arkansas court on Tuesday that released the Arkansas
Derby purse of $300,000 to the owner, James Jackson. The purse had
been held up by Oaklawn Park pending an investigation into the
possible use of an electrical buzzer by the jockey, Billy Patin, to
get the gelding to run faster.
</P>
<P>
   Patin has been replaced as the jockey by Willie Martinez, who
worked the horse half a mile Tuesday morning in 48 1/5 seconds.
``Willie's excited about this horse,'' Keen said. ``He's been
watching tapes of his races to get familiar with him.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the legal decision that put Valhol in the Derby, Keen
said: ``The law was clear, and we felt confident leaving the
courtroom that the decision would be favorable. This horse deserves
the opportunity to run in the Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Jackson nor Keen was discouraged by Valhol's being
lumped with four other horses in the mutuel field. ``He was 107-1
in Louisiana,'' Keen said of Valhol's fourth-place showing, ``and
31-1 in the Arkansas Derby. He's never let us down yet. He won't
embarrass us on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Godolphin stable isn't sure who will ride its second Derby
entry, Aljabr. It had hoped to tab last year's Derby winner, Kent
Desormeaux, but he is the regular rider on the filly entered by Bob
Baffert, Excellent Meeting. The European rider Daragh O'Donahue was
flown in for the race. But the trainer Saeed bin Suroor made it
clear that Desormeaux would ride Aljabr if Baffert scratched
Excellent Meeting.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
