<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0489 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7378 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-DERBY-ART-570&AMP;ADD     04-28 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-ART-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO FILLIES AMONG 20 IN WIDE-OPEN RUN FOR THE ROSES
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RAC-DERBY-VALHOL) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ A full field of 20 horses was entered
Wednesday in the 125th Kentucky Derby and, for the first time in 15
years, it included two fillies, Three Ring and Excellent Meeting,
who was named half of the favored entry with her stablemate General
Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The race was considered wide open, and the draw for post
positions did nothing to dispel the fact that no dominant
3-year-old horse had surfaced in the prep races of the last few
months.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting, who was named this morning for the Derby on
Saturday and who is still entered in the Kentucky Oaks for fillies
on Friday, was made part of a powerful pair entered by Bob Baffert
at 3-1 as he shoots for his third consecutive victory in America's
most prestigious race.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the first time in 15 years that 20 horses were
booked into the two starting gates at Churchill Downs: 14 in the
main gate, 6 in the auxiliary gate. And the two fillies fared well
in that respect: Excellent Meeting drew the No. 6 spot, the same
post she drew in the Oaks, and Three Ring drew No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the most highly prized horses in the country drew
unfavorable positions: Prime Timber, the third of Baffert's stars
from California, got the 14th slot and General Challenge got the
15th. Farther outside to their right came Vicar, winner of the
Florida Derby, in No. 18; Menifee, winner of the Blue Grass Stakes,
in No. 19, and Lemon Drop Kid, winner of the Belmont Futurity, No.
20.
</P>
<P>
   The two mystery horses from Dubai were personally entered by
their owner, Sheik Mohammed bin Rashid al-Maktoum, and both did all
right: Aljabr was placed fifth from the rail, Worldly Manner 12th.
The entry was listed at 12-1.
</P>
<P>
   The draw was conducted for the third year under a new system
that reduces the random selection of post positions of years past.
For most races, the horse is assigned his post in the gate
according to the number drawn from a box. Under the new system, the
draw from the box determines the selection order by the owners and
trainers.
</P>
<P>
   So, Scotty Schulhofer, who trains Lemon Drop Kid, drew No. 20
and was the last to make his selection. Naturally, only one post
position was left, the one on the far outside. ``After much
deliberation,'' Schulhofer announced with a straight face to the
crowd assembled in the track's museum, ``we'll pick No. 20.''
</P>
<P>
   A kind of gallows humor descended on several other trainers,
too, including Baffert, who said: ``It could be worse. We could be
back in California watching on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   The rail position, often shunned because it subjects the horse
to heavy traffic pressure from others trying to rush to the inside,
was avoided until Nick Zito got to make his selections, both of
which were favorable. He picked No. 4 for Stephen Got Even, winner
of the Turfway Stakes, and No. 1 for Adonis, winner of the Wood
Memorial. ``To tell the truth,'' he said, ``I don't want to be near
Baffert.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, turning serious, said: ``There is no ideal post
position. The horse still has to break, and that's the most
important thing. If you don't break in this race, you'll find
yourself behind 12 horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excellent Meeting has the same style that Real Quiet has. She
can take dirt kicked in her face. With the others, I didn't want to
get picked off, so I took 14 and 15. You can get hit on only one
side out there. And I didn't want Prime Timber to stand in the gate
too long; he gets antsy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Baffert was asked if Excellent Meeting's favorable post may
decide whether she skips the Oaks and run in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know how a filly will run,'' he replied. ``I wish
Three Ring had run in the Florida Derby. On paper, Excellent
Meeting looks great. Right now, I'm going to the Derby with her.
But John Mabee might show up at the barn tomorrow and change his
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time two fillies ran in the Derby was 1984, when the
trainer D. Wayne Lukas sent out Life's Magic and Althea.
</P>
<P>
   The intrigue surrounding Excellent Meeting thickened Wednesday
morning when Baffert announced that he would cross-enter her in the
Derby the day after the Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   He made the decision after meeting with the filly's owners,
Betty and John Mabee of Golden Eagle Farm in California, and
indicated that he was following his strategic plan: taking out
insurance in case he didn't like the post position in either race.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting drew the sixth spot in a field of eight in the
starting gate for the Oaks. She would break just to the right of
Silverbulletday, a star filly also trained by Baffert but owned by
Mike Pegram, who owned Real Quiet, last year's Derby winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This filly is doing great,'' Baffert said, ``and she earned
her way into the Derby. She's good enough to win. Entering her in
the Derby keeps our options open. A lot can happen between now and
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert's decision also meant that Excellent Meeting would bump
Etbauer from the Derby. The colt won the Rebel Stakes at Oaklawn
Park, and stood last in the line of 20 candidates for the Derby
with $75,000 in winnings in graded stakes. Excellent Meeting, with
more than $1 million in earnings, thereby qualified for one of the
20 slots and Etbauer fell to No. 21.
</P>
<P>
   So, no matter which race Excellent Meeting started, Etbauer was
out of the Derby. The rules do not allow replacements for scratched
horses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
