<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW COMES HARD PART FOR LAKERS _ WINNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ In a season of bad starts and worse
finishes, the Los Angeles Lakers start anew once more tonight,
emboldened by a team bloodletting meeting and two solid days of
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Whether any of the events of the past two days _ the intense
players-only meeting, the airing of issues and grievances, the
renewed dedication to defense _ translates into better play will be
evident soon. The Portland Trail Blazers, newly crowned champs of
the Pacific Division, come to the Forum tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are as optimistic as any team riding a three-game
losing streak can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way that we feel is there's nowhere to go but up,'' Kobe
Bryant said. ``There's no time to be down. The more down we get on
ourselves, the worse it's gonna get. So we have to pick ourselves
up and keep on trying, keep on playing hard.... Hopefully, the
longer you struggle, the greater you become.''
</P>
<P>
   For two straight days in practice, they have. In this condensed
50-game season, just practicing two consecutive days has been a
rarity and a luxury, and that alone should help.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the two best practices we've had all year,'' coach
Kurt Rambis said. ``Are these two practices gonna cure all of our
ills? Probably not. But it is a steppingstone in the right
direction....
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody clearing the air, they feel good. It's like
a burden that's been released getting things off their chest. There
may have been pent-up emotions or feelings, and now they're out in
the open and everybody feels good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal said it will all be pointless if the team
doesn't pull together come tipoff. As for whether all the talking
helps, O'Neal said flatly, ``not to me. It doesn't help our
standings. We gotta go out and get it done now.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Forum walls, observers expect a total meltdown as
the Lakers head into the postseason. In the Lakers locker room,
they're doing all they can to fight that negativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's us against the world,'' J.R. Reid said. ``When we get
down to it, it's just gonna be the coaches and the players in this
locker room. So that's the only guys we can depend on, and we need
to re-establish that trust with each other from that meeting on.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Derek Fisher: ``We haven't given up, and we won't give
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Del speaks: Del Harris, fired as head coach Feb. 24, said the
Lakers ``hung me out all summer'' by not extending his contract and
decided back then that this would be his last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact I did get fired last year,'' he said Wednesday on
ESPN's ``UpClose.'' ``They should have extended me last year, along
with (executive Jerry) West and (GM Mitch) Kupchak and Rambis....
Or they should have fired me, one or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris was brought back to finish out his contract, then fired
when the team started out 6-6. He said he has no regrets but said
the team acted hastily in dismissing him at a time the Lakers were
banged up and had not yet signed Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have stayed the course with the old fella,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers management ``failed to recognize what we had done over
the last four years in going from a lottery team to 48 (wins), 53,
57, 61 wins and having a tremendous season last year that was
unrecognized and unappreciated,'' said Harris, who decided then
that ``it was best that I ... move on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
