<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CONGRESS AND KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting) (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, April 29:
</P>
<P>
   Prosecuting a war in consultation with Congress is not always
easy for the White House, but it is necessary under the
Constitution. Given the sensitive military and diplomatic ground in
Kosovo, the House is for the most part steering a reasonable if
spendthrift course this week in acting on several measures
involving the war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers were right on Wednesday to insist that President
Clinton seek congressional approval if he decides to order ground
troops into combat. The measure was advanced by Republican leaders
but supported by 45 Democrats in a 249-to-180 vote that Democratic
opponents mischaracterized as a message of weakness to Slobodan
Milosevic. Clinton says he has no intention of invading Kosovo or
Serbia, and NATO has made no preparations to do so, beyond the
drafting of contingency plans. If sentiment within the alliance
changes, Clinton would be well advised to start moving troops and
weapons to the Balkans to keep the option open and to increase the
pressure on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Congress should not limit Clinton's hand on such preparations.
But if the president chooses to send ground forces into battle, he
will need the full support of Congress and the American people.
Yesterday he assured the House he would seek congressional support.
To act without it would invite the kind of division and political
unrest that developed during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   The House also properly rejected an appeal from Rep. Tom
Campbell of California to issue a formal declaration of war against
Yugoslavia. With diplomacy at a delicate stage, the act of
declaring war would escalate the conflict and harden Serbian
resistance to a political settlement. Diplomatic efforts are likely
to intensify now that Russia has taken a lead role in trying to
mediate the conflict. Kofi Annan, the U.N. secretary general, plans
to travel to Moscow on Thursday, following the visit there earlier
this week by Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott.
</P>
<P>
   It is regrettable that the House could not muster a majority to
support a resolution in favor of the air war. The House is also
fumbling a defense-spending measure. It should quickly approve
Clinton's $6 billion emergency request to pay for the air war and
assistance for hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians driven
from Kosovo by Serbian forces. Instead the House is moving to
provide more than double that amount, with additional money for a
military pay raise, construction projects and other matters that
should be considered as part of the normal Pentagon budget. The
Senate is likely to do the same. Using the war to circumvent budget
limitations is a misuse of congressional power and will not help
NATO prevail in Yugoslavia. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-28-99 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
