<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990428.0492 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7385 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-1STLD     04-28 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE BARS GROUND TROOPS IN KOSOVO WITHOUT CONGRESSIONAL OK 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with House refusing to support
air strikes, with fresh quotes, details; Pickup 7th graf pvs, In a
meeting ...; Story now in 2 takes.) 
 (mb) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a sharp challenge to President Clinton, the
House voted Wednesday to bar the president from sending ground
troops to Yugoslavia without congressional approval and then on a
tie vote refused to support NATO air strikes against Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The votes came during a day of heated and sometimes anguished
speeches that showcased deep divisions in Congress over the
escalating conflict in the Balkans. The all-day session marked the
first formal congressional debate since NATO began its bombing
campaign on March 24 to drive the forces of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic out of Kosovo. The Senate had voted on March 23
to approve the air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 249-180 to require the president to seek
congressional approval for ground forces. Forty-five Democrats and
an independent joined 203 Republicans to support the measure.
Sixteen Republicans and 164 Democrats opposed the bill.
</P>
<P>
   But the surprise came when the House finished its deliberations
by failing to pass a Democratic resolution intended to give
symbolic support to the president's air campaign. The measure
failed in a tie vote of 213-213 even though Speaker Dennis Hastert
threw his support behind it. In all, 31 Republicans broke with
their party to back the air campaign and 26 Democrats voted against
it.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said it would press ahead with the air strikes.
``The House today voted `no' on going forward, `no' on going back
and they tied on standing still,'' said Jake Siewert, a White House
spokesman. ``We will continue to prosecute the air campaign and to
stop the violence being perpetrated by Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the rebuke of the president on air strikes, Hastert
said, ``I would hope that the president would take this diverse
debate as a signal that he should better explain the goals, the
costs and the long-term strategy of why we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   The House votes should have no immediate practical effect on the
White House conduct of the war, since the president has said
repeatedly there are no plans to use ground troops, and since he
does not need the House's moral support to continue air strikes.
And it is not clear what the Senate, which voted in support of air
strikes on March 23, will do.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate does not have to take up the House measure on ground
troops. But in an effort to take their own stand on the Balkan
policy, the Republican and Democratic leaders were working behind
the scenes to see if they could draft bipartisan language on
Kosovo. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., has introduced his own
resolution authorizing Clinton to use ``all necessary force'' to
win in the Balkans, but Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott has
objected to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting with lawmakers at the White House on Wednesday,
Clinton once again said he had no plans for ground troops and vowed
that he would seek congressional ``support'' if he changed that
stance. But he would not seek congressional approval, his spokesman
Joe Lockhart said, arguing that such a step would raise a host of
constitutional questions.
</P>
<P>
   While Lockhart stopped short of a veto threat, Democrats in the
House said the president would veto any measure requiring such
approval of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the long day of debate, some House members invoked
the quagmire of Vietnam to call for America to withdraw from the
Balkans. Others drew comparisons with World War II and the
Holocaust to argue for the air campaign to go on. And Rep. Gene
Taylor, D-Miss., urged the rare step of a full declaration of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that in voting for war I will share the responsibility
for those young Americans who may die,'' Taylor said. ``But to do
anything else is much worse. The best course of action for this
nation is to use the overwhelming military might we have at our
disposal to end this war swiftly and quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House had tried in the past to discourage such open
debate in Congress about the Kosovo conflict in the hopes of
sending a united message to Yugoslavia and to present a unified
voice of support for the troops. Until now, the Republican
leadership had also shied away from such a debate, with some senior
Republicans calculating that their party would be best served by
distancing itself from the conflict and letting President Clinton
take any blame for involvement in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Defense Secretary
William Cohen argued in a letter to Hastert that a prohibition on
ground troops ``could be misinterpreted as a U.S. retrenchment''
from its solidarity with NATO, and would impede the president in
his role as commander in chief. But the Administration's effort to
influence the House vote was low key and the White House was not
demanding party-line support.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's debates were forced by Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif.,
who used his prerogatives under the Vietnam-era War Powers
resolution to force votes on what he has called an unconstitutional
war, undeclared by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes we're at war,'' said Campbell, who is a law professor.
``We're on the verge of ground troops. The framers were quite clear
that war was too important to be decided by one individual. Ground
troops are very seriously being considered. Therefore we must
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Working its way through an array of proposals, the House
rejected the measure to issue a formal declaration of war against
Yugoslavia by a vote of 2-427. The House also declined, by a vote
of 139-290, to call for an immediate withdrawal of all American
forces from the region.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans poured out their reservations about a conflict
they said had ill-defined goals and was not in the nation's vital
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it worth it to stay in Vietnam to save face?'' asked Rep.
Tom DeLay, the majority whip. Sharply criticizing the NATO bombing
campaign, DeLay said, ``What good has been accomplished so far?
Absolutely nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, who, like McCain, is seeking the
Republican presidential nomination, said, ``The fact is the civil
war in Kosovo has been raging since 1389.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasich added, ``The fact is our intervening in the middle of an
ethnic civil war that has been going on for six centuries is not
likely to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Charles Norwood, R-Ga., predicted that if Congress did
not act, the president ``will commit our grandchildren to policing
the Balkans. Not because we are threatened. Not because we are
under attack. But simply to enforce a new world order.''
</P>
<P>
   The many Democrats who rallied around Clinton invoked memories
of the Holocaust. They said the ban on ground troops without
authorization would hamstring NATO commanders, force the courts to
decide what constituted ground troops and sent the wrong message to
Milosevic. Some said the bill's restrictions on what it termed
``ground elements'' were so vague that they could be interpreted as
banning financing for the support troops already in Albania and the
Balkan region with the Apache helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really want to say to him today, `we don't know what
we're doing, we probably won't be for ground troops?''' implored
Rep. Dick Gephardt, the minority leader, ``You want to take that
option off the table? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Bonior, the Democratic whip said, ``Some say the
suffering Kosovars are not America's responsibility. That the gang
rapes, the burned villages, the mass graves are not our problem.''
He added ``We are a superpower at the peak of our prosperity and
strength. What is America supposed to do? Look the other way?''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the Democrats agreed. ``We cannot win peace through
war,'' said Rep. Dennis Kucinich of Ohio. ``The failure of the
bombing campaign is proof.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
