<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-PISTONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS SEND A MESSAGE FOR THREE QUARTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ For three quarters, the Nets defied the
odds. With precision, hustle and heart they put a team fighting
desperately for playoff position in jeopardy. Perhaps that is all
one can ask of a club that is bereft of healthy big men and playing
for nothing more than pride.
</P>
<P>
   As the fourth quarter grew old, the undermanned Nets lost
strength, enabling the Detroit Pistons to pull away for a 101-93
victory before 17,795 fans at The Palace.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons, who trailed throughout the first half and for most
of the third period, outscored the Nets by 23-15 in the final
quarter to prevail. The victory was large for Detroit, which
improved to 26-20 and moved two games ahead of the eighth-place
Knicks (24-22) in the Eastern Conference playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons are tied for sixth with the Milwaukee Bucks. But the
Nets almost felt victorious themselves. After being destroyed on
Tuesday by the Miami Heat, they were encouraged by how close they
came to winning with Jamie Feick and Mark Hendrickson manning the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   While it is hard for a team with a 14-32 record to send a
message, Kendall Gill, who battled neck-and-neck all night with
Grant Hill, believes the Nets did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to let people know that hey, we're here and that next
year we're going to be a team to be reckoned with,'' Gill said.
``We're going to have everybody with us and they know that over
there in the other locker room. They're thinking, `These guys are
almost beating us and they don't have four or five of their guys.
What's going to happen next year?' We know that that thought is
over there in their minds and that's the same thought that we're
trying to put in everybody's minds that we play.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill's boldness came from playing Hill to a near draw. The Nets'
swingman scored 22 points and made five steals, compared with
Hill's 25 points, seven rebounds and six assists. Though he had six
turnovers, Hill emerged as the winner by scoring 7 fourth-quarter
points.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, Gill and the Nets had Detroit fearing the worst.
Stephon Marbury played another strong game, finishing with 21
points and 12 assists, and had 20 and 10, respectively, through
three periods. His play, along with the contributions of Gill,
Kittles (14 points), Feick (13 points, 16 rebounds) and Hendrickson
(12 points, eight rebounds), allowed the Nets to enter the fourth
quarter tied at 78-78.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Jud Buechler hit his first of two late 3-pointers to
break an 81-81 tie early in the fourth, and the Pistons moved ahead
by 5 points before the Nets pulled within 3 at 90-87. Marbury had a
chance to take them closer but missed two free throws with 4
minutes 22 seconds left. Then Hill scored two quick baskets, and
Buechler drilled his final 3-pointer to seal it.
</P>
</TEXT>
